{"type":"tool_execution_end","toolCallId":"call_b9f90c55f2824ea0be4354","toolName":"mcp","result":{"content":[{"type":"text","text":"ok: true\nstatus: ready\nstate: ready\nmessage: An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\nafter_version: 15\nafter_opportunity_id: deliberation:1:C2\nmember_id: C2\ncase_id: arb-ex03-20260629192557\nwait_reason: ready\nphase: deliberation\nopportunity_id: deliberation:1:C2\nremaining_ms: 887183\nattempts_remaining: 3\njson: {\"after_opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C2\",\"after_version\":15,\"case_id\":\"arb-ex03-20260629192557\",\"limits\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"max_evidence_read_bytes\":65536,\"max_evidence_read_bytes_per_opportunity\":524288,\"max_evidence_reads_per_opportunity\":32,\"max_response_bytes\":131072,\"remaining_evidence_read_bytes_for_opportunity\":524288,\"remaining_evidence_reads_for_opportunity\":32},\"member_id\":\"C2\",\"message\":\"An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\",\"ok\":true,\"prompt\":\"Role: council member\\nMember ID: C2\\nDeliberation round: 1\\nProposition: For the Kalshi market \\\"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\\", the strike \\\"Ronaldo\\\" should resolve Yes because Trump said \\\"Ronaldo\\\" in public remarks at the World Cup Draw venue immediately before the formal program, and the market wording plus the governing mention-market terms did not clearly exclude those event-linked remarks.\\nStandard of evidence: Preponderance of the evidence.\\nPersona:\\nYou are a careful juror and council member.\\n\\nEvaluate the record faithfully. Decide only from the evidence, the stated rules, and the applicable burden of proof. Do not favor either side, fill gaps with speculation, or ignore uncertainty.\\n\\nGive weight to reliable sources, direct evidence, consistent reasoning, and clear admissions. Discount unsupported claims, rhetorical force, irrelevant facts, and conclusions that exceed the record.\\n\\nWhen the evidence supports one answer, state it plainly. When the evidence is incomplete or balanced, say so. Be concise, honest, and exact.\\n\\nRecord:\\nOpenings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, this case is not mainly about whether the syllables were spoken. The case-packet transcript says they were. The real dispute is the market boundary: when Kalshi asked what Trump would say \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw,\\\" did that phrase clearly exclude his public, event-linked remarks at the World Cup Draw venue immediately before the formal program? On this record, it did not.\\n\\nThe market page fixes the contract at issue: the public title was \\\"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\\"; the contract family was PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION; the strike was \\\"Ronaldo\\\"; Kalshi challenged the resolution as No; and the requested resolution is Yes. That means the council's task is to apply the mention-market terms to that title and strike, not to import a narrower limitation that the market did not plainly announce.\\n\\nThe reporter-exchange packet is direct evidence on the word and setting. It is titled as remarks in an exchange with reporters prior to the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw, dated December 5, 2025. It places the President at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts, speaking with FIFA President Gianni Infantino and reporters in a sequence repeatedly labeled around the 2026 World Cup and the Draw. In that exchange, in a soccer discussion, Trump says he met Ronaldo, praises him, and uses \\\"Ronaldo\\\" as a distinct standalone word. Under the mention rules, a distinct standalone appearance of the strike is the kind of use that counts if it falls within the time period.\\n\\nThe terms matter because they do not say that an event market is limited only to scripted remarks from a formal stage segment. They define a time period as potentially an event or context, and they give the Exchange power to specify what is included when a time period refers to a specific event. They also distinguish official/public event content from behind-the-scenes, rehearsals, and unofficial recordings. That distinction helps plaintiff: the packet is not a rumor, rehearsal, private soundcheck, or leaked recording. It is a sourced public transcript of remarks at the event venue, immediately tied to the Draw. If Kalshi meant \\\"only the formal televised draw program after doors close\\\" or \\\"only remarks in the separate formal archive,\\\" it needed to say so clearly.\\n\\nI also want to be candid about what the packet does not yet prove. The formal-draw archive note says a separate archived transcript page exists for Trump's formal attendance remarks, but that the session could not retrieve the full text because the page was password-protected. So, at opening, plaintiff is not asking you to infer that the formal program itself contained \\\"Ronaldo.\\\" Nor does plaintiff need that inference. The Yes theory is that the qualifying period reasonably includes the public pre-program reporter exchange that was part of Trump's World Cup Draw appearance. The formal archive is relevant because it marks defendant's likely narrower boundary; it does not resolve the boundary in defendant's favor.\\n\\nProvenance and weight also favor treating the packet seriously at this stage. The market and terms files are system case-packet records. The reporter exchange includes a source URL to a public presidential transcript source and notes a corrected transcript date, while also acknowledging that some audio could not be verified because the audio was incomplete. That caveat may affect inaudible portions, but it does not erase the visible, contextual Ronaldo passage. Later, when evidence admission opens, the parties should preserve the official transcript source, any govinfo or Presidency Project copy, the market page capture, and any accessible formal-program transcript or video. The adverse check should ask whether the formal program omits the word, but omission there would matter only if the council first accepts the defense's artificially narrow reading of \\\"during.\\\"\\n\\nThe plaintiff's burden is preponderance. The record already points to a straightforward path to Yes: Trump, the specified entity, said the specified strike as a standalone word in public remarks linked to and immediately preceding the World Cup Draw at the venue; the market title and governing terms did not clearly exclude that event-linked exchange. On a fair reading of the contract the trader saw, the challenged No resolution should give way to Yes.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the defense opening is simple: this case is not won by proving that the word \\\"Ronaldo\\\" appears somewhere in a public transcript. The plaintiff must prove, by a preponderance, that the word was said during the market's specified event: the FIFA World Cup Draw.\\n\\nThe current packet leaves that critical link unproven. The market page does not say \\\"while Trump was at the venue,\\\" \\\"during a World Cup press availability,\\\" or \\\"during any remarks connected to the Draw.\\\" It says: \\\"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\\" The challenged resolution was No. The requested Yes theory therefore needs more than event-adjacent context; it needs a boundary showing that the reporter exchange was part of the Draw period the market asked traders to price.\\n\\nThe plaintiff's own best transcript cuts against that boundary. The case-packet file is titled \\\"Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw.\\\" It says the President's remarks were joined in progress, and the source note says portions could not be verified because the audio was incomplete. It places Trump at the Kennedy Center and includes World Cup topics, and yes, it contains \\\"Ronaldo\\\" as a standalone word in a soccer exchange. But its title and structure identify those remarks as an exchange with reporters prior to the Draw, not the formal Draw itself.\\n\\nThe terms do not rescue plaintiff from that distinction. They define a mention market around words used by the entity during the time period. A time period may be a specific event, and when it is a specific event, the Exchange may specify what is included. The technical details also distinguish official presentation content from behind-the-scenes, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings unless those are officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. Those provisions do not mean every public, nearby, event-related conversation becomes part of the event. They make the event boundary the central question.\\n\\nThe formal-draw archive note reinforces why the distinction matters. It reports that there is a separate archived transcript page for Trump's formal attendance remarks at the FIFA World Cup Drawing, but that the full text was not retrieved because the page was password-protected. That note does not prove the formal program omitted Ronaldo. It also does not prove the formal program included it. What it does show, at opening, is that the record itself separates the pre-event reporter exchange from the formal drawing remarks.\\n\\nSo the defense will focus the council on proof of inclusion, not mere association. If later phases produce a market page provision, official broadcast record, program transcript, video metadata, or source-agency material showing that the red-carpet reporter exchange was officially part of the FIFA World Cup Draw presentation for this market, the council can weigh that. If the later evidence instead shows a formal program with a separate pre-program press availability, then the correct result is No even though the word was spoken nearby.\\n\\nOn this opening record, plaintiff has shown a Ronaldo mention in remarks prior to the event. Plaintiff has not shown that those remarks occurred during the market event. The defense position is that Kalshi's No resolution follows the market wording and the mention-market terms unless plaintiff supplies that missing boundary proof.\\n\\nArguments:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the merits question is whether the contract clearly limited “during the FIFA World Cup Draw” to only the formal staged ceremony. Plaintiff submits that it did not, and the record now proves the Yes result by a preponderance.\\n\\nFirst, the market itself is broad. PX-1 identifies the public question as “What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?”, contract family PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION, strike “Ronaldo,” challenged resolution No, and requested resolution Yes. The market page does not say “during the formal televised ceremony,” “on the main stage only,” or “excluding public remarks immediately before the program at the venue.” That absence matters because Kalshi drafted the boundary traders had to price.\\n\\nSecond, the word was said. PX-2, the case-packet transcript, and PX-5, the GovInfo/OFR source excerpt, both show Trump used “Ronaldo” as a standalone word in soccer-related remarks. PX-5 is especially useful on provenance: it is the GovInfo Compilation of Presidential Documents source, published by the Office of the Federal Register/NARA, for DCPD202501162. It identifies the same event date, title, and source note, and it places the remarks at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center. In the relevant passage, Trump says he met Ronaldo, then says Ronaldo is great; later, when asked whether he played soccer or football, Trump says he was not Ronaldo or Messi. Either use satisfies the mention rule if the remarks fall within the market’s time period.\\n\\nThird, the remarks are event-linked in the way the market title reasonably covers. PX-2 and PX-5 are not private gossip, rehearsal, or an unofficial leak. They are public presidential remarks at the World Cup Draw venue, with FIFA President Infantino present, repeatedly discussing the Draw, the World Cup, ticket sales, the Kennedy Center, the audience, and the imminent program. The transcript itself includes headings such as “2026 World Cup Draw Event,” “2026 World Cup Draw Event/John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts,” and “2026 World Cup Draw/Ticket Sales for World Cup.” Trump and Infantino even discuss being a little late to “get in there” and the audience waiting. That sequence is not a random earlier interview; it is part of the public event appearance immediately surrounding the Draw.\\n\\nFourth, PX-3’s terms do not impose defendant’s formal-only line. They say the underlying is words used by the entity during the specified time period; a time period may be an event or context; and, when a time period refers to a specific event, the Exchange may specify what is included. They also say official/published content presented as part of the official presentation can count, while behind-the-scenes, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings do not count unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. Those exclusions show what this is not. The transcript is an official published record of public remarks at the event venue, not a hidden backstage clip. Nothing in PX-1 or PX-3 clearly tells traders that public, event-linked venue remarks immediately before the formal program are out.\\n\\nDefendant’s best point is PX-4 and the formal Roll Call/Factba.se page: there is a separate formal-drawing transcript, and my search found no “Ronaldo” there. Plaintiff does not hide that. But that adverse point proves only that the narrower formal-program source may omit the strike. It does not answer the contractual question. If Kalshi had meant to resolve solely by that formal transcript, it could have said so. Instead, the public market title used the broader phrase “during the FIFA World Cup Draw,” and the mention terms leave event boundaries to what the market clearly specifies.\\n\\nOn burden, plaintiff does not need absolute certainty or a formal-stage mention. Plaintiff must show it is more likely than not that the market wording plus terms include the event-linked remarks. The evidence satisfies that standard: PX-1 gives no exclusion; PX-2 and PX-5 prove the standalone Ronaldo mentions in public World Cup Draw venue remarks; PX-3 supplies a flexible event/time-period framework and excludes only categories unlike this source; PX-4 merely identifies the defense’s alternate formal-program boundary. The fair resolution is Yes.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the record now makes the defense point sharper, not weaker. Plaintiff has proved that Trump said \\\"Ronaldo\\\" in an official transcript of remarks connected to the World Cup Draw. Plaintiff has not proved that those remarks were during the market event.\\n\\nStart with the contract. DX/PX-1 gives the trader-facing question: \\\"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\\" It does not say \\\"at the Kennedy Center,\\\" \\\"on World Cup Draw day,\\\" \\\"in remarks prior to the Draw,\\\" or \\\"in any public press exchange associated with the Draw.\\\" For this strike to resolve Yes, the relevant mention must fall inside that specified time period.\\n\\nThe strongest evidence of the Ronaldo utterance is also the strongest evidence against plaintiff's boundary. PX-2 and PX-5 are titled \\\"Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw.\\\" PX-5, plaintiff's GovInfo/OFR source, confirms the same title, says the remarks were joined in progress, identifies the source as an exchange with the news media, and notes that some portions could not be verified because the audio was incomplete. That evidence proves an official pre-event reporter transcript. It does not prove the reporter exchange was the FIFA World Cup Draw.\\n\\nThe terms, PX-3, require words used by the entity during the specified time period. They permit an event or context as a time period, and they discuss what is included when the time period is a specific event. That framework does not turn all event-adjacent speech into event speech. The distinction between official presentation content and non-included behind-the-scenes or unofficial content matters because the question is not just whether a record is public or official. The question is whether this source was part of the market's event period. A public official transcript can still be a transcript of remarks prior to the event.\\n\\nDX-2 supplies the missing contrast. It is a focused extraction from the separate Roll Call/Factba.se formal FIFA World Cup Drawing transcript. That page is the formal source identified in the case-packet archive note. It is titled \\\"Remarks: Donald Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing in Washington - December 5, 2025.\\\" Its transcript begins with the formal drawing participants; at 00:00:50, Infantino says, \\\"This is the World Cup trophy\\\" and \\\"we are now going to do the draw.\\\" The page's Trump soccer answer mentions Pele and the Cosmos, not Ronaldo. The extracted page text was searched for both \\\"Ronaldo\\\" and \\\"Messi\\\" and neither appears.\\n\\nThat does not prove Trump never said Ronaldo anywhere at the venue. It proves the opposite boundary from plaintiff's: the formal Draw transcript is separate from the pre-event reporter exchange, and the formal transcript does not contain the strike. Plaintiff needs a bridge between those two sources. It has not offered one. There is no market page detail saying red-carpet or pre-program press remarks count. There is no official program metadata showing the reporter exchange was part of the Draw presentation. There is no source hierarchy provision selecting the pre-event reporter exchange over the formal Draw transcript for this market.\\n\\nPlaintiff argues ambiguity should favor Yes because Kalshi could have drafted a narrower rule. But this is a preponderance case about a challenged No resolution, not a penalty for every conceivable ambiguity. The ordinary reading of \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw\\\" is the draw program, not every public appearance immediately before it. The record's own labels preserve that ordinary line: \\\"Prior to\\\" on the Ronaldo source; \\\"Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing\\\" on the formal source; and a formal transcript that starts the draw and omits the strike.\\n\\nWeight and provenance also favor the defense on the decisive issue. PX-5 is official and useful, but it authenticates a pre-event reporter exchange. DX-2 is a captured formal transcript extraction from the source class identified in PX-4; its absence finding is limited but material. PX-4 was initially only a note that the formal page existed and could not be retrieved. We have now retrieved and searched it. The adverse check therefore confirms, rather than merely speculates, that the formal drawing transcript does not carry plaintiff's Ronaldo mention.\\n\\nThe council should resolve the proposition against plaintiff. The record shows Trump said Ronaldo before the FIFA World Cup Draw in an event-linked reporter exchange. It does not show he said Ronaldo during the FIFA World Cup Draw. On this market wording and these terms, the challenged No resolution should stand.\\n\\nRebuttals:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, defendant’s new formal-transcript extraction proves less than defendant needs.\\n\\nPlaintiff accepts the narrow fact defendant has now preserved: the Roll Call/Factba.se formal drawing-program extraction contains no “Ronaldo” or “Messi.” That is why plaintiff did not build the case on a formal-stage mention. The proposition instead asks whether the market wording and mention terms clearly excluded Trump’s public, official, event-linked remarks at the venue immediately before the formal program. Defendant has not supplied that exclusion.\\n\\nDefendant’s argument treats the title “Prior to the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw” as if “prior to” automatically means outside the Kalshi market’s event period. But PX-1 does not say “formal transcript only,” “after the draw host begins,” “after 00:00:50,” or “excluding press availability at the venue.” It asks what Trump would say “during the FIFA World Cup Draw.” The source label tells us sequence; it does not tell us the market’s legal boundary.\\n\\nDX-2 actually illustrates why defendant’s bright line is chosen after the fact. In defendant’s own formal extraction, the page begins before the mechanical draw: Mark Carney speaks at 00:00:00, and Infantino says at 00:00:50, “we are now going to do the draw.” If “during the FIFA World Cup Draw” can include ceremony and preamble on the formal page before the draw itself begins, then the phrase is not self-defining down to a single moment or transcript. The question is what the market clearly specified. It did not specify defendant’s transcript-only rule.\\n\\nThe terms do not fill that gap for defendant. PX-3 excludes hidden categories such as rehearsals, sound checks, unofficial recordings, and behind-the-scenes content unless officially published as part of the period. PX-2 and PX-5 are not those categories. PX-5 is an official GovInfo/OFR presidential transcript, published with source metadata, at 11:13 a.m. at the Kennedy Center, with FIFA’s president present and the World Cup Draw repeatedly discussed. That gives the Ronaldo mentions strong provenance and an event connection; it does not make them informal backstage chatter.\\n\\nDefendant says plaintiff needs a bridge. The bridge is the market text plus the terms’ failure to draw the narrow line defendant proposes. A No resolution can stand only if the contract fairly told traders that “during the FIFA World Cup Draw” meant only the separate formal-program transcript. On this record, the more likely reading is broader: public, official remarks at the venue, immediately tied to and immediately preceding the World Cup Draw program, were within the event-linked period unless clearly excluded.\\n\\nSo DX-2 narrows one factual issue but does not decide the case. It shows no formal-stage Ronaldo mention. It does not show that the market excluded the official pre-program event remarks where Trump did say Ronaldo. Under the preponderance standard, the Yes resolution remains the fair one.\\n\\nSurrebuttals:\\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff’s rebuttal usefully narrows the dispute. Plaintiff accepts that the formal Roll Call/Factba.se drawing transcript contains no “Ronaldo” or “Messi.” So the case remains entirely about whether a separate reporter exchange titled “Prior to the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw” should be treated as inside the market period.\\n\\nPlaintiff says “prior to” is only sequence, not legal boundary. But sequence is exactly what the market phrase makes material. The contract asks what Trump would say “during the FIFA World Cup Draw.” A source-agency title identifying the Ronaldo transcript as an exchange with reporters prior to that Draw is not a stray label; it is the best record description of when and what that source is. Plaintiff cannot convert that source into the event itself by saying the market failed to list every excluded pre-event setting.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s formal-preamble point also does not carry the burden. Yes, the formal transcript begins before the mechanical ball selection, and Infantino says at 00:00:50 that “we are now going to do the draw.” But that supports the defense distinction. A host’s preamble inside the formal drawing transcript is part of the program. A separate press exchange, separately titled and sourced as prior to the Draw, is not made part of the program simply because it happened nearby and discussed the same event.\\n\\nNor does official publication settle the issue. PX-5 strengthens provenance: Trump did say Ronaldo in an official public transcript. But provenance answers whether the words were said, not whether they were said during the market’s specified event. The terms require both: the word by the entity, and the word during the time period. Plaintiff has the first element. The second is still missing.\\n\\nThe remaining bridge plaintiff proposes is essentially: public, official, event-linked, and not expressly excluded. That is not enough under a preponderance standard when the same record supplies a cleaner boundary: the Ronaldo source is prior to the Draw, and the formal Draw source omits the strike. The challenged No resolution should stand.\\n\\nClosings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the record has narrowed to one real issue.\\n\\nThe word is proven. The market page identifies the strike as “Ronaldo” and the challenged resolution as No. The case-packet transcript and the GovInfo/OFR excerpt prove that Trump said “Ronaldo” as a standalone word in public remarks at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center, in a World Cup Draw setting, with FIFA President Infantino present, and amid repeated discussion of the Draw, the Kennedy Center, ticket sales, the audience, and the imminent event. That is strong provenance: GovInfo, NARA/OFR, DCPD202501162, matching the packet source and note.\\n\\nDefendant has also proved its best fact. The Roll Call/Factba.se formal-program extraction does not contain “Ronaldo” or “Messi.” Plaintiff does not ask you to find otherwise. If the market had said “only the formal drawing transcript,” defendant would win. But that is not the market traders saw.\\n\\nThe market asked: “What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?” It did not say “during the formal transcript only,” “after the host announces the draw has begun,” “excluding public press remarks at the venue,” or “excluding remarks immediately before the program.” The governing terms do not add that limitation. They define words used by the entity during the time period, allow event/context time periods, and exclude categories such as rehearsals, sound checks, behind-the-scenes content, and unofficial recordings. Plaintiff’s source is none of those. It is an official public presidential transcript of event-linked remarks at the venue.\\n\\nDefendant’s formal extraction shows why a bright line cannot simply be assumed. Even on that page, before balls are drawn, there is ceremony, introduction, and Infantino saying “we are now going to do the draw.” Event boundaries are not self-defining. The question is whether Kalshi clearly chose defendant’s narrower boundary. The record contains no such choice.\\n\\nSo the burden is met. More likely than not, a reasonable reading of the market and terms includes Trump’s official, public, venue-based remarks immediately tied to the World Cup Draw. The strongest contrary evidence proves only that a narrower formal transcript omits the strike. It does not prove the contract excluded the remarks where the strike was actually said.\\n\\nThe challenged No resolution should be overturned. The strike “Ronaldo” should resolve Yes.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff’s closing concedes the decisive factual split: the formal World Cup Drawing transcript contains no “Ronaldo” or “Messi.” The only Ronaldo evidence is the separate official transcript titled “Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw.”\\n\\nThat is enough to decide the case. The market did not ask what Trump would say at the Kennedy Center, on World Cup Draw day, in public presidential remarks, or in event-linked press availability. It asked what Trump would say “during the FIFA World Cup Draw.” The terms require the word to be used by the entity during the specified time period. Plaintiff has proven the word and the speaker. It has not proven the time period.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s strongest point is that the market did not expressly say “formal transcript only” or “exclude pre-program remarks.” But plaintiff has the burden. A challenged No resolution does not become Yes merely because the contract could have been even more verbose. The record must make it more likely than not that the pre-event reporter exchange was inside the market period. The record does the opposite.\\n\\nThe source labels matter. PX-2 and PX-5 are official and probative, but they are official proof of remarks prior to the Draw. The formal Roll Call/Factba.se extraction is the source for Trump’s formal attendance at the FIFA World Cup Drawing; it begins the program, includes the draw presentation, and omits the strike. Plaintiff’s theory asks you to treat a separate prior reporter exchange as “during” the Draw even though the formal Draw source exists and does not contain the word.\\n\\nThe terms do not collapse that distinction. They recognize event/context time periods and official presentation content, but they still require the word to occur during the chosen time period. Official publication proves provenance. Event connection proves relevance. Neither proves inclusion. A public official transcript can be accurately preserved and still be outside the market window if it is, as titled, prior to the event.\\n\\nSo the fair synthesis is narrow and grounded: Trump said Ronaldo in event-linked public remarks before the FIFA World Cup Draw; Trump did not say Ronaldo in the formal drawing transcript preserved in this record; and no admitted market term or source-chain evidence bridges the pre-event exchange into the market’s “during the FIFA World Cup Draw” period.\\n\\nUnder the preponderance standard, plaintiff has not carried the proposition. The challenged No resolution should stand.\\n\\nExhibits:\\n[plaintiff] PX-1 Market page and challenged resolution\\nMarket URL: https://kalshi.com/markets/kxtrumpmentionb/trump-mention-b/kxtrumpmentionb-25dec06\\n\\nPublic market title: What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\n\\nContract family: PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION\\n\\nStrike at issue: Ronaldo\\n\\nChallenged resolution: No\\n\\nRequested resolution: Yes\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-2 Pre-event reporter exchange transcript\\nRemarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\nDecember 05, 2025\\n\\n[The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\\nThe President. It's a great honor to be here. Gianni has done a fantastic job. We're setting records—[inaudible].\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. Well, I think so. They have a little bit of a shot. Pretty stiff competition. But I would say they would have a small chance.\\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize\\nQ. [Inaudible]—win the FIFA Peace Award?\\nThe President. Well, it would be an honor.\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\nQ. Will you root for some selection? Will you root for someone?\\nThe President. Well, I root for a lot of countries, but in this case, I'll be rooting for the U.S.A. [Laughter]\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. That's great. That's great. We really love it.\\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize\\nQ. Mr. President, have you been told that you are going to receive the inaugural peace prize today——\\nThe President. I have not——\\nQ. ——from FIFA?\\nThe President. I have not been told. There's a rumor about it, but I have not been told. That would be a great honor, and I'm a big fan of Gianni, as you know.\\nQ. What can fans expect——\\nQ. Are you hoping to receive that?\\nThe President. Excuse me.\\nQ. Are you hoping to receive the peace prize?\\nThe President. Well, I don't like to say \\\"hope,\\\" but it would be a great honor.\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. What can fans expect of, like, the World Cup in the U.S.?\\nThe President. I think it's going to be fantastic. We've set every record you can set.\\nQ. What are you telling people who are worried——\\nFédération Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) President Giovanni V. Infantino\\nQ. [Inaudible]—friend Gianni—[inaudible]—a word about him?\\nThe President. I think he has done a fantastic job.\\nThe President's Schedule\\nQ. Are you going to be meeting with the President of Mexico today and the——\\nThe President. We might. Yes.\\nQ. ——Prime Minister of Canada as well?\\nThe President. I might. I might do that.\\nQ. Will you be discussing immigration and trade with them?\\nThe President. Yes, we'll be discussing.\\n[At this point, the President and Mr. Infantino posed for photographs.]\\nThe President. Thank you, everybody.\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event/John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts\\nQ. Mr. President, what do you think about the crowd?\\nThe President. Oh, look, the new star—[inaudible].\\nCongratulations.\\nQ. Thank you.\\nThe President. You're the new star of television and Fox.\\nQ. Thank you. How are you doing, Mr. President?\\nThe President. I'm doing very well.\\nQ. What do you think about the crowd here?\\nThe President. I think the crowd is great, and I think the building is great. We've made a lot of improvements over the last 6 months. Taking—the Kennedy Center was in very bad shape. Now it's getting to be really good. And in 6 months, it's going to be incredible with the improvements we've made.\\nQ. The first time for the U.S. to host since the nineties.\\nThe President. Right.\\nQ. Are you ready for it?\\nThe President. I'm ready for it, and they're ready for it. And Gianni, who you know——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——has done a fantastic job with FIFA. And we're looking to have—you know, we're set—we have already set records for tickets sales. I don't think there's ever been anything like it in any sport. And so, I want to congratulate you.\\nMr. Infantino. Thank you.\\nThe President. I don't even have to wait. But major records have been set.\\nHow are you?\\nQ. Good, how are you, sir?\\nThe President. Nice to see you.\\nQ. Today it's not football—American football. It's soccer. It's——\\nThe President. Right.\\nQ. ——the big event of soccer.\\nThe President. That's right. That's right.\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\nQ. So can you tell me about this big day today?\\nThe President. It's just a big day, and it's a great sport. And it really is coming to America. And never—nobody ever thought a thing like this could happen. And I'm very happy to say that we've already set the alltime record on ticket sales long before the first ball is kicked. Right?\\nMr. Infantino. A hundred percent. One hundred percent.\\n2026 World Cup Host Cities\\nQ. You've had some concerns about crime in American cities, some of the cities that will be hosting. Have they remedied that for you? Are you still considering maybe asking FIFA to move some of those cities?\\nThe President. No, I don't want to do that. But I will tell you, if they do have a problem, by the time we get there, we'll take care of that problem. We can solve that problem.\\nI've proven that in DC and everywhere else we went, so we'll take care of that very easily. So, if they have a problem, hopefully, they'll let us know that, and we will solve any problem.\\nOkay? Thank you.\\nQ. Thank you so much.\\nMr. Infantino. All right, thank you so much.\\nQ. Thank you, Mr. President.\\nQ. Thank you. Appreciate it.\\nThe President. Congratulations.\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. Mr. President, Brazilian television. America will be hosting the World Cup and the Olympics in 2 years. How important it is—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. I think very. It's a great honor. I think Gianni is doing a phenomenal job. We've set every record on ticket sales. It's been really fantastic. But Gianni has done an unbelievable job with FIFA.\\nThe President's Experience With Soccer\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. He was a great—not only that. I got to see a man name Pelé play—right?—that tells you how old I am—when he was on the Cosmos. Do you remember that a long time ago? And it was quite a treat. That was quite an event. And he was—not only was he playing, he was great. He scored two goals, I think. And so, I was one of the few who got to see Pelé, and I assume he is one of your alltime greats. Right?\\nMr. Infantino. Definitely.\\nThe President. So I got to see him.\\nThe President's Favorite World Cup Competitor\\nQ. Do you have some favorite teams for World Cup?\\nThe President. Well, I have a favorite. It's the U.S.A. [Laughter] I don't know what their chances are, Gianni, but maybe the U.S.A. is the——\\nMr. Infantino. They're getting better and better, actually.\\nThe President. I think they'll do well.\\nMr. Infantino. They are getting better and better.\\nThe President. I think they'll do well.\\nThank you very much, everybody.\\nQ. Thank you so much.\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. Mr. President, World Cup in America just means—[inaudible]. So what do you expect from this World Cup?\\nThe President. [Inaudible]—record business and only in the United States, but we're also doing record ticket sales with FIFA. And they've already bought—beat their highest record. And we—you know, this a long time before the first ball is kicked. You've sold more tickets than they've ever done before, and better pricing than they've ever gotten before. It's a tremendous success. And it's an honor. And Gianni has done a phenomenal job with FIFA.\\nQ. [Inaudible]—ever?\\nThe President. I think so. I think it's going to be—I mean, ideally, you want to see that every year. Every 4 years, it gets bigger and better. I think we have set every record in the book. We're very happy about it.\\nThank you.\\nThe President's Favorite World Cup Competitor\\nQ. [Inaudible]—part of America. Who are you going to support as well?\\nThe President. Well, I think I have to support U.S.A. Otherwise, I'd be in trouble. I wouldn't be President for long.\\nMr. Infantino. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. [Inaudible]—but you have a lot of great teams. You're going to have a lot of great teams.\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\\\"football,\\\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\\n2026 World Cup Draw/Ticket Sales for World Cup\\nQ. How does it feel to be part of this amazing event? And obviously, your being a part of participating in all the—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. The President of Mexico is here, and she's doing a very good job. She's a good woman, very, very excellent job. It's an honor, and we're setting every record, and you're helping us set those records.\\nMr. Infantino. And we will do it.\\nThe President. You know, Mexico and Canada are helping us set those records. But as you know, we have a record in ticket sales already, long before the first ball is kicked, and we're going to do great.\\nI think that Gianni—as you know, he's the head, and he has done a fantastic job.\\nU.S. Cooperation With Mexico and Canada\\nQ. And how is the biggest challenge being three countries?\\nThe President. Well, I think that—do you mean for the three countries?\\nWell, they've gotten together really well, I mean.\\nMr. Infantino. All right.\\nThe President. They're getting along very well.\\nMr. Infantino. Collaboration is fantastic between the three.\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer/2026 World Cup\\nQ. And you like soccer?\\nThe President. I do. I like it. I like it more and more.\\nQ. Yes?\\nThe President. I like it. It's growing in this country—very, really—I mean, someday, maybe it's going to be bigger than anything else.\\nMr. Infantino. We'll have to become number one.\\nThe President. I will say this——\\nMr. Infantino. Definitely.\\nThe President. ——the ticket sales——\\nQ. Definitely will happen.\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. Ticket sales are bigger than anything we have ever done in the history of the country, in terms of sports.\\nMr. Infantino. For certain.\\nQ. And the audience is going to be huge.\\nThe President. The audience is going to be tremendous.\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. Yes.\\nMr. Infantino. Six billion people.\\nThe President. [Inaudible]\\nQ. Six billion? That's amazing.\\nMr. Infantino. Six billion people.\\nAnd today, one billion.\\nQ. Wow.\\nMr. Infantino. [Inaudible]\\nQ. Enjoy show time. Thank you so much.\\nThe President. [Inaudible]\\nQ. Mr. President, how are you? Just a quick—[inaudible].\\nQ. This is for Telemundo.\\nThe President. How are you?\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\nQ. Hello, Mr. President. How are you? This for Telemundo.\\nThe President. How are you? Good.\\nQ. How are you?\\nThe President. Very good. Thank you.\\nQ. How does it feel to have the most important event of sports—that global—in the U.S.?\\nThe President. Well, we do. And right at the Kennedy Center. I'm Chairman of the Kennedy Center. And I hear the Kennedy Center is doing a very good job, so it feels great. Really good.\\nAnd Telemundo is doing a good job, too. Thank you.\\nQ. Thank you.\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. What is the significance of hosting the FIFA World Cup this year?\\nThe President. It's a—in terms of sports, I would say the ultimate. There is no sport like this. It's the biggest sport in the world. And we are setting every record. You know, our ticket sales have gone and set every—every sport—no matter what it is, we've set the record. So—and every though it's very early, there's no ball being kicked yet, but we've already set a ticket sales record.\\nArgentina National Team\\nQ. How do you see Argentinean team for this World Cup?\\nThe President. Well, I love Argentina. And your President is doing a very good job, as you know. Milei. You know that right? It's make Argentina great again. MAGA.\\nQ. And——\\nU.S. National Team\\nQ. Do you think the States are building a powerful team for next year?\\nThe President. Who?\\nQ. The States.\\nThe President. Oh, yes. Sure. I—you're going to have a lot of powerful teams. Everybody has a lot of powerful teams, but you're going to have a lot of great teams. [Inaudible]\\nU.S. Role in Hosting the 2026 World Cup\\nQ. Mr. President, what does it mean for you guys to host the World Cup right here in the U.S.?\\nThe President. I'm honored to host it. It's a great honor. I mean, it's turned out to be bigger than we thought. We're setting a record for ticket sales, the likes of which no sport has ever seen before.\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\\nThe President. But they have a little more speed.\\nBut no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\\nPopularity of Soccer in Latin America\\nQ. Mr. President, a message for the Latin America and soccer fans?\\nThe President. Yes, I am. And Latin America is great. And they have great soccer. So, good luck in the matches.\\n[A reporter asked a question in Spanish, which was translated by an interpreter as follows.]\\nU.S. Visas for World Cup Ticketholders\\nQ. Who is going to be in—[inaudible]—about these visas for the—these fans that want to come here to the World Cup?\\nThe President. Well, we're going to make it very easy for them. We're working on that right now. We're going to make it very easy. It's going to be a very easy process.\\nQ. Okay. Say, hi to Colombia over there.\\nThe President. Hello. Is that Colombia?\\nQ. Yes.\\nThe President. I love Colombia. Hello, Colombia. [Laughter]\\nQ. Okay. Okay. Muy bien.\\nThe President. So where are you from?\\nQ. Paraguay.\\nThe President. Oh.\\nQ. He's from Paraguay. Yes.\\nThe President. Very good. I love it. I—it's a beautiful country. We get along very well with them. We do a little trade deal with them, and they like us. And that's what's happening.\\nQ. Panama.\\nThe President. Where?\\nVery good. I like the canal. [Laughter] That canal is pretty good.\\n[A reporter spoke in Spanish; no translation was provided.]\\n2026 World Cup\\nThe President. What?\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. Well, it's going to be incredible. The event is going to be very good. Just this event alone—it's at the Kennedy Center. I see you have it fixed up perfectly.\\nMr. Infantino. It will set the tone.\\nThe President. Right? It's beautiful.\\nMr. Infantino. It's beautiful.\\nThe President. It's a beautiful place.\\nHave a good time.\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President.\\n[A reporter spoke in Spanish; no translation was provided.]\\nMr. Infantino. No, gracias. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. It's great.\\nJohn F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts/Renovation Work\\nQ. Mr. President, the U.S. press?\\nThe President. Thank you, everybody, very much. It's a great honor. This has been an honor for a lot of reasons. Number one, they've sold more tickets than any event has ever sold already—long before the kickoff.\\nAnd number two, we've done a lot of work at the Kennedy Center. It was falling apart, and now it's pretty much back. And we'll get it back within the next 4 or 5 months through construction, and—but you see the way it looks.\\nAnd Gianni is just telling me—who's done an incredible job, by the way. He's just telling, you know, how good a job we've done.\\nMr. Infantino. That's right.\\nThe President. You can look at the walls. The marble was broken. Everything was a mess. And we've really taken the Kennedy Center—a lot of people thought it was going to be ripped down, and we did just the opposite. So we've done a really great renovation job on it. And over the next 3, 4 months, it will be complete. And we're honored to have it here, and it's been—it's been very special.\\nWe've set a record on ticket sales, as you probably heard, already, even way before—long before the event itself. And we're working with Canada, and we're working with Mexico. And it's been a really spectacular—so far, it's been spectacular.\\nDaniel [Daniel Baldwin, One America News Network], do you have a question?\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. What are your expectations? You once said that the FIFA World Cup is an opportunity to put—a once-in-a-lifetime opportunity to put the greatness of the United States on display.\\nThe President. Well, I think—\\nQ. One billion eyeballs will be watching, Mr. President.\\nThe President. Yes, I—think——\\nQ. What will they here today?\\nThe President. Even today, I understand. I hear that, you know——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——I know we're a little late to get in there, but——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——that's okay.\\nMr. Infantino. They wait.\\nThe President. So all my friends, I guess they have to wait. They have no choice, right? [Laughter]\\nMr. Infantino. Yes, they wait.\\nThe President. But no, the numbers are incredible. I hear today's numbers are——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——very big. I hope CNN is covering this.\\nQ. One billion eyeballs.\\nMr. Infantino. Today, 1 billion eyeballs.\\nThe President. Today's numbers are very, very big.\\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize/The President's Foreign Policy\\nQ. We are covering it. And you're expected to get the FIFA Peace Prize, Mr. President. What would you say to people who say that prize might conflict with your pledge to strike Venezuela?\\nThe President. Well, I think the peace prize—I mean, I settled eight wars. I don't know that I'm getting it. I haven't been officially noticed. I've been hearing about a peace prize, and I'm here to represent our country in a different sense. But I can tell you, I did settle eight wars, and we have a ninth coming, but—which nobody has ever done before.\\nBut I want to really save lives. I don't need prizes. I need to save lives. And we're saving a lot of lives. And I've saved millions and millions of lives, and that's really what I want to do.\\nAnd I also want to run a great country. And the United States right now is the hottest country anywhere in the world. And 1 year ago, it was dead. We had a dead country, and now we have the hottest country anywhere in the world.\\nQ. Mr. President, will you——\\nThe President's Meeting With President Claudia Sheinbaum Pardo of Mexico and Prime Minister Mark Carney of Canada\\nQ. What are you going to discuss with Canada and Mexico, Mr.—what are you going to discuss with the leaders of Canada and Mexico?\\nThe President. Well, we're getting—we're going to meet with both. And we're getting along very well. You know, we're getting along very well. I don't know. I think we have a meeting set up for some time after the event.\\nQ. Will you discuss trade?\\nThe President. Yes, we'll discuss trade. We—get along very well.\\nThank you, everybody, very much.\\nQ. Will you pardon any other Honduran officials?\\nQ. Do you want them to keep trying to indict Ms. James?\\n\\nNOTE: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. In his remarks, he referred to Trey Yingst, chief foreign correspondent, Fox News Channel; Cristiano Ronaldo, forward for Saudi Pro League club Al-Nass and Portugal's national soccer team; and Lionel Messi, forward for Major League Soccer club Inter Miami and Argentina's national team. A reporter referred to New York State Attorney General Letitia James. The transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\n\\nSource URL: https://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/documents/remarks-exchange-with-reporters-prior-the-2026-federation-internationale-des-associations\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-3 PRESMENTION/NEWMENTION terms\\n                                         NEWMENTION\\n\\nScope: These rules shall apply to this contract.\\n\\nUnderlying: The Underlying for this Contract is words used by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nRevisions to the Underlying made after Expiration will not be accounted for in determining the\\nExpiration Value.\\n\\nSource Agency: The Source Agencies are \\u003csource\\u003e.\\n\\nType: The type of Contract is an Event Contract.\\n\\nIssuance: After the initial Contract, Contract iterations will be listed on an as-needed basis at\\nthe discretion of the Exchange and corresponding to the risk management needs of Members.\\n\\n\\u003centity\\u003e: \\u003centity\\u003e refers to the speaker, writer, performer, or communicator specified by the\\nExchange. This may include (but is not limited to): a specific named individual, multiple\\nindividuals specified using AND/OR logic, an individual identified by position or title, a group,\\nband, team or collective entity, a specified member or members of a group, an organization,\\ncompany, or institutional entity, or any combination of the aforementioned.\\n\\nWhen \\u003centity\\u003e is defined by a position or title, the Contract tracks whoever holds that position\\nduring \\u003ctime period\\u003e, even if the individual holding the position changes. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a\\nspecific named individual, the identity remains consistent throughout. Name changes (e.g.,\\nstage names, married names) do not create a new entity. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a group or\\norganization and the Contract does not specify particular members, any official\\ncommunication or statement by any member or designated spokesperson counts. When using\\nAND logic, all specified entities must independently say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e. When\\nusing OR logic, at least one of the specified entities must say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nThe Exchange may specify additional conditions such as “at least X members of” a group or\\n“the majority of” a group.\\n\\n\\u003csource\\u003e: \\u003csource\\u003e refers to a Source Agency or ordered collection of Source Agencies\\nspecified by the Exchange at the time of Contract listing, which will be incorporated into the\\nSource Agency hierarchy above and used to determine the occurrence of the Underlying.\\n\\u003csource\\u003e may refer to a singular agency, multiple agencies, an agency by distinguishing\\ncharacteristics, by category or type (e.g., “official government statistical body,” “primary wire\\nservice”), or any combination thereof. When multiple agencies are specified, they may be\\napplied in the hierarchical order designated by the Exchange if so specified, with the highest-\\nranked available and responsive agency taking precedence for purposes of determining the\\nExpiration Value. A lower-ranked agency shall only be consulted if all higher-ranked agencies\\nare unavailable, unresponsive, have not reported on the Underlying by the Expiration time, or\\nif the Exchange, in its sole discretion, determines that a higher-ranked agency’s reporting is\\nincomplete, erroneous, or otherwise insufficient to determine the Expiration Value. If \\u003csource\\u003e\\ndesignates multiple agencies without specifying a hierarchical order, the Exchange shall\\nresolve any conflict between reporting agencies at its sole discretion.\\n\\n\\u003cword\\u003e: \\u003cword\\u003e refers to the particular word or phrase potentially to be mentioned by\\n\\u003centity\\u003e. It may refer to a word being said a minimum number of times. It may also refer to\\none of multiple words/phrases, any of which are acceptable (e.g., “Doge/Dogecoin”).\\n\\f\\u003ctime period\\u003e: \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific range of time, event or discrete date and\\ntime specified by the Exchange. This may be defined by, but is not limited to: a specific event\\nor context (e.g., “during the State of the Union address”), exact dates or times, relative time\\nmarkers (e.g., “before July 1, 2027,” “in Q1 2026”), event-based periods (e.g., “during any\\ncampaign rally in October 2026,” “during the awards ceremony”), and broader intervals (e.g.,\\n“Q1–Q2 2027,” “January–March 2026”).\\n\\nUnless stated otherwise, “Between” is inclusive of both endpoints, while “before” and “after”\\nexclude the specified date. \\u003ctime period\\u003e may also refer to “Any” or “None”, to multiple dates\\n(even if non-consecutive), or to a singular and discrete date or time.\\n\\nWhen \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event (such as an address, speech, performance, or\\nbroadcast), the Exchange may specify what is included, including whether it includes both live\\nand pre-recorded segments (including whether advertisements are included). Where a\\ntimezone is not specified, ET is assumed.\\n\\n\\nPayout Criterion: The Payout Criterion for the Contract encompasses the Expiration Values that\\n\\u003cword\\u003e is said by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n\\n\\nThe word must appear as a distinct, standalone unit, not buried inside another word. Plural\\nand possessive noun forms count. Other grammatical changes (tense, conjugation, derivation)\\ndo not. If \\u003cword\\u003e appears separated from other words by a space or hyphen or in a\\ncompound form with a space or hyphen, it counts. If \\u003cword\\u003e is fused into a single\\nunhyphenated word, it does not count.\\n\\nIf \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled, and the market contains a\\nstrike stating “Event does not qualify/occur”, such a strike shall resolve “Yes” and all others\\n“No”. If \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled but such strikes are NOT\\nlisted, the Contracts will resolve to the last fair price determined at the discretion of the\\nExchange. If the event is postponed, and such a postponement is announced by the end of the\\nfollowing calendar day to be rescheduled to a time within 14 calendar days, the markets shall\\nremain open. If the event captured in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast, the\\nExchange may keep the market open for 24 hours for the release of an official recording.\\nFurther granular details on conditions for these Contracts is available below.\\n\\nAdditional clarification(s):\\n\\n     Possessive noun forms of \\u003cword\\u003e, plurals, and possessive plural noun forms are\\n     INCLUDED:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigrants” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Egg” → “eggs’ shells” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Russia” → “Russia’s” counts, “Russian” does not\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e exists only in adjective form, no plural form exists:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Economic” → “Economics” does not count (“Economic” is an adjective\\n          for which “Economics” is not a plural)\\n     Plural nouns occurring within proper nouns and noun phrases are included:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Cat” → “Cats the musical” counts\\n\\f    Grammatical variations beyond plurals/possessives are NOT included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigration” does NOT count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Run” → “Running” or “Ran” do NOT count\\n    When \\u003cword\\u003e specifies a plural form, the singular does NOT count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Veterans” → “Veteran” does NOT count\\n    Words that are spelled the same as the plural form of \\u003cword\\u003e (if such exists) but are\\n    themselves not a plural noun are included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Wind” → “Winds up the clock” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Border” → “The United States has strong borders” counts\\n    Open compounds (words separated by spaces) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fire station” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “couch” → “couch potato” counts\\n    Hyphenated compounds (words connected by hyphens) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Palestine” → “pro-Palestine” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fat” → “non-fat” counts\\n    Closed compounds (single word, no spaces/hyphens) do not count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire” does not count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firefighter” does not count\\n    Multi-word \\u003cword\\u003e in larger constructions: When \\u003cword\\u003e is a multi-word phrase\\n    appearing within a hyphenated construction, it counts only if \\u003cword\\u003e appears as a\\n    complete, unmodified element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “New York” → “New York-based” counts (complete element)\\n    Portmanteaus (words blended from two words where parts of each are combined) are\\n    NOT included unless the portmanteau clearly contains \\u003cword\\u003e as a distinct, unaltered\\n    element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “MAGA” → “MAGA-nificent” counts (MAGA appears as distinct element)\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “magnificent” → “MAGA-nificent” does NOT count (portmanteau blend)\\n\\nDictionary determination: Both the Merriam-Webster Dictionary (available online) AND the\\nOxford English Dictionary shall be used to determine compound type and/or conventional\\nspelling patterns. Inclusion in either dictionary as an open or hyphenated compound shall\\nsatisfy the Payout Criterion. If neither provides clarity (or the word is not included),\\ndetermination is based on whether written as single unit (closed/doesn’t count) vs. spaces or\\nhyphens (open or hyphenated/counts) and/or context and previous usage.\\n\\nPHONETIC EQUIVALENCIES\\n\\n    Homophones (same sound, different spelling) do not count:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “write” → “right” does not count\\n    Homonyms and homographs (same spelling) COUNT regardless of meaning or\\n    pronunciation:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “bass” → both “bass guitar” and “bass fishing” count\\n    Proper and common nouns are treated identically:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Apple” → both “Apple Inc.” and “apple” (fruit) count\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Will” → both “Will Smith” and “I will go” count\\n    Minor unintentional mispronunciations COUNT if context makes intent clear:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Mamdani” → “Mandani” counts\\n    Severe mispronunciations that make \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable do NOT count.\\n    Trademarked spellings do not count, even when pronounced identically, unless the word\\n\\fitself is the same:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “lift” → “Lyft” (pronounced “lift”) does not count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “uber” → “Uber” counts\\nWords with non-standard transliteration to English count within reason, provided they are\\nphonetically equivalent:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Zelensky” → any of “Zelenski,” “Zelenskii,” “Zelensky,” or “Zelenskiy”\\n      count if pronounced equivalently\\nContractions do not count for their constituent words unless otherwise explicitly specified\\nby the Exchange:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “not” → “won’t,” “can’t,” “don’t,” “isn’t” do not count\\nNumbers spoken as words COUNT, when spoken exactly (not part of a larger number):\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “five” → saying “five” or reading “$5” aloud as “five dollars” counts,\\n      saying “five hundred” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “410” → “four hundred ten”, “four one zero” or “four ten” counts\\nOrdinals COUNT when \\u003cword\\u003e is written numerically OR a phrase that includes a\\nnumber:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “January 6” → “January 6th” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “3” (written numerically) → “3rd” (spoken as “third”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Eight War” → “8 Wars” and “Eighth War” will count\\nCardinal and ordinal number words are distinct:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “one” → “first” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “first” → “one” does NOT count\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count when pronunciation or letter-by-letter spelling\\nmatches \\u003cword\\u003e:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “NASA” (pronounced “NAH-suh”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “N-A-S-A” (spelled out) counts\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count as \\u003cword\\u003e when pronounced as the full word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Doctor” → “Dr.” (pronounced “Doctor”) counts\\nExpanded forms of acronyms do NOT count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “AI” → “artificial intelligence” does not count\\nWords in foreign languages do NOT count unless they are perfect cognates with an\\nEnglish word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fuego” (Spanish) does NOT count\\nEnglish words within foreign sentences count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “policy” → “Nuestra policy es clara” counts\\n\\u003cword\\u003e in organization/company names counts:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Securities” → “Bank of America Securities” counts\\nWords in URLs, emails, handles, and hashtags (exclusive of domain structure, email\\nprovider or symbols) are treated as compounds when spoken as complete words, with the\\ntype of compound subject to aforementioned rules:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firestation.com” pronounced “fire station dot com” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire.com” pronounced “wildfire dot com” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “apple” → “apple.com” pronounced “apple dot com” does count\\n      When presented in URL, email, handle, or hashtag form, \\u003cword\\u003e shall be treated as\\n      a compound, not a multi-word word\\nSung, rapped, or poetic words COUNT if phonetically recognizable:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “money” → “moneyyy” (extended in rap) counts\\n      Extreme distortion making \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable does NOT count.\\nPhonetic alphabet spelling (“Foxtrot India Romeo Echo” for “FIRE”) does NOT count.\\n\\fCANCELLATIONS AND DELAYS\\n\\n   The Exchange may list an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike for any Contract. If listed,\\n   such a strike refers to the structural conditions of the market, and is NOT adjudicated as a\\n   \\u003cword\\u003e needing to be said by or validated by having been said by \\u003centity\\u003e. If listed, this\\n   strike resolves to “Yes” whenever the event fails to occur or qualify under the Payout\\n   Criterion, or any other circumstance prevents normal resolution.\\n   If no such strike is listed, and \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, the following rules\\n   apply if the event is cancelled, postponed, rescheduled, or materially altered (including\\n   being closed to press) such that no video is released within one calendar day of the\\n   original start time of the event:\\n         If the event is cancelled, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price determined in\\n         the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         If the event is postponed or rescheduled, the outcome depends on whether a new\\n         date is publicly announced within one calendar day (i.e. if the event was scheduled\\n         to begin on Monday, any time up to 11:59PM on Tuesday falls within this period) of\\n         the originally scheduled start time:\\n               If no new date is announced within one calendar day, the Contract will resolve\\n               to the last fair price determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n               If a new date is announced within one calendar day, the outcome depends on\\n               when the rescheduled event is set to occur:\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls within fourteen (14) calendar days of the\\n                     originally scheduled date, the Contract shall remain open and \\u003cword\\u003e\\n                     stated during the rescheduled event will count.\\n                           The fourteen-day window begins at 12:00 AM ET on the originally\\n                           scheduled date and ends at 11:59 PM ET fourteen days later, unless\\n                           an alternate timezone is explicitly specified.\\n                           Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the State of the Union on January\\n                           15, 2026” rescheduled to January 20, 2026 → words spoken during\\n                           the rescheduled address count.\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls more than fourteen (14) calendar days after\\n                     the originally scheduled date, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price\\n                     determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         Any Contract that cannot be resolved through the Source Agency hierarchy will\\n         instead be settled at the Last Fair Price. The Exchange will disclose the methodology\\n         used to determine the Last Fair Price (e.g., Last Traded Price, Time-Weighted\\n         Average Price) at the time of Issuance.\\n         If an event begins but is interrupted, abbreviated, or ends prematurely, words\\n         stated by \\u003centity\\u003e during the portion of the event that did occur will count and the\\n         market will otherwise resolve.\\n   If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window but the venue, format, or medium\\n   changes (e.g., moved to a different location, changed from in-person to virtual (with the\\n   exception of being closed to press)), words stated during the event will count.\\n   Special condition: Across both cases, whether an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike is\\n   listed or not, if the event specified as or in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast (or\\n   relayed as such) but the live stream/broadcast does not occur, the Exchange will instead\\n   use an officially released recording as the Underlying, and may delay resolution by up to\\n   one calendar day to allow for the release of such a recording.\\n\\f          If partial snippets are released, Contracts on words that do not appear will be\\n          resolved to last fair price, and Contracts on those that do will be resolved to “Yes”.\\n          If no recording is released, the relevant outcomes triggered by the\\n          presence/absence of an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike shall occur as outlined\\n          above.\\n\\nTECHNICAL DETAILS (UNLESS OTHERWISE SPECIFIED)\\n\\n     When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, pre-recorded content broadcast,\\n     streamed, or published as part of that event is included if presented as part of the official\\n     presentation.\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the concert” with pre-recorded video interlude\\n          where entity speaks → words from interlude count\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the television appearance” with pre-taped\\n          segment aired during broadcast → words from segment count\\n     Behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are NOT\\n     included unless officially broadcast or published as part of \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n     Subtitles and captions that display \\u003cword\\u003e on screen but are not spoken aloud by\\n     \\u003centity\\u003e do NOT count.\\n     Sign language interpretation or usage by entity does NOT count as saying \\u003cword\\u003e unless\\n     the Contract explicitly specifies that sign language counts.\\n     Text that entity displays on screen (presentation slides, teleprompter visible to audience,\\n     signatures) does NOT count unless entity reads it aloud.\\n     Content generated by AI, deepfakes, or synthetic voice technology impersonating entity\\n     does NOT count unless the synthetic content is officially commissioned, authorized, or\\n     published by entity, OR the Contract explicitly specifies that AI-generated content counts.\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e is muted due to technical failure or censorship it shall not count unless\\n     corroborating contextual evidence (including surrounding speech, or an official\\n     uncensored recording or transcript) confirms that \\u003centity\\u003e specifically uttered \\u003cword\\u003e\\n     during the muted period.\\n\\nMinimum Tick: The Minimum Tick size for the Contract shall be $0.01.\\n\\nPosition Accountability Level: The Position Accountability Level for the Contract shall be\\n$25,000 per strike, per Member.\\n\\nLast Trading Date: The Last Trading Date of the Contract will be the Expiration Date. The Last\\nTrading Time will be the Expiration time.\\n\\nSettlement Date: The Settlement Date of the Contract shall be no later than the day after the\\nExpiration Date, unless the Market Outcome is under review pursuant to Rule 7.1.\\n\\nExpiration Date: When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event: The latest Expiration Date of\\nthe Contract shall be fourteen (14) calendar days after the originally scheduled date of the\\nevent. If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window, expiration will be moved to an\\nearlier date and time in accordance with Rule 7.2. When \\u003ctime period\\u003e is defined by specific\\ndates: The latest Expiration Date of the Contract shall be two weeks after the end of \\u003ctime\\nperiod\\u003e. If an event described in the Payout Criterion occurs and a consensus has been\\nreached on all terms, then expiration will be moved to an earlier date and time in accordance\\nwith Rule 7.2.\\n\\fExpiration time: The Expiration time of the Contract shall be 10:00 AM ET.\\n\\nSettlement Value: The Settlement Value for this Contract is $1.00.\\n\\nExpiration Value: The Expiration Value is the value of the Underlying as documented by the\\nSource Agency on the Expiration Date at the Expiration time.\\n\\nContingencies: Before Settlement, Kalshi may, at its sole discretion, initiate the Market\\nOutcome Review Process pursuant to Rule 7.1 of the Rulebook. If an Expiration Value cannot\\nbe determined on the Expiration Date, Kalshi has the right to determine payouts pursuant to\\nRule 7.1 in the Rulebook.\\n\\f\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-4 Formal draw archive note\\nSource checked: Roll Call / Factba.se archive\\n\\nArchive title: Remarks: Donald Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing in Washington - December 5, 2025\\n\\nArchive URL: https://rollcall.com/factbase/trump/transcript/donald-trump-remarks-fifa-world-cup-drawing-december-5-2025/\\n\\nWhat this file establishes:\\n\\nThere is a separate archived transcript page for Trump's formal attendance remarks at the draw.\\n\\nWhat this file does not establish:\\n\\nThis session could not retrieve the full transcript text from that archive.  The page is password-protected.  This example therefore does not claim, from local files alone, whether the formal program transcript does or does not contain the word \\\"Ronaldo.\\\"\\n\\nWhy this matters:\\n\\nThe complaint does not need to prove that the formal program omitted the strike.  It needs to show that Trump said \\\"Ronaldo\\\" in event-linked remarks and that the market boundary reasonably includes those remarks.  The formal archive remains relevant because it marks the distinction between the pre-event reporter exchange and the formal program.\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-5 GovInfo official transcript excerpt and metadata\\nSource: GovInfo, DCPD202501162, Office of the Federal Register / National Archives and Records Administration.\\nURL: https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/DCPD-202501162/html/DCPD-202501162.htm\\nTitle: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\nEvent date: December 5, 2025.\\n\\nRelevant extracted page text:\\n\\\"Administration of Donald J. Trump, 2025\\\"\\n\\\"Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw December 5, 2025\\\"\\n\\\"[The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\\\"\\n\\nUnder the section \\\"The President's Interest in Soccer\\\":\\n\\\"Q. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\\\"\\n\\\"The President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\\\\\\\"football,\\\\\\\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\\\"\\n\\\"Thank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\\\"\\n\\nAdditional relevant extracted page text:\\n\\\"The President's Interest in Soccer\\\"\\n\\\"Q. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\\\"\\n\\\"The President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\\\"\\n\\\"Mr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\\\"\\n\\\"The President. But they have a little more speed. But no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\\\"\\n\\nGovInfo note:\\n\\\"NOTE: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. In his remarks, he referred to Trey Yingst, chief foreign correspondent, Fox News Channel; Cristiano Ronaldo, forward for Saudi Pro League club Al-Nass and Portugal's national soccer team; and Lionel Messi, forward for Major League Soccer club Inter Miami and Argentina's national team. A reporter referred to New York State Attorney General Letitia James. The transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\\"\\n\\nGovInfo content details page also identifies category \\\"Interviews With the News Media : Exchanges with reporters, Washington, DC,\\\" subjects including \\\"Federation Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) World Cup,\\\" \\\"John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts,\\\" and \\\"Soccer,\\\" and names including \\\"Ronaldo, Cristiano\\\" and \\\"Messi, Lionel.\\\"\\n\\n[defendant] DX-1 Market wording and challenged resolution\\nMarket URL: https://kalshi.com/markets/kxtrumpmentionb/trump-mention-b/kxtrumpmentionb-25dec06\\n\\nPublic market title: What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\n\\nContract family: PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION\\n\\nStrike at issue: Ronaldo\\n\\nChallenged resolution: No\\n\\nRequested resolution: Yes\\n\\n\\n[defendant] DX-2 Pre-event reporter exchange transcript\\nRemarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\nDecember 05, 2025\\n\\n[The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\\nThe President. It's a great honor to be here. Gianni has done a fantastic job. We're setting records—[inaudible].\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. Well, I think so. They have a little bit of a shot. Pretty stiff competition. But I would say they would have a small chance.\\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize\\nQ. [Inaudible]—win the FIFA Peace Award?\\nThe President. Well, it would be an honor.\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\nQ. Will you root for some selection? Will you root for someone?\\nThe President. Well, I root for a lot of countries, but in this case, I'll be rooting for the U.S.A. [Laughter]\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. That's great. That's great. We really love it.\\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize\\nQ. Mr. President, have you been told that you are going to receive the inaugural peace prize today——\\nThe President. I have not——\\nQ. ——from FIFA?\\nThe President. I have not been told. There's a rumor about it, but I have not been told. That would be a great honor, and I'm a big fan of Gianni, as you know.\\nQ. What can fans expect——\\nQ. Are you hoping to receive that?\\nThe President. Excuse me.\\nQ. Are you hoping to receive the peace prize?\\nThe President. Well, I don't like to say \\\"hope,\\\" but it would be a great honor.\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. What can fans expect of, like, the World Cup in the U.S.?\\nThe President. I think it's going to be fantastic. We've set every record you can set.\\nQ. What are you telling people who are worried——\\nFédération Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) President Giovanni V. Infantino\\nQ. [Inaudible]—friend Gianni—[inaudible]—a word about him?\\nThe President. I think he has done a fantastic job.\\nThe President's Schedule\\nQ. Are you going to be meeting with the President of Mexico today and the——\\nThe President. We might. Yes.\\nQ. ——Prime Minister of Canada as well?\\nThe President. I might. I might do that.\\nQ. Will you be discussing immigration and trade with them?\\nThe President. Yes, we'll be discussing.\\n[At this point, the President and Mr. Infantino posed for photographs.]\\nThe President. Thank you, everybody.\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event/John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts\\nQ. Mr. President, what do you think about the crowd?\\nThe President. Oh, look, the new star—[inaudible].\\nCongratulations.\\nQ. Thank you.\\nThe President. You're the new star of television and Fox.\\nQ. Thank you. How are you doing, Mr. President?\\nThe President. I'm doing very well.\\nQ. What do you think about the crowd here?\\nThe President. I think the crowd is great, and I think the building is great. We've made a lot of improvements over the last 6 months. Taking—the Kennedy Center was in very bad shape. Now it's getting to be really good. And in 6 months, it's going to be incredible with the improvements we've made.\\nQ. The first time for the U.S. to host since the nineties.\\nThe President. Right.\\nQ. Are you ready for it?\\nThe President. I'm ready for it, and they're ready for it. And Gianni, who you know——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——has done a fantastic job with FIFA. And we're looking to have—you know, we're set—we have already set records for tickets sales. I don't think there's ever been anything like it in any sport. And so, I want to congratulate you.\\nMr. Infantino. Thank you.\\nThe President. I don't even have to wait. But major records have been set.\\nHow are you?\\nQ. Good, how are you, sir?\\nThe President. Nice to see you.\\nQ. Today it's not football—American football. It's soccer. It's——\\nThe President. Right.\\nQ. ——the big event of soccer.\\nThe President. That's right. That's right.\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\nQ. So can you tell me about this big day today?\\nThe President. It's just a big day, and it's a great sport. And it really is coming to America. And never—nobody ever thought a thing like this could happen. And I'm very happy to say that we've already set the alltime record on ticket sales long before the first ball is kicked. Right?\\nMr. Infantino. A hundred percent. One hundred percent.\\n2026 World Cup Host Cities\\nQ. You've had some concerns about crime in American cities, some of the cities that will be hosting. Have they remedied that for you? Are you still considering maybe asking FIFA to move some of those cities?\\nThe President. No, I don't want to do that. But I will tell you, if they do have a problem, by the time we get there, we'll take care of that problem. We can solve that problem.\\nI've proven that in DC and everywhere else we went, so we'll take care of that very easily. So, if they have a problem, hopefully, they'll let us know that, and we will solve any problem.\\nOkay? Thank you.\\nQ. Thank you so much.\\nMr. Infantino. All right, thank you so much.\\nQ. Thank you, Mr. President.\\nQ. Thank you. Appreciate it.\\nThe President. Congratulations.\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. Mr. President, Brazilian television. America will be hosting the World Cup and the Olympics in 2 years. How important it is—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. I think very. It's a great honor. I think Gianni is doing a phenomenal job. We've set every record on ticket sales. It's been really fantastic. But Gianni has done an unbelievable job with FIFA.\\nThe President's Experience With Soccer\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. He was a great—not only that. I got to see a man name Pelé play—right?—that tells you how old I am—when he was on the Cosmos. Do you remember that a long time ago? And it was quite a treat. That was quite an event. And he was—not only was he playing, he was great. He scored two goals, I think. And so, I was one of the few who got to see Pelé, and I assume he is one of your alltime greats. Right?\\nMr. Infantino. Definitely.\\nThe President. So I got to see him.\\nThe President's Favorite World Cup Competitor\\nQ. Do you have some favorite teams for World Cup?\\nThe President. Well, I have a favorite. It's the U.S.A. [Laughter] I don't know what their chances are, Gianni, but maybe the U.S.A. is the——\\nMr. Infantino. They're getting better and better, actually.\\nThe President. I think they'll do well.\\nMr. Infantino. They are getting better and better.\\nThe President. I think they'll do well.\\nThank you very much, everybody.\\nQ. Thank you so much.\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. Mr. President, World Cup in America just means—[inaudible]. So what do you expect from this World Cup?\\nThe President. [Inaudible]—record business and only in the United States, but we're also doing record ticket sales with FIFA. And they've already bought—beat their highest record. And we—you know, this a long time before the first ball is kicked. You've sold more tickets than they've ever done before, and better pricing than they've ever gotten before. It's a tremendous success. And it's an honor. And Gianni has done a phenomenal job with FIFA.\\nQ. [Inaudible]—ever?\\nThe President. I think so. I think it's going to be—I mean, ideally, you want to see that every year. Every 4 years, it gets bigger and better. I think we have set every record in the book. We're very happy about it.\\nThank you.\\nThe President's Favorite World Cup Competitor\\nQ. [Inaudible]—part of America. Who are you going to support as well?\\nThe President. Well, I think I have to support U.S.A. Otherwise, I'd be in trouble. I wouldn't be President for long.\\nMr. Infantino. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. [Inaudible]—but you have a lot of great teams. You're going to have a lot of great teams.\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\\\"football,\\\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\\n2026 World Cup Draw/Ticket Sales for World Cup\\nQ. How does it feel to be part of this amazing event? And obviously, your being a part of participating in all the—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. The President of Mexico is here, and she's doing a very good job. She's a good woman, very, very excellent job. It's an honor, and we're setting every record, and you're helping us set those records.\\nMr. Infantino. And we will do it.\\nThe President. You know, Mexico and Canada are helping us set those records. But as you know, we have a record in ticket sales already, long before the first ball is kicked, and we're going to do great.\\nI think that Gianni—as you know, he's the head, and he has done a fantastic job.\\nU.S. Cooperation With Mexico and Canada\\nQ. And how is the biggest challenge being three countries?\\nThe President. Well, I think that—do you mean for the three countries?\\nWell, they've gotten together really well, I mean.\\nMr. Infantino. All right.\\nThe President. They're getting along very well.\\nMr. Infantino. Collaboration is fantastic between the three.\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer/2026 World Cup\\nQ. And you like soccer?\\nThe President. I do. I like it. I like it more and more.\\nQ. Yes?\\nThe President. I like it. It's growing in this country—very, really—I mean, someday, maybe it's going to be bigger than anything else.\\nMr. Infantino. We'll have to become number one.\\nThe President. I will say this——\\nMr. Infantino. Definitely.\\nThe President. ——the ticket sales——\\nQ. Definitely will happen.\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. Ticket sales are bigger than anything we have ever done in the history of the country, in terms of sports.\\nMr. Infantino. For certain.\\nQ. And the audience is going to be huge.\\nThe President. The audience is going to be tremendous.\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. Yes.\\nMr. Infantino. Six billion people.\\nThe President. [Inaudible]\\nQ. Six billion? That's amazing.\\nMr. Infantino. Six billion people.\\nAnd today, one billion.\\nQ. Wow.\\nMr. Infantino. [Inaudible]\\nQ. Enjoy show time. Thank you so much.\\nThe President. [Inaudible]\\nQ. Mr. President, how are you? Just a quick—[inaudible].\\nQ. This is for Telemundo.\\nThe President. How are you?\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\nQ. Hello, Mr. President. How are you? This for Telemundo.\\nThe President. How are you? Good.\\nQ. How are you?\\nThe President. Very good. Thank you.\\nQ. How does it feel to have the most important event of sports—that global—in the U.S.?\\nThe President. Well, we do. And right at the Kennedy Center. I'm Chairman of the Kennedy Center. And I hear the Kennedy Center is doing a very good job, so it feels great. Really good.\\nAnd Telemundo is doing a good job, too. Thank you.\\nQ. Thank you.\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. What is the significance of hosting the FIFA World Cup this year?\\nThe President. It's a—in terms of sports, I would say the ultimate. There is no sport like this. It's the biggest sport in the world. And we are setting every record. You know, our ticket sales have gone and set every—every sport—no matter what it is, we've set the record. So—and every though it's very early, there's no ball being kicked yet, but we've already set a ticket sales record.\\nArgentina National Team\\nQ. How do you see Argentinean team for this World Cup?\\nThe President. Well, I love Argentina. And your President is doing a very good job, as you know. Milei. You know that right? It's make Argentina great again. MAGA.\\nQ. And——\\nU.S. National Team\\nQ. Do you think the States are building a powerful team for next year?\\nThe President. Who?\\nQ. The States.\\nThe President. Oh, yes. Sure. I—you're going to have a lot of powerful teams. Everybody has a lot of powerful teams, but you're going to have a lot of great teams. [Inaudible]\\nU.S. Role in Hosting the 2026 World Cup\\nQ. Mr. President, what does it mean for you guys to host the World Cup right here in the U.S.?\\nThe President. I'm honored to host it. It's a great honor. I mean, it's turned out to be bigger than we thought. We're setting a record for ticket sales, the likes of which no sport has ever seen before.\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\\nThe President. But they have a little more speed.\\nBut no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\\nPopularity of Soccer in Latin America\\nQ. Mr. President, a message for the Latin America and soccer fans?\\nThe President. Yes, I am. And Latin America is great. And they have great soccer. So, good luck in the matches.\\n[A reporter asked a question in Spanish, which was translated by an interpreter as follows.]\\nU.S. Visas for World Cup Ticketholders\\nQ. Who is going to be in—[inaudible]—about these visas for the—these fans that want to come here to the World Cup?\\nThe President. Well, we're going to make it very easy for them. We're working on that right now. We're going to make it very easy. It's going to be a very easy process.\\nQ. Okay. Say, hi to Colombia over there.\\nThe President. Hello. Is that Colombia?\\nQ. Yes.\\nThe President. I love Colombia. Hello, Colombia. [Laughter]\\nQ. Okay. Okay. Muy bien.\\nThe President. So where are you from?\\nQ. Paraguay.\\nThe President. Oh.\\nQ. He's from Paraguay. Yes.\\nThe President. Very good. I love it. I—it's a beautiful country. We get along very well with them. We do a little trade deal with them, and they like us. And that's what's happening.\\nQ. Panama.\\nThe President. Where?\\nVery good. I like the canal. [Laughter] That canal is pretty good.\\n[A reporter spoke in Spanish; no translation was provided.]\\n2026 World Cup\\nThe President. What?\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. Well, it's going to be incredible. The event is going to be very good. Just this event alone—it's at the Kennedy Center. I see you have it fixed up perfectly.\\nMr. Infantino. It will set the tone.\\nThe President. Right? It's beautiful.\\nMr. Infantino. It's beautiful.\\nThe President. It's a beautiful place.\\nHave a good time.\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President.\\n[A reporter spoke in Spanish; no translation was provided.]\\nMr. Infantino. No, gracias. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. It's great.\\nJohn F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts/Renovation Work\\nQ. Mr. President, the U.S. press?\\nThe President. Thank you, everybody, very much. It's a great honor. This has been an honor for a lot of reasons. Number one, they've sold more tickets than any event has ever sold already—long before the kickoff.\\nAnd number two, we've done a lot of work at the Kennedy Center. It was falling apart, and now it's pretty much back. And we'll get it back within the next 4 or 5 months through construction, and—but you see the way it looks.\\nAnd Gianni is just telling me—who's done an incredible job, by the way. He's just telling, you know, how good a job we've done.\\nMr. Infantino. That's right.\\nThe President. You can look at the walls. The marble was broken. Everything was a mess. And we've really taken the Kennedy Center—a lot of people thought it was going to be ripped down, and we did just the opposite. So we've done a really great renovation job on it. And over the next 3, 4 months, it will be complete. And we're honored to have it here, and it's been—it's been very special.\\nWe've set a record on ticket sales, as you probably heard, already, even way before—long before the event itself. And we're working with Canada, and we're working with Mexico. And it's been a really spectacular—so far, it's been spectacular.\\nDaniel [Daniel Baldwin, One America News Network], do you have a question?\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. What are your expectations? You once said that the FIFA World Cup is an opportunity to put—a once-in-a-lifetime opportunity to put the greatness of the United States on display.\\nThe President. Well, I think—\\nQ. One billion eyeballs will be watching, Mr. President.\\nThe President. Yes, I—think——\\nQ. What will they here today?\\nThe President. Even today, I understand. I hear that, you know——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——I know we're a little late to get in there, but——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——that's okay.\\nMr. Infantino. They wait.\\nThe President. So all my friends, I guess they have to wait. They have no choice, right? [Laughter]\\nMr. Infantino. Yes, they wait.\\nThe President. But no, the numbers are incredible. I hear today's numbers are——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——very big. I hope CNN is covering this.\\nQ. One billion eyeballs.\\nMr. Infantino. Today, 1 billion eyeballs.\\nThe President. Today's numbers are very, very big.\\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize/The President's Foreign Policy\\nQ. We are covering it. And you're expected to get the FIFA Peace Prize, Mr. President. What would you say to people who say that prize might conflict with your pledge to strike Venezuela?\\nThe President. Well, I think the peace prize—I mean, I settled eight wars. I don't know that I'm getting it. I haven't been officially noticed. I've been hearing about a peace prize, and I'm here to represent our country in a different sense. But I can tell you, I did settle eight wars, and we have a ninth coming, but—which nobody has ever done before.\\nBut I want to really save lives. I don't need prizes. I need to save lives. And we're saving a lot of lives. And I've saved millions and millions of lives, and that's really what I want to do.\\nAnd I also want to run a great country. And the United States right now is the hottest country anywhere in the world. And 1 year ago, it was dead. We had a dead country, and now we have the hottest country anywhere in the world.\\nQ. Mr. President, will you——\\nThe President's Meeting With President Claudia Sheinbaum Pardo of Mexico and Prime Minister Mark Carney of Canada\\nQ. What are you going to discuss with Canada and Mexico, Mr.—what are you going to discuss with the leaders of Canada and Mexico?\\nThe President. Well, we're getting—we're going to meet with both. And we're getting along very well. You know, we're getting along very well. I don't know. I think we have a meeting set up for some time after the event.\\nQ. Will you discuss trade?\\nThe President. Yes, we'll discuss trade. We—get along very well.\\nThank you, everybody, very much.\\nQ. Will you pardon any other Honduran officials?\\nQ. Do you want them to keep trying to indict Ms. James?\\n\\nNOTE: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. In his remarks, he referred to Trey Yingst, chief foreign correspondent, Fox News Channel; Cristiano Ronaldo, forward for Saudi Pro League club Al-Nass and Portugal's national soccer team; and Lionel Messi, forward for Major League Soccer club Inter Miami and Argentina's national team. A reporter referred to New York State Attorney General Letitia James. The transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\n\\nSource URL: https://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/documents/remarks-exchange-with-reporters-prior-the-2026-federation-internationale-des-associations\\n\\n\\n[defendant] DX-3 GovInfo/OFR pre-event transcript excerpt\\nSource: GovInfo, DCPD202501162, Office of the Federal Register / National Archives and Records Administration.\\nURL: https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/DCPD-202501162/html/DCPD-202501162.htm\\nTitle: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\nEvent date: December 5, 2025.\\n\\nRelevant extracted page text:\\n\\\"Administration of Donald J. Trump, 2025\\\"\\n\\\"Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw December 5, 2025\\\"\\n\\\"[The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\\\"\\n\\nUnder the section \\\"The President's Interest in Soccer\\\":\\n\\\"Q. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\\\"\\n\\\"The President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\\\\\\\"football,\\\\\\\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\\\"\\n\\\"Thank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\\\"\\n\\nAdditional relevant extracted page text:\\n\\\"The President's Interest in Soccer\\\"\\n\\\"Q. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\\\"\\n\\\"The President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\\\"\\n\\\"Mr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\\\"\\n\\\"The President. But they have a little more speed. But no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\\\"\\n\\nGovInfo note:\\n\\\"NOTE: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. In his remarks, he referred to Trey Yingst, chief foreign correspondent, Fox News Channel; Cristiano Ronaldo, forward for Saudi Pro League club Al-Nass and Portugal's national soccer team; and Lionel Messi, forward for Major League Soccer club Inter Miami and Argentina's national team. A reporter referred to New York State Attorney General Letitia James. The transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\\"\\n\\nGovInfo content details page also identifies category \\\"Interviews With the News Media : Exchanges with reporters, Washington, DC,\\\" subjects including \\\"Federation Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) World Cup,\\\" \\\"John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts,\\\" and \\\"Soccer,\\\" and names including \\\"Ronaldo, Cristiano\\\" and \\\"Messi, Lionel.\\\"\\n\\n[defendant] DX-4 PRESMENTION/NEWMENTION terms\\n                                         NEWMENTION\\n\\nScope: These rules shall apply to this contract.\\n\\nUnderlying: The Underlying for this Contract is words used by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nRevisions to the Underlying made after Expiration will not be accounted for in determining the\\nExpiration Value.\\n\\nSource Agency: The Source Agencies are \\u003csource\\u003e.\\n\\nType: The type of Contract is an Event Contract.\\n\\nIssuance: After the initial Contract, Contract iterations will be listed on an as-needed basis at\\nthe discretion of the Exchange and corresponding to the risk management needs of Members.\\n\\n\\u003centity\\u003e: \\u003centity\\u003e refers to the speaker, writer, performer, or communicator specified by the\\nExchange. This may include (but is not limited to): a specific named individual, multiple\\nindividuals specified using AND/OR logic, an individual identified by position or title, a group,\\nband, team or collective entity, a specified member or members of a group, an organization,\\ncompany, or institutional entity, or any combination of the aforementioned.\\n\\nWhen \\u003centity\\u003e is defined by a position or title, the Contract tracks whoever holds that position\\nduring \\u003ctime period\\u003e, even if the individual holding the position changes. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a\\nspecific named individual, the identity remains consistent throughout. Name changes (e.g.,\\nstage names, married names) do not create a new entity. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a group or\\norganization and the Contract does not specify particular members, any official\\ncommunication or statement by any member or designated spokesperson counts. When using\\nAND logic, all specified entities must independently say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e. When\\nusing OR logic, at least one of the specified entities must say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nThe Exchange may specify additional conditions such as “at least X members of” a group or\\n“the majority of” a group.\\n\\n\\u003csource\\u003e: \\u003csource\\u003e refers to a Source Agency or ordered collection of Source Agencies\\nspecified by the Exchange at the time of Contract listing, which will be incorporated into the\\nSource Agency hierarchy above and used to determine the occurrence of the Underlying.\\n\\u003csource\\u003e may refer to a singular agency, multiple agencies, an agency by distinguishing\\ncharacteristics, by category or type (e.g., “official government statistical body,” “primary wire\\nservice”), or any combination thereof. When multiple agencies are specified, they may be\\napplied in the hierarchical order designated by the Exchange if so specified, with the highest-\\nranked available and responsive agency taking precedence for purposes of determining the\\nExpiration Value. A lower-ranked agency shall only be consulted if all higher-ranked agencies\\nare unavailable, unresponsive, have not reported on the Underlying by the Expiration time, or\\nif the Exchange, in its sole discretion, determines that a higher-ranked agency’s reporting is\\nincomplete, erroneous, or otherwise insufficient to determine the Expiration Value. If \\u003csource\\u003e\\ndesignates multiple agencies without specifying a hierarchical order, the Exchange shall\\nresolve any conflict between reporting agencies at its sole discretion.\\n\\n\\u003cword\\u003e: \\u003cword\\u003e refers to the particular word or phrase potentially to be mentioned by\\n\\u003centity\\u003e. It may refer to a word being said a minimum number of times. It may also refer to\\none of multiple words/phrases, any of which are acceptable (e.g., “Doge/Dogecoin”).\\n\\f\\u003ctime period\\u003e: \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific range of time, event or discrete date and\\ntime specified by the Exchange. This may be defined by, but is not limited to: a specific event\\nor context (e.g., “during the State of the Union address”), exact dates or times, relative time\\nmarkers (e.g., “before July 1, 2027,” “in Q1 2026”), event-based periods (e.g., “during any\\ncampaign rally in October 2026,” “during the awards ceremony”), and broader intervals (e.g.,\\n“Q1–Q2 2027,” “January–March 2026”).\\n\\nUnless stated otherwise, “Between” is inclusive of both endpoints, while “before” and “after”\\nexclude the specified date. \\u003ctime period\\u003e may also refer to “Any” or “None”, to multiple dates\\n(even if non-consecutive), or to a singular and discrete date or time.\\n\\nWhen \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event (such as an address, speech, performance, or\\nbroadcast), the Exchange may specify what is included, including whether it includes both live\\nand pre-recorded segments (including whether advertisements are included). Where a\\ntimezone is not specified, ET is assumed.\\n\\n\\nPayout Criterion: The Payout Criterion for the Contract encompasses the Expiration Values that\\n\\u003cword\\u003e is said by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n\\n\\nThe word must appear as a distinct, standalone unit, not buried inside another word. Plural\\nand possessive noun forms count. Other grammatical changes (tense, conjugation, derivation)\\ndo not. If \\u003cword\\u003e appears separated from other words by a space or hyphen or in a\\ncompound form with a space or hyphen, it counts. If \\u003cword\\u003e is fused into a single\\nunhyphenated word, it does not count.\\n\\nIf \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled, and the market contains a\\nstrike stating “Event does not qualify/occur”, such a strike shall resolve “Yes” and all others\\n“No”. If \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled but such strikes are NOT\\nlisted, the Contracts will resolve to the last fair price determined at the discretion of the\\nExchange. If the event is postponed, and such a postponement is announced by the end of the\\nfollowing calendar day to be rescheduled to a time within 14 calendar days, the markets shall\\nremain open. If the event captured in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast, the\\nExchange may keep the market open for 24 hours for the release of an official recording.\\nFurther granular details on conditions for these Contracts is available below.\\n\\nAdditional clarification(s):\\n\\n     Possessive noun forms of \\u003cword\\u003e, plurals, and possessive plural noun forms are\\n     INCLUDED:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigrants” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Egg” → “eggs’ shells” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Russia” → “Russia’s” counts, “Russian” does not\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e exists only in adjective form, no plural form exists:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Economic” → “Economics” does not count (“Economic” is an adjective\\n          for which “Economics” is not a plural)\\n     Plural nouns occurring within proper nouns and noun phrases are included:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Cat” → “Cats the musical” counts\\n\\f    Grammatical variations beyond plurals/possessives are NOT included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigration” does NOT count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Run” → “Running” or “Ran” do NOT count\\n    When \\u003cword\\u003e specifies a plural form, the singular does NOT count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Veterans” → “Veteran” does NOT count\\n    Words that are spelled the same as the plural form of \\u003cword\\u003e (if such exists) but are\\n    themselves not a plural noun are included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Wind” → “Winds up the clock” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Border” → “The United States has strong borders” counts\\n    Open compounds (words separated by spaces) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fire station” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “couch” → “couch potato” counts\\n    Hyphenated compounds (words connected by hyphens) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Palestine” → “pro-Palestine” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fat” → “non-fat” counts\\n    Closed compounds (single word, no spaces/hyphens) do not count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire” does not count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firefighter” does not count\\n    Multi-word \\u003cword\\u003e in larger constructions: When \\u003cword\\u003e is a multi-word phrase\\n    appearing within a hyphenated construction, it counts only if \\u003cword\\u003e appears as a\\n    complete, unmodified element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “New York” → “New York-based” counts (complete element)\\n    Portmanteaus (words blended from two words where parts of each are combined) are\\n    NOT included unless the portmanteau clearly contains \\u003cword\\u003e as a distinct, unaltered\\n    element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “MAGA” → “MAGA-nificent” counts (MAGA appears as distinct element)\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “magnificent” → “MAGA-nificent” does NOT count (portmanteau blend)\\n\\nDictionary determination: Both the Merriam-Webster Dictionary (available online) AND the\\nOxford English Dictionary shall be used to determine compound type and/or conventional\\nspelling patterns. Inclusion in either dictionary as an open or hyphenated compound shall\\nsatisfy the Payout Criterion. If neither provides clarity (or the word is not included),\\ndetermination is based on whether written as single unit (closed/doesn’t count) vs. spaces or\\nhyphens (open or hyphenated/counts) and/or context and previous usage.\\n\\nPHONETIC EQUIVALENCIES\\n\\n    Homophones (same sound, different spelling) do not count:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “write” → “right” does not count\\n    Homonyms and homographs (same spelling) COUNT regardless of meaning or\\n    pronunciation:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “bass” → both “bass guitar” and “bass fishing” count\\n    Proper and common nouns are treated identically:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Apple” → both “Apple Inc.” and “apple” (fruit) count\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Will” → both “Will Smith” and “I will go” count\\n    Minor unintentional mispronunciations COUNT if context makes intent clear:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Mamdani” → “Mandani” counts\\n    Severe mispronunciations that make \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable do NOT count.\\n    Trademarked spellings do not count, even when pronounced identically, unless the word\\n\\fitself is the same:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “lift” → “Lyft” (pronounced “lift”) does not count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “uber” → “Uber” counts\\nWords with non-standard transliteration to English count within reason, provided they are\\nphonetically equivalent:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Zelensky” → any of “Zelenski,” “Zelenskii,” “Zelensky,” or “Zelenskiy”\\n      count if pronounced equivalently\\nContractions do not count for their constituent words unless otherwise explicitly specified\\nby the Exchange:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “not” → “won’t,” “can’t,” “don’t,” “isn’t” do not count\\nNumbers spoken as words COUNT, when spoken exactly (not part of a larger number):\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “five” → saying “five” or reading “$5” aloud as “five dollars” counts,\\n      saying “five hundred” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “410” → “four hundred ten”, “four one zero” or “four ten” counts\\nOrdinals COUNT when \\u003cword\\u003e is written numerically OR a phrase that includes a\\nnumber:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “January 6” → “January 6th” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “3” (written numerically) → “3rd” (spoken as “third”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Eight War” → “8 Wars” and “Eighth War” will count\\nCardinal and ordinal number words are distinct:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “one” → “first” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “first” → “one” does NOT count\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count when pronunciation or letter-by-letter spelling\\nmatches \\u003cword\\u003e:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “NASA” (pronounced “NAH-suh”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “N-A-S-A” (spelled out) counts\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count as \\u003cword\\u003e when pronounced as the full word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Doctor” → “Dr.” (pronounced “Doctor”) counts\\nExpanded forms of acronyms do NOT count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “AI” → “artificial intelligence” does not count\\nWords in foreign languages do NOT count unless they are perfect cognates with an\\nEnglish word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fuego” (Spanish) does NOT count\\nEnglish words within foreign sentences count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “policy” → “Nuestra policy es clara” counts\\n\\u003cword\\u003e in organization/company names counts:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Securities” → “Bank of America Securities” counts\\nWords in URLs, emails, handles, and hashtags (exclusive of domain structure, email\\nprovider or symbols) are treated as compounds when spoken as complete words, with the\\ntype of compound subject to aforementioned rules:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firestation.com” pronounced “fire station dot com” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire.com” pronounced “wildfire dot com” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “apple” → “apple.com” pronounced “apple dot com” does count\\n      When presented in URL, email, handle, or hashtag form, \\u003cword\\u003e shall be treated as\\n      a compound, not a multi-word word\\nSung, rapped, or poetic words COUNT if phonetically recognizable:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “money” → “moneyyy” (extended in rap) counts\\n      Extreme distortion making \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable does NOT count.\\nPhonetic alphabet spelling (“Foxtrot India Romeo Echo” for “FIRE”) does NOT count.\\n\\fCANCELLATIONS AND DELAYS\\n\\n   The Exchange may list an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike for any Contract. If listed,\\n   such a strike refers to the structural conditions of the market, and is NOT adjudicated as a\\n   \\u003cword\\u003e needing to be said by or validated by having been said by \\u003centity\\u003e. If listed, this\\n   strike resolves to “Yes” whenever the event fails to occur or qualify under the Payout\\n   Criterion, or any other circumstance prevents normal resolution.\\n   If no such strike is listed, and \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, the following rules\\n   apply if the event is cancelled, postponed, rescheduled, or materially altered (including\\n   being closed to press) such that no video is released within one calendar day of the\\n   original start time of the event:\\n         If the event is cancelled, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price determined in\\n         the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         If the event is postponed or rescheduled, the outcome depends on whether a new\\n         date is publicly announced within one calendar day (i.e. if the event was scheduled\\n         to begin on Monday, any time up to 11:59PM on Tuesday falls within this period) of\\n         the originally scheduled start time:\\n               If no new date is announced within one calendar day, the Contract will resolve\\n               to the last fair price determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n               If a new date is announced within one calendar day, the outcome depends on\\n               when the rescheduled event is set to occur:\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls within fourteen (14) calendar days of the\\n                     originally scheduled date, the Contract shall remain open and \\u003cword\\u003e\\n                     stated during the rescheduled event will count.\\n                           The fourteen-day window begins at 12:00 AM ET on the originally\\n                           scheduled date and ends at 11:59 PM ET fourteen days later, unless\\n                           an alternate timezone is explicitly specified.\\n                           Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the State of the Union on January\\n                           15, 2026” rescheduled to January 20, 2026 → words spoken during\\n                           the rescheduled address count.\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls more than fourteen (14) calendar days after\\n                     the originally scheduled date, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price\\n                     determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         Any Contract that cannot be resolved through the Source Agency hierarchy will\\n         instead be settled at the Last Fair Price. The Exchange will disclose the methodology\\n         used to determine the Last Fair Price (e.g., Last Traded Price, Time-Weighted\\n         Average Price) at the time of Issuance.\\n         If an event begins but is interrupted, abbreviated, or ends prematurely, words\\n         stated by \\u003centity\\u003e during the portion of the event that did occur will count and the\\n         market will otherwise resolve.\\n   If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window but the venue, format, or medium\\n   changes (e.g., moved to a different location, changed from in-person to virtual (with the\\n   exception of being closed to press)), words stated during the event will count.\\n   Special condition: Across both cases, whether an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike is\\n   listed or not, if the event specified as or in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast (or\\n   relayed as such) but the live stream/broadcast does not occur, the Exchange will instead\\n   use an officially released recording as the Underlying, and may delay resolution by up to\\n   one calendar day to allow for the release of such a recording.\\n\\f          If partial snippets are released, Contracts on words that do not appear will be\\n          resolved to last fair price, and Contracts on those that do will be resolved to “Yes”.\\n          If no recording is released, the relevant outcomes triggered by the\\n          presence/absence of an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike shall occur as outlined\\n          above.\\n\\nTECHNICAL DETAILS (UNLESS OTHERWISE SPECIFIED)\\n\\n     When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, pre-recorded content broadcast,\\n     streamed, or published as part of that event is included if presented as part of the official\\n     presentation.\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the concert” with pre-recorded video interlude\\n          where entity speaks → words from interlude count\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the television appearance” with pre-taped\\n          segment aired during broadcast → words from segment count\\n     Behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are NOT\\n     included unless officially broadcast or published as part of \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n     Subtitles and captions that display \\u003cword\\u003e on screen but are not spoken aloud by\\n     \\u003centity\\u003e do NOT count.\\n     Sign language interpretation or usage by entity does NOT count as saying \\u003cword\\u003e unless\\n     the Contract explicitly specifies that sign language counts.\\n     Text that entity displays on screen (presentation slides, teleprompter visible to audience,\\n     signatures) does NOT count unless entity reads it aloud.\\n     Content generated by AI, deepfakes, or synthetic voice technology impersonating entity\\n     does NOT count unless the synthetic content is officially commissioned, authorized, or\\n     published by entity, OR the Contract explicitly specifies that AI-generated content counts.\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e is muted due to technical failure or censorship it shall not count unless\\n     corroborating contextual evidence (including surrounding speech, or an official\\n     uncensored recording or transcript) confirms that \\u003centity\\u003e specifically uttered \\u003cword\\u003e\\n     during the muted period.\\n\\nMinimum Tick: The Minimum Tick size for the Contract shall be $0.01.\\n\\nPosition Accountability Level: The Position Accountability Level for the Contract shall be\\n$25,000 per strike, per Member.\\n\\nLast Trading Date: The Last Trading Date of the Contract will be the Expiration Date. The Last\\nTrading Time will be the Expiration time.\\n\\nSettlement Date: The Settlement Date of the Contract shall be no later than the day after the\\nExpiration Date, unless the Market Outcome is under review pursuant to Rule 7.1.\\n\\nExpiration Date: When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event: The latest Expiration Date of\\nthe Contract shall be fourteen (14) calendar days after the originally scheduled date of the\\nevent. If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window, expiration will be moved to an\\nearlier date and time in accordance with Rule 7.2. When \\u003ctime period\\u003e is defined by specific\\ndates: The latest Expiration Date of the Contract shall be two weeks after the end of \\u003ctime\\nperiod\\u003e. If an event described in the Payout Criterion occurs and a consensus has been\\nreached on all terms, then expiration will be moved to an earlier date and time in accordance\\nwith Rule 7.2.\\n\\fExpiration time: The Expiration time of the Contract shall be 10:00 AM ET.\\n\\nSettlement Value: The Settlement Value for this Contract is $1.00.\\n\\nExpiration Value: The Expiration Value is the value of the Underlying as documented by the\\nSource Agency on the Expiration Date at the Expiration time.\\n\\nContingencies: Before Settlement, Kalshi may, at its sole discretion, initiate the Market\\nOutcome Review Process pursuant to Rule 7.1 of the Rulebook. If an Expiration Value cannot\\nbe determined on the Expiration Date, Kalshi has the right to determine payouts pursuant to\\nRule 7.1 in the Rulebook.\\n\\f\\n\\n[defendant] DX-5 Formal draw archive note\\nSource checked: Roll Call / Factba.se archive\\n\\nArchive title: Remarks: Donald Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing in Washington - December 5, 2025\\n\\nArchive URL: https://rollcall.com/factbase/trump/transcript/donald-trump-remarks-fifa-world-cup-drawing-december-5-2025/\\n\\nWhat this file establishes:\\n\\nThere is a separate archived transcript page for Trump's formal attendance remarks at the draw.\\n\\nWhat this file does not establish:\\n\\nThis session could not retrieve the full transcript text from that archive.  The page is password-protected.  This example therefore does not claim, from local files alone, whether the formal program transcript does or does not contain the word \\\"Ronaldo.\\\"\\n\\nWhy this matters:\\n\\nThe complaint does not need to prove that the formal program omitted the strike.  It needs to show that Trump said \\\"Ronaldo\\\" in event-linked remarks and that the market boundary reasonably includes those remarks.  The formal archive remains relevant because it marks the distinction between the pre-event reporter exchange and the formal program.\\n\\n\\n[defendant] DX-6 Formal Roll Call/Factba.se transcript extraction\\nSource: Roll Call / Factba.se\\nURL: https://rollcall.com/factbase/trump/transcript/donald-trump-remarks-fifa-world-cup-drawing-december-5-2025/\\nCaptured page title: Remarks: Donald Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing in Washington - December 5, 2025\\n\\nRendered page metadata excerpt:\\nTopics: Sport; Sport \\u003e Competition Discipline \\u003e Soccer; Lifestyle and Leisure \\u003e Leisure \\u003e Game.\\nEntities listed: bowl; deal; Donald J. Trump; FIFA World Cup; Mark Carney; place; President; trophy; United States; way.\\nSpeakers listed: Gianni Infantino, Donald Trump, Mark Carney, Claudia Sheinbaum.\\nSpeaker statistics excerpt: Donald Trump said 25 sentences of a total of 141 sentences; Donald Trump said 274 words of a total of 1009 words; Donald Trump talked 92 seconds of a total of 484 seconds.\\n\\nFormal transcript excerpt at start of draw:\\nMark Carney, 00:00:00-00:00:02: Thank you, my friend.\\nGianni Infantino, 00:00:50-00:01:22: So this is the World Cup trophy. This is the official bowl for the World Cup and we are now going to do the draw, ladies and gentlemen. But before that, as is customary, there is always a question that the moderator asks the draw assistant. So I would like to start with Mr. Carney. How big a deal is it to co-host the World Cup for Canada?\\n\\nFormal transcript excerpt of Trump's soccer answer:\\nDonald Trump, 00:03:14-00:03:32: Well, for years, Gianni, they've thought soccer or football would be so big, so fast. And I remember, I shouldn't say this because it was a long time ago, but I remember watching Pele play on a team called the Cosmos, Pele, who was fantastic, as you know. I assume one of the greats.\\n\\nText-extraction/search notes:\\nLocal Python urllib retrieval of the page returned HTTP 200 for the source URL and extracted approximately 175,864 characters of page text with Python html.parser. Case-sensitive searches in the extracted page text returned no occurrence of \\\"Ronaldo\\\" and no occurrence of \\\"Messi\\\". The same terms were not found using the browser page find function on the rendered page.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R1 Defendant formal transcript extraction for limited rebuttal use\\nSource: Roll Call / Factba.se\\nURL: https://rollcall.com/factbase/trump/transcript/donald-trump-remarks-fifa-world-cup-drawing-december-5-2025/\\nCaptured page title: Remarks: Donald Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing in Washington - December 5, 2025\\n\\nRendered page metadata excerpt:\\nTopics: Sport; Sport \\u003e Competition Discipline \\u003e Soccer; Lifestyle and Leisure \\u003e Leisure \\u003e Game.\\nEntities listed: bowl; deal; Donald J. Trump; FIFA World Cup; Mark Carney; place; President; trophy; United States; way.\\nSpeakers listed: Gianni Infantino, Donald Trump, Mark Carney, Claudia Sheinbaum.\\nSpeaker statistics excerpt: Donald Trump said 25 sentences of a total of 141 sentences; Donald Trump said 274 words of a total of 1009 words; Donald Trump talked 92 seconds of a total of 484 seconds.\\n\\nFormal transcript excerpt at start of draw:\\nMark Carney, 00:00:00-00:00:02: Thank you, my friend.\\nGianni Infantino, 00:00:50-00:01:22: So this is the World Cup trophy. This is the official bowl for the World Cup and we are now going to do the draw, ladies and gentlemen. But before that, as is customary, there is always a question that the moderator asks the draw assistant. So I would like to start with Mr. Carney. How big a deal is it to co-host the World Cup for Canada?\\n\\nFormal transcript excerpt of Trump's soccer answer:\\nDonald Trump, 00:03:14-00:03:32: Well, for years, Gianni, they've thought soccer or football would be so big, so fast. And I remember, I shouldn't say this because it was a long time ago, but I remember watching Pele play on a team called the Cosmos, Pele, who was fantastic, as you know. I assume one of the greats.\\n\\nText-extraction/search notes:\\nLocal Python urllib retrieval of the page returned HTTP 200 for the source URL and extracted approximately 175,864 characters of page text with Python html.parser. Case-sensitive searches in the extracted page text returned no occurrence of \\\"Ronaldo\\\" and no occurrence of \\\"Messi\\\". The same terms were not found using the browser page find function on the rendered page.\\n\\nSubmitted evidence:\\n[plaintiff arguments] GovInfo DCPD202501162 transcript excerpt and metadata (ev_3fc783920414_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-3fc783920414)\\nSource: https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/DCPD-202501162/html/DCPD-202501162.htm\\nSHA-256: `3fc783920414399098d86210070dd9fe83c14fe1dbded1a56a554f8f4b3448f2`\\nBytes: 2641\\nRelevance: Official government transcript source corroborating that Trump spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center before the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw and said the strike word Ronaldo in World-Cup-related remarks.\\n\\n[defendant arguments] Roll Call/Factba.se formal FIFA World Cup Drawing transcript extraction (ev_fbb53e87ccb3_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-fbb53e87ccb3)\\nSource: https://rollcall.com/factbase/trump/transcript/donald-trump-remarks-fifa-world-cup-drawing-december-5-2025/\\nSHA-256: `fbb53e87ccb3f4381fc2bdc06ac2f2a1ea3848aadde56122b22d34dfbdf4533b`\\nBytes: 2032\\nRelevance: Formal drawing-program transcript evidence showing a separate formal Draw source from the pre-event reporter exchange; the extracted page text contains no occurrence of Ronaldo or Messi, supporting defendant's event-boundary argument.\\n\\nTechnical reports:\\n[plaintiff] Plaintiff source and adverse-search ledger\\nChecked the visible case packet and then searched official/source-specific repositories. GovInfo DCPD202501162 was opened and preserved as submitted evidence; it corroborates the packet transcript, source metadata, location, event date, and Ronaldo passages. The Roll Call/Factba.se formal drawing page rendered despite the packet's password-protection note; browser find searches for 'Ronaldo,' 'Cristiano,' and 'Messi' returned no matches. Plaintiff therefore treats the formal-program transcript as an adverse boundary check, not as proof of a formal-stage mention. The remaining dispute is contractual scope: whether the market clearly excluded public event-linked venue remarks immediately before the formal program.\\n\\n[defendant] Defense source-check ledger\\nDefendant searched for the formal Roll Call/Factba.se transcript identified by the case packet, opened the rendered Roll Call page, and fetched it locally with Python urllib. The fetch returned HTTP 200 for the formal FIFA World Cup Drawing transcript page. Text extraction produced approximately 175,864 characters; searches for \\\"Ronaldo\\\" and \\\"Messi\\\" returned no occurrences. The retrieval also captured formal-program excerpts, including Infantino's statement that \\\"we are now going to do the draw\\\" and Trump's formal soccer answer mentioning Pele rather than Ronaldo. The focused extraction was submitted and accepted as ev_fbb53e87ccb3_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-fbb53e87ccb3.\\n\\nCall submit_council_vote with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated.\\nKeep the rationale brief: no more than three sentences.\\n\\nCouncil API instructions:\\nYou are a council member. Decide the proposition from the admitted record.\\nYou may examine admitted evidence through read-only tools when exact bytes, metadata, or exhibit contents matter.\\nDo not search the web, introduce new facts, create new evidence, or upload evidence.\\nWhen ready, call submit_council_vote exactly once with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated and a concise rationale.\\n\",\"state\":\"ready\",\"status\":\"ready\",\"tools\":[{\"description\":\"Return the current visible arbitration record for this council member.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"get_case\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"List visible immutable record evidence.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"list_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Return metadata and read limits for one visible evidence item.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"stat_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Read a bounded byte range from one visible evidence item as base64.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"length\":{\"minimum\":1,\"type\":\"integer\"},\"offset\":{\"minimum\":0,\"type\":\"integer\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\",\"offset\",\"length\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"read_evidence_range\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Submit one council vote for the current deliberation opportunity.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"rationale\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"vote\":{\"enum\":[\"demonstrated\",\"not_demonstrated\"],\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"vote\",\"rationale\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"submit_council_vote\",\"read_only\":false}],\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":false,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-29T19:58:02.156322961Z\",\"deliberation_round\":1,\"member_id\":\"C2\",\"opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C2\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"remaining_ms\":887183,\"role_id\":\"council\",\"turn_number\":10},\"wait\":{\"reason\":\"ready\",\"state_version\":12,\"version\":15}}"}],"details":{"mode":"call","mcpResult":{"content":[{"type":"text","text":"ok: true\nstatus: ready\nstate: ready\nmessage: An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\nafter_version: 15\nafter_opportunity_id: deliberation:1:C2\nmember_id: C2\ncase_id: arb-ex03-20260629192557\nwait_reason: ready\nphase: deliberation\nopportunity_id: deliberation:1:C2\nremaining_ms: 887183\nattempts_remaining: 3\njson: {\"after_opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C2\",\"after_version\":15,\"case_id\":\"arb-ex03-20260629192557\",\"limits\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"max_evidence_read_bytes\":65536,\"max_evidence_read_bytes_per_opportunity\":524288,\"max_evidence_reads_per_opportunity\":32,\"max_response_bytes\":131072,\"remaining_evidence_read_bytes_for_opportunity\":524288,\"remaining_evidence_reads_for_opportunity\":32},\"member_id\":\"C2\",\"message\":\"An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\",\"ok\":true,\"prompt\":\"Role: council member\\nMember ID: C2\\nDeliberation round: 1\\nProposition: For the Kalshi market \\\"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\\", the strike \\\"Ronaldo\\\" should resolve Yes because Trump said \\\"Ronaldo\\\" in public remarks at the World Cup Draw venue immediately before the formal program, and the market wording plus the governing mention-market terms did not clearly exclude those event-linked remarks.\\nStandard of evidence: Preponderance of the evidence.\\nPersona:\\nYou are a careful juror and council member.\\n\\nEvaluate the record faithfully. Decide only from the evidence, the stated rules, and the applicable burden of proof. Do not favor either side, fill gaps with speculation, or ignore uncertainty.\\n\\nGive weight to reliable sources, direct evidence, consistent reasoning, and clear admissions. Discount unsupported claims, rhetorical force, irrelevant facts, and conclusions that exceed the record.\\n\\nWhen the evidence supports one answer, state it plainly. When the evidence is incomplete or balanced, say so. Be concise, honest, and exact.\\n\\nRecord:\\nOpenings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, this case is not mainly about whether the syllables were spoken. The case-packet transcript says they were. The real dispute is the market boundary: when Kalshi asked what Trump would say \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw,\\\" did that phrase clearly exclude his public, event-linked remarks at the World Cup Draw venue immediately before the formal program? On this record, it did not.\\n\\nThe market page fixes the contract at issue: the public title was \\\"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\\"; the contract family was PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION; the strike was \\\"Ronaldo\\\"; Kalshi challenged the resolution as No; and the requested resolution is Yes. That means the council's task is to apply the mention-market terms to that title and strike, not to import a narrower limitation that the market did not plainly announce.\\n\\nThe reporter-exchange packet is direct evidence on the word and setting. It is titled as remarks in an exchange with reporters prior to the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw, dated December 5, 2025. It places the President at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts, speaking with FIFA President Gianni Infantino and reporters in a sequence repeatedly labeled around the 2026 World Cup and the Draw. In that exchange, in a soccer discussion, Trump says he met Ronaldo, praises him, and uses \\\"Ronaldo\\\" as a distinct standalone word. Under the mention rules, a distinct standalone appearance of the strike is the kind of use that counts if it falls within the time period.\\n\\nThe terms matter because they do not say that an event market is limited only to scripted remarks from a formal stage segment. They define a time period as potentially an event or context, and they give the Exchange power to specify what is included when a time period refers to a specific event. They also distinguish official/public event content from behind-the-scenes, rehearsals, and unofficial recordings. That distinction helps plaintiff: the packet is not a rumor, rehearsal, private soundcheck, or leaked recording. It is a sourced public transcript of remarks at the event venue, immediately tied to the Draw. If Kalshi meant \\\"only the formal televised draw program after doors close\\\" or \\\"only remarks in the separate formal archive,\\\" it needed to say so clearly.\\n\\nI also want to be candid about what the packet does not yet prove. The formal-draw archive note says a separate archived transcript page exists for Trump's formal attendance remarks, but that the session could not retrieve the full text because the page was password-protected. So, at opening, plaintiff is not asking you to infer that the formal program itself contained \\\"Ronaldo.\\\" Nor does plaintiff need that inference. The Yes theory is that the qualifying period reasonably includes the public pre-program reporter exchange that was part of Trump's World Cup Draw appearance. The formal archive is relevant because it marks defendant's likely narrower boundary; it does not resolve the boundary in defendant's favor.\\n\\nProvenance and weight also favor treating the packet seriously at this stage. The market and terms files are system case-packet records. The reporter exchange includes a source URL to a public presidential transcript source and notes a corrected transcript date, while also acknowledging that some audio could not be verified because the audio was incomplete. That caveat may affect inaudible portions, but it does not erase the visible, contextual Ronaldo passage. Later, when evidence admission opens, the parties should preserve the official transcript source, any govinfo or Presidency Project copy, the market page capture, and any accessible formal-program transcript or video. The adverse check should ask whether the formal program omits the word, but omission there would matter only if the council first accepts the defense's artificially narrow reading of \\\"during.\\\"\\n\\nThe plaintiff's burden is preponderance. The record already points to a straightforward path to Yes: Trump, the specified entity, said the specified strike as a standalone word in public remarks linked to and immediately preceding the World Cup Draw at the venue; the market title and governing terms did not clearly exclude that event-linked exchange. On a fair reading of the contract the trader saw, the challenged No resolution should give way to Yes.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the defense opening is simple: this case is not won by proving that the word \\\"Ronaldo\\\" appears somewhere in a public transcript. The plaintiff must prove, by a preponderance, that the word was said during the market's specified event: the FIFA World Cup Draw.\\n\\nThe current packet leaves that critical link unproven. The market page does not say \\\"while Trump was at the venue,\\\" \\\"during a World Cup press availability,\\\" or \\\"during any remarks connected to the Draw.\\\" It says: \\\"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\\" The challenged resolution was No. The requested Yes theory therefore needs more than event-adjacent context; it needs a boundary showing that the reporter exchange was part of the Draw period the market asked traders to price.\\n\\nThe plaintiff's own best transcript cuts against that boundary. The case-packet file is titled \\\"Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw.\\\" It says the President's remarks were joined in progress, and the source note says portions could not be verified because the audio was incomplete. It places Trump at the Kennedy Center and includes World Cup topics, and yes, it contains \\\"Ronaldo\\\" as a standalone word in a soccer exchange. But its title and structure identify those remarks as an exchange with reporters prior to the Draw, not the formal Draw itself.\\n\\nThe terms do not rescue plaintiff from that distinction. They define a mention market around words used by the entity during the time period. A time period may be a specific event, and when it is a specific event, the Exchange may specify what is included. The technical details also distinguish official presentation content from behind-the-scenes, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings unless those are officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. Those provisions do not mean every public, nearby, event-related conversation becomes part of the event. They make the event boundary the central question.\\n\\nThe formal-draw archive note reinforces why the distinction matters. It reports that there is a separate archived transcript page for Trump's formal attendance remarks at the FIFA World Cup Drawing, but that the full text was not retrieved because the page was password-protected. That note does not prove the formal program omitted Ronaldo. It also does not prove the formal program included it. What it does show, at opening, is that the record itself separates the pre-event reporter exchange from the formal drawing remarks.\\n\\nSo the defense will focus the council on proof of inclusion, not mere association. If later phases produce a market page provision, official broadcast record, program transcript, video metadata, or source-agency material showing that the red-carpet reporter exchange was officially part of the FIFA World Cup Draw presentation for this market, the council can weigh that. If the later evidence instead shows a formal program with a separate pre-program press availability, then the correct result is No even though the word was spoken nearby.\\n\\nOn this opening record, plaintiff has shown a Ronaldo mention in remarks prior to the event. Plaintiff has not shown that those remarks occurred during the market event. The defense position is that Kalshi's No resolution follows the market wording and the mention-market terms unless plaintiff supplies that missing boundary proof.\\n\\nArguments:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the merits question is whether the contract clearly limited “during the FIFA World Cup Draw” to only the formal staged ceremony. Plaintiff submits that it did not, and the record now proves the Yes result by a preponderance.\\n\\nFirst, the market itself is broad. PX-1 identifies the public question as “What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?”, contract family PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION, strike “Ronaldo,” challenged resolution No, and requested resolution Yes. The market page does not say “during the formal televised ceremony,” “on the main stage only,” or “excluding public remarks immediately before the program at the venue.” That absence matters because Kalshi drafted the boundary traders had to price.\\n\\nSecond, the word was said. PX-2, the case-packet transcript, and PX-5, the GovInfo/OFR source excerpt, both show Trump used “Ronaldo” as a standalone word in soccer-related remarks. PX-5 is especially useful on provenance: it is the GovInfo Compilation of Presidential Documents source, published by the Office of the Federal Register/NARA, for DCPD202501162. It identifies the same event date, title, and source note, and it places the remarks at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center. In the relevant passage, Trump says he met Ronaldo, then says Ronaldo is great; later, when asked whether he played soccer or football, Trump says he was not Ronaldo or Messi. Either use satisfies the mention rule if the remarks fall within the market’s time period.\\n\\nThird, the remarks are event-linked in the way the market title reasonably covers. PX-2 and PX-5 are not private gossip, rehearsal, or an unofficial leak. They are public presidential remarks at the World Cup Draw venue, with FIFA President Infantino present, repeatedly discussing the Draw, the World Cup, ticket sales, the Kennedy Center, the audience, and the imminent program. The transcript itself includes headings such as “2026 World Cup Draw Event,” “2026 World Cup Draw Event/John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts,” and “2026 World Cup Draw/Ticket Sales for World Cup.” Trump and Infantino even discuss being a little late to “get in there” and the audience waiting. That sequence is not a random earlier interview; it is part of the public event appearance immediately surrounding the Draw.\\n\\nFourth, PX-3’s terms do not impose defendant’s formal-only line. They say the underlying is words used by the entity during the specified time period; a time period may be an event or context; and, when a time period refers to a specific event, the Exchange may specify what is included. They also say official/published content presented as part of the official presentation can count, while behind-the-scenes, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings do not count unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. Those exclusions show what this is not. The transcript is an official published record of public remarks at the event venue, not a hidden backstage clip. Nothing in PX-1 or PX-3 clearly tells traders that public, event-linked venue remarks immediately before the formal program are out.\\n\\nDefendant’s best point is PX-4 and the formal Roll Call/Factba.se page: there is a separate formal-drawing transcript, and my search found no “Ronaldo” there. Plaintiff does not hide that. But that adverse point proves only that the narrower formal-program source may omit the strike. It does not answer the contractual question. If Kalshi had meant to resolve solely by that formal transcript, it could have said so. Instead, the public market title used the broader phrase “during the FIFA World Cup Draw,” and the mention terms leave event boundaries to what the market clearly specifies.\\n\\nOn burden, plaintiff does not need absolute certainty or a formal-stage mention. Plaintiff must show it is more likely than not that the market wording plus terms include the event-linked remarks. The evidence satisfies that standard: PX-1 gives no exclusion; PX-2 and PX-5 prove the standalone Ronaldo mentions in public World Cup Draw venue remarks; PX-3 supplies a flexible event/time-period framework and excludes only categories unlike this source; PX-4 merely identifies the defense’s alternate formal-program boundary. The fair resolution is Yes.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the record now makes the defense point sharper, not weaker. Plaintiff has proved that Trump said \\\"Ronaldo\\\" in an official transcript of remarks connected to the World Cup Draw. Plaintiff has not proved that those remarks were during the market event.\\n\\nStart with the contract. DX/PX-1 gives the trader-facing question: \\\"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\\" It does not say \\\"at the Kennedy Center,\\\" \\\"on World Cup Draw day,\\\" \\\"in remarks prior to the Draw,\\\" or \\\"in any public press exchange associated with the Draw.\\\" For this strike to resolve Yes, the relevant mention must fall inside that specified time period.\\n\\nThe strongest evidence of the Ronaldo utterance is also the strongest evidence against plaintiff's boundary. PX-2 and PX-5 are titled \\\"Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw.\\\" PX-5, plaintiff's GovInfo/OFR source, confirms the same title, says the remarks were joined in progress, identifies the source as an exchange with the news media, and notes that some portions could not be verified because the audio was incomplete. That evidence proves an official pre-event reporter transcript. It does not prove the reporter exchange was the FIFA World Cup Draw.\\n\\nThe terms, PX-3, require words used by the entity during the specified time period. They permit an event or context as a time period, and they discuss what is included when the time period is a specific event. That framework does not turn all event-adjacent speech into event speech. The distinction between official presentation content and non-included behind-the-scenes or unofficial content matters because the question is not just whether a record is public or official. The question is whether this source was part of the market's event period. A public official transcript can still be a transcript of remarks prior to the event.\\n\\nDX-2 supplies the missing contrast. It is a focused extraction from the separate Roll Call/Factba.se formal FIFA World Cup Drawing transcript. That page is the formal source identified in the case-packet archive note. It is titled \\\"Remarks: Donald Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing in Washington - December 5, 2025.\\\" Its transcript begins with the formal drawing participants; at 00:00:50, Infantino says, \\\"This is the World Cup trophy\\\" and \\\"we are now going to do the draw.\\\" The page's Trump soccer answer mentions Pele and the Cosmos, not Ronaldo. The extracted page text was searched for both \\\"Ronaldo\\\" and \\\"Messi\\\" and neither appears.\\n\\nThat does not prove Trump never said Ronaldo anywhere at the venue. It proves the opposite boundary from plaintiff's: the formal Draw transcript is separate from the pre-event reporter exchange, and the formal transcript does not contain the strike. Plaintiff needs a bridge between those two sources. It has not offered one. There is no market page detail saying red-carpet or pre-program press remarks count. There is no official program metadata showing the reporter exchange was part of the Draw presentation. There is no source hierarchy provision selecting the pre-event reporter exchange over the formal Draw transcript for this market.\\n\\nPlaintiff argues ambiguity should favor Yes because Kalshi could have drafted a narrower rule. But this is a preponderance case about a challenged No resolution, not a penalty for every conceivable ambiguity. The ordinary reading of \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw\\\" is the draw program, not every public appearance immediately before it. The record's own labels preserve that ordinary line: \\\"Prior to\\\" on the Ronaldo source; \\\"Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing\\\" on the formal source; and a formal transcript that starts the draw and omits the strike.\\n\\nWeight and provenance also favor the defense on the decisive issue. PX-5 is official and useful, but it authenticates a pre-event reporter exchange. DX-2 is a captured formal transcript extraction from the source class identified in PX-4; its absence finding is limited but material. PX-4 was initially only a note that the formal page existed and could not be retrieved. We have now retrieved and searched it. The adverse check therefore confirms, rather than merely speculates, that the formal drawing transcript does not carry plaintiff's Ronaldo mention.\\n\\nThe council should resolve the proposition against plaintiff. The record shows Trump said Ronaldo before the FIFA World Cup Draw in an event-linked reporter exchange. It does not show he said Ronaldo during the FIFA World Cup Draw. On this market wording and these terms, the challenged No resolution should stand.\\n\\nRebuttals:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, defendant’s new formal-transcript extraction proves less than defendant needs.\\n\\nPlaintiff accepts the narrow fact defendant has now preserved: the Roll Call/Factba.se formal drawing-program extraction contains no “Ronaldo” or “Messi.” That is why plaintiff did not build the case on a formal-stage mention. The proposition instead asks whether the market wording and mention terms clearly excluded Trump’s public, official, event-linked remarks at the venue immediately before the formal program. Defendant has not supplied that exclusion.\\n\\nDefendant’s argument treats the title “Prior to the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw” as if “prior to” automatically means outside the Kalshi market’s event period. But PX-1 does not say “formal transcript only,” “after the draw host begins,” “after 00:00:50,” or “excluding press availability at the venue.” It asks what Trump would say “during the FIFA World Cup Draw.” The source label tells us sequence; it does not tell us the market’s legal boundary.\\n\\nDX-2 actually illustrates why defendant’s bright line is chosen after the fact. In defendant’s own formal extraction, the page begins before the mechanical draw: Mark Carney speaks at 00:00:00, and Infantino says at 00:00:50, “we are now going to do the draw.” If “during the FIFA World Cup Draw” can include ceremony and preamble on the formal page before the draw itself begins, then the phrase is not self-defining down to a single moment or transcript. The question is what the market clearly specified. It did not specify defendant’s transcript-only rule.\\n\\nThe terms do not fill that gap for defendant. PX-3 excludes hidden categories such as rehearsals, sound checks, unofficial recordings, and behind-the-scenes content unless officially published as part of the period. PX-2 and PX-5 are not those categories. PX-5 is an official GovInfo/OFR presidential transcript, published with source metadata, at 11:13 a.m. at the Kennedy Center, with FIFA’s president present and the World Cup Draw repeatedly discussed. That gives the Ronaldo mentions strong provenance and an event connection; it does not make them informal backstage chatter.\\n\\nDefendant says plaintiff needs a bridge. The bridge is the market text plus the terms’ failure to draw the narrow line defendant proposes. A No resolution can stand only if the contract fairly told traders that “during the FIFA World Cup Draw” meant only the separate formal-program transcript. On this record, the more likely reading is broader: public, official remarks at the venue, immediately tied to and immediately preceding the World Cup Draw program, were within the event-linked period unless clearly excluded.\\n\\nSo DX-2 narrows one factual issue but does not decide the case. It shows no formal-stage Ronaldo mention. It does not show that the market excluded the official pre-program event remarks where Trump did say Ronaldo. Under the preponderance standard, the Yes resolution remains the fair one.\\n\\nSurrebuttals:\\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff’s rebuttal usefully narrows the dispute. Plaintiff accepts that the formal Roll Call/Factba.se drawing transcript contains no “Ronaldo” or “Messi.” So the case remains entirely about whether a separate reporter exchange titled “Prior to the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw” should be treated as inside the market period.\\n\\nPlaintiff says “prior to” is only sequence, not legal boundary. But sequence is exactly what the market phrase makes material. The contract asks what Trump would say “during the FIFA World Cup Draw.” A source-agency title identifying the Ronaldo transcript as an exchange with reporters prior to that Draw is not a stray label; it is the best record description of when and what that source is. Plaintiff cannot convert that source into the event itself by saying the market failed to list every excluded pre-event setting.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s formal-preamble point also does not carry the burden. Yes, the formal transcript begins before the mechanical ball selection, and Infantino says at 00:00:50 that “we are now going to do the draw.” But that supports the defense distinction. A host’s preamble inside the formal drawing transcript is part of the program. A separate press exchange, separately titled and sourced as prior to the Draw, is not made part of the program simply because it happened nearby and discussed the same event.\\n\\nNor does official publication settle the issue. PX-5 strengthens provenance: Trump did say Ronaldo in an official public transcript. But provenance answers whether the words were said, not whether they were said during the market’s specified event. The terms require both: the word by the entity, and the word during the time period. Plaintiff has the first element. The second is still missing.\\n\\nThe remaining bridge plaintiff proposes is essentially: public, official, event-linked, and not expressly excluded. That is not enough under a preponderance standard when the same record supplies a cleaner boundary: the Ronaldo source is prior to the Draw, and the formal Draw source omits the strike. The challenged No resolution should stand.\\n\\nClosings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the record has narrowed to one real issue.\\n\\nThe word is proven. The market page identifies the strike as “Ronaldo” and the challenged resolution as No. The case-packet transcript and the GovInfo/OFR excerpt prove that Trump said “Ronaldo” as a standalone word in public remarks at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center, in a World Cup Draw setting, with FIFA President Infantino present, and amid repeated discussion of the Draw, the Kennedy Center, ticket sales, the audience, and the imminent event. That is strong provenance: GovInfo, NARA/OFR, DCPD202501162, matching the packet source and note.\\n\\nDefendant has also proved its best fact. The Roll Call/Factba.se formal-program extraction does not contain “Ronaldo” or “Messi.” Plaintiff does not ask you to find otherwise. If the market had said “only the formal drawing transcript,” defendant would win. But that is not the market traders saw.\\n\\nThe market asked: “What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?” It did not say “during the formal transcript only,” “after the host announces the draw has begun,” “excluding public press remarks at the venue,” or “excluding remarks immediately before the program.” The governing terms do not add that limitation. They define words used by the entity during the time period, allow event/context time periods, and exclude categories such as rehearsals, sound checks, behind-the-scenes content, and unofficial recordings. Plaintiff’s source is none of those. It is an official public presidential transcript of event-linked remarks at the venue.\\n\\nDefendant’s formal extraction shows why a bright line cannot simply be assumed. Even on that page, before balls are drawn, there is ceremony, introduction, and Infantino saying “we are now going to do the draw.” Event boundaries are not self-defining. The question is whether Kalshi clearly chose defendant’s narrower boundary. The record contains no such choice.\\n\\nSo the burden is met. More likely than not, a reasonable reading of the market and terms includes Trump’s official, public, venue-based remarks immediately tied to the World Cup Draw. The strongest contrary evidence proves only that a narrower formal transcript omits the strike. It does not prove the contract excluded the remarks where the strike was actually said.\\n\\nThe challenged No resolution should be overturned. The strike “Ronaldo” should resolve Yes.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff’s closing concedes the decisive factual split: the formal World Cup Drawing transcript contains no “Ronaldo” or “Messi.” The only Ronaldo evidence is the separate official transcript titled “Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw.”\\n\\nThat is enough to decide the case. The market did not ask what Trump would say at the Kennedy Center, on World Cup Draw day, in public presidential remarks, or in event-linked press availability. It asked what Trump would say “during the FIFA World Cup Draw.” The terms require the word to be used by the entity during the specified time period. Plaintiff has proven the word and the speaker. It has not proven the time period.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s strongest point is that the market did not expressly say “formal transcript only” or “exclude pre-program remarks.” But plaintiff has the burden. A challenged No resolution does not become Yes merely because the contract could have been even more verbose. The record must make it more likely than not that the pre-event reporter exchange was inside the market period. The record does the opposite.\\n\\nThe source labels matter. PX-2 and PX-5 are official and probative, but they are official proof of remarks prior to the Draw. The formal Roll Call/Factba.se extraction is the source for Trump’s formal attendance at the FIFA World Cup Drawing; it begins the program, includes the draw presentation, and omits the strike. Plaintiff’s theory asks you to treat a separate prior reporter exchange as “during” the Draw even though the formal Draw source exists and does not contain the word.\\n\\nThe terms do not collapse that distinction. They recognize event/context time periods and official presentation content, but they still require the word to occur during the chosen time period. Official publication proves provenance. Event connection proves relevance. Neither proves inclusion. A public official transcript can be accurately preserved and still be outside the market window if it is, as titled, prior to the event.\\n\\nSo the fair synthesis is narrow and grounded: Trump said Ronaldo in event-linked public remarks before the FIFA World Cup Draw; Trump did not say Ronaldo in the formal drawing transcript preserved in this record; and no admitted market term or source-chain evidence bridges the pre-event exchange into the market’s “during the FIFA World Cup Draw” period.\\n\\nUnder the preponderance standard, plaintiff has not carried the proposition. The challenged No resolution should stand.\\n\\nExhibits:\\n[plaintiff] PX-1 Market page and challenged resolution\\nMarket URL: https://kalshi.com/markets/kxtrumpmentionb/trump-mention-b/kxtrumpmentionb-25dec06\\n\\nPublic market title: What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\n\\nContract family: PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION\\n\\nStrike at issue: Ronaldo\\n\\nChallenged resolution: No\\n\\nRequested resolution: Yes\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-2 Pre-event reporter exchange transcript\\nRemarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\nDecember 05, 2025\\n\\n[The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\\nThe President. It's a great honor to be here. Gianni has done a fantastic job. We're setting records—[inaudible].\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. Well, I think so. They have a little bit of a shot. Pretty stiff competition. But I would say they would have a small chance.\\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize\\nQ. [Inaudible]—win the FIFA Peace Award?\\nThe President. Well, it would be an honor.\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\nQ. Will you root for some selection? Will you root for someone?\\nThe President. Well, I root for a lot of countries, but in this case, I'll be rooting for the U.S.A. [Laughter]\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. That's great. That's great. We really love it.\\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize\\nQ. Mr. President, have you been told that you are going to receive the inaugural peace prize today——\\nThe President. I have not——\\nQ. ——from FIFA?\\nThe President. I have not been told. There's a rumor about it, but I have not been told. That would be a great honor, and I'm a big fan of Gianni, as you know.\\nQ. What can fans expect——\\nQ. Are you hoping to receive that?\\nThe President. Excuse me.\\nQ. Are you hoping to receive the peace prize?\\nThe President. Well, I don't like to say \\\"hope,\\\" but it would be a great honor.\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. What can fans expect of, like, the World Cup in the U.S.?\\nThe President. I think it's going to be fantastic. We've set every record you can set.\\nQ. What are you telling people who are worried——\\nFédération Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) President Giovanni V. Infantino\\nQ. [Inaudible]—friend Gianni—[inaudible]—a word about him?\\nThe President. I think he has done a fantastic job.\\nThe President's Schedule\\nQ. Are you going to be meeting with the President of Mexico today and the——\\nThe President. We might. Yes.\\nQ. ——Prime Minister of Canada as well?\\nThe President. I might. I might do that.\\nQ. Will you be discussing immigration and trade with them?\\nThe President. Yes, we'll be discussing.\\n[At this point, the President and Mr. Infantino posed for photographs.]\\nThe President. Thank you, everybody.\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event/John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts\\nQ. Mr. President, what do you think about the crowd?\\nThe President. Oh, look, the new star—[inaudible].\\nCongratulations.\\nQ. Thank you.\\nThe President. You're the new star of television and Fox.\\nQ. Thank you. How are you doing, Mr. President?\\nThe President. I'm doing very well.\\nQ. What do you think about the crowd here?\\nThe President. I think the crowd is great, and I think the building is great. We've made a lot of improvements over the last 6 months. Taking—the Kennedy Center was in very bad shape. Now it's getting to be really good. And in 6 months, it's going to be incredible with the improvements we've made.\\nQ. The first time for the U.S. to host since the nineties.\\nThe President. Right.\\nQ. Are you ready for it?\\nThe President. I'm ready for it, and they're ready for it. And Gianni, who you know——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——has done a fantastic job with FIFA. And we're looking to have—you know, we're set—we have already set records for tickets sales. I don't think there's ever been anything like it in any sport. And so, I want to congratulate you.\\nMr. Infantino. Thank you.\\nThe President. I don't even have to wait. But major records have been set.\\nHow are you?\\nQ. Good, how are you, sir?\\nThe President. Nice to see you.\\nQ. Today it's not football—American football. It's soccer. It's——\\nThe President. Right.\\nQ. ——the big event of soccer.\\nThe President. That's right. That's right.\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\nQ. So can you tell me about this big day today?\\nThe President. It's just a big day, and it's a great sport. And it really is coming to America. And never—nobody ever thought a thing like this could happen. And I'm very happy to say that we've already set the alltime record on ticket sales long before the first ball is kicked. Right?\\nMr. Infantino. A hundred percent. One hundred percent.\\n2026 World Cup Host Cities\\nQ. You've had some concerns about crime in American cities, some of the cities that will be hosting. Have they remedied that for you? Are you still considering maybe asking FIFA to move some of those cities?\\nThe President. No, I don't want to do that. But I will tell you, if they do have a problem, by the time we get there, we'll take care of that problem. We can solve that problem.\\nI've proven that in DC and everywhere else we went, so we'll take care of that very easily. So, if they have a problem, hopefully, they'll let us know that, and we will solve any problem.\\nOkay? Thank you.\\nQ. Thank you so much.\\nMr. Infantino. All right, thank you so much.\\nQ. Thank you, Mr. President.\\nQ. Thank you. Appreciate it.\\nThe President. Congratulations.\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. Mr. President, Brazilian television. America will be hosting the World Cup and the Olympics in 2 years. How important it is—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. I think very. It's a great honor. I think Gianni is doing a phenomenal job. We've set every record on ticket sales. It's been really fantastic. But Gianni has done an unbelievable job with FIFA.\\nThe President's Experience With Soccer\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. He was a great—not only that. I got to see a man name Pelé play—right?—that tells you how old I am—when he was on the Cosmos. Do you remember that a long time ago? And it was quite a treat. That was quite an event. And he was—not only was he playing, he was great. He scored two goals, I think. And so, I was one of the few who got to see Pelé, and I assume he is one of your alltime greats. Right?\\nMr. Infantino. Definitely.\\nThe President. So I got to see him.\\nThe President's Favorite World Cup Competitor\\nQ. Do you have some favorite teams for World Cup?\\nThe President. Well, I have a favorite. It's the U.S.A. [Laughter] I don't know what their chances are, Gianni, but maybe the U.S.A. is the——\\nMr. Infantino. They're getting better and better, actually.\\nThe President. I think they'll do well.\\nMr. Infantino. They are getting better and better.\\nThe President. I think they'll do well.\\nThank you very much, everybody.\\nQ. Thank you so much.\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. Mr. President, World Cup in America just means—[inaudible]. So what do you expect from this World Cup?\\nThe President. [Inaudible]—record business and only in the United States, but we're also doing record ticket sales with FIFA. And they've already bought—beat their highest record. And we—you know, this a long time before the first ball is kicked. You've sold more tickets than they've ever done before, and better pricing than they've ever gotten before. It's a tremendous success. And it's an honor. And Gianni has done a phenomenal job with FIFA.\\nQ. [Inaudible]—ever?\\nThe President. I think so. I think it's going to be—I mean, ideally, you want to see that every year. Every 4 years, it gets bigger and better. I think we have set every record in the book. We're very happy about it.\\nThank you.\\nThe President's Favorite World Cup Competitor\\nQ. [Inaudible]—part of America. Who are you going to support as well?\\nThe President. Well, I think I have to support U.S.A. Otherwise, I'd be in trouble. I wouldn't be President for long.\\nMr. Infantino. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. [Inaudible]—but you have a lot of great teams. You're going to have a lot of great teams.\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\\\"football,\\\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\\n2026 World Cup Draw/Ticket Sales for World Cup\\nQ. How does it feel to be part of this amazing event? And obviously, your being a part of participating in all the—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. The President of Mexico is here, and she's doing a very good job. She's a good woman, very, very excellent job. It's an honor, and we're setting every record, and you're helping us set those records.\\nMr. Infantino. And we will do it.\\nThe President. You know, Mexico and Canada are helping us set those records. But as you know, we have a record in ticket sales already, long before the first ball is kicked, and we're going to do great.\\nI think that Gianni—as you know, he's the head, and he has done a fantastic job.\\nU.S. Cooperation With Mexico and Canada\\nQ. And how is the biggest challenge being three countries?\\nThe President. Well, I think that—do you mean for the three countries?\\nWell, they've gotten together really well, I mean.\\nMr. Infantino. All right.\\nThe President. They're getting along very well.\\nMr. Infantino. Collaboration is fantastic between the three.\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer/2026 World Cup\\nQ. And you like soccer?\\nThe President. I do. I like it. I like it more and more.\\nQ. Yes?\\nThe President. I like it. It's growing in this country—very, really—I mean, someday, maybe it's going to be bigger than anything else.\\nMr. Infantino. We'll have to become number one.\\nThe President. I will say this——\\nMr. Infantino. Definitely.\\nThe President. ——the ticket sales——\\nQ. Definitely will happen.\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. Ticket sales are bigger than anything we have ever done in the history of the country, in terms of sports.\\nMr. Infantino. For certain.\\nQ. And the audience is going to be huge.\\nThe President. The audience is going to be tremendous.\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. Yes.\\nMr. Infantino. Six billion people.\\nThe President. [Inaudible]\\nQ. Six billion? That's amazing.\\nMr. Infantino. Six billion people.\\nAnd today, one billion.\\nQ. Wow.\\nMr. Infantino. [Inaudible]\\nQ. Enjoy show time. Thank you so much.\\nThe President. [Inaudible]\\nQ. Mr. President, how are you? Just a quick—[inaudible].\\nQ. This is for Telemundo.\\nThe President. How are you?\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\nQ. Hello, Mr. President. How are you? This for Telemundo.\\nThe President. How are you? Good.\\nQ. How are you?\\nThe President. Very good. Thank you.\\nQ. How does it feel to have the most important event of sports—that global—in the U.S.?\\nThe President. Well, we do. And right at the Kennedy Center. I'm Chairman of the Kennedy Center. And I hear the Kennedy Center is doing a very good job, so it feels great. Really good.\\nAnd Telemundo is doing a good job, too. Thank you.\\nQ. Thank you.\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. What is the significance of hosting the FIFA World Cup this year?\\nThe President. It's a—in terms of sports, I would say the ultimate. There is no sport like this. It's the biggest sport in the world. And we are setting every record. You know, our ticket sales have gone and set every—every sport—no matter what it is, we've set the record. So—and every though it's very early, there's no ball being kicked yet, but we've already set a ticket sales record.\\nArgentina National Team\\nQ. How do you see Argentinean team for this World Cup?\\nThe President. Well, I love Argentina. And your President is doing a very good job, as you know. Milei. You know that right? It's make Argentina great again. MAGA.\\nQ. And——\\nU.S. National Team\\nQ. Do you think the States are building a powerful team for next year?\\nThe President. Who?\\nQ. The States.\\nThe President. Oh, yes. Sure. I—you're going to have a lot of powerful teams. Everybody has a lot of powerful teams, but you're going to have a lot of great teams. [Inaudible]\\nU.S. Role in Hosting the 2026 World Cup\\nQ. Mr. President, what does it mean for you guys to host the World Cup right here in the U.S.?\\nThe President. I'm honored to host it. It's a great honor. I mean, it's turned out to be bigger than we thought. We're setting a record for ticket sales, the likes of which no sport has ever seen before.\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\\nThe President. But they have a little more speed.\\nBut no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\\nPopularity of Soccer in Latin America\\nQ. Mr. President, a message for the Latin America and soccer fans?\\nThe President. Yes, I am. And Latin America is great. And they have great soccer. So, good luck in the matches.\\n[A reporter asked a question in Spanish, which was translated by an interpreter as follows.]\\nU.S. Visas for World Cup Ticketholders\\nQ. Who is going to be in—[inaudible]—about these visas for the—these fans that want to come here to the World Cup?\\nThe President. Well, we're going to make it very easy for them. We're working on that right now. We're going to make it very easy. It's going to be a very easy process.\\nQ. Okay. Say, hi to Colombia over there.\\nThe President. Hello. Is that Colombia?\\nQ. Yes.\\nThe President. I love Colombia. Hello, Colombia. [Laughter]\\nQ. Okay. Okay. Muy bien.\\nThe President. So where are you from?\\nQ. Paraguay.\\nThe President. Oh.\\nQ. He's from Paraguay. Yes.\\nThe President. Very good. I love it. I—it's a beautiful country. We get along very well with them. We do a little trade deal with them, and they like us. And that's what's happening.\\nQ. Panama.\\nThe President. Where?\\nVery good. I like the canal. [Laughter] That canal is pretty good.\\n[A reporter spoke in Spanish; no translation was provided.]\\n2026 World Cup\\nThe President. What?\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. Well, it's going to be incredible. The event is going to be very good. Just this event alone—it's at the Kennedy Center. I see you have it fixed up perfectly.\\nMr. Infantino. It will set the tone.\\nThe President. Right? It's beautiful.\\nMr. Infantino. It's beautiful.\\nThe President. It's a beautiful place.\\nHave a good time.\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President.\\n[A reporter spoke in Spanish; no translation was provided.]\\nMr. Infantino. No, gracias. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. It's great.\\nJohn F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts/Renovation Work\\nQ. Mr. President, the U.S. press?\\nThe President. Thank you, everybody, very much. It's a great honor. This has been an honor for a lot of reasons. Number one, they've sold more tickets than any event has ever sold already—long before the kickoff.\\nAnd number two, we've done a lot of work at the Kennedy Center. It was falling apart, and now it's pretty much back. And we'll get it back within the next 4 or 5 months through construction, and—but you see the way it looks.\\nAnd Gianni is just telling me—who's done an incredible job, by the way. He's just telling, you know, how good a job we've done.\\nMr. Infantino. That's right.\\nThe President. You can look at the walls. The marble was broken. Everything was a mess. And we've really taken the Kennedy Center—a lot of people thought it was going to be ripped down, and we did just the opposite. So we've done a really great renovation job on it. And over the next 3, 4 months, it will be complete. And we're honored to have it here, and it's been—it's been very special.\\nWe've set a record on ticket sales, as you probably heard, already, even way before—long before the event itself. And we're working with Canada, and we're working with Mexico. And it's been a really spectacular—so far, it's been spectacular.\\nDaniel [Daniel Baldwin, One America News Network], do you have a question?\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. What are your expectations? You once said that the FIFA World Cup is an opportunity to put—a once-in-a-lifetime opportunity to put the greatness of the United States on display.\\nThe President. Well, I think—\\nQ. One billion eyeballs will be watching, Mr. President.\\nThe President. Yes, I—think——\\nQ. What will they here today?\\nThe President. Even today, I understand. I hear that, you know——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——I know we're a little late to get in there, but——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——that's okay.\\nMr. Infantino. They wait.\\nThe President. So all my friends, I guess they have to wait. They have no choice, right? [Laughter]\\nMr. Infantino. Yes, they wait.\\nThe President. But no, the numbers are incredible. I hear today's numbers are——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——very big. I hope CNN is covering this.\\nQ. One billion eyeballs.\\nMr. Infantino. Today, 1 billion eyeballs.\\nThe President. Today's numbers are very, very big.\\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize/The President's Foreign Policy\\nQ. We are covering it. And you're expected to get the FIFA Peace Prize, Mr. President. What would you say to people who say that prize might conflict with your pledge to strike Venezuela?\\nThe President. Well, I think the peace prize—I mean, I settled eight wars. I don't know that I'm getting it. I haven't been officially noticed. I've been hearing about a peace prize, and I'm here to represent our country in a different sense. But I can tell you, I did settle eight wars, and we have a ninth coming, but—which nobody has ever done before.\\nBut I want to really save lives. I don't need prizes. I need to save lives. And we're saving a lot of lives. And I've saved millions and millions of lives, and that's really what I want to do.\\nAnd I also want to run a great country. And the United States right now is the hottest country anywhere in the world. And 1 year ago, it was dead. We had a dead country, and now we have the hottest country anywhere in the world.\\nQ. Mr. President, will you——\\nThe President's Meeting With President Claudia Sheinbaum Pardo of Mexico and Prime Minister Mark Carney of Canada\\nQ. What are you going to discuss with Canada and Mexico, Mr.—what are you going to discuss with the leaders of Canada and Mexico?\\nThe President. Well, we're getting—we're going to meet with both. And we're getting along very well. You know, we're getting along very well. I don't know. I think we have a meeting set up for some time after the event.\\nQ. Will you discuss trade?\\nThe President. Yes, we'll discuss trade. We—get along very well.\\nThank you, everybody, very much.\\nQ. Will you pardon any other Honduran officials?\\nQ. Do you want them to keep trying to indict Ms. James?\\n\\nNOTE: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. In his remarks, he referred to Trey Yingst, chief foreign correspondent, Fox News Channel; Cristiano Ronaldo, forward for Saudi Pro League club Al-Nass and Portugal's national soccer team; and Lionel Messi, forward for Major League Soccer club Inter Miami and Argentina's national team. A reporter referred to New York State Attorney General Letitia James. The transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\n\\nSource URL: https://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/documents/remarks-exchange-with-reporters-prior-the-2026-federation-internationale-des-associations\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-3 PRESMENTION/NEWMENTION terms\\n                                         NEWMENTION\\n\\nScope: These rules shall apply to this contract.\\n\\nUnderlying: The Underlying for this Contract is words used by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nRevisions to the Underlying made after Expiration will not be accounted for in determining the\\nExpiration Value.\\n\\nSource Agency: The Source Agencies are \\u003csource\\u003e.\\n\\nType: The type of Contract is an Event Contract.\\n\\nIssuance: After the initial Contract, Contract iterations will be listed on an as-needed basis at\\nthe discretion of the Exchange and corresponding to the risk management needs of Members.\\n\\n\\u003centity\\u003e: \\u003centity\\u003e refers to the speaker, writer, performer, or communicator specified by the\\nExchange. This may include (but is not limited to): a specific named individual, multiple\\nindividuals specified using AND/OR logic, an individual identified by position or title, a group,\\nband, team or collective entity, a specified member or members of a group, an organization,\\ncompany, or institutional entity, or any combination of the aforementioned.\\n\\nWhen \\u003centity\\u003e is defined by a position or title, the Contract tracks whoever holds that position\\nduring \\u003ctime period\\u003e, even if the individual holding the position changes. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a\\nspecific named individual, the identity remains consistent throughout. Name changes (e.g.,\\nstage names, married names) do not create a new entity. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a group or\\norganization and the Contract does not specify particular members, any official\\ncommunication or statement by any member or designated spokesperson counts. When using\\nAND logic, all specified entities must independently say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e. When\\nusing OR logic, at least one of the specified entities must say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nThe Exchange may specify additional conditions such as “at least X members of” a group or\\n“the majority of” a group.\\n\\n\\u003csource\\u003e: \\u003csource\\u003e refers to a Source Agency or ordered collection of Source Agencies\\nspecified by the Exchange at the time of Contract listing, which will be incorporated into the\\nSource Agency hierarchy above and used to determine the occurrence of the Underlying.\\n\\u003csource\\u003e may refer to a singular agency, multiple agencies, an agency by distinguishing\\ncharacteristics, by category or type (e.g., “official government statistical body,” “primary wire\\nservice”), or any combination thereof. When multiple agencies are specified, they may be\\napplied in the hierarchical order designated by the Exchange if so specified, with the highest-\\nranked available and responsive agency taking precedence for purposes of determining the\\nExpiration Value. A lower-ranked agency shall only be consulted if all higher-ranked agencies\\nare unavailable, unresponsive, have not reported on the Underlying by the Expiration time, or\\nif the Exchange, in its sole discretion, determines that a higher-ranked agency’s reporting is\\nincomplete, erroneous, or otherwise insufficient to determine the Expiration Value. If \\u003csource\\u003e\\ndesignates multiple agencies without specifying a hierarchical order, the Exchange shall\\nresolve any conflict between reporting agencies at its sole discretion.\\n\\n\\u003cword\\u003e: \\u003cword\\u003e refers to the particular word or phrase potentially to be mentioned by\\n\\u003centity\\u003e. It may refer to a word being said a minimum number of times. It may also refer to\\none of multiple words/phrases, any of which are acceptable (e.g., “Doge/Dogecoin”).\\n\\f\\u003ctime period\\u003e: \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific range of time, event or discrete date and\\ntime specified by the Exchange. This may be defined by, but is not limited to: a specific event\\nor context (e.g., “during the State of the Union address”), exact dates or times, relative time\\nmarkers (e.g., “before July 1, 2027,” “in Q1 2026”), event-based periods (e.g., “during any\\ncampaign rally in October 2026,” “during the awards ceremony”), and broader intervals (e.g.,\\n“Q1–Q2 2027,” “January–March 2026”).\\n\\nUnless stated otherwise, “Between” is inclusive of both endpoints, while “before” and “after”\\nexclude the specified date. \\u003ctime period\\u003e may also refer to “Any” or “None”, to multiple dates\\n(even if non-consecutive), or to a singular and discrete date or time.\\n\\nWhen \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event (such as an address, speech, performance, or\\nbroadcast), the Exchange may specify what is included, including whether it includes both live\\nand pre-recorded segments (including whether advertisements are included). Where a\\ntimezone is not specified, ET is assumed.\\n\\n\\nPayout Criterion: The Payout Criterion for the Contract encompasses the Expiration Values that\\n\\u003cword\\u003e is said by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n\\n\\nThe word must appear as a distinct, standalone unit, not buried inside another word. Plural\\nand possessive noun forms count. Other grammatical changes (tense, conjugation, derivation)\\ndo not. If \\u003cword\\u003e appears separated from other words by a space or hyphen or in a\\ncompound form with a space or hyphen, it counts. If \\u003cword\\u003e is fused into a single\\nunhyphenated word, it does not count.\\n\\nIf \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled, and the market contains a\\nstrike stating “Event does not qualify/occur”, such a strike shall resolve “Yes” and all others\\n“No”. If \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled but such strikes are NOT\\nlisted, the Contracts will resolve to the last fair price determined at the discretion of the\\nExchange. If the event is postponed, and such a postponement is announced by the end of the\\nfollowing calendar day to be rescheduled to a time within 14 calendar days, the markets shall\\nremain open. If the event captured in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast, the\\nExchange may keep the market open for 24 hours for the release of an official recording.\\nFurther granular details on conditions for these Contracts is available below.\\n\\nAdditional clarification(s):\\n\\n     Possessive noun forms of \\u003cword\\u003e, plurals, and possessive plural noun forms are\\n     INCLUDED:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigrants” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Egg” → “eggs’ shells” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Russia” → “Russia’s” counts, “Russian” does not\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e exists only in adjective form, no plural form exists:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Economic” → “Economics” does not count (“Economic” is an adjective\\n          for which “Economics” is not a plural)\\n     Plural nouns occurring within proper nouns and noun phrases are included:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Cat” → “Cats the musical” counts\\n\\f    Grammatical variations beyond plurals/possessives are NOT included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigration” does NOT count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Run” → “Running” or “Ran” do NOT count\\n    When \\u003cword\\u003e specifies a plural form, the singular does NOT count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Veterans” → “Veteran” does NOT count\\n    Words that are spelled the same as the plural form of \\u003cword\\u003e (if such exists) but are\\n    themselves not a plural noun are included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Wind” → “Winds up the clock” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Border” → “The United States has strong borders” counts\\n    Open compounds (words separated by spaces) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fire station” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “couch” → “couch potato” counts\\n    Hyphenated compounds (words connected by hyphens) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Palestine” → “pro-Palestine” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fat” → “non-fat” counts\\n    Closed compounds (single word, no spaces/hyphens) do not count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire” does not count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firefighter” does not count\\n    Multi-word \\u003cword\\u003e in larger constructions: When \\u003cword\\u003e is a multi-word phrase\\n    appearing within a hyphenated construction, it counts only if \\u003cword\\u003e appears as a\\n    complete, unmodified element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “New York” → “New York-based” counts (complete element)\\n    Portmanteaus (words blended from two words where parts of each are combined) are\\n    NOT included unless the portmanteau clearly contains \\u003cword\\u003e as a distinct, unaltered\\n    element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “MAGA” → “MAGA-nificent” counts (MAGA appears as distinct element)\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “magnificent” → “MAGA-nificent” does NOT count (portmanteau blend)\\n\\nDictionary determination: Both the Merriam-Webster Dictionary (available online) AND the\\nOxford English Dictionary shall be used to determine compound type and/or conventional\\nspelling patterns. Inclusion in either dictionary as an open or hyphenated compound shall\\nsatisfy the Payout Criterion. If neither provides clarity (or the word is not included),\\ndetermination is based on whether written as single unit (closed/doesn’t count) vs. spaces or\\nhyphens (open or hyphenated/counts) and/or context and previous usage.\\n\\nPHONETIC EQUIVALENCIES\\n\\n    Homophones (same sound, different spelling) do not count:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “write” → “right” does not count\\n    Homonyms and homographs (same spelling) COUNT regardless of meaning or\\n    pronunciation:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “bass” → both “bass guitar” and “bass fishing” count\\n    Proper and common nouns are treated identically:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Apple” → both “Apple Inc.” and “apple” (fruit) count\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Will” → both “Will Smith” and “I will go” count\\n    Minor unintentional mispronunciations COUNT if context makes intent clear:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Mamdani” → “Mandani” counts\\n    Severe mispronunciations that make \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable do NOT count.\\n    Trademarked spellings do not count, even when pronounced identically, unless the word\\n\\fitself is the same:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “lift” → “Lyft” (pronounced “lift”) does not count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “uber” → “Uber” counts\\nWords with non-standard transliteration to English count within reason, provided they are\\nphonetically equivalent:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Zelensky” → any of “Zelenski,” “Zelenskii,” “Zelensky,” or “Zelenskiy”\\n      count if pronounced equivalently\\nContractions do not count for their constituent words unless otherwise explicitly specified\\nby the Exchange:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “not” → “won’t,” “can’t,” “don’t,” “isn’t” do not count\\nNumbers spoken as words COUNT, when spoken exactly (not part of a larger number):\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “five” → saying “five” or reading “$5” aloud as “five dollars” counts,\\n      saying “five hundred” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “410” → “four hundred ten”, “four one zero” or “four ten” counts\\nOrdinals COUNT when \\u003cword\\u003e is written numerically OR a phrase that includes a\\nnumber:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “January 6” → “January 6th” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “3” (written numerically) → “3rd” (spoken as “third”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Eight War” → “8 Wars” and “Eighth War” will count\\nCardinal and ordinal number words are distinct:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “one” → “first” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “first” → “one” does NOT count\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count when pronunciation or letter-by-letter spelling\\nmatches \\u003cword\\u003e:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “NASA” (pronounced “NAH-suh”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “N-A-S-A” (spelled out) counts\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count as \\u003cword\\u003e when pronounced as the full word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Doctor” → “Dr.” (pronounced “Doctor”) counts\\nExpanded forms of acronyms do NOT count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “AI” → “artificial intelligence” does not count\\nWords in foreign languages do NOT count unless they are perfect cognates with an\\nEnglish word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fuego” (Spanish) does NOT count\\nEnglish words within foreign sentences count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “policy” → “Nuestra policy es clara” counts\\n\\u003cword\\u003e in organization/company names counts:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Securities” → “Bank of America Securities” counts\\nWords in URLs, emails, handles, and hashtags (exclusive of domain structure, email\\nprovider or symbols) are treated as compounds when spoken as complete words, with the\\ntype of compound subject to aforementioned rules:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firestation.com” pronounced “fire station dot com” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire.com” pronounced “wildfire dot com” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “apple” → “apple.com” pronounced “apple dot com” does count\\n      When presented in URL, email, handle, or hashtag form, \\u003cword\\u003e shall be treated as\\n      a compound, not a multi-word word\\nSung, rapped, or poetic words COUNT if phonetically recognizable:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “money” → “moneyyy” (extended in rap) counts\\n      Extreme distortion making \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable does NOT count.\\nPhonetic alphabet spelling (“Foxtrot India Romeo Echo” for “FIRE”) does NOT count.\\n\\fCANCELLATIONS AND DELAYS\\n\\n   The Exchange may list an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike for any Contract. If listed,\\n   such a strike refers to the structural conditions of the market, and is NOT adjudicated as a\\n   \\u003cword\\u003e needing to be said by or validated by having been said by \\u003centity\\u003e. If listed, this\\n   strike resolves to “Yes” whenever the event fails to occur or qualify under the Payout\\n   Criterion, or any other circumstance prevents normal resolution.\\n   If no such strike is listed, and \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, the following rules\\n   apply if the event is cancelled, postponed, rescheduled, or materially altered (including\\n   being closed to press) such that no video is released within one calendar day of the\\n   original start time of the event:\\n         If the event is cancelled, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price determined in\\n         the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         If the event is postponed or rescheduled, the outcome depends on whether a new\\n         date is publicly announced within one calendar day (i.e. if the event was scheduled\\n         to begin on Monday, any time up to 11:59PM on Tuesday falls within this period) of\\n         the originally scheduled start time:\\n               If no new date is announced within one calendar day, the Contract will resolve\\n               to the last fair price determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n               If a new date is announced within one calendar day, the outcome depends on\\n               when the rescheduled event is set to occur:\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls within fourteen (14) calendar days of the\\n                     originally scheduled date, the Contract shall remain open and \\u003cword\\u003e\\n                     stated during the rescheduled event will count.\\n                           The fourteen-day window begins at 12:00 AM ET on the originally\\n                           scheduled date and ends at 11:59 PM ET fourteen days later, unless\\n                           an alternate timezone is explicitly specified.\\n                           Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the State of the Union on January\\n                           15, 2026” rescheduled to January 20, 2026 → words spoken during\\n                           the rescheduled address count.\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls more than fourteen (14) calendar days after\\n                     the originally scheduled date, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price\\n                     determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         Any Contract that cannot be resolved through the Source Agency hierarchy will\\n         instead be settled at the Last Fair Price. The Exchange will disclose the methodology\\n         used to determine the Last Fair Price (e.g., Last Traded Price, Time-Weighted\\n         Average Price) at the time of Issuance.\\n         If an event begins but is interrupted, abbreviated, or ends prematurely, words\\n         stated by \\u003centity\\u003e during the portion of the event that did occur will count and the\\n         market will otherwise resolve.\\n   If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window but the venue, format, or medium\\n   changes (e.g., moved to a different location, changed from in-person to virtual (with the\\n   exception of being closed to press)), words stated during the event will count.\\n   Special condition: Across both cases, whether an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike is\\n   listed or not, if the event specified as or in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast (or\\n   relayed as such) but the live stream/broadcast does not occur, the Exchange will instead\\n   use an officially released recording as the Underlying, and may delay resolution by up to\\n   one calendar day to allow for the release of such a recording.\\n\\f          If partial snippets are released, Contracts on words that do not appear will be\\n          resolved to last fair price, and Contracts on those that do will be resolved to “Yes”.\\n          If no recording is released, the relevant outcomes triggered by the\\n          presence/absence of an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike shall occur as outlined\\n          above.\\n\\nTECHNICAL DETAILS (UNLESS OTHERWISE SPECIFIED)\\n\\n     When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, pre-recorded content broadcast,\\n     streamed, or published as part of that event is included if presented as part of the official\\n     presentation.\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the concert” with pre-recorded video interlude\\n          where entity speaks → words from interlude count\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the television appearance” with pre-taped\\n          segment aired during broadcast → words from segment count\\n     Behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are NOT\\n     included unless officially broadcast or published as part of \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n     Subtitles and captions that display \\u003cword\\u003e on screen but are not spoken aloud by\\n     \\u003centity\\u003e do NOT count.\\n     Sign language interpretation or usage by entity does NOT count as saying \\u003cword\\u003e unless\\n     the Contract explicitly specifies that sign language counts.\\n     Text that entity displays on screen (presentation slides, teleprompter visible to audience,\\n     signatures) does NOT count unless entity reads it aloud.\\n     Content generated by AI, deepfakes, or synthetic voice technology impersonating entity\\n     does NOT count unless the synthetic content is officially commissioned, authorized, or\\n     published by entity, OR the Contract explicitly specifies that AI-generated content counts.\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e is muted due to technical failure or censorship it shall not count unless\\n     corroborating contextual evidence (including surrounding speech, or an official\\n     uncensored recording or transcript) confirms that \\u003centity\\u003e specifically uttered \\u003cword\\u003e\\n     during the muted period.\\n\\nMinimum Tick: The Minimum Tick size for the Contract shall be $0.01.\\n\\nPosition Accountability Level: The Position Accountability Level for the Contract shall be\\n$25,000 per strike, per Member.\\n\\nLast Trading Date: The Last Trading Date of the Contract will be the Expiration Date. The Last\\nTrading Time will be the Expiration time.\\n\\nSettlement Date: The Settlement Date of the Contract shall be no later than the day after the\\nExpiration Date, unless the Market Outcome is under review pursuant to Rule 7.1.\\n\\nExpiration Date: When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event: The latest Expiration Date of\\nthe Contract shall be fourteen (14) calendar days after the originally scheduled date of the\\nevent. If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window, expiration will be moved to an\\nearlier date and time in accordance with Rule 7.2. When \\u003ctime period\\u003e is defined by specific\\ndates: The latest Expiration Date of the Contract shall be two weeks after the end of \\u003ctime\\nperiod\\u003e. If an event described in the Payout Criterion occurs and a consensus has been\\nreached on all terms, then expiration will be moved to an earlier date and time in accordance\\nwith Rule 7.2.\\n\\fExpiration time: The Expiration time of the Contract shall be 10:00 AM ET.\\n\\nSettlement Value: The Settlement Value for this Contract is $1.00.\\n\\nExpiration Value: The Expiration Value is the value of the Underlying as documented by the\\nSource Agency on the Expiration Date at the Expiration time.\\n\\nContingencies: Before Settlement, Kalshi may, at its sole discretion, initiate the Market\\nOutcome Review Process pursuant to Rule 7.1 of the Rulebook. If an Expiration Value cannot\\nbe determined on the Expiration Date, Kalshi has the right to determine payouts pursuant to\\nRule 7.1 in the Rulebook.\\n\\f\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-4 Formal draw archive note\\nSource checked: Roll Call / Factba.se archive\\n\\nArchive title: Remarks: Donald Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing in Washington - December 5, 2025\\n\\nArchive URL: https://rollcall.com/factbase/trump/transcript/donald-trump-remarks-fifa-world-cup-drawing-december-5-2025/\\n\\nWhat this file establishes:\\n\\nThere is a separate archived transcript page for Trump's formal attendance remarks at the draw.\\n\\nWhat this file does not establish:\\n\\nThis session could not retrieve the full transcript text from that archive.  The page is password-protected.  This example therefore does not claim, from local files alone, whether the formal program transcript does or does not contain the word \\\"Ronaldo.\\\"\\n\\nWhy this matters:\\n\\nThe complaint does not need to prove that the formal program omitted the strike.  It needs to show that Trump said \\\"Ronaldo\\\" in event-linked remarks and that the market boundary reasonably includes those remarks.  The formal archive remains relevant because it marks the distinction between the pre-event reporter exchange and the formal program.\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-5 GovInfo official transcript excerpt and metadata\\nSource: GovInfo, DCPD202501162, Office of the Federal Register / National Archives and Records Administration.\\nURL: https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/DCPD-202501162/html/DCPD-202501162.htm\\nTitle: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\nEvent date: December 5, 2025.\\n\\nRelevant extracted page text:\\n\\\"Administration of Donald J. Trump, 2025\\\"\\n\\\"Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw December 5, 2025\\\"\\n\\\"[The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\\\"\\n\\nUnder the section \\\"The President's Interest in Soccer\\\":\\n\\\"Q. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\\\"\\n\\\"The President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\\\\\\\"football,\\\\\\\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\\\"\\n\\\"Thank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\\\"\\n\\nAdditional relevant extracted page text:\\n\\\"The President's Interest in Soccer\\\"\\n\\\"Q. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\\\"\\n\\\"The President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\\\"\\n\\\"Mr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\\\"\\n\\\"The President. But they have a little more speed. But no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\\\"\\n\\nGovInfo note:\\n\\\"NOTE: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. In his remarks, he referred to Trey Yingst, chief foreign correspondent, Fox News Channel; Cristiano Ronaldo, forward for Saudi Pro League club Al-Nass and Portugal's national soccer team; and Lionel Messi, forward for Major League Soccer club Inter Miami and Argentina's national team. A reporter referred to New York State Attorney General Letitia James. The transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\\"\\n\\nGovInfo content details page also identifies category \\\"Interviews With the News Media : Exchanges with reporters, Washington, DC,\\\" subjects including \\\"Federation Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) World Cup,\\\" \\\"John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts,\\\" and \\\"Soccer,\\\" and names including \\\"Ronaldo, Cristiano\\\" and \\\"Messi, Lionel.\\\"\\n\\n[defendant] DX-1 Market wording and challenged resolution\\nMarket URL: https://kalshi.com/markets/kxtrumpmentionb/trump-mention-b/kxtrumpmentionb-25dec06\\n\\nPublic market title: What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\n\\nContract family: PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION\\n\\nStrike at issue: Ronaldo\\n\\nChallenged resolution: No\\n\\nRequested resolution: Yes\\n\\n\\n[defendant] DX-2 Pre-event reporter exchange transcript\\nRemarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\nDecember 05, 2025\\n\\n[The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\\nThe President. It's a great honor to be here. Gianni has done a fantastic job. We're setting records—[inaudible].\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. Well, I think so. They have a little bit of a shot. Pretty stiff competition. But I would say they would have a small chance.\\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize\\nQ. [Inaudible]—win the FIFA Peace Award?\\nThe President. Well, it would be an honor.\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\nQ. Will you root for some selection? Will you root for someone?\\nThe President. Well, I root for a lot of countries, but in this case, I'll be rooting for the U.S.A. [Laughter]\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. That's great. That's great. We really love it.\\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize\\nQ. Mr. President, have you been told that you are going to receive the inaugural peace prize today——\\nThe President. I have not——\\nQ. ——from FIFA?\\nThe President. I have not been told. There's a rumor about it, but I have not been told. That would be a great honor, and I'm a big fan of Gianni, as you know.\\nQ. What can fans expect——\\nQ. Are you hoping to receive that?\\nThe President. Excuse me.\\nQ. Are you hoping to receive the peace prize?\\nThe President. Well, I don't like to say \\\"hope,\\\" but it would be a great honor.\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. What can fans expect of, like, the World Cup in the U.S.?\\nThe President. I think it's going to be fantastic. We've set every record you can set.\\nQ. What are you telling people who are worried——\\nFédération Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) President Giovanni V. Infantino\\nQ. [Inaudible]—friend Gianni—[inaudible]—a word about him?\\nThe President. I think he has done a fantastic job.\\nThe President's Schedule\\nQ. Are you going to be meeting with the President of Mexico today and the——\\nThe President. We might. Yes.\\nQ. ——Prime Minister of Canada as well?\\nThe President. I might. I might do that.\\nQ. Will you be discussing immigration and trade with them?\\nThe President. Yes, we'll be discussing.\\n[At this point, the President and Mr. Infantino posed for photographs.]\\nThe President. Thank you, everybody.\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event/John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts\\nQ. Mr. President, what do you think about the crowd?\\nThe President. Oh, look, the new star—[inaudible].\\nCongratulations.\\nQ. Thank you.\\nThe President. You're the new star of television and Fox.\\nQ. Thank you. How are you doing, Mr. President?\\nThe President. I'm doing very well.\\nQ. What do you think about the crowd here?\\nThe President. I think the crowd is great, and I think the building is great. We've made a lot of improvements over the last 6 months. Taking—the Kennedy Center was in very bad shape. Now it's getting to be really good. And in 6 months, it's going to be incredible with the improvements we've made.\\nQ. The first time for the U.S. to host since the nineties.\\nThe President. Right.\\nQ. Are you ready for it?\\nThe President. I'm ready for it, and they're ready for it. And Gianni, who you know——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——has done a fantastic job with FIFA. And we're looking to have—you know, we're set—we have already set records for tickets sales. I don't think there's ever been anything like it in any sport. And so, I want to congratulate you.\\nMr. Infantino. Thank you.\\nThe President. I don't even have to wait. But major records have been set.\\nHow are you?\\nQ. Good, how are you, sir?\\nThe President. Nice to see you.\\nQ. Today it's not football—American football. It's soccer. It's——\\nThe President. Right.\\nQ. ——the big event of soccer.\\nThe President. That's right. That's right.\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\nQ. So can you tell me about this big day today?\\nThe President. It's just a big day, and it's a great sport. And it really is coming to America. And never—nobody ever thought a thing like this could happen. And I'm very happy to say that we've already set the alltime record on ticket sales long before the first ball is kicked. Right?\\nMr. Infantino. A hundred percent. One hundred percent.\\n2026 World Cup Host Cities\\nQ. You've had some concerns about crime in American cities, some of the cities that will be hosting. Have they remedied that for you? Are you still considering maybe asking FIFA to move some of those cities?\\nThe President. No, I don't want to do that. But I will tell you, if they do have a problem, by the time we get there, we'll take care of that problem. We can solve that problem.\\nI've proven that in DC and everywhere else we went, so we'll take care of that very easily. So, if they have a problem, hopefully, they'll let us know that, and we will solve any problem.\\nOkay? Thank you.\\nQ. Thank you so much.\\nMr. Infantino. All right, thank you so much.\\nQ. Thank you, Mr. President.\\nQ. Thank you. Appreciate it.\\nThe President. Congratulations.\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. Mr. President, Brazilian television. America will be hosting the World Cup and the Olympics in 2 years. How important it is—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. I think very. It's a great honor. I think Gianni is doing a phenomenal job. We've set every record on ticket sales. It's been really fantastic. But Gianni has done an unbelievable job with FIFA.\\nThe President's Experience With Soccer\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. He was a great—not only that. I got to see a man name Pelé play—right?—that tells you how old I am—when he was on the Cosmos. Do you remember that a long time ago? And it was quite a treat. That was quite an event. And he was—not only was he playing, he was great. He scored two goals, I think. And so, I was one of the few who got to see Pelé, and I assume he is one of your alltime greats. Right?\\nMr. Infantino. Definitely.\\nThe President. So I got to see him.\\nThe President's Favorite World Cup Competitor\\nQ. Do you have some favorite teams for World Cup?\\nThe President. Well, I have a favorite. It's the U.S.A. [Laughter] I don't know what their chances are, Gianni, but maybe the U.S.A. is the——\\nMr. Infantino. They're getting better and better, actually.\\nThe President. I think they'll do well.\\nMr. Infantino. They are getting better and better.\\nThe President. I think they'll do well.\\nThank you very much, everybody.\\nQ. Thank you so much.\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. Mr. President, World Cup in America just means—[inaudible]. So what do you expect from this World Cup?\\nThe President. [Inaudible]—record business and only in the United States, but we're also doing record ticket sales with FIFA. And they've already bought—beat their highest record. And we—you know, this a long time before the first ball is kicked. You've sold more tickets than they've ever done before, and better pricing than they've ever gotten before. It's a tremendous success. And it's an honor. And Gianni has done a phenomenal job with FIFA.\\nQ. [Inaudible]—ever?\\nThe President. I think so. I think it's going to be—I mean, ideally, you want to see that every year. Every 4 years, it gets bigger and better. I think we have set every record in the book. We're very happy about it.\\nThank you.\\nThe President's Favorite World Cup Competitor\\nQ. [Inaudible]—part of America. Who are you going to support as well?\\nThe President. Well, I think I have to support U.S.A. Otherwise, I'd be in trouble. I wouldn't be President for long.\\nMr. Infantino. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. [Inaudible]—but you have a lot of great teams. You're going to have a lot of great teams.\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\\\"football,\\\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\\n2026 World Cup Draw/Ticket Sales for World Cup\\nQ. How does it feel to be part of this amazing event? And obviously, your being a part of participating in all the—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. The President of Mexico is here, and she's doing a very good job. She's a good woman, very, very excellent job. It's an honor, and we're setting every record, and you're helping us set those records.\\nMr. Infantino. And we will do it.\\nThe President. You know, Mexico and Canada are helping us set those records. But as you know, we have a record in ticket sales already, long before the first ball is kicked, and we're going to do great.\\nI think that Gianni—as you know, he's the head, and he has done a fantastic job.\\nU.S. Cooperation With Mexico and Canada\\nQ. And how is the biggest challenge being three countries?\\nThe President. Well, I think that—do you mean for the three countries?\\nWell, they've gotten together really well, I mean.\\nMr. Infantino. All right.\\nThe President. They're getting along very well.\\nMr. Infantino. Collaboration is fantastic between the three.\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer/2026 World Cup\\nQ. And you like soccer?\\nThe President. I do. I like it. I like it more and more.\\nQ. Yes?\\nThe President. I like it. It's growing in this country—very, really—I mean, someday, maybe it's going to be bigger than anything else.\\nMr. Infantino. We'll have to become number one.\\nThe President. I will say this——\\nMr. Infantino. Definitely.\\nThe President. ——the ticket sales——\\nQ. Definitely will happen.\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. Ticket sales are bigger than anything we have ever done in the history of the country, in terms of sports.\\nMr. Infantino. For certain.\\nQ. And the audience is going to be huge.\\nThe President. The audience is going to be tremendous.\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. Yes.\\nMr. Infantino. Six billion people.\\nThe President. [Inaudible]\\nQ. Six billion? That's amazing.\\nMr. Infantino. Six billion people.\\nAnd today, one billion.\\nQ. Wow.\\nMr. Infantino. [Inaudible]\\nQ. Enjoy show time. Thank you so much.\\nThe President. [Inaudible]\\nQ. Mr. President, how are you? Just a quick—[inaudible].\\nQ. This is for Telemundo.\\nThe President. How are you?\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\nQ. Hello, Mr. President. How are you? This for Telemundo.\\nThe President. How are you? Good.\\nQ. How are you?\\nThe President. Very good. Thank you.\\nQ. How does it feel to have the most important event of sports—that global—in the U.S.?\\nThe President. Well, we do. And right at the Kennedy Center. I'm Chairman of the Kennedy Center. And I hear the Kennedy Center is doing a very good job, so it feels great. Really good.\\nAnd Telemundo is doing a good job, too. Thank you.\\nQ. Thank you.\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. What is the significance of hosting the FIFA World Cup this year?\\nThe President. It's a—in terms of sports, I would say the ultimate. There is no sport like this. It's the biggest sport in the world. And we are setting every record. You know, our ticket sales have gone and set every—every sport—no matter what it is, we've set the record. So—and every though it's very early, there's no ball being kicked yet, but we've already set a ticket sales record.\\nArgentina National Team\\nQ. How do you see Argentinean team for this World Cup?\\nThe President. Well, I love Argentina. And your President is doing a very good job, as you know. Milei. You know that right? It's make Argentina great again. MAGA.\\nQ. And——\\nU.S. National Team\\nQ. Do you think the States are building a powerful team for next year?\\nThe President. Who?\\nQ. The States.\\nThe President. Oh, yes. Sure. I—you're going to have a lot of powerful teams. Everybody has a lot of powerful teams, but you're going to have a lot of great teams. [Inaudible]\\nU.S. Role in Hosting the 2026 World Cup\\nQ. Mr. President, what does it mean for you guys to host the World Cup right here in the U.S.?\\nThe President. I'm honored to host it. It's a great honor. I mean, it's turned out to be bigger than we thought. We're setting a record for ticket sales, the likes of which no sport has ever seen before.\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\\nThe President. But they have a little more speed.\\nBut no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\\nPopularity of Soccer in Latin America\\nQ. Mr. President, a message for the Latin America and soccer fans?\\nThe President. Yes, I am. And Latin America is great. And they have great soccer. So, good luck in the matches.\\n[A reporter asked a question in Spanish, which was translated by an interpreter as follows.]\\nU.S. Visas for World Cup Ticketholders\\nQ. Who is going to be in—[inaudible]—about these visas for the—these fans that want to come here to the World Cup?\\nThe President. Well, we're going to make it very easy for them. We're working on that right now. We're going to make it very easy. It's going to be a very easy process.\\nQ. Okay. Say, hi to Colombia over there.\\nThe President. Hello. Is that Colombia?\\nQ. Yes.\\nThe President. I love Colombia. Hello, Colombia. [Laughter]\\nQ. Okay. Okay. Muy bien.\\nThe President. So where are you from?\\nQ. Paraguay.\\nThe President. Oh.\\nQ. He's from Paraguay. Yes.\\nThe President. Very good. I love it. I—it's a beautiful country. We get along very well with them. We do a little trade deal with them, and they like us. And that's what's happening.\\nQ. Panama.\\nThe President. Where?\\nVery good. I like the canal. [Laughter] That canal is pretty good.\\n[A reporter spoke in Spanish; no translation was provided.]\\n2026 World Cup\\nThe President. What?\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. Well, it's going to be incredible. The event is going to be very good. Just this event alone—it's at the Kennedy Center. I see you have it fixed up perfectly.\\nMr. Infantino. It will set the tone.\\nThe President. Right? It's beautiful.\\nMr. Infantino. It's beautiful.\\nThe President. It's a beautiful place.\\nHave a good time.\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President.\\n[A reporter spoke in Spanish; no translation was provided.]\\nMr. Infantino. No, gracias. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. It's great.\\nJohn F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts/Renovation Work\\nQ. Mr. President, the U.S. press?\\nThe President. Thank you, everybody, very much. It's a great honor. This has been an honor for a lot of reasons. Number one, they've sold more tickets than any event has ever sold already—long before the kickoff.\\nAnd number two, we've done a lot of work at the Kennedy Center. It was falling apart, and now it's pretty much back. And we'll get it back within the next 4 or 5 months through construction, and—but you see the way it looks.\\nAnd Gianni is just telling me—who's done an incredible job, by the way. He's just telling, you know, how good a job we've done.\\nMr. Infantino. That's right.\\nThe President. You can look at the walls. The marble was broken. Everything was a mess. And we've really taken the Kennedy Center—a lot of people thought it was going to be ripped down, and we did just the opposite. So we've done a really great renovation job on it. And over the next 3, 4 months, it will be complete. And we're honored to have it here, and it's been—it's been very special.\\nWe've set a record on ticket sales, as you probably heard, already, even way before—long before the event itself. And we're working with Canada, and we're working with Mexico. And it's been a really spectacular—so far, it's been spectacular.\\nDaniel [Daniel Baldwin, One America News Network], do you have a question?\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. What are your expectations? You once said that the FIFA World Cup is an opportunity to put—a once-in-a-lifetime opportunity to put the greatness of the United States on display.\\nThe President. Well, I think—\\nQ. One billion eyeballs will be watching, Mr. President.\\nThe President. Yes, I—think——\\nQ. What will they here today?\\nThe President. Even today, I understand. I hear that, you know——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——I know we're a little late to get in there, but——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——that's okay.\\nMr. Infantino. They wait.\\nThe President. So all my friends, I guess they have to wait. They have no choice, right? [Laughter]\\nMr. Infantino. Yes, they wait.\\nThe President. But no, the numbers are incredible. I hear today's numbers are——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——very big. I hope CNN is covering this.\\nQ. One billion eyeballs.\\nMr. Infantino. Today, 1 billion eyeballs.\\nThe President. Today's numbers are very, very big.\\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize/The President's Foreign Policy\\nQ. We are covering it. And you're expected to get the FIFA Peace Prize, Mr. President. What would you say to people who say that prize might conflict with your pledge to strike Venezuela?\\nThe President. Well, I think the peace prize—I mean, I settled eight wars. I don't know that I'm getting it. I haven't been officially noticed. I've been hearing about a peace prize, and I'm here to represent our country in a different sense. But I can tell you, I did settle eight wars, and we have a ninth coming, but—which nobody has ever done before.\\nBut I want to really save lives. I don't need prizes. I need to save lives. And we're saving a lot of lives. And I've saved millions and millions of lives, and that's really what I want to do.\\nAnd I also want to run a great country. And the United States right now is the hottest country anywhere in the world. And 1 year ago, it was dead. We had a dead country, and now we have the hottest country anywhere in the world.\\nQ. Mr. President, will you——\\nThe President's Meeting With President Claudia Sheinbaum Pardo of Mexico and Prime Minister Mark Carney of Canada\\nQ. What are you going to discuss with Canada and Mexico, Mr.—what are you going to discuss with the leaders of Canada and Mexico?\\nThe President. Well, we're getting—we're going to meet with both. And we're getting along very well. You know, we're getting along very well. I don't know. I think we have a meeting set up for some time after the event.\\nQ. Will you discuss trade?\\nThe President. Yes, we'll discuss trade. We—get along very well.\\nThank you, everybody, very much.\\nQ. Will you pardon any other Honduran officials?\\nQ. Do you want them to keep trying to indict Ms. James?\\n\\nNOTE: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. In his remarks, he referred to Trey Yingst, chief foreign correspondent, Fox News Channel; Cristiano Ronaldo, forward for Saudi Pro League club Al-Nass and Portugal's national soccer team; and Lionel Messi, forward for Major League Soccer club Inter Miami and Argentina's national team. A reporter referred to New York State Attorney General Letitia James. The transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\n\\nSource URL: https://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/documents/remarks-exchange-with-reporters-prior-the-2026-federation-internationale-des-associations\\n\\n\\n[defendant] DX-3 GovInfo/OFR pre-event transcript excerpt\\nSource: GovInfo, DCPD202501162, Office of the Federal Register / National Archives and Records Administration.\\nURL: https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/DCPD-202501162/html/DCPD-202501162.htm\\nTitle: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\nEvent date: December 5, 2025.\\n\\nRelevant extracted page text:\\n\\\"Administration of Donald J. Trump, 2025\\\"\\n\\\"Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw December 5, 2025\\\"\\n\\\"[The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\\\"\\n\\nUnder the section \\\"The President's Interest in Soccer\\\":\\n\\\"Q. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\\\"\\n\\\"The President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\\\\\\\"football,\\\\\\\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\\\"\\n\\\"Thank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\\\"\\n\\nAdditional relevant extracted page text:\\n\\\"The President's Interest in Soccer\\\"\\n\\\"Q. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\\\"\\n\\\"The President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\\\"\\n\\\"Mr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\\\"\\n\\\"The President. But they have a little more speed. But no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\\\"\\n\\nGovInfo note:\\n\\\"NOTE: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. In his remarks, he referred to Trey Yingst, chief foreign correspondent, Fox News Channel; Cristiano Ronaldo, forward for Saudi Pro League club Al-Nass and Portugal's national soccer team; and Lionel Messi, forward for Major League Soccer club Inter Miami and Argentina's national team. A reporter referred to New York State Attorney General Letitia James. The transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\\"\\n\\nGovInfo content details page also identifies category \\\"Interviews With the News Media : Exchanges with reporters, Washington, DC,\\\" subjects including \\\"Federation Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) World Cup,\\\" \\\"John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts,\\\" and \\\"Soccer,\\\" and names including \\\"Ronaldo, Cristiano\\\" and \\\"Messi, Lionel.\\\"\\n\\n[defendant] DX-4 PRESMENTION/NEWMENTION terms\\n                                         NEWMENTION\\n\\nScope: These rules shall apply to this contract.\\n\\nUnderlying: The Underlying for this Contract is words used by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nRevisions to the Underlying made after Expiration will not be accounted for in determining the\\nExpiration Value.\\n\\nSource Agency: The Source Agencies are \\u003csource\\u003e.\\n\\nType: The type of Contract is an Event Contract.\\n\\nIssuance: After the initial Contract, Contract iterations will be listed on an as-needed basis at\\nthe discretion of the Exchange and corresponding to the risk management needs of Members.\\n\\n\\u003centity\\u003e: \\u003centity\\u003e refers to the speaker, writer, performer, or communicator specified by the\\nExchange. This may include (but is not limited to): a specific named individual, multiple\\nindividuals specified using AND/OR logic, an individual identified by position or title, a group,\\nband, team or collective entity, a specified member or members of a group, an organization,\\ncompany, or institutional entity, or any combination of the aforementioned.\\n\\nWhen \\u003centity\\u003e is defined by a position or title, the Contract tracks whoever holds that position\\nduring \\u003ctime period\\u003e, even if the individual holding the position changes. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a\\nspecific named individual, the identity remains consistent throughout. Name changes (e.g.,\\nstage names, married names) do not create a new entity. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a group or\\norganization and the Contract does not specify particular members, any official\\ncommunication or statement by any member or designated spokesperson counts. When using\\nAND logic, all specified entities must independently say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e. When\\nusing OR logic, at least one of the specified entities must say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nThe Exchange may specify additional conditions such as “at least X members of” a group or\\n“the majority of” a group.\\n\\n\\u003csource\\u003e: \\u003csource\\u003e refers to a Source Agency or ordered collection of Source Agencies\\nspecified by the Exchange at the time of Contract listing, which will be incorporated into the\\nSource Agency hierarchy above and used to determine the occurrence of the Underlying.\\n\\u003csource\\u003e may refer to a singular agency, multiple agencies, an agency by distinguishing\\ncharacteristics, by category or type (e.g., “official government statistical body,” “primary wire\\nservice”), or any combination thereof. When multiple agencies are specified, they may be\\napplied in the hierarchical order designated by the Exchange if so specified, with the highest-\\nranked available and responsive agency taking precedence for purposes of determining the\\nExpiration Value. A lower-ranked agency shall only be consulted if all higher-ranked agencies\\nare unavailable, unresponsive, have not reported on the Underlying by the Expiration time, or\\nif the Exchange, in its sole discretion, determines that a higher-ranked agency’s reporting is\\nincomplete, erroneous, or otherwise insufficient to determine the Expiration Value. If \\u003csource\\u003e\\ndesignates multiple agencies without specifying a hierarchical order, the Exchange shall\\nresolve any conflict between reporting agencies at its sole discretion.\\n\\n\\u003cword\\u003e: \\u003cword\\u003e refers to the particular word or phrase potentially to be mentioned by\\n\\u003centity\\u003e. It may refer to a word being said a minimum number of times. It may also refer to\\none of multiple words/phrases, any of which are acceptable (e.g., “Doge/Dogecoin”).\\n\\f\\u003ctime period\\u003e: \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific range of time, event or discrete date and\\ntime specified by the Exchange. This may be defined by, but is not limited to: a specific event\\nor context (e.g., “during the State of the Union address”), exact dates or times, relative time\\nmarkers (e.g., “before July 1, 2027,” “in Q1 2026”), event-based periods (e.g., “during any\\ncampaign rally in October 2026,” “during the awards ceremony”), and broader intervals (e.g.,\\n“Q1–Q2 2027,” “January–March 2026”).\\n\\nUnless stated otherwise, “Between” is inclusive of both endpoints, while “before” and “after”\\nexclude the specified date. \\u003ctime period\\u003e may also refer to “Any” or “None”, to multiple dates\\n(even if non-consecutive), or to a singular and discrete date or time.\\n\\nWhen \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event (such as an address, speech, performance, or\\nbroadcast), the Exchange may specify what is included, including whether it includes both live\\nand pre-recorded segments (including whether advertisements are included). Where a\\ntimezone is not specified, ET is assumed.\\n\\n\\nPayout Criterion: The Payout Criterion for the Contract encompasses the Expiration Values that\\n\\u003cword\\u003e is said by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n\\n\\nThe word must appear as a distinct, standalone unit, not buried inside another word. Plural\\nand possessive noun forms count. Other grammatical changes (tense, conjugation, derivation)\\ndo not. If \\u003cword\\u003e appears separated from other words by a space or hyphen or in a\\ncompound form with a space or hyphen, it counts. If \\u003cword\\u003e is fused into a single\\nunhyphenated word, it does not count.\\n\\nIf \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled, and the market contains a\\nstrike stating “Event does not qualify/occur”, such a strike shall resolve “Yes” and all others\\n“No”. If \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled but such strikes are NOT\\nlisted, the Contracts will resolve to the last fair price determined at the discretion of the\\nExchange. If the event is postponed, and such a postponement is announced by the end of the\\nfollowing calendar day to be rescheduled to a time within 14 calendar days, the markets shall\\nremain open. If the event captured in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast, the\\nExchange may keep the market open for 24 hours for the release of an official recording.\\nFurther granular details on conditions for these Contracts is available below.\\n\\nAdditional clarification(s):\\n\\n     Possessive noun forms of \\u003cword\\u003e, plurals, and possessive plural noun forms are\\n     INCLUDED:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigrants” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Egg” → “eggs’ shells” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Russia” → “Russia’s” counts, “Russian” does not\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e exists only in adjective form, no plural form exists:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Economic” → “Economics” does not count (“Economic” is an adjective\\n          for which “Economics” is not a plural)\\n     Plural nouns occurring within proper nouns and noun phrases are included:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Cat” → “Cats the musical” counts\\n\\f    Grammatical variations beyond plurals/possessives are NOT included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigration” does NOT count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Run” → “Running” or “Ran” do NOT count\\n    When \\u003cword\\u003e specifies a plural form, the singular does NOT count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Veterans” → “Veteran” does NOT count\\n    Words that are spelled the same as the plural form of \\u003cword\\u003e (if such exists) but are\\n    themselves not a plural noun are included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Wind” → “Winds up the clock” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Border” → “The United States has strong borders” counts\\n    Open compounds (words separated by spaces) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fire station” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “couch” → “couch potato” counts\\n    Hyphenated compounds (words connected by hyphens) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Palestine” → “pro-Palestine” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fat” → “non-fat” counts\\n    Closed compounds (single word, no spaces/hyphens) do not count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire” does not count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firefighter” does not count\\n    Multi-word \\u003cword\\u003e in larger constructions: When \\u003cword\\u003e is a multi-word phrase\\n    appearing within a hyphenated construction, it counts only if \\u003cword\\u003e appears as a\\n    complete, unmodified element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “New York” → “New York-based” counts (complete element)\\n    Portmanteaus (words blended from two words where parts of each are combined) are\\n    NOT included unless the portmanteau clearly contains \\u003cword\\u003e as a distinct, unaltered\\n    element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “MAGA” → “MAGA-nificent” counts (MAGA appears as distinct element)\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “magnificent” → “MAGA-nificent” does NOT count (portmanteau blend)\\n\\nDictionary determination: Both the Merriam-Webster Dictionary (available online) AND the\\nOxford English Dictionary shall be used to determine compound type and/or conventional\\nspelling patterns. Inclusion in either dictionary as an open or hyphenated compound shall\\nsatisfy the Payout Criterion. If neither provides clarity (or the word is not included),\\ndetermination is based on whether written as single unit (closed/doesn’t count) vs. spaces or\\nhyphens (open or hyphenated/counts) and/or context and previous usage.\\n\\nPHONETIC EQUIVALENCIES\\n\\n    Homophones (same sound, different spelling) do not count:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “write” → “right” does not count\\n    Homonyms and homographs (same spelling) COUNT regardless of meaning or\\n    pronunciation:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “bass” → both “bass guitar” and “bass fishing” count\\n    Proper and common nouns are treated identically:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Apple” → both “Apple Inc.” and “apple” (fruit) count\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Will” → both “Will Smith” and “I will go” count\\n    Minor unintentional mispronunciations COUNT if context makes intent clear:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Mamdani” → “Mandani” counts\\n    Severe mispronunciations that make \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable do NOT count.\\n    Trademarked spellings do not count, even when pronounced identically, unless the word\\n\\fitself is the same:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “lift” → “Lyft” (pronounced “lift”) does not count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “uber” → “Uber” counts\\nWords with non-standard transliteration to English count within reason, provided they are\\nphonetically equivalent:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Zelensky” → any of “Zelenski,” “Zelenskii,” “Zelensky,” or “Zelenskiy”\\n      count if pronounced equivalently\\nContractions do not count for their constituent words unless otherwise explicitly specified\\nby the Exchange:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “not” → “won’t,” “can’t,” “don’t,” “isn’t” do not count\\nNumbers spoken as words COUNT, when spoken exactly (not part of a larger number):\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “five” → saying “five” or reading “$5” aloud as “five dollars” counts,\\n      saying “five hundred” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “410” → “four hundred ten”, “four one zero” or “four ten” counts\\nOrdinals COUNT when \\u003cword\\u003e is written numerically OR a phrase that includes a\\nnumber:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “January 6” → “January 6th” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “3” (written numerically) → “3rd” (spoken as “third”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Eight War” → “8 Wars” and “Eighth War” will count\\nCardinal and ordinal number words are distinct:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “one” → “first” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “first” → “one” does NOT count\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count when pronunciation or letter-by-letter spelling\\nmatches \\u003cword\\u003e:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “NASA” (pronounced “NAH-suh”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “N-A-S-A” (spelled out) counts\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count as \\u003cword\\u003e when pronounced as the full word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Doctor” → “Dr.” (pronounced “Doctor”) counts\\nExpanded forms of acronyms do NOT count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “AI” → “artificial intelligence” does not count\\nWords in foreign languages do NOT count unless they are perfect cognates with an\\nEnglish word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fuego” (Spanish) does NOT count\\nEnglish words within foreign sentences count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “policy” → “Nuestra policy es clara” counts\\n\\u003cword\\u003e in organization/company names counts:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Securities” → “Bank of America Securities” counts\\nWords in URLs, emails, handles, and hashtags (exclusive of domain structure, email\\nprovider or symbols) are treated as compounds when spoken as complete words, with the\\ntype of compound subject to aforementioned rules:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firestation.com” pronounced “fire station dot com” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire.com” pronounced “wildfire dot com” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “apple” → “apple.com” pronounced “apple dot com” does count\\n      When presented in URL, email, handle, or hashtag form, \\u003cword\\u003e shall be treated as\\n      a compound, not a multi-word word\\nSung, rapped, or poetic words COUNT if phonetically recognizable:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “money” → “moneyyy” (extended in rap) counts\\n      Extreme distortion making \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable does NOT count.\\nPhonetic alphabet spelling (“Foxtrot India Romeo Echo” for “FIRE”) does NOT count.\\n\\fCANCELLATIONS AND DELAYS\\n\\n   The Exchange may list an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike for any Contract. If listed,\\n   such a strike refers to the structural conditions of the market, and is NOT adjudicated as a\\n   \\u003cword\\u003e needing to be said by or validated by having been said by \\u003centity\\u003e. If listed, this\\n   strike resolves to “Yes” whenever the event fails to occur or qualify under the Payout\\n   Criterion, or any other circumstance prevents normal resolution.\\n   If no such strike is listed, and \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, the following rules\\n   apply if the event is cancelled, postponed, rescheduled, or materially altered (including\\n   being closed to press) such that no video is released within one calendar day of the\\n   original start time of the event:\\n         If the event is cancelled, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price determined in\\n         the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         If the event is postponed or rescheduled, the outcome depends on whether a new\\n         date is publicly announced within one calendar day (i.e. if the event was scheduled\\n         to begin on Monday, any time up to 11:59PM on Tuesday falls within this period) of\\n         the originally scheduled start time:\\n               If no new date is announced within one calendar day, the Contract will resolve\\n               to the last fair price determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n               If a new date is announced within one calendar day, the outcome depends on\\n               when the rescheduled event is set to occur:\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls within fourteen (14) calendar days of the\\n                     originally scheduled date, the Contract shall remain open and \\u003cword\\u003e\\n                     stated during the rescheduled event will count.\\n                           The fourteen-day window begins at 12:00 AM ET on the originally\\n                           scheduled date and ends at 11:59 PM ET fourteen days later, unless\\n                           an alternate timezone is explicitly specified.\\n                           Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the State of the Union on January\\n                           15, 2026” rescheduled to January 20, 2026 → words spoken during\\n                           the rescheduled address count.\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls more than fourteen (14) calendar days after\\n                     the originally scheduled date, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price\\n                     determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         Any Contract that cannot be resolved through the Source Agency hierarchy will\\n         instead be settled at the Last Fair Price. The Exchange will disclose the methodology\\n         used to determine the Last Fair Price (e.g., Last Traded Price, Time-Weighted\\n         Average Price) at the time of Issuance.\\n         If an event begins but is interrupted, abbreviated, or ends prematurely, words\\n         stated by \\u003centity\\u003e during the portion of the event that did occur will count and the\\n         market will otherwise resolve.\\n   If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window but the venue, format, or medium\\n   changes (e.g., moved to a different location, changed from in-person to virtual (with the\\n   exception of being closed to press)), words stated during the event will count.\\n   Special condition: Across both cases, whether an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike is\\n   listed or not, if the event specified as or in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast (or\\n   relayed as such) but the live stream/broadcast does not occur, the Exchange will instead\\n   use an officially released recording as the Underlying, and may delay resolution by up to\\n   one calendar day to allow for the release of such a recording.\\n\\f          If partial snippets are released, Contracts on words that do not appear will be\\n          resolved to last fair price, and Contracts on those that do will be resolved to “Yes”.\\n          If no recording is released, the relevant outcomes triggered by the\\n          presence/absence of an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike shall occur as outlined\\n          above.\\n\\nTECHNICAL DETAILS (UNLESS OTHERWISE SPECIFIED)\\n\\n     When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, pre-recorded content broadcast,\\n     streamed, or published as part of that event is included if presented as part of the official\\n     presentation.\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the concert” with pre-recorded video interlude\\n          where entity speaks → words from interlude count\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the television appearance” with pre-taped\\n          segment aired during broadcast → words from segment count\\n     Behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are NOT\\n     included unless officially broadcast or published as part of \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n     Subtitles and captions that display \\u003cword\\u003e on screen but are not spoken aloud by\\n     \\u003centity\\u003e do NOT count.\\n     Sign language interpretation or usage by entity does NOT count as saying \\u003cword\\u003e unless\\n     the Contract explicitly specifies that sign language counts.\\n     Text that entity displays on screen (presentation slides, teleprompter visible to audience,\\n     signatures) does NOT count unless entity reads it aloud.\\n     Content generated by AI, deepfakes, or synthetic voice technology impersonating entity\\n     does NOT count unless the synthetic content is officially commissioned, authorized, or\\n     published by entity, OR the Contract explicitly specifies that AI-generated content counts.\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e is muted due to technical failure or censorship it shall not count unless\\n     corroborating contextual evidence (including surrounding speech, or an official\\n     uncensored recording or transcript) confirms that \\u003centity\\u003e specifically uttered \\u003cword\\u003e\\n     during the muted period.\\n\\nMinimum Tick: The Minimum Tick size for the Contract shall be $0.01.\\n\\nPosition Accountability Level: The Position Accountability Level for the Contract shall be\\n$25,000 per strike, per Member.\\n\\nLast Trading Date: The Last Trading Date of the Contract will be the Expiration Date. The Last\\nTrading Time will be the Expiration time.\\n\\nSettlement Date: The Settlement Date of the Contract shall be no later than the day after the\\nExpiration Date, unless the Market Outcome is under review pursuant to Rule 7.1.\\n\\nExpiration Date: When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event: The latest Expiration Date of\\nthe Contract shall be fourteen (14) calendar days after the originally scheduled date of the\\nevent. If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window, expiration will be moved to an\\nearlier date and time in accordance with Rule 7.2. When \\u003ctime period\\u003e is defined by specific\\ndates: The latest Expiration Date of the Contract shall be two weeks after the end of \\u003ctime\\nperiod\\u003e. If an event described in the Payout Criterion occurs and a consensus has been\\nreached on all terms, then expiration will be moved to an earlier date and time in accordance\\nwith Rule 7.2.\\n\\fExpiration time: The Expiration time of the Contract shall be 10:00 AM ET.\\n\\nSettlement Value: The Settlement Value for this Contract is $1.00.\\n\\nExpiration Value: The Expiration Value is the value of the Underlying as documented by the\\nSource Agency on the Expiration Date at the Expiration time.\\n\\nContingencies: Before Settlement, Kalshi may, at its sole discretion, initiate the Market\\nOutcome Review Process pursuant to Rule 7.1 of the Rulebook. If an Expiration Value cannot\\nbe determined on the Expiration Date, Kalshi has the right to determine payouts pursuant to\\nRule 7.1 in the Rulebook.\\n\\f\\n\\n[defendant] DX-5 Formal draw archive note\\nSource checked: Roll Call / Factba.se archive\\n\\nArchive title: Remarks: Donald Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing in Washington - December 5, 2025\\n\\nArchive URL: https://rollcall.com/factbase/trump/transcript/donald-trump-remarks-fifa-world-cup-drawing-december-5-2025/\\n\\nWhat this file establishes:\\n\\nThere is a separate archived transcript page for Trump's formal attendance remarks at the draw.\\n\\nWhat this file does not establish:\\n\\nThis session could not retrieve the full transcript text from that archive.  The page is password-protected.  This example therefore does not claim, from local files alone, whether the formal program transcript does or does not contain the word \\\"Ronaldo.\\\"\\n\\nWhy this matters:\\n\\nThe complaint does not need to prove that the formal program omitted the strike.  It needs to show that Trump said \\\"Ronaldo\\\" in event-linked remarks and that the market boundary reasonably includes those remarks.  The formal archive remains relevant because it marks the distinction between the pre-event reporter exchange and the formal program.\\n\\n\\n[defendant] DX-6 Formal Roll Call/Factba.se transcript extraction\\nSource: Roll Call / Factba.se\\nURL: https://rollcall.com/factbase/trump/transcript/donald-trump-remarks-fifa-world-cup-drawing-december-5-2025/\\nCaptured page title: Remarks: Donald Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing in Washington - December 5, 2025\\n\\nRendered page metadata excerpt:\\nTopics: Sport; Sport \\u003e Competition Discipline \\u003e Soccer; Lifestyle and Leisure \\u003e Leisure \\u003e Game.\\nEntities listed: bowl; deal; Donald J. Trump; FIFA World Cup; Mark Carney; place; President; trophy; United States; way.\\nSpeakers listed: Gianni Infantino, Donald Trump, Mark Carney, Claudia Sheinbaum.\\nSpeaker statistics excerpt: Donald Trump said 25 sentences of a total of 141 sentences; Donald Trump said 274 words of a total of 1009 words; Donald Trump talked 92 seconds of a total of 484 seconds.\\n\\nFormal transcript excerpt at start of draw:\\nMark Carney, 00:00:00-00:00:02: Thank you, my friend.\\nGianni Infantino, 00:00:50-00:01:22: So this is the World Cup trophy. This is the official bowl for the World Cup and we are now going to do the draw, ladies and gentlemen. But before that, as is customary, there is always a question that the moderator asks the draw assistant. So I would like to start with Mr. Carney. How big a deal is it to co-host the World Cup for Canada?\\n\\nFormal transcript excerpt of Trump's soccer answer:\\nDonald Trump, 00:03:14-00:03:32: Well, for years, Gianni, they've thought soccer or football would be so big, so fast. And I remember, I shouldn't say this because it was a long time ago, but I remember watching Pele play on a team called the Cosmos, Pele, who was fantastic, as you know. I assume one of the greats.\\n\\nText-extraction/search notes:\\nLocal Python urllib retrieval of the page returned HTTP 200 for the source URL and extracted approximately 175,864 characters of page text with Python html.parser. Case-sensitive searches in the extracted page text returned no occurrence of \\\"Ronaldo\\\" and no occurrence of \\\"Messi\\\". The same terms were not found using the browser page find function on the rendered page.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R1 Defendant formal transcript extraction for limited rebuttal use\\nSource: Roll Call / Factba.se\\nURL: https://rollcall.com/factbase/trump/transcript/donald-trump-remarks-fifa-world-cup-drawing-december-5-2025/\\nCaptured page title: Remarks: Donald Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing in Washington - December 5, 2025\\n\\nRendered page metadata excerpt:\\nTopics: Sport; Sport \\u003e Competition Discipline \\u003e Soccer; Lifestyle and Leisure \\u003e Leisure \\u003e Game.\\nEntities listed: bowl; deal; Donald J. Trump; FIFA World Cup; Mark Carney; place; President; trophy; United States; way.\\nSpeakers listed: Gianni Infantino, Donald Trump, Mark Carney, Claudia Sheinbaum.\\nSpeaker statistics excerpt: Donald Trump said 25 sentences of a total of 141 sentences; Donald Trump said 274 words of a total of 1009 words; Donald Trump talked 92 seconds of a total of 484 seconds.\\n\\nFormal transcript excerpt at start of draw:\\nMark Carney, 00:00:00-00:00:02: Thank you, my friend.\\nGianni Infantino, 00:00:50-00:01:22: So this is the World Cup trophy. This is the official bowl for the World Cup and we are now going to do the draw, ladies and gentlemen. But before that, as is customary, there is always a question that the moderator asks the draw assistant. So I would like to start with Mr. Carney. How big a deal is it to co-host the World Cup for Canada?\\n\\nFormal transcript excerpt of Trump's soccer answer:\\nDonald Trump, 00:03:14-00:03:32: Well, for years, Gianni, they've thought soccer or football would be so big, so fast. And I remember, I shouldn't say this because it was a long time ago, but I remember watching Pele play on a team called the Cosmos, Pele, who was fantastic, as you know. I assume one of the greats.\\n\\nText-extraction/search notes:\\nLocal Python urllib retrieval of the page returned HTTP 200 for the source URL and extracted approximately 175,864 characters of page text with Python html.parser. Case-sensitive searches in the extracted page text returned no occurrence of \\\"Ronaldo\\\" and no occurrence of \\\"Messi\\\". The same terms were not found using the browser page find function on the rendered page.\\n\\nSubmitted evidence:\\n[plaintiff arguments] GovInfo DCPD202501162 transcript excerpt and metadata (ev_3fc783920414_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-3fc783920414)\\nSource: https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/DCPD-202501162/html/DCPD-202501162.htm\\nSHA-256: `3fc783920414399098d86210070dd9fe83c14fe1dbded1a56a554f8f4b3448f2`\\nBytes: 2641\\nRelevance: Official government transcript source corroborating that Trump spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center before the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw and said the strike word Ronaldo in World-Cup-related remarks.\\n\\n[defendant arguments] Roll Call/Factba.se formal FIFA World Cup Drawing transcript extraction (ev_fbb53e87ccb3_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-fbb53e87ccb3)\\nSource: https://rollcall.com/factbase/trump/transcript/donald-trump-remarks-fifa-world-cup-drawing-december-5-2025/\\nSHA-256: `fbb53e87ccb3f4381fc2bdc06ac2f2a1ea3848aadde56122b22d34dfbdf4533b`\\nBytes: 2032\\nRelevance: Formal drawing-program transcript evidence showing a separate formal Draw source from the pre-event reporter exchange; the extracted page text contains no occurrence of Ronaldo or Messi, supporting defendant's event-boundary argument.\\n\\nTechnical reports:\\n[plaintiff] Plaintiff source and adverse-search ledger\\nChecked the visible case packet and then searched official/source-specific repositories. GovInfo DCPD202501162 was opened and preserved as submitted evidence; it corroborates the packet transcript, source metadata, location, event date, and Ronaldo passages. The Roll Call/Factba.se formal drawing page rendered despite the packet's password-protection note; browser find searches for 'Ronaldo,' 'Cristiano,' and 'Messi' returned no matches. Plaintiff therefore treats the formal-program transcript as an adverse boundary check, not as proof of a formal-stage mention. The remaining dispute is contractual scope: whether the market clearly excluded public event-linked venue remarks immediately before the formal program.\\n\\n[defendant] Defense source-check ledger\\nDefendant searched for the formal Roll Call/Factba.se transcript identified by the case packet, opened the rendered Roll Call page, and fetched it locally with Python urllib. The fetch returned HTTP 200 for the formal FIFA World Cup Drawing transcript page. Text extraction produced approximately 175,864 characters; searches for \\\"Ronaldo\\\" and \\\"Messi\\\" returned no occurrences. The retrieval also captured formal-program excerpts, including Infantino's statement that \\\"we are now going to do the draw\\\" and Trump's formal soccer answer mentioning Pele rather than Ronaldo. The focused extraction was submitted and accepted as ev_fbb53e87ccb3_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-fbb53e87ccb3.\\n\\nCall submit_council_vote with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated.\\nKeep the rationale brief: no more than three sentences.\\n\\nCouncil API instructions:\\nYou are a council member. Decide the proposition from the admitted record.\\nYou may examine admitted evidence through read-only tools when exact bytes, metadata, or exhibit contents matter.\\nDo not search the web, introduce new facts, create new evidence, or upload evidence.\\nWhen ready, call submit_council_vote exactly once with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated and a concise rationale.\\n\",\"state\":\"ready\",\"status\":\"ready\",\"tools\":[{\"description\":\"Return the current visible arbitration record for this council member.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"get_case\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"List visible immutable record evidence.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"list_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Return metadata and read limits for one visible evidence item.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"stat_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Read a bounded byte range from one visible evidence item as base64.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"length\":{\"minimum\":1,\"type\":\"integer\"},\"offset\":{\"minimum\":0,\"type\":\"integer\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\",\"offset\",\"length\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"read_evidence_range\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Submit one council vote for the current deliberation opportunity.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"rationale\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"vote\":{\"enum\":[\"demonstrated\",\"not_demonstrated\"],\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"vote\",\"rationale\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"submit_council_vote\",\"read_only\":false}],\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":false,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-29T19:58:02.156322961Z\",\"deliberation_round\":1,\"member_id\":\"C2\",\"opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C2\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"remaining_ms\":887183,\"role_id\":\"council\",\"turn_number\":10},\"wait\":{\"reason\":\"ready\",\"state_version\":12,\"version\":15}}"}],"structuredContent":{"after_opportunity_id":"deliberation:1:C2","after_version":15,"case_id":"arb-ex03-20260629192557","limits":{"attempts_max":3,"attempts_remaining":3,"max_evidence_read_bytes":65536,"max_evidence_read_bytes_per_opportunity":524288,"max_evidence_reads_per_opportunity":32,"max_response_bytes":131072,"remaining_evidence_read_bytes_for_opportunity":524288,"remaining_evidence_reads_for_opportunity":32},"member_id":"C2","message":"An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.","ok":true,"prompt":"Role: council member\nMember ID: C2\nDeliberation round: 1\nProposition: For the Kalshi market \"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\", the strike \"Ronaldo\" should resolve Yes because Trump said \"Ronaldo\" in public remarks at the World Cup Draw venue immediately before the formal program, and the market wording plus the governing mention-market terms did not clearly exclude those event-linked remarks.\nStandard of evidence: Preponderance of the evidence.\nPersona:\nYou are a careful juror and council member.\n\nEvaluate the record faithfully. Decide only from the evidence, the stated rules, and the applicable burden of proof. Do not favor either side, fill gaps with speculation, or ignore uncertainty.\n\nGive weight to reliable sources, direct evidence, consistent reasoning, and clear admissions. Discount unsupported claims, rhetorical force, irrelevant facts, and conclusions that exceed the record.\n\nWhen the evidence supports one answer, state it plainly. When the evidence is incomplete or balanced, say so. Be concise, honest, and exact.\n\nRecord:\nOpenings:\n[plaintiff] Council members, this case is not mainly about whether the syllables were spoken. The case-packet transcript says they were. The real dispute is the market boundary: when Kalshi asked what Trump would say \"during the FIFA World Cup Draw,\" did that phrase clearly exclude his public, event-linked remarks at the World Cup Draw venue immediately before the formal program? On this record, it did not.\n\nThe market page fixes the contract at issue: the public title was \"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\"; the contract family was PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION; the strike was \"Ronaldo\"; Kalshi challenged the resolution as No; and the requested resolution is Yes. That means the council's task is to apply the mention-market terms to that title and strike, not to import a narrower limitation that the market did not plainly announce.\n\nThe reporter-exchange packet is direct evidence on the word and setting. It is titled as remarks in an exchange with reporters prior to the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw, dated December 5, 2025. It places the President at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts, speaking with FIFA President Gianni Infantino and reporters in a sequence repeatedly labeled around the 2026 World Cup and the Draw. In that exchange, in a soccer discussion, Trump says he met Ronaldo, praises him, and uses \"Ronaldo\" as a distinct standalone word. Under the mention rules, a distinct standalone appearance of the strike is the kind of use that counts if it falls within the time period.\n\nThe terms matter because they do not say that an event market is limited only to scripted remarks from a formal stage segment. They define a time period as potentially an event or context, and they give the Exchange power to specify what is included when a time period refers to a specific event. They also distinguish official/public event content from behind-the-scenes, rehearsals, and unofficial recordings. That distinction helps plaintiff: the packet is not a rumor, rehearsal, private soundcheck, or leaked recording. It is a sourced public transcript of remarks at the event venue, immediately tied to the Draw. If Kalshi meant \"only the formal televised draw program after doors close\" or \"only remarks in the separate formal archive,\" it needed to say so clearly.\n\nI also want to be candid about what the packet does not yet prove. The formal-draw archive note says a separate archived transcript page exists for Trump's formal attendance remarks, but that the session could not retrieve the full text because the page was password-protected. So, at opening, plaintiff is not asking you to infer that the formal program itself contained \"Ronaldo.\" Nor does plaintiff need that inference. The Yes theory is that the qualifying period reasonably includes the public pre-program reporter exchange that was part of Trump's World Cup Draw appearance. The formal archive is relevant because it marks defendant's likely narrower boundary; it does not resolve the boundary in defendant's favor.\n\nProvenance and weight also favor treating the packet seriously at this stage. The market and terms files are system case-packet records. The reporter exchange includes a source URL to a public presidential transcript source and notes a corrected transcript date, while also acknowledging that some audio could not be verified because the audio was incomplete. That caveat may affect inaudible portions, but it does not erase the visible, contextual Ronaldo passage. Later, when evidence admission opens, the parties should preserve the official transcript source, any govinfo or Presidency Project copy, the market page capture, and any accessible formal-program transcript or video. The adverse check should ask whether the formal program omits the word, but omission there would matter only if the council first accepts the defense's artificially narrow reading of \"during.\"\n\nThe plaintiff's burden is preponderance. The record already points to a straightforward path to Yes: Trump, the specified entity, said the specified strike as a standalone word in public remarks linked to and immediately preceding the World Cup Draw at the venue; the market title and governing terms did not clearly exclude that event-linked exchange. On a fair reading of the contract the trader saw, the challenged No resolution should give way to Yes.\n\n[defendant] Council members, the defense opening is simple: this case is not won by proving that the word \"Ronaldo\" appears somewhere in a public transcript. The plaintiff must prove, by a preponderance, that the word was said during the market's specified event: the FIFA World Cup Draw.\n\nThe current packet leaves that critical link unproven. The market page does not say \"while Trump was at the venue,\" \"during a World Cup press availability,\" or \"during any remarks connected to the Draw.\" It says: \"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\" The challenged resolution was No. The requested Yes theory therefore needs more than event-adjacent context; it needs a boundary showing that the reporter exchange was part of the Draw period the market asked traders to price.\n\nThe plaintiff's own best transcript cuts against that boundary. The case-packet file is titled \"Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw.\" It says the President's remarks were joined in progress, and the source note says portions could not be verified because the audio was incomplete. It places Trump at the Kennedy Center and includes World Cup topics, and yes, it contains \"Ronaldo\" as a standalone word in a soccer exchange. But its title and structure identify those remarks as an exchange with reporters prior to the Draw, not the formal Draw itself.\n\nThe terms do not rescue plaintiff from that distinction. They define a mention market around words used by the entity during the time period. A time period may be a specific event, and when it is a specific event, the Exchange may specify what is included. The technical details also distinguish official presentation content from behind-the-scenes, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings unless those are officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. Those provisions do not mean every public, nearby, event-related conversation becomes part of the event. They make the event boundary the central question.\n\nThe formal-draw archive note reinforces why the distinction matters. It reports that there is a separate archived transcript page for Trump's formal attendance remarks at the FIFA World Cup Drawing, but that the full text was not retrieved because the page was password-protected. That note does not prove the formal program omitted Ronaldo. It also does not prove the formal program included it. What it does show, at opening, is that the record itself separates the pre-event reporter exchange from the formal drawing remarks.\n\nSo the defense will focus the council on proof of inclusion, not mere association. If later phases produce a market page provision, official broadcast record, program transcript, video metadata, or source-agency material showing that the red-carpet reporter exchange was officially part of the FIFA World Cup Draw presentation for this market, the council can weigh that. If the later evidence instead shows a formal program with a separate pre-program press availability, then the correct result is No even though the word was spoken nearby.\n\nOn this opening record, plaintiff has shown a Ronaldo mention in remarks prior to the event. Plaintiff has not shown that those remarks occurred during the market event. The defense position is that Kalshi's No resolution follows the market wording and the mention-market terms unless plaintiff supplies that missing boundary proof.\n\nArguments:\n[plaintiff] Council members, the merits question is whether the contract clearly limited “during the FIFA World Cup Draw” to only the formal staged ceremony. Plaintiff submits that it did not, and the record now proves the Yes result by a preponderance.\n\nFirst, the market itself is broad. PX-1 identifies the public question as “What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?”, contract family PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION, strike “Ronaldo,” challenged resolution No, and requested resolution Yes. The market page does not say “during the formal televised ceremony,” “on the main stage only,” or “excluding public remarks immediately before the program at the venue.” That absence matters because Kalshi drafted the boundary traders had to price.\n\nSecond, the word was said. PX-2, the case-packet transcript, and PX-5, the GovInfo/OFR source excerpt, both show Trump used “Ronaldo” as a standalone word in soccer-related remarks. PX-5 is especially useful on provenance: it is the GovInfo Compilation of Presidential Documents source, published by the Office of the Federal Register/NARA, for DCPD202501162. It identifies the same event date, title, and source note, and it places the remarks at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center. In the relevant passage, Trump says he met Ronaldo, then says Ronaldo is great; later, when asked whether he played soccer or football, Trump says he was not Ronaldo or Messi. Either use satisfies the mention rule if the remarks fall within the market’s time period.\n\nThird, the remarks are event-linked in the way the market title reasonably covers. PX-2 and PX-5 are not private gossip, rehearsal, or an unofficial leak. They are public presidential remarks at the World Cup Draw venue, with FIFA President Infantino present, repeatedly discussing the Draw, the World Cup, ticket sales, the Kennedy Center, the audience, and the imminent program. The transcript itself includes headings such as “2026 World Cup Draw Event,” “2026 World Cup Draw Event/John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts,” and “2026 World Cup Draw/Ticket Sales for World Cup.” Trump and Infantino even discuss being a little late to “get in there” and the audience waiting. That sequence is not a random earlier interview; it is part of the public event appearance immediately surrounding the Draw.\n\nFourth, PX-3’s terms do not impose defendant’s formal-only line. They say the underlying is words used by the entity during the specified time period; a time period may be an event or context; and, when a time period refers to a specific event, the Exchange may specify what is included. They also say official/published content presented as part of the official presentation can count, while behind-the-scenes, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings do not count unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. Those exclusions show what this is not. The transcript is an official published record of public remarks at the event venue, not a hidden backstage clip. Nothing in PX-1 or PX-3 clearly tells traders that public, event-linked venue remarks immediately before the formal program are out.\n\nDefendant’s best point is PX-4 and the formal Roll Call/Factba.se page: there is a separate formal-drawing transcript, and my search found no “Ronaldo” there. Plaintiff does not hide that. But that adverse point proves only that the narrower formal-program source may omit the strike. It does not answer the contractual question. If Kalshi had meant to resolve solely by that formal transcript, it could have said so. Instead, the public market title used the broader phrase “during the FIFA World Cup Draw,” and the mention terms leave event boundaries to what the market clearly specifies.\n\nOn burden, plaintiff does not need absolute certainty or a formal-stage mention. Plaintiff must show it is more likely than not that the market wording plus terms include the event-linked remarks. The evidence satisfies that standard: PX-1 gives no exclusion; PX-2 and PX-5 prove the standalone Ronaldo mentions in public World Cup Draw venue remarks; PX-3 supplies a flexible event/time-period framework and excludes only categories unlike this source; PX-4 merely identifies the defense’s alternate formal-program boundary. The fair resolution is Yes.\n\n[defendant] Council members, the record now makes the defense point sharper, not weaker. Plaintiff has proved that Trump said \"Ronaldo\" in an official transcript of remarks connected to the World Cup Draw. Plaintiff has not proved that those remarks were during the market event.\n\nStart with the contract. DX/PX-1 gives the trader-facing question: \"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\" It does not say \"at the Kennedy Center,\" \"on World Cup Draw day,\" \"in remarks prior to the Draw,\" or \"in any public press exchange associated with the Draw.\" For this strike to resolve Yes, the relevant mention must fall inside that specified time period.\n\nThe strongest evidence of the Ronaldo utterance is also the strongest evidence against plaintiff's boundary. PX-2 and PX-5 are titled \"Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw.\" PX-5, plaintiff's GovInfo/OFR source, confirms the same title, says the remarks were joined in progress, identifies the source as an exchange with the news media, and notes that some portions could not be verified because the audio was incomplete. That evidence proves an official pre-event reporter transcript. It does not prove the reporter exchange was the FIFA World Cup Draw.\n\nThe terms, PX-3, require words used by the entity during the specified time period. They permit an event or context as a time period, and they discuss what is included when the time period is a specific event. That framework does not turn all event-adjacent speech into event speech. The distinction between official presentation content and non-included behind-the-scenes or unofficial content matters because the question is not just whether a record is public or official. The question is whether this source was part of the market's event period. A public official transcript can still be a transcript of remarks prior to the event.\n\nDX-2 supplies the missing contrast. It is a focused extraction from the separate Roll Call/Factba.se formal FIFA World Cup Drawing transcript. That page is the formal source identified in the case-packet archive note. It is titled \"Remarks: Donald Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing in Washington - December 5, 2025.\" Its transcript begins with the formal drawing participants; at 00:00:50, Infantino says, \"This is the World Cup trophy\" and \"we are now going to do the draw.\" The page's Trump soccer answer mentions Pele and the Cosmos, not Ronaldo. The extracted page text was searched for both \"Ronaldo\" and \"Messi\" and neither appears.\n\nThat does not prove Trump never said Ronaldo anywhere at the venue. It proves the opposite boundary from plaintiff's: the formal Draw transcript is separate from the pre-event reporter exchange, and the formal transcript does not contain the strike. Plaintiff needs a bridge between those two sources. It has not offered one. There is no market page detail saying red-carpet or pre-program press remarks count. There is no official program metadata showing the reporter exchange was part of the Draw presentation. There is no source hierarchy provision selecting the pre-event reporter exchange over the formal Draw transcript for this market.\n\nPlaintiff argues ambiguity should favor Yes because Kalshi could have drafted a narrower rule. But this is a preponderance case about a challenged No resolution, not a penalty for every conceivable ambiguity. The ordinary reading of \"during the FIFA World Cup Draw\" is the draw program, not every public appearance immediately before it. The record's own labels preserve that ordinary line: \"Prior to\" on the Ronaldo source; \"Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing\" on the formal source; and a formal transcript that starts the draw and omits the strike.\n\nWeight and provenance also favor the defense on the decisive issue. PX-5 is official and useful, but it authenticates a pre-event reporter exchange. DX-2 is a captured formal transcript extraction from the source class identified in PX-4; its absence finding is limited but material. PX-4 was initially only a note that the formal page existed and could not be retrieved. We have now retrieved and searched it. The adverse check therefore confirms, rather than merely speculates, that the formal drawing transcript does not carry plaintiff's Ronaldo mention.\n\nThe council should resolve the proposition against plaintiff. The record shows Trump said Ronaldo before the FIFA World Cup Draw in an event-linked reporter exchange. It does not show he said Ronaldo during the FIFA World Cup Draw. On this market wording and these terms, the challenged No resolution should stand.\n\nRebuttals:\n[plaintiff] Council members, defendant’s new formal-transcript extraction proves less than defendant needs.\n\nPlaintiff accepts the narrow fact defendant has now preserved: the Roll Call/Factba.se formal drawing-program extraction contains no “Ronaldo” or “Messi.” That is why plaintiff did not build the case on a formal-stage mention. The proposition instead asks whether the market wording and mention terms clearly excluded Trump’s public, official, event-linked remarks at the venue immediately before the formal program. Defendant has not supplied that exclusion.\n\nDefendant’s argument treats the title “Prior to the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw” as if “prior to” automatically means outside the Kalshi market’s event period. But PX-1 does not say “formal transcript only,” “after the draw host begins,” “after 00:00:50,” or “excluding press availability at the venue.” It asks what Trump would say “during the FIFA World Cup Draw.” The source label tells us sequence; it does not tell us the market’s legal boundary.\n\nDX-2 actually illustrates why defendant’s bright line is chosen after the fact. In defendant’s own formal extraction, the page begins before the mechanical draw: Mark Carney speaks at 00:00:00, and Infantino says at 00:00:50, “we are now going to do the draw.” If “during the FIFA World Cup Draw” can include ceremony and preamble on the formal page before the draw itself begins, then the phrase is not self-defining down to a single moment or transcript. The question is what the market clearly specified. It did not specify defendant’s transcript-only rule.\n\nThe terms do not fill that gap for defendant. PX-3 excludes hidden categories such as rehearsals, sound checks, unofficial recordings, and behind-the-scenes content unless officially published as part of the period. PX-2 and PX-5 are not those categories. PX-5 is an official GovInfo/OFR presidential transcript, published with source metadata, at 11:13 a.m. at the Kennedy Center, with FIFA’s president present and the World Cup Draw repeatedly discussed. That gives the Ronaldo mentions strong provenance and an event connection; it does not make them informal backstage chatter.\n\nDefendant says plaintiff needs a bridge. The bridge is the market text plus the terms’ failure to draw the narrow line defendant proposes. A No resolution can stand only if the contract fairly told traders that “during the FIFA World Cup Draw” meant only the separate formal-program transcript. On this record, the more likely reading is broader: public, official remarks at the venue, immediately tied to and immediately preceding the World Cup Draw program, were within the event-linked period unless clearly excluded.\n\nSo DX-2 narrows one factual issue but does not decide the case. It shows no formal-stage Ronaldo mention. It does not show that the market excluded the official pre-program event remarks where Trump did say Ronaldo. Under the preponderance standard, the Yes resolution remains the fair one.\n\nSurrebuttals:\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff’s rebuttal usefully narrows the dispute. Plaintiff accepts that the formal Roll Call/Factba.se drawing transcript contains no “Ronaldo” or “Messi.” So the case remains entirely about whether a separate reporter exchange titled “Prior to the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw” should be treated as inside the market period.\n\nPlaintiff says “prior to” is only sequence, not legal boundary. But sequence is exactly what the market phrase makes material. The contract asks what Trump would say “during the FIFA World Cup Draw.” A source-agency title identifying the Ronaldo transcript as an exchange with reporters prior to that Draw is not a stray label; it is the best record description of when and what that source is. Plaintiff cannot convert that source into the event itself by saying the market failed to list every excluded pre-event setting.\n\nPlaintiff’s formal-preamble point also does not carry the burden. Yes, the formal transcript begins before the mechanical ball selection, and Infantino says at 00:00:50 that “we are now going to do the draw.” But that supports the defense distinction. A host’s preamble inside the formal drawing transcript is part of the program. A separate press exchange, separately titled and sourced as prior to the Draw, is not made part of the program simply because it happened nearby and discussed the same event.\n\nNor does official publication settle the issue. PX-5 strengthens provenance: Trump did say Ronaldo in an official public transcript. But provenance answers whether the words were said, not whether they were said during the market’s specified event. The terms require both: the word by the entity, and the word during the time period. Plaintiff has the first element. The second is still missing.\n\nThe remaining bridge plaintiff proposes is essentially: public, official, event-linked, and not expressly excluded. That is not enough under a preponderance standard when the same record supplies a cleaner boundary: the Ronaldo source is prior to the Draw, and the formal Draw source omits the strike. The challenged No resolution should stand.\n\nClosings:\n[plaintiff] Council members, the record has narrowed to one real issue.\n\nThe word is proven. The market page identifies the strike as “Ronaldo” and the challenged resolution as No. The case-packet transcript and the GovInfo/OFR excerpt prove that Trump said “Ronaldo” as a standalone word in public remarks at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center, in a World Cup Draw setting, with FIFA President Infantino present, and amid repeated discussion of the Draw, the Kennedy Center, ticket sales, the audience, and the imminent event. That is strong provenance: GovInfo, NARA/OFR, DCPD202501162, matching the packet source and note.\n\nDefendant has also proved its best fact. The Roll Call/Factba.se formal-program extraction does not contain “Ronaldo” or “Messi.” Plaintiff does not ask you to find otherwise. If the market had said “only the formal drawing transcript,” defendant would win. But that is not the market traders saw.\n\nThe market asked: “What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?” It did not say “during the formal transcript only,” “after the host announces the draw has begun,” “excluding public press remarks at the venue,” or “excluding remarks immediately before the program.” The governing terms do not add that limitation. They define words used by the entity during the time period, allow event/context time periods, and exclude categories such as rehearsals, sound checks, behind-the-scenes content, and unofficial recordings. Plaintiff’s source is none of those. It is an official public presidential transcript of event-linked remarks at the venue.\n\nDefendant’s formal extraction shows why a bright line cannot simply be assumed. Even on that page, before balls are drawn, there is ceremony, introduction, and Infantino saying “we are now going to do the draw.” Event boundaries are not self-defining. The question is whether Kalshi clearly chose defendant’s narrower boundary. The record contains no such choice.\n\nSo the burden is met. More likely than not, a reasonable reading of the market and terms includes Trump’s official, public, venue-based remarks immediately tied to the World Cup Draw. The strongest contrary evidence proves only that a narrower formal transcript omits the strike. It does not prove the contract excluded the remarks where the strike was actually said.\n\nThe challenged No resolution should be overturned. The strike “Ronaldo” should resolve Yes.\n\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff’s closing concedes the decisive factual split: the formal World Cup Drawing transcript contains no “Ronaldo” or “Messi.” The only Ronaldo evidence is the separate official transcript titled “Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw.”\n\nThat is enough to decide the case. The market did not ask what Trump would say at the Kennedy Center, on World Cup Draw day, in public presidential remarks, or in event-linked press availability. It asked what Trump would say “during the FIFA World Cup Draw.” The terms require the word to be used by the entity during the specified time period. Plaintiff has proven the word and the speaker. It has not proven the time period.\n\nPlaintiff’s strongest point is that the market did not expressly say “formal transcript only” or “exclude pre-program remarks.” But plaintiff has the burden. A challenged No resolution does not become Yes merely because the contract could have been even more verbose. The record must make it more likely than not that the pre-event reporter exchange was inside the market period. The record does the opposite.\n\nThe source labels matter. PX-2 and PX-5 are official and probative, but they are official proof of remarks prior to the Draw. The formal Roll Call/Factba.se extraction is the source for Trump’s formal attendance at the FIFA World Cup Drawing; it begins the program, includes the draw presentation, and omits the strike. Plaintiff’s theory asks you to treat a separate prior reporter exchange as “during” the Draw even though the formal Draw source exists and does not contain the word.\n\nThe terms do not collapse that distinction. They recognize event/context time periods and official presentation content, but they still require the word to occur during the chosen time period. Official publication proves provenance. Event connection proves relevance. Neither proves inclusion. A public official transcript can be accurately preserved and still be outside the market window if it is, as titled, prior to the event.\n\nSo the fair synthesis is narrow and grounded: Trump said Ronaldo in event-linked public remarks before the FIFA World Cup Draw; Trump did not say Ronaldo in the formal drawing transcript preserved in this record; and no admitted market term or source-chain evidence bridges the pre-event exchange into the market’s “during the FIFA World Cup Draw” period.\n\nUnder the preponderance standard, plaintiff has not carried the proposition. The challenged No resolution should stand.\n\nExhibits:\n[plaintiff] PX-1 Market page and challenged resolution\nMarket URL: https://kalshi.com/markets/kxtrumpmentionb/trump-mention-b/kxtrumpmentionb-25dec06\n\nPublic market title: What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\n\nContract family: PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION\n\nStrike at issue: Ronaldo\n\nChallenged resolution: No\n\nRequested resolution: Yes\n\n\n[plaintiff] PX-2 Pre-event reporter exchange transcript\nRemarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\nDecember 05, 2025\n\n[The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\nThe President. It's a great honor to be here. Gianni has done a fantastic job. We're setting records—[inaudible].\nQ. [Inaudible]\nThe President. Well, I think so. They have a little bit of a shot. Pretty stiff competition. But I would say they would have a small chance.\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize\nQ. [Inaudible]—win the FIFA Peace Award?\nThe President. Well, it would be an honor.\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\nQ. Will you root for some selection? Will you root for someone?\nThe President. Well, I root for a lot of countries, but in this case, I'll be rooting for the U.S.A. [Laughter]\nQ. [Inaudible]\nThe President. That's great. That's great. We really love it.\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize\nQ. Mr. President, have you been told that you are going to receive the inaugural peace prize today——\nThe President. I have not——\nQ. ——from FIFA?\nThe President. I have not been told. There's a rumor about it, but I have not been told. That would be a great honor, and I'm a big fan of Gianni, as you know.\nQ. What can fans expect——\nQ. Are you hoping to receive that?\nThe President. Excuse me.\nQ. Are you hoping to receive the peace prize?\nThe President. Well, I don't like to say \"hope,\" but it would be a great honor.\n2026 World Cup\nQ. What can fans expect of, like, the World Cup in the U.S.?\nThe President. I think it's going to be fantastic. We've set every record you can set.\nQ. What are you telling people who are worried——\nFédération Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) President Giovanni V. Infantino\nQ. [Inaudible]—friend Gianni—[inaudible]—a word about him?\nThe President. I think he has done a fantastic job.\nThe President's Schedule\nQ. Are you going to be meeting with the President of Mexico today and the——\nThe President. We might. Yes.\nQ. ——Prime Minister of Canada as well?\nThe President. I might. I might do that.\nQ. Will you be discussing immigration and trade with them?\nThe President. Yes, we'll be discussing.\n[At this point, the President and Mr. Infantino posed for photographs.]\nThe President. Thank you, everybody.\n2026 World Cup Draw Event/John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts\nQ. Mr. President, what do you think about the crowd?\nThe President. Oh, look, the new star—[inaudible].\nCongratulations.\nQ. Thank you.\nThe President. You're the new star of television and Fox.\nQ. Thank you. How are you doing, Mr. President?\nThe President. I'm doing very well.\nQ. What do you think about the crowd here?\nThe President. I think the crowd is great, and I think the building is great. We've made a lot of improvements over the last 6 months. Taking—the Kennedy Center was in very bad shape. Now it's getting to be really good. And in 6 months, it's going to be incredible with the improvements we've made.\nQ. The first time for the U.S. to host since the nineties.\nThe President. Right.\nQ. Are you ready for it?\nThe President. I'm ready for it, and they're ready for it. And Gianni, who you know——\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\nThe President. ——has done a fantastic job with FIFA. And we're looking to have—you know, we're set—we have already set records for tickets sales. I don't think there's ever been anything like it in any sport. And so, I want to congratulate you.\nMr. Infantino. Thank you.\nThe President. I don't even have to wait. But major records have been set.\nHow are you?\nQ. Good, how are you, sir?\nThe President. Nice to see you.\nQ. Today it's not football—American football. It's soccer. It's——\nThe President. Right.\nQ. ——the big event of soccer.\nThe President. That's right. That's right.\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\nQ. So can you tell me about this big day today?\nThe President. It's just a big day, and it's a great sport. And it really is coming to America. And never—nobody ever thought a thing like this could happen. And I'm very happy to say that we've already set the alltime record on ticket sales long before the first ball is kicked. Right?\nMr. Infantino. A hundred percent. One hundred percent.\n2026 World Cup Host Cities\nQ. You've had some concerns about crime in American cities, some of the cities that will be hosting. Have they remedied that for you? Are you still considering maybe asking FIFA to move some of those cities?\nThe President. No, I don't want to do that. But I will tell you, if they do have a problem, by the time we get there, we'll take care of that problem. We can solve that problem.\nI've proven that in DC and everywhere else we went, so we'll take care of that very easily. So, if they have a problem, hopefully, they'll let us know that, and we will solve any problem.\nOkay? Thank you.\nQ. Thank you so much.\nMr. Infantino. All right, thank you so much.\nQ. Thank you, Mr. President.\nQ. Thank you. Appreciate it.\nThe President. Congratulations.\n2026 World Cup\nQ. Mr. President, Brazilian television. America will be hosting the World Cup and the Olympics in 2 years. How important it is—[inaudible]?\nThe President. I think very. It's a great honor. I think Gianni is doing a phenomenal job. We've set every record on ticket sales. It's been really fantastic. But Gianni has done an unbelievable job with FIFA.\nThe President's Experience With Soccer\nQ. [Inaudible]\nThe President. He was a great—not only that. I got to see a man name Pelé play—right?—that tells you how old I am—when he was on the Cosmos. Do you remember that a long time ago? And it was quite a treat. That was quite an event. And he was—not only was he playing, he was great. He scored two goals, I think. And so, I was one of the few who got to see Pelé, and I assume he is one of your alltime greats. Right?\nMr. Infantino. Definitely.\nThe President. So I got to see him.\nThe President's Favorite World Cup Competitor\nQ. Do you have some favorite teams for World Cup?\nThe President. Well, I have a favorite. It's the U.S.A. [Laughter] I don't know what their chances are, Gianni, but maybe the U.S.A. is the——\nMr. Infantino. They're getting better and better, actually.\nThe President. I think they'll do well.\nMr. Infantino. They are getting better and better.\nThe President. I think they'll do well.\nThank you very much, everybody.\nQ. Thank you so much.\n2026 World Cup\nQ. Mr. President, World Cup in America just means—[inaudible]. So what do you expect from this World Cup?\nThe President. [Inaudible]—record business and only in the United States, but we're also doing record ticket sales with FIFA. And they've already bought—beat their highest record. And we—you know, this a long time before the first ball is kicked. You've sold more tickets than they've ever done before, and better pricing than they've ever gotten before. It's a tremendous success. And it's an honor. And Gianni has done a phenomenal job with FIFA.\nQ. [Inaudible]—ever?\nThe President. I think so. I think it's going to be—I mean, ideally, you want to see that every year. Every 4 years, it gets bigger and better. I think we have set every record in the book. We're very happy about it.\nThank you.\nThe President's Favorite World Cup Competitor\nQ. [Inaudible]—part of America. Who are you going to support as well?\nThe President. Well, I think I have to support U.S.A. Otherwise, I'd be in trouble. I wouldn't be President for long.\nMr. Infantino. [Inaudible]\nThe President. [Inaudible]—but you have a lot of great teams. You're going to have a lot of great teams.\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\"football,\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\n2026 World Cup Draw/Ticket Sales for World Cup\nQ. How does it feel to be part of this amazing event? And obviously, your being a part of participating in all the—[inaudible]?\nThe President. The President of Mexico is here, and she's doing a very good job. She's a good woman, very, very excellent job. It's an honor, and we're setting every record, and you're helping us set those records.\nMr. Infantino. And we will do it.\nThe President. You know, Mexico and Canada are helping us set those records. But as you know, we have a record in ticket sales already, long before the first ball is kicked, and we're going to do great.\nI think that Gianni—as you know, he's the head, and he has done a fantastic job.\nU.S. Cooperation With Mexico and Canada\nQ. And how is the biggest challenge being three countries?\nThe President. Well, I think that—do you mean for the three countries?\nWell, they've gotten together really well, I mean.\nMr. Infantino. All right.\nThe President. They're getting along very well.\nMr. Infantino. Collaboration is fantastic between the three.\nThe President's Interest in Soccer/2026 World Cup\nQ. And you like soccer?\nThe President. I do. I like it. I like it more and more.\nQ. Yes?\nThe President. I like it. It's growing in this country—very, really—I mean, someday, maybe it's going to be bigger than anything else.\nMr. Infantino. We'll have to become number one.\nThe President. I will say this——\nMr. Infantino. Definitely.\nThe President. ——the ticket sales——\nQ. Definitely will happen.\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\nThe President. Ticket sales are bigger than anything we have ever done in the history of the country, in terms of sports.\nMr. Infantino. For certain.\nQ. And the audience is going to be huge.\nThe President. The audience is going to be tremendous.\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\nThe President. Yes.\nMr. Infantino. Six billion people.\nThe President. [Inaudible]\nQ. Six billion? That's amazing.\nMr. Infantino. Six billion people.\nAnd today, one billion.\nQ. Wow.\nMr. Infantino. [Inaudible]\nQ. Enjoy show time. Thank you so much.\nThe President. [Inaudible]\nQ. Mr. President, how are you? Just a quick—[inaudible].\nQ. This is for Telemundo.\nThe President. How are you?\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\nQ. Hello, Mr. President. How are you? This for Telemundo.\nThe President. How are you? Good.\nQ. How are you?\nThe President. Very good. Thank you.\nQ. How does it feel to have the most important event of sports—that global—in the U.S.?\nThe President. Well, we do. And right at the Kennedy Center. I'm Chairman of the Kennedy Center. And I hear the Kennedy Center is doing a very good job, so it feels great. Really good.\nAnd Telemundo is doing a good job, too. Thank you.\nQ. Thank you.\n2026 World Cup\nQ. What is the significance of hosting the FIFA World Cup this year?\nThe President. It's a—in terms of sports, I would say the ultimate. There is no sport like this. It's the biggest sport in the world. And we are setting every record. You know, our ticket sales have gone and set every—every sport—no matter what it is, we've set the record. So—and every though it's very early, there's no ball being kicked yet, but we've already set a ticket sales record.\nArgentina National Team\nQ. How do you see Argentinean team for this World Cup?\nThe President. Well, I love Argentina. And your President is doing a very good job, as you know. Milei. You know that right? It's make Argentina great again. MAGA.\nQ. And——\nU.S. National Team\nQ. Do you think the States are building a powerful team for next year?\nThe President. Who?\nQ. The States.\nThe President. Oh, yes. Sure. I—you're going to have a lot of powerful teams. Everybody has a lot of powerful teams, but you're going to have a lot of great teams. [Inaudible]\nU.S. Role in Hosting the 2026 World Cup\nQ. Mr. President, what does it mean for you guys to host the World Cup right here in the U.S.?\nThe President. I'm honored to host it. It's a great honor. I mean, it's turned out to be bigger than we thought. We're setting a record for ticket sales, the likes of which no sport has ever seen before.\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\nThe President. But they have a little more speed.\nBut no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\nPopularity of Soccer in Latin America\nQ. Mr. President, a message for the Latin America and soccer fans?\nThe President. Yes, I am. And Latin America is great. And they have great soccer. So, good luck in the matches.\n[A reporter asked a question in Spanish, which was translated by an interpreter as follows.]\nU.S. Visas for World Cup Ticketholders\nQ. Who is going to be in—[inaudible]—about these visas for the—these fans that want to come here to the World Cup?\nThe President. Well, we're going to make it very easy for them. We're working on that right now. We're going to make it very easy. It's going to be a very easy process.\nQ. Okay. Say, hi to Colombia over there.\nThe President. Hello. Is that Colombia?\nQ. Yes.\nThe President. I love Colombia. Hello, Colombia. [Laughter]\nQ. Okay. Okay. Muy bien.\nThe President. So where are you from?\nQ. Paraguay.\nThe President. Oh.\nQ. He's from Paraguay. Yes.\nThe President. Very good. I love it. I—it's a beautiful country. We get along very well with them. We do a little trade deal with them, and they like us. And that's what's happening.\nQ. Panama.\nThe President. Where?\nVery good. I like the canal. [Laughter] That canal is pretty good.\n[A reporter spoke in Spanish; no translation was provided.]\n2026 World Cup\nThe President. What?\nQ. [Inaudible]\nThe President. Well, it's going to be incredible. The event is going to be very good. Just this event alone—it's at the Kennedy Center. I see you have it fixed up perfectly.\nMr. Infantino. It will set the tone.\nThe President. Right? It's beautiful.\nMr. Infantino. It's beautiful.\nThe President. It's a beautiful place.\nHave a good time.\nQ. [Inaudible]\nThe President.\n[A reporter spoke in Spanish; no translation was provided.]\nMr. Infantino. No, gracias. [Inaudible]\nThe President. It's great.\nJohn F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts/Renovation Work\nQ. Mr. President, the U.S. press?\nThe President. Thank you, everybody, very much. It's a great honor. This has been an honor for a lot of reasons. Number one, they've sold more tickets than any event has ever sold already—long before the kickoff.\nAnd number two, we've done a lot of work at the Kennedy Center. It was falling apart, and now it's pretty much back. And we'll get it back within the next 4 or 5 months through construction, and—but you see the way it looks.\nAnd Gianni is just telling me—who's done an incredible job, by the way. He's just telling, you know, how good a job we've done.\nMr. Infantino. That's right.\nThe President. You can look at the walls. The marble was broken. Everything was a mess. And we've really taken the Kennedy Center—a lot of people thought it was going to be ripped down, and we did just the opposite. So we've done a really great renovation job on it. And over the next 3, 4 months, it will be complete. And we're honored to have it here, and it's been—it's been very special.\nWe've set a record on ticket sales, as you probably heard, already, even way before—long before the event itself. And we're working with Canada, and we're working with Mexico. And it's been a really spectacular—so far, it's been spectacular.\nDaniel [Daniel Baldwin, One America News Network], do you have a question?\n2026 World Cup\nQ. What are your expectations? You once said that the FIFA World Cup is an opportunity to put—a once-in-a-lifetime opportunity to put the greatness of the United States on display.\nThe President. Well, I think—\nQ. One billion eyeballs will be watching, Mr. President.\nThe President. Yes, I—think——\nQ. What will they here today?\nThe President. Even today, I understand. I hear that, you know——\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\nThe President. ——I know we're a little late to get in there, but——\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\nThe President. ——that's okay.\nMr. Infantino. They wait.\nThe President. So all my friends, I guess they have to wait. They have no choice, right? [Laughter]\nMr. Infantino. Yes, they wait.\nThe President. But no, the numbers are incredible. I hear today's numbers are——\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\nThe President. ——very big. I hope CNN is covering this.\nQ. One billion eyeballs.\nMr. Infantino. Today, 1 billion eyeballs.\nThe President. Today's numbers are very, very big.\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize/The President's Foreign Policy\nQ. We are covering it. And you're expected to get the FIFA Peace Prize, Mr. President. What would you say to people who say that prize might conflict with your pledge to strike Venezuela?\nThe President. Well, I think the peace prize—I mean, I settled eight wars. I don't know that I'm getting it. I haven't been officially noticed. I've been hearing about a peace prize, and I'm here to represent our country in a different sense. But I can tell you, I did settle eight wars, and we have a ninth coming, but—which nobody has ever done before.\nBut I want to really save lives. I don't need prizes. I need to save lives. And we're saving a lot of lives. And I've saved millions and millions of lives, and that's really what I want to do.\nAnd I also want to run a great country. And the United States right now is the hottest country anywhere in the world. And 1 year ago, it was dead. We had a dead country, and now we have the hottest country anywhere in the world.\nQ. Mr. President, will you——\nThe President's Meeting With President Claudia Sheinbaum Pardo of Mexico and Prime Minister Mark Carney of Canada\nQ. What are you going to discuss with Canada and Mexico, Mr.—what are you going to discuss with the leaders of Canada and Mexico?\nThe President. Well, we're getting—we're going to meet with both. And we're getting along very well. You know, we're getting along very well. I don't know. I think we have a meeting set up for some time after the event.\nQ. Will you discuss trade?\nThe President. Yes, we'll discuss trade. We—get along very well.\nThank you, everybody, very much.\nQ. Will you pardon any other Honduran officials?\nQ. Do you want them to keep trying to indict Ms. James?\n\nNOTE: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. In his remarks, he referred to Trey Yingst, chief foreign correspondent, Fox News Channel; Cristiano Ronaldo, forward for Saudi Pro League club Al-Nass and Portugal's national soccer team; and Lionel Messi, forward for Major League Soccer club Inter Miami and Argentina's national team. A reporter referred to New York State Attorney General Letitia James. The transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\n\nSource URL: https://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/documents/remarks-exchange-with-reporters-prior-the-2026-federation-internationale-des-associations\n\n\n[plaintiff] PX-3 PRESMENTION/NEWMENTION terms\n                                         NEWMENTION\n\nScope: These rules shall apply to this contract.\n\nUnderlying: The Underlying for this Contract is words used by <entity> <time period>.\nRevisions to the Underlying made after Expiration will not be accounted for in determining the\nExpiration Value.\n\nSource Agency: The Source Agencies are <source>.\n\nType: The type of Contract is an Event Contract.\n\nIssuance: After the initial Contract, Contract iterations will be listed on an as-needed basis at\nthe discretion of the Exchange and corresponding to the risk management needs of Members.\n\n<entity>: <entity> refers to the speaker, writer, performer, or communicator specified by the\nExchange. This may include (but is not limited to): a specific named individual, multiple\nindividuals specified using AND/OR logic, an individual identified by position or title, a group,\nband, team or collective entity, a specified member or members of a group, an organization,\ncompany, or institutional entity, or any combination of the aforementioned.\n\nWhen <entity> is defined by a position or title, the Contract tracks whoever holds that position\nduring <time period>, even if the individual holding the position changes. When <entity> is a\nspecific named individual, the identity remains consistent throughout. Name changes (e.g.,\nstage names, married names) do not create a new entity. When <entity> is a group or\norganization and the Contract does not specify particular members, any official\ncommunication or statement by any member or designated spokesperson counts. When using\nAND logic, all specified entities must independently say <word> during <time period>. When\nusing OR logic, at least one of the specified entities must say <word> during <time period>.\nThe Exchange may specify additional conditions such as “at least X members of” a group or\n“the majority of” a group.\n\n<source>: <source> refers to a Source Agency or ordered collection of Source Agencies\nspecified by the Exchange at the time of Contract listing, which will be incorporated into the\nSource Agency hierarchy above and used to determine the occurrence of the Underlying.\n<source> may refer to a singular agency, multiple agencies, an agency by distinguishing\ncharacteristics, by category or type (e.g., “official government statistical body,” “primary wire\nservice”), or any combination thereof. When multiple agencies are specified, they may be\napplied in the hierarchical order designated by the Exchange if so specified, with the highest-\nranked available and responsive agency taking precedence for purposes of determining the\nExpiration Value. A lower-ranked agency shall only be consulted if all higher-ranked agencies\nare unavailable, unresponsive, have not reported on the Underlying by the Expiration time, or\nif the Exchange, in its sole discretion, determines that a higher-ranked agency’s reporting is\nincomplete, erroneous, or otherwise insufficient to determine the Expiration Value. If <source>\ndesignates multiple agencies without specifying a hierarchical order, the Exchange shall\nresolve any conflict between reporting agencies at its sole discretion.\n\n<word>: <word> refers to the particular word or phrase potentially to be mentioned by\n<entity>. It may refer to a word being said a minimum number of times. It may also refer to\none of multiple words/phrases, any of which are acceptable (e.g., “Doge/Dogecoin”).\n\f<time period>: <time period> refers to a specific range of time, event or discrete date and\ntime specified by the Exchange. This may be defined by, but is not limited to: a specific event\nor context (e.g., “during the State of the Union address”), exact dates or times, relative time\nmarkers (e.g., “before July 1, 2027,” “in Q1 2026”), event-based periods (e.g., “during any\ncampaign rally in October 2026,” “during the awards ceremony”), and broader intervals (e.g.,\n“Q1–Q2 2027,” “January–March 2026”).\n\nUnless stated otherwise, “Between” is inclusive of both endpoints, while “before” and “after”\nexclude the specified date. <time period> may also refer to “Any” or “None”, to multiple dates\n(even if non-consecutive), or to a singular and discrete date or time.\n\nWhen <time period> refers to a specific event (such as an address, speech, performance, or\nbroadcast), the Exchange may specify what is included, including whether it includes both live\nand pre-recorded segments (including whether advertisements are included). Where a\ntimezone is not specified, ET is assumed.\n\n\nPayout Criterion: The Payout Criterion for the Contract encompasses the Expiration Values that\n<word> is said by <entity> <time period>.\n\n\nThe word must appear as a distinct, standalone unit, not buried inside another word. Plural\nand possessive noun forms count. Other grammatical changes (tense, conjugation, derivation)\ndo not. If <word> appears separated from other words by a space or hyphen or in a\ncompound form with a space or hyphen, it counts. If <word> is fused into a single\nunhyphenated word, it does not count.\n\nIf <time period> refers to an event and that event is cancelled, and the market contains a\nstrike stating “Event does not qualify/occur”, such a strike shall resolve “Yes” and all others\n“No”. If <time period> refers to an event and that event is cancelled but such strikes are NOT\nlisted, the Contracts will resolve to the last fair price determined at the discretion of the\nExchange. If the event is postponed, and such a postponement is announced by the end of the\nfollowing calendar day to be rescheduled to a time within 14 calendar days, the markets shall\nremain open. If the event captured in <time period> is a live-stream or broadcast, the\nExchange may keep the market open for 24 hours for the release of an official recording.\nFurther granular details on conditions for these Contracts is available below.\n\nAdditional clarification(s):\n\n     Possessive noun forms of <word>, plurals, and possessive plural noun forms are\n     INCLUDED:\n          <word> is “Immigrant” → “Immigrants” counts\n          <word> is “Egg” → “eggs’ shells” counts\n          <word> is “Russia” → “Russia’s” counts, “Russian” does not\n     If <word> exists only in adjective form, no plural form exists:\n          <word> is “Economic” → “Economics” does not count (“Economic” is an adjective\n          for which “Economics” is not a plural)\n     Plural nouns occurring within proper nouns and noun phrases are included:\n          <word> is “Cat” → “Cats the musical” counts\n\f    Grammatical variations beyond plurals/possessives are NOT included:\n         <word> is “Immigrant” → “Immigration” does NOT count\n         <word> is “Run” → “Running” or “Ran” do NOT count\n    When <word> specifies a plural form, the singular does NOT count:\n         <word> is “Veterans” → “Veteran” does NOT count\n    Words that are spelled the same as the plural form of <word> (if such exists) but are\n    themselves not a plural noun are included:\n         <word> is “Wind” → “Winds up the clock” counts\n         <word> is “Border” → “The United States has strong borders” counts\n    Open compounds (words separated by spaces) count:\n         <word> is “fire” → “fire station” counts\n         <word> is “couch” → “couch potato” counts\n    Hyphenated compounds (words connected by hyphens) count:\n         <word> is “Palestine” → “pro-Palestine” counts\n         <word> is “fat” → “non-fat” counts\n    Closed compounds (single word, no spaces/hyphens) do not count:\n         <word> is “fire” → “wildfire” does not count\n         <word> is “fire” → “firefighter” does not count\n    Multi-word <word> in larger constructions: When <word> is a multi-word phrase\n    appearing within a hyphenated construction, it counts only if <word> appears as a\n    complete, unmodified element:\n         <word> is “New York” → “New York-based” counts (complete element)\n    Portmanteaus (words blended from two words where parts of each are combined) are\n    NOT included unless the portmanteau clearly contains <word> as a distinct, unaltered\n    element:\n         <word> is “MAGA” → “MAGA-nificent” counts (MAGA appears as distinct element)\n         <word> is “magnificent” → “MAGA-nificent” does NOT count (portmanteau blend)\n\nDictionary determination: Both the Merriam-Webster Dictionary (available online) AND the\nOxford English Dictionary shall be used to determine compound type and/or conventional\nspelling patterns. Inclusion in either dictionary as an open or hyphenated compound shall\nsatisfy the Payout Criterion. If neither provides clarity (or the word is not included),\ndetermination is based on whether written as single unit (closed/doesn’t count) vs. spaces or\nhyphens (open or hyphenated/counts) and/or context and previous usage.\n\nPHONETIC EQUIVALENCIES\n\n    Homophones (same sound, different spelling) do not count:\n        <word> is “write” → “right” does not count\n    Homonyms and homographs (same spelling) COUNT regardless of meaning or\n    pronunciation:\n        <word> is “bass” → both “bass guitar” and “bass fishing” count\n    Proper and common nouns are treated identically:\n        <word> is “Apple” → both “Apple Inc.” and “apple” (fruit) count\n        <word> is “Will” → both “Will Smith” and “I will go” count\n    Minor unintentional mispronunciations COUNT if context makes intent clear:\n        <word> is “Mamdani” → “Mandani” counts\n    Severe mispronunciations that make <word> unrecognizable do NOT count.\n    Trademarked spellings do not count, even when pronounced identically, unless the word\n\fitself is the same:\n      <word> is “lift” → “Lyft” (pronounced “lift”) does not count\n      <word> is “uber” → “Uber” counts\nWords with non-standard transliteration to English count within reason, provided they are\nphonetically equivalent:\n      <word> is “Zelensky” → any of “Zelenski,” “Zelenskii,” “Zelensky,” or “Zelenskiy”\n      count if pronounced equivalently\nContractions do not count for their constituent words unless otherwise explicitly specified\nby the Exchange:\n      <word> is “not” → “won’t,” “can’t,” “don’t,” “isn’t” do not count\nNumbers spoken as words COUNT, when spoken exactly (not part of a larger number):\n      <word> is “five” → saying “five” or reading “$5” aloud as “five dollars” counts,\n      saying “five hundred” does NOT count\n      <word> is “410” → “four hundred ten”, “four one zero” or “four ten” counts\nOrdinals COUNT when <word> is written numerically OR a phrase that includes a\nnumber:\n      <word> is “January 6” → “January 6th” counts\n      <word> is “3” (written numerically) → “3rd” (spoken as “third”) counts\n      <word> is “Eight War” → “8 Wars” and “Eighth War” will count\nCardinal and ordinal number words are distinct:\n      <word> is “one” → “first” does NOT count\n      <word> is “first” → “one” does NOT count\nAcronyms and abbreviations count when pronunciation or letter-by-letter spelling\nmatches <word>:\n      <word> is “NASA” → “NASA” (pronounced “NAH-suh”) counts\n      <word> is “NASA” → “N-A-S-A” (spelled out) counts\nAcronyms and abbreviations count as <word> when pronounced as the full word:\n      <word> is “Doctor” → “Dr.” (pronounced “Doctor”) counts\nExpanded forms of acronyms do NOT count:\n      <word> is “AI” → “artificial intelligence” does not count\nWords in foreign languages do NOT count unless they are perfect cognates with an\nEnglish word:\n      <word> is “fire” → “fuego” (Spanish) does NOT count\nEnglish words within foreign sentences count:\n      <word> is “policy” → “Nuestra policy es clara” counts\n<word> in organization/company names counts:\n      <word> is “Securities” → “Bank of America Securities” counts\nWords in URLs, emails, handles, and hashtags (exclusive of domain structure, email\nprovider or symbols) are treated as compounds when spoken as complete words, with the\ntype of compound subject to aforementioned rules:\n      <word> is “fire” → “firestation.com” pronounced “fire station dot com” counts\n      <word> is “fire” → “wildfire.com” pronounced “wildfire dot com” does NOT count\n      <word> is “apple” → “apple.com” pronounced “apple dot com” does count\n      When presented in URL, email, handle, or hashtag form, <word> shall be treated as\n      a compound, not a multi-word word\nSung, rapped, or poetic words COUNT if phonetically recognizable:\n      <word> is “money” → “moneyyy” (extended in rap) counts\n      Extreme distortion making <word> unrecognizable does NOT count.\nPhonetic alphabet spelling (“Foxtrot India Romeo Echo” for “FIRE”) does NOT count.\n\fCANCELLATIONS AND DELAYS\n\n   The Exchange may list an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike for any Contract. If listed,\n   such a strike refers to the structural conditions of the market, and is NOT adjudicated as a\n   <word> needing to be said by or validated by having been said by <entity>. If listed, this\n   strike resolves to “Yes” whenever the event fails to occur or qualify under the Payout\n   Criterion, or any other circumstance prevents normal resolution.\n   If no such strike is listed, and <time period> refers to a specific event, the following rules\n   apply if the event is cancelled, postponed, rescheduled, or materially altered (including\n   being closed to press) such that no video is released within one calendar day of the\n   original start time of the event:\n         If the event is cancelled, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price determined in\n         the sole discretion of the Exchange.\n         If the event is postponed or rescheduled, the outcome depends on whether a new\n         date is publicly announced within one calendar day (i.e. if the event was scheduled\n         to begin on Monday, any time up to 11:59PM on Tuesday falls within this period) of\n         the originally scheduled start time:\n               If no new date is announced within one calendar day, the Contract will resolve\n               to the last fair price determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\n               If a new date is announced within one calendar day, the outcome depends on\n               when the rescheduled event is set to occur:\n                     If the rescheduled date falls within fourteen (14) calendar days of the\n                     originally scheduled date, the Contract shall remain open and <word>\n                     stated during the rescheduled event will count.\n                           The fourteen-day window begins at 12:00 AM ET on the originally\n                           scheduled date and ends at 11:59 PM ET fourteen days later, unless\n                           an alternate timezone is explicitly specified.\n                           Example: <time period> is “during the State of the Union on January\n                           15, 2026” rescheduled to January 20, 2026 → words spoken during\n                           the rescheduled address count.\n                     If the rescheduled date falls more than fourteen (14) calendar days after\n                     the originally scheduled date, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price\n                     determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\n         Any Contract that cannot be resolved through the Source Agency hierarchy will\n         instead be settled at the Last Fair Price. The Exchange will disclose the methodology\n         used to determine the Last Fair Price (e.g., Last Traded Price, Time-Weighted\n         Average Price) at the time of Issuance.\n         If an event begins but is interrupted, abbreviated, or ends prematurely, words\n         stated by <entity> during the portion of the event that did occur will count and the\n         market will otherwise resolve.\n   If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window but the venue, format, or medium\n   changes (e.g., moved to a different location, changed from in-person to virtual (with the\n   exception of being closed to press)), words stated during the event will count.\n   Special condition: Across both cases, whether an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike is\n   listed or not, if the event specified as or in <time period> is a live-stream or broadcast (or\n   relayed as such) but the live stream/broadcast does not occur, the Exchange will instead\n   use an officially released recording as the Underlying, and may delay resolution by up to\n   one calendar day to allow for the release of such a recording.\n\f          If partial snippets are released, Contracts on words that do not appear will be\n          resolved to last fair price, and Contracts on those that do will be resolved to “Yes”.\n          If no recording is released, the relevant outcomes triggered by the\n          presence/absence of an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike shall occur as outlined\n          above.\n\nTECHNICAL DETAILS (UNLESS OTHERWISE SPECIFIED)\n\n     When <time period> refers to a specific event, pre-recorded content broadcast,\n     streamed, or published as part of that event is included if presented as part of the official\n     presentation.\n          Example: <time period> is “during the concert” with pre-recorded video interlude\n          where entity speaks → words from interlude count\n          Example: <time period> is “during the television appearance” with pre-taped\n          segment aired during broadcast → words from segment count\n     Behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are NOT\n     included unless officially broadcast or published as part of <time period>.\n     Subtitles and captions that display <word> on screen but are not spoken aloud by\n     <entity> do NOT count.\n     Sign language interpretation or usage by entity does NOT count as saying <word> unless\n     the Contract explicitly specifies that sign language counts.\n     Text that entity displays on screen (presentation slides, teleprompter visible to audience,\n     signatures) does NOT count unless entity reads it aloud.\n     Content generated by AI, deepfakes, or synthetic voice technology impersonating entity\n     does NOT count unless the synthetic content is officially commissioned, authorized, or\n     published by entity, OR the Contract explicitly specifies that AI-generated content counts.\n     If <word> is muted due to technical failure or censorship it shall not count unless\n     corroborating contextual evidence (including surrounding speech, or an official\n     uncensored recording or transcript) confirms that <entity> specifically uttered <word>\n     during the muted period.\n\nMinimum Tick: The Minimum Tick size for the Contract shall be $0.01.\n\nPosition Accountability Level: The Position Accountability Level for the Contract shall be\n$25,000 per strike, per Member.\n\nLast Trading Date: The Last Trading Date of the Contract will be the Expiration Date. The Last\nTrading Time will be the Expiration time.\n\nSettlement Date: The Settlement Date of the Contract shall be no later than the day after the\nExpiration Date, unless the Market Outcome is under review pursuant to Rule 7.1.\n\nExpiration Date: When <time period> refers to a specific event: The latest Expiration Date of\nthe Contract shall be fourteen (14) calendar days after the originally scheduled date of the\nevent. If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window, expiration will be moved to an\nearlier date and time in accordance with Rule 7.2. When <time period> is defined by specific\ndates: The latest Expiration Date of the Contract shall be two weeks after the end of <time\nperiod>. If an event described in the Payout Criterion occurs and a consensus has been\nreached on all terms, then expiration will be moved to an earlier date and time in accordance\nwith Rule 7.2.\n\fExpiration time: The Expiration time of the Contract shall be 10:00 AM ET.\n\nSettlement Value: The Settlement Value for this Contract is $1.00.\n\nExpiration Value: The Expiration Value is the value of the Underlying as documented by the\nSource Agency on the Expiration Date at the Expiration time.\n\nContingencies: Before Settlement, Kalshi may, at its sole discretion, initiate the Market\nOutcome Review Process pursuant to Rule 7.1 of the Rulebook. If an Expiration Value cannot\nbe determined on the Expiration Date, Kalshi has the right to determine payouts pursuant to\nRule 7.1 in the Rulebook.\n\f\n\n[plaintiff] PX-4 Formal draw archive note\nSource checked: Roll Call / Factba.se archive\n\nArchive title: Remarks: Donald Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing in Washington - December 5, 2025\n\nArchive URL: https://rollcall.com/factbase/trump/transcript/donald-trump-remarks-fifa-world-cup-drawing-december-5-2025/\n\nWhat this file establishes:\n\nThere is a separate archived transcript page for Trump's formal attendance remarks at the draw.\n\nWhat this file does not establish:\n\nThis session could not retrieve the full transcript text from that archive.  The page is password-protected.  This example therefore does not claim, from local files alone, whether the formal program transcript does or does not contain the word \"Ronaldo.\"\n\nWhy this matters:\n\nThe complaint does not need to prove that the formal program omitted the strike.  It needs to show that Trump said \"Ronaldo\" in event-linked remarks and that the market boundary reasonably includes those remarks.  The formal archive remains relevant because it marks the distinction between the pre-event reporter exchange and the formal program.\n\n\n[plaintiff] PX-5 GovInfo official transcript excerpt and metadata\nSource: GovInfo, DCPD202501162, Office of the Federal Register / National Archives and Records Administration.\nURL: https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/DCPD-202501162/html/DCPD-202501162.htm\nTitle: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\nEvent date: December 5, 2025.\n\nRelevant extracted page text:\n\"Administration of Donald J. Trump, 2025\"\n\"Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw December 5, 2025\"\n\"[The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\"\n\nUnder the section \"The President's Interest in Soccer\":\n\"Q. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\"\n\"The President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\\\"football,\\\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\"\n\"Thank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\"\n\nAdditional relevant extracted page text:\n\"The President's Interest in Soccer\"\n\"Q. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\"\n\"The President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\"\n\"Mr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\"\n\"The President. But they have a little more speed. But no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\"\n\nGovInfo note:\n\"NOTE: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. In his remarks, he referred to Trey Yingst, chief foreign correspondent, Fox News Channel; Cristiano Ronaldo, forward for Saudi Pro League club Al-Nass and Portugal's national soccer team; and Lionel Messi, forward for Major League Soccer club Inter Miami and Argentina's national team. A reporter referred to New York State Attorney General Letitia James. The transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\"\n\nGovInfo content details page also identifies category \"Interviews With the News Media : Exchanges with reporters, Washington, DC,\" subjects including \"Federation Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) World Cup,\" \"John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts,\" and \"Soccer,\" and names including \"Ronaldo, Cristiano\" and \"Messi, Lionel.\"\n\n[defendant] DX-1 Market wording and challenged resolution\nMarket URL: https://kalshi.com/markets/kxtrumpmentionb/trump-mention-b/kxtrumpmentionb-25dec06\n\nPublic market title: What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\n\nContract family: PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION\n\nStrike at issue: Ronaldo\n\nChallenged resolution: No\n\nRequested resolution: Yes\n\n\n[defendant] DX-2 Pre-event reporter exchange transcript\nRemarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\nDecember 05, 2025\n\n[The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\nThe President. It's a great honor to be here. Gianni has done a fantastic job. We're setting records—[inaudible].\nQ. [Inaudible]\nThe President. Well, I think so. They have a little bit of a shot. Pretty stiff competition. But I would say they would have a small chance.\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize\nQ. [Inaudible]—win the FIFA Peace Award?\nThe President. Well, it would be an honor.\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\nQ. Will you root for some selection? Will you root for someone?\nThe President. Well, I root for a lot of countries, but in this case, I'll be rooting for the U.S.A. [Laughter]\nQ. [Inaudible]\nThe President. That's great. That's great. We really love it.\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize\nQ. Mr. President, have you been told that you are going to receive the inaugural peace prize today——\nThe President. I have not——\nQ. ——from FIFA?\nThe President. I have not been told. There's a rumor about it, but I have not been told. That would be a great honor, and I'm a big fan of Gianni, as you know.\nQ. What can fans expect——\nQ. Are you hoping to receive that?\nThe President. Excuse me.\nQ. Are you hoping to receive the peace prize?\nThe President. Well, I don't like to say \"hope,\" but it would be a great honor.\n2026 World Cup\nQ. What can fans expect of, like, the World Cup in the U.S.?\nThe President. I think it's going to be fantastic. We've set every record you can set.\nQ. What are you telling people who are worried——\nFédération Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) President Giovanni V. Infantino\nQ. [Inaudible]—friend Gianni—[inaudible]—a word about him?\nThe President. I think he has done a fantastic job.\nThe President's Schedule\nQ. Are you going to be meeting with the President of Mexico today and the——\nThe President. We might. Yes.\nQ. ——Prime Minister of Canada as well?\nThe President. I might. I might do that.\nQ. Will you be discussing immigration and trade with them?\nThe President. Yes, we'll be discussing.\n[At this point, the President and Mr. Infantino posed for photographs.]\nThe President. Thank you, everybody.\n2026 World Cup Draw Event/John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts\nQ. Mr. President, what do you think about the crowd?\nThe President. Oh, look, the new star—[inaudible].\nCongratulations.\nQ. Thank you.\nThe President. You're the new star of television and Fox.\nQ. Thank you. How are you doing, Mr. President?\nThe President. I'm doing very well.\nQ. What do you think about the crowd here?\nThe President. I think the crowd is great, and I think the building is great. We've made a lot of improvements over the last 6 months. Taking—the Kennedy Center was in very bad shape. Now it's getting to be really good. And in 6 months, it's going to be incredible with the improvements we've made.\nQ. The first time for the U.S. to host since the nineties.\nThe President. Right.\nQ. Are you ready for it?\nThe President. I'm ready for it, and they're ready for it. And Gianni, who you know——\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\nThe President. ——has done a fantastic job with FIFA. And we're looking to have—you know, we're set—we have already set records for tickets sales. I don't think there's ever been anything like it in any sport. And so, I want to congratulate you.\nMr. Infantino. Thank you.\nThe President. I don't even have to wait. But major records have been set.\nHow are you?\nQ. Good, how are you, sir?\nThe President. Nice to see you.\nQ. Today it's not football—American football. It's soccer. It's——\nThe President. Right.\nQ. ——the big event of soccer.\nThe President. That's right. That's right.\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\nQ. So can you tell me about this big day today?\nThe President. It's just a big day, and it's a great sport. And it really is coming to America. And never—nobody ever thought a thing like this could happen. And I'm very happy to say that we've already set the alltime record on ticket sales long before the first ball is kicked. Right?\nMr. Infantino. A hundred percent. One hundred percent.\n2026 World Cup Host Cities\nQ. You've had some concerns about crime in American cities, some of the cities that will be hosting. Have they remedied that for you? Are you still considering maybe asking FIFA to move some of those cities?\nThe President. No, I don't want to do that. But I will tell you, if they do have a problem, by the time we get there, we'll take care of that problem. We can solve that problem.\nI've proven that in DC and everywhere else we went, so we'll take care of that very easily. So, if they have a problem, hopefully, they'll let us know that, and we will solve any problem.\nOkay? Thank you.\nQ. Thank you so much.\nMr. Infantino. All right, thank you so much.\nQ. Thank you, Mr. President.\nQ. Thank you. Appreciate it.\nThe President. Congratulations.\n2026 World Cup\nQ. Mr. President, Brazilian television. America will be hosting the World Cup and the Olympics in 2 years. How important it is—[inaudible]?\nThe President. I think very. It's a great honor. I think Gianni is doing a phenomenal job. We've set every record on ticket sales. It's been really fantastic. But Gianni has done an unbelievable job with FIFA.\nThe President's Experience With Soccer\nQ. [Inaudible]\nThe President. He was a great—not only that. I got to see a man name Pelé play—right?—that tells you how old I am—when he was on the Cosmos. Do you remember that a long time ago? And it was quite a treat. That was quite an event. And he was—not only was he playing, he was great. He scored two goals, I think. And so, I was one of the few who got to see Pelé, and I assume he is one of your alltime greats. Right?\nMr. Infantino. Definitely.\nThe President. So I got to see him.\nThe President's Favorite World Cup Competitor\nQ. Do you have some favorite teams for World Cup?\nThe President. Well, I have a favorite. It's the U.S.A. [Laughter] I don't know what their chances are, Gianni, but maybe the U.S.A. is the——\nMr. Infantino. They're getting better and better, actually.\nThe President. I think they'll do well.\nMr. Infantino. They are getting better and better.\nThe President. I think they'll do well.\nThank you very much, everybody.\nQ. Thank you so much.\n2026 World Cup\nQ. Mr. President, World Cup in America just means—[inaudible]. So what do you expect from this World Cup?\nThe President. [Inaudible]—record business and only in the United States, but we're also doing record ticket sales with FIFA. And they've already bought—beat their highest record. And we—you know, this a long time before the first ball is kicked. You've sold more tickets than they've ever done before, and better pricing than they've ever gotten before. It's a tremendous success. And it's an honor. And Gianni has done a phenomenal job with FIFA.\nQ. [Inaudible]—ever?\nThe President. I think so. I think it's going to be—I mean, ideally, you want to see that every year. Every 4 years, it gets bigger and better. I think we have set every record in the book. We're very happy about it.\nThank you.\nThe President's Favorite World Cup Competitor\nQ. [Inaudible]—part of America. Who are you going to support as well?\nThe President. Well, I think I have to support U.S.A. Otherwise, I'd be in trouble. I wouldn't be President for long.\nMr. Infantino. [Inaudible]\nThe President. [Inaudible]—but you have a lot of great teams. You're going to have a lot of great teams.\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\"football,\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\n2026 World Cup Draw/Ticket Sales for World Cup\nQ. How does it feel to be part of this amazing event? And obviously, your being a part of participating in all the—[inaudible]?\nThe President. The President of Mexico is here, and she's doing a very good job. She's a good woman, very, very excellent job. It's an honor, and we're setting every record, and you're helping us set those records.\nMr. Infantino. And we will do it.\nThe President. You know, Mexico and Canada are helping us set those records. But as you know, we have a record in ticket sales already, long before the first ball is kicked, and we're going to do great.\nI think that Gianni—as you know, he's the head, and he has done a fantastic job.\nU.S. Cooperation With Mexico and Canada\nQ. And how is the biggest challenge being three countries?\nThe President. Well, I think that—do you mean for the three countries?\nWell, they've gotten together really well, I mean.\nMr. Infantino. All right.\nThe President. They're getting along very well.\nMr. Infantino. Collaboration is fantastic between the three.\nThe President's Interest in Soccer/2026 World Cup\nQ. And you like soccer?\nThe President. I do. I like it. I like it more and more.\nQ. Yes?\nThe President. I like it. It's growing in this country—very, really—I mean, someday, maybe it's going to be bigger than anything else.\nMr. Infantino. We'll have to become number one.\nThe President. I will say this——\nMr. Infantino. Definitely.\nThe President. ——the ticket sales——\nQ. Definitely will happen.\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\nThe President. Ticket sales are bigger than anything we have ever done in the history of the country, in terms of sports.\nMr. Infantino. For certain.\nQ. And the audience is going to be huge.\nThe President. The audience is going to be tremendous.\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\nThe President. Yes.\nMr. Infantino. Six billion people.\nThe President. [Inaudible]\nQ. Six billion? That's amazing.\nMr. Infantino. Six billion people.\nAnd today, one billion.\nQ. Wow.\nMr. Infantino. [Inaudible]\nQ. Enjoy show time. Thank you so much.\nThe President. [Inaudible]\nQ. Mr. President, how are you? Just a quick—[inaudible].\nQ. This is for Telemundo.\nThe President. How are you?\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\nQ. Hello, Mr. President. How are you? This for Telemundo.\nThe President. How are you? Good.\nQ. How are you?\nThe President. Very good. Thank you.\nQ. How does it feel to have the most important event of sports—that global—in the U.S.?\nThe President. Well, we do. And right at the Kennedy Center. I'm Chairman of the Kennedy Center. And I hear the Kennedy Center is doing a very good job, so it feels great. Really good.\nAnd Telemundo is doing a good job, too. Thank you.\nQ. Thank you.\n2026 World Cup\nQ. What is the significance of hosting the FIFA World Cup this year?\nThe President. It's a—in terms of sports, I would say the ultimate. There is no sport like this. It's the biggest sport in the world. And we are setting every record. You know, our ticket sales have gone and set every—every sport—no matter what it is, we've set the record. So—and every though it's very early, there's no ball being kicked yet, but we've already set a ticket sales record.\nArgentina National Team\nQ. How do you see Argentinean team for this World Cup?\nThe President. Well, I love Argentina. And your President is doing a very good job, as you know. Milei. You know that right? It's make Argentina great again. MAGA.\nQ. And——\nU.S. National Team\nQ. Do you think the States are building a powerful team for next year?\nThe President. Who?\nQ. The States.\nThe President. Oh, yes. Sure. I—you're going to have a lot of powerful teams. Everybody has a lot of powerful teams, but you're going to have a lot of great teams. [Inaudible]\nU.S. Role in Hosting the 2026 World Cup\nQ. Mr. President, what does it mean for you guys to host the World Cup right here in the U.S.?\nThe President. I'm honored to host it. It's a great honor. I mean, it's turned out to be bigger than we thought. We're setting a record for ticket sales, the likes of which no sport has ever seen before.\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\nThe President. But they have a little more speed.\nBut no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\nPopularity of Soccer in Latin America\nQ. Mr. President, a message for the Latin America and soccer fans?\nThe President. Yes, I am. And Latin America is great. And they have great soccer. So, good luck in the matches.\n[A reporter asked a question in Spanish, which was translated by an interpreter as follows.]\nU.S. Visas for World Cup Ticketholders\nQ. Who is going to be in—[inaudible]—about these visas for the—these fans that want to come here to the World Cup?\nThe President. Well, we're going to make it very easy for them. We're working on that right now. We're going to make it very easy. It's going to be a very easy process.\nQ. Okay. Say, hi to Colombia over there.\nThe President. Hello. Is that Colombia?\nQ. Yes.\nThe President. I love Colombia. Hello, Colombia. [Laughter]\nQ. Okay. Okay. Muy bien.\nThe President. So where are you from?\nQ. Paraguay.\nThe President. Oh.\nQ. He's from Paraguay. Yes.\nThe President. Very good. I love it. I—it's a beautiful country. We get along very well with them. We do a little trade deal with them, and they like us. And that's what's happening.\nQ. Panama.\nThe President. Where?\nVery good. I like the canal. [Laughter] That canal is pretty good.\n[A reporter spoke in Spanish; no translation was provided.]\n2026 World Cup\nThe President. What?\nQ. [Inaudible]\nThe President. Well, it's going to be incredible. The event is going to be very good. Just this event alone—it's at the Kennedy Center. I see you have it fixed up perfectly.\nMr. Infantino. It will set the tone.\nThe President. Right? It's beautiful.\nMr. Infantino. It's beautiful.\nThe President. It's a beautiful place.\nHave a good time.\nQ. [Inaudible]\nThe President.\n[A reporter spoke in Spanish; no translation was provided.]\nMr. Infantino. No, gracias. [Inaudible]\nThe President. It's great.\nJohn F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts/Renovation Work\nQ. Mr. President, the U.S. press?\nThe President. Thank you, everybody, very much. It's a great honor. This has been an honor for a lot of reasons. Number one, they've sold more tickets than any event has ever sold already—long before the kickoff.\nAnd number two, we've done a lot of work at the Kennedy Center. It was falling apart, and now it's pretty much back. And we'll get it back within the next 4 or 5 months through construction, and—but you see the way it looks.\nAnd Gianni is just telling me—who's done an incredible job, by the way. He's just telling, you know, how good a job we've done.\nMr. Infantino. That's right.\nThe President. You can look at the walls. The marble was broken. Everything was a mess. And we've really taken the Kennedy Center—a lot of people thought it was going to be ripped down, and we did just the opposite. So we've done a really great renovation job on it. And over the next 3, 4 months, it will be complete. And we're honored to have it here, and it's been—it's been very special.\nWe've set a record on ticket sales, as you probably heard, already, even way before—long before the event itself. And we're working with Canada, and we're working with Mexico. And it's been a really spectacular—so far, it's been spectacular.\nDaniel [Daniel Baldwin, One America News Network], do you have a question?\n2026 World Cup\nQ. What are your expectations? You once said that the FIFA World Cup is an opportunity to put—a once-in-a-lifetime opportunity to put the greatness of the United States on display.\nThe President. Well, I think—\nQ. One billion eyeballs will be watching, Mr. President.\nThe President. Yes, I—think——\nQ. What will they here today?\nThe President. Even today, I understand. I hear that, you know——\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\nThe President. ——I know we're a little late to get in there, but——\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\nThe President. ——that's okay.\nMr. Infantino. They wait.\nThe President. So all my friends, I guess they have to wait. They have no choice, right? [Laughter]\nMr. Infantino. Yes, they wait.\nThe President. But no, the numbers are incredible. I hear today's numbers are——\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\nThe President. ——very big. I hope CNN is covering this.\nQ. One billion eyeballs.\nMr. Infantino. Today, 1 billion eyeballs.\nThe President. Today's numbers are very, very big.\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize/The President's Foreign Policy\nQ. We are covering it. And you're expected to get the FIFA Peace Prize, Mr. President. What would you say to people who say that prize might conflict with your pledge to strike Venezuela?\nThe President. Well, I think the peace prize—I mean, I settled eight wars. I don't know that I'm getting it. I haven't been officially noticed. I've been hearing about a peace prize, and I'm here to represent our country in a different sense. But I can tell you, I did settle eight wars, and we have a ninth coming, but—which nobody has ever done before.\nBut I want to really save lives. I don't need prizes. I need to save lives. And we're saving a lot of lives. And I've saved millions and millions of lives, and that's really what I want to do.\nAnd I also want to run a great country. And the United States right now is the hottest country anywhere in the world. And 1 year ago, it was dead. We had a dead country, and now we have the hottest country anywhere in the world.\nQ. Mr. President, will you——\nThe President's Meeting With President Claudia Sheinbaum Pardo of Mexico and Prime Minister Mark Carney of Canada\nQ. What are you going to discuss with Canada and Mexico, Mr.—what are you going to discuss with the leaders of Canada and Mexico?\nThe President. Well, we're getting—we're going to meet with both. And we're getting along very well. You know, we're getting along very well. I don't know. I think we have a meeting set up for some time after the event.\nQ. Will you discuss trade?\nThe President. Yes, we'll discuss trade. We—get along very well.\nThank you, everybody, very much.\nQ. Will you pardon any other Honduran officials?\nQ. Do you want them to keep trying to indict Ms. James?\n\nNOTE: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. In his remarks, he referred to Trey Yingst, chief foreign correspondent, Fox News Channel; Cristiano Ronaldo, forward for Saudi Pro League club Al-Nass and Portugal's national soccer team; and Lionel Messi, forward for Major League Soccer club Inter Miami and Argentina's national team. A reporter referred to New York State Attorney General Letitia James. The transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\n\nSource URL: https://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/documents/remarks-exchange-with-reporters-prior-the-2026-federation-internationale-des-associations\n\n\n[defendant] DX-3 GovInfo/OFR pre-event transcript excerpt\nSource: GovInfo, DCPD202501162, Office of the Federal Register / National Archives and Records Administration.\nURL: https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/DCPD-202501162/html/DCPD-202501162.htm\nTitle: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\nEvent date: December 5, 2025.\n\nRelevant extracted page text:\n\"Administration of Donald J. Trump, 2025\"\n\"Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw December 5, 2025\"\n\"[The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\"\n\nUnder the section \"The President's Interest in Soccer\":\n\"Q. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\"\n\"The President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\\\"football,\\\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\"\n\"Thank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\"\n\nAdditional relevant extracted page text:\n\"The President's Interest in Soccer\"\n\"Q. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\"\n\"The President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\"\n\"Mr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\"\n\"The President. But they have a little more speed. But no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\"\n\nGovInfo note:\n\"NOTE: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. In his remarks, he referred to Trey Yingst, chief foreign correspondent, Fox News Channel; Cristiano Ronaldo, forward for Saudi Pro League club Al-Nass and Portugal's national soccer team; and Lionel Messi, forward for Major League Soccer club Inter Miami and Argentina's national team. A reporter referred to New York State Attorney General Letitia James. The transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\"\n\nGovInfo content details page also identifies category \"Interviews With the News Media : Exchanges with reporters, Washington, DC,\" subjects including \"Federation Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) World Cup,\" \"John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts,\" and \"Soccer,\" and names including \"Ronaldo, Cristiano\" and \"Messi, Lionel.\"\n\n[defendant] DX-4 PRESMENTION/NEWMENTION terms\n                                         NEWMENTION\n\nScope: These rules shall apply to this contract.\n\nUnderlying: The Underlying for this Contract is words used by <entity> <time period>.\nRevisions to the Underlying made after Expiration will not be accounted for in determining the\nExpiration Value.\n\nSource Agency: The Source Agencies are <source>.\n\nType: The type of Contract is an Event Contract.\n\nIssuance: After the initial Contract, Contract iterations will be listed on an as-needed basis at\nthe discretion of the Exchange and corresponding to the risk management needs of Members.\n\n<entity>: <entity> refers to the speaker, writer, performer, or communicator specified by the\nExchange. This may include (but is not limited to): a specific named individual, multiple\nindividuals specified using AND/OR logic, an individual identified by position or title, a group,\nband, team or collective entity, a specified member or members of a group, an organization,\ncompany, or institutional entity, or any combination of the aforementioned.\n\nWhen <entity> is defined by a position or title, the Contract tracks whoever holds that position\nduring <time period>, even if the individual holding the position changes. When <entity> is a\nspecific named individual, the identity remains consistent throughout. Name changes (e.g.,\nstage names, married names) do not create a new entity. When <entity> is a group or\norganization and the Contract does not specify particular members, any official\ncommunication or statement by any member or designated spokesperson counts. When using\nAND logic, all specified entities must independently say <word> during <time period>. When\nusing OR logic, at least one of the specified entities must say <word> during <time period>.\nThe Exchange may specify additional conditions such as “at least X members of” a group or\n“the majority of” a group.\n\n<source>: <source> refers to a Source Agency or ordered collection of Source Agencies\nspecified by the Exchange at the time of Contract listing, which will be incorporated into the\nSource Agency hierarchy above and used to determine the occurrence of the Underlying.\n<source> may refer to a singular agency, multiple agencies, an agency by distinguishing\ncharacteristics, by category or type (e.g., “official government statistical body,” “primary wire\nservice”), or any combination thereof. When multiple agencies are specified, they may be\napplied in the hierarchical order designated by the Exchange if so specified, with the highest-\nranked available and responsive agency taking precedence for purposes of determining the\nExpiration Value. A lower-ranked agency shall only be consulted if all higher-ranked agencies\nare unavailable, unresponsive, have not reported on the Underlying by the Expiration time, or\nif the Exchange, in its sole discretion, determines that a higher-ranked agency’s reporting is\nincomplete, erroneous, or otherwise insufficient to determine the Expiration Value. If <source>\ndesignates multiple agencies without specifying a hierarchical order, the Exchange shall\nresolve any conflict between reporting agencies at its sole discretion.\n\n<word>: <word> refers to the particular word or phrase potentially to be mentioned by\n<entity>. It may refer to a word being said a minimum number of times. It may also refer to\none of multiple words/phrases, any of which are acceptable (e.g., “Doge/Dogecoin”).\n\f<time period>: <time period> refers to a specific range of time, event or discrete date and\ntime specified by the Exchange. This may be defined by, but is not limited to: a specific event\nor context (e.g., “during the State of the Union address”), exact dates or times, relative time\nmarkers (e.g., “before July 1, 2027,” “in Q1 2026”), event-based periods (e.g., “during any\ncampaign rally in October 2026,” “during the awards ceremony”), and broader intervals (e.g.,\n“Q1–Q2 2027,” “January–March 2026”).\n\nUnless stated otherwise, “Between” is inclusive of both endpoints, while “before” and “after”\nexclude the specified date. <time period> may also refer to “Any” or “None”, to multiple dates\n(even if non-consecutive), or to a singular and discrete date or time.\n\nWhen <time period> refers to a specific event (such as an address, speech, performance, or\nbroadcast), the Exchange may specify what is included, including whether it includes both live\nand pre-recorded segments (including whether advertisements are included). Where a\ntimezone is not specified, ET is assumed.\n\n\nPayout Criterion: The Payout Criterion for the Contract encompasses the Expiration Values that\n<word> is said by <entity> <time period>.\n\n\nThe word must appear as a distinct, standalone unit, not buried inside another word. Plural\nand possessive noun forms count. Other grammatical changes (tense, conjugation, derivation)\ndo not. If <word> appears separated from other words by a space or hyphen or in a\ncompound form with a space or hyphen, it counts. If <word> is fused into a single\nunhyphenated word, it does not count.\n\nIf <time period> refers to an event and that event is cancelled, and the market contains a\nstrike stating “Event does not qualify/occur”, such a strike shall resolve “Yes” and all others\n“No”. If <time period> refers to an event and that event is cancelled but such strikes are NOT\nlisted, the Contracts will resolve to the last fair price determined at the discretion of the\nExchange. If the event is postponed, and such a postponement is announced by the end of the\nfollowing calendar day to be rescheduled to a time within 14 calendar days, the markets shall\nremain open. If the event captured in <time period> is a live-stream or broadcast, the\nExchange may keep the market open for 24 hours for the release of an official recording.\nFurther granular details on conditions for these Contracts is available below.\n\nAdditional clarification(s):\n\n     Possessive noun forms of <word>, plurals, and possessive plural noun forms are\n     INCLUDED:\n          <word> is “Immigrant” → “Immigrants” counts\n          <word> is “Egg” → “eggs’ shells” counts\n          <word> is “Russia” → “Russia’s” counts, “Russian” does not\n     If <word> exists only in adjective form, no plural form exists:\n          <word> is “Economic” → “Economics” does not count (“Economic” is an adjective\n          for which “Economics” is not a plural)\n     Plural nouns occurring within proper nouns and noun phrases are included:\n          <word> is “Cat” → “Cats the musical” counts\n\f    Grammatical variations beyond plurals/possessives are NOT included:\n         <word> is “Immigrant” → “Immigration” does NOT count\n         <word> is “Run” → “Running” or “Ran” do NOT count\n    When <word> specifies a plural form, the singular does NOT count:\n         <word> is “Veterans” → “Veteran” does NOT count\n    Words that are spelled the same as the plural form of <word> (if such exists) but are\n    themselves not a plural noun are included:\n         <word> is “Wind” → “Winds up the clock” counts\n         <word> is “Border” → “The United States has strong borders” counts\n    Open compounds (words separated by spaces) count:\n         <word> is “fire” → “fire station” counts\n         <word> is “couch” → “couch potato” counts\n    Hyphenated compounds (words connected by hyphens) count:\n         <word> is “Palestine” → “pro-Palestine” counts\n         <word> is “fat” → “non-fat” counts\n    Closed compounds (single word, no spaces/hyphens) do not count:\n         <word> is “fire” → “wildfire” does not count\n         <word> is “fire” → “firefighter” does not count\n    Multi-word <word> in larger constructions: When <word> is a multi-word phrase\n    appearing within a hyphenated construction, it counts only if <word> appears as a\n    complete, unmodified element:\n         <word> is “New York” → “New York-based” counts (complete element)\n    Portmanteaus (words blended from two words where parts of each are combined) are\n    NOT included unless the portmanteau clearly contains <word> as a distinct, unaltered\n    element:\n         <word> is “MAGA” → “MAGA-nificent” counts (MAGA appears as distinct element)\n         <word> is “magnificent” → “MAGA-nificent” does NOT count (portmanteau blend)\n\nDictionary determination: Both the Merriam-Webster Dictionary (available online) AND the\nOxford English Dictionary shall be used to determine compound type and/or conventional\nspelling patterns. Inclusion in either dictionary as an open or hyphenated compound shall\nsatisfy the Payout Criterion. If neither provides clarity (or the word is not included),\ndetermination is based on whether written as single unit (closed/doesn’t count) vs. spaces or\nhyphens (open or hyphenated/counts) and/or context and previous usage.\n\nPHONETIC EQUIVALENCIES\n\n    Homophones (same sound, different spelling) do not count:\n        <word> is “write” → “right” does not count\n    Homonyms and homographs (same spelling) COUNT regardless of meaning or\n    pronunciation:\n        <word> is “bass” → both “bass guitar” and “bass fishing” count\n    Proper and common nouns are treated identically:\n        <word> is “Apple” → both “Apple Inc.” and “apple” (fruit) count\n        <word> is “Will” → both “Will Smith” and “I will go” count\n    Minor unintentional mispronunciations COUNT if context makes intent clear:\n        <word> is “Mamdani” → “Mandani” counts\n    Severe mispronunciations that make <word> unrecognizable do NOT count.\n    Trademarked spellings do not count, even when pronounced identically, unless the word\n\fitself is the same:\n      <word> is “lift” → “Lyft” (pronounced “lift”) does not count\n      <word> is “uber” → “Uber” counts\nWords with non-standard transliteration to English count within reason, provided they are\nphonetically equivalent:\n      <word> is “Zelensky” → any of “Zelenski,” “Zelenskii,” “Zelensky,” or “Zelenskiy”\n      count if pronounced equivalently\nContractions do not count for their constituent words unless otherwise explicitly specified\nby the Exchange:\n      <word> is “not” → “won’t,” “can’t,” “don’t,” “isn’t” do not count\nNumbers spoken as words COUNT, when spoken exactly (not part of a larger number):\n      <word> is “five” → saying “five” or reading “$5” aloud as “five dollars” counts,\n      saying “five hundred” does NOT count\n      <word> is “410” → “four hundred ten”, “four one zero” or “four ten” counts\nOrdinals COUNT when <word> is written numerically OR a phrase that includes a\nnumber:\n      <word> is “January 6” → “January 6th” counts\n      <word> is “3” (written numerically) → “3rd” (spoken as “third”) counts\n      <word> is “Eight War” → “8 Wars” and “Eighth War” will count\nCardinal and ordinal number words are distinct:\n      <word> is “one” → “first” does NOT count\n      <word> is “first” → “one” does NOT count\nAcronyms and abbreviations count when pronunciation or letter-by-letter spelling\nmatches <word>:\n      <word> is “NASA” → “NASA” (pronounced “NAH-suh”) counts\n      <word> is “NASA” → “N-A-S-A” (spelled out) counts\nAcronyms and abbreviations count as <word> when pronounced as the full word:\n      <word> is “Doctor” → “Dr.” (pronounced “Doctor”) counts\nExpanded forms of acronyms do NOT count:\n      <word> is “AI” → “artificial intelligence” does not count\nWords in foreign languages do NOT count unless they are perfect cognates with an\nEnglish word:\n      <word> is “fire” → “fuego” (Spanish) does NOT count\nEnglish words within foreign sentences count:\n      <word> is “policy” → “Nuestra policy es clara” counts\n<word> in organization/company names counts:\n      <word> is “Securities” → “Bank of America Securities” counts\nWords in URLs, emails, handles, and hashtags (exclusive of domain structure, email\nprovider or symbols) are treated as compounds when spoken as complete words, with the\ntype of compound subject to aforementioned rules:\n      <word> is “fire” → “firestation.com” pronounced “fire station dot com” counts\n      <word> is “fire” → “wildfire.com” pronounced “wildfire dot com” does NOT count\n      <word> is “apple” → “apple.com” pronounced “apple dot com” does count\n      When presented in URL, email, handle, or hashtag form, <word> shall be treated as\n      a compound, not a multi-word word\nSung, rapped, or poetic words COUNT if phonetically recognizable:\n      <word> is “money” → “moneyyy” (extended in rap) counts\n      Extreme distortion making <word> unrecognizable does NOT count.\nPhonetic alphabet spelling (“Foxtrot India Romeo Echo” for “FIRE”) does NOT count.\n\fCANCELLATIONS AND DELAYS\n\n   The Exchange may list an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike for any Contract. If listed,\n   such a strike refers to the structural conditions of the market, and is NOT adjudicated as a\n   <word> needing to be said by or validated by having been said by <entity>. If listed, this\n   strike resolves to “Yes” whenever the event fails to occur or qualify under the Payout\n   Criterion, or any other circumstance prevents normal resolution.\n   If no such strike is listed, and <time period> refers to a specific event, the following rules\n   apply if the event is cancelled, postponed, rescheduled, or materially altered (including\n   being closed to press) such that no video is released within one calendar day of the\n   original start time of the event:\n         If the event is cancelled, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price determined in\n         the sole discretion of the Exchange.\n         If the event is postponed or rescheduled, the outcome depends on whether a new\n         date is publicly announced within one calendar day (i.e. if the event was scheduled\n         to begin on Monday, any time up to 11:59PM on Tuesday falls within this period) of\n         the originally scheduled start time:\n               If no new date is announced within one calendar day, the Contract will resolve\n               to the last fair price determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\n               If a new date is announced within one calendar day, the outcome depends on\n               when the rescheduled event is set to occur:\n                     If the rescheduled date falls within fourteen (14) calendar days of the\n                     originally scheduled date, the Contract shall remain open and <word>\n                     stated during the rescheduled event will count.\n                           The fourteen-day window begins at 12:00 AM ET on the originally\n                           scheduled date and ends at 11:59 PM ET fourteen days later, unless\n                           an alternate timezone is explicitly specified.\n                           Example: <time period> is “during the State of the Union on January\n                           15, 2026” rescheduled to January 20, 2026 → words spoken during\n                           the rescheduled address count.\n                     If the rescheduled date falls more than fourteen (14) calendar days after\n                     the originally scheduled date, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price\n                     determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\n         Any Contract that cannot be resolved through the Source Agency hierarchy will\n         instead be settled at the Last Fair Price. The Exchange will disclose the methodology\n         used to determine the Last Fair Price (e.g., Last Traded Price, Time-Weighted\n         Average Price) at the time of Issuance.\n         If an event begins but is interrupted, abbreviated, or ends prematurely, words\n         stated by <entity> during the portion of the event that did occur will count and the\n         market will otherwise resolve.\n   If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window but the venue, format, or medium\n   changes (e.g., moved to a different location, changed from in-person to virtual (with the\n   exception of being closed to press)), words stated during the event will count.\n   Special condition: Across both cases, whether an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike is\n   listed or not, if the event specified as or in <time period> is a live-stream or broadcast (or\n   relayed as such) but the live stream/broadcast does not occur, the Exchange will instead\n   use an officially released recording as the Underlying, and may delay resolution by up to\n   one calendar day to allow for the release of such a recording.\n\f          If partial snippets are released, Contracts on words that do not appear will be\n          resolved to last fair price, and Contracts on those that do will be resolved to “Yes”.\n          If no recording is released, the relevant outcomes triggered by the\n          presence/absence of an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike shall occur as outlined\n          above.\n\nTECHNICAL DETAILS (UNLESS OTHERWISE SPECIFIED)\n\n     When <time period> refers to a specific event, pre-recorded content broadcast,\n     streamed, or published as part of that event is included if presented as part of the official\n     presentation.\n          Example: <time period> is “during the concert” with pre-recorded video interlude\n          where entity speaks → words from interlude count\n          Example: <time period> is “during the television appearance” with pre-taped\n          segment aired during broadcast → words from segment count\n     Behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are NOT\n     included unless officially broadcast or published as part of <time period>.\n     Subtitles and captions that display <word> on screen but are not spoken aloud by\n     <entity> do NOT count.\n     Sign language interpretation or usage by entity does NOT count as saying <word> unless\n     the Contract explicitly specifies that sign language counts.\n     Text that entity displays on screen (presentation slides, teleprompter visible to audience,\n     signatures) does NOT count unless entity reads it aloud.\n     Content generated by AI, deepfakes, or synthetic voice technology impersonating entity\n     does NOT count unless the synthetic content is officially commissioned, authorized, or\n     published by entity, OR the Contract explicitly specifies that AI-generated content counts.\n     If <word> is muted due to technical failure or censorship it shall not count unless\n     corroborating contextual evidence (including surrounding speech, or an official\n     uncensored recording or transcript) confirms that <entity> specifically uttered <word>\n     during the muted period.\n\nMinimum Tick: The Minimum Tick size for the Contract shall be $0.01.\n\nPosition Accountability Level: The Position Accountability Level for the Contract shall be\n$25,000 per strike, per Member.\n\nLast Trading Date: The Last Trading Date of the Contract will be the Expiration Date. The Last\nTrading Time will be the Expiration time.\n\nSettlement Date: The Settlement Date of the Contract shall be no later than the day after the\nExpiration Date, unless the Market Outcome is under review pursuant to Rule 7.1.\n\nExpiration Date: When <time period> refers to a specific event: The latest Expiration Date of\nthe Contract shall be fourteen (14) calendar days after the originally scheduled date of the\nevent. If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window, expiration will be moved to an\nearlier date and time in accordance with Rule 7.2. When <time period> is defined by specific\ndates: The latest Expiration Date of the Contract shall be two weeks after the end of <time\nperiod>. If an event described in the Payout Criterion occurs and a consensus has been\nreached on all terms, then expiration will be moved to an earlier date and time in accordance\nwith Rule 7.2.\n\fExpiration time: The Expiration time of the Contract shall be 10:00 AM ET.\n\nSettlement Value: The Settlement Value for this Contract is $1.00.\n\nExpiration Value: The Expiration Value is the value of the Underlying as documented by the\nSource Agency on the Expiration Date at the Expiration time.\n\nContingencies: Before Settlement, Kalshi may, at its sole discretion, initiate the Market\nOutcome Review Process pursuant to Rule 7.1 of the Rulebook. If an Expiration Value cannot\nbe determined on the Expiration Date, Kalshi has the right to determine payouts pursuant to\nRule 7.1 in the Rulebook.\n\f\n\n[defendant] DX-5 Formal draw archive note\nSource checked: Roll Call / Factba.se archive\n\nArchive title: Remarks: Donald Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing in Washington - December 5, 2025\n\nArchive URL: https://rollcall.com/factbase/trump/transcript/donald-trump-remarks-fifa-world-cup-drawing-december-5-2025/\n\nWhat this file establishes:\n\nThere is a separate archived transcript page for Trump's formal attendance remarks at the draw.\n\nWhat this file does not establish:\n\nThis session could not retrieve the full transcript text from that archive.  The page is password-protected.  This example therefore does not claim, from local files alone, whether the formal program transcript does or does not contain the word \"Ronaldo.\"\n\nWhy this matters:\n\nThe complaint does not need to prove that the formal program omitted the strike.  It needs to show that Trump said \"Ronaldo\" in event-linked remarks and that the market boundary reasonably includes those remarks.  The formal archive remains relevant because it marks the distinction between the pre-event reporter exchange and the formal program.\n\n\n[defendant] DX-6 Formal Roll Call/Factba.se transcript extraction\nSource: Roll Call / Factba.se\nURL: https://rollcall.com/factbase/trump/transcript/donald-trump-remarks-fifa-world-cup-drawing-december-5-2025/\nCaptured page title: Remarks: Donald Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing in Washington - December 5, 2025\n\nRendered page metadata excerpt:\nTopics: Sport; Sport > Competition Discipline > Soccer; Lifestyle and Leisure > Leisure > Game.\nEntities listed: bowl; deal; Donald J. Trump; FIFA World Cup; Mark Carney; place; President; trophy; United States; way.\nSpeakers listed: Gianni Infantino, Donald Trump, Mark Carney, Claudia Sheinbaum.\nSpeaker statistics excerpt: Donald Trump said 25 sentences of a total of 141 sentences; Donald Trump said 274 words of a total of 1009 words; Donald Trump talked 92 seconds of a total of 484 seconds.\n\nFormal transcript excerpt at start of draw:\nMark Carney, 00:00:00-00:00:02: Thank you, my friend.\nGianni Infantino, 00:00:50-00:01:22: So this is the World Cup trophy. This is the official bowl for the World Cup and we are now going to do the draw, ladies and gentlemen. But before that, as is customary, there is always a question that the moderator asks the draw assistant. So I would like to start with Mr. Carney. How big a deal is it to co-host the World Cup for Canada?\n\nFormal transcript excerpt of Trump's soccer answer:\nDonald Trump, 00:03:14-00:03:32: Well, for years, Gianni, they've thought soccer or football would be so big, so fast. And I remember, I shouldn't say this because it was a long time ago, but I remember watching Pele play on a team called the Cosmos, Pele, who was fantastic, as you know. I assume one of the greats.\n\nText-extraction/search notes:\nLocal Python urllib retrieval of the page returned HTTP 200 for the source URL and extracted approximately 175,864 characters of page text with Python html.parser. Case-sensitive searches in the extracted page text returned no occurrence of \"Ronaldo\" and no occurrence of \"Messi\". The same terms were not found using the browser page find function on the rendered page.\n\n[plaintiff] PX-R1 Defendant formal transcript extraction for limited rebuttal use\nSource: Roll Call / Factba.se\nURL: https://rollcall.com/factbase/trump/transcript/donald-trump-remarks-fifa-world-cup-drawing-december-5-2025/\nCaptured page title: Remarks: Donald Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing in Washington - December 5, 2025\n\nRendered page metadata excerpt:\nTopics: Sport; Sport > Competition Discipline > Soccer; Lifestyle and Leisure > Leisure > Game.\nEntities listed: bowl; deal; Donald J. Trump; FIFA World Cup; Mark Carney; place; President; trophy; United States; way.\nSpeakers listed: Gianni Infantino, Donald Trump, Mark Carney, Claudia Sheinbaum.\nSpeaker statistics excerpt: Donald Trump said 25 sentences of a total of 141 sentences; Donald Trump said 274 words of a total of 1009 words; Donald Trump talked 92 seconds of a total of 484 seconds.\n\nFormal transcript excerpt at start of draw:\nMark Carney, 00:00:00-00:00:02: Thank you, my friend.\nGianni Infantino, 00:00:50-00:01:22: So this is the World Cup trophy. This is the official bowl for the World Cup and we are now going to do the draw, ladies and gentlemen. But before that, as is customary, there is always a question that the moderator asks the draw assistant. So I would like to start with Mr. Carney. How big a deal is it to co-host the World Cup for Canada?\n\nFormal transcript excerpt of Trump's soccer answer:\nDonald Trump, 00:03:14-00:03:32: Well, for years, Gianni, they've thought soccer or football would be so big, so fast. And I remember, I shouldn't say this because it was a long time ago, but I remember watching Pele play on a team called the Cosmos, Pele, who was fantastic, as you know. I assume one of the greats.\n\nText-extraction/search notes:\nLocal Python urllib retrieval of the page returned HTTP 200 for the source URL and extracted approximately 175,864 characters of page text with Python html.parser. Case-sensitive searches in the extracted page text returned no occurrence of \"Ronaldo\" and no occurrence of \"Messi\". The same terms were not found using the browser page find function on the rendered page.\n\nSubmitted evidence:\n[plaintiff arguments] GovInfo DCPD202501162 transcript excerpt and metadata (ev_3fc783920414_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-3fc783920414)\nSource: https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/DCPD-202501162/html/DCPD-202501162.htm\nSHA-256: `3fc783920414399098d86210070dd9fe83c14fe1dbded1a56a554f8f4b3448f2`\nBytes: 2641\nRelevance: Official government transcript source corroborating that Trump spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center before the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw and said the strike word Ronaldo in World-Cup-related remarks.\n\n[defendant arguments] Roll Call/Factba.se formal FIFA World Cup Drawing transcript extraction (ev_fbb53e87ccb3_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-fbb53e87ccb3)\nSource: https://rollcall.com/factbase/trump/transcript/donald-trump-remarks-fifa-world-cup-drawing-december-5-2025/\nSHA-256: `fbb53e87ccb3f4381fc2bdc06ac2f2a1ea3848aadde56122b22d34dfbdf4533b`\nBytes: 2032\nRelevance: Formal drawing-program transcript evidence showing a separate formal Draw source from the pre-event reporter exchange; the extracted page text contains no occurrence of Ronaldo or Messi, supporting defendant's event-boundary argument.\n\nTechnical reports:\n[plaintiff] Plaintiff source and adverse-search ledger\nChecked the visible case packet and then searched official/source-specific repositories. GovInfo DCPD202501162 was opened and preserved as submitted evidence; it corroborates the packet transcript, source metadata, location, event date, and Ronaldo passages. The Roll Call/Factba.se formal drawing page rendered despite the packet's password-protection note; browser find searches for 'Ronaldo,' 'Cristiano,' and 'Messi' returned no matches. Plaintiff therefore treats the formal-program transcript as an adverse boundary check, not as proof of a formal-stage mention. The remaining dispute is contractual scope: whether the market clearly excluded public event-linked venue remarks immediately before the formal program.\n\n[defendant] Defense source-check ledger\nDefendant searched for the formal Roll Call/Factba.se transcript identified by the case packet, opened the rendered Roll Call page, and fetched it locally with Python urllib. The fetch returned HTTP 200 for the formal FIFA World Cup Drawing transcript page. Text extraction produced approximately 175,864 characters; searches for \"Ronaldo\" and \"Messi\" returned no occurrences. The retrieval also captured formal-program excerpts, including Infantino's statement that \"we are now going to do the draw\" and Trump's formal soccer answer mentioning Pele rather than Ronaldo. The focused extraction was submitted and accepted as ev_fbb53e87ccb3_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-fbb53e87ccb3.\n\nCall submit_council_vote with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated.\nKeep the rationale brief: no more than three sentences.\n\nCouncil API instructions:\nYou are a council member. Decide the proposition from the admitted record.\nYou may examine admitted evidence through read-only tools when exact bytes, metadata, or exhibit contents matter.\nDo not search the web, introduce new facts, create new evidence, or upload evidence.\nWhen ready, call submit_council_vote exactly once with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated and a concise rationale.\n","state":"ready","status":"ready","tools":[{"description":"Return the current visible arbitration record for this council member.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{},"type":"object"},"name":"get_case","read_only":true},{"description":"List visible immutable record evidence.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{},"type":"object"},"name":"list_evidence","read_only":true},{"description":"Return metadata and read limits for one visible evidence item.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"evidence_id":{"type":"string"}},"required":["evidence_id"],"type":"object"},"name":"stat_evidence","read_only":true},{"description":"Read a bounded byte range from one visible evidence item as base64.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"evidence_id":{"type":"string"},"length":{"minimum":1,"type":"integer"},"offset":{"minimum":0,"type":"integer"}},"required":["evidence_id","offset","length"],"type":"object"},"name":"read_evidence_range","read_only":true},{"description":"Submit one council vote for the current deliberation opportunity.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"rationale":{"type":"string"},"vote":{"enum":["demonstrated","not_demonstrated"],"type":"string"}},"required":["vote","rationale"],"type":"object"},"name":"submit_council_vote","read_only":false}],"turn":{"attempts_max":3,"attempts_remaining":3,"completed":false,"deadline":"2026-06-29T19:58:02.156322961Z","deliberation_round":1,"member_id":"C2","opportunity_id":"deliberation:1:C2","phase":"deliberation","remaining_ms":887183,"role_id":"council","turn_number":10},"wait":{"reason":"ready","state_version":12,"version":15}},"isError":false},"server":"aar","tool":"wait_for_opportunity"}},"isError":false}
{"type":"message_start","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_b9f90c55f2824ea0be4354","toolName":"mcp","content":[{"type":"text","text":"ok: true\nstatus: ready\nstate: ready\nmessage: An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\nafter_version: 15\nafter_opportunity_id: deliberation:1:C2\nmember_id: C2\ncase_id: arb-ex03-20260629192557\nwait_reason: ready\nphase: deliberation\nopportunity_id: deliberation:1:C2\nremaining_ms: 887183\nattempts_remaining: 3\njson: {\"after_opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C2\",\"after_version\":15,\"case_id\":\"arb-ex03-20260629192557\",\"limits\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"max_evidence_read_bytes\":65536,\"max_evidence_read_bytes_per_opportunity\":524288,\"max_evidence_reads_per_opportunity\":32,\"max_response_bytes\":131072,\"remaining_evidence_read_bytes_for_opportunity\":524288,\"remaining_evidence_reads_for_opportunity\":32},\"member_id\":\"C2\",\"message\":\"An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\",\"ok\":true,\"prompt\":\"Role: council member\\nMember ID: C2\\nDeliberation round: 1\\nProposition: For the Kalshi market \\\"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\\", the strike \\\"Ronaldo\\\" should resolve Yes because Trump said \\\"Ronaldo\\\" in public remarks at the World Cup Draw venue immediately before the formal program, and the market wording plus the governing mention-market terms did not clearly exclude those event-linked remarks.\\nStandard of evidence: Preponderance of the evidence.\\nPersona:\\nYou are a careful juror and council member.\\n\\nEvaluate the record faithfully. Decide only from the evidence, the stated rules, and the applicable burden of proof. Do not favor either side, fill gaps with speculation, or ignore uncertainty.\\n\\nGive weight to reliable sources, direct evidence, consistent reasoning, and clear admissions. Discount unsupported claims, rhetorical force, irrelevant facts, and conclusions that exceed the record.\\n\\nWhen the evidence supports one answer, state it plainly. When the evidence is incomplete or balanced, say so. Be concise, honest, and exact.\\n\\nRecord:\\nOpenings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, this case is not mainly about whether the syllables were spoken. The case-packet transcript says they were. The real dispute is the market boundary: when Kalshi asked what Trump would say \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw,\\\" did that phrase clearly exclude his public, event-linked remarks at the World Cup Draw venue immediately before the formal program? On this record, it did not.\\n\\nThe market page fixes the contract at issue: the public title was \\\"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\\"; the contract family was PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION; the strike was \\\"Ronaldo\\\"; Kalshi challenged the resolution as No; and the requested resolution is Yes. That means the council's task is to apply the mention-market terms to that title and strike, not to import a narrower limitation that the market did not plainly announce.\\n\\nThe reporter-exchange packet is direct evidence on the word and setting. It is titled as remarks in an exchange with reporters prior to the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw, dated December 5, 2025. It places the President at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts, speaking with FIFA President Gianni Infantino and reporters in a sequence repeatedly labeled around the 2026 World Cup and the Draw. In that exchange, in a soccer discussion, Trump says he met Ronaldo, praises him, and uses \\\"Ronaldo\\\" as a distinct standalone word. Under the mention rules, a distinct standalone appearance of the strike is the kind of use that counts if it falls within the time period.\\n\\nThe terms matter because they do not say that an event market is limited only to scripted remarks from a formal stage segment. They define a time period as potentially an event or context, and they give the Exchange power to specify what is included when a time period refers to a specific event. They also distinguish official/public event content from behind-the-scenes, rehearsals, and unofficial recordings. That distinction helps plaintiff: the packet is not a rumor, rehearsal, private soundcheck, or leaked recording. It is a sourced public transcript of remarks at the event venue, immediately tied to the Draw. If Kalshi meant \\\"only the formal televised draw program after doors close\\\" or \\\"only remarks in the separate formal archive,\\\" it needed to say so clearly.\\n\\nI also want to be candid about what the packet does not yet prove. The formal-draw archive note says a separate archived transcript page exists for Trump's formal attendance remarks, but that the session could not retrieve the full text because the page was password-protected. So, at opening, plaintiff is not asking you to infer that the formal program itself contained \\\"Ronaldo.\\\" Nor does plaintiff need that inference. The Yes theory is that the qualifying period reasonably includes the public pre-program reporter exchange that was part of Trump's World Cup Draw appearance. The formal archive is relevant because it marks defendant's likely narrower boundary; it does not resolve the boundary in defendant's favor.\\n\\nProvenance and weight also favor treating the packet seriously at this stage. The market and terms files are system case-packet records. The reporter exchange includes a source URL to a public presidential transcript source and notes a corrected transcript date, while also acknowledging that some audio could not be verified because the audio was incomplete. That caveat may affect inaudible portions, but it does not erase the visible, contextual Ronaldo passage. Later, when evidence admission opens, the parties should preserve the official transcript source, any govinfo or Presidency Project copy, the market page capture, and any accessible formal-program transcript or video. The adverse check should ask whether the formal program omits the word, but omission there would matter only if the council first accepts the defense's artificially narrow reading of \\\"during.\\\"\\n\\nThe plaintiff's burden is preponderance. The record already points to a straightforward path to Yes: Trump, the specified entity, said the specified strike as a standalone word in public remarks linked to and immediately preceding the World Cup Draw at the venue; the market title and governing terms did not clearly exclude that event-linked exchange. On a fair reading of the contract the trader saw, the challenged No resolution should give way to Yes.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the defense opening is simple: this case is not won by proving that the word \\\"Ronaldo\\\" appears somewhere in a public transcript. The plaintiff must prove, by a preponderance, that the word was said during the market's specified event: the FIFA World Cup Draw.\\n\\nThe current packet leaves that critical link unproven. The market page does not say \\\"while Trump was at the venue,\\\" \\\"during a World Cup press availability,\\\" or \\\"during any remarks connected to the Draw.\\\" It says: \\\"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\\" The challenged resolution was No. The requested Yes theory therefore needs more than event-adjacent context; it needs a boundary showing that the reporter exchange was part of the Draw period the market asked traders to price.\\n\\nThe plaintiff's own best transcript cuts against that boundary. The case-packet file is titled \\\"Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw.\\\" It says the President's remarks were joined in progress, and the source note says portions could not be verified because the audio was incomplete. It places Trump at the Kennedy Center and includes World Cup topics, and yes, it contains \\\"Ronaldo\\\" as a standalone word in a soccer exchange. But its title and structure identify those remarks as an exchange with reporters prior to the Draw, not the formal Draw itself.\\n\\nThe terms do not rescue plaintiff from that distinction. They define a mention market around words used by the entity during the time period. A time period may be a specific event, and when it is a specific event, the Exchange may specify what is included. The technical details also distinguish official presentation content from behind-the-scenes, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings unless those are officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. Those provisions do not mean every public, nearby, event-related conversation becomes part of the event. They make the event boundary the central question.\\n\\nThe formal-draw archive note reinforces why the distinction matters. It reports that there is a separate archived transcript page for Trump's formal attendance remarks at the FIFA World Cup Drawing, but that the full text was not retrieved because the page was password-protected. That note does not prove the formal program omitted Ronaldo. It also does not prove the formal program included it. What it does show, at opening, is that the record itself separates the pre-event reporter exchange from the formal drawing remarks.\\n\\nSo the defense will focus the council on proof of inclusion, not mere association. If later phases produce a market page provision, official broadcast record, program transcript, video metadata, or source-agency material showing that the red-carpet reporter exchange was officially part of the FIFA World Cup Draw presentation for this market, the council can weigh that. If the later evidence instead shows a formal program with a separate pre-program press availability, then the correct result is No even though the word was spoken nearby.\\n\\nOn this opening record, plaintiff has shown a Ronaldo mention in remarks prior to the event. Plaintiff has not shown that those remarks occurred during the market event. The defense position is that Kalshi's No resolution follows the market wording and the mention-market terms unless plaintiff supplies that missing boundary proof.\\n\\nArguments:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the merits question is whether the contract clearly limited “during the FIFA World Cup Draw” to only the formal staged ceremony. Plaintiff submits that it did not, and the record now proves the Yes result by a preponderance.\\n\\nFirst, the market itself is broad. PX-1 identifies the public question as “What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?”, contract family PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION, strike “Ronaldo,” challenged resolution No, and requested resolution Yes. The market page does not say “during the formal televised ceremony,” “on the main stage only,” or “excluding public remarks immediately before the program at the venue.” That absence matters because Kalshi drafted the boundary traders had to price.\\n\\nSecond, the word was said. PX-2, the case-packet transcript, and PX-5, the GovInfo/OFR source excerpt, both show Trump used “Ronaldo” as a standalone word in soccer-related remarks. PX-5 is especially useful on provenance: it is the GovInfo Compilation of Presidential Documents source, published by the Office of the Federal Register/NARA, for DCPD202501162. It identifies the same event date, title, and source note, and it places the remarks at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center. In the relevant passage, Trump says he met Ronaldo, then says Ronaldo is great; later, when asked whether he played soccer or football, Trump says he was not Ronaldo or Messi. Either use satisfies the mention rule if the remarks fall within the market’s time period.\\n\\nThird, the remarks are event-linked in the way the market title reasonably covers. PX-2 and PX-5 are not private gossip, rehearsal, or an unofficial leak. They are public presidential remarks at the World Cup Draw venue, with FIFA President Infantino present, repeatedly discussing the Draw, the World Cup, ticket sales, the Kennedy Center, the audience, and the imminent program. The transcript itself includes headings such as “2026 World Cup Draw Event,” “2026 World Cup Draw Event/John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts,” and “2026 World Cup Draw/Ticket Sales for World Cup.” Trump and Infantino even discuss being a little late to “get in there” and the audience waiting. That sequence is not a random earlier interview; it is part of the public event appearance immediately surrounding the Draw.\\n\\nFourth, PX-3’s terms do not impose defendant’s formal-only line. They say the underlying is words used by the entity during the specified time period; a time period may be an event or context; and, when a time period refers to a specific event, the Exchange may specify what is included. They also say official/published content presented as part of the official presentation can count, while behind-the-scenes, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings do not count unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. Those exclusions show what this is not. The transcript is an official published record of public remarks at the event venue, not a hidden backstage clip. Nothing in PX-1 or PX-3 clearly tells traders that public, event-linked venue remarks immediately before the formal program are out.\\n\\nDefendant’s best point is PX-4 and the formal Roll Call/Factba.se page: there is a separate formal-drawing transcript, and my search found no “Ronaldo” there. Plaintiff does not hide that. But that adverse point proves only that the narrower formal-program source may omit the strike. It does not answer the contractual question. If Kalshi had meant to resolve solely by that formal transcript, it could have said so. Instead, the public market title used the broader phrase “during the FIFA World Cup Draw,” and the mention terms leave event boundaries to what the market clearly specifies.\\n\\nOn burden, plaintiff does not need absolute certainty or a formal-stage mention. Plaintiff must show it is more likely than not that the market wording plus terms include the event-linked remarks. The evidence satisfies that standard: PX-1 gives no exclusion; PX-2 and PX-5 prove the standalone Ronaldo mentions in public World Cup Draw venue remarks; PX-3 supplies a flexible event/time-period framework and excludes only categories unlike this source; PX-4 merely identifies the defense’s alternate formal-program boundary. The fair resolution is Yes.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the record now makes the defense point sharper, not weaker. Plaintiff has proved that Trump said \\\"Ronaldo\\\" in an official transcript of remarks connected to the World Cup Draw. Plaintiff has not proved that those remarks were during the market event.\\n\\nStart with the contract. DX/PX-1 gives the trader-facing question: \\\"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\\" It does not say \\\"at the Kennedy Center,\\\" \\\"on World Cup Draw day,\\\" \\\"in remarks prior to the Draw,\\\" or \\\"in any public press exchange associated with the Draw.\\\" For this strike to resolve Yes, the relevant mention must fall inside that specified time period.\\n\\nThe strongest evidence of the Ronaldo utterance is also the strongest evidence against plaintiff's boundary. PX-2 and PX-5 are titled \\\"Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw.\\\" PX-5, plaintiff's GovInfo/OFR source, confirms the same title, says the remarks were joined in progress, identifies the source as an exchange with the news media, and notes that some portions could not be verified because the audio was incomplete. That evidence proves an official pre-event reporter transcript. It does not prove the reporter exchange was the FIFA World Cup Draw.\\n\\nThe terms, PX-3, require words used by the entity during the specified time period. They permit an event or context as a time period, and they discuss what is included when the time period is a specific event. That framework does not turn all event-adjacent speech into event speech. The distinction between official presentation content and non-included behind-the-scenes or unofficial content matters because the question is not just whether a record is public or official. The question is whether this source was part of the market's event period. A public official transcript can still be a transcript of remarks prior to the event.\\n\\nDX-2 supplies the missing contrast. It is a focused extraction from the separate Roll Call/Factba.se formal FIFA World Cup Drawing transcript. That page is the formal source identified in the case-packet archive note. It is titled \\\"Remarks: Donald Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing in Washington - December 5, 2025.\\\" Its transcript begins with the formal drawing participants; at 00:00:50, Infantino says, \\\"This is the World Cup trophy\\\" and \\\"we are now going to do the draw.\\\" The page's Trump soccer answer mentions Pele and the Cosmos, not Ronaldo. The extracted page text was searched for both \\\"Ronaldo\\\" and \\\"Messi\\\" and neither appears.\\n\\nThat does not prove Trump never said Ronaldo anywhere at the venue. It proves the opposite boundary from plaintiff's: the formal Draw transcript is separate from the pre-event reporter exchange, and the formal transcript does not contain the strike. Plaintiff needs a bridge between those two sources. It has not offered one. There is no market page detail saying red-carpet or pre-program press remarks count. There is no official program metadata showing the reporter exchange was part of the Draw presentation. There is no source hierarchy provision selecting the pre-event reporter exchange over the formal Draw transcript for this market.\\n\\nPlaintiff argues ambiguity should favor Yes because Kalshi could have drafted a narrower rule. But this is a preponderance case about a challenged No resolution, not a penalty for every conceivable ambiguity. The ordinary reading of \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw\\\" is the draw program, not every public appearance immediately before it. The record's own labels preserve that ordinary line: \\\"Prior to\\\" on the Ronaldo source; \\\"Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing\\\" on the formal source; and a formal transcript that starts the draw and omits the strike.\\n\\nWeight and provenance also favor the defense on the decisive issue. PX-5 is official and useful, but it authenticates a pre-event reporter exchange. DX-2 is a captured formal transcript extraction from the source class identified in PX-4; its absence finding is limited but material. PX-4 was initially only a note that the formal page existed and could not be retrieved. We have now retrieved and searched it. The adverse check therefore confirms, rather than merely speculates, that the formal drawing transcript does not carry plaintiff's Ronaldo mention.\\n\\nThe council should resolve the proposition against plaintiff. The record shows Trump said Ronaldo before the FIFA World Cup Draw in an event-linked reporter exchange. It does not show he said Ronaldo during the FIFA World Cup Draw. On this market wording and these terms, the challenged No resolution should stand.\\n\\nRebuttals:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, defendant’s new formal-transcript extraction proves less than defendant needs.\\n\\nPlaintiff accepts the narrow fact defendant has now preserved: the Roll Call/Factba.se formal drawing-program extraction contains no “Ronaldo” or “Messi.” That is why plaintiff did not build the case on a formal-stage mention. The proposition instead asks whether the market wording and mention terms clearly excluded Trump’s public, official, event-linked remarks at the venue immediately before the formal program. Defendant has not supplied that exclusion.\\n\\nDefendant’s argument treats the title “Prior to the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw” as if “prior to” automatically means outside the Kalshi market’s event period. But PX-1 does not say “formal transcript only,” “after the draw host begins,” “after 00:00:50,” or “excluding press availability at the venue.” It asks what Trump would say “during the FIFA World Cup Draw.” The source label tells us sequence; it does not tell us the market’s legal boundary.\\n\\nDX-2 actually illustrates why defendant’s bright line is chosen after the fact. In defendant’s own formal extraction, the page begins before the mechanical draw: Mark Carney speaks at 00:00:00, and Infantino says at 00:00:50, “we are now going to do the draw.” If “during the FIFA World Cup Draw” can include ceremony and preamble on the formal page before the draw itself begins, then the phrase is not self-defining down to a single moment or transcript. The question is what the market clearly specified. It did not specify defendant’s transcript-only rule.\\n\\nThe terms do not fill that gap for defendant. PX-3 excludes hidden categories such as rehearsals, sound checks, unofficial recordings, and behind-the-scenes content unless officially published as part of the period. PX-2 and PX-5 are not those categories. PX-5 is an official GovInfo/OFR presidential transcript, published with source metadata, at 11:13 a.m. at the Kennedy Center, with FIFA’s president present and the World Cup Draw repeatedly discussed. That gives the Ronaldo mentions strong provenance and an event connection; it does not make them informal backstage chatter.\\n\\nDefendant says plaintiff needs a bridge. The bridge is the market text plus the terms’ failure to draw the narrow line defendant proposes. A No resolution can stand only if the contract fairly told traders that “during the FIFA World Cup Draw” meant only the separate formal-program transcript. On this record, the more likely reading is broader: public, official remarks at the venue, immediately tied to and immediately preceding the World Cup Draw program, were within the event-linked period unless clearly excluded.\\n\\nSo DX-2 narrows one factual issue but does not decide the case. It shows no formal-stage Ronaldo mention. It does not show that the market excluded the official pre-program event remarks where Trump did say Ronaldo. Under the preponderance standard, the Yes resolution remains the fair one.\\n\\nSurrebuttals:\\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff’s rebuttal usefully narrows the dispute. Plaintiff accepts that the formal Roll Call/Factba.se drawing transcript contains no “Ronaldo” or “Messi.” So the case remains entirely about whether a separate reporter exchange titled “Prior to the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw” should be treated as inside the market period.\\n\\nPlaintiff says “prior to” is only sequence, not legal boundary. But sequence is exactly what the market phrase makes material. The contract asks what Trump would say “during the FIFA World Cup Draw.” A source-agency title identifying the Ronaldo transcript as an exchange with reporters prior to that Draw is not a stray label; it is the best record description of when and what that source is. Plaintiff cannot convert that source into the event itself by saying the market failed to list every excluded pre-event setting.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s formal-preamble point also does not carry the burden. Yes, the formal transcript begins before the mechanical ball selection, and Infantino says at 00:00:50 that “we are now going to do the draw.” But that supports the defense distinction. A host’s preamble inside the formal drawing transcript is part of the program. A separate press exchange, separately titled and sourced as prior to the Draw, is not made part of the program simply because it happened nearby and discussed the same event.\\n\\nNor does official publication settle the issue. PX-5 strengthens provenance: Trump did say Ronaldo in an official public transcript. But provenance answers whether the words were said, not whether they were said during the market’s specified event. The terms require both: the word by the entity, and the word during the time period. Plaintiff has the first element. The second is still missing.\\n\\nThe remaining bridge plaintiff proposes is essentially: public, official, event-linked, and not expressly excluded. That is not enough under a preponderance standard when the same record supplies a cleaner boundary: the Ronaldo source is prior to the Draw, and the formal Draw source omits the strike. The challenged No resolution should stand.\\n\\nClosings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the record has narrowed to one real issue.\\n\\nThe word is proven. The market page identifies the strike as “Ronaldo” and the challenged resolution as No. The case-packet transcript and the GovInfo/OFR excerpt prove that Trump said “Ronaldo” as a standalone word in public remarks at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center, in a World Cup Draw setting, with FIFA President Infantino present, and amid repeated discussion of the Draw, the Kennedy Center, ticket sales, the audience, and the imminent event. That is strong provenance: GovInfo, NARA/OFR, DCPD202501162, matching the packet source and note.\\n\\nDefendant has also proved its best fact. The Roll Call/Factba.se formal-program extraction does not contain “Ronaldo” or “Messi.” Plaintiff does not ask you to find otherwise. If the market had said “only the formal drawing transcript,” defendant would win. But that is not the market traders saw.\\n\\nThe market asked: “What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?” It did not say “during the formal transcript only,” “after the host announces the draw has begun,” “excluding public press remarks at the venue,” or “excluding remarks immediately before the program.” The governing terms do not add that limitation. They define words used by the entity during the time period, allow event/context time periods, and exclude categories such as rehearsals, sound checks, behind-the-scenes content, and unofficial recordings. Plaintiff’s source is none of those. It is an official public presidential transcript of event-linked remarks at the venue.\\n\\nDefendant’s formal extraction shows why a bright line cannot simply be assumed. Even on that page, before balls are drawn, there is ceremony, introduction, and Infantino saying “we are now going to do the draw.” Event boundaries are not self-defining. The question is whether Kalshi clearly chose defendant’s narrower boundary. The record contains no such choice.\\n\\nSo the burden is met. More likely than not, a reasonable reading of the market and terms includes Trump’s official, public, venue-based remarks immediately tied to the World Cup Draw. The strongest contrary evidence proves only that a narrower formal transcript omits the strike. It does not prove the contract excluded the remarks where the strike was actually said.\\n\\nThe challenged No resolution should be overturned. The strike “Ronaldo” should resolve Yes.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff’s closing concedes the decisive factual split: the formal World Cup Drawing transcript contains no “Ronaldo” or “Messi.” The only Ronaldo evidence is the separate official transcript titled “Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw.”\\n\\nThat is enough to decide the case. The market did not ask what Trump would say at the Kennedy Center, on World Cup Draw day, in public presidential remarks, or in event-linked press availability. It asked what Trump would say “during the FIFA World Cup Draw.” The terms require the word to be used by the entity during the specified time period. Plaintiff has proven the word and the speaker. It has not proven the time period.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s strongest point is that the market did not expressly say “formal transcript only” or “exclude pre-program remarks.” But plaintiff has the burden. A challenged No resolution does not become Yes merely because the contract could have been even more verbose. The record must make it more likely than not that the pre-event reporter exchange was inside the market period. The record does the opposite.\\n\\nThe source labels matter. PX-2 and PX-5 are official and probative, but they are official proof of remarks prior to the Draw. The formal Roll Call/Factba.se extraction is the source for Trump’s formal attendance at the FIFA World Cup Drawing; it begins the program, includes the draw presentation, and omits the strike. Plaintiff’s theory asks you to treat a separate prior reporter exchange as “during” the Draw even though the formal Draw source exists and does not contain the word.\\n\\nThe terms do not collapse that distinction. They recognize event/context time periods and official presentation content, but they still require the word to occur during the chosen time period. Official publication proves provenance. Event connection proves relevance. Neither proves inclusion. A public official transcript can be accurately preserved and still be outside the market window if it is, as titled, prior to the event.\\n\\nSo the fair synthesis is narrow and grounded: Trump said Ronaldo in event-linked public remarks before the FIFA World Cup Draw; Trump did not say Ronaldo in the formal drawing transcript preserved in this record; and no admitted market term or source-chain evidence bridges the pre-event exchange into the market’s “during the FIFA World Cup Draw” period.\\n\\nUnder the preponderance standard, plaintiff has not carried the proposition. The challenged No resolution should stand.\\n\\nExhibits:\\n[plaintiff] PX-1 Market page and challenged resolution\\nMarket URL: https://kalshi.com/markets/kxtrumpmentionb/trump-mention-b/kxtrumpmentionb-25dec06\\n\\nPublic market title: What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\n\\nContract family: PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION\\n\\nStrike at issue: Ronaldo\\n\\nChallenged resolution: No\\n\\nRequested resolution: Yes\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-2 Pre-event reporter exchange transcript\\nRemarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\nDecember 05, 2025\\n\\n[The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\\nThe President. It's a great honor to be here. Gianni has done a fantastic job. We're setting records—[inaudible].\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. Well, I think so. They have a little bit of a shot. Pretty stiff competition. But I would say they would have a small chance.\\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize\\nQ. [Inaudible]—win the FIFA Peace Award?\\nThe President. Well, it would be an honor.\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\nQ. Will you root for some selection? Will you root for someone?\\nThe President. Well, I root for a lot of countries, but in this case, I'll be rooting for the U.S.A. [Laughter]\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. That's great. That's great. We really love it.\\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize\\nQ. Mr. President, have you been told that you are going to receive the inaugural peace prize today——\\nThe President. I have not——\\nQ. ——from FIFA?\\nThe President. I have not been told. There's a rumor about it, but I have not been told. That would be a great honor, and I'm a big fan of Gianni, as you know.\\nQ. What can fans expect——\\nQ. Are you hoping to receive that?\\nThe President. Excuse me.\\nQ. Are you hoping to receive the peace prize?\\nThe President. Well, I don't like to say \\\"hope,\\\" but it would be a great honor.\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. What can fans expect of, like, the World Cup in the U.S.?\\nThe President. I think it's going to be fantastic. We've set every record you can set.\\nQ. What are you telling people who are worried——\\nFédération Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) President Giovanni V. Infantino\\nQ. [Inaudible]—friend Gianni—[inaudible]—a word about him?\\nThe President. I think he has done a fantastic job.\\nThe President's Schedule\\nQ. Are you going to be meeting with the President of Mexico today and the——\\nThe President. We might. Yes.\\nQ. ——Prime Minister of Canada as well?\\nThe President. I might. I might do that.\\nQ. Will you be discussing immigration and trade with them?\\nThe President. Yes, we'll be discussing.\\n[At this point, the President and Mr. Infantino posed for photographs.]\\nThe President. Thank you, everybody.\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event/John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts\\nQ. Mr. President, what do you think about the crowd?\\nThe President. Oh, look, the new star—[inaudible].\\nCongratulations.\\nQ. Thank you.\\nThe President. You're the new star of television and Fox.\\nQ. Thank you. How are you doing, Mr. President?\\nThe President. I'm doing very well.\\nQ. What do you think about the crowd here?\\nThe President. I think the crowd is great, and I think the building is great. We've made a lot of improvements over the last 6 months. Taking—the Kennedy Center was in very bad shape. Now it's getting to be really good. And in 6 months, it's going to be incredible with the improvements we've made.\\nQ. The first time for the U.S. to host since the nineties.\\nThe President. Right.\\nQ. Are you ready for it?\\nThe President. I'm ready for it, and they're ready for it. And Gianni, who you know——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——has done a fantastic job with FIFA. And we're looking to have—you know, we're set—we have already set records for tickets sales. I don't think there's ever been anything like it in any sport. And so, I want to congratulate you.\\nMr. Infantino. Thank you.\\nThe President. I don't even have to wait. But major records have been set.\\nHow are you?\\nQ. Good, how are you, sir?\\nThe President. Nice to see you.\\nQ. Today it's not football—American football. It's soccer. It's——\\nThe President. Right.\\nQ. ——the big event of soccer.\\nThe President. That's right. That's right.\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\nQ. So can you tell me about this big day today?\\nThe President. It's just a big day, and it's a great sport. And it really is coming to America. And never—nobody ever thought a thing like this could happen. And I'm very happy to say that we've already set the alltime record on ticket sales long before the first ball is kicked. Right?\\nMr. Infantino. A hundred percent. One hundred percent.\\n2026 World Cup Host Cities\\nQ. You've had some concerns about crime in American cities, some of the cities that will be hosting. Have they remedied that for you? Are you still considering maybe asking FIFA to move some of those cities?\\nThe President. No, I don't want to do that. But I will tell you, if they do have a problem, by the time we get there, we'll take care of that problem. We can solve that problem.\\nI've proven that in DC and everywhere else we went, so we'll take care of that very easily. So, if they have a problem, hopefully, they'll let us know that, and we will solve any problem.\\nOkay? Thank you.\\nQ. Thank you so much.\\nMr. Infantino. All right, thank you so much.\\nQ. Thank you, Mr. President.\\nQ. Thank you. Appreciate it.\\nThe President. Congratulations.\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. Mr. President, Brazilian television. America will be hosting the World Cup and the Olympics in 2 years. How important it is—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. I think very. It's a great honor. I think Gianni is doing a phenomenal job. We've set every record on ticket sales. It's been really fantastic. But Gianni has done an unbelievable job with FIFA.\\nThe President's Experience With Soccer\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. He was a great—not only that. I got to see a man name Pelé play—right?—that tells you how old I am—when he was on the Cosmos. Do you remember that a long time ago? And it was quite a treat. That was quite an event. And he was—not only was he playing, he was great. He scored two goals, I think. And so, I was one of the few who got to see Pelé, and I assume he is one of your alltime greats. Right?\\nMr. Infantino. Definitely.\\nThe President. So I got to see him.\\nThe President's Favorite World Cup Competitor\\nQ. Do you have some favorite teams for World Cup?\\nThe President. Well, I have a favorite. It's the U.S.A. [Laughter] I don't know what their chances are, Gianni, but maybe the U.S.A. is the——\\nMr. Infantino. They're getting better and better, actually.\\nThe President. I think they'll do well.\\nMr. Infantino. They are getting better and better.\\nThe President. I think they'll do well.\\nThank you very much, everybody.\\nQ. Thank you so much.\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. Mr. President, World Cup in America just means—[inaudible]. So what do you expect from this World Cup?\\nThe President. [Inaudible]—record business and only in the United States, but we're also doing record ticket sales with FIFA. And they've already bought—beat their highest record. And we—you know, this a long time before the first ball is kicked. You've sold more tickets than they've ever done before, and better pricing than they've ever gotten before. It's a tremendous success. And it's an honor. And Gianni has done a phenomenal job with FIFA.\\nQ. [Inaudible]—ever?\\nThe President. I think so. I think it's going to be—I mean, ideally, you want to see that every year. Every 4 years, it gets bigger and better. I think we have set every record in the book. We're very happy about it.\\nThank you.\\nThe President's Favorite World Cup Competitor\\nQ. [Inaudible]—part of America. Who are you going to support as well?\\nThe President. Well, I think I have to support U.S.A. Otherwise, I'd be in trouble. I wouldn't be President for long.\\nMr. Infantino. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. [Inaudible]—but you have a lot of great teams. You're going to have a lot of great teams.\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\\\"football,\\\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\\n2026 World Cup Draw/Ticket Sales for World Cup\\nQ. How does it feel to be part of this amazing event? And obviously, your being a part of participating in all the—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. The President of Mexico is here, and she's doing a very good job. She's a good woman, very, very excellent job. It's an honor, and we're setting every record, and you're helping us set those records.\\nMr. Infantino. And we will do it.\\nThe President. You know, Mexico and Canada are helping us set those records. But as you know, we have a record in ticket sales already, long before the first ball is kicked, and we're going to do great.\\nI think that Gianni—as you know, he's the head, and he has done a fantastic job.\\nU.S. Cooperation With Mexico and Canada\\nQ. And how is the biggest challenge being three countries?\\nThe President. Well, I think that—do you mean for the three countries?\\nWell, they've gotten together really well, I mean.\\nMr. Infantino. All right.\\nThe President. They're getting along very well.\\nMr. Infantino. Collaboration is fantastic between the three.\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer/2026 World Cup\\nQ. And you like soccer?\\nThe President. I do. I like it. I like it more and more.\\nQ. Yes?\\nThe President. I like it. It's growing in this country—very, really—I mean, someday, maybe it's going to be bigger than anything else.\\nMr. Infantino. We'll have to become number one.\\nThe President. I will say this——\\nMr. Infantino. Definitely.\\nThe President. ——the ticket sales——\\nQ. Definitely will happen.\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. Ticket sales are bigger than anything we have ever done in the history of the country, in terms of sports.\\nMr. Infantino. For certain.\\nQ. And the audience is going to be huge.\\nThe President. The audience is going to be tremendous.\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. Yes.\\nMr. Infantino. Six billion people.\\nThe President. [Inaudible]\\nQ. Six billion? That's amazing.\\nMr. Infantino. Six billion people.\\nAnd today, one billion.\\nQ. Wow.\\nMr. Infantino. [Inaudible]\\nQ. Enjoy show time. Thank you so much.\\nThe President. [Inaudible]\\nQ. Mr. President, how are you? Just a quick—[inaudible].\\nQ. This is for Telemundo.\\nThe President. How are you?\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\nQ. Hello, Mr. President. How are you? This for Telemundo.\\nThe President. How are you? Good.\\nQ. How are you?\\nThe President. Very good. Thank you.\\nQ. How does it feel to have the most important event of sports—that global—in the U.S.?\\nThe President. Well, we do. And right at the Kennedy Center. I'm Chairman of the Kennedy Center. And I hear the Kennedy Center is doing a very good job, so it feels great. Really good.\\nAnd Telemundo is doing a good job, too. Thank you.\\nQ. Thank you.\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. What is the significance of hosting the FIFA World Cup this year?\\nThe President. It's a—in terms of sports, I would say the ultimate. There is no sport like this. It's the biggest sport in the world. And we are setting every record. You know, our ticket sales have gone and set every—every sport—no matter what it is, we've set the record. So—and every though it's very early, there's no ball being kicked yet, but we've already set a ticket sales record.\\nArgentina National Team\\nQ. How do you see Argentinean team for this World Cup?\\nThe President. Well, I love Argentina. And your President is doing a very good job, as you know. Milei. You know that right? It's make Argentina great again. MAGA.\\nQ. And——\\nU.S. National Team\\nQ. Do you think the States are building a powerful team for next year?\\nThe President. Who?\\nQ. The States.\\nThe President. Oh, yes. Sure. I—you're going to have a lot of powerful teams. Everybody has a lot of powerful teams, but you're going to have a lot of great teams. [Inaudible]\\nU.S. Role in Hosting the 2026 World Cup\\nQ. Mr. President, what does it mean for you guys to host the World Cup right here in the U.S.?\\nThe President. I'm honored to host it. It's a great honor. I mean, it's turned out to be bigger than we thought. We're setting a record for ticket sales, the likes of which no sport has ever seen before.\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\\nThe President. But they have a little more speed.\\nBut no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\\nPopularity of Soccer in Latin America\\nQ. Mr. President, a message for the Latin America and soccer fans?\\nThe President. Yes, I am. And Latin America is great. And they have great soccer. So, good luck in the matches.\\n[A reporter asked a question in Spanish, which was translated by an interpreter as follows.]\\nU.S. Visas for World Cup Ticketholders\\nQ. Who is going to be in—[inaudible]—about these visas for the—these fans that want to come here to the World Cup?\\nThe President. Well, we're going to make it very easy for them. We're working on that right now. We're going to make it very easy. It's going to be a very easy process.\\nQ. Okay. Say, hi to Colombia over there.\\nThe President. Hello. Is that Colombia?\\nQ. Yes.\\nThe President. I love Colombia. Hello, Colombia. [Laughter]\\nQ. Okay. Okay. Muy bien.\\nThe President. So where are you from?\\nQ. Paraguay.\\nThe President. Oh.\\nQ. He's from Paraguay. Yes.\\nThe President. Very good. I love it. I—it's a beautiful country. We get along very well with them. We do a little trade deal with them, and they like us. And that's what's happening.\\nQ. Panama.\\nThe President. Where?\\nVery good. I like the canal. [Laughter] That canal is pretty good.\\n[A reporter spoke in Spanish; no translation was provided.]\\n2026 World Cup\\nThe President. What?\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. Well, it's going to be incredible. The event is going to be very good. Just this event alone—it's at the Kennedy Center. I see you have it fixed up perfectly.\\nMr. Infantino. It will set the tone.\\nThe President. Right? It's beautiful.\\nMr. Infantino. It's beautiful.\\nThe President. It's a beautiful place.\\nHave a good time.\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President.\\n[A reporter spoke in Spanish; no translation was provided.]\\nMr. Infantino. No, gracias. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. It's great.\\nJohn F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts/Renovation Work\\nQ. Mr. President, the U.S. press?\\nThe President. Thank you, everybody, very much. It's a great honor. This has been an honor for a lot of reasons. Number one, they've sold more tickets than any event has ever sold already—long before the kickoff.\\nAnd number two, we've done a lot of work at the Kennedy Center. It was falling apart, and now it's pretty much back. And we'll get it back within the next 4 or 5 months through construction, and—but you see the way it looks.\\nAnd Gianni is just telling me—who's done an incredible job, by the way. He's just telling, you know, how good a job we've done.\\nMr. Infantino. That's right.\\nThe President. You can look at the walls. The marble was broken. Everything was a mess. And we've really taken the Kennedy Center—a lot of people thought it was going to be ripped down, and we did just the opposite. So we've done a really great renovation job on it. And over the next 3, 4 months, it will be complete. And we're honored to have it here, and it's been—it's been very special.\\nWe've set a record on ticket sales, as you probably heard, already, even way before—long before the event itself. And we're working with Canada, and we're working with Mexico. And it's been a really spectacular—so far, it's been spectacular.\\nDaniel [Daniel Baldwin, One America News Network], do you have a question?\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. What are your expectations? You once said that the FIFA World Cup is an opportunity to put—a once-in-a-lifetime opportunity to put the greatness of the United States on display.\\nThe President. Well, I think—\\nQ. One billion eyeballs will be watching, Mr. President.\\nThe President. Yes, I—think——\\nQ. What will they here today?\\nThe President. Even today, I understand. I hear that, you know——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——I know we're a little late to get in there, but——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——that's okay.\\nMr. Infantino. They wait.\\nThe President. So all my friends, I guess they have to wait. They have no choice, right? [Laughter]\\nMr. Infantino. Yes, they wait.\\nThe President. But no, the numbers are incredible. I hear today's numbers are——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——very big. I hope CNN is covering this.\\nQ. One billion eyeballs.\\nMr. Infantino. Today, 1 billion eyeballs.\\nThe President. Today's numbers are very, very big.\\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize/The President's Foreign Policy\\nQ. We are covering it. And you're expected to get the FIFA Peace Prize, Mr. President. What would you say to people who say that prize might conflict with your pledge to strike Venezuela?\\nThe President. Well, I think the peace prize—I mean, I settled eight wars. I don't know that I'm getting it. I haven't been officially noticed. I've been hearing about a peace prize, and I'm here to represent our country in a different sense. But I can tell you, I did settle eight wars, and we have a ninth coming, but—which nobody has ever done before.\\nBut I want to really save lives. I don't need prizes. I need to save lives. And we're saving a lot of lives. And I've saved millions and millions of lives, and that's really what I want to do.\\nAnd I also want to run a great country. And the United States right now is the hottest country anywhere in the world. And 1 year ago, it was dead. We had a dead country, and now we have the hottest country anywhere in the world.\\nQ. Mr. President, will you——\\nThe President's Meeting With President Claudia Sheinbaum Pardo of Mexico and Prime Minister Mark Carney of Canada\\nQ. What are you going to discuss with Canada and Mexico, Mr.—what are you going to discuss with the leaders of Canada and Mexico?\\nThe President. Well, we're getting—we're going to meet with both. And we're getting along very well. You know, we're getting along very well. I don't know. I think we have a meeting set up for some time after the event.\\nQ. Will you discuss trade?\\nThe President. Yes, we'll discuss trade. We—get along very well.\\nThank you, everybody, very much.\\nQ. Will you pardon any other Honduran officials?\\nQ. Do you want them to keep trying to indict Ms. James?\\n\\nNOTE: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. In his remarks, he referred to Trey Yingst, chief foreign correspondent, Fox News Channel; Cristiano Ronaldo, forward for Saudi Pro League club Al-Nass and Portugal's national soccer team; and Lionel Messi, forward for Major League Soccer club Inter Miami and Argentina's national team. A reporter referred to New York State Attorney General Letitia James. The transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\n\\nSource URL: https://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/documents/remarks-exchange-with-reporters-prior-the-2026-federation-internationale-des-associations\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-3 PRESMENTION/NEWMENTION terms\\n                                         NEWMENTION\\n\\nScope: These rules shall apply to this contract.\\n\\nUnderlying: The Underlying for this Contract is words used by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nRevisions to the Underlying made after Expiration will not be accounted for in determining the\\nExpiration Value.\\n\\nSource Agency: The Source Agencies are \\u003csource\\u003e.\\n\\nType: The type of Contract is an Event Contract.\\n\\nIssuance: After the initial Contract, Contract iterations will be listed on an as-needed basis at\\nthe discretion of the Exchange and corresponding to the risk management needs of Members.\\n\\n\\u003centity\\u003e: \\u003centity\\u003e refers to the speaker, writer, performer, or communicator specified by the\\nExchange. This may include (but is not limited to): a specific named individual, multiple\\nindividuals specified using AND/OR logic, an individual identified by position or title, a group,\\nband, team or collective entity, a specified member or members of a group, an organization,\\ncompany, or institutional entity, or any combination of the aforementioned.\\n\\nWhen \\u003centity\\u003e is defined by a position or title, the Contract tracks whoever holds that position\\nduring \\u003ctime period\\u003e, even if the individual holding the position changes. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a\\nspecific named individual, the identity remains consistent throughout. Name changes (e.g.,\\nstage names, married names) do not create a new entity. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a group or\\norganization and the Contract does not specify particular members, any official\\ncommunication or statement by any member or designated spokesperson counts. When using\\nAND logic, all specified entities must independently say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e. When\\nusing OR logic, at least one of the specified entities must say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nThe Exchange may specify additional conditions such as “at least X members of” a group or\\n“the majority of” a group.\\n\\n\\u003csource\\u003e: \\u003csource\\u003e refers to a Source Agency or ordered collection of Source Agencies\\nspecified by the Exchange at the time of Contract listing, which will be incorporated into the\\nSource Agency hierarchy above and used to determine the occurrence of the Underlying.\\n\\u003csource\\u003e may refer to a singular agency, multiple agencies, an agency by distinguishing\\ncharacteristics, by category or type (e.g., “official government statistical body,” “primary wire\\nservice”), or any combination thereof. When multiple agencies are specified, they may be\\napplied in the hierarchical order designated by the Exchange if so specified, with the highest-\\nranked available and responsive agency taking precedence for purposes of determining the\\nExpiration Value. A lower-ranked agency shall only be consulted if all higher-ranked agencies\\nare unavailable, unresponsive, have not reported on the Underlying by the Expiration time, or\\nif the Exchange, in its sole discretion, determines that a higher-ranked agency’s reporting is\\nincomplete, erroneous, or otherwise insufficient to determine the Expiration Value. If \\u003csource\\u003e\\ndesignates multiple agencies without specifying a hierarchical order, the Exchange shall\\nresolve any conflict between reporting agencies at its sole discretion.\\n\\n\\u003cword\\u003e: \\u003cword\\u003e refers to the particular word or phrase potentially to be mentioned by\\n\\u003centity\\u003e. It may refer to a word being said a minimum number of times. It may also refer to\\none of multiple words/phrases, any of which are acceptable (e.g., “Doge/Dogecoin”).\\n\\f\\u003ctime period\\u003e: \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific range of time, event or discrete date and\\ntime specified by the Exchange. This may be defined by, but is not limited to: a specific event\\nor context (e.g., “during the State of the Union address”), exact dates or times, relative time\\nmarkers (e.g., “before July 1, 2027,” “in Q1 2026”), event-based periods (e.g., “during any\\ncampaign rally in October 2026,” “during the awards ceremony”), and broader intervals (e.g.,\\n“Q1–Q2 2027,” “January–March 2026”).\\n\\nUnless stated otherwise, “Between” is inclusive of both endpoints, while “before” and “after”\\nexclude the specified date. \\u003ctime period\\u003e may also refer to “Any” or “None”, to multiple dates\\n(even if non-consecutive), or to a singular and discrete date or time.\\n\\nWhen \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event (such as an address, speech, performance, or\\nbroadcast), the Exchange may specify what is included, including whether it includes both live\\nand pre-recorded segments (including whether advertisements are included). Where a\\ntimezone is not specified, ET is assumed.\\n\\n\\nPayout Criterion: The Payout Criterion for the Contract encompasses the Expiration Values that\\n\\u003cword\\u003e is said by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n\\n\\nThe word must appear as a distinct, standalone unit, not buried inside another word. Plural\\nand possessive noun forms count. Other grammatical changes (tense, conjugation, derivation)\\ndo not. If \\u003cword\\u003e appears separated from other words by a space or hyphen or in a\\ncompound form with a space or hyphen, it counts. If \\u003cword\\u003e is fused into a single\\nunhyphenated word, it does not count.\\n\\nIf \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled, and the market contains a\\nstrike stating “Event does not qualify/occur”, such a strike shall resolve “Yes” and all others\\n“No”. If \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled but such strikes are NOT\\nlisted, the Contracts will resolve to the last fair price determined at the discretion of the\\nExchange. If the event is postponed, and such a postponement is announced by the end of the\\nfollowing calendar day to be rescheduled to a time within 14 calendar days, the markets shall\\nremain open. If the event captured in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast, the\\nExchange may keep the market open for 24 hours for the release of an official recording.\\nFurther granular details on conditions for these Contracts is available below.\\n\\nAdditional clarification(s):\\n\\n     Possessive noun forms of \\u003cword\\u003e, plurals, and possessive plural noun forms are\\n     INCLUDED:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigrants” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Egg” → “eggs’ shells” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Russia” → “Russia’s” counts, “Russian” does not\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e exists only in adjective form, no plural form exists:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Economic” → “Economics” does not count (“Economic” is an adjective\\n          for which “Economics” is not a plural)\\n     Plural nouns occurring within proper nouns and noun phrases are included:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Cat” → “Cats the musical” counts\\n\\f    Grammatical variations beyond plurals/possessives are NOT included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigration” does NOT count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Run” → “Running” or “Ran” do NOT count\\n    When \\u003cword\\u003e specifies a plural form, the singular does NOT count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Veterans” → “Veteran” does NOT count\\n    Words that are spelled the same as the plural form of \\u003cword\\u003e (if such exists) but are\\n    themselves not a plural noun are included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Wind” → “Winds up the clock” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Border” → “The United States has strong borders” counts\\n    Open compounds (words separated by spaces) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fire station” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “couch” → “couch potato” counts\\n    Hyphenated compounds (words connected by hyphens) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Palestine” → “pro-Palestine” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fat” → “non-fat” counts\\n    Closed compounds (single word, no spaces/hyphens) do not count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire” does not count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firefighter” does not count\\n    Multi-word \\u003cword\\u003e in larger constructions: When \\u003cword\\u003e is a multi-word phrase\\n    appearing within a hyphenated construction, it counts only if \\u003cword\\u003e appears as a\\n    complete, unmodified element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “New York” → “New York-based” counts (complete element)\\n    Portmanteaus (words blended from two words where parts of each are combined) are\\n    NOT included unless the portmanteau clearly contains \\u003cword\\u003e as a distinct, unaltered\\n    element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “MAGA” → “MAGA-nificent” counts (MAGA appears as distinct element)\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “magnificent” → “MAGA-nificent” does NOT count (portmanteau blend)\\n\\nDictionary determination: Both the Merriam-Webster Dictionary (available online) AND the\\nOxford English Dictionary shall be used to determine compound type and/or conventional\\nspelling patterns. Inclusion in either dictionary as an open or hyphenated compound shall\\nsatisfy the Payout Criterion. If neither provides clarity (or the word is not included),\\ndetermination is based on whether written as single unit (closed/doesn’t count) vs. spaces or\\nhyphens (open or hyphenated/counts) and/or context and previous usage.\\n\\nPHONETIC EQUIVALENCIES\\n\\n    Homophones (same sound, different spelling) do not count:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “write” → “right” does not count\\n    Homonyms and homographs (same spelling) COUNT regardless of meaning or\\n    pronunciation:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “bass” → both “bass guitar” and “bass fishing” count\\n    Proper and common nouns are treated identically:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Apple” → both “Apple Inc.” and “apple” (fruit) count\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Will” → both “Will Smith” and “I will go” count\\n    Minor unintentional mispronunciations COUNT if context makes intent clear:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Mamdani” → “Mandani” counts\\n    Severe mispronunciations that make \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable do NOT count.\\n    Trademarked spellings do not count, even when pronounced identically, unless the word\\n\\fitself is the same:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “lift” → “Lyft” (pronounced “lift”) does not count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “uber” → “Uber” counts\\nWords with non-standard transliteration to English count within reason, provided they are\\nphonetically equivalent:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Zelensky” → any of “Zelenski,” “Zelenskii,” “Zelensky,” or “Zelenskiy”\\n      count if pronounced equivalently\\nContractions do not count for their constituent words unless otherwise explicitly specified\\nby the Exchange:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “not” → “won’t,” “can’t,” “don’t,” “isn’t” do not count\\nNumbers spoken as words COUNT, when spoken exactly (not part of a larger number):\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “five” → saying “five” or reading “$5” aloud as “five dollars” counts,\\n      saying “five hundred” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “410” → “four hundred ten”, “four one zero” or “four ten” counts\\nOrdinals COUNT when \\u003cword\\u003e is written numerically OR a phrase that includes a\\nnumber:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “January 6” → “January 6th” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “3” (written numerically) → “3rd” (spoken as “third”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Eight War” → “8 Wars” and “Eighth War” will count\\nCardinal and ordinal number words are distinct:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “one” → “first” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “first” → “one” does NOT count\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count when pronunciation or letter-by-letter spelling\\nmatches \\u003cword\\u003e:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “NASA” (pronounced “NAH-suh”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “N-A-S-A” (spelled out) counts\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count as \\u003cword\\u003e when pronounced as the full word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Doctor” → “Dr.” (pronounced “Doctor”) counts\\nExpanded forms of acronyms do NOT count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “AI” → “artificial intelligence” does not count\\nWords in foreign languages do NOT count unless they are perfect cognates with an\\nEnglish word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fuego” (Spanish) does NOT count\\nEnglish words within foreign sentences count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “policy” → “Nuestra policy es clara” counts\\n\\u003cword\\u003e in organization/company names counts:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Securities” → “Bank of America Securities” counts\\nWords in URLs, emails, handles, and hashtags (exclusive of domain structure, email\\nprovider or symbols) are treated as compounds when spoken as complete words, with the\\ntype of compound subject to aforementioned rules:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firestation.com” pronounced “fire station dot com” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire.com” pronounced “wildfire dot com” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “apple” → “apple.com” pronounced “apple dot com” does count\\n      When presented in URL, email, handle, or hashtag form, \\u003cword\\u003e shall be treated as\\n      a compound, not a multi-word word\\nSung, rapped, or poetic words COUNT if phonetically recognizable:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “money” → “moneyyy” (extended in rap) counts\\n      Extreme distortion making \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable does NOT count.\\nPhonetic alphabet spelling (“Foxtrot India Romeo Echo” for “FIRE”) does NOT count.\\n\\fCANCELLATIONS AND DELAYS\\n\\n   The Exchange may list an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike for any Contract. If listed,\\n   such a strike refers to the structural conditions of the market, and is NOT adjudicated as a\\n   \\u003cword\\u003e needing to be said by or validated by having been said by \\u003centity\\u003e. If listed, this\\n   strike resolves to “Yes” whenever the event fails to occur or qualify under the Payout\\n   Criterion, or any other circumstance prevents normal resolution.\\n   If no such strike is listed, and \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, the following rules\\n   apply if the event is cancelled, postponed, rescheduled, or materially altered (including\\n   being closed to press) such that no video is released within one calendar day of the\\n   original start time of the event:\\n         If the event is cancelled, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price determined in\\n         the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         If the event is postponed or rescheduled, the outcome depends on whether a new\\n         date is publicly announced within one calendar day (i.e. if the event was scheduled\\n         to begin on Monday, any time up to 11:59PM on Tuesday falls within this period) of\\n         the originally scheduled start time:\\n               If no new date is announced within one calendar day, the Contract will resolve\\n               to the last fair price determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n               If a new date is announced within one calendar day, the outcome depends on\\n               when the rescheduled event is set to occur:\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls within fourteen (14) calendar days of the\\n                     originally scheduled date, the Contract shall remain open and \\u003cword\\u003e\\n                     stated during the rescheduled event will count.\\n                           The fourteen-day window begins at 12:00 AM ET on the originally\\n                           scheduled date and ends at 11:59 PM ET fourteen days later, unless\\n                           an alternate timezone is explicitly specified.\\n                           Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the State of the Union on January\\n                           15, 2026” rescheduled to January 20, 2026 → words spoken during\\n                           the rescheduled address count.\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls more than fourteen (14) calendar days after\\n                     the originally scheduled date, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price\\n                     determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         Any Contract that cannot be resolved through the Source Agency hierarchy will\\n         instead be settled at the Last Fair Price. The Exchange will disclose the methodology\\n         used to determine the Last Fair Price (e.g., Last Traded Price, Time-Weighted\\n         Average Price) at the time of Issuance.\\n         If an event begins but is interrupted, abbreviated, or ends prematurely, words\\n         stated by \\u003centity\\u003e during the portion of the event that did occur will count and the\\n         market will otherwise resolve.\\n   If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window but the venue, format, or medium\\n   changes (e.g., moved to a different location, changed from in-person to virtual (with the\\n   exception of being closed to press)), words stated during the event will count.\\n   Special condition: Across both cases, whether an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike is\\n   listed or not, if the event specified as or in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast (or\\n   relayed as such) but the live stream/broadcast does not occur, the Exchange will instead\\n   use an officially released recording as the Underlying, and may delay resolution by up to\\n   one calendar day to allow for the release of such a recording.\\n\\f          If partial snippets are released, Contracts on words that do not appear will be\\n          resolved to last fair price, and Contracts on those that do will be resolved to “Yes”.\\n          If no recording is released, the relevant outcomes triggered by the\\n          presence/absence of an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike shall occur as outlined\\n          above.\\n\\nTECHNICAL DETAILS (UNLESS OTHERWISE SPECIFIED)\\n\\n     When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, pre-recorded content broadcast,\\n     streamed, or published as part of that event is included if presented as part of the official\\n     presentation.\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the concert” with pre-recorded video interlude\\n          where entity speaks → words from interlude count\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the television appearance” with pre-taped\\n          segment aired during broadcast → words from segment count\\n     Behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are NOT\\n     included unless officially broadcast or published as part of \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n     Subtitles and captions that display \\u003cword\\u003e on screen but are not spoken aloud by\\n     \\u003centity\\u003e do NOT count.\\n     Sign language interpretation or usage by entity does NOT count as saying \\u003cword\\u003e unless\\n     the Contract explicitly specifies that sign language counts.\\n     Text that entity displays on screen (presentation slides, teleprompter visible to audience,\\n     signatures) does NOT count unless entity reads it aloud.\\n     Content generated by AI, deepfakes, or synthetic voice technology impersonating entity\\n     does NOT count unless the synthetic content is officially commissioned, authorized, or\\n     published by entity, OR the Contract explicitly specifies that AI-generated content counts.\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e is muted due to technical failure or censorship it shall not count unless\\n     corroborating contextual evidence (including surrounding speech, or an official\\n     uncensored recording or transcript) confirms that \\u003centity\\u003e specifically uttered \\u003cword\\u003e\\n     during the muted period.\\n\\nMinimum Tick: The Minimum Tick size for the Contract shall be $0.01.\\n\\nPosition Accountability Level: The Position Accountability Level for the Contract shall be\\n$25,000 per strike, per Member.\\n\\nLast Trading Date: The Last Trading Date of the Contract will be the Expiration Date. The Last\\nTrading Time will be the Expiration time.\\n\\nSettlement Date: The Settlement Date of the Contract shall be no later than the day after the\\nExpiration Date, unless the Market Outcome is under review pursuant to Rule 7.1.\\n\\nExpiration Date: When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event: The latest Expiration Date of\\nthe Contract shall be fourteen (14) calendar days after the originally scheduled date of the\\nevent. If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window, expiration will be moved to an\\nearlier date and time in accordance with Rule 7.2. When \\u003ctime period\\u003e is defined by specific\\ndates: The latest Expiration Date of the Contract shall be two weeks after the end of \\u003ctime\\nperiod\\u003e. If an event described in the Payout Criterion occurs and a consensus has been\\nreached on all terms, then expiration will be moved to an earlier date and time in accordance\\nwith Rule 7.2.\\n\\fExpiration time: The Expiration time of the Contract shall be 10:00 AM ET.\\n\\nSettlement Value: The Settlement Value for this Contract is $1.00.\\n\\nExpiration Value: The Expiration Value is the value of the Underlying as documented by the\\nSource Agency on the Expiration Date at the Expiration time.\\n\\nContingencies: Before Settlement, Kalshi may, at its sole discretion, initiate the Market\\nOutcome Review Process pursuant to Rule 7.1 of the Rulebook. If an Expiration Value cannot\\nbe determined on the Expiration Date, Kalshi has the right to determine payouts pursuant to\\nRule 7.1 in the Rulebook.\\n\\f\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-4 Formal draw archive note\\nSource checked: Roll Call / Factba.se archive\\n\\nArchive title: Remarks: Donald Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing in Washington - December 5, 2025\\n\\nArchive URL: https://rollcall.com/factbase/trump/transcript/donald-trump-remarks-fifa-world-cup-drawing-december-5-2025/\\n\\nWhat this file establishes:\\n\\nThere is a separate archived transcript page for Trump's formal attendance remarks at the draw.\\n\\nWhat this file does not establish:\\n\\nThis session could not retrieve the full transcript text from that archive.  The page is password-protected.  This example therefore does not claim, from local files alone, whether the formal program transcript does or does not contain the word \\\"Ronaldo.\\\"\\n\\nWhy this matters:\\n\\nThe complaint does not need to prove that the formal program omitted the strike.  It needs to show that Trump said \\\"Ronaldo\\\" in event-linked remarks and that the market boundary reasonably includes those remarks.  The formal archive remains relevant because it marks the distinction between the pre-event reporter exchange and the formal program.\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-5 GovInfo official transcript excerpt and metadata\\nSource: GovInfo, DCPD202501162, Office of the Federal Register / National Archives and Records Administration.\\nURL: https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/DCPD-202501162/html/DCPD-202501162.htm\\nTitle: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\nEvent date: December 5, 2025.\\n\\nRelevant extracted page text:\\n\\\"Administration of Donald J. Trump, 2025\\\"\\n\\\"Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw December 5, 2025\\\"\\n\\\"[The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\\\"\\n\\nUnder the section \\\"The President's Interest in Soccer\\\":\\n\\\"Q. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\\\"\\n\\\"The President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\\\\\\\"football,\\\\\\\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\\\"\\n\\\"Thank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\\\"\\n\\nAdditional relevant extracted page text:\\n\\\"The President's Interest in Soccer\\\"\\n\\\"Q. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\\\"\\n\\\"The President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\\\"\\n\\\"Mr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\\\"\\n\\\"The President. But they have a little more speed. But no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\\\"\\n\\nGovInfo note:\\n\\\"NOTE: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. In his remarks, he referred to Trey Yingst, chief foreign correspondent, Fox News Channel; Cristiano Ronaldo, forward for Saudi Pro League club Al-Nass and Portugal's national soccer team; and Lionel Messi, forward for Major League Soccer club Inter Miami and Argentina's national team. A reporter referred to New York State Attorney General Letitia James. The transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\\"\\n\\nGovInfo content details page also identifies category \\\"Interviews With the News Media : Exchanges with reporters, Washington, DC,\\\" subjects including \\\"Federation Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) World Cup,\\\" \\\"John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts,\\\" and \\\"Soccer,\\\" and names including \\\"Ronaldo, Cristiano\\\" and \\\"Messi, Lionel.\\\"\\n\\n[defendant] DX-1 Market wording and challenged resolution\\nMarket URL: https://kalshi.com/markets/kxtrumpmentionb/trump-mention-b/kxtrumpmentionb-25dec06\\n\\nPublic market title: What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\n\\nContract family: PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION\\n\\nStrike at issue: Ronaldo\\n\\nChallenged resolution: No\\n\\nRequested resolution: Yes\\n\\n\\n[defendant] DX-2 Pre-event reporter exchange transcript\\nRemarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\nDecember 05, 2025\\n\\n[The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\\nThe President. It's a great honor to be here. Gianni has done a fantastic job. We're setting records—[inaudible].\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. Well, I think so. They have a little bit of a shot. Pretty stiff competition. But I would say they would have a small chance.\\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize\\nQ. [Inaudible]—win the FIFA Peace Award?\\nThe President. Well, it would be an honor.\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\nQ. Will you root for some selection? Will you root for someone?\\nThe President. Well, I root for a lot of countries, but in this case, I'll be rooting for the U.S.A. [Laughter]\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. That's great. That's great. We really love it.\\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize\\nQ. Mr. President, have you been told that you are going to receive the inaugural peace prize today——\\nThe President. I have not——\\nQ. ——from FIFA?\\nThe President. I have not been told. There's a rumor about it, but I have not been told. That would be a great honor, and I'm a big fan of Gianni, as you know.\\nQ. What can fans expect——\\nQ. Are you hoping to receive that?\\nThe President. Excuse me.\\nQ. Are you hoping to receive the peace prize?\\nThe President. Well, I don't like to say \\\"hope,\\\" but it would be a great honor.\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. What can fans expect of, like, the World Cup in the U.S.?\\nThe President. I think it's going to be fantastic. We've set every record you can set.\\nQ. What are you telling people who are worried——\\nFédération Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) President Giovanni V. Infantino\\nQ. [Inaudible]—friend Gianni—[inaudible]—a word about him?\\nThe President. I think he has done a fantastic job.\\nThe President's Schedule\\nQ. Are you going to be meeting with the President of Mexico today and the——\\nThe President. We might. Yes.\\nQ. ——Prime Minister of Canada as well?\\nThe President. I might. I might do that.\\nQ. Will you be discussing immigration and trade with them?\\nThe President. Yes, we'll be discussing.\\n[At this point, the President and Mr. Infantino posed for photographs.]\\nThe President. Thank you, everybody.\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event/John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts\\nQ. Mr. President, what do you think about the crowd?\\nThe President. Oh, look, the new star—[inaudible].\\nCongratulations.\\nQ. Thank you.\\nThe President. You're the new star of television and Fox.\\nQ. Thank you. How are you doing, Mr. President?\\nThe President. I'm doing very well.\\nQ. What do you think about the crowd here?\\nThe President. I think the crowd is great, and I think the building is great. We've made a lot of improvements over the last 6 months. Taking—the Kennedy Center was in very bad shape. Now it's getting to be really good. And in 6 months, it's going to be incredible with the improvements we've made.\\nQ. The first time for the U.S. to host since the nineties.\\nThe President. Right.\\nQ. Are you ready for it?\\nThe President. I'm ready for it, and they're ready for it. And Gianni, who you know——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——has done a fantastic job with FIFA. And we're looking to have—you know, we're set—we have already set records for tickets sales. I don't think there's ever been anything like it in any sport. And so, I want to congratulate you.\\nMr. Infantino. Thank you.\\nThe President. I don't even have to wait. But major records have been set.\\nHow are you?\\nQ. Good, how are you, sir?\\nThe President. Nice to see you.\\nQ. Today it's not football—American football. It's soccer. It's——\\nThe President. Right.\\nQ. ——the big event of soccer.\\nThe President. That's right. That's right.\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\nQ. So can you tell me about this big day today?\\nThe President. It's just a big day, and it's a great sport. And it really is coming to America. And never—nobody ever thought a thing like this could happen. And I'm very happy to say that we've already set the alltime record on ticket sales long before the first ball is kicked. Right?\\nMr. Infantino. A hundred percent. One hundred percent.\\n2026 World Cup Host Cities\\nQ. You've had some concerns about crime in American cities, some of the cities that will be hosting. Have they remedied that for you? Are you still considering maybe asking FIFA to move some of those cities?\\nThe President. No, I don't want to do that. But I will tell you, if they do have a problem, by the time we get there, we'll take care of that problem. We can solve that problem.\\nI've proven that in DC and everywhere else we went, so we'll take care of that very easily. So, if they have a problem, hopefully, they'll let us know that, and we will solve any problem.\\nOkay? Thank you.\\nQ. Thank you so much.\\nMr. Infantino. All right, thank you so much.\\nQ. Thank you, Mr. President.\\nQ. Thank you. Appreciate it.\\nThe President. Congratulations.\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. Mr. President, Brazilian television. America will be hosting the World Cup and the Olympics in 2 years. How important it is—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. I think very. It's a great honor. I think Gianni is doing a phenomenal job. We've set every record on ticket sales. It's been really fantastic. But Gianni has done an unbelievable job with FIFA.\\nThe President's Experience With Soccer\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. He was a great—not only that. I got to see a man name Pelé play—right?—that tells you how old I am—when he was on the Cosmos. Do you remember that a long time ago? And it was quite a treat. That was quite an event. And he was—not only was he playing, he was great. He scored two goals, I think. And so, I was one of the few who got to see Pelé, and I assume he is one of your alltime greats. Right?\\nMr. Infantino. Definitely.\\nThe President. So I got to see him.\\nThe President's Favorite World Cup Competitor\\nQ. Do you have some favorite teams for World Cup?\\nThe President. Well, I have a favorite. It's the U.S.A. [Laughter] I don't know what their chances are, Gianni, but maybe the U.S.A. is the——\\nMr. Infantino. They're getting better and better, actually.\\nThe President. I think they'll do well.\\nMr. Infantino. They are getting better and better.\\nThe President. I think they'll do well.\\nThank you very much, everybody.\\nQ. Thank you so much.\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. Mr. President, World Cup in America just means—[inaudible]. So what do you expect from this World Cup?\\nThe President. [Inaudible]—record business and only in the United States, but we're also doing record ticket sales with FIFA. And they've already bought—beat their highest record. And we—you know, this a long time before the first ball is kicked. You've sold more tickets than they've ever done before, and better pricing than they've ever gotten before. It's a tremendous success. And it's an honor. And Gianni has done a phenomenal job with FIFA.\\nQ. [Inaudible]—ever?\\nThe President. I think so. I think it's going to be—I mean, ideally, you want to see that every year. Every 4 years, it gets bigger and better. I think we have set every record in the book. We're very happy about it.\\nThank you.\\nThe President's Favorite World Cup Competitor\\nQ. [Inaudible]—part of America. Who are you going to support as well?\\nThe President. Well, I think I have to support U.S.A. Otherwise, I'd be in trouble. I wouldn't be President for long.\\nMr. Infantino. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. [Inaudible]—but you have a lot of great teams. You're going to have a lot of great teams.\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\\\"football,\\\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\\n2026 World Cup Draw/Ticket Sales for World Cup\\nQ. How does it feel to be part of this amazing event? And obviously, your being a part of participating in all the—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. The President of Mexico is here, and she's doing a very good job. She's a good woman, very, very excellent job. It's an honor, and we're setting every record, and you're helping us set those records.\\nMr. Infantino. And we will do it.\\nThe President. You know, Mexico and Canada are helping us set those records. But as you know, we have a record in ticket sales already, long before the first ball is kicked, and we're going to do great.\\nI think that Gianni—as you know, he's the head, and he has done a fantastic job.\\nU.S. Cooperation With Mexico and Canada\\nQ. And how is the biggest challenge being three countries?\\nThe President. Well, I think that—do you mean for the three countries?\\nWell, they've gotten together really well, I mean.\\nMr. Infantino. All right.\\nThe President. They're getting along very well.\\nMr. Infantino. Collaboration is fantastic between the three.\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer/2026 World Cup\\nQ. And you like soccer?\\nThe President. I do. I like it. I like it more and more.\\nQ. Yes?\\nThe President. I like it. It's growing in this country—very, really—I mean, someday, maybe it's going to be bigger than anything else.\\nMr. Infantino. We'll have to become number one.\\nThe President. I will say this——\\nMr. Infantino. Definitely.\\nThe President. ——the ticket sales——\\nQ. Definitely will happen.\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. Ticket sales are bigger than anything we have ever done in the history of the country, in terms of sports.\\nMr. Infantino. For certain.\\nQ. And the audience is going to be huge.\\nThe President. The audience is going to be tremendous.\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. Yes.\\nMr. Infantino. Six billion people.\\nThe President. [Inaudible]\\nQ. Six billion? That's amazing.\\nMr. Infantino. Six billion people.\\nAnd today, one billion.\\nQ. Wow.\\nMr. Infantino. [Inaudible]\\nQ. Enjoy show time. Thank you so much.\\nThe President. [Inaudible]\\nQ. Mr. President, how are you? Just a quick—[inaudible].\\nQ. This is for Telemundo.\\nThe President. How are you?\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\nQ. Hello, Mr. President. How are you? This for Telemundo.\\nThe President. How are you? Good.\\nQ. How are you?\\nThe President. Very good. Thank you.\\nQ. How does it feel to have the most important event of sports—that global—in the U.S.?\\nThe President. Well, we do. And right at the Kennedy Center. I'm Chairman of the Kennedy Center. And I hear the Kennedy Center is doing a very good job, so it feels great. Really good.\\nAnd Telemundo is doing a good job, too. Thank you.\\nQ. Thank you.\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. What is the significance of hosting the FIFA World Cup this year?\\nThe President. It's a—in terms of sports, I would say the ultimate. There is no sport like this. It's the biggest sport in the world. And we are setting every record. You know, our ticket sales have gone and set every—every sport—no matter what it is, we've set the record. So—and every though it's very early, there's no ball being kicked yet, but we've already set a ticket sales record.\\nArgentina National Team\\nQ. How do you see Argentinean team for this World Cup?\\nThe President. Well, I love Argentina. And your President is doing a very good job, as you know. Milei. You know that right? It's make Argentina great again. MAGA.\\nQ. And——\\nU.S. National Team\\nQ. Do you think the States are building a powerful team for next year?\\nThe President. Who?\\nQ. The States.\\nThe President. Oh, yes. Sure. I—you're going to have a lot of powerful teams. Everybody has a lot of powerful teams, but you're going to have a lot of great teams. [Inaudible]\\nU.S. Role in Hosting the 2026 World Cup\\nQ. Mr. President, what does it mean for you guys to host the World Cup right here in the U.S.?\\nThe President. I'm honored to host it. It's a great honor. I mean, it's turned out to be bigger than we thought. We're setting a record for ticket sales, the likes of which no sport has ever seen before.\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\\nThe President. But they have a little more speed.\\nBut no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\\nPopularity of Soccer in Latin America\\nQ. Mr. President, a message for the Latin America and soccer fans?\\nThe President. Yes, I am. And Latin America is great. And they have great soccer. So, good luck in the matches.\\n[A reporter asked a question in Spanish, which was translated by an interpreter as follows.]\\nU.S. Visas for World Cup Ticketholders\\nQ. Who is going to be in—[inaudible]—about these visas for the—these fans that want to come here to the World Cup?\\nThe President. Well, we're going to make it very easy for them. We're working on that right now. We're going to make it very easy. It's going to be a very easy process.\\nQ. Okay. Say, hi to Colombia over there.\\nThe President. Hello. Is that Colombia?\\nQ. Yes.\\nThe President. I love Colombia. Hello, Colombia. [Laughter]\\nQ. Okay. Okay. Muy bien.\\nThe President. So where are you from?\\nQ. Paraguay.\\nThe President. Oh.\\nQ. He's from Paraguay. Yes.\\nThe President. Very good. I love it. I—it's a beautiful country. We get along very well with them. We do a little trade deal with them, and they like us. And that's what's happening.\\nQ. Panama.\\nThe President. Where?\\nVery good. I like the canal. [Laughter] That canal is pretty good.\\n[A reporter spoke in Spanish; no translation was provided.]\\n2026 World Cup\\nThe President. What?\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. Well, it's going to be incredible. The event is going to be very good. Just this event alone—it's at the Kennedy Center. I see you have it fixed up perfectly.\\nMr. Infantino. It will set the tone.\\nThe President. Right? It's beautiful.\\nMr. Infantino. It's beautiful.\\nThe President. It's a beautiful place.\\nHave a good time.\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President.\\n[A reporter spoke in Spanish; no translation was provided.]\\nMr. Infantino. No, gracias. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. It's great.\\nJohn F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts/Renovation Work\\nQ. Mr. President, the U.S. press?\\nThe President. Thank you, everybody, very much. It's a great honor. This has been an honor for a lot of reasons. Number one, they've sold more tickets than any event has ever sold already—long before the kickoff.\\nAnd number two, we've done a lot of work at the Kennedy Center. It was falling apart, and now it's pretty much back. And we'll get it back within the next 4 or 5 months through construction, and—but you see the way it looks.\\nAnd Gianni is just telling me—who's done an incredible job, by the way. He's just telling, you know, how good a job we've done.\\nMr. Infantino. That's right.\\nThe President. You can look at the walls. The marble was broken. Everything was a mess. And we've really taken the Kennedy Center—a lot of people thought it was going to be ripped down, and we did just the opposite. So we've done a really great renovation job on it. And over the next 3, 4 months, it will be complete. And we're honored to have it here, and it's been—it's been very special.\\nWe've set a record on ticket sales, as you probably heard, already, even way before—long before the event itself. And we're working with Canada, and we're working with Mexico. And it's been a really spectacular—so far, it's been spectacular.\\nDaniel [Daniel Baldwin, One America News Network], do you have a question?\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. What are your expectations? You once said that the FIFA World Cup is an opportunity to put—a once-in-a-lifetime opportunity to put the greatness of the United States on display.\\nThe President. Well, I think—\\nQ. One billion eyeballs will be watching, Mr. President.\\nThe President. Yes, I—think——\\nQ. What will they here today?\\nThe President. Even today, I understand. I hear that, you know——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——I know we're a little late to get in there, but——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——that's okay.\\nMr. Infantino. They wait.\\nThe President. So all my friends, I guess they have to wait. They have no choice, right? [Laughter]\\nMr. Infantino. Yes, they wait.\\nThe President. But no, the numbers are incredible. I hear today's numbers are——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——very big. I hope CNN is covering this.\\nQ. One billion eyeballs.\\nMr. Infantino. Today, 1 billion eyeballs.\\nThe President. Today's numbers are very, very big.\\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize/The President's Foreign Policy\\nQ. We are covering it. And you're expected to get the FIFA Peace Prize, Mr. President. What would you say to people who say that prize might conflict with your pledge to strike Venezuela?\\nThe President. Well, I think the peace prize—I mean, I settled eight wars. I don't know that I'm getting it. I haven't been officially noticed. I've been hearing about a peace prize, and I'm here to represent our country in a different sense. But I can tell you, I did settle eight wars, and we have a ninth coming, but—which nobody has ever done before.\\nBut I want to really save lives. I don't need prizes. I need to save lives. And we're saving a lot of lives. And I've saved millions and millions of lives, and that's really what I want to do.\\nAnd I also want to run a great country. And the United States right now is the hottest country anywhere in the world. And 1 year ago, it was dead. We had a dead country, and now we have the hottest country anywhere in the world.\\nQ. Mr. President, will you——\\nThe President's Meeting With President Claudia Sheinbaum Pardo of Mexico and Prime Minister Mark Carney of Canada\\nQ. What are you going to discuss with Canada and Mexico, Mr.—what are you going to discuss with the leaders of Canada and Mexico?\\nThe President. Well, we're getting—we're going to meet with both. And we're getting along very well. You know, we're getting along very well. I don't know. I think we have a meeting set up for some time after the event.\\nQ. Will you discuss trade?\\nThe President. Yes, we'll discuss trade. We—get along very well.\\nThank you, everybody, very much.\\nQ. Will you pardon any other Honduran officials?\\nQ. Do you want them to keep trying to indict Ms. James?\\n\\nNOTE: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. In his remarks, he referred to Trey Yingst, chief foreign correspondent, Fox News Channel; Cristiano Ronaldo, forward for Saudi Pro League club Al-Nass and Portugal's national soccer team; and Lionel Messi, forward for Major League Soccer club Inter Miami and Argentina's national team. A reporter referred to New York State Attorney General Letitia James. The transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\n\\nSource URL: https://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/documents/remarks-exchange-with-reporters-prior-the-2026-federation-internationale-des-associations\\n\\n\\n[defendant] DX-3 GovInfo/OFR pre-event transcript excerpt\\nSource: GovInfo, DCPD202501162, Office of the Federal Register / National Archives and Records Administration.\\nURL: https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/DCPD-202501162/html/DCPD-202501162.htm\\nTitle: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\nEvent date: December 5, 2025.\\n\\nRelevant extracted page text:\\n\\\"Administration of Donald J. Trump, 2025\\\"\\n\\\"Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw December 5, 2025\\\"\\n\\\"[The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\\\"\\n\\nUnder the section \\\"The President's Interest in Soccer\\\":\\n\\\"Q. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\\\"\\n\\\"The President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\\\\\\\"football,\\\\\\\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\\\"\\n\\\"Thank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\\\"\\n\\nAdditional relevant extracted page text:\\n\\\"The President's Interest in Soccer\\\"\\n\\\"Q. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\\\"\\n\\\"The President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\\\"\\n\\\"Mr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\\\"\\n\\\"The President. But they have a little more speed. But no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\\\"\\n\\nGovInfo note:\\n\\\"NOTE: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. In his remarks, he referred to Trey Yingst, chief foreign correspondent, Fox News Channel; Cristiano Ronaldo, forward for Saudi Pro League club Al-Nass and Portugal's national soccer team; and Lionel Messi, forward for Major League Soccer club Inter Miami and Argentina's national team. A reporter referred to New York State Attorney General Letitia James. The transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\\"\\n\\nGovInfo content details page also identifies category \\\"Interviews With the News Media : Exchanges with reporters, Washington, DC,\\\" subjects including \\\"Federation Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) World Cup,\\\" \\\"John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts,\\\" and \\\"Soccer,\\\" and names including \\\"Ronaldo, Cristiano\\\" and \\\"Messi, Lionel.\\\"\\n\\n[defendant] DX-4 PRESMENTION/NEWMENTION terms\\n                                         NEWMENTION\\n\\nScope: These rules shall apply to this contract.\\n\\nUnderlying: The Underlying for this Contract is words used by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nRevisions to the Underlying made after Expiration will not be accounted for in determining the\\nExpiration Value.\\n\\nSource Agency: The Source Agencies are \\u003csource\\u003e.\\n\\nType: The type of Contract is an Event Contract.\\n\\nIssuance: After the initial Contract, Contract iterations will be listed on an as-needed basis at\\nthe discretion of the Exchange and corresponding to the risk management needs of Members.\\n\\n\\u003centity\\u003e: \\u003centity\\u003e refers to the speaker, writer, performer, or communicator specified by the\\nExchange. This may include (but is not limited to): a specific named individual, multiple\\nindividuals specified using AND/OR logic, an individual identified by position or title, a group,\\nband, team or collective entity, a specified member or members of a group, an organization,\\ncompany, or institutional entity, or any combination of the aforementioned.\\n\\nWhen \\u003centity\\u003e is defined by a position or title, the Contract tracks whoever holds that position\\nduring \\u003ctime period\\u003e, even if the individual holding the position changes. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a\\nspecific named individual, the identity remains consistent throughout. Name changes (e.g.,\\nstage names, married names) do not create a new entity. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a group or\\norganization and the Contract does not specify particular members, any official\\ncommunication or statement by any member or designated spokesperson counts. When using\\nAND logic, all specified entities must independently say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e. When\\nusing OR logic, at least one of the specified entities must say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nThe Exchange may specify additional conditions such as “at least X members of” a group or\\n“the majority of” a group.\\n\\n\\u003csource\\u003e: \\u003csource\\u003e refers to a Source Agency or ordered collection of Source Agencies\\nspecified by the Exchange at the time of Contract listing, which will be incorporated into the\\nSource Agency hierarchy above and used to determine the occurrence of the Underlying.\\n\\u003csource\\u003e may refer to a singular agency, multiple agencies, an agency by distinguishing\\ncharacteristics, by category or type (e.g., “official government statistical body,” “primary wire\\nservice”), or any combination thereof. When multiple agencies are specified, they may be\\napplied in the hierarchical order designated by the Exchange if so specified, with the highest-\\nranked available and responsive agency taking precedence for purposes of determining the\\nExpiration Value. A lower-ranked agency shall only be consulted if all higher-ranked agencies\\nare unavailable, unresponsive, have not reported on the Underlying by the Expiration time, or\\nif the Exchange, in its sole discretion, determines that a higher-ranked agency’s reporting is\\nincomplete, erroneous, or otherwise insufficient to determine the Expiration Value. If \\u003csource\\u003e\\ndesignates multiple agencies without specifying a hierarchical order, the Exchange shall\\nresolve any conflict between reporting agencies at its sole discretion.\\n\\n\\u003cword\\u003e: \\u003cword\\u003e refers to the particular word or phrase potentially to be mentioned by\\n\\u003centity\\u003e. It may refer to a word being said a minimum number of times. It may also refer to\\none of multiple words/phrases, any of which are acceptable (e.g., “Doge/Dogecoin”).\\n\\f\\u003ctime period\\u003e: \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific range of time, event or discrete date and\\ntime specified by the Exchange. This may be defined by, but is not limited to: a specific event\\nor context (e.g., “during the State of the Union address”), exact dates or times, relative time\\nmarkers (e.g., “before July 1, 2027,” “in Q1 2026”), event-based periods (e.g., “during any\\ncampaign rally in October 2026,” “during the awards ceremony”), and broader intervals (e.g.,\\n“Q1–Q2 2027,” “January–March 2026”).\\n\\nUnless stated otherwise, “Between” is inclusive of both endpoints, while “before” and “after”\\nexclude the specified date. \\u003ctime period\\u003e may also refer to “Any” or “None”, to multiple dates\\n(even if non-consecutive), or to a singular and discrete date or time.\\n\\nWhen \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event (such as an address, speech, performance, or\\nbroadcast), the Exchange may specify what is included, including whether it includes both live\\nand pre-recorded segments (including whether advertisements are included). Where a\\ntimezone is not specified, ET is assumed.\\n\\n\\nPayout Criterion: The Payout Criterion for the Contract encompasses the Expiration Values that\\n\\u003cword\\u003e is said by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n\\n\\nThe word must appear as a distinct, standalone unit, not buried inside another word. Plural\\nand possessive noun forms count. Other grammatical changes (tense, conjugation, derivation)\\ndo not. If \\u003cword\\u003e appears separated from other words by a space or hyphen or in a\\ncompound form with a space or hyphen, it counts. If \\u003cword\\u003e is fused into a single\\nunhyphenated word, it does not count.\\n\\nIf \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled, and the market contains a\\nstrike stating “Event does not qualify/occur”, such a strike shall resolve “Yes” and all others\\n“No”. If \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled but such strikes are NOT\\nlisted, the Contracts will resolve to the last fair price determined at the discretion of the\\nExchange. If the event is postponed, and such a postponement is announced by the end of the\\nfollowing calendar day to be rescheduled to a time within 14 calendar days, the markets shall\\nremain open. If the event captured in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast, the\\nExchange may keep the market open for 24 hours for the release of an official recording.\\nFurther granular details on conditions for these Contracts is available below.\\n\\nAdditional clarification(s):\\n\\n     Possessive noun forms of \\u003cword\\u003e, plurals, and possessive plural noun forms are\\n     INCLUDED:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigrants” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Egg” → “eggs’ shells” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Russia” → “Russia’s” counts, “Russian” does not\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e exists only in adjective form, no plural form exists:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Economic” → “Economics” does not count (“Economic” is an adjective\\n          for which “Economics” is not a plural)\\n     Plural nouns occurring within proper nouns and noun phrases are included:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Cat” → “Cats the musical” counts\\n\\f    Grammatical variations beyond plurals/possessives are NOT included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigration” does NOT count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Run” → “Running” or “Ran” do NOT count\\n    When \\u003cword\\u003e specifies a plural form, the singular does NOT count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Veterans” → “Veteran” does NOT count\\n    Words that are spelled the same as the plural form of \\u003cword\\u003e (if such exists) but are\\n    themselves not a plural noun are included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Wind” → “Winds up the clock” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Border” → “The United States has strong borders” counts\\n    Open compounds (words separated by spaces) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fire station” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “couch” → “couch potato” counts\\n    Hyphenated compounds (words connected by hyphens) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Palestine” → “pro-Palestine” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fat” → “non-fat” counts\\n    Closed compounds (single word, no spaces/hyphens) do not count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire” does not count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firefighter” does not count\\n    Multi-word \\u003cword\\u003e in larger constructions: When \\u003cword\\u003e is a multi-word phrase\\n    appearing within a hyphenated construction, it counts only if \\u003cword\\u003e appears as a\\n    complete, unmodified element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “New York” → “New York-based” counts (complete element)\\n    Portmanteaus (words blended from two words where parts of each are combined) are\\n    NOT included unless the portmanteau clearly contains \\u003cword\\u003e as a distinct, unaltered\\n    element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “MAGA” → “MAGA-nificent” counts (MAGA appears as distinct element)\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “magnificent” → “MAGA-nificent” does NOT count (portmanteau blend)\\n\\nDictionary determination: Both the Merriam-Webster Dictionary (available online) AND the\\nOxford English Dictionary shall be used to determine compound type and/or conventional\\nspelling patterns. Inclusion in either dictionary as an open or hyphenated compound shall\\nsatisfy the Payout Criterion. If neither provides clarity (or the word is not included),\\ndetermination is based on whether written as single unit (closed/doesn’t count) vs. spaces or\\nhyphens (open or hyphenated/counts) and/or context and previous usage.\\n\\nPHONETIC EQUIVALENCIES\\n\\n    Homophones (same sound, different spelling) do not count:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “write” → “right” does not count\\n    Homonyms and homographs (same spelling) COUNT regardless of meaning or\\n    pronunciation:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “bass” → both “bass guitar” and “bass fishing” count\\n    Proper and common nouns are treated identically:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Apple” → both “Apple Inc.” and “apple” (fruit) count\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Will” → both “Will Smith” and “I will go” count\\n    Minor unintentional mispronunciations COUNT if context makes intent clear:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Mamdani” → “Mandani” counts\\n    Severe mispronunciations that make \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable do NOT count.\\n    Trademarked spellings do not count, even when pronounced identically, unless the word\\n\\fitself is the same:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “lift” → “Lyft” (pronounced “lift”) does not count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “uber” → “Uber” counts\\nWords with non-standard transliteration to English count within reason, provided they are\\nphonetically equivalent:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Zelensky” → any of “Zelenski,” “Zelenskii,” “Zelensky,” or “Zelenskiy”\\n      count if pronounced equivalently\\nContractions do not count for their constituent words unless otherwise explicitly specified\\nby the Exchange:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “not” → “won’t,” “can’t,” “don’t,” “isn’t” do not count\\nNumbers spoken as words COUNT, when spoken exactly (not part of a larger number):\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “five” → saying “five” or reading “$5” aloud as “five dollars” counts,\\n      saying “five hundred” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “410” → “four hundred ten”, “four one zero” or “four ten” counts\\nOrdinals COUNT when \\u003cword\\u003e is written numerically OR a phrase that includes a\\nnumber:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “January 6” → “January 6th” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “3” (written numerically) → “3rd” (spoken as “third”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Eight War” → “8 Wars” and “Eighth War” will count\\nCardinal and ordinal number words are distinct:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “one” → “first” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “first” → “one” does NOT count\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count when pronunciation or letter-by-letter spelling\\nmatches \\u003cword\\u003e:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “NASA” (pronounced “NAH-suh”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “N-A-S-A” (spelled out) counts\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count as \\u003cword\\u003e when pronounced as the full word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Doctor” → “Dr.” (pronounced “Doctor”) counts\\nExpanded forms of acronyms do NOT count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “AI” → “artificial intelligence” does not count\\nWords in foreign languages do NOT count unless they are perfect cognates with an\\nEnglish word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fuego” (Spanish) does NOT count\\nEnglish words within foreign sentences count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “policy” → “Nuestra policy es clara” counts\\n\\u003cword\\u003e in organization/company names counts:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Securities” → “Bank of America Securities” counts\\nWords in URLs, emails, handles, and hashtags (exclusive of domain structure, email\\nprovider or symbols) are treated as compounds when spoken as complete words, with the\\ntype of compound subject to aforementioned rules:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firestation.com” pronounced “fire station dot com” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire.com” pronounced “wildfire dot com” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “apple” → “apple.com” pronounced “apple dot com” does count\\n      When presented in URL, email, handle, or hashtag form, \\u003cword\\u003e shall be treated as\\n      a compound, not a multi-word word\\nSung, rapped, or poetic words COUNT if phonetically recognizable:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “money” → “moneyyy” (extended in rap) counts\\n      Extreme distortion making \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable does NOT count.\\nPhonetic alphabet spelling (“Foxtrot India Romeo Echo” for “FIRE”) does NOT count.\\n\\fCANCELLATIONS AND DELAYS\\n\\n   The Exchange may list an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike for any Contract. If listed,\\n   such a strike refers to the structural conditions of the market, and is NOT adjudicated as a\\n   \\u003cword\\u003e needing to be said by or validated by having been said by \\u003centity\\u003e. If listed, this\\n   strike resolves to “Yes” whenever the event fails to occur or qualify under the Payout\\n   Criterion, or any other circumstance prevents normal resolution.\\n   If no such strike is listed, and \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, the following rules\\n   apply if the event is cancelled, postponed, rescheduled, or materially altered (including\\n   being closed to press) such that no video is released within one calendar day of the\\n   original start time of the event:\\n         If the event is cancelled, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price determined in\\n         the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         If the event is postponed or rescheduled, the outcome depends on whether a new\\n         date is publicly announced within one calendar day (i.e. if the event was scheduled\\n         to begin on Monday, any time up to 11:59PM on Tuesday falls within this period) of\\n         the originally scheduled start time:\\n               If no new date is announced within one calendar day, the Contract will resolve\\n               to the last fair price determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n               If a new date is announced within one calendar day, the outcome depends on\\n               when the rescheduled event is set to occur:\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls within fourteen (14) calendar days of the\\n                     originally scheduled date, the Contract shall remain open and \\u003cword\\u003e\\n                     stated during the rescheduled event will count.\\n                           The fourteen-day window begins at 12:00 AM ET on the originally\\n                           scheduled date and ends at 11:59 PM ET fourteen days later, unless\\n                           an alternate timezone is explicitly specified.\\n                           Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the State of the Union on January\\n                           15, 2026” rescheduled to January 20, 2026 → words spoken during\\n                           the rescheduled address count.\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls more than fourteen (14) calendar days after\\n                     the originally scheduled date, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price\\n                     determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         Any Contract that cannot be resolved through the Source Agency hierarchy will\\n         instead be settled at the Last Fair Price. The Exchange will disclose the methodology\\n         used to determine the Last Fair Price (e.g., Last Traded Price, Time-Weighted\\n         Average Price) at the time of Issuance.\\n         If an event begins but is interrupted, abbreviated, or ends prematurely, words\\n         stated by \\u003centity\\u003e during the portion of the event that did occur will count and the\\n         market will otherwise resolve.\\n   If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window but the venue, format, or medium\\n   changes (e.g., moved to a different location, changed from in-person to virtual (with the\\n   exception of being closed to press)), words stated during the event will count.\\n   Special condition: Across both cases, whether an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike is\\n   listed or not, if the event specified as or in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast (or\\n   relayed as such) but the live stream/broadcast does not occur, the Exchange will instead\\n   use an officially released recording as the Underlying, and may delay resolution by up to\\n   one calendar day to allow for the release of such a recording.\\n\\f          If partial snippets are released, Contracts on words that do not appear will be\\n          resolved to last fair price, and Contracts on those that do will be resolved to “Yes”.\\n          If no recording is released, the relevant outcomes triggered by the\\n          presence/absence of an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike shall occur as outlined\\n          above.\\n\\nTECHNICAL DETAILS (UNLESS OTHERWISE SPECIFIED)\\n\\n     When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, pre-recorded content broadcast,\\n     streamed, or published as part of that event is included if presented as part of the official\\n     presentation.\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the concert” with pre-recorded video interlude\\n          where entity speaks → words from interlude count\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the television appearance” with pre-taped\\n          segment aired during broadcast → words from segment count\\n     Behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are NOT\\n     included unless officially broadcast or published as part of \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n     Subtitles and captions that display \\u003cword\\u003e on screen but are not spoken aloud by\\n     \\u003centity\\u003e do NOT count.\\n     Sign language interpretation or usage by entity does NOT count as saying \\u003cword\\u003e unless\\n     the Contract explicitly specifies that sign language counts.\\n     Text that entity displays on screen (presentation slides, teleprompter visible to audience,\\n     signatures) does NOT count unless entity reads it aloud.\\n     Content generated by AI, deepfakes, or synthetic voice technology impersonating entity\\n     does NOT count unless the synthetic content is officially commissioned, authorized, or\\n     published by entity, OR the Contract explicitly specifies that AI-generated content counts.\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e is muted due to technical failure or censorship it shall not count unless\\n     corroborating contextual evidence (including surrounding speech, or an official\\n     uncensored recording or transcript) confirms that \\u003centity\\u003e specifically uttered \\u003cword\\u003e\\n     during the muted period.\\n\\nMinimum Tick: The Minimum Tick size for the Contract shall be $0.01.\\n\\nPosition Accountability Level: The Position Accountability Level for the Contract shall be\\n$25,000 per strike, per Member.\\n\\nLast Trading Date: The Last Trading Date of the Contract will be the Expiration Date. The Last\\nTrading Time will be the Expiration time.\\n\\nSettlement Date: The Settlement Date of the Contract shall be no later than the day after the\\nExpiration Date, unless the Market Outcome is under review pursuant to Rule 7.1.\\n\\nExpiration Date: When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event: The latest Expiration Date of\\nthe Contract shall be fourteen (14) calendar days after the originally scheduled date of the\\nevent. If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window, expiration will be moved to an\\nearlier date and time in accordance with Rule 7.2. When \\u003ctime period\\u003e is defined by specific\\ndates: The latest Expiration Date of the Contract shall be two weeks after the end of \\u003ctime\\nperiod\\u003e. If an event described in the Payout Criterion occurs and a consensus has been\\nreached on all terms, then expiration will be moved to an earlier date and time in accordance\\nwith Rule 7.2.\\n\\fExpiration time: The Expiration time of the Contract shall be 10:00 AM ET.\\n\\nSettlement Value: The Settlement Value for this Contract is $1.00.\\n\\nExpiration Value: The Expiration Value is the value of the Underlying as documented by the\\nSource Agency on the Expiration Date at the Expiration time.\\n\\nContingencies: Before Settlement, Kalshi may, at its sole discretion, initiate the Market\\nOutcome Review Process pursuant to Rule 7.1 of the Rulebook. If an Expiration Value cannot\\nbe determined on the Expiration Date, Kalshi has the right to determine payouts pursuant to\\nRule 7.1 in the Rulebook.\\n\\f\\n\\n[defendant] DX-5 Formal draw archive note\\nSource checked: Roll Call / Factba.se archive\\n\\nArchive title: Remarks: Donald Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing in Washington - December 5, 2025\\n\\nArchive URL: https://rollcall.com/factbase/trump/transcript/donald-trump-remarks-fifa-world-cup-drawing-december-5-2025/\\n\\nWhat this file establishes:\\n\\nThere is a separate archived transcript page for Trump's formal attendance remarks at the draw.\\n\\nWhat this file does not establish:\\n\\nThis session could not retrieve the full transcript text from that archive.  The page is password-protected.  This example therefore does not claim, from local files alone, whether the formal program transcript does or does not contain the word \\\"Ronaldo.\\\"\\n\\nWhy this matters:\\n\\nThe complaint does not need to prove that the formal program omitted the strike.  It needs to show that Trump said \\\"Ronaldo\\\" in event-linked remarks and that the market boundary reasonably includes those remarks.  The formal archive remains relevant because it marks the distinction between the pre-event reporter exchange and the formal program.\\n\\n\\n[defendant] DX-6 Formal Roll Call/Factba.se transcript extraction\\nSource: Roll Call / Factba.se\\nURL: https://rollcall.com/factbase/trump/transcript/donald-trump-remarks-fifa-world-cup-drawing-december-5-2025/\\nCaptured page title: Remarks: Donald Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing in Washington - December 5, 2025\\n\\nRendered page metadata excerpt:\\nTopics: Sport; Sport \\u003e Competition Discipline \\u003e Soccer; Lifestyle and Leisure \\u003e Leisure \\u003e Game.\\nEntities listed: bowl; deal; Donald J. Trump; FIFA World Cup; Mark Carney; place; President; trophy; United States; way.\\nSpeakers listed: Gianni Infantino, Donald Trump, Mark Carney, Claudia Sheinbaum.\\nSpeaker statistics excerpt: Donald Trump said 25 sentences of a total of 141 sentences; Donald Trump said 274 words of a total of 1009 words; Donald Trump talked 92 seconds of a total of 484 seconds.\\n\\nFormal transcript excerpt at start of draw:\\nMark Carney, 00:00:00-00:00:02: Thank you, my friend.\\nGianni Infantino, 00:00:50-00:01:22: So this is the World Cup trophy. This is the official bowl for the World Cup and we are now going to do the draw, ladies and gentlemen. But before that, as is customary, there is always a question that the moderator asks the draw assistant. So I would like to start with Mr. Carney. How big a deal is it to co-host the World Cup for Canada?\\n\\nFormal transcript excerpt of Trump's soccer answer:\\nDonald Trump, 00:03:14-00:03:32: Well, for years, Gianni, they've thought soccer or football would be so big, so fast. And I remember, I shouldn't say this because it was a long time ago, but I remember watching Pele play on a team called the Cosmos, Pele, who was fantastic, as you know. I assume one of the greats.\\n\\nText-extraction/search notes:\\nLocal Python urllib retrieval of the page returned HTTP 200 for the source URL and extracted approximately 175,864 characters of page text with Python html.parser. Case-sensitive searches in the extracted page text returned no occurrence of \\\"Ronaldo\\\" and no occurrence of \\\"Messi\\\". The same terms were not found using the browser page find function on the rendered page.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R1 Defendant formal transcript extraction for limited rebuttal use\\nSource: Roll Call / Factba.se\\nURL: https://rollcall.com/factbase/trump/transcript/donald-trump-remarks-fifa-world-cup-drawing-december-5-2025/\\nCaptured page title: Remarks: Donald Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing in Washington - December 5, 2025\\n\\nRendered page metadata excerpt:\\nTopics: Sport; Sport \\u003e Competition Discipline \\u003e Soccer; Lifestyle and Leisure \\u003e Leisure \\u003e Game.\\nEntities listed: bowl; deal; Donald J. Trump; FIFA World Cup; Mark Carney; place; President; trophy; United States; way.\\nSpeakers listed: Gianni Infantino, Donald Trump, Mark Carney, Claudia Sheinbaum.\\nSpeaker statistics excerpt: Donald Trump said 25 sentences of a total of 141 sentences; Donald Trump said 274 words of a total of 1009 words; Donald Trump talked 92 seconds of a total of 484 seconds.\\n\\nFormal transcript excerpt at start of draw:\\nMark Carney, 00:00:00-00:00:02: Thank you, my friend.\\nGianni Infantino, 00:00:50-00:01:22: So this is the World Cup trophy. This is the official bowl for the World Cup and we are now going to do the draw, ladies and gentlemen. But before that, as is customary, there is always a question that the moderator asks the draw assistant. So I would like to start with Mr. Carney. How big a deal is it to co-host the World Cup for Canada?\\n\\nFormal transcript excerpt of Trump's soccer answer:\\nDonald Trump, 00:03:14-00:03:32: Well, for years, Gianni, they've thought soccer or football would be so big, so fast. And I remember, I shouldn't say this because it was a long time ago, but I remember watching Pele play on a team called the Cosmos, Pele, who was fantastic, as you know. I assume one of the greats.\\n\\nText-extraction/search notes:\\nLocal Python urllib retrieval of the page returned HTTP 200 for the source URL and extracted approximately 175,864 characters of page text with Python html.parser. Case-sensitive searches in the extracted page text returned no occurrence of \\\"Ronaldo\\\" and no occurrence of \\\"Messi\\\". The same terms were not found using the browser page find function on the rendered page.\\n\\nSubmitted evidence:\\n[plaintiff arguments] GovInfo DCPD202501162 transcript excerpt and metadata (ev_3fc783920414_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-3fc783920414)\\nSource: https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/DCPD-202501162/html/DCPD-202501162.htm\\nSHA-256: `3fc783920414399098d86210070dd9fe83c14fe1dbded1a56a554f8f4b3448f2`\\nBytes: 2641\\nRelevance: Official government transcript source corroborating that Trump spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center before the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw and said the strike word Ronaldo in World-Cup-related remarks.\\n\\n[defendant arguments] Roll Call/Factba.se formal FIFA World Cup Drawing transcript extraction (ev_fbb53e87ccb3_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-fbb53e87ccb3)\\nSource: https://rollcall.com/factbase/trump/transcript/donald-trump-remarks-fifa-world-cup-drawing-december-5-2025/\\nSHA-256: `fbb53e87ccb3f4381fc2bdc06ac2f2a1ea3848aadde56122b22d34dfbdf4533b`\\nBytes: 2032\\nRelevance: Formal drawing-program transcript evidence showing a separate formal Draw source from the pre-event reporter exchange; the extracted page text contains no occurrence of Ronaldo or Messi, supporting defendant's event-boundary argument.\\n\\nTechnical reports:\\n[plaintiff] Plaintiff source and adverse-search ledger\\nChecked the visible case packet and then searched official/source-specific repositories. GovInfo DCPD202501162 was opened and preserved as submitted evidence; it corroborates the packet transcript, source metadata, location, event date, and Ronaldo passages. The Roll Call/Factba.se formal drawing page rendered despite the packet's password-protection note; browser find searches for 'Ronaldo,' 'Cristiano,' and 'Messi' returned no matches. Plaintiff therefore treats the formal-program transcript as an adverse boundary check, not as proof of a formal-stage mention. The remaining dispute is contractual scope: whether the market clearly excluded public event-linked venue remarks immediately before the formal program.\\n\\n[defendant] Defense source-check ledger\\nDefendant searched for the formal Roll Call/Factba.se transcript identified by the case packet, opened the rendered Roll Call page, and fetched it locally with Python urllib. The fetch returned HTTP 200 for the formal FIFA World Cup Drawing transcript page. Text extraction produced approximately 175,864 characters; searches for \\\"Ronaldo\\\" and \\\"Messi\\\" returned no occurrences. The retrieval also captured formal-program excerpts, including Infantino's statement that \\\"we are now going to do the draw\\\" and Trump's formal soccer answer mentioning Pele rather than Ronaldo. The focused extraction was submitted and accepted as ev_fbb53e87ccb3_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-fbb53e87ccb3.\\n\\nCall submit_council_vote with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated.\\nKeep the rationale brief: no more than three sentences.\\n\\nCouncil API instructions:\\nYou are a council member. Decide the proposition from the admitted record.\\nYou may examine admitted evidence through read-only tools when exact bytes, metadata, or exhibit contents matter.\\nDo not search the web, introduce new facts, create new evidence, or upload evidence.\\nWhen ready, call submit_council_vote exactly once with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated and a concise rationale.\\n\",\"state\":\"ready\",\"status\":\"ready\",\"tools\":[{\"description\":\"Return the current visible arbitration record for this council member.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"get_case\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"List visible immutable record evidence.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"list_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Return metadata and read limits for one visible evidence item.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"stat_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Read a bounded byte range from one visible evidence item as base64.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"length\":{\"minimum\":1,\"type\":\"integer\"},\"offset\":{\"minimum\":0,\"type\":\"integer\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\",\"offset\",\"length\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"read_evidence_range\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Submit one council vote for the current deliberation opportunity.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"rationale\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"vote\":{\"enum\":[\"demonstrated\",\"not_demonstrated\"],\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"vote\",\"rationale\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"submit_council_vote\",\"read_only\":false}],\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":false,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-29T19:58:02.156322961Z\",\"deliberation_round\":1,\"member_id\":\"C2\",\"opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C2\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"remaining_ms\":887183,\"role_id\":\"council\",\"turn_number\":10},\"wait\":{\"reason\":\"ready\",\"state_version\":12,\"version\":15}}"}],"details":{"mode":"call","mcpResult":{"content":[{"type":"text","text":"ok: true\nstatus: ready\nstate: ready\nmessage: An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\nafter_version: 15\nafter_opportunity_id: deliberation:1:C2\nmember_id: C2\ncase_id: arb-ex03-20260629192557\nwait_reason: ready\nphase: deliberation\nopportunity_id: deliberation:1:C2\nremaining_ms: 887183\nattempts_remaining: 3\njson: {\"after_opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C2\",\"after_version\":15,\"case_id\":\"arb-ex03-20260629192557\",\"limits\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"max_evidence_read_bytes\":65536,\"max_evidence_read_bytes_per_opportunity\":524288,\"max_evidence_reads_per_opportunity\":32,\"max_response_bytes\":131072,\"remaining_evidence_read_bytes_for_opportunity\":524288,\"remaining_evidence_reads_for_opportunity\":32},\"member_id\":\"C2\",\"message\":\"An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\",\"ok\":true,\"prompt\":\"Role: council member\\nMember ID: C2\\nDeliberation round: 1\\nProposition: For the Kalshi market \\\"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\\", the strike \\\"Ronaldo\\\" should resolve Yes because Trump said \\\"Ronaldo\\\" in public remarks at the World Cup Draw venue immediately before the formal program, and the market wording plus the governing mention-market terms did not clearly exclude those event-linked remarks.\\nStandard of evidence: Preponderance of the evidence.\\nPersona:\\nYou are a careful juror and council member.\\n\\nEvaluate the record faithfully. Decide only from the evidence, the stated rules, and the applicable burden of proof. Do not favor either side, fill gaps with speculation, or ignore uncertainty.\\n\\nGive weight to reliable sources, direct evidence, consistent reasoning, and clear admissions. Discount unsupported claims, rhetorical force, irrelevant facts, and conclusions that exceed the record.\\n\\nWhen the evidence supports one answer, state it plainly. When the evidence is incomplete or balanced, say so. Be concise, honest, and exact.\\n\\nRecord:\\nOpenings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, this case is not mainly about whether the syllables were spoken. The case-packet transcript says they were. The real dispute is the market boundary: when Kalshi asked what Trump would say \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw,\\\" did that phrase clearly exclude his public, event-linked remarks at the World Cup Draw venue immediately before the formal program? On this record, it did not.\\n\\nThe market page fixes the contract at issue: the public title was \\\"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\\"; the contract family was PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION; the strike was \\\"Ronaldo\\\"; Kalshi challenged the resolution as No; and the requested resolution is Yes. That means the council's task is to apply the mention-market terms to that title and strike, not to import a narrower limitation that the market did not plainly announce.\\n\\nThe reporter-exchange packet is direct evidence on the word and setting. It is titled as remarks in an exchange with reporters prior to the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw, dated December 5, 2025. It places the President at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts, speaking with FIFA President Gianni Infantino and reporters in a sequence repeatedly labeled around the 2026 World Cup and the Draw. In that exchange, in a soccer discussion, Trump says he met Ronaldo, praises him, and uses \\\"Ronaldo\\\" as a distinct standalone word. Under the mention rules, a distinct standalone appearance of the strike is the kind of use that counts if it falls within the time period.\\n\\nThe terms matter because they do not say that an event market is limited only to scripted remarks from a formal stage segment. They define a time period as potentially an event or context, and they give the Exchange power to specify what is included when a time period refers to a specific event. They also distinguish official/public event content from behind-the-scenes, rehearsals, and unofficial recordings. That distinction helps plaintiff: the packet is not a rumor, rehearsal, private soundcheck, or leaked recording. It is a sourced public transcript of remarks at the event venue, immediately tied to the Draw. If Kalshi meant \\\"only the formal televised draw program after doors close\\\" or \\\"only remarks in the separate formal archive,\\\" it needed to say so clearly.\\n\\nI also want to be candid about what the packet does not yet prove. The formal-draw archive note says a separate archived transcript page exists for Trump's formal attendance remarks, but that the session could not retrieve the full text because the page was password-protected. So, at opening, plaintiff is not asking you to infer that the formal program itself contained \\\"Ronaldo.\\\" Nor does plaintiff need that inference. The Yes theory is that the qualifying period reasonably includes the public pre-program reporter exchange that was part of Trump's World Cup Draw appearance. The formal archive is relevant because it marks defendant's likely narrower boundary; it does not resolve the boundary in defendant's favor.\\n\\nProvenance and weight also favor treating the packet seriously at this stage. The market and terms files are system case-packet records. The reporter exchange includes a source URL to a public presidential transcript source and notes a corrected transcript date, while also acknowledging that some audio could not be verified because the audio was incomplete. That caveat may affect inaudible portions, but it does not erase the visible, contextual Ronaldo passage. Later, when evidence admission opens, the parties should preserve the official transcript source, any govinfo or Presidency Project copy, the market page capture, and any accessible formal-program transcript or video. The adverse check should ask whether the formal program omits the word, but omission there would matter only if the council first accepts the defense's artificially narrow reading of \\\"during.\\\"\\n\\nThe plaintiff's burden is preponderance. The record already points to a straightforward path to Yes: Trump, the specified entity, said the specified strike as a standalone word in public remarks linked to and immediately preceding the World Cup Draw at the venue; the market title and governing terms did not clearly exclude that event-linked exchange. On a fair reading of the contract the trader saw, the challenged No resolution should give way to Yes.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the defense opening is simple: this case is not won by proving that the word \\\"Ronaldo\\\" appears somewhere in a public transcript. The plaintiff must prove, by a preponderance, that the word was said during the market's specified event: the FIFA World Cup Draw.\\n\\nThe current packet leaves that critical link unproven. The market page does not say \\\"while Trump was at the venue,\\\" \\\"during a World Cup press availability,\\\" or \\\"during any remarks connected to the Draw.\\\" It says: \\\"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\\" The challenged resolution was No. The requested Yes theory therefore needs more than event-adjacent context; it needs a boundary showing that the reporter exchange was part of the Draw period the market asked traders to price.\\n\\nThe plaintiff's own best transcript cuts against that boundary. The case-packet file is titled \\\"Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw.\\\" It says the President's remarks were joined in progress, and the source note says portions could not be verified because the audio was incomplete. It places Trump at the Kennedy Center and includes World Cup topics, and yes, it contains \\\"Ronaldo\\\" as a standalone word in a soccer exchange. But its title and structure identify those remarks as an exchange with reporters prior to the Draw, not the formal Draw itself.\\n\\nThe terms do not rescue plaintiff from that distinction. They define a mention market around words used by the entity during the time period. A time period may be a specific event, and when it is a specific event, the Exchange may specify what is included. The technical details also distinguish official presentation content from behind-the-scenes, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings unless those are officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. Those provisions do not mean every public, nearby, event-related conversation becomes part of the event. They make the event boundary the central question.\\n\\nThe formal-draw archive note reinforces why the distinction matters. It reports that there is a separate archived transcript page for Trump's formal attendance remarks at the FIFA World Cup Drawing, but that the full text was not retrieved because the page was password-protected. That note does not prove the formal program omitted Ronaldo. It also does not prove the formal program included it. What it does show, at opening, is that the record itself separates the pre-event reporter exchange from the formal drawing remarks.\\n\\nSo the defense will focus the council on proof of inclusion, not mere association. If later phases produce a market page provision, official broadcast record, program transcript, video metadata, or source-agency material showing that the red-carpet reporter exchange was officially part of the FIFA World Cup Draw presentation for this market, the council can weigh that. If the later evidence instead shows a formal program with a separate pre-program press availability, then the correct result is No even though the word was spoken nearby.\\n\\nOn this opening record, plaintiff has shown a Ronaldo mention in remarks prior to the event. Plaintiff has not shown that those remarks occurred during the market event. The defense position is that Kalshi's No resolution follows the market wording and the mention-market terms unless plaintiff supplies that missing boundary proof.\\n\\nArguments:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the merits question is whether the contract clearly limited “during the FIFA World Cup Draw” to only the formal staged ceremony. Plaintiff submits that it did not, and the record now proves the Yes result by a preponderance.\\n\\nFirst, the market itself is broad. PX-1 identifies the public question as “What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?”, contract family PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION, strike “Ronaldo,” challenged resolution No, and requested resolution Yes. The market page does not say “during the formal televised ceremony,” “on the main stage only,” or “excluding public remarks immediately before the program at the venue.” That absence matters because Kalshi drafted the boundary traders had to price.\\n\\nSecond, the word was said. PX-2, the case-packet transcript, and PX-5, the GovInfo/OFR source excerpt, both show Trump used “Ronaldo” as a standalone word in soccer-related remarks. PX-5 is especially useful on provenance: it is the GovInfo Compilation of Presidential Documents source, published by the Office of the Federal Register/NARA, for DCPD202501162. It identifies the same event date, title, and source note, and it places the remarks at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center. In the relevant passage, Trump says he met Ronaldo, then says Ronaldo is great; later, when asked whether he played soccer or football, Trump says he was not Ronaldo or Messi. Either use satisfies the mention rule if the remarks fall within the market’s time period.\\n\\nThird, the remarks are event-linked in the way the market title reasonably covers. PX-2 and PX-5 are not private gossip, rehearsal, or an unofficial leak. They are public presidential remarks at the World Cup Draw venue, with FIFA President Infantino present, repeatedly discussing the Draw, the World Cup, ticket sales, the Kennedy Center, the audience, and the imminent program. The transcript itself includes headings such as “2026 World Cup Draw Event,” “2026 World Cup Draw Event/John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts,” and “2026 World Cup Draw/Ticket Sales for World Cup.” Trump and Infantino even discuss being a little late to “get in there” and the audience waiting. That sequence is not a random earlier interview; it is part of the public event appearance immediately surrounding the Draw.\\n\\nFourth, PX-3’s terms do not impose defendant’s formal-only line. They say the underlying is words used by the entity during the specified time period; a time period may be an event or context; and, when a time period refers to a specific event, the Exchange may specify what is included. They also say official/published content presented as part of the official presentation can count, while behind-the-scenes, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings do not count unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. Those exclusions show what this is not. The transcript is an official published record of public remarks at the event venue, not a hidden backstage clip. Nothing in PX-1 or PX-3 clearly tells traders that public, event-linked venue remarks immediately before the formal program are out.\\n\\nDefendant’s best point is PX-4 and the formal Roll Call/Factba.se page: there is a separate formal-drawing transcript, and my search found no “Ronaldo” there. Plaintiff does not hide that. But that adverse point proves only that the narrower formal-program source may omit the strike. It does not answer the contractual question. If Kalshi had meant to resolve solely by that formal transcript, it could have said so. Instead, the public market title used the broader phrase “during the FIFA World Cup Draw,” and the mention terms leave event boundaries to what the market clearly specifies.\\n\\nOn burden, plaintiff does not need absolute certainty or a formal-stage mention. Plaintiff must show it is more likely than not that the market wording plus terms include the event-linked remarks. The evidence satisfies that standard: PX-1 gives no exclusion; PX-2 and PX-5 prove the standalone Ronaldo mentions in public World Cup Draw venue remarks; PX-3 supplies a flexible event/time-period framework and excludes only categories unlike this source; PX-4 merely identifies the defense’s alternate formal-program boundary. The fair resolution is Yes.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the record now makes the defense point sharper, not weaker. Plaintiff has proved that Trump said \\\"Ronaldo\\\" in an official transcript of remarks connected to the World Cup Draw. Plaintiff has not proved that those remarks were during the market event.\\n\\nStart with the contract. DX/PX-1 gives the trader-facing question: \\\"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\\" It does not say \\\"at the Kennedy Center,\\\" \\\"on World Cup Draw day,\\\" \\\"in remarks prior to the Draw,\\\" or \\\"in any public press exchange associated with the Draw.\\\" For this strike to resolve Yes, the relevant mention must fall inside that specified time period.\\n\\nThe strongest evidence of the Ronaldo utterance is also the strongest evidence against plaintiff's boundary. PX-2 and PX-5 are titled \\\"Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw.\\\" PX-5, plaintiff's GovInfo/OFR source, confirms the same title, says the remarks were joined in progress, identifies the source as an exchange with the news media, and notes that some portions could not be verified because the audio was incomplete. That evidence proves an official pre-event reporter transcript. It does not prove the reporter exchange was the FIFA World Cup Draw.\\n\\nThe terms, PX-3, require words used by the entity during the specified time period. They permit an event or context as a time period, and they discuss what is included when the time period is a specific event. That framework does not turn all event-adjacent speech into event speech. The distinction between official presentation content and non-included behind-the-scenes or unofficial content matters because the question is not just whether a record is public or official. The question is whether this source was part of the market's event period. A public official transcript can still be a transcript of remarks prior to the event.\\n\\nDX-2 supplies the missing contrast. It is a focused extraction from the separate Roll Call/Factba.se formal FIFA World Cup Drawing transcript. That page is the formal source identified in the case-packet archive note. It is titled \\\"Remarks: Donald Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing in Washington - December 5, 2025.\\\" Its transcript begins with the formal drawing participants; at 00:00:50, Infantino says, \\\"This is the World Cup trophy\\\" and \\\"we are now going to do the draw.\\\" The page's Trump soccer answer mentions Pele and the Cosmos, not Ronaldo. The extracted page text was searched for both \\\"Ronaldo\\\" and \\\"Messi\\\" and neither appears.\\n\\nThat does not prove Trump never said Ronaldo anywhere at the venue. It proves the opposite boundary from plaintiff's: the formal Draw transcript is separate from the pre-event reporter exchange, and the formal transcript does not contain the strike. Plaintiff needs a bridge between those two sources. It has not offered one. There is no market page detail saying red-carpet or pre-program press remarks count. There is no official program metadata showing the reporter exchange was part of the Draw presentation. There is no source hierarchy provision selecting the pre-event reporter exchange over the formal Draw transcript for this market.\\n\\nPlaintiff argues ambiguity should favor Yes because Kalshi could have drafted a narrower rule. But this is a preponderance case about a challenged No resolution, not a penalty for every conceivable ambiguity. The ordinary reading of \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw\\\" is the draw program, not every public appearance immediately before it. The record's own labels preserve that ordinary line: \\\"Prior to\\\" on the Ronaldo source; \\\"Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing\\\" on the formal source; and a formal transcript that starts the draw and omits the strike.\\n\\nWeight and provenance also favor the defense on the decisive issue. PX-5 is official and useful, but it authenticates a pre-event reporter exchange. DX-2 is a captured formal transcript extraction from the source class identified in PX-4; its absence finding is limited but material. PX-4 was initially only a note that the formal page existed and could not be retrieved. We have now retrieved and searched it. The adverse check therefore confirms, rather than merely speculates, that the formal drawing transcript does not carry plaintiff's Ronaldo mention.\\n\\nThe council should resolve the proposition against plaintiff. The record shows Trump said Ronaldo before the FIFA World Cup Draw in an event-linked reporter exchange. It does not show he said Ronaldo during the FIFA World Cup Draw. On this market wording and these terms, the challenged No resolution should stand.\\n\\nRebuttals:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, defendant’s new formal-transcript extraction proves less than defendant needs.\\n\\nPlaintiff accepts the narrow fact defendant has now preserved: the Roll Call/Factba.se formal drawing-program extraction contains no “Ronaldo” or “Messi.” That is why plaintiff did not build the case on a formal-stage mention. The proposition instead asks whether the market wording and mention terms clearly excluded Trump’s public, official, event-linked remarks at the venue immediately before the formal program. Defendant has not supplied that exclusion.\\n\\nDefendant’s argument treats the title “Prior to the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw” as if “prior to” automatically means outside the Kalshi market’s event period. But PX-1 does not say “formal transcript only,” “after the draw host begins,” “after 00:00:50,” or “excluding press availability at the venue.” It asks what Trump would say “during the FIFA World Cup Draw.” The source label tells us sequence; it does not tell us the market’s legal boundary.\\n\\nDX-2 actually illustrates why defendant’s bright line is chosen after the fact. In defendant’s own formal extraction, the page begins before the mechanical draw: Mark Carney speaks at 00:00:00, and Infantino says at 00:00:50, “we are now going to do the draw.” If “during the FIFA World Cup Draw” can include ceremony and preamble on the formal page before the draw itself begins, then the phrase is not self-defining down to a single moment or transcript. The question is what the market clearly specified. It did not specify defendant’s transcript-only rule.\\n\\nThe terms do not fill that gap for defendant. PX-3 excludes hidden categories such as rehearsals, sound checks, unofficial recordings, and behind-the-scenes content unless officially published as part of the period. PX-2 and PX-5 are not those categories. PX-5 is an official GovInfo/OFR presidential transcript, published with source metadata, at 11:13 a.m. at the Kennedy Center, with FIFA’s president present and the World Cup Draw repeatedly discussed. That gives the Ronaldo mentions strong provenance and an event connection; it does not make them informal backstage chatter.\\n\\nDefendant says plaintiff needs a bridge. The bridge is the market text plus the terms’ failure to draw the narrow line defendant proposes. A No resolution can stand only if the contract fairly told traders that “during the FIFA World Cup Draw” meant only the separate formal-program transcript. On this record, the more likely reading is broader: public, official remarks at the venue, immediately tied to and immediately preceding the World Cup Draw program, were within the event-linked period unless clearly excluded.\\n\\nSo DX-2 narrows one factual issue but does not decide the case. It shows no formal-stage Ronaldo mention. It does not show that the market excluded the official pre-program event remarks where Trump did say Ronaldo. Under the preponderance standard, the Yes resolution remains the fair one.\\n\\nSurrebuttals:\\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff’s rebuttal usefully narrows the dispute. Plaintiff accepts that the formal Roll Call/Factba.se drawing transcript contains no “Ronaldo” or “Messi.” So the case remains entirely about whether a separate reporter exchange titled “Prior to the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw” should be treated as inside the market period.\\n\\nPlaintiff says “prior to” is only sequence, not legal boundary. But sequence is exactly what the market phrase makes material. The contract asks what Trump would say “during the FIFA World Cup Draw.” A source-agency title identifying the Ronaldo transcript as an exchange with reporters prior to that Draw is not a stray label; it is the best record description of when and what that source is. Plaintiff cannot convert that source into the event itself by saying the market failed to list every excluded pre-event setting.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s formal-preamble point also does not carry the burden. Yes, the formal transcript begins before the mechanical ball selection, and Infantino says at 00:00:50 that “we are now going to do the draw.” But that supports the defense distinction. A host’s preamble inside the formal drawing transcript is part of the program. A separate press exchange, separately titled and sourced as prior to the Draw, is not made part of the program simply because it happened nearby and discussed the same event.\\n\\nNor does official publication settle the issue. PX-5 strengthens provenance: Trump did say Ronaldo in an official public transcript. But provenance answers whether the words were said, not whether they were said during the market’s specified event. The terms require both: the word by the entity, and the word during the time period. Plaintiff has the first element. The second is still missing.\\n\\nThe remaining bridge plaintiff proposes is essentially: public, official, event-linked, and not expressly excluded. That is not enough under a preponderance standard when the same record supplies a cleaner boundary: the Ronaldo source is prior to the Draw, and the formal Draw source omits the strike. The challenged No resolution should stand.\\n\\nClosings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the record has narrowed to one real issue.\\n\\nThe word is proven. The market page identifies the strike as “Ronaldo” and the challenged resolution as No. The case-packet transcript and the GovInfo/OFR excerpt prove that Trump said “Ronaldo” as a standalone word in public remarks at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center, in a World Cup Draw setting, with FIFA President Infantino present, and amid repeated discussion of the Draw, the Kennedy Center, ticket sales, the audience, and the imminent event. That is strong provenance: GovInfo, NARA/OFR, DCPD202501162, matching the packet source and note.\\n\\nDefendant has also proved its best fact. The Roll Call/Factba.se formal-program extraction does not contain “Ronaldo” or “Messi.” Plaintiff does not ask you to find otherwise. If the market had said “only the formal drawing transcript,” defendant would win. But that is not the market traders saw.\\n\\nThe market asked: “What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?” It did not say “during the formal transcript only,” “after the host announces the draw has begun,” “excluding public press remarks at the venue,” or “excluding remarks immediately before the program.” The governing terms do not add that limitation. They define words used by the entity during the time period, allow event/context time periods, and exclude categories such as rehearsals, sound checks, behind-the-scenes content, and unofficial recordings. Plaintiff’s source is none of those. It is an official public presidential transcript of event-linked remarks at the venue.\\n\\nDefendant’s formal extraction shows why a bright line cannot simply be assumed. Even on that page, before balls are drawn, there is ceremony, introduction, and Infantino saying “we are now going to do the draw.” Event boundaries are not self-defining. The question is whether Kalshi clearly chose defendant’s narrower boundary. The record contains no such choice.\\n\\nSo the burden is met. More likely than not, a reasonable reading of the market and terms includes Trump’s official, public, venue-based remarks immediately tied to the World Cup Draw. The strongest contrary evidence proves only that a narrower formal transcript omits the strike. It does not prove the contract excluded the remarks where the strike was actually said.\\n\\nThe challenged No resolution should be overturned. The strike “Ronaldo” should resolve Yes.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff’s closing concedes the decisive factual split: the formal World Cup Drawing transcript contains no “Ronaldo” or “Messi.” The only Ronaldo evidence is the separate official transcript titled “Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw.”\\n\\nThat is enough to decide the case. The market did not ask what Trump would say at the Kennedy Center, on World Cup Draw day, in public presidential remarks, or in event-linked press availability. It asked what Trump would say “during the FIFA World Cup Draw.” The terms require the word to be used by the entity during the specified time period. Plaintiff has proven the word and the speaker. It has not proven the time period.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s strongest point is that the market did not expressly say “formal transcript only” or “exclude pre-program remarks.” But plaintiff has the burden. A challenged No resolution does not become Yes merely because the contract could have been even more verbose. The record must make it more likely than not that the pre-event reporter exchange was inside the market period. The record does the opposite.\\n\\nThe source labels matter. PX-2 and PX-5 are official and probative, but they are official proof of remarks prior to the Draw. The formal Roll Call/Factba.se extraction is the source for Trump’s formal attendance at the FIFA World Cup Drawing; it begins the program, includes the draw presentation, and omits the strike. Plaintiff’s theory asks you to treat a separate prior reporter exchange as “during” the Draw even though the formal Draw source exists and does not contain the word.\\n\\nThe terms do not collapse that distinction. They recognize event/context time periods and official presentation content, but they still require the word to occur during the chosen time period. Official publication proves provenance. Event connection proves relevance. Neither proves inclusion. A public official transcript can be accurately preserved and still be outside the market window if it is, as titled, prior to the event.\\n\\nSo the fair synthesis is narrow and grounded: Trump said Ronaldo in event-linked public remarks before the FIFA World Cup Draw; Trump did not say Ronaldo in the formal drawing transcript preserved in this record; and no admitted market term or source-chain evidence bridges the pre-event exchange into the market’s “during the FIFA World Cup Draw” period.\\n\\nUnder the preponderance standard, plaintiff has not carried the proposition. The challenged No resolution should stand.\\n\\nExhibits:\\n[plaintiff] PX-1 Market page and challenged resolution\\nMarket URL: https://kalshi.com/markets/kxtrumpmentionb/trump-mention-b/kxtrumpmentionb-25dec06\\n\\nPublic market title: What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\n\\nContract family: PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION\\n\\nStrike at issue: Ronaldo\\n\\nChallenged resolution: No\\n\\nRequested resolution: Yes\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-2 Pre-event reporter exchange transcript\\nRemarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\nDecember 05, 2025\\n\\n[The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\\nThe President. It's a great honor to be here. Gianni has done a fantastic job. We're setting records—[inaudible].\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. Well, I think so. They have a little bit of a shot. Pretty stiff competition. But I would say they would have a small chance.\\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize\\nQ. [Inaudible]—win the FIFA Peace Award?\\nThe President. Well, it would be an honor.\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\nQ. Will you root for some selection? Will you root for someone?\\nThe President. Well, I root for a lot of countries, but in this case, I'll be rooting for the U.S.A. [Laughter]\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. That's great. That's great. We really love it.\\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize\\nQ. Mr. President, have you been told that you are going to receive the inaugural peace prize today——\\nThe President. I have not——\\nQ. ——from FIFA?\\nThe President. I have not been told. There's a rumor about it, but I have not been told. That would be a great honor, and I'm a big fan of Gianni, as you know.\\nQ. What can fans expect——\\nQ. Are you hoping to receive that?\\nThe President. Excuse me.\\nQ. Are you hoping to receive the peace prize?\\nThe President. Well, I don't like to say \\\"hope,\\\" but it would be a great honor.\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. What can fans expect of, like, the World Cup in the U.S.?\\nThe President. I think it's going to be fantastic. We've set every record you can set.\\nQ. What are you telling people who are worried——\\nFédération Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) President Giovanni V. Infantino\\nQ. [Inaudible]—friend Gianni—[inaudible]—a word about him?\\nThe President. I think he has done a fantastic job.\\nThe President's Schedule\\nQ. Are you going to be meeting with the President of Mexico today and the——\\nThe President. We might. Yes.\\nQ. ——Prime Minister of Canada as well?\\nThe President. I might. I might do that.\\nQ. Will you be discussing immigration and trade with them?\\nThe President. Yes, we'll be discussing.\\n[At this point, the President and Mr. Infantino posed for photographs.]\\nThe President. Thank you, everybody.\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event/John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts\\nQ. Mr. President, what do you think about the crowd?\\nThe President. Oh, look, the new star—[inaudible].\\nCongratulations.\\nQ. Thank you.\\nThe President. You're the new star of television and Fox.\\nQ. Thank you. How are you doing, Mr. President?\\nThe President. I'm doing very well.\\nQ. What do you think about the crowd here?\\nThe President. I think the crowd is great, and I think the building is great. We've made a lot of improvements over the last 6 months. Taking—the Kennedy Center was in very bad shape. Now it's getting to be really good. And in 6 months, it's going to be incredible with the improvements we've made.\\nQ. The first time for the U.S. to host since the nineties.\\nThe President. Right.\\nQ. Are you ready for it?\\nThe President. I'm ready for it, and they're ready for it. And Gianni, who you know——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——has done a fantastic job with FIFA. And we're looking to have—you know, we're set—we have already set records for tickets sales. I don't think there's ever been anything like it in any sport. And so, I want to congratulate you.\\nMr. Infantino. Thank you.\\nThe President. I don't even have to wait. But major records have been set.\\nHow are you?\\nQ. Good, how are you, sir?\\nThe President. Nice to see you.\\nQ. Today it's not football—American football. It's soccer. It's——\\nThe President. Right.\\nQ. ——the big event of soccer.\\nThe President. That's right. That's right.\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\nQ. So can you tell me about this big day today?\\nThe President. It's just a big day, and it's a great sport. And it really is coming to America. And never—nobody ever thought a thing like this could happen. And I'm very happy to say that we've already set the alltime record on ticket sales long before the first ball is kicked. Right?\\nMr. Infantino. A hundred percent. One hundred percent.\\n2026 World Cup Host Cities\\nQ. You've had some concerns about crime in American cities, some of the cities that will be hosting. Have they remedied that for you? Are you still considering maybe asking FIFA to move some of those cities?\\nThe President. No, I don't want to do that. But I will tell you, if they do have a problem, by the time we get there, we'll take care of that problem. We can solve that problem.\\nI've proven that in DC and everywhere else we went, so we'll take care of that very easily. So, if they have a problem, hopefully, they'll let us know that, and we will solve any problem.\\nOkay? Thank you.\\nQ. Thank you so much.\\nMr. Infantino. All right, thank you so much.\\nQ. Thank you, Mr. President.\\nQ. Thank you. Appreciate it.\\nThe President. Congratulations.\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. Mr. President, Brazilian television. America will be hosting the World Cup and the Olympics in 2 years. How important it is—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. I think very. It's a great honor. I think Gianni is doing a phenomenal job. We've set every record on ticket sales. It's been really fantastic. But Gianni has done an unbelievable job with FIFA.\\nThe President's Experience With Soccer\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. He was a great—not only that. I got to see a man name Pelé play—right?—that tells you how old I am—when he was on the Cosmos. Do you remember that a long time ago? And it was quite a treat. That was quite an event. And he was—not only was he playing, he was great. He scored two goals, I think. And so, I was one of the few who got to see Pelé, and I assume he is one of your alltime greats. Right?\\nMr. Infantino. Definitely.\\nThe President. So I got to see him.\\nThe President's Favorite World Cup Competitor\\nQ. Do you have some favorite teams for World Cup?\\nThe President. Well, I have a favorite. It's the U.S.A. [Laughter] I don't know what their chances are, Gianni, but maybe the U.S.A. is the——\\nMr. Infantino. They're getting better and better, actually.\\nThe President. I think they'll do well.\\nMr. Infantino. They are getting better and better.\\nThe President. I think they'll do well.\\nThank you very much, everybody.\\nQ. Thank you so much.\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. Mr. President, World Cup in America just means—[inaudible]. So what do you expect from this World Cup?\\nThe President. [Inaudible]—record business and only in the United States, but we're also doing record ticket sales with FIFA. And they've already bought—beat their highest record. And we—you know, this a long time before the first ball is kicked. You've sold more tickets than they've ever done before, and better pricing than they've ever gotten before. It's a tremendous success. And it's an honor. And Gianni has done a phenomenal job with FIFA.\\nQ. [Inaudible]—ever?\\nThe President. I think so. I think it's going to be—I mean, ideally, you want to see that every year. Every 4 years, it gets bigger and better. I think we have set every record in the book. We're very happy about it.\\nThank you.\\nThe President's Favorite World Cup Competitor\\nQ. [Inaudible]—part of America. Who are you going to support as well?\\nThe President. Well, I think I have to support U.S.A. Otherwise, I'd be in trouble. I wouldn't be President for long.\\nMr. Infantino. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. [Inaudible]—but you have a lot of great teams. You're going to have a lot of great teams.\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\\\"football,\\\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\\n2026 World Cup Draw/Ticket Sales for World Cup\\nQ. How does it feel to be part of this amazing event? And obviously, your being a part of participating in all the—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. The President of Mexico is here, and she's doing a very good job. She's a good woman, very, very excellent job. It's an honor, and we're setting every record, and you're helping us set those records.\\nMr. Infantino. And we will do it.\\nThe President. You know, Mexico and Canada are helping us set those records. But as you know, we have a record in ticket sales already, long before the first ball is kicked, and we're going to do great.\\nI think that Gianni—as you know, he's the head, and he has done a fantastic job.\\nU.S. Cooperation With Mexico and Canada\\nQ. And how is the biggest challenge being three countries?\\nThe President. Well, I think that—do you mean for the three countries?\\nWell, they've gotten together really well, I mean.\\nMr. Infantino. All right.\\nThe President. They're getting along very well.\\nMr. Infantino. Collaboration is fantastic between the three.\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer/2026 World Cup\\nQ. And you like soccer?\\nThe President. I do. I like it. I like it more and more.\\nQ. Yes?\\nThe President. I like it. It's growing in this country—very, really—I mean, someday, maybe it's going to be bigger than anything else.\\nMr. Infantino. We'll have to become number one.\\nThe President. I will say this——\\nMr. Infantino. Definitely.\\nThe President. ——the ticket sales——\\nQ. Definitely will happen.\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. Ticket sales are bigger than anything we have ever done in the history of the country, in terms of sports.\\nMr. Infantino. For certain.\\nQ. And the audience is going to be huge.\\nThe President. The audience is going to be tremendous.\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. Yes.\\nMr. Infantino. Six billion people.\\nThe President. [Inaudible]\\nQ. Six billion? That's amazing.\\nMr. Infantino. Six billion people.\\nAnd today, one billion.\\nQ. Wow.\\nMr. Infantino. [Inaudible]\\nQ. Enjoy show time. Thank you so much.\\nThe President. [Inaudible]\\nQ. Mr. President, how are you? Just a quick—[inaudible].\\nQ. This is for Telemundo.\\nThe President. How are you?\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\nQ. Hello, Mr. President. How are you? This for Telemundo.\\nThe President. How are you? Good.\\nQ. How are you?\\nThe President. Very good. Thank you.\\nQ. How does it feel to have the most important event of sports—that global—in the U.S.?\\nThe President. Well, we do. And right at the Kennedy Center. I'm Chairman of the Kennedy Center. And I hear the Kennedy Center is doing a very good job, so it feels great. Really good.\\nAnd Telemundo is doing a good job, too. Thank you.\\nQ. Thank you.\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. What is the significance of hosting the FIFA World Cup this year?\\nThe President. It's a—in terms of sports, I would say the ultimate. There is no sport like this. It's the biggest sport in the world. And we are setting every record. You know, our ticket sales have gone and set every—every sport—no matter what it is, we've set the record. So—and every though it's very early, there's no ball being kicked yet, but we've already set a ticket sales record.\\nArgentina National Team\\nQ. How do you see Argentinean team for this World Cup?\\nThe President. Well, I love Argentina. And your President is doing a very good job, as you know. Milei. You know that right? It's make Argentina great again. MAGA.\\nQ. And——\\nU.S. National Team\\nQ. Do you think the States are building a powerful team for next year?\\nThe President. Who?\\nQ. The States.\\nThe President. Oh, yes. Sure. I—you're going to have a lot of powerful teams. Everybody has a lot of powerful teams, but you're going to have a lot of great teams. [Inaudible]\\nU.S. Role in Hosting the 2026 World Cup\\nQ. Mr. President, what does it mean for you guys to host the World Cup right here in the U.S.?\\nThe President. I'm honored to host it. It's a great honor. I mean, it's turned out to be bigger than we thought. We're setting a record for ticket sales, the likes of which no sport has ever seen before.\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\\nThe President. But they have a little more speed.\\nBut no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\\nPopularity of Soccer in Latin America\\nQ. Mr. President, a message for the Latin America and soccer fans?\\nThe President. Yes, I am. And Latin America is great. And they have great soccer. So, good luck in the matches.\\n[A reporter asked a question in Spanish, which was translated by an interpreter as follows.]\\nU.S. Visas for World Cup Ticketholders\\nQ. Who is going to be in—[inaudible]—about these visas for the—these fans that want to come here to the World Cup?\\nThe President. Well, we're going to make it very easy for them. We're working on that right now. We're going to make it very easy. It's going to be a very easy process.\\nQ. Okay. Say, hi to Colombia over there.\\nThe President. Hello. Is that Colombia?\\nQ. Yes.\\nThe President. I love Colombia. Hello, Colombia. [Laughter]\\nQ. Okay. Okay. Muy bien.\\nThe President. So where are you from?\\nQ. Paraguay.\\nThe President. Oh.\\nQ. He's from Paraguay. Yes.\\nThe President. Very good. I love it. I—it's a beautiful country. We get along very well with them. We do a little trade deal with them, and they like us. And that's what's happening.\\nQ. Panama.\\nThe President. Where?\\nVery good. I like the canal. [Laughter] That canal is pretty good.\\n[A reporter spoke in Spanish; no translation was provided.]\\n2026 World Cup\\nThe President. What?\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. Well, it's going to be incredible. The event is going to be very good. Just this event alone—it's at the Kennedy Center. I see you have it fixed up perfectly.\\nMr. Infantino. It will set the tone.\\nThe President. Right? It's beautiful.\\nMr. Infantino. It's beautiful.\\nThe President. It's a beautiful place.\\nHave a good time.\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President.\\n[A reporter spoke in Spanish; no translation was provided.]\\nMr. Infantino. No, gracias. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. It's great.\\nJohn F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts/Renovation Work\\nQ. Mr. President, the U.S. press?\\nThe President. Thank you, everybody, very much. It's a great honor. This has been an honor for a lot of reasons. Number one, they've sold more tickets than any event has ever sold already—long before the kickoff.\\nAnd number two, we've done a lot of work at the Kennedy Center. It was falling apart, and now it's pretty much back. And we'll get it back within the next 4 or 5 months through construction, and—but you see the way it looks.\\nAnd Gianni is just telling me—who's done an incredible job, by the way. He's just telling, you know, how good a job we've done.\\nMr. Infantino. That's right.\\nThe President. You can look at the walls. The marble was broken. Everything was a mess. And we've really taken the Kennedy Center—a lot of people thought it was going to be ripped down, and we did just the opposite. So we've done a really great renovation job on it. And over the next 3, 4 months, it will be complete. And we're honored to have it here, and it's been—it's been very special.\\nWe've set a record on ticket sales, as you probably heard, already, even way before—long before the event itself. And we're working with Canada, and we're working with Mexico. And it's been a really spectacular—so far, it's been spectacular.\\nDaniel [Daniel Baldwin, One America News Network], do you have a question?\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. What are your expectations? You once said that the FIFA World Cup is an opportunity to put—a once-in-a-lifetime opportunity to put the greatness of the United States on display.\\nThe President. Well, I think—\\nQ. One billion eyeballs will be watching, Mr. President.\\nThe President. Yes, I—think——\\nQ. What will they here today?\\nThe President. Even today, I understand. I hear that, you know——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——I know we're a little late to get in there, but——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——that's okay.\\nMr. Infantino. They wait.\\nThe President. So all my friends, I guess they have to wait. They have no choice, right? [Laughter]\\nMr. Infantino. Yes, they wait.\\nThe President. But no, the numbers are incredible. I hear today's numbers are——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——very big. I hope CNN is covering this.\\nQ. One billion eyeballs.\\nMr. Infantino. Today, 1 billion eyeballs.\\nThe President. Today's numbers are very, very big.\\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize/The President's Foreign Policy\\nQ. We are covering it. And you're expected to get the FIFA Peace Prize, Mr. President. What would you say to people who say that prize might conflict with your pledge to strike Venezuela?\\nThe President. Well, I think the peace prize—I mean, I settled eight wars. I don't know that I'm getting it. I haven't been officially noticed. I've been hearing about a peace prize, and I'm here to represent our country in a different sense. But I can tell you, I did settle eight wars, and we have a ninth coming, but—which nobody has ever done before.\\nBut I want to really save lives. I don't need prizes. I need to save lives. And we're saving a lot of lives. And I've saved millions and millions of lives, and that's really what I want to do.\\nAnd I also want to run a great country. And the United States right now is the hottest country anywhere in the world. And 1 year ago, it was dead. We had a dead country, and now we have the hottest country anywhere in the world.\\nQ. Mr. President, will you——\\nThe President's Meeting With President Claudia Sheinbaum Pardo of Mexico and Prime Minister Mark Carney of Canada\\nQ. What are you going to discuss with Canada and Mexico, Mr.—what are you going to discuss with the leaders of Canada and Mexico?\\nThe President. Well, we're getting—we're going to meet with both. And we're getting along very well. You know, we're getting along very well. I don't know. I think we have a meeting set up for some time after the event.\\nQ. Will you discuss trade?\\nThe President. Yes, we'll discuss trade. We—get along very well.\\nThank you, everybody, very much.\\nQ. Will you pardon any other Honduran officials?\\nQ. Do you want them to keep trying to indict Ms. James?\\n\\nNOTE: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. In his remarks, he referred to Trey Yingst, chief foreign correspondent, Fox News Channel; Cristiano Ronaldo, forward for Saudi Pro League club Al-Nass and Portugal's national soccer team; and Lionel Messi, forward for Major League Soccer club Inter Miami and Argentina's national team. A reporter referred to New York State Attorney General Letitia James. The transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\n\\nSource URL: https://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/documents/remarks-exchange-with-reporters-prior-the-2026-federation-internationale-des-associations\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-3 PRESMENTION/NEWMENTION terms\\n                                         NEWMENTION\\n\\nScope: These rules shall apply to this contract.\\n\\nUnderlying: The Underlying for this Contract is words used by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nRevisions to the Underlying made after Expiration will not be accounted for in determining the\\nExpiration Value.\\n\\nSource Agency: The Source Agencies are \\u003csource\\u003e.\\n\\nType: The type of Contract is an Event Contract.\\n\\nIssuance: After the initial Contract, Contract iterations will be listed on an as-needed basis at\\nthe discretion of the Exchange and corresponding to the risk management needs of Members.\\n\\n\\u003centity\\u003e: \\u003centity\\u003e refers to the speaker, writer, performer, or communicator specified by the\\nExchange. This may include (but is not limited to): a specific named individual, multiple\\nindividuals specified using AND/OR logic, an individual identified by position or title, a group,\\nband, team or collective entity, a specified member or members of a group, an organization,\\ncompany, or institutional entity, or any combination of the aforementioned.\\n\\nWhen \\u003centity\\u003e is defined by a position or title, the Contract tracks whoever holds that position\\nduring \\u003ctime period\\u003e, even if the individual holding the position changes. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a\\nspecific named individual, the identity remains consistent throughout. Name changes (e.g.,\\nstage names, married names) do not create a new entity. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a group or\\norganization and the Contract does not specify particular members, any official\\ncommunication or statement by any member or designated spokesperson counts. When using\\nAND logic, all specified entities must independently say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e. When\\nusing OR logic, at least one of the specified entities must say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nThe Exchange may specify additional conditions such as “at least X members of” a group or\\n“the majority of” a group.\\n\\n\\u003csource\\u003e: \\u003csource\\u003e refers to a Source Agency or ordered collection of Source Agencies\\nspecified by the Exchange at the time of Contract listing, which will be incorporated into the\\nSource Agency hierarchy above and used to determine the occurrence of the Underlying.\\n\\u003csource\\u003e may refer to a singular agency, multiple agencies, an agency by distinguishing\\ncharacteristics, by category or type (e.g., “official government statistical body,” “primary wire\\nservice”), or any combination thereof. When multiple agencies are specified, they may be\\napplied in the hierarchical order designated by the Exchange if so specified, with the highest-\\nranked available and responsive agency taking precedence for purposes of determining the\\nExpiration Value. A lower-ranked agency shall only be consulted if all higher-ranked agencies\\nare unavailable, unresponsive, have not reported on the Underlying by the Expiration time, or\\nif the Exchange, in its sole discretion, determines that a higher-ranked agency’s reporting is\\nincomplete, erroneous, or otherwise insufficient to determine the Expiration Value. If \\u003csource\\u003e\\ndesignates multiple agencies without specifying a hierarchical order, the Exchange shall\\nresolve any conflict between reporting agencies at its sole discretion.\\n\\n\\u003cword\\u003e: \\u003cword\\u003e refers to the particular word or phrase potentially to be mentioned by\\n\\u003centity\\u003e. It may refer to a word being said a minimum number of times. It may also refer to\\none of multiple words/phrases, any of which are acceptable (e.g., “Doge/Dogecoin”).\\n\\f\\u003ctime period\\u003e: \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific range of time, event or discrete date and\\ntime specified by the Exchange. This may be defined by, but is not limited to: a specific event\\nor context (e.g., “during the State of the Union address”), exact dates or times, relative time\\nmarkers (e.g., “before July 1, 2027,” “in Q1 2026”), event-based periods (e.g., “during any\\ncampaign rally in October 2026,” “during the awards ceremony”), and broader intervals (e.g.,\\n“Q1–Q2 2027,” “January–March 2026”).\\n\\nUnless stated otherwise, “Between” is inclusive of both endpoints, while “before” and “after”\\nexclude the specified date. \\u003ctime period\\u003e may also refer to “Any” or “None”, to multiple dates\\n(even if non-consecutive), or to a singular and discrete date or time.\\n\\nWhen \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event (such as an address, speech, performance, or\\nbroadcast), the Exchange may specify what is included, including whether it includes both live\\nand pre-recorded segments (including whether advertisements are included). Where a\\ntimezone is not specified, ET is assumed.\\n\\n\\nPayout Criterion: The Payout Criterion for the Contract encompasses the Expiration Values that\\n\\u003cword\\u003e is said by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n\\n\\nThe word must appear as a distinct, standalone unit, not buried inside another word. Plural\\nand possessive noun forms count. Other grammatical changes (tense, conjugation, derivation)\\ndo not. If \\u003cword\\u003e appears separated from other words by a space or hyphen or in a\\ncompound form with a space or hyphen, it counts. If \\u003cword\\u003e is fused into a single\\nunhyphenated word, it does not count.\\n\\nIf \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled, and the market contains a\\nstrike stating “Event does not qualify/occur”, such a strike shall resolve “Yes” and all others\\n“No”. If \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled but such strikes are NOT\\nlisted, the Contracts will resolve to the last fair price determined at the discretion of the\\nExchange. If the event is postponed, and such a postponement is announced by the end of the\\nfollowing calendar day to be rescheduled to a time within 14 calendar days, the markets shall\\nremain open. If the event captured in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast, the\\nExchange may keep the market open for 24 hours for the release of an official recording.\\nFurther granular details on conditions for these Contracts is available below.\\n\\nAdditional clarification(s):\\n\\n     Possessive noun forms of \\u003cword\\u003e, plurals, and possessive plural noun forms are\\n     INCLUDED:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigrants” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Egg” → “eggs’ shells” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Russia” → “Russia’s” counts, “Russian” does not\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e exists only in adjective form, no plural form exists:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Economic” → “Economics” does not count (“Economic” is an adjective\\n          for which “Economics” is not a plural)\\n     Plural nouns occurring within proper nouns and noun phrases are included:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Cat” → “Cats the musical” counts\\n\\f    Grammatical variations beyond plurals/possessives are NOT included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigration” does NOT count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Run” → “Running” or “Ran” do NOT count\\n    When \\u003cword\\u003e specifies a plural form, the singular does NOT count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Veterans” → “Veteran” does NOT count\\n    Words that are spelled the same as the plural form of \\u003cword\\u003e (if such exists) but are\\n    themselves not a plural noun are included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Wind” → “Winds up the clock” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Border” → “The United States has strong borders” counts\\n    Open compounds (words separated by spaces) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fire station” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “couch” → “couch potato” counts\\n    Hyphenated compounds (words connected by hyphens) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Palestine” → “pro-Palestine” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fat” → “non-fat” counts\\n    Closed compounds (single word, no spaces/hyphens) do not count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire” does not count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firefighter” does not count\\n    Multi-word \\u003cword\\u003e in larger constructions: When \\u003cword\\u003e is a multi-word phrase\\n    appearing within a hyphenated construction, it counts only if \\u003cword\\u003e appears as a\\n    complete, unmodified element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “New York” → “New York-based” counts (complete element)\\n    Portmanteaus (words blended from two words where parts of each are combined) are\\n    NOT included unless the portmanteau clearly contains \\u003cword\\u003e as a distinct, unaltered\\n    element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “MAGA” → “MAGA-nificent” counts (MAGA appears as distinct element)\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “magnificent” → “MAGA-nificent” does NOT count (portmanteau blend)\\n\\nDictionary determination: Both the Merriam-Webster Dictionary (available online) AND the\\nOxford English Dictionary shall be used to determine compound type and/or conventional\\nspelling patterns. Inclusion in either dictionary as an open or hyphenated compound shall\\nsatisfy the Payout Criterion. If neither provides clarity (or the word is not included),\\ndetermination is based on whether written as single unit (closed/doesn’t count) vs. spaces or\\nhyphens (open or hyphenated/counts) and/or context and previous usage.\\n\\nPHONETIC EQUIVALENCIES\\n\\n    Homophones (same sound, different spelling) do not count:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “write” → “right” does not count\\n    Homonyms and homographs (same spelling) COUNT regardless of meaning or\\n    pronunciation:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “bass” → both “bass guitar” and “bass fishing” count\\n    Proper and common nouns are treated identically:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Apple” → both “Apple Inc.” and “apple” (fruit) count\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Will” → both “Will Smith” and “I will go” count\\n    Minor unintentional mispronunciations COUNT if context makes intent clear:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Mamdani” → “Mandani” counts\\n    Severe mispronunciations that make \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable do NOT count.\\n    Trademarked spellings do not count, even when pronounced identically, unless the word\\n\\fitself is the same:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “lift” → “Lyft” (pronounced “lift”) does not count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “uber” → “Uber” counts\\nWords with non-standard transliteration to English count within reason, provided they are\\nphonetically equivalent:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Zelensky” → any of “Zelenski,” “Zelenskii,” “Zelensky,” or “Zelenskiy”\\n      count if pronounced equivalently\\nContractions do not count for their constituent words unless otherwise explicitly specified\\nby the Exchange:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “not” → “won’t,” “can’t,” “don’t,” “isn’t” do not count\\nNumbers spoken as words COUNT, when spoken exactly (not part of a larger number):\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “five” → saying “five” or reading “$5” aloud as “five dollars” counts,\\n      saying “five hundred” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “410” → “four hundred ten”, “four one zero” or “four ten” counts\\nOrdinals COUNT when \\u003cword\\u003e is written numerically OR a phrase that includes a\\nnumber:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “January 6” → “January 6th” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “3” (written numerically) → “3rd” (spoken as “third”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Eight War” → “8 Wars” and “Eighth War” will count\\nCardinal and ordinal number words are distinct:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “one” → “first” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “first” → “one” does NOT count\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count when pronunciation or letter-by-letter spelling\\nmatches \\u003cword\\u003e:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “NASA” (pronounced “NAH-suh”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “N-A-S-A” (spelled out) counts\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count as \\u003cword\\u003e when pronounced as the full word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Doctor” → “Dr.” (pronounced “Doctor”) counts\\nExpanded forms of acronyms do NOT count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “AI” → “artificial intelligence” does not count\\nWords in foreign languages do NOT count unless they are perfect cognates with an\\nEnglish word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fuego” (Spanish) does NOT count\\nEnglish words within foreign sentences count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “policy” → “Nuestra policy es clara” counts\\n\\u003cword\\u003e in organization/company names counts:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Securities” → “Bank of America Securities” counts\\nWords in URLs, emails, handles, and hashtags (exclusive of domain structure, email\\nprovider or symbols) are treated as compounds when spoken as complete words, with the\\ntype of compound subject to aforementioned rules:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firestation.com” pronounced “fire station dot com” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire.com” pronounced “wildfire dot com” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “apple” → “apple.com” pronounced “apple dot com” does count\\n      When presented in URL, email, handle, or hashtag form, \\u003cword\\u003e shall be treated as\\n      a compound, not a multi-word word\\nSung, rapped, or poetic words COUNT if phonetically recognizable:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “money” → “moneyyy” (extended in rap) counts\\n      Extreme distortion making \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable does NOT count.\\nPhonetic alphabet spelling (“Foxtrot India Romeo Echo” for “FIRE”) does NOT count.\\n\\fCANCELLATIONS AND DELAYS\\n\\n   The Exchange may list an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike for any Contract. If listed,\\n   such a strike refers to the structural conditions of the market, and is NOT adjudicated as a\\n   \\u003cword\\u003e needing to be said by or validated by having been said by \\u003centity\\u003e. If listed, this\\n   strike resolves to “Yes” whenever the event fails to occur or qualify under the Payout\\n   Criterion, or any other circumstance prevents normal resolution.\\n   If no such strike is listed, and \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, the following rules\\n   apply if the event is cancelled, postponed, rescheduled, or materially altered (including\\n   being closed to press) such that no video is released within one calendar day of the\\n   original start time of the event:\\n         If the event is cancelled, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price determined in\\n         the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         If the event is postponed or rescheduled, the outcome depends on whether a new\\n         date is publicly announced within one calendar day (i.e. if the event was scheduled\\n         to begin on Monday, any time up to 11:59PM on Tuesday falls within this period) of\\n         the originally scheduled start time:\\n               If no new date is announced within one calendar day, the Contract will resolve\\n               to the last fair price determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n               If a new date is announced within one calendar day, the outcome depends on\\n               when the rescheduled event is set to occur:\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls within fourteen (14) calendar days of the\\n                     originally scheduled date, the Contract shall remain open and \\u003cword\\u003e\\n                     stated during the rescheduled event will count.\\n                           The fourteen-day window begins at 12:00 AM ET on the originally\\n                           scheduled date and ends at 11:59 PM ET fourteen days later, unless\\n                           an alternate timezone is explicitly specified.\\n                           Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the State of the Union on January\\n                           15, 2026” rescheduled to January 20, 2026 → words spoken during\\n                           the rescheduled address count.\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls more than fourteen (14) calendar days after\\n                     the originally scheduled date, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price\\n                     determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         Any Contract that cannot be resolved through the Source Agency hierarchy will\\n         instead be settled at the Last Fair Price. The Exchange will disclose the methodology\\n         used to determine the Last Fair Price (e.g., Last Traded Price, Time-Weighted\\n         Average Price) at the time of Issuance.\\n         If an event begins but is interrupted, abbreviated, or ends prematurely, words\\n         stated by \\u003centity\\u003e during the portion of the event that did occur will count and the\\n         market will otherwise resolve.\\n   If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window but the venue, format, or medium\\n   changes (e.g., moved to a different location, changed from in-person to virtual (with the\\n   exception of being closed to press)), words stated during the event will count.\\n   Special condition: Across both cases, whether an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike is\\n   listed or not, if the event specified as or in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast (or\\n   relayed as such) but the live stream/broadcast does not occur, the Exchange will instead\\n   use an officially released recording as the Underlying, and may delay resolution by up to\\n   one calendar day to allow for the release of such a recording.\\n\\f          If partial snippets are released, Contracts on words that do not appear will be\\n          resolved to last fair price, and Contracts on those that do will be resolved to “Yes”.\\n          If no recording is released, the relevant outcomes triggered by the\\n          presence/absence of an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike shall occur as outlined\\n          above.\\n\\nTECHNICAL DETAILS (UNLESS OTHERWISE SPECIFIED)\\n\\n     When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, pre-recorded content broadcast,\\n     streamed, or published as part of that event is included if presented as part of the official\\n     presentation.\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the concert” with pre-recorded video interlude\\n          where entity speaks → words from interlude count\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the television appearance” with pre-taped\\n          segment aired during broadcast → words from segment count\\n     Behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are NOT\\n     included unless officially broadcast or published as part of \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n     Subtitles and captions that display \\u003cword\\u003e on screen but are not spoken aloud by\\n     \\u003centity\\u003e do NOT count.\\n     Sign language interpretation or usage by entity does NOT count as saying \\u003cword\\u003e unless\\n     the Contract explicitly specifies that sign language counts.\\n     Text that entity displays on screen (presentation slides, teleprompter visible to audience,\\n     signatures) does NOT count unless entity reads it aloud.\\n     Content generated by AI, deepfakes, or synthetic voice technology impersonating entity\\n     does NOT count unless the synthetic content is officially commissioned, authorized, or\\n     published by entity, OR the Contract explicitly specifies that AI-generated content counts.\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e is muted due to technical failure or censorship it shall not count unless\\n     corroborating contextual evidence (including surrounding speech, or an official\\n     uncensored recording or transcript) confirms that \\u003centity\\u003e specifically uttered \\u003cword\\u003e\\n     during the muted period.\\n\\nMinimum Tick: The Minimum Tick size for the Contract shall be $0.01.\\n\\nPosition Accountability Level: The Position Accountability Level for the Contract shall be\\n$25,000 per strike, per Member.\\n\\nLast Trading Date: The Last Trading Date of the Contract will be the Expiration Date. The Last\\nTrading Time will be the Expiration time.\\n\\nSettlement Date: The Settlement Date of the Contract shall be no later than the day after the\\nExpiration Date, unless the Market Outcome is under review pursuant to Rule 7.1.\\n\\nExpiration Date: When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event: The latest Expiration Date of\\nthe Contract shall be fourteen (14) calendar days after the originally scheduled date of the\\nevent. If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window, expiration will be moved to an\\nearlier date and time in accordance with Rule 7.2. When \\u003ctime period\\u003e is defined by specific\\ndates: The latest Expiration Date of the Contract shall be two weeks after the end of \\u003ctime\\nperiod\\u003e. If an event described in the Payout Criterion occurs and a consensus has been\\nreached on all terms, then expiration will be moved to an earlier date and time in accordance\\nwith Rule 7.2.\\n\\fExpiration time: The Expiration time of the Contract shall be 10:00 AM ET.\\n\\nSettlement Value: The Settlement Value for this Contract is $1.00.\\n\\nExpiration Value: The Expiration Value is the value of the Underlying as documented by the\\nSource Agency on the Expiration Date at the Expiration time.\\n\\nContingencies: Before Settlement, Kalshi may, at its sole discretion, initiate the Market\\nOutcome Review Process pursuant to Rule 7.1 of the Rulebook. If an Expiration Value cannot\\nbe determined on the Expiration Date, Kalshi has the right to determine payouts pursuant to\\nRule 7.1 in the Rulebook.\\n\\f\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-4 Formal draw archive note\\nSource checked: Roll Call / Factba.se archive\\n\\nArchive title: Remarks: Donald Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing in Washington - December 5, 2025\\n\\nArchive URL: https://rollcall.com/factbase/trump/transcript/donald-trump-remarks-fifa-world-cup-drawing-december-5-2025/\\n\\nWhat this file establishes:\\n\\nThere is a separate archived transcript page for Trump's formal attendance remarks at the draw.\\n\\nWhat this file does not establish:\\n\\nThis session could not retrieve the full transcript text from that archive.  The page is password-protected.  This example therefore does not claim, from local files alone, whether the formal program transcript does or does not contain the word \\\"Ronaldo.\\\"\\n\\nWhy this matters:\\n\\nThe complaint does not need to prove that the formal program omitted the strike.  It needs to show that Trump said \\\"Ronaldo\\\" in event-linked remarks and that the market boundary reasonably includes those remarks.  The formal archive remains relevant because it marks the distinction between the pre-event reporter exchange and the formal program.\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-5 GovInfo official transcript excerpt and metadata\\nSource: GovInfo, DCPD202501162, Office of the Federal Register / National Archives and Records Administration.\\nURL: https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/DCPD-202501162/html/DCPD-202501162.htm\\nTitle: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\nEvent date: December 5, 2025.\\n\\nRelevant extracted page text:\\n\\\"Administration of Donald J. Trump, 2025\\\"\\n\\\"Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw December 5, 2025\\\"\\n\\\"[The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\\\"\\n\\nUnder the section \\\"The President's Interest in Soccer\\\":\\n\\\"Q. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\\\"\\n\\\"The President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\\\\\\\"football,\\\\\\\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\\\"\\n\\\"Thank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\\\"\\n\\nAdditional relevant extracted page text:\\n\\\"The President's Interest in Soccer\\\"\\n\\\"Q. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\\\"\\n\\\"The President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\\\"\\n\\\"Mr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\\\"\\n\\\"The President. But they have a little more speed. But no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\\\"\\n\\nGovInfo note:\\n\\\"NOTE: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. In his remarks, he referred to Trey Yingst, chief foreign correspondent, Fox News Channel; Cristiano Ronaldo, forward for Saudi Pro League club Al-Nass and Portugal's national soccer team; and Lionel Messi, forward for Major League Soccer club Inter Miami and Argentina's national team. A reporter referred to New York State Attorney General Letitia James. The transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\\"\\n\\nGovInfo content details page also identifies category \\\"Interviews With the News Media : Exchanges with reporters, Washington, DC,\\\" subjects including \\\"Federation Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) World Cup,\\\" \\\"John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts,\\\" and \\\"Soccer,\\\" and names including \\\"Ronaldo, Cristiano\\\" and \\\"Messi, Lionel.\\\"\\n\\n[defendant] DX-1 Market wording and challenged resolution\\nMarket URL: https://kalshi.com/markets/kxtrumpmentionb/trump-mention-b/kxtrumpmentionb-25dec06\\n\\nPublic market title: What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\n\\nContract family: PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION\\n\\nStrike at issue: Ronaldo\\n\\nChallenged resolution: No\\n\\nRequested resolution: Yes\\n\\n\\n[defendant] DX-2 Pre-event reporter exchange transcript\\nRemarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\nDecember 05, 2025\\n\\n[The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\\nThe President. It's a great honor to be here. Gianni has done a fantastic job. We're setting records—[inaudible].\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. Well, I think so. They have a little bit of a shot. Pretty stiff competition. But I would say they would have a small chance.\\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize\\nQ. [Inaudible]—win the FIFA Peace Award?\\nThe President. Well, it would be an honor.\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\nQ. Will you root for some selection? Will you root for someone?\\nThe President. Well, I root for a lot of countries, but in this case, I'll be rooting for the U.S.A. [Laughter]\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. That's great. That's great. We really love it.\\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize\\nQ. Mr. President, have you been told that you are going to receive the inaugural peace prize today——\\nThe President. I have not——\\nQ. ——from FIFA?\\nThe President. I have not been told. There's a rumor about it, but I have not been told. That would be a great honor, and I'm a big fan of Gianni, as you know.\\nQ. What can fans expect——\\nQ. Are you hoping to receive that?\\nThe President. Excuse me.\\nQ. Are you hoping to receive the peace prize?\\nThe President. Well, I don't like to say \\\"hope,\\\" but it would be a great honor.\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. What can fans expect of, like, the World Cup in the U.S.?\\nThe President. I think it's going to be fantastic. We've set every record you can set.\\nQ. What are you telling people who are worried——\\nFédération Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) President Giovanni V. Infantino\\nQ. [Inaudible]—friend Gianni—[inaudible]—a word about him?\\nThe President. I think he has done a fantastic job.\\nThe President's Schedule\\nQ. Are you going to be meeting with the President of Mexico today and the——\\nThe President. We might. Yes.\\nQ. ——Prime Minister of Canada as well?\\nThe President. I might. I might do that.\\nQ. Will you be discussing immigration and trade with them?\\nThe President. Yes, we'll be discussing.\\n[At this point, the President and Mr. Infantino posed for photographs.]\\nThe President. Thank you, everybody.\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event/John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts\\nQ. Mr. President, what do you think about the crowd?\\nThe President. Oh, look, the new star—[inaudible].\\nCongratulations.\\nQ. Thank you.\\nThe President. You're the new star of television and Fox.\\nQ. Thank you. How are you doing, Mr. President?\\nThe President. I'm doing very well.\\nQ. What do you think about the crowd here?\\nThe President. I think the crowd is great, and I think the building is great. We've made a lot of improvements over the last 6 months. Taking—the Kennedy Center was in very bad shape. Now it's getting to be really good. And in 6 months, it's going to be incredible with the improvements we've made.\\nQ. The first time for the U.S. to host since the nineties.\\nThe President. Right.\\nQ. Are you ready for it?\\nThe President. I'm ready for it, and they're ready for it. And Gianni, who you know——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——has done a fantastic job with FIFA. And we're looking to have—you know, we're set—we have already set records for tickets sales. I don't think there's ever been anything like it in any sport. And so, I want to congratulate you.\\nMr. Infantino. Thank you.\\nThe President. I don't even have to wait. But major records have been set.\\nHow are you?\\nQ. Good, how are you, sir?\\nThe President. Nice to see you.\\nQ. Today it's not football—American football. It's soccer. It's——\\nThe President. Right.\\nQ. ——the big event of soccer.\\nThe President. That's right. That's right.\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\nQ. So can you tell me about this big day today?\\nThe President. It's just a big day, and it's a great sport. And it really is coming to America. And never—nobody ever thought a thing like this could happen. And I'm very happy to say that we've already set the alltime record on ticket sales long before the first ball is kicked. Right?\\nMr. Infantino. A hundred percent. One hundred percent.\\n2026 World Cup Host Cities\\nQ. You've had some concerns about crime in American cities, some of the cities that will be hosting. Have they remedied that for you? Are you still considering maybe asking FIFA to move some of those cities?\\nThe President. No, I don't want to do that. But I will tell you, if they do have a problem, by the time we get there, we'll take care of that problem. We can solve that problem.\\nI've proven that in DC and everywhere else we went, so we'll take care of that very easily. So, if they have a problem, hopefully, they'll let us know that, and we will solve any problem.\\nOkay? Thank you.\\nQ. Thank you so much.\\nMr. Infantino. All right, thank you so much.\\nQ. Thank you, Mr. President.\\nQ. Thank you. Appreciate it.\\nThe President. Congratulations.\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. Mr. President, Brazilian television. America will be hosting the World Cup and the Olympics in 2 years. How important it is—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. I think very. It's a great honor. I think Gianni is doing a phenomenal job. We've set every record on ticket sales. It's been really fantastic. But Gianni has done an unbelievable job with FIFA.\\nThe President's Experience With Soccer\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. He was a great—not only that. I got to see a man name Pelé play—right?—that tells you how old I am—when he was on the Cosmos. Do you remember that a long time ago? And it was quite a treat. That was quite an event. And he was—not only was he playing, he was great. He scored two goals, I think. And so, I was one of the few who got to see Pelé, and I assume he is one of your alltime greats. Right?\\nMr. Infantino. Definitely.\\nThe President. So I got to see him.\\nThe President's Favorite World Cup Competitor\\nQ. Do you have some favorite teams for World Cup?\\nThe President. Well, I have a favorite. It's the U.S.A. [Laughter] I don't know what their chances are, Gianni, but maybe the U.S.A. is the——\\nMr. Infantino. They're getting better and better, actually.\\nThe President. I think they'll do well.\\nMr. Infantino. They are getting better and better.\\nThe President. I think they'll do well.\\nThank you very much, everybody.\\nQ. Thank you so much.\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. Mr. President, World Cup in America just means—[inaudible]. So what do you expect from this World Cup?\\nThe President. [Inaudible]—record business and only in the United States, but we're also doing record ticket sales with FIFA. And they've already bought—beat their highest record. And we—you know, this a long time before the first ball is kicked. You've sold more tickets than they've ever done before, and better pricing than they've ever gotten before. It's a tremendous success. And it's an honor. And Gianni has done a phenomenal job with FIFA.\\nQ. [Inaudible]—ever?\\nThe President. I think so. I think it's going to be—I mean, ideally, you want to see that every year. Every 4 years, it gets bigger and better. I think we have set every record in the book. We're very happy about it.\\nThank you.\\nThe President's Favorite World Cup Competitor\\nQ. [Inaudible]—part of America. Who are you going to support as well?\\nThe President. Well, I think I have to support U.S.A. Otherwise, I'd be in trouble. I wouldn't be President for long.\\nMr. Infantino. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. [Inaudible]—but you have a lot of great teams. You're going to have a lot of great teams.\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\\\"football,\\\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\\n2026 World Cup Draw/Ticket Sales for World Cup\\nQ. How does it feel to be part of this amazing event? And obviously, your being a part of participating in all the—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. The President of Mexico is here, and she's doing a very good job. She's a good woman, very, very excellent job. It's an honor, and we're setting every record, and you're helping us set those records.\\nMr. Infantino. And we will do it.\\nThe President. You know, Mexico and Canada are helping us set those records. But as you know, we have a record in ticket sales already, long before the first ball is kicked, and we're going to do great.\\nI think that Gianni—as you know, he's the head, and he has done a fantastic job.\\nU.S. Cooperation With Mexico and Canada\\nQ. And how is the biggest challenge being three countries?\\nThe President. Well, I think that—do you mean for the three countries?\\nWell, they've gotten together really well, I mean.\\nMr. Infantino. All right.\\nThe President. They're getting along very well.\\nMr. Infantino. Collaboration is fantastic between the three.\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer/2026 World Cup\\nQ. And you like soccer?\\nThe President. I do. I like it. I like it more and more.\\nQ. Yes?\\nThe President. I like it. It's growing in this country—very, really—I mean, someday, maybe it's going to be bigger than anything else.\\nMr. Infantino. We'll have to become number one.\\nThe President. I will say this——\\nMr. Infantino. Definitely.\\nThe President. ——the ticket sales——\\nQ. Definitely will happen.\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. Ticket sales are bigger than anything we have ever done in the history of the country, in terms of sports.\\nMr. Infantino. For certain.\\nQ. And the audience is going to be huge.\\nThe President. The audience is going to be tremendous.\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. Yes.\\nMr. Infantino. Six billion people.\\nThe President. [Inaudible]\\nQ. Six billion? That's amazing.\\nMr. Infantino. Six billion people.\\nAnd today, one billion.\\nQ. Wow.\\nMr. Infantino. [Inaudible]\\nQ. Enjoy show time. Thank you so much.\\nThe President. [Inaudible]\\nQ. Mr. President, how are you? Just a quick—[inaudible].\\nQ. This is for Telemundo.\\nThe President. How are you?\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\nQ. Hello, Mr. President. How are you? This for Telemundo.\\nThe President. How are you? Good.\\nQ. How are you?\\nThe President. Very good. Thank you.\\nQ. How does it feel to have the most important event of sports—that global—in the U.S.?\\nThe President. Well, we do. And right at the Kennedy Center. I'm Chairman of the Kennedy Center. And I hear the Kennedy Center is doing a very good job, so it feels great. Really good.\\nAnd Telemundo is doing a good job, too. Thank you.\\nQ. Thank you.\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. What is the significance of hosting the FIFA World Cup this year?\\nThe President. It's a—in terms of sports, I would say the ultimate. There is no sport like this. It's the biggest sport in the world. And we are setting every record. You know, our ticket sales have gone and set every—every sport—no matter what it is, we've set the record. So—and every though it's very early, there's no ball being kicked yet, but we've already set a ticket sales record.\\nArgentina National Team\\nQ. How do you see Argentinean team for this World Cup?\\nThe President. Well, I love Argentina. And your President is doing a very good job, as you know. Milei. You know that right? It's make Argentina great again. MAGA.\\nQ. And——\\nU.S. National Team\\nQ. Do you think the States are building a powerful team for next year?\\nThe President. Who?\\nQ. The States.\\nThe President. Oh, yes. Sure. I—you're going to have a lot of powerful teams. Everybody has a lot of powerful teams, but you're going to have a lot of great teams. [Inaudible]\\nU.S. Role in Hosting the 2026 World Cup\\nQ. Mr. President, what does it mean for you guys to host the World Cup right here in the U.S.?\\nThe President. I'm honored to host it. It's a great honor. I mean, it's turned out to be bigger than we thought. We're setting a record for ticket sales, the likes of which no sport has ever seen before.\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\\nThe President. But they have a little more speed.\\nBut no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\\nPopularity of Soccer in Latin America\\nQ. Mr. President, a message for the Latin America and soccer fans?\\nThe President. Yes, I am. And Latin America is great. And they have great soccer. So, good luck in the matches.\\n[A reporter asked a question in Spanish, which was translated by an interpreter as follows.]\\nU.S. Visas for World Cup Ticketholders\\nQ. Who is going to be in—[inaudible]—about these visas for the—these fans that want to come here to the World Cup?\\nThe President. Well, we're going to make it very easy for them. We're working on that right now. We're going to make it very easy. It's going to be a very easy process.\\nQ. Okay. Say, hi to Colombia over there.\\nThe President. Hello. Is that Colombia?\\nQ. Yes.\\nThe President. I love Colombia. Hello, Colombia. [Laughter]\\nQ. Okay. Okay. Muy bien.\\nThe President. So where are you from?\\nQ. Paraguay.\\nThe President. Oh.\\nQ. He's from Paraguay. Yes.\\nThe President. Very good. I love it. I—it's a beautiful country. We get along very well with them. We do a little trade deal with them, and they like us. And that's what's happening.\\nQ. Panama.\\nThe President. Where?\\nVery good. I like the canal. [Laughter] That canal is pretty good.\\n[A reporter spoke in Spanish; no translation was provided.]\\n2026 World Cup\\nThe President. What?\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. Well, it's going to be incredible. The event is going to be very good. Just this event alone—it's at the Kennedy Center. I see you have it fixed up perfectly.\\nMr. Infantino. It will set the tone.\\nThe President. Right? It's beautiful.\\nMr. Infantino. It's beautiful.\\nThe President. It's a beautiful place.\\nHave a good time.\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President.\\n[A reporter spoke in Spanish; no translation was provided.]\\nMr. Infantino. No, gracias. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. It's great.\\nJohn F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts/Renovation Work\\nQ. Mr. President, the U.S. press?\\nThe President. Thank you, everybody, very much. It's a great honor. This has been an honor for a lot of reasons. Number one, they've sold more tickets than any event has ever sold already—long before the kickoff.\\nAnd number two, we've done a lot of work at the Kennedy Center. It was falling apart, and now it's pretty much back. And we'll get it back within the next 4 or 5 months through construction, and—but you see the way it looks.\\nAnd Gianni is just telling me—who's done an incredible job, by the way. He's just telling, you know, how good a job we've done.\\nMr. Infantino. That's right.\\nThe President. You can look at the walls. The marble was broken. Everything was a mess. And we've really taken the Kennedy Center—a lot of people thought it was going to be ripped down, and we did just the opposite. So we've done a really great renovation job on it. And over the next 3, 4 months, it will be complete. And we're honored to have it here, and it's been—it's been very special.\\nWe've set a record on ticket sales, as you probably heard, already, even way before—long before the event itself. And we're working with Canada, and we're working with Mexico. And it's been a really spectacular—so far, it's been spectacular.\\nDaniel [Daniel Baldwin, One America News Network], do you have a question?\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. What are your expectations? You once said that the FIFA World Cup is an opportunity to put—a once-in-a-lifetime opportunity to put the greatness of the United States on display.\\nThe President. Well, I think—\\nQ. One billion eyeballs will be watching, Mr. President.\\nThe President. Yes, I—think——\\nQ. What will they here today?\\nThe President. Even today, I understand. I hear that, you know——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——I know we're a little late to get in there, but——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——that's okay.\\nMr. Infantino. They wait.\\nThe President. So all my friends, I guess they have to wait. They have no choice, right? [Laughter]\\nMr. Infantino. Yes, they wait.\\nThe President. But no, the numbers are incredible. I hear today's numbers are——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——very big. I hope CNN is covering this.\\nQ. One billion eyeballs.\\nMr. Infantino. Today, 1 billion eyeballs.\\nThe President. Today's numbers are very, very big.\\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize/The President's Foreign Policy\\nQ. We are covering it. And you're expected to get the FIFA Peace Prize, Mr. President. What would you say to people who say that prize might conflict with your pledge to strike Venezuela?\\nThe President. Well, I think the peace prize—I mean, I settled eight wars. I don't know that I'm getting it. I haven't been officially noticed. I've been hearing about a peace prize, and I'm here to represent our country in a different sense. But I can tell you, I did settle eight wars, and we have a ninth coming, but—which nobody has ever done before.\\nBut I want to really save lives. I don't need prizes. I need to save lives. And we're saving a lot of lives. And I've saved millions and millions of lives, and that's really what I want to do.\\nAnd I also want to run a great country. And the United States right now is the hottest country anywhere in the world. And 1 year ago, it was dead. We had a dead country, and now we have the hottest country anywhere in the world.\\nQ. Mr. President, will you——\\nThe President's Meeting With President Claudia Sheinbaum Pardo of Mexico and Prime Minister Mark Carney of Canada\\nQ. What are you going to discuss with Canada and Mexico, Mr.—what are you going to discuss with the leaders of Canada and Mexico?\\nThe President. Well, we're getting—we're going to meet with both. And we're getting along very well. You know, we're getting along very well. I don't know. I think we have a meeting set up for some time after the event.\\nQ. Will you discuss trade?\\nThe President. Yes, we'll discuss trade. We—get along very well.\\nThank you, everybody, very much.\\nQ. Will you pardon any other Honduran officials?\\nQ. Do you want them to keep trying to indict Ms. James?\\n\\nNOTE: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. In his remarks, he referred to Trey Yingst, chief foreign correspondent, Fox News Channel; Cristiano Ronaldo, forward for Saudi Pro League club Al-Nass and Portugal's national soccer team; and Lionel Messi, forward for Major League Soccer club Inter Miami and Argentina's national team. A reporter referred to New York State Attorney General Letitia James. The transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\n\\nSource URL: https://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/documents/remarks-exchange-with-reporters-prior-the-2026-federation-internationale-des-associations\\n\\n\\n[defendant] DX-3 GovInfo/OFR pre-event transcript excerpt\\nSource: GovInfo, DCPD202501162, Office of the Federal Register / National Archives and Records Administration.\\nURL: https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/DCPD-202501162/html/DCPD-202501162.htm\\nTitle: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\nEvent date: December 5, 2025.\\n\\nRelevant extracted page text:\\n\\\"Administration of Donald J. Trump, 2025\\\"\\n\\\"Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw December 5, 2025\\\"\\n\\\"[The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\\\"\\n\\nUnder the section \\\"The President's Interest in Soccer\\\":\\n\\\"Q. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\\\"\\n\\\"The President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\\\\\\\"football,\\\\\\\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\\\"\\n\\\"Thank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\\\"\\n\\nAdditional relevant extracted page text:\\n\\\"The President's Interest in Soccer\\\"\\n\\\"Q. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\\\"\\n\\\"The President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\\\"\\n\\\"Mr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\\\"\\n\\\"The President. But they have a little more speed. But no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\\\"\\n\\nGovInfo note:\\n\\\"NOTE: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. In his remarks, he referred to Trey Yingst, chief foreign correspondent, Fox News Channel; Cristiano Ronaldo, forward for Saudi Pro League club Al-Nass and Portugal's national soccer team; and Lionel Messi, forward for Major League Soccer club Inter Miami and Argentina's national team. A reporter referred to New York State Attorney General Letitia James. The transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\\"\\n\\nGovInfo content details page also identifies category \\\"Interviews With the News Media : Exchanges with reporters, Washington, DC,\\\" subjects including \\\"Federation Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) World Cup,\\\" \\\"John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts,\\\" and \\\"Soccer,\\\" and names including \\\"Ronaldo, Cristiano\\\" and \\\"Messi, Lionel.\\\"\\n\\n[defendant] DX-4 PRESMENTION/NEWMENTION terms\\n                                         NEWMENTION\\n\\nScope: These rules shall apply to this contract.\\n\\nUnderlying: The Underlying for this Contract is words used by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nRevisions to the Underlying made after Expiration will not be accounted for in determining the\\nExpiration Value.\\n\\nSource Agency: The Source Agencies are \\u003csource\\u003e.\\n\\nType: The type of Contract is an Event Contract.\\n\\nIssuance: After the initial Contract, Contract iterations will be listed on an as-needed basis at\\nthe discretion of the Exchange and corresponding to the risk management needs of Members.\\n\\n\\u003centity\\u003e: \\u003centity\\u003e refers to the speaker, writer, performer, or communicator specified by the\\nExchange. This may include (but is not limited to): a specific named individual, multiple\\nindividuals specified using AND/OR logic, an individual identified by position or title, a group,\\nband, team or collective entity, a specified member or members of a group, an organization,\\ncompany, or institutional entity, or any combination of the aforementioned.\\n\\nWhen \\u003centity\\u003e is defined by a position or title, the Contract tracks whoever holds that position\\nduring \\u003ctime period\\u003e, even if the individual holding the position changes. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a\\nspecific named individual, the identity remains consistent throughout. Name changes (e.g.,\\nstage names, married names) do not create a new entity. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a group or\\norganization and the Contract does not specify particular members, any official\\ncommunication or statement by any member or designated spokesperson counts. When using\\nAND logic, all specified entities must independently say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e. When\\nusing OR logic, at least one of the specified entities must say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nThe Exchange may specify additional conditions such as “at least X members of” a group or\\n“the majority of” a group.\\n\\n\\u003csource\\u003e: \\u003csource\\u003e refers to a Source Agency or ordered collection of Source Agencies\\nspecified by the Exchange at the time of Contract listing, which will be incorporated into the\\nSource Agency hierarchy above and used to determine the occurrence of the Underlying.\\n\\u003csource\\u003e may refer to a singular agency, multiple agencies, an agency by distinguishing\\ncharacteristics, by category or type (e.g., “official government statistical body,” “primary wire\\nservice”), or any combination thereof. When multiple agencies are specified, they may be\\napplied in the hierarchical order designated by the Exchange if so specified, with the highest-\\nranked available and responsive agency taking precedence for purposes of determining the\\nExpiration Value. A lower-ranked agency shall only be consulted if all higher-ranked agencies\\nare unavailable, unresponsive, have not reported on the Underlying by the Expiration time, or\\nif the Exchange, in its sole discretion, determines that a higher-ranked agency’s reporting is\\nincomplete, erroneous, or otherwise insufficient to determine the Expiration Value. If \\u003csource\\u003e\\ndesignates multiple agencies without specifying a hierarchical order, the Exchange shall\\nresolve any conflict between reporting agencies at its sole discretion.\\n\\n\\u003cword\\u003e: \\u003cword\\u003e refers to the particular word or phrase potentially to be mentioned by\\n\\u003centity\\u003e. It may refer to a word being said a minimum number of times. It may also refer to\\none of multiple words/phrases, any of which are acceptable (e.g., “Doge/Dogecoin”).\\n\\f\\u003ctime period\\u003e: \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific range of time, event or discrete date and\\ntime specified by the Exchange. This may be defined by, but is not limited to: a specific event\\nor context (e.g., “during the State of the Union address”), exact dates or times, relative time\\nmarkers (e.g., “before July 1, 2027,” “in Q1 2026”), event-based periods (e.g., “during any\\ncampaign rally in October 2026,” “during the awards ceremony”), and broader intervals (e.g.,\\n“Q1–Q2 2027,” “January–March 2026”).\\n\\nUnless stated otherwise, “Between” is inclusive of both endpoints, while “before” and “after”\\nexclude the specified date. \\u003ctime period\\u003e may also refer to “Any” or “None”, to multiple dates\\n(even if non-consecutive), or to a singular and discrete date or time.\\n\\nWhen \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event (such as an address, speech, performance, or\\nbroadcast), the Exchange may specify what is included, including whether it includes both live\\nand pre-recorded segments (including whether advertisements are included). Where a\\ntimezone is not specified, ET is assumed.\\n\\n\\nPayout Criterion: The Payout Criterion for the Contract encompasses the Expiration Values that\\n\\u003cword\\u003e is said by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n\\n\\nThe word must appear as a distinct, standalone unit, not buried inside another word. Plural\\nand possessive noun forms count. Other grammatical changes (tense, conjugation, derivation)\\ndo not. If \\u003cword\\u003e appears separated from other words by a space or hyphen or in a\\ncompound form with a space or hyphen, it counts. If \\u003cword\\u003e is fused into a single\\nunhyphenated word, it does not count.\\n\\nIf \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled, and the market contains a\\nstrike stating “Event does not qualify/occur”, such a strike shall resolve “Yes” and all others\\n“No”. If \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled but such strikes are NOT\\nlisted, the Contracts will resolve to the last fair price determined at the discretion of the\\nExchange. If the event is postponed, and such a postponement is announced by the end of the\\nfollowing calendar day to be rescheduled to a time within 14 calendar days, the markets shall\\nremain open. If the event captured in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast, the\\nExchange may keep the market open for 24 hours for the release of an official recording.\\nFurther granular details on conditions for these Contracts is available below.\\n\\nAdditional clarification(s):\\n\\n     Possessive noun forms of \\u003cword\\u003e, plurals, and possessive plural noun forms are\\n     INCLUDED:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigrants” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Egg” → “eggs’ shells” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Russia” → “Russia’s” counts, “Russian” does not\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e exists only in adjective form, no plural form exists:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Economic” → “Economics” does not count (“Economic” is an adjective\\n          for which “Economics” is not a plural)\\n     Plural nouns occurring within proper nouns and noun phrases are included:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Cat” → “Cats the musical” counts\\n\\f    Grammatical variations beyond plurals/possessives are NOT included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigration” does NOT count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Run” → “Running” or “Ran” do NOT count\\n    When \\u003cword\\u003e specifies a plural form, the singular does NOT count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Veterans” → “Veteran” does NOT count\\n    Words that are spelled the same as the plural form of \\u003cword\\u003e (if such exists) but are\\n    themselves not a plural noun are included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Wind” → “Winds up the clock” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Border” → “The United States has strong borders” counts\\n    Open compounds (words separated by spaces) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fire station” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “couch” → “couch potato” counts\\n    Hyphenated compounds (words connected by hyphens) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Palestine” → “pro-Palestine” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fat” → “non-fat” counts\\n    Closed compounds (single word, no spaces/hyphens) do not count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire” does not count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firefighter” does not count\\n    Multi-word \\u003cword\\u003e in larger constructions: When \\u003cword\\u003e is a multi-word phrase\\n    appearing within a hyphenated construction, it counts only if \\u003cword\\u003e appears as a\\n    complete, unmodified element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “New York” → “New York-based” counts (complete element)\\n    Portmanteaus (words blended from two words where parts of each are combined) are\\n    NOT included unless the portmanteau clearly contains \\u003cword\\u003e as a distinct, unaltered\\n    element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “MAGA” → “MAGA-nificent” counts (MAGA appears as distinct element)\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “magnificent” → “MAGA-nificent” does NOT count (portmanteau blend)\\n\\nDictionary determination: Both the Merriam-Webster Dictionary (available online) AND the\\nOxford English Dictionary shall be used to determine compound type and/or conventional\\nspelling patterns. Inclusion in either dictionary as an open or hyphenated compound shall\\nsatisfy the Payout Criterion. If neither provides clarity (or the word is not included),\\ndetermination is based on whether written as single unit (closed/doesn’t count) vs. spaces or\\nhyphens (open or hyphenated/counts) and/or context and previous usage.\\n\\nPHONETIC EQUIVALENCIES\\n\\n    Homophones (same sound, different spelling) do not count:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “write” → “right” does not count\\n    Homonyms and homographs (same spelling) COUNT regardless of meaning or\\n    pronunciation:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “bass” → both “bass guitar” and “bass fishing” count\\n    Proper and common nouns are treated identically:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Apple” → both “Apple Inc.” and “apple” (fruit) count\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Will” → both “Will Smith” and “I will go” count\\n    Minor unintentional mispronunciations COUNT if context makes intent clear:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Mamdani” → “Mandani” counts\\n    Severe mispronunciations that make \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable do NOT count.\\n    Trademarked spellings do not count, even when pronounced identically, unless the word\\n\\fitself is the same:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “lift” → “Lyft” (pronounced “lift”) does not count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “uber” → “Uber” counts\\nWords with non-standard transliteration to English count within reason, provided they are\\nphonetically equivalent:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Zelensky” → any of “Zelenski,” “Zelenskii,” “Zelensky,” or “Zelenskiy”\\n      count if pronounced equivalently\\nContractions do not count for their constituent words unless otherwise explicitly specified\\nby the Exchange:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “not” → “won’t,” “can’t,” “don’t,” “isn’t” do not count\\nNumbers spoken as words COUNT, when spoken exactly (not part of a larger number):\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “five” → saying “five” or reading “$5” aloud as “five dollars” counts,\\n      saying “five hundred” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “410” → “four hundred ten”, “four one zero” or “four ten” counts\\nOrdinals COUNT when \\u003cword\\u003e is written numerically OR a phrase that includes a\\nnumber:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “January 6” → “January 6th” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “3” (written numerically) → “3rd” (spoken as “third”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Eight War” → “8 Wars” and “Eighth War” will count\\nCardinal and ordinal number words are distinct:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “one” → “first” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “first” → “one” does NOT count\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count when pronunciation or letter-by-letter spelling\\nmatches \\u003cword\\u003e:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “NASA” (pronounced “NAH-suh”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “N-A-S-A” (spelled out) counts\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count as \\u003cword\\u003e when pronounced as the full word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Doctor” → “Dr.” (pronounced “Doctor”) counts\\nExpanded forms of acronyms do NOT count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “AI” → “artificial intelligence” does not count\\nWords in foreign languages do NOT count unless they are perfect cognates with an\\nEnglish word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fuego” (Spanish) does NOT count\\nEnglish words within foreign sentences count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “policy” → “Nuestra policy es clara” counts\\n\\u003cword\\u003e in organization/company names counts:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Securities” → “Bank of America Securities” counts\\nWords in URLs, emails, handles, and hashtags (exclusive of domain structure, email\\nprovider or symbols) are treated as compounds when spoken as complete words, with the\\ntype of compound subject to aforementioned rules:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firestation.com” pronounced “fire station dot com” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire.com” pronounced “wildfire dot com” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “apple” → “apple.com” pronounced “apple dot com” does count\\n      When presented in URL, email, handle, or hashtag form, \\u003cword\\u003e shall be treated as\\n      a compound, not a multi-word word\\nSung, rapped, or poetic words COUNT if phonetically recognizable:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “money” → “moneyyy” (extended in rap) counts\\n      Extreme distortion making \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable does NOT count.\\nPhonetic alphabet spelling (“Foxtrot India Romeo Echo” for “FIRE”) does NOT count.\\n\\fCANCELLATIONS AND DELAYS\\n\\n   The Exchange may list an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike for any Contract. If listed,\\n   such a strike refers to the structural conditions of the market, and is NOT adjudicated as a\\n   \\u003cword\\u003e needing to be said by or validated by having been said by \\u003centity\\u003e. If listed, this\\n   strike resolves to “Yes” whenever the event fails to occur or qualify under the Payout\\n   Criterion, or any other circumstance prevents normal resolution.\\n   If no such strike is listed, and \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, the following rules\\n   apply if the event is cancelled, postponed, rescheduled, or materially altered (including\\n   being closed to press) such that no video is released within one calendar day of the\\n   original start time of the event:\\n         If the event is cancelled, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price determined in\\n         the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         If the event is postponed or rescheduled, the outcome depends on whether a new\\n         date is publicly announced within one calendar day (i.e. if the event was scheduled\\n         to begin on Monday, any time up to 11:59PM on Tuesday falls within this period) of\\n         the originally scheduled start time:\\n               If no new date is announced within one calendar day, the Contract will resolve\\n               to the last fair price determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n               If a new date is announced within one calendar day, the outcome depends on\\n               when the rescheduled event is set to occur:\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls within fourteen (14) calendar days of the\\n                     originally scheduled date, the Contract shall remain open and \\u003cword\\u003e\\n                     stated during the rescheduled event will count.\\n                           The fourteen-day window begins at 12:00 AM ET on the originally\\n                           scheduled date and ends at 11:59 PM ET fourteen days later, unless\\n                           an alternate timezone is explicitly specified.\\n                           Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the State of the Union on January\\n                           15, 2026” rescheduled to January 20, 2026 → words spoken during\\n                           the rescheduled address count.\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls more than fourteen (14) calendar days after\\n                     the originally scheduled date, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price\\n                     determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         Any Contract that cannot be resolved through the Source Agency hierarchy will\\n         instead be settled at the Last Fair Price. The Exchange will disclose the methodology\\n         used to determine the Last Fair Price (e.g., Last Traded Price, Time-Weighted\\n         Average Price) at the time of Issuance.\\n         If an event begins but is interrupted, abbreviated, or ends prematurely, words\\n         stated by \\u003centity\\u003e during the portion of the event that did occur will count and the\\n         market will otherwise resolve.\\n   If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window but the venue, format, or medium\\n   changes (e.g., moved to a different location, changed from in-person to virtual (with the\\n   exception of being closed to press)), words stated during the event will count.\\n   Special condition: Across both cases, whether an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike is\\n   listed or not, if the event specified as or in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast (or\\n   relayed as such) but the live stream/broadcast does not occur, the Exchange will instead\\n   use an officially released recording as the Underlying, and may delay resolution by up to\\n   one calendar day to allow for the release of such a recording.\\n\\f          If partial snippets are released, Contracts on words that do not appear will be\\n          resolved to last fair price, and Contracts on those that do will be resolved to “Yes”.\\n          If no recording is released, the relevant outcomes triggered by the\\n          presence/absence of an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike shall occur as outlined\\n          above.\\n\\nTECHNICAL DETAILS (UNLESS OTHERWISE SPECIFIED)\\n\\n     When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, pre-recorded content broadcast,\\n     streamed, or published as part of that event is included if presented as part of the official\\n     presentation.\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the concert” with pre-recorded video interlude\\n          where entity speaks → words from interlude count\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the television appearance” with pre-taped\\n          segment aired during broadcast → words from segment count\\n     Behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are NOT\\n     included unless officially broadcast or published as part of \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n     Subtitles and captions that display \\u003cword\\u003e on screen but are not spoken aloud by\\n     \\u003centity\\u003e do NOT count.\\n     Sign language interpretation or usage by entity does NOT count as saying \\u003cword\\u003e unless\\n     the Contract explicitly specifies that sign language counts.\\n     Text that entity displays on screen (presentation slides, teleprompter visible to audience,\\n     signatures) does NOT count unless entity reads it aloud.\\n     Content generated by AI, deepfakes, or synthetic voice technology impersonating entity\\n     does NOT count unless the synthetic content is officially commissioned, authorized, or\\n     published by entity, OR the Contract explicitly specifies that AI-generated content counts.\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e is muted due to technical failure or censorship it shall not count unless\\n     corroborating contextual evidence (including surrounding speech, or an official\\n     uncensored recording or transcript) confirms that \\u003centity\\u003e specifically uttered \\u003cword\\u003e\\n     during the muted period.\\n\\nMinimum Tick: The Minimum Tick size for the Contract shall be $0.01.\\n\\nPosition Accountability Level: The Position Accountability Level for the Contract shall be\\n$25,000 per strike, per Member.\\n\\nLast Trading Date: The Last Trading Date of the Contract will be the Expiration Date. The Last\\nTrading Time will be the Expiration time.\\n\\nSettlement Date: The Settlement Date of the Contract shall be no later than the day after the\\nExpiration Date, unless the Market Outcome is under review pursuant to Rule 7.1.\\n\\nExpiration Date: When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event: The latest Expiration Date of\\nthe Contract shall be fourteen (14) calendar days after the originally scheduled date of the\\nevent. If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window, expiration will be moved to an\\nearlier date and time in accordance with Rule 7.2. When \\u003ctime period\\u003e is defined by specific\\ndates: The latest Expiration Date of the Contract shall be two weeks after the end of \\u003ctime\\nperiod\\u003e. If an event described in the Payout Criterion occurs and a consensus has been\\nreached on all terms, then expiration will be moved to an earlier date and time in accordance\\nwith Rule 7.2.\\n\\fExpiration time: The Expiration time of the Contract shall be 10:00 AM ET.\\n\\nSettlement Value: The Settlement Value for this Contract is $1.00.\\n\\nExpiration Value: The Expiration Value is the value of the Underlying as documented by the\\nSource Agency on the Expiration Date at the Expiration time.\\n\\nContingencies: Before Settlement, Kalshi may, at its sole discretion, initiate the Market\\nOutcome Review Process pursuant to Rule 7.1 of the Rulebook. If an Expiration Value cannot\\nbe determined on the Expiration Date, Kalshi has the right to determine payouts pursuant to\\nRule 7.1 in the Rulebook.\\n\\f\\n\\n[defendant] DX-5 Formal draw archive note\\nSource checked: Roll Call / Factba.se archive\\n\\nArchive title: Remarks: Donald Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing in Washington - December 5, 2025\\n\\nArchive URL: https://rollcall.com/factbase/trump/transcript/donald-trump-remarks-fifa-world-cup-drawing-december-5-2025/\\n\\nWhat this file establishes:\\n\\nThere is a separate archived transcript page for Trump's formal attendance remarks at the draw.\\n\\nWhat this file does not establish:\\n\\nThis session could not retrieve the full transcript text from that archive.  The page is password-protected.  This example therefore does not claim, from local files alone, whether the formal program transcript does or does not contain the word \\\"Ronaldo.\\\"\\n\\nWhy this matters:\\n\\nThe complaint does not need to prove that the formal program omitted the strike.  It needs to show that Trump said \\\"Ronaldo\\\" in event-linked remarks and that the market boundary reasonably includes those remarks.  The formal archive remains relevant because it marks the distinction between the pre-event reporter exchange and the formal program.\\n\\n\\n[defendant] DX-6 Formal Roll Call/Factba.se transcript extraction\\nSource: Roll Call / Factba.se\\nURL: https://rollcall.com/factbase/trump/transcript/donald-trump-remarks-fifa-world-cup-drawing-december-5-2025/\\nCaptured page title: Remarks: Donald Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing in Washington - December 5, 2025\\n\\nRendered page metadata excerpt:\\nTopics: Sport; Sport \\u003e Competition Discipline \\u003e Soccer; Lifestyle and Leisure \\u003e Leisure \\u003e Game.\\nEntities listed: bowl; deal; Donald J. Trump; FIFA World Cup; Mark Carney; place; President; trophy; United States; way.\\nSpeakers listed: Gianni Infantino, Donald Trump, Mark Carney, Claudia Sheinbaum.\\nSpeaker statistics excerpt: Donald Trump said 25 sentences of a total of 141 sentences; Donald Trump said 274 words of a total of 1009 words; Donald Trump talked 92 seconds of a total of 484 seconds.\\n\\nFormal transcript excerpt at start of draw:\\nMark Carney, 00:00:00-00:00:02: Thank you, my friend.\\nGianni Infantino, 00:00:50-00:01:22: So this is the World Cup trophy. This is the official bowl for the World Cup and we are now going to do the draw, ladies and gentlemen. But before that, as is customary, there is always a question that the moderator asks the draw assistant. So I would like to start with Mr. Carney. How big a deal is it to co-host the World Cup for Canada?\\n\\nFormal transcript excerpt of Trump's soccer answer:\\nDonald Trump, 00:03:14-00:03:32: Well, for years, Gianni, they've thought soccer or football would be so big, so fast. And I remember, I shouldn't say this because it was a long time ago, but I remember watching Pele play on a team called the Cosmos, Pele, who was fantastic, as you know. I assume one of the greats.\\n\\nText-extraction/search notes:\\nLocal Python urllib retrieval of the page returned HTTP 200 for the source URL and extracted approximately 175,864 characters of page text with Python html.parser. Case-sensitive searches in the extracted page text returned no occurrence of \\\"Ronaldo\\\" and no occurrence of \\\"Messi\\\". The same terms were not found using the browser page find function on the rendered page.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R1 Defendant formal transcript extraction for limited rebuttal use\\nSource: Roll Call / Factba.se\\nURL: https://rollcall.com/factbase/trump/transcript/donald-trump-remarks-fifa-world-cup-drawing-december-5-2025/\\nCaptured page title: Remarks: Donald Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing in Washington - December 5, 2025\\n\\nRendered page metadata excerpt:\\nTopics: Sport; Sport \\u003e Competition Discipline \\u003e Soccer; Lifestyle and Leisure \\u003e Leisure \\u003e Game.\\nEntities listed: bowl; deal; Donald J. Trump; FIFA World Cup; Mark Carney; place; President; trophy; United States; way.\\nSpeakers listed: Gianni Infantino, Donald Trump, Mark Carney, Claudia Sheinbaum.\\nSpeaker statistics excerpt: Donald Trump said 25 sentences of a total of 141 sentences; Donald Trump said 274 words of a total of 1009 words; Donald Trump talked 92 seconds of a total of 484 seconds.\\n\\nFormal transcript excerpt at start of draw:\\nMark Carney, 00:00:00-00:00:02: Thank you, my friend.\\nGianni Infantino, 00:00:50-00:01:22: So this is the World Cup trophy. This is the official bowl for the World Cup and we are now going to do the draw, ladies and gentlemen. But before that, as is customary, there is always a question that the moderator asks the draw assistant. So I would like to start with Mr. Carney. How big a deal is it to co-host the World Cup for Canada?\\n\\nFormal transcript excerpt of Trump's soccer answer:\\nDonald Trump, 00:03:14-00:03:32: Well, for years, Gianni, they've thought soccer or football would be so big, so fast. And I remember, I shouldn't say this because it was a long time ago, but I remember watching Pele play on a team called the Cosmos, Pele, who was fantastic, as you know. I assume one of the greats.\\n\\nText-extraction/search notes:\\nLocal Python urllib retrieval of the page returned HTTP 200 for the source URL and extracted approximately 175,864 characters of page text with Python html.parser. Case-sensitive searches in the extracted page text returned no occurrence of \\\"Ronaldo\\\" and no occurrence of \\\"Messi\\\". The same terms were not found using the browser page find function on the rendered page.\\n\\nSubmitted evidence:\\n[plaintiff arguments] GovInfo DCPD202501162 transcript excerpt and metadata (ev_3fc783920414_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-3fc783920414)\\nSource: https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/DCPD-202501162/html/DCPD-202501162.htm\\nSHA-256: `3fc783920414399098d86210070dd9fe83c14fe1dbded1a56a554f8f4b3448f2`\\nBytes: 2641\\nRelevance: Official government transcript source corroborating that Trump spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center before the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw and said the strike word Ronaldo in World-Cup-related remarks.\\n\\n[defendant arguments] Roll Call/Factba.se formal FIFA World Cup Drawing transcript extraction (ev_fbb53e87ccb3_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-fbb53e87ccb3)\\nSource: https://rollcall.com/factbase/trump/transcript/donald-trump-remarks-fifa-world-cup-drawing-december-5-2025/\\nSHA-256: `fbb53e87ccb3f4381fc2bdc06ac2f2a1ea3848aadde56122b22d34dfbdf4533b`\\nBytes: 2032\\nRelevance: Formal drawing-program transcript evidence showing a separate formal Draw source from the pre-event reporter exchange; the extracted page text contains no occurrence of Ronaldo or Messi, supporting defendant's event-boundary argument.\\n\\nTechnical reports:\\n[plaintiff] Plaintiff source and adverse-search ledger\\nChecked the visible case packet and then searched official/source-specific repositories. GovInfo DCPD202501162 was opened and preserved as submitted evidence; it corroborates the packet transcript, source metadata, location, event date, and Ronaldo passages. The Roll Call/Factba.se formal drawing page rendered despite the packet's password-protection note; browser find searches for 'Ronaldo,' 'Cristiano,' and 'Messi' returned no matches. Plaintiff therefore treats the formal-program transcript as an adverse boundary check, not as proof of a formal-stage mention. The remaining dispute is contractual scope: whether the market clearly excluded public event-linked venue remarks immediately before the formal program.\\n\\n[defendant] Defense source-check ledger\\nDefendant searched for the formal Roll Call/Factba.se transcript identified by the case packet, opened the rendered Roll Call page, and fetched it locally with Python urllib. The fetch returned HTTP 200 for the formal FIFA World Cup Drawing transcript page. Text extraction produced approximately 175,864 characters; searches for \\\"Ronaldo\\\" and \\\"Messi\\\" returned no occurrences. The retrieval also captured formal-program excerpts, including Infantino's statement that \\\"we are now going to do the draw\\\" and Trump's formal soccer answer mentioning Pele rather than Ronaldo. The focused extraction was submitted and accepted as ev_fbb53e87ccb3_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-fbb53e87ccb3.\\n\\nCall submit_council_vote with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated.\\nKeep the rationale brief: no more than three sentences.\\n\\nCouncil API instructions:\\nYou are a council member. Decide the proposition from the admitted record.\\nYou may examine admitted evidence through read-only tools when exact bytes, metadata, or exhibit contents matter.\\nDo not search the web, introduce new facts, create new evidence, or upload evidence.\\nWhen ready, call submit_council_vote exactly once with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated and a concise rationale.\\n\",\"state\":\"ready\",\"status\":\"ready\",\"tools\":[{\"description\":\"Return the current visible arbitration record for this council member.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"get_case\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"List visible immutable record evidence.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"list_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Return metadata and read limits for one visible evidence item.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"stat_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Read a bounded byte range from one visible evidence item as base64.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"length\":{\"minimum\":1,\"type\":\"integer\"},\"offset\":{\"minimum\":0,\"type\":\"integer\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\",\"offset\",\"length\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"read_evidence_range\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Submit one council vote for the current deliberation opportunity.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"rationale\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"vote\":{\"enum\":[\"demonstrated\",\"not_demonstrated\"],\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"vote\",\"rationale\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"submit_council_vote\",\"read_only\":false}],\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":false,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-29T19:58:02.156322961Z\",\"deliberation_round\":1,\"member_id\":\"C2\",\"opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C2\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"remaining_ms\":887183,\"role_id\":\"council\",\"turn_number\":10},\"wait\":{\"reason\":\"ready\",\"state_version\":12,\"version\":15}}"}],"structuredContent":{"after_opportunity_id":"deliberation:1:C2","after_version":15,"case_id":"arb-ex03-20260629192557","limits":{"attempts_max":3,"attempts_remaining":3,"max_evidence_read_bytes":65536,"max_evidence_read_bytes_per_opportunity":524288,"max_evidence_reads_per_opportunity":32,"max_response_bytes":131072,"remaining_evidence_read_bytes_for_opportunity":524288,"remaining_evidence_reads_for_opportunity":32},"member_id":"C2","message":"An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.","ok":true,"prompt":"Role: council member\nMember ID: C2\nDeliberation round: 1\nProposition: For the Kalshi market \"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\", the strike \"Ronaldo\" should resolve Yes because Trump said \"Ronaldo\" in public remarks at the World Cup Draw venue immediately before the formal program, and the market wording plus the governing mention-market terms did not clearly exclude those event-linked remarks.\nStandard of evidence: Preponderance of the evidence.\nPersona:\nYou are a careful juror and council member.\n\nEvaluate the record faithfully. Decide only from the evidence, the stated rules, and the applicable burden of proof. Do not favor either side, fill gaps with speculation, or ignore uncertainty.\n\nGive weight to reliable sources, direct evidence, consistent reasoning, and clear admissions. Discount unsupported claims, rhetorical force, irrelevant facts, and conclusions that exceed the record.\n\nWhen the evidence supports one answer, state it plainly. When the evidence is incomplete or balanced, say so. Be concise, honest, and exact.\n\nRecord:\nOpenings:\n[plaintiff] Council members, this case is not mainly about whether the syllables were spoken. The case-packet transcript says they were. The real dispute is the market boundary: when Kalshi asked what Trump would say \"during the FIFA World Cup Draw,\" did that phrase clearly exclude his public, event-linked remarks at the World Cup Draw venue immediately before the formal program? On this record, it did not.\n\nThe market page fixes the contract at issue: the public title was \"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\"; the contract family was PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION; the strike was \"Ronaldo\"; Kalshi challenged the resolution as No; and the requested resolution is Yes. That means the council's task is to apply the mention-market terms to that title and strike, not to import a narrower limitation that the market did not plainly announce.\n\nThe reporter-exchange packet is direct evidence on the word and setting. It is titled as remarks in an exchange with reporters prior to the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw, dated December 5, 2025. It places the President at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts, speaking with FIFA President Gianni Infantino and reporters in a sequence repeatedly labeled around the 2026 World Cup and the Draw. In that exchange, in a soccer discussion, Trump says he met Ronaldo, praises him, and uses \"Ronaldo\" as a distinct standalone word. Under the mention rules, a distinct standalone appearance of the strike is the kind of use that counts if it falls within the time period.\n\nThe terms matter because they do not say that an event market is limited only to scripted remarks from a formal stage segment. They define a time period as potentially an event or context, and they give the Exchange power to specify what is included when a time period refers to a specific event. They also distinguish official/public event content from behind-the-scenes, rehearsals, and unofficial recordings. That distinction helps plaintiff: the packet is not a rumor, rehearsal, private soundcheck, or leaked recording. It is a sourced public transcript of remarks at the event venue, immediately tied to the Draw. If Kalshi meant \"only the formal televised draw program after doors close\" or \"only remarks in the separate formal archive,\" it needed to say so clearly.\n\nI also want to be candid about what the packet does not yet prove. The formal-draw archive note says a separate archived transcript page exists for Trump's formal attendance remarks, but that the session could not retrieve the full text because the page was password-protected. So, at opening, plaintiff is not asking you to infer that the formal program itself contained \"Ronaldo.\" Nor does plaintiff need that inference. The Yes theory is that the qualifying period reasonably includes the public pre-program reporter exchange that was part of Trump's World Cup Draw appearance. The formal archive is relevant because it marks defendant's likely narrower boundary; it does not resolve the boundary in defendant's favor.\n\nProvenance and weight also favor treating the packet seriously at this stage. The market and terms files are system case-packet records. The reporter exchange includes a source URL to a public presidential transcript source and notes a corrected transcript date, while also acknowledging that some audio could not be verified because the audio was incomplete. That caveat may affect inaudible portions, but it does not erase the visible, contextual Ronaldo passage. Later, when evidence admission opens, the parties should preserve the official transcript source, any govinfo or Presidency Project copy, the market page capture, and any accessible formal-program transcript or video. The adverse check should ask whether the formal program omits the word, but omission there would matter only if the council first accepts the defense's artificially narrow reading of \"during.\"\n\nThe plaintiff's burden is preponderance. The record already points to a straightforward path to Yes: Trump, the specified entity, said the specified strike as a standalone word in public remarks linked to and immediately preceding the World Cup Draw at the venue; the market title and governing terms did not clearly exclude that event-linked exchange. On a fair reading of the contract the trader saw, the challenged No resolution should give way to Yes.\n\n[defendant] Council members, the defense opening is simple: this case is not won by proving that the word \"Ronaldo\" appears somewhere in a public transcript. The plaintiff must prove, by a preponderance, that the word was said during the market's specified event: the FIFA World Cup Draw.\n\nThe current packet leaves that critical link unproven. The market page does not say \"while Trump was at the venue,\" \"during a World Cup press availability,\" or \"during any remarks connected to the Draw.\" It says: \"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\" The challenged resolution was No. The requested Yes theory therefore needs more than event-adjacent context; it needs a boundary showing that the reporter exchange was part of the Draw period the market asked traders to price.\n\nThe plaintiff's own best transcript cuts against that boundary. The case-packet file is titled \"Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw.\" It says the President's remarks were joined in progress, and the source note says portions could not be verified because the audio was incomplete. It places Trump at the Kennedy Center and includes World Cup topics, and yes, it contains \"Ronaldo\" as a standalone word in a soccer exchange. But its title and structure identify those remarks as an exchange with reporters prior to the Draw, not the formal Draw itself.\n\nThe terms do not rescue plaintiff from that distinction. They define a mention market around words used by the entity during the time period. A time period may be a specific event, and when it is a specific event, the Exchange may specify what is included. The technical details also distinguish official presentation content from behind-the-scenes, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings unless those are officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. Those provisions do not mean every public, nearby, event-related conversation becomes part of the event. They make the event boundary the central question.\n\nThe formal-draw archive note reinforces why the distinction matters. It reports that there is a separate archived transcript page for Trump's formal attendance remarks at the FIFA World Cup Drawing, but that the full text was not retrieved because the page was password-protected. That note does not prove the formal program omitted Ronaldo. It also does not prove the formal program included it. What it does show, at opening, is that the record itself separates the pre-event reporter exchange from the formal drawing remarks.\n\nSo the defense will focus the council on proof of inclusion, not mere association. If later phases produce a market page provision, official broadcast record, program transcript, video metadata, or source-agency material showing that the red-carpet reporter exchange was officially part of the FIFA World Cup Draw presentation for this market, the council can weigh that. If the later evidence instead shows a formal program with a separate pre-program press availability, then the correct result is No even though the word was spoken nearby.\n\nOn this opening record, plaintiff has shown a Ronaldo mention in remarks prior to the event. Plaintiff has not shown that those remarks occurred during the market event. The defense position is that Kalshi's No resolution follows the market wording and the mention-market terms unless plaintiff supplies that missing boundary proof.\n\nArguments:\n[plaintiff] Council members, the merits question is whether the contract clearly limited “during the FIFA World Cup Draw” to only the formal staged ceremony. Plaintiff submits that it did not, and the record now proves the Yes result by a preponderance.\n\nFirst, the market itself is broad. PX-1 identifies the public question as “What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?”, contract family PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION, strike “Ronaldo,” challenged resolution No, and requested resolution Yes. The market page does not say “during the formal televised ceremony,” “on the main stage only,” or “excluding public remarks immediately before the program at the venue.” That absence matters because Kalshi drafted the boundary traders had to price.\n\nSecond, the word was said. PX-2, the case-packet transcript, and PX-5, the GovInfo/OFR source excerpt, both show Trump used “Ronaldo” as a standalone word in soccer-related remarks. PX-5 is especially useful on provenance: it is the GovInfo Compilation of Presidential Documents source, published by the Office of the Federal Register/NARA, for DCPD202501162. It identifies the same event date, title, and source note, and it places the remarks at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center. In the relevant passage, Trump says he met Ronaldo, then says Ronaldo is great; later, when asked whether he played soccer or football, Trump says he was not Ronaldo or Messi. Either use satisfies the mention rule if the remarks fall within the market’s time period.\n\nThird, the remarks are event-linked in the way the market title reasonably covers. PX-2 and PX-5 are not private gossip, rehearsal, or an unofficial leak. They are public presidential remarks at the World Cup Draw venue, with FIFA President Infantino present, repeatedly discussing the Draw, the World Cup, ticket sales, the Kennedy Center, the audience, and the imminent program. The transcript itself includes headings such as “2026 World Cup Draw Event,” “2026 World Cup Draw Event/John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts,” and “2026 World Cup Draw/Ticket Sales for World Cup.” Trump and Infantino even discuss being a little late to “get in there” and the audience waiting. That sequence is not a random earlier interview; it is part of the public event appearance immediately surrounding the Draw.\n\nFourth, PX-3’s terms do not impose defendant’s formal-only line. They say the underlying is words used by the entity during the specified time period; a time period may be an event or context; and, when a time period refers to a specific event, the Exchange may specify what is included. They also say official/published content presented as part of the official presentation can count, while behind-the-scenes, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings do not count unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. Those exclusions show what this is not. The transcript is an official published record of public remarks at the event venue, not a hidden backstage clip. Nothing in PX-1 or PX-3 clearly tells traders that public, event-linked venue remarks immediately before the formal program are out.\n\nDefendant’s best point is PX-4 and the formal Roll Call/Factba.se page: there is a separate formal-drawing transcript, and my search found no “Ronaldo” there. Plaintiff does not hide that. But that adverse point proves only that the narrower formal-program source may omit the strike. It does not answer the contractual question. If Kalshi had meant to resolve solely by that formal transcript, it could have said so. Instead, the public market title used the broader phrase “during the FIFA World Cup Draw,” and the mention terms leave event boundaries to what the market clearly specifies.\n\nOn burden, plaintiff does not need absolute certainty or a formal-stage mention. Plaintiff must show it is more likely than not that the market wording plus terms include the event-linked remarks. The evidence satisfies that standard: PX-1 gives no exclusion; PX-2 and PX-5 prove the standalone Ronaldo mentions in public World Cup Draw venue remarks; PX-3 supplies a flexible event/time-period framework and excludes only categories unlike this source; PX-4 merely identifies the defense’s alternate formal-program boundary. The fair resolution is Yes.\n\n[defendant] Council members, the record now makes the defense point sharper, not weaker. Plaintiff has proved that Trump said \"Ronaldo\" in an official transcript of remarks connected to the World Cup Draw. Plaintiff has not proved that those remarks were during the market event.\n\nStart with the contract. DX/PX-1 gives the trader-facing question: \"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\" It does not say \"at the Kennedy Center,\" \"on World Cup Draw day,\" \"in remarks prior to the Draw,\" or \"in any public press exchange associated with the Draw.\" For this strike to resolve Yes, the relevant mention must fall inside that specified time period.\n\nThe strongest evidence of the Ronaldo utterance is also the strongest evidence against plaintiff's boundary. PX-2 and PX-5 are titled \"Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw.\" PX-5, plaintiff's GovInfo/OFR source, confirms the same title, says the remarks were joined in progress, identifies the source as an exchange with the news media, and notes that some portions could not be verified because the audio was incomplete. That evidence proves an official pre-event reporter transcript. It does not prove the reporter exchange was the FIFA World Cup Draw.\n\nThe terms, PX-3, require words used by the entity during the specified time period. They permit an event or context as a time period, and they discuss what is included when the time period is a specific event. That framework does not turn all event-adjacent speech into event speech. The distinction between official presentation content and non-included behind-the-scenes or unofficial content matters because the question is not just whether a record is public or official. The question is whether this source was part of the market's event period. A public official transcript can still be a transcript of remarks prior to the event.\n\nDX-2 supplies the missing contrast. It is a focused extraction from the separate Roll Call/Factba.se formal FIFA World Cup Drawing transcript. That page is the formal source identified in the case-packet archive note. It is titled \"Remarks: Donald Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing in Washington - December 5, 2025.\" Its transcript begins with the formal drawing participants; at 00:00:50, Infantino says, \"This is the World Cup trophy\" and \"we are now going to do the draw.\" The page's Trump soccer answer mentions Pele and the Cosmos, not Ronaldo. The extracted page text was searched for both \"Ronaldo\" and \"Messi\" and neither appears.\n\nThat does not prove Trump never said Ronaldo anywhere at the venue. It proves the opposite boundary from plaintiff's: the formal Draw transcript is separate from the pre-event reporter exchange, and the formal transcript does not contain the strike. Plaintiff needs a bridge between those two sources. It has not offered one. There is no market page detail saying red-carpet or pre-program press remarks count. There is no official program metadata showing the reporter exchange was part of the Draw presentation. There is no source hierarchy provision selecting the pre-event reporter exchange over the formal Draw transcript for this market.\n\nPlaintiff argues ambiguity should favor Yes because Kalshi could have drafted a narrower rule. But this is a preponderance case about a challenged No resolution, not a penalty for every conceivable ambiguity. The ordinary reading of \"during the FIFA World Cup Draw\" is the draw program, not every public appearance immediately before it. The record's own labels preserve that ordinary line: \"Prior to\" on the Ronaldo source; \"Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing\" on the formal source; and a formal transcript that starts the draw and omits the strike.\n\nWeight and provenance also favor the defense on the decisive issue. PX-5 is official and useful, but it authenticates a pre-event reporter exchange. DX-2 is a captured formal transcript extraction from the source class identified in PX-4; its absence finding is limited but material. PX-4 was initially only a note that the formal page existed and could not be retrieved. We have now retrieved and searched it. The adverse check therefore confirms, rather than merely speculates, that the formal drawing transcript does not carry plaintiff's Ronaldo mention.\n\nThe council should resolve the proposition against plaintiff. The record shows Trump said Ronaldo before the FIFA World Cup Draw in an event-linked reporter exchange. It does not show he said Ronaldo during the FIFA World Cup Draw. On this market wording and these terms, the challenged No resolution should stand.\n\nRebuttals:\n[plaintiff] Council members, defendant’s new formal-transcript extraction proves less than defendant needs.\n\nPlaintiff accepts the narrow fact defendant has now preserved: the Roll Call/Factba.se formal drawing-program extraction contains no “Ronaldo” or “Messi.” That is why plaintiff did not build the case on a formal-stage mention. The proposition instead asks whether the market wording and mention terms clearly excluded Trump’s public, official, event-linked remarks at the venue immediately before the formal program. Defendant has not supplied that exclusion.\n\nDefendant’s argument treats the title “Prior to the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw” as if “prior to” automatically means outside the Kalshi market’s event period. But PX-1 does not say “formal transcript only,” “after the draw host begins,” “after 00:00:50,” or “excluding press availability at the venue.” It asks what Trump would say “during the FIFA World Cup Draw.” The source label tells us sequence; it does not tell us the market’s legal boundary.\n\nDX-2 actually illustrates why defendant’s bright line is chosen after the fact. In defendant’s own formal extraction, the page begins before the mechanical draw: Mark Carney speaks at 00:00:00, and Infantino says at 00:00:50, “we are now going to do the draw.” If “during the FIFA World Cup Draw” can include ceremony and preamble on the formal page before the draw itself begins, then the phrase is not self-defining down to a single moment or transcript. The question is what the market clearly specified. It did not specify defendant’s transcript-only rule.\n\nThe terms do not fill that gap for defendant. PX-3 excludes hidden categories such as rehearsals, sound checks, unofficial recordings, and behind-the-scenes content unless officially published as part of the period. PX-2 and PX-5 are not those categories. PX-5 is an official GovInfo/OFR presidential transcript, published with source metadata, at 11:13 a.m. at the Kennedy Center, with FIFA’s president present and the World Cup Draw repeatedly discussed. That gives the Ronaldo mentions strong provenance and an event connection; it does not make them informal backstage chatter.\n\nDefendant says plaintiff needs a bridge. The bridge is the market text plus the terms’ failure to draw the narrow line defendant proposes. A No resolution can stand only if the contract fairly told traders that “during the FIFA World Cup Draw” meant only the separate formal-program transcript. On this record, the more likely reading is broader: public, official remarks at the venue, immediately tied to and immediately preceding the World Cup Draw program, were within the event-linked period unless clearly excluded.\n\nSo DX-2 narrows one factual issue but does not decide the case. It shows no formal-stage Ronaldo mention. It does not show that the market excluded the official pre-program event remarks where Trump did say Ronaldo. Under the preponderance standard, the Yes resolution remains the fair one.\n\nSurrebuttals:\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff’s rebuttal usefully narrows the dispute. Plaintiff accepts that the formal Roll Call/Factba.se drawing transcript contains no “Ronaldo” or “Messi.” So the case remains entirely about whether a separate reporter exchange titled “Prior to the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw” should be treated as inside the market period.\n\nPlaintiff says “prior to” is only sequence, not legal boundary. But sequence is exactly what the market phrase makes material. The contract asks what Trump would say “during the FIFA World Cup Draw.” A source-agency title identifying the Ronaldo transcript as an exchange with reporters prior to that Draw is not a stray label; it is the best record description of when and what that source is. Plaintiff cannot convert that source into the event itself by saying the market failed to list every excluded pre-event setting.\n\nPlaintiff’s formal-preamble point also does not carry the burden. Yes, the formal transcript begins before the mechanical ball selection, and Infantino says at 00:00:50 that “we are now going to do the draw.” But that supports the defense distinction. A host’s preamble inside the formal drawing transcript is part of the program. A separate press exchange, separately titled and sourced as prior to the Draw, is not made part of the program simply because it happened nearby and discussed the same event.\n\nNor does official publication settle the issue. PX-5 strengthens provenance: Trump did say Ronaldo in an official public transcript. But provenance answers whether the words were said, not whether they were said during the market’s specified event. The terms require both: the word by the entity, and the word during the time period. Plaintiff has the first element. The second is still missing.\n\nThe remaining bridge plaintiff proposes is essentially: public, official, event-linked, and not expressly excluded. That is not enough under a preponderance standard when the same record supplies a cleaner boundary: the Ronaldo source is prior to the Draw, and the formal Draw source omits the strike. The challenged No resolution should stand.\n\nClosings:\n[plaintiff] Council members, the record has narrowed to one real issue.\n\nThe word is proven. The market page identifies the strike as “Ronaldo” and the challenged resolution as No. The case-packet transcript and the GovInfo/OFR excerpt prove that Trump said “Ronaldo” as a standalone word in public remarks at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center, in a World Cup Draw setting, with FIFA President Infantino present, and amid repeated discussion of the Draw, the Kennedy Center, ticket sales, the audience, and the imminent event. That is strong provenance: GovInfo, NARA/OFR, DCPD202501162, matching the packet source and note.\n\nDefendant has also proved its best fact. The Roll Call/Factba.se formal-program extraction does not contain “Ronaldo” or “Messi.” Plaintiff does not ask you to find otherwise. If the market had said “only the formal drawing transcript,” defendant would win. But that is not the market traders saw.\n\nThe market asked: “What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?” It did not say “during the formal transcript only,” “after the host announces the draw has begun,” “excluding public press remarks at the venue,” or “excluding remarks immediately before the program.” The governing terms do not add that limitation. They define words used by the entity during the time period, allow event/context time periods, and exclude categories such as rehearsals, sound checks, behind-the-scenes content, and unofficial recordings. Plaintiff’s source is none of those. It is an official public presidential transcript of event-linked remarks at the venue.\n\nDefendant’s formal extraction shows why a bright line cannot simply be assumed. Even on that page, before balls are drawn, there is ceremony, introduction, and Infantino saying “we are now going to do the draw.” Event boundaries are not self-defining. The question is whether Kalshi clearly chose defendant’s narrower boundary. The record contains no such choice.\n\nSo the burden is met. More likely than not, a reasonable reading of the market and terms includes Trump’s official, public, venue-based remarks immediately tied to the World Cup Draw. The strongest contrary evidence proves only that a narrower formal transcript omits the strike. It does not prove the contract excluded the remarks where the strike was actually said.\n\nThe challenged No resolution should be overturned. The strike “Ronaldo” should resolve Yes.\n\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff’s closing concedes the decisive factual split: the formal World Cup Drawing transcript contains no “Ronaldo” or “Messi.” The only Ronaldo evidence is the separate official transcript titled “Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw.”\n\nThat is enough to decide the case. The market did not ask what Trump would say at the Kennedy Center, on World Cup Draw day, in public presidential remarks, or in event-linked press availability. It asked what Trump would say “during the FIFA World Cup Draw.” The terms require the word to be used by the entity during the specified time period. Plaintiff has proven the word and the speaker. It has not proven the time period.\n\nPlaintiff’s strongest point is that the market did not expressly say “formal transcript only” or “exclude pre-program remarks.” But plaintiff has the burden. A challenged No resolution does not become Yes merely because the contract could have been even more verbose. The record must make it more likely than not that the pre-event reporter exchange was inside the market period. The record does the opposite.\n\nThe source labels matter. PX-2 and PX-5 are official and probative, but they are official proof of remarks prior to the Draw. The formal Roll Call/Factba.se extraction is the source for Trump’s formal attendance at the FIFA World Cup Drawing; it begins the program, includes the draw presentation, and omits the strike. Plaintiff’s theory asks you to treat a separate prior reporter exchange as “during” the Draw even though the formal Draw source exists and does not contain the word.\n\nThe terms do not collapse that distinction. They recognize event/context time periods and official presentation content, but they still require the word to occur during the chosen time period. Official publication proves provenance. Event connection proves relevance. Neither proves inclusion. A public official transcript can be accurately preserved and still be outside the market window if it is, as titled, prior to the event.\n\nSo the fair synthesis is narrow and grounded: Trump said Ronaldo in event-linked public remarks before the FIFA World Cup Draw; Trump did not say Ronaldo in the formal drawing transcript preserved in this record; and no admitted market term or source-chain evidence bridges the pre-event exchange into the market’s “during the FIFA World Cup Draw” period.\n\nUnder the preponderance standard, plaintiff has not carried the proposition. The challenged No resolution should stand.\n\nExhibits:\n[plaintiff] PX-1 Market page and challenged resolution\nMarket URL: https://kalshi.com/markets/kxtrumpmentionb/trump-mention-b/kxtrumpmentionb-25dec06\n\nPublic market title: What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\n\nContract family: PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION\n\nStrike at issue: Ronaldo\n\nChallenged resolution: No\n\nRequested resolution: Yes\n\n\n[plaintiff] PX-2 Pre-event reporter exchange transcript\nRemarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\nDecember 05, 2025\n\n[The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\nThe President. It's a great honor to be here. Gianni has done a fantastic job. We're setting records—[inaudible].\nQ. [Inaudible]\nThe President. Well, I think so. They have a little bit of a shot. Pretty stiff competition. But I would say they would have a small chance.\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize\nQ. [Inaudible]—win the FIFA Peace Award?\nThe President. Well, it would be an honor.\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\nQ. Will you root for some selection? Will you root for someone?\nThe President. Well, I root for a lot of countries, but in this case, I'll be rooting for the U.S.A. [Laughter]\nQ. [Inaudible]\nThe President. That's great. That's great. We really love it.\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize\nQ. Mr. President, have you been told that you are going to receive the inaugural peace prize today——\nThe President. I have not——\nQ. ——from FIFA?\nThe President. I have not been told. There's a rumor about it, but I have not been told. That would be a great honor, and I'm a big fan of Gianni, as you know.\nQ. What can fans expect——\nQ. Are you hoping to receive that?\nThe President. Excuse me.\nQ. Are you hoping to receive the peace prize?\nThe President. Well, I don't like to say \"hope,\" but it would be a great honor.\n2026 World Cup\nQ. What can fans expect of, like, the World Cup in the U.S.?\nThe President. I think it's going to be fantastic. We've set every record you can set.\nQ. What are you telling people who are worried——\nFédération Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) President Giovanni V. Infantino\nQ. [Inaudible]—friend Gianni—[inaudible]—a word about him?\nThe President. I think he has done a fantastic job.\nThe President's Schedule\nQ. Are you going to be meeting with the President of Mexico today and the——\nThe President. We might. Yes.\nQ. ——Prime Minister of Canada as well?\nThe President. I might. I might do that.\nQ. Will you be discussing immigration and trade with them?\nThe President. Yes, we'll be discussing.\n[At this point, the President and Mr. Infantino posed for photographs.]\nThe President. Thank you, everybody.\n2026 World Cup Draw Event/John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts\nQ. Mr. President, what do you think about the crowd?\nThe President. Oh, look, the new star—[inaudible].\nCongratulations.\nQ. Thank you.\nThe President. You're the new star of television and Fox.\nQ. Thank you. How are you doing, Mr. President?\nThe President. I'm doing very well.\nQ. What do you think about the crowd here?\nThe President. I think the crowd is great, and I think the building is great. We've made a lot of improvements over the last 6 months. Taking—the Kennedy Center was in very bad shape. Now it's getting to be really good. And in 6 months, it's going to be incredible with the improvements we've made.\nQ. The first time for the U.S. to host since the nineties.\nThe President. Right.\nQ. Are you ready for it?\nThe President. I'm ready for it, and they're ready for it. And Gianni, who you know——\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\nThe President. ——has done a fantastic job with FIFA. And we're looking to have—you know, we're set—we have already set records for tickets sales. I don't think there's ever been anything like it in any sport. And so, I want to congratulate you.\nMr. Infantino. Thank you.\nThe President. I don't even have to wait. But major records have been set.\nHow are you?\nQ. Good, how are you, sir?\nThe President. Nice to see you.\nQ. Today it's not football—American football. It's soccer. It's——\nThe President. Right.\nQ. ——the big event of soccer.\nThe President. That's right. That's right.\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\nQ. So can you tell me about this big day today?\nThe President. It's just a big day, and it's a great sport. And it really is coming to America. And never—nobody ever thought a thing like this could happen. And I'm very happy to say that we've already set the alltime record on ticket sales long before the first ball is kicked. Right?\nMr. Infantino. A hundred percent. One hundred percent.\n2026 World Cup Host Cities\nQ. You've had some concerns about crime in American cities, some of the cities that will be hosting. Have they remedied that for you? Are you still considering maybe asking FIFA to move some of those cities?\nThe President. No, I don't want to do that. But I will tell you, if they do have a problem, by the time we get there, we'll take care of that problem. We can solve that problem.\nI've proven that in DC and everywhere else we went, so we'll take care of that very easily. So, if they have a problem, hopefully, they'll let us know that, and we will solve any problem.\nOkay? Thank you.\nQ. Thank you so much.\nMr. Infantino. All right, thank you so much.\nQ. Thank you, Mr. President.\nQ. Thank you. Appreciate it.\nThe President. Congratulations.\n2026 World Cup\nQ. Mr. President, Brazilian television. America will be hosting the World Cup and the Olympics in 2 years. How important it is—[inaudible]?\nThe President. I think very. It's a great honor. I think Gianni is doing a phenomenal job. We've set every record on ticket sales. It's been really fantastic. But Gianni has done an unbelievable job with FIFA.\nThe President's Experience With Soccer\nQ. [Inaudible]\nThe President. He was a great—not only that. I got to see a man name Pelé play—right?—that tells you how old I am—when he was on the Cosmos. Do you remember that a long time ago? And it was quite a treat. That was quite an event. And he was—not only was he playing, he was great. He scored two goals, I think. And so, I was one of the few who got to see Pelé, and I assume he is one of your alltime greats. Right?\nMr. Infantino. Definitely.\nThe President. So I got to see him.\nThe President's Favorite World Cup Competitor\nQ. Do you have some favorite teams for World Cup?\nThe President. Well, I have a favorite. It's the U.S.A. [Laughter] I don't know what their chances are, Gianni, but maybe the U.S.A. is the——\nMr. Infantino. They're getting better and better, actually.\nThe President. I think they'll do well.\nMr. Infantino. They are getting better and better.\nThe President. I think they'll do well.\nThank you very much, everybody.\nQ. Thank you so much.\n2026 World Cup\nQ. Mr. President, World Cup in America just means—[inaudible]. So what do you expect from this World Cup?\nThe President. [Inaudible]—record business and only in the United States, but we're also doing record ticket sales with FIFA. And they've already bought—beat their highest record. And we—you know, this a long time before the first ball is kicked. You've sold more tickets than they've ever done before, and better pricing than they've ever gotten before. It's a tremendous success. And it's an honor. And Gianni has done a phenomenal job with FIFA.\nQ. [Inaudible]—ever?\nThe President. I think so. I think it's going to be—I mean, ideally, you want to see that every year. Every 4 years, it gets bigger and better. I think we have set every record in the book. We're very happy about it.\nThank you.\nThe President's Favorite World Cup Competitor\nQ. [Inaudible]—part of America. Who are you going to support as well?\nThe President. Well, I think I have to support U.S.A. Otherwise, I'd be in trouble. I wouldn't be President for long.\nMr. Infantino. [Inaudible]\nThe President. [Inaudible]—but you have a lot of great teams. You're going to have a lot of great teams.\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\"football,\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\n2026 World Cup Draw/Ticket Sales for World Cup\nQ. How does it feel to be part of this amazing event? And obviously, your being a part of participating in all the—[inaudible]?\nThe President. The President of Mexico is here, and she's doing a very good job. She's a good woman, very, very excellent job. It's an honor, and we're setting every record, and you're helping us set those records.\nMr. Infantino. And we will do it.\nThe President. You know, Mexico and Canada are helping us set those records. But as you know, we have a record in ticket sales already, long before the first ball is kicked, and we're going to do great.\nI think that Gianni—as you know, he's the head, and he has done a fantastic job.\nU.S. Cooperation With Mexico and Canada\nQ. And how is the biggest challenge being three countries?\nThe President. Well, I think that—do you mean for the three countries?\nWell, they've gotten together really well, I mean.\nMr. Infantino. All right.\nThe President. They're getting along very well.\nMr. Infantino. Collaboration is fantastic between the three.\nThe President's Interest in Soccer/2026 World Cup\nQ. And you like soccer?\nThe President. I do. I like it. I like it more and more.\nQ. Yes?\nThe President. I like it. It's growing in this country—very, really—I mean, someday, maybe it's going to be bigger than anything else.\nMr. Infantino. We'll have to become number one.\nThe President. I will say this——\nMr. Infantino. Definitely.\nThe President. ——the ticket sales——\nQ. Definitely will happen.\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\nThe President. Ticket sales are bigger than anything we have ever done in the history of the country, in terms of sports.\nMr. Infantino. For certain.\nQ. And the audience is going to be huge.\nThe President. The audience is going to be tremendous.\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\nThe President. Yes.\nMr. Infantino. Six billion people.\nThe President. [Inaudible]\nQ. Six billion? That's amazing.\nMr. Infantino. Six billion people.\nAnd today, one billion.\nQ. Wow.\nMr. Infantino. [Inaudible]\nQ. Enjoy show time. Thank you so much.\nThe President. [Inaudible]\nQ. Mr. President, how are you? Just a quick—[inaudible].\nQ. This is for Telemundo.\nThe President. How are you?\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\nQ. Hello, Mr. President. How are you? This for Telemundo.\nThe President. How are you? Good.\nQ. How are you?\nThe President. Very good. Thank you.\nQ. How does it feel to have the most important event of sports—that global—in the U.S.?\nThe President. Well, we do. And right at the Kennedy Center. I'm Chairman of the Kennedy Center. And I hear the Kennedy Center is doing a very good job, so it feels great. Really good.\nAnd Telemundo is doing a good job, too. Thank you.\nQ. Thank you.\n2026 World Cup\nQ. What is the significance of hosting the FIFA World Cup this year?\nThe President. It's a—in terms of sports, I would say the ultimate. There is no sport like this. It's the biggest sport in the world. And we are setting every record. You know, our ticket sales have gone and set every—every sport—no matter what it is, we've set the record. So—and every though it's very early, there's no ball being kicked yet, but we've already set a ticket sales record.\nArgentina National Team\nQ. How do you see Argentinean team for this World Cup?\nThe President. Well, I love Argentina. And your President is doing a very good job, as you know. Milei. You know that right? It's make Argentina great again. MAGA.\nQ. And——\nU.S. National Team\nQ. Do you think the States are building a powerful team for next year?\nThe President. Who?\nQ. The States.\nThe President. Oh, yes. Sure. I—you're going to have a lot of powerful teams. Everybody has a lot of powerful teams, but you're going to have a lot of great teams. [Inaudible]\nU.S. Role in Hosting the 2026 World Cup\nQ. Mr. President, what does it mean for you guys to host the World Cup right here in the U.S.?\nThe President. I'm honored to host it. It's a great honor. I mean, it's turned out to be bigger than we thought. We're setting a record for ticket sales, the likes of which no sport has ever seen before.\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\nThe President. But they have a little more speed.\nBut no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\nPopularity of Soccer in Latin America\nQ. Mr. President, a message for the Latin America and soccer fans?\nThe President. Yes, I am. And Latin America is great. And they have great soccer. So, good luck in the matches.\n[A reporter asked a question in Spanish, which was translated by an interpreter as follows.]\nU.S. Visas for World Cup Ticketholders\nQ. Who is going to be in—[inaudible]—about these visas for the—these fans that want to come here to the World Cup?\nThe President. Well, we're going to make it very easy for them. We're working on that right now. We're going to make it very easy. It's going to be a very easy process.\nQ. Okay. Say, hi to Colombia over there.\nThe President. Hello. Is that Colombia?\nQ. Yes.\nThe President. I love Colombia. Hello, Colombia. [Laughter]\nQ. Okay. Okay. Muy bien.\nThe President. So where are you from?\nQ. Paraguay.\nThe President. Oh.\nQ. He's from Paraguay. Yes.\nThe President. Very good. I love it. I—it's a beautiful country. We get along very well with them. We do a little trade deal with them, and they like us. And that's what's happening.\nQ. Panama.\nThe President. Where?\nVery good. I like the canal. [Laughter] That canal is pretty good.\n[A reporter spoke in Spanish; no translation was provided.]\n2026 World Cup\nThe President. What?\nQ. [Inaudible]\nThe President. Well, it's going to be incredible. The event is going to be very good. Just this event alone—it's at the Kennedy Center. I see you have it fixed up perfectly.\nMr. Infantino. It will set the tone.\nThe President. Right? It's beautiful.\nMr. Infantino. It's beautiful.\nThe President. It's a beautiful place.\nHave a good time.\nQ. [Inaudible]\nThe President.\n[A reporter spoke in Spanish; no translation was provided.]\nMr. Infantino. No, gracias. [Inaudible]\nThe President. It's great.\nJohn F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts/Renovation Work\nQ. Mr. President, the U.S. press?\nThe President. Thank you, everybody, very much. It's a great honor. This has been an honor for a lot of reasons. Number one, they've sold more tickets than any event has ever sold already—long before the kickoff.\nAnd number two, we've done a lot of work at the Kennedy Center. It was falling apart, and now it's pretty much back. And we'll get it back within the next 4 or 5 months through construction, and—but you see the way it looks.\nAnd Gianni is just telling me—who's done an incredible job, by the way. He's just telling, you know, how good a job we've done.\nMr. Infantino. That's right.\nThe President. You can look at the walls. The marble was broken. Everything was a mess. And we've really taken the Kennedy Center—a lot of people thought it was going to be ripped down, and we did just the opposite. So we've done a really great renovation job on it. And over the next 3, 4 months, it will be complete. And we're honored to have it here, and it's been—it's been very special.\nWe've set a record on ticket sales, as you probably heard, already, even way before—long before the event itself. And we're working with Canada, and we're working with Mexico. And it's been a really spectacular—so far, it's been spectacular.\nDaniel [Daniel Baldwin, One America News Network], do you have a question?\n2026 World Cup\nQ. What are your expectations? You once said that the FIFA World Cup is an opportunity to put—a once-in-a-lifetime opportunity to put the greatness of the United States on display.\nThe President. Well, I think—\nQ. One billion eyeballs will be watching, Mr. President.\nThe President. Yes, I—think——\nQ. What will they here today?\nThe President. Even today, I understand. I hear that, you know——\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\nThe President. ——I know we're a little late to get in there, but——\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\nThe President. ——that's okay.\nMr. Infantino. They wait.\nThe President. So all my friends, I guess they have to wait. They have no choice, right? [Laughter]\nMr. Infantino. Yes, they wait.\nThe President. But no, the numbers are incredible. I hear today's numbers are——\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\nThe President. ——very big. I hope CNN is covering this.\nQ. One billion eyeballs.\nMr. Infantino. Today, 1 billion eyeballs.\nThe President. Today's numbers are very, very big.\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize/The President's Foreign Policy\nQ. We are covering it. And you're expected to get the FIFA Peace Prize, Mr. President. What would you say to people who say that prize might conflict with your pledge to strike Venezuela?\nThe President. Well, I think the peace prize—I mean, I settled eight wars. I don't know that I'm getting it. I haven't been officially noticed. I've been hearing about a peace prize, and I'm here to represent our country in a different sense. But I can tell you, I did settle eight wars, and we have a ninth coming, but—which nobody has ever done before.\nBut I want to really save lives. I don't need prizes. I need to save lives. And we're saving a lot of lives. And I've saved millions and millions of lives, and that's really what I want to do.\nAnd I also want to run a great country. And the United States right now is the hottest country anywhere in the world. And 1 year ago, it was dead. We had a dead country, and now we have the hottest country anywhere in the world.\nQ. Mr. President, will you——\nThe President's Meeting With President Claudia Sheinbaum Pardo of Mexico and Prime Minister Mark Carney of Canada\nQ. What are you going to discuss with Canada and Mexico, Mr.—what are you going to discuss with the leaders of Canada and Mexico?\nThe President. Well, we're getting—we're going to meet with both. And we're getting along very well. You know, we're getting along very well. I don't know. I think we have a meeting set up for some time after the event.\nQ. Will you discuss trade?\nThe President. Yes, we'll discuss trade. We—get along very well.\nThank you, everybody, very much.\nQ. Will you pardon any other Honduran officials?\nQ. Do you want them to keep trying to indict Ms. James?\n\nNOTE: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. In his remarks, he referred to Trey Yingst, chief foreign correspondent, Fox News Channel; Cristiano Ronaldo, forward for Saudi Pro League club Al-Nass and Portugal's national soccer team; and Lionel Messi, forward for Major League Soccer club Inter Miami and Argentina's national team. A reporter referred to New York State Attorney General Letitia James. The transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\n\nSource URL: https://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/documents/remarks-exchange-with-reporters-prior-the-2026-federation-internationale-des-associations\n\n\n[plaintiff] PX-3 PRESMENTION/NEWMENTION terms\n                                         NEWMENTION\n\nScope: These rules shall apply to this contract.\n\nUnderlying: The Underlying for this Contract is words used by <entity> <time period>.\nRevisions to the Underlying made after Expiration will not be accounted for in determining the\nExpiration Value.\n\nSource Agency: The Source Agencies are <source>.\n\nType: The type of Contract is an Event Contract.\n\nIssuance: After the initial Contract, Contract iterations will be listed on an as-needed basis at\nthe discretion of the Exchange and corresponding to the risk management needs of Members.\n\n<entity>: <entity> refers to the speaker, writer, performer, or communicator specified by the\nExchange. This may include (but is not limited to): a specific named individual, multiple\nindividuals specified using AND/OR logic, an individual identified by position or title, a group,\nband, team or collective entity, a specified member or members of a group, an organization,\ncompany, or institutional entity, or any combination of the aforementioned.\n\nWhen <entity> is defined by a position or title, the Contract tracks whoever holds that position\nduring <time period>, even if the individual holding the position changes. When <entity> is a\nspecific named individual, the identity remains consistent throughout. Name changes (e.g.,\nstage names, married names) do not create a new entity. When <entity> is a group or\norganization and the Contract does not specify particular members, any official\ncommunication or statement by any member or designated spokesperson counts. When using\nAND logic, all specified entities must independently say <word> during <time period>. When\nusing OR logic, at least one of the specified entities must say <word> during <time period>.\nThe Exchange may specify additional conditions such as “at least X members of” a group or\n“the majority of” a group.\n\n<source>: <source> refers to a Source Agency or ordered collection of Source Agencies\nspecified by the Exchange at the time of Contract listing, which will be incorporated into the\nSource Agency hierarchy above and used to determine the occurrence of the Underlying.\n<source> may refer to a singular agency, multiple agencies, an agency by distinguishing\ncharacteristics, by category or type (e.g., “official government statistical body,” “primary wire\nservice”), or any combination thereof. When multiple agencies are specified, they may be\napplied in the hierarchical order designated by the Exchange if so specified, with the highest-\nranked available and responsive agency taking precedence for purposes of determining the\nExpiration Value. A lower-ranked agency shall only be consulted if all higher-ranked agencies\nare unavailable, unresponsive, have not reported on the Underlying by the Expiration time, or\nif the Exchange, in its sole discretion, determines that a higher-ranked agency’s reporting is\nincomplete, erroneous, or otherwise insufficient to determine the Expiration Value. If <source>\ndesignates multiple agencies without specifying a hierarchical order, the Exchange shall\nresolve any conflict between reporting agencies at its sole discretion.\n\n<word>: <word> refers to the particular word or phrase potentially to be mentioned by\n<entity>. It may refer to a word being said a minimum number of times. It may also refer to\none of multiple words/phrases, any of which are acceptable (e.g., “Doge/Dogecoin”).\n\f<time period>: <time period> refers to a specific range of time, event or discrete date and\ntime specified by the Exchange. This may be defined by, but is not limited to: a specific event\nor context (e.g., “during the State of the Union address”), exact dates or times, relative time\nmarkers (e.g., “before July 1, 2027,” “in Q1 2026”), event-based periods (e.g., “during any\ncampaign rally in October 2026,” “during the awards ceremony”), and broader intervals (e.g.,\n“Q1–Q2 2027,” “January–March 2026”).\n\nUnless stated otherwise, “Between” is inclusive of both endpoints, while “before” and “after”\nexclude the specified date. <time period> may also refer to “Any” or “None”, to multiple dates\n(even if non-consecutive), or to a singular and discrete date or time.\n\nWhen <time period> refers to a specific event (such as an address, speech, performance, or\nbroadcast), the Exchange may specify what is included, including whether it includes both live\nand pre-recorded segments (including whether advertisements are included). Where a\ntimezone is not specified, ET is assumed.\n\n\nPayout Criterion: The Payout Criterion for the Contract encompasses the Expiration Values that\n<word> is said by <entity> <time period>.\n\n\nThe word must appear as a distinct, standalone unit, not buried inside another word. Plural\nand possessive noun forms count. Other grammatical changes (tense, conjugation, derivation)\ndo not. If <word> appears separated from other words by a space or hyphen or in a\ncompound form with a space or hyphen, it counts. If <word> is fused into a single\nunhyphenated word, it does not count.\n\nIf <time period> refers to an event and that event is cancelled, and the market contains a\nstrike stating “Event does not qualify/occur”, such a strike shall resolve “Yes” and all others\n“No”. If <time period> refers to an event and that event is cancelled but such strikes are NOT\nlisted, the Contracts will resolve to the last fair price determined at the discretion of the\nExchange. If the event is postponed, and such a postponement is announced by the end of the\nfollowing calendar day to be rescheduled to a time within 14 calendar days, the markets shall\nremain open. If the event captured in <time period> is a live-stream or broadcast, the\nExchange may keep the market open for 24 hours for the release of an official recording.\nFurther granular details on conditions for these Contracts is available below.\n\nAdditional clarification(s):\n\n     Possessive noun forms of <word>, plurals, and possessive plural noun forms are\n     INCLUDED:\n          <word> is “Immigrant” → “Immigrants” counts\n          <word> is “Egg” → “eggs’ shells” counts\n          <word> is “Russia” → “Russia’s” counts, “Russian” does not\n     If <word> exists only in adjective form, no plural form exists:\n          <word> is “Economic” → “Economics” does not count (“Economic” is an adjective\n          for which “Economics” is not a plural)\n     Plural nouns occurring within proper nouns and noun phrases are included:\n          <word> is “Cat” → “Cats the musical” counts\n\f    Grammatical variations beyond plurals/possessives are NOT included:\n         <word> is “Immigrant” → “Immigration” does NOT count\n         <word> is “Run” → “Running” or “Ran” do NOT count\n    When <word> specifies a plural form, the singular does NOT count:\n         <word> is “Veterans” → “Veteran” does NOT count\n    Words that are spelled the same as the plural form of <word> (if such exists) but are\n    themselves not a plural noun are included:\n         <word> is “Wind” → “Winds up the clock” counts\n         <word> is “Border” → “The United States has strong borders” counts\n    Open compounds (words separated by spaces) count:\n         <word> is “fire” → “fire station” counts\n         <word> is “couch” → “couch potato” counts\n    Hyphenated compounds (words connected by hyphens) count:\n         <word> is “Palestine” → “pro-Palestine” counts\n         <word> is “fat” → “non-fat” counts\n    Closed compounds (single word, no spaces/hyphens) do not count:\n         <word> is “fire” → “wildfire” does not count\n         <word> is “fire” → “firefighter” does not count\n    Multi-word <word> in larger constructions: When <word> is a multi-word phrase\n    appearing within a hyphenated construction, it counts only if <word> appears as a\n    complete, unmodified element:\n         <word> is “New York” → “New York-based” counts (complete element)\n    Portmanteaus (words blended from two words where parts of each are combined) are\n    NOT included unless the portmanteau clearly contains <word> as a distinct, unaltered\n    element:\n         <word> is “MAGA” → “MAGA-nificent” counts (MAGA appears as distinct element)\n         <word> is “magnificent” → “MAGA-nificent” does NOT count (portmanteau blend)\n\nDictionary determination: Both the Merriam-Webster Dictionary (available online) AND the\nOxford English Dictionary shall be used to determine compound type and/or conventional\nspelling patterns. Inclusion in either dictionary as an open or hyphenated compound shall\nsatisfy the Payout Criterion. If neither provides clarity (or the word is not included),\ndetermination is based on whether written as single unit (closed/doesn’t count) vs. spaces or\nhyphens (open or hyphenated/counts) and/or context and previous usage.\n\nPHONETIC EQUIVALENCIES\n\n    Homophones (same sound, different spelling) do not count:\n        <word> is “write” → “right” does not count\n    Homonyms and homographs (same spelling) COUNT regardless of meaning or\n    pronunciation:\n        <word> is “bass” → both “bass guitar” and “bass fishing” count\n    Proper and common nouns are treated identically:\n        <word> is “Apple” → both “Apple Inc.” and “apple” (fruit) count\n        <word> is “Will” → both “Will Smith” and “I will go” count\n    Minor unintentional mispronunciations COUNT if context makes intent clear:\n        <word> is “Mamdani” → “Mandani” counts\n    Severe mispronunciations that make <word> unrecognizable do NOT count.\n    Trademarked spellings do not count, even when pronounced identically, unless the word\n\fitself is the same:\n      <word> is “lift” → “Lyft” (pronounced “lift”) does not count\n      <word> is “uber” → “Uber” counts\nWords with non-standard transliteration to English count within reason, provided they are\nphonetically equivalent:\n      <word> is “Zelensky” → any of “Zelenski,” “Zelenskii,” “Zelensky,” or “Zelenskiy”\n      count if pronounced equivalently\nContractions do not count for their constituent words unless otherwise explicitly specified\nby the Exchange:\n      <word> is “not” → “won’t,” “can’t,” “don’t,” “isn’t” do not count\nNumbers spoken as words COUNT, when spoken exactly (not part of a larger number):\n      <word> is “five” → saying “five” or reading “$5” aloud as “five dollars” counts,\n      saying “five hundred” does NOT count\n      <word> is “410” → “four hundred ten”, “four one zero” or “four ten” counts\nOrdinals COUNT when <word> is written numerically OR a phrase that includes a\nnumber:\n      <word> is “January 6” → “January 6th” counts\n      <word> is “3” (written numerically) → “3rd” (spoken as “third”) counts\n      <word> is “Eight War” → “8 Wars” and “Eighth War” will count\nCardinal and ordinal number words are distinct:\n      <word> is “one” → “first” does NOT count\n      <word> is “first” → “one” does NOT count\nAcronyms and abbreviations count when pronunciation or letter-by-letter spelling\nmatches <word>:\n      <word> is “NASA” → “NASA” (pronounced “NAH-suh”) counts\n      <word> is “NASA” → “N-A-S-A” (spelled out) counts\nAcronyms and abbreviations count as <word> when pronounced as the full word:\n      <word> is “Doctor” → “Dr.” (pronounced “Doctor”) counts\nExpanded forms of acronyms do NOT count:\n      <word> is “AI” → “artificial intelligence” does not count\nWords in foreign languages do NOT count unless they are perfect cognates with an\nEnglish word:\n      <word> is “fire” → “fuego” (Spanish) does NOT count\nEnglish words within foreign sentences count:\n      <word> is “policy” → “Nuestra policy es clara” counts\n<word> in organization/company names counts:\n      <word> is “Securities” → “Bank of America Securities” counts\nWords in URLs, emails, handles, and hashtags (exclusive of domain structure, email\nprovider or symbols) are treated as compounds when spoken as complete words, with the\ntype of compound subject to aforementioned rules:\n      <word> is “fire” → “firestation.com” pronounced “fire station dot com” counts\n      <word> is “fire” → “wildfire.com” pronounced “wildfire dot com” does NOT count\n      <word> is “apple” → “apple.com” pronounced “apple dot com” does count\n      When presented in URL, email, handle, or hashtag form, <word> shall be treated as\n      a compound, not a multi-word word\nSung, rapped, or poetic words COUNT if phonetically recognizable:\n      <word> is “money” → “moneyyy” (extended in rap) counts\n      Extreme distortion making <word> unrecognizable does NOT count.\nPhonetic alphabet spelling (“Foxtrot India Romeo Echo” for “FIRE”) does NOT count.\n\fCANCELLATIONS AND DELAYS\n\n   The Exchange may list an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike for any Contract. If listed,\n   such a strike refers to the structural conditions of the market, and is NOT adjudicated as a\n   <word> needing to be said by or validated by having been said by <entity>. If listed, this\n   strike resolves to “Yes” whenever the event fails to occur or qualify under the Payout\n   Criterion, or any other circumstance prevents normal resolution.\n   If no such strike is listed, and <time period> refers to a specific event, the following rules\n   apply if the event is cancelled, postponed, rescheduled, or materially altered (including\n   being closed to press) such that no video is released within one calendar day of the\n   original start time of the event:\n         If the event is cancelled, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price determined in\n         the sole discretion of the Exchange.\n         If the event is postponed or rescheduled, the outcome depends on whether a new\n         date is publicly announced within one calendar day (i.e. if the event was scheduled\n         to begin on Monday, any time up to 11:59PM on Tuesday falls within this period) of\n         the originally scheduled start time:\n               If no new date is announced within one calendar day, the Contract will resolve\n               to the last fair price determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\n               If a new date is announced within one calendar day, the outcome depends on\n               when the rescheduled event is set to occur:\n                     If the rescheduled date falls within fourteen (14) calendar days of the\n                     originally scheduled date, the Contract shall remain open and <word>\n                     stated during the rescheduled event will count.\n                           The fourteen-day window begins at 12:00 AM ET on the originally\n                           scheduled date and ends at 11:59 PM ET fourteen days later, unless\n                           an alternate timezone is explicitly specified.\n                           Example: <time period> is “during the State of the Union on January\n                           15, 2026” rescheduled to January 20, 2026 → words spoken during\n                           the rescheduled address count.\n                     If the rescheduled date falls more than fourteen (14) calendar days after\n                     the originally scheduled date, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price\n                     determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\n         Any Contract that cannot be resolved through the Source Agency hierarchy will\n         instead be settled at the Last Fair Price. The Exchange will disclose the methodology\n         used to determine the Last Fair Price (e.g., Last Traded Price, Time-Weighted\n         Average Price) at the time of Issuance.\n         If an event begins but is interrupted, abbreviated, or ends prematurely, words\n         stated by <entity> during the portion of the event that did occur will count and the\n         market will otherwise resolve.\n   If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window but the venue, format, or medium\n   changes (e.g., moved to a different location, changed from in-person to virtual (with the\n   exception of being closed to press)), words stated during the event will count.\n   Special condition: Across both cases, whether an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike is\n   listed or not, if the event specified as or in <time period> is a live-stream or broadcast (or\n   relayed as such) but the live stream/broadcast does not occur, the Exchange will instead\n   use an officially released recording as the Underlying, and may delay resolution by up to\n   one calendar day to allow for the release of such a recording.\n\f          If partial snippets are released, Contracts on words that do not appear will be\n          resolved to last fair price, and Contracts on those that do will be resolved to “Yes”.\n          If no recording is released, the relevant outcomes triggered by the\n          presence/absence of an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike shall occur as outlined\n          above.\n\nTECHNICAL DETAILS (UNLESS OTHERWISE SPECIFIED)\n\n     When <time period> refers to a specific event, pre-recorded content broadcast,\n     streamed, or published as part of that event is included if presented as part of the official\n     presentation.\n          Example: <time period> is “during the concert” with pre-recorded video interlude\n          where entity speaks → words from interlude count\n          Example: <time period> is “during the television appearance” with pre-taped\n          segment aired during broadcast → words from segment count\n     Behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are NOT\n     included unless officially broadcast or published as part of <time period>.\n     Subtitles and captions that display <word> on screen but are not spoken aloud by\n     <entity> do NOT count.\n     Sign language interpretation or usage by entity does NOT count as saying <word> unless\n     the Contract explicitly specifies that sign language counts.\n     Text that entity displays on screen (presentation slides, teleprompter visible to audience,\n     signatures) does NOT count unless entity reads it aloud.\n     Content generated by AI, deepfakes, or synthetic voice technology impersonating entity\n     does NOT count unless the synthetic content is officially commissioned, authorized, or\n     published by entity, OR the Contract explicitly specifies that AI-generated content counts.\n     If <word> is muted due to technical failure or censorship it shall not count unless\n     corroborating contextual evidence (including surrounding speech, or an official\n     uncensored recording or transcript) confirms that <entity> specifically uttered <word>\n     during the muted period.\n\nMinimum Tick: The Minimum Tick size for the Contract shall be $0.01.\n\nPosition Accountability Level: The Position Accountability Level for the Contract shall be\n$25,000 per strike, per Member.\n\nLast Trading Date: The Last Trading Date of the Contract will be the Expiration Date. The Last\nTrading Time will be the Expiration time.\n\nSettlement Date: The Settlement Date of the Contract shall be no later than the day after the\nExpiration Date, unless the Market Outcome is under review pursuant to Rule 7.1.\n\nExpiration Date: When <time period> refers to a specific event: The latest Expiration Date of\nthe Contract shall be fourteen (14) calendar days after the originally scheduled date of the\nevent. If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window, expiration will be moved to an\nearlier date and time in accordance with Rule 7.2. When <time period> is defined by specific\ndates: The latest Expiration Date of the Contract shall be two weeks after the end of <time\nperiod>. If an event described in the Payout Criterion occurs and a consensus has been\nreached on all terms, then expiration will be moved to an earlier date and time in accordance\nwith Rule 7.2.\n\fExpiration time: The Expiration time of the Contract shall be 10:00 AM ET.\n\nSettlement Value: The Settlement Value for this Contract is $1.00.\n\nExpiration Value: The Expiration Value is the value of the Underlying as documented by the\nSource Agency on the Expiration Date at the Expiration time.\n\nContingencies: Before Settlement, Kalshi may, at its sole discretion, initiate the Market\nOutcome Review Process pursuant to Rule 7.1 of the Rulebook. If an Expiration Value cannot\nbe determined on the Expiration Date, Kalshi has the right to determine payouts pursuant to\nRule 7.1 in the Rulebook.\n\f\n\n[plaintiff] PX-4 Formal draw archive note\nSource checked: Roll Call / Factba.se archive\n\nArchive title: Remarks: Donald Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing in Washington - December 5, 2025\n\nArchive URL: https://rollcall.com/factbase/trump/transcript/donald-trump-remarks-fifa-world-cup-drawing-december-5-2025/\n\nWhat this file establishes:\n\nThere is a separate archived transcript page for Trump's formal attendance remarks at the draw.\n\nWhat this file does not establish:\n\nThis session could not retrieve the full transcript text from that archive.  The page is password-protected.  This example therefore does not claim, from local files alone, whether the formal program transcript does or does not contain the word \"Ronaldo.\"\n\nWhy this matters:\n\nThe complaint does not need to prove that the formal program omitted the strike.  It needs to show that Trump said \"Ronaldo\" in event-linked remarks and that the market boundary reasonably includes those remarks.  The formal archive remains relevant because it marks the distinction between the pre-event reporter exchange and the formal program.\n\n\n[plaintiff] PX-5 GovInfo official transcript excerpt and metadata\nSource: GovInfo, DCPD202501162, Office of the Federal Register / National Archives and Records Administration.\nURL: https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/DCPD-202501162/html/DCPD-202501162.htm\nTitle: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\nEvent date: December 5, 2025.\n\nRelevant extracted page text:\n\"Administration of Donald J. Trump, 2025\"\n\"Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw December 5, 2025\"\n\"[The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\"\n\nUnder the section \"The President's Interest in Soccer\":\n\"Q. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\"\n\"The President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\\\"football,\\\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\"\n\"Thank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\"\n\nAdditional relevant extracted page text:\n\"The President's Interest in Soccer\"\n\"Q. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\"\n\"The President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\"\n\"Mr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\"\n\"The President. But they have a little more speed. But no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\"\n\nGovInfo note:\n\"NOTE: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. In his remarks, he referred to Trey Yingst, chief foreign correspondent, Fox News Channel; Cristiano Ronaldo, forward for Saudi Pro League club Al-Nass and Portugal's national soccer team; and Lionel Messi, forward for Major League Soccer club Inter Miami and Argentina's national team. A reporter referred to New York State Attorney General Letitia James. The transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\"\n\nGovInfo content details page also identifies category \"Interviews With the News Media : Exchanges with reporters, Washington, DC,\" subjects including \"Federation Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) World Cup,\" \"John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts,\" and \"Soccer,\" and names including \"Ronaldo, Cristiano\" and \"Messi, Lionel.\"\n\n[defendant] DX-1 Market wording and challenged resolution\nMarket URL: https://kalshi.com/markets/kxtrumpmentionb/trump-mention-b/kxtrumpmentionb-25dec06\n\nPublic market title: What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\n\nContract family: PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION\n\nStrike at issue: Ronaldo\n\nChallenged resolution: No\n\nRequested resolution: Yes\n\n\n[defendant] DX-2 Pre-event reporter exchange transcript\nRemarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\nDecember 05, 2025\n\n[The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\nThe President. It's a great honor to be here. Gianni has done a fantastic job. We're setting records—[inaudible].\nQ. [Inaudible]\nThe President. Well, I think so. They have a little bit of a shot. Pretty stiff competition. But I would say they would have a small chance.\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize\nQ. [Inaudible]—win the FIFA Peace Award?\nThe President. Well, it would be an honor.\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\nQ. Will you root for some selection? Will you root for someone?\nThe President. Well, I root for a lot of countries, but in this case, I'll be rooting for the U.S.A. [Laughter]\nQ. [Inaudible]\nThe President. That's great. That's great. We really love it.\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize\nQ. Mr. President, have you been told that you are going to receive the inaugural peace prize today——\nThe President. I have not——\nQ. ——from FIFA?\nThe President. I have not been told. There's a rumor about it, but I have not been told. That would be a great honor, and I'm a big fan of Gianni, as you know.\nQ. What can fans expect——\nQ. Are you hoping to receive that?\nThe President. Excuse me.\nQ. Are you hoping to receive the peace prize?\nThe President. Well, I don't like to say \"hope,\" but it would be a great honor.\n2026 World Cup\nQ. What can fans expect of, like, the World Cup in the U.S.?\nThe President. I think it's going to be fantastic. We've set every record you can set.\nQ. What are you telling people who are worried——\nFédération Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) President Giovanni V. Infantino\nQ. [Inaudible]—friend Gianni—[inaudible]—a word about him?\nThe President. I think he has done a fantastic job.\nThe President's Schedule\nQ. Are you going to be meeting with the President of Mexico today and the——\nThe President. We might. Yes.\nQ. ——Prime Minister of Canada as well?\nThe President. I might. I might do that.\nQ. Will you be discussing immigration and trade with them?\nThe President. Yes, we'll be discussing.\n[At this point, the President and Mr. Infantino posed for photographs.]\nThe President. Thank you, everybody.\n2026 World Cup Draw Event/John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts\nQ. Mr. President, what do you think about the crowd?\nThe President. Oh, look, the new star—[inaudible].\nCongratulations.\nQ. Thank you.\nThe President. You're the new star of television and Fox.\nQ. Thank you. How are you doing, Mr. President?\nThe President. I'm doing very well.\nQ. What do you think about the crowd here?\nThe President. I think the crowd is great, and I think the building is great. We've made a lot of improvements over the last 6 months. Taking—the Kennedy Center was in very bad shape. Now it's getting to be really good. And in 6 months, it's going to be incredible with the improvements we've made.\nQ. The first time for the U.S. to host since the nineties.\nThe President. Right.\nQ. Are you ready for it?\nThe President. I'm ready for it, and they're ready for it. And Gianni, who you know——\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\nThe President. ——has done a fantastic job with FIFA. And we're looking to have—you know, we're set—we have already set records for tickets sales. I don't think there's ever been anything like it in any sport. And so, I want to congratulate you.\nMr. Infantino. Thank you.\nThe President. I don't even have to wait. But major records have been set.\nHow are you?\nQ. Good, how are you, sir?\nThe President. Nice to see you.\nQ. Today it's not football—American football. It's soccer. It's——\nThe President. Right.\nQ. ——the big event of soccer.\nThe President. That's right. That's right.\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\nQ. So can you tell me about this big day today?\nThe President. It's just a big day, and it's a great sport. And it really is coming to America. And never—nobody ever thought a thing like this could happen. And I'm very happy to say that we've already set the alltime record on ticket sales long before the first ball is kicked. Right?\nMr. Infantino. A hundred percent. One hundred percent.\n2026 World Cup Host Cities\nQ. You've had some concerns about crime in American cities, some of the cities that will be hosting. Have they remedied that for you? Are you still considering maybe asking FIFA to move some of those cities?\nThe President. No, I don't want to do that. But I will tell you, if they do have a problem, by the time we get there, we'll take care of that problem. We can solve that problem.\nI've proven that in DC and everywhere else we went, so we'll take care of that very easily. So, if they have a problem, hopefully, they'll let us know that, and we will solve any problem.\nOkay? Thank you.\nQ. Thank you so much.\nMr. Infantino. All right, thank you so much.\nQ. Thank you, Mr. President.\nQ. Thank you. Appreciate it.\nThe President. Congratulations.\n2026 World Cup\nQ. Mr. President, Brazilian television. America will be hosting the World Cup and the Olympics in 2 years. How important it is—[inaudible]?\nThe President. I think very. It's a great honor. I think Gianni is doing a phenomenal job. We've set every record on ticket sales. It's been really fantastic. But Gianni has done an unbelievable job with FIFA.\nThe President's Experience With Soccer\nQ. [Inaudible]\nThe President. He was a great—not only that. I got to see a man name Pelé play—right?—that tells you how old I am—when he was on the Cosmos. Do you remember that a long time ago? And it was quite a treat. That was quite an event. And he was—not only was he playing, he was great. He scored two goals, I think. And so, I was one of the few who got to see Pelé, and I assume he is one of your alltime greats. Right?\nMr. Infantino. Definitely.\nThe President. So I got to see him.\nThe President's Favorite World Cup Competitor\nQ. Do you have some favorite teams for World Cup?\nThe President. Well, I have a favorite. It's the U.S.A. [Laughter] I don't know what their chances are, Gianni, but maybe the U.S.A. is the——\nMr. Infantino. They're getting better and better, actually.\nThe President. I think they'll do well.\nMr. Infantino. They are getting better and better.\nThe President. I think they'll do well.\nThank you very much, everybody.\nQ. Thank you so much.\n2026 World Cup\nQ. Mr. President, World Cup in America just means—[inaudible]. So what do you expect from this World Cup?\nThe President. [Inaudible]—record business and only in the United States, but we're also doing record ticket sales with FIFA. And they've already bought—beat their highest record. And we—you know, this a long time before the first ball is kicked. You've sold more tickets than they've ever done before, and better pricing than they've ever gotten before. It's a tremendous success. And it's an honor. And Gianni has done a phenomenal job with FIFA.\nQ. [Inaudible]—ever?\nThe President. I think so. I think it's going to be—I mean, ideally, you want to see that every year. Every 4 years, it gets bigger and better. I think we have set every record in the book. We're very happy about it.\nThank you.\nThe President's Favorite World Cup Competitor\nQ. [Inaudible]—part of America. Who are you going to support as well?\nThe President. Well, I think I have to support U.S.A. Otherwise, I'd be in trouble. I wouldn't be President for long.\nMr. Infantino. [Inaudible]\nThe President. [Inaudible]—but you have a lot of great teams. You're going to have a lot of great teams.\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\"football,\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\n2026 World Cup Draw/Ticket Sales for World Cup\nQ. How does it feel to be part of this amazing event? And obviously, your being a part of participating in all the—[inaudible]?\nThe President. The President of Mexico is here, and she's doing a very good job. She's a good woman, very, very excellent job. It's an honor, and we're setting every record, and you're helping us set those records.\nMr. Infantino. And we will do it.\nThe President. You know, Mexico and Canada are helping us set those records. But as you know, we have a record in ticket sales already, long before the first ball is kicked, and we're going to do great.\nI think that Gianni—as you know, he's the head, and he has done a fantastic job.\nU.S. Cooperation With Mexico and Canada\nQ. And how is the biggest challenge being three countries?\nThe President. Well, I think that—do you mean for the three countries?\nWell, they've gotten together really well, I mean.\nMr. Infantino. All right.\nThe President. They're getting along very well.\nMr. Infantino. Collaboration is fantastic between the three.\nThe President's Interest in Soccer/2026 World Cup\nQ. And you like soccer?\nThe President. I do. I like it. I like it more and more.\nQ. Yes?\nThe President. I like it. It's growing in this country—very, really—I mean, someday, maybe it's going to be bigger than anything else.\nMr. Infantino. We'll have to become number one.\nThe President. I will say this——\nMr. Infantino. Definitely.\nThe President. ——the ticket sales——\nQ. Definitely will happen.\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\nThe President. Ticket sales are bigger than anything we have ever done in the history of the country, in terms of sports.\nMr. Infantino. For certain.\nQ. And the audience is going to be huge.\nThe President. The audience is going to be tremendous.\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\nThe President. Yes.\nMr. Infantino. Six billion people.\nThe President. [Inaudible]\nQ. Six billion? That's amazing.\nMr. Infantino. Six billion people.\nAnd today, one billion.\nQ. Wow.\nMr. Infantino. [Inaudible]\nQ. Enjoy show time. Thank you so much.\nThe President. [Inaudible]\nQ. Mr. President, how are you? Just a quick—[inaudible].\nQ. This is for Telemundo.\nThe President. How are you?\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\nQ. Hello, Mr. President. How are you? This for Telemundo.\nThe President. How are you? Good.\nQ. How are you?\nThe President. Very good. Thank you.\nQ. How does it feel to have the most important event of sports—that global—in the U.S.?\nThe President. Well, we do. And right at the Kennedy Center. I'm Chairman of the Kennedy Center. And I hear the Kennedy Center is doing a very good job, so it feels great. Really good.\nAnd Telemundo is doing a good job, too. Thank you.\nQ. Thank you.\n2026 World Cup\nQ. What is the significance of hosting the FIFA World Cup this year?\nThe President. It's a—in terms of sports, I would say the ultimate. There is no sport like this. It's the biggest sport in the world. And we are setting every record. You know, our ticket sales have gone and set every—every sport—no matter what it is, we've set the record. So—and every though it's very early, there's no ball being kicked yet, but we've already set a ticket sales record.\nArgentina National Team\nQ. How do you see Argentinean team for this World Cup?\nThe President. Well, I love Argentina. And your President is doing a very good job, as you know. Milei. You know that right? It's make Argentina great again. MAGA.\nQ. And——\nU.S. National Team\nQ. Do you think the States are building a powerful team for next year?\nThe President. Who?\nQ. The States.\nThe President. Oh, yes. Sure. I—you're going to have a lot of powerful teams. Everybody has a lot of powerful teams, but you're going to have a lot of great teams. [Inaudible]\nU.S. Role in Hosting the 2026 World Cup\nQ. Mr. President, what does it mean for you guys to host the World Cup right here in the U.S.?\nThe President. I'm honored to host it. It's a great honor. I mean, it's turned out to be bigger than we thought. We're setting a record for ticket sales, the likes of which no sport has ever seen before.\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\nThe President. But they have a little more speed.\nBut no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\nPopularity of Soccer in Latin America\nQ. Mr. President, a message for the Latin America and soccer fans?\nThe President. Yes, I am. And Latin America is great. And they have great soccer. So, good luck in the matches.\n[A reporter asked a question in Spanish, which was translated by an interpreter as follows.]\nU.S. Visas for World Cup Ticketholders\nQ. Who is going to be in—[inaudible]—about these visas for the—these fans that want to come here to the World Cup?\nThe President. Well, we're going to make it very easy for them. We're working on that right now. We're going to make it very easy. It's going to be a very easy process.\nQ. Okay. Say, hi to Colombia over there.\nThe President. Hello. Is that Colombia?\nQ. Yes.\nThe President. I love Colombia. Hello, Colombia. [Laughter]\nQ. Okay. Okay. Muy bien.\nThe President. So where are you from?\nQ. Paraguay.\nThe President. Oh.\nQ. He's from Paraguay. Yes.\nThe President. Very good. I love it. I—it's a beautiful country. We get along very well with them. We do a little trade deal with them, and they like us. And that's what's happening.\nQ. Panama.\nThe President. Where?\nVery good. I like the canal. [Laughter] That canal is pretty good.\n[A reporter spoke in Spanish; no translation was provided.]\n2026 World Cup\nThe President. What?\nQ. [Inaudible]\nThe President. Well, it's going to be incredible. The event is going to be very good. Just this event alone—it's at the Kennedy Center. I see you have it fixed up perfectly.\nMr. Infantino. It will set the tone.\nThe President. Right? It's beautiful.\nMr. Infantino. It's beautiful.\nThe President. It's a beautiful place.\nHave a good time.\nQ. [Inaudible]\nThe President.\n[A reporter spoke in Spanish; no translation was provided.]\nMr. Infantino. No, gracias. [Inaudible]\nThe President. It's great.\nJohn F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts/Renovation Work\nQ. Mr. President, the U.S. press?\nThe President. Thank you, everybody, very much. It's a great honor. This has been an honor for a lot of reasons. Number one, they've sold more tickets than any event has ever sold already—long before the kickoff.\nAnd number two, we've done a lot of work at the Kennedy Center. It was falling apart, and now it's pretty much back. And we'll get it back within the next 4 or 5 months through construction, and—but you see the way it looks.\nAnd Gianni is just telling me—who's done an incredible job, by the way. He's just telling, you know, how good a job we've done.\nMr. Infantino. That's right.\nThe President. You can look at the walls. The marble was broken. Everything was a mess. And we've really taken the Kennedy Center—a lot of people thought it was going to be ripped down, and we did just the opposite. So we've done a really great renovation job on it. And over the next 3, 4 months, it will be complete. And we're honored to have it here, and it's been—it's been very special.\nWe've set a record on ticket sales, as you probably heard, already, even way before—long before the event itself. And we're working with Canada, and we're working with Mexico. And it's been a really spectacular—so far, it's been spectacular.\nDaniel [Daniel Baldwin, One America News Network], do you have a question?\n2026 World Cup\nQ. What are your expectations? You once said that the FIFA World Cup is an opportunity to put—a once-in-a-lifetime opportunity to put the greatness of the United States on display.\nThe President. Well, I think—\nQ. One billion eyeballs will be watching, Mr. President.\nThe President. Yes, I—think——\nQ. What will they here today?\nThe President. Even today, I understand. I hear that, you know——\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\nThe President. ——I know we're a little late to get in there, but——\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\nThe President. ——that's okay.\nMr. Infantino. They wait.\nThe President. So all my friends, I guess they have to wait. They have no choice, right? [Laughter]\nMr. Infantino. Yes, they wait.\nThe President. But no, the numbers are incredible. I hear today's numbers are——\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\nThe President. ——very big. I hope CNN is covering this.\nQ. One billion eyeballs.\nMr. Infantino. Today, 1 billion eyeballs.\nThe President. Today's numbers are very, very big.\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize/The President's Foreign Policy\nQ. We are covering it. And you're expected to get the FIFA Peace Prize, Mr. President. What would you say to people who say that prize might conflict with your pledge to strike Venezuela?\nThe President. Well, I think the peace prize—I mean, I settled eight wars. I don't know that I'm getting it. I haven't been officially noticed. I've been hearing about a peace prize, and I'm here to represent our country in a different sense. But I can tell you, I did settle eight wars, and we have a ninth coming, but—which nobody has ever done before.\nBut I want to really save lives. I don't need prizes. I need to save lives. And we're saving a lot of lives. And I've saved millions and millions of lives, and that's really what I want to do.\nAnd I also want to run a great country. And the United States right now is the hottest country anywhere in the world. And 1 year ago, it was dead. We had a dead country, and now we have the hottest country anywhere in the world.\nQ. Mr. President, will you——\nThe President's Meeting With President Claudia Sheinbaum Pardo of Mexico and Prime Minister Mark Carney of Canada\nQ. What are you going to discuss with Canada and Mexico, Mr.—what are you going to discuss with the leaders of Canada and Mexico?\nThe President. Well, we're getting—we're going to meet with both. And we're getting along very well. You know, we're getting along very well. I don't know. I think we have a meeting set up for some time after the event.\nQ. Will you discuss trade?\nThe President. Yes, we'll discuss trade. We—get along very well.\nThank you, everybody, very much.\nQ. Will you pardon any other Honduran officials?\nQ. Do you want them to keep trying to indict Ms. James?\n\nNOTE: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. In his remarks, he referred to Trey Yingst, chief foreign correspondent, Fox News Channel; Cristiano Ronaldo, forward for Saudi Pro League club Al-Nass and Portugal's national soccer team; and Lionel Messi, forward for Major League Soccer club Inter Miami and Argentina's national team. A reporter referred to New York State Attorney General Letitia James. The transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\n\nSource URL: https://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/documents/remarks-exchange-with-reporters-prior-the-2026-federation-internationale-des-associations\n\n\n[defendant] DX-3 GovInfo/OFR pre-event transcript excerpt\nSource: GovInfo, DCPD202501162, Office of the Federal Register / National Archives and Records Administration.\nURL: https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/DCPD-202501162/html/DCPD-202501162.htm\nTitle: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\nEvent date: December 5, 2025.\n\nRelevant extracted page text:\n\"Administration of Donald J. Trump, 2025\"\n\"Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw December 5, 2025\"\n\"[The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\"\n\nUnder the section \"The President's Interest in Soccer\":\n\"Q. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\"\n\"The President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\\\"football,\\\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\"\n\"Thank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\"\n\nAdditional relevant extracted page text:\n\"The President's Interest in Soccer\"\n\"Q. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\"\n\"The President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\"\n\"Mr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\"\n\"The President. But they have a little more speed. But no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\"\n\nGovInfo note:\n\"NOTE: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. In his remarks, he referred to Trey Yingst, chief foreign correspondent, Fox News Channel; Cristiano Ronaldo, forward for Saudi Pro League club Al-Nass and Portugal's national soccer team; and Lionel Messi, forward for Major League Soccer club Inter Miami and Argentina's national team. A reporter referred to New York State Attorney General Letitia James. The transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\"\n\nGovInfo content details page also identifies category \"Interviews With the News Media : Exchanges with reporters, Washington, DC,\" subjects including \"Federation Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) World Cup,\" \"John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts,\" and \"Soccer,\" and names including \"Ronaldo, Cristiano\" and \"Messi, Lionel.\"\n\n[defendant] DX-4 PRESMENTION/NEWMENTION terms\n                                         NEWMENTION\n\nScope: These rules shall apply to this contract.\n\nUnderlying: The Underlying for this Contract is words used by <entity> <time period>.\nRevisions to the Underlying made after Expiration will not be accounted for in determining the\nExpiration Value.\n\nSource Agency: The Source Agencies are <source>.\n\nType: The type of Contract is an Event Contract.\n\nIssuance: After the initial Contract, Contract iterations will be listed on an as-needed basis at\nthe discretion of the Exchange and corresponding to the risk management needs of Members.\n\n<entity>: <entity> refers to the speaker, writer, performer, or communicator specified by the\nExchange. This may include (but is not limited to): a specific named individual, multiple\nindividuals specified using AND/OR logic, an individual identified by position or title, a group,\nband, team or collective entity, a specified member or members of a group, an organization,\ncompany, or institutional entity, or any combination of the aforementioned.\n\nWhen <entity> is defined by a position or title, the Contract tracks whoever holds that position\nduring <time period>, even if the individual holding the position changes. When <entity> is a\nspecific named individual, the identity remains consistent throughout. Name changes (e.g.,\nstage names, married names) do not create a new entity. When <entity> is a group or\norganization and the Contract does not specify particular members, any official\ncommunication or statement by any member or designated spokesperson counts. When using\nAND logic, all specified entities must independently say <word> during <time period>. When\nusing OR logic, at least one of the specified entities must say <word> during <time period>.\nThe Exchange may specify additional conditions such as “at least X members of” a group or\n“the majority of” a group.\n\n<source>: <source> refers to a Source Agency or ordered collection of Source Agencies\nspecified by the Exchange at the time of Contract listing, which will be incorporated into the\nSource Agency hierarchy above and used to determine the occurrence of the Underlying.\n<source> may refer to a singular agency, multiple agencies, an agency by distinguishing\ncharacteristics, by category or type (e.g., “official government statistical body,” “primary wire\nservice”), or any combination thereof. When multiple agencies are specified, they may be\napplied in the hierarchical order designated by the Exchange if so specified, with the highest-\nranked available and responsive agency taking precedence for purposes of determining the\nExpiration Value. A lower-ranked agency shall only be consulted if all higher-ranked agencies\nare unavailable, unresponsive, have not reported on the Underlying by the Expiration time, or\nif the Exchange, in its sole discretion, determines that a higher-ranked agency’s reporting is\nincomplete, erroneous, or otherwise insufficient to determine the Expiration Value. If <source>\ndesignates multiple agencies without specifying a hierarchical order, the Exchange shall\nresolve any conflict between reporting agencies at its sole discretion.\n\n<word>: <word> refers to the particular word or phrase potentially to be mentioned by\n<entity>. It may refer to a word being said a minimum number of times. It may also refer to\none of multiple words/phrases, any of which are acceptable (e.g., “Doge/Dogecoin”).\n\f<time period>: <time period> refers to a specific range of time, event or discrete date and\ntime specified by the Exchange. This may be defined by, but is not limited to: a specific event\nor context (e.g., “during the State of the Union address”), exact dates or times, relative time\nmarkers (e.g., “before July 1, 2027,” “in Q1 2026”), event-based periods (e.g., “during any\ncampaign rally in October 2026,” “during the awards ceremony”), and broader intervals (e.g.,\n“Q1–Q2 2027,” “January–March 2026”).\n\nUnless stated otherwise, “Between” is inclusive of both endpoints, while “before” and “after”\nexclude the specified date. <time period> may also refer to “Any” or “None”, to multiple dates\n(even if non-consecutive), or to a singular and discrete date or time.\n\nWhen <time period> refers to a specific event (such as an address, speech, performance, or\nbroadcast), the Exchange may specify what is included, including whether it includes both live\nand pre-recorded segments (including whether advertisements are included). Where a\ntimezone is not specified, ET is assumed.\n\n\nPayout Criterion: The Payout Criterion for the Contract encompasses the Expiration Values that\n<word> is said by <entity> <time period>.\n\n\nThe word must appear as a distinct, standalone unit, not buried inside another word. Plural\nand possessive noun forms count. Other grammatical changes (tense, conjugation, derivation)\ndo not. If <word> appears separated from other words by a space or hyphen or in a\ncompound form with a space or hyphen, it counts. If <word> is fused into a single\nunhyphenated word, it does not count.\n\nIf <time period> refers to an event and that event is cancelled, and the market contains a\nstrike stating “Event does not qualify/occur”, such a strike shall resolve “Yes” and all others\n“No”. If <time period> refers to an event and that event is cancelled but such strikes are NOT\nlisted, the Contracts will resolve to the last fair price determined at the discretion of the\nExchange. If the event is postponed, and such a postponement is announced by the end of the\nfollowing calendar day to be rescheduled to a time within 14 calendar days, the markets shall\nremain open. If the event captured in <time period> is a live-stream or broadcast, the\nExchange may keep the market open for 24 hours for the release of an official recording.\nFurther granular details on conditions for these Contracts is available below.\n\nAdditional clarification(s):\n\n     Possessive noun forms of <word>, plurals, and possessive plural noun forms are\n     INCLUDED:\n          <word> is “Immigrant” → “Immigrants” counts\n          <word> is “Egg” → “eggs’ shells” counts\n          <word> is “Russia” → “Russia’s” counts, “Russian” does not\n     If <word> exists only in adjective form, no plural form exists:\n          <word> is “Economic” → “Economics” does not count (“Economic” is an adjective\n          for which “Economics” is not a plural)\n     Plural nouns occurring within proper nouns and noun phrases are included:\n          <word> is “Cat” → “Cats the musical” counts\n\f    Grammatical variations beyond plurals/possessives are NOT included:\n         <word> is “Immigrant” → “Immigration” does NOT count\n         <word> is “Run” → “Running” or “Ran” do NOT count\n    When <word> specifies a plural form, the singular does NOT count:\n         <word> is “Veterans” → “Veteran” does NOT count\n    Words that are spelled the same as the plural form of <word> (if such exists) but are\n    themselves not a plural noun are included:\n         <word> is “Wind” → “Winds up the clock” counts\n         <word> is “Border” → “The United States has strong borders” counts\n    Open compounds (words separated by spaces) count:\n         <word> is “fire” → “fire station” counts\n         <word> is “couch” → “couch potato” counts\n    Hyphenated compounds (words connected by hyphens) count:\n         <word> is “Palestine” → “pro-Palestine” counts\n         <word> is “fat” → “non-fat” counts\n    Closed compounds (single word, no spaces/hyphens) do not count:\n         <word> is “fire” → “wildfire” does not count\n         <word> is “fire” → “firefighter” does not count\n    Multi-word <word> in larger constructions: When <word> is a multi-word phrase\n    appearing within a hyphenated construction, it counts only if <word> appears as a\n    complete, unmodified element:\n         <word> is “New York” → “New York-based” counts (complete element)\n    Portmanteaus (words blended from two words where parts of each are combined) are\n    NOT included unless the portmanteau clearly contains <word> as a distinct, unaltered\n    element:\n         <word> is “MAGA” → “MAGA-nificent” counts (MAGA appears as distinct element)\n         <word> is “magnificent” → “MAGA-nificent” does NOT count (portmanteau blend)\n\nDictionary determination: Both the Merriam-Webster Dictionary (available online) AND the\nOxford English Dictionary shall be used to determine compound type and/or conventional\nspelling patterns. Inclusion in either dictionary as an open or hyphenated compound shall\nsatisfy the Payout Criterion. If neither provides clarity (or the word is not included),\ndetermination is based on whether written as single unit (closed/doesn’t count) vs. spaces or\nhyphens (open or hyphenated/counts) and/or context and previous usage.\n\nPHONETIC EQUIVALENCIES\n\n    Homophones (same sound, different spelling) do not count:\n        <word> is “write” → “right” does not count\n    Homonyms and homographs (same spelling) COUNT regardless of meaning or\n    pronunciation:\n        <word> is “bass” → both “bass guitar” and “bass fishing” count\n    Proper and common nouns are treated identically:\n        <word> is “Apple” → both “Apple Inc.” and “apple” (fruit) count\n        <word> is “Will” → both “Will Smith” and “I will go” count\n    Minor unintentional mispronunciations COUNT if context makes intent clear:\n        <word> is “Mamdani” → “Mandani” counts\n    Severe mispronunciations that make <word> unrecognizable do NOT count.\n    Trademarked spellings do not count, even when pronounced identically, unless the word\n\fitself is the same:\n      <word> is “lift” → “Lyft” (pronounced “lift”) does not count\n      <word> is “uber” → “Uber” counts\nWords with non-standard transliteration to English count within reason, provided they are\nphonetically equivalent:\n      <word> is “Zelensky” → any of “Zelenski,” “Zelenskii,” “Zelensky,” or “Zelenskiy”\n      count if pronounced equivalently\nContractions do not count for their constituent words unless otherwise explicitly specified\nby the Exchange:\n      <word> is “not” → “won’t,” “can’t,” “don’t,” “isn’t” do not count\nNumbers spoken as words COUNT, when spoken exactly (not part of a larger number):\n      <word> is “five” → saying “five” or reading “$5” aloud as “five dollars” counts,\n      saying “five hundred” does NOT count\n      <word> is “410” → “four hundred ten”, “four one zero” or “four ten” counts\nOrdinals COUNT when <word> is written numerically OR a phrase that includes a\nnumber:\n      <word> is “January 6” → “January 6th” counts\n      <word> is “3” (written numerically) → “3rd” (spoken as “third”) counts\n      <word> is “Eight War” → “8 Wars” and “Eighth War” will count\nCardinal and ordinal number words are distinct:\n      <word> is “one” → “first” does NOT count\n      <word> is “first” → “one” does NOT count\nAcronyms and abbreviations count when pronunciation or letter-by-letter spelling\nmatches <word>:\n      <word> is “NASA” → “NASA” (pronounced “NAH-suh”) counts\n      <word> is “NASA” → “N-A-S-A” (spelled out) counts\nAcronyms and abbreviations count as <word> when pronounced as the full word:\n      <word> is “Doctor” → “Dr.” (pronounced “Doctor”) counts\nExpanded forms of acronyms do NOT count:\n      <word> is “AI” → “artificial intelligence” does not count\nWords in foreign languages do NOT count unless they are perfect cognates with an\nEnglish word:\n      <word> is “fire” → “fuego” (Spanish) does NOT count\nEnglish words within foreign sentences count:\n      <word> is “policy” → “Nuestra policy es clara” counts\n<word> in organization/company names counts:\n      <word> is “Securities” → “Bank of America Securities” counts\nWords in URLs, emails, handles, and hashtags (exclusive of domain structure, email\nprovider or symbols) are treated as compounds when spoken as complete words, with the\ntype of compound subject to aforementioned rules:\n      <word> is “fire” → “firestation.com” pronounced “fire station dot com” counts\n      <word> is “fire” → “wildfire.com” pronounced “wildfire dot com” does NOT count\n      <word> is “apple” → “apple.com” pronounced “apple dot com” does count\n      When presented in URL, email, handle, or hashtag form, <word> shall be treated as\n      a compound, not a multi-word word\nSung, rapped, or poetic words COUNT if phonetically recognizable:\n      <word> is “money” → “moneyyy” (extended in rap) counts\n      Extreme distortion making <word> unrecognizable does NOT count.\nPhonetic alphabet spelling (“Foxtrot India Romeo Echo” for “FIRE”) does NOT count.\n\fCANCELLATIONS AND DELAYS\n\n   The Exchange may list an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike for any Contract. If listed,\n   such a strike refers to the structural conditions of the market, and is NOT adjudicated as a\n   <word> needing to be said by or validated by having been said by <entity>. If listed, this\n   strike resolves to “Yes” whenever the event fails to occur or qualify under the Payout\n   Criterion, or any other circumstance prevents normal resolution.\n   If no such strike is listed, and <time period> refers to a specific event, the following rules\n   apply if the event is cancelled, postponed, rescheduled, or materially altered (including\n   being closed to press) such that no video is released within one calendar day of the\n   original start time of the event:\n         If the event is cancelled, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price determined in\n         the sole discretion of the Exchange.\n         If the event is postponed or rescheduled, the outcome depends on whether a new\n         date is publicly announced within one calendar day (i.e. if the event was scheduled\n         to begin on Monday, any time up to 11:59PM on Tuesday falls within this period) of\n         the originally scheduled start time:\n               If no new date is announced within one calendar day, the Contract will resolve\n               to the last fair price determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\n               If a new date is announced within one calendar day, the outcome depends on\n               when the rescheduled event is set to occur:\n                     If the rescheduled date falls within fourteen (14) calendar days of the\n                     originally scheduled date, the Contract shall remain open and <word>\n                     stated during the rescheduled event will count.\n                           The fourteen-day window begins at 12:00 AM ET on the originally\n                           scheduled date and ends at 11:59 PM ET fourteen days later, unless\n                           an alternate timezone is explicitly specified.\n                           Example: <time period> is “during the State of the Union on January\n                           15, 2026” rescheduled to January 20, 2026 → words spoken during\n                           the rescheduled address count.\n                     If the rescheduled date falls more than fourteen (14) calendar days after\n                     the originally scheduled date, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price\n                     determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\n         Any Contract that cannot be resolved through the Source Agency hierarchy will\n         instead be settled at the Last Fair Price. The Exchange will disclose the methodology\n         used to determine the Last Fair Price (e.g., Last Traded Price, Time-Weighted\n         Average Price) at the time of Issuance.\n         If an event begins but is interrupted, abbreviated, or ends prematurely, words\n         stated by <entity> during the portion of the event that did occur will count and the\n         market will otherwise resolve.\n   If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window but the venue, format, or medium\n   changes (e.g., moved to a different location, changed from in-person to virtual (with the\n   exception of being closed to press)), words stated during the event will count.\n   Special condition: Across both cases, whether an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike is\n   listed or not, if the event specified as or in <time period> is a live-stream or broadcast (or\n   relayed as such) but the live stream/broadcast does not occur, the Exchange will instead\n   use an officially released recording as the Underlying, and may delay resolution by up to\n   one calendar day to allow for the release of such a recording.\n\f          If partial snippets are released, Contracts on words that do not appear will be\n          resolved to last fair price, and Contracts on those that do will be resolved to “Yes”.\n          If no recording is released, the relevant outcomes triggered by the\n          presence/absence of an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike shall occur as outlined\n          above.\n\nTECHNICAL DETAILS (UNLESS OTHERWISE SPECIFIED)\n\n     When <time period> refers to a specific event, pre-recorded content broadcast,\n     streamed, or published as part of that event is included if presented as part of the official\n     presentation.\n          Example: <time period> is “during the concert” with pre-recorded video interlude\n          where entity speaks → words from interlude count\n          Example: <time period> is “during the television appearance” with pre-taped\n          segment aired during broadcast → words from segment count\n     Behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are NOT\n     included unless officially broadcast or published as part of <time period>.\n     Subtitles and captions that display <word> on screen but are not spoken aloud by\n     <entity> do NOT count.\n     Sign language interpretation or usage by entity does NOT count as saying <word> unless\n     the Contract explicitly specifies that sign language counts.\n     Text that entity displays on screen (presentation slides, teleprompter visible to audience,\n     signatures) does NOT count unless entity reads it aloud.\n     Content generated by AI, deepfakes, or synthetic voice technology impersonating entity\n     does NOT count unless the synthetic content is officially commissioned, authorized, or\n     published by entity, OR the Contract explicitly specifies that AI-generated content counts.\n     If <word> is muted due to technical failure or censorship it shall not count unless\n     corroborating contextual evidence (including surrounding speech, or an official\n     uncensored recording or transcript) confirms that <entity> specifically uttered <word>\n     during the muted period.\n\nMinimum Tick: The Minimum Tick size for the Contract shall be $0.01.\n\nPosition Accountability Level: The Position Accountability Level for the Contract shall be\n$25,000 per strike, per Member.\n\nLast Trading Date: The Last Trading Date of the Contract will be the Expiration Date. The Last\nTrading Time will be the Expiration time.\n\nSettlement Date: The Settlement Date of the Contract shall be no later than the day after the\nExpiration Date, unless the Market Outcome is under review pursuant to Rule 7.1.\n\nExpiration Date: When <time period> refers to a specific event: The latest Expiration Date of\nthe Contract shall be fourteen (14) calendar days after the originally scheduled date of the\nevent. If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window, expiration will be moved to an\nearlier date and time in accordance with Rule 7.2. When <time period> is defined by specific\ndates: The latest Expiration Date of the Contract shall be two weeks after the end of <time\nperiod>. If an event described in the Payout Criterion occurs and a consensus has been\nreached on all terms, then expiration will be moved to an earlier date and time in accordance\nwith Rule 7.2.\n\fExpiration time: The Expiration time of the Contract shall be 10:00 AM ET.\n\nSettlement Value: The Settlement Value for this Contract is $1.00.\n\nExpiration Value: The Expiration Value is the value of the Underlying as documented by the\nSource Agency on the Expiration Date at the Expiration time.\n\nContingencies: Before Settlement, Kalshi may, at its sole discretion, initiate the Market\nOutcome Review Process pursuant to Rule 7.1 of the Rulebook. If an Expiration Value cannot\nbe determined on the Expiration Date, Kalshi has the right to determine payouts pursuant to\nRule 7.1 in the Rulebook.\n\f\n\n[defendant] DX-5 Formal draw archive note\nSource checked: Roll Call / Factba.se archive\n\nArchive title: Remarks: Donald Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing in Washington - December 5, 2025\n\nArchive URL: https://rollcall.com/factbase/trump/transcript/donald-trump-remarks-fifa-world-cup-drawing-december-5-2025/\n\nWhat this file establishes:\n\nThere is a separate archived transcript page for Trump's formal attendance remarks at the draw.\n\nWhat this file does not establish:\n\nThis session could not retrieve the full transcript text from that archive.  The page is password-protected.  This example therefore does not claim, from local files alone, whether the formal program transcript does or does not contain the word \"Ronaldo.\"\n\nWhy this matters:\n\nThe complaint does not need to prove that the formal program omitted the strike.  It needs to show that Trump said \"Ronaldo\" in event-linked remarks and that the market boundary reasonably includes those remarks.  The formal archive remains relevant because it marks the distinction between the pre-event reporter exchange and the formal program.\n\n\n[defendant] DX-6 Formal Roll Call/Factba.se transcript extraction\nSource: Roll Call / Factba.se\nURL: https://rollcall.com/factbase/trump/transcript/donald-trump-remarks-fifa-world-cup-drawing-december-5-2025/\nCaptured page title: Remarks: Donald Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing in Washington - December 5, 2025\n\nRendered page metadata excerpt:\nTopics: Sport; Sport > Competition Discipline > Soccer; Lifestyle and Leisure > Leisure > Game.\nEntities listed: bowl; deal; Donald J. Trump; FIFA World Cup; Mark Carney; place; President; trophy; United States; way.\nSpeakers listed: Gianni Infantino, Donald Trump, Mark Carney, Claudia Sheinbaum.\nSpeaker statistics excerpt: Donald Trump said 25 sentences of a total of 141 sentences; Donald Trump said 274 words of a total of 1009 words; Donald Trump talked 92 seconds of a total of 484 seconds.\n\nFormal transcript excerpt at start of draw:\nMark Carney, 00:00:00-00:00:02: Thank you, my friend.\nGianni Infantino, 00:00:50-00:01:22: So this is the World Cup trophy. This is the official bowl for the World Cup and we are now going to do the draw, ladies and gentlemen. But before that, as is customary, there is always a question that the moderator asks the draw assistant. So I would like to start with Mr. Carney. How big a deal is it to co-host the World Cup for Canada?\n\nFormal transcript excerpt of Trump's soccer answer:\nDonald Trump, 00:03:14-00:03:32: Well, for years, Gianni, they've thought soccer or football would be so big, so fast. And I remember, I shouldn't say this because it was a long time ago, but I remember watching Pele play on a team called the Cosmos, Pele, who was fantastic, as you know. I assume one of the greats.\n\nText-extraction/search notes:\nLocal Python urllib retrieval of the page returned HTTP 200 for the source URL and extracted approximately 175,864 characters of page text with Python html.parser. Case-sensitive searches in the extracted page text returned no occurrence of \"Ronaldo\" and no occurrence of \"Messi\". The same terms were not found using the browser page find function on the rendered page.\n\n[plaintiff] PX-R1 Defendant formal transcript extraction for limited rebuttal use\nSource: Roll Call / Factba.se\nURL: https://rollcall.com/factbase/trump/transcript/donald-trump-remarks-fifa-world-cup-drawing-december-5-2025/\nCaptured page title: Remarks: Donald Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing in Washington - December 5, 2025\n\nRendered page metadata excerpt:\nTopics: Sport; Sport > Competition Discipline > Soccer; Lifestyle and Leisure > Leisure > Game.\nEntities listed: bowl; deal; Donald J. Trump; FIFA World Cup; Mark Carney; place; President; trophy; United States; way.\nSpeakers listed: Gianni Infantino, Donald Trump, Mark Carney, Claudia Sheinbaum.\nSpeaker statistics excerpt: Donald Trump said 25 sentences of a total of 141 sentences; Donald Trump said 274 words of a total of 1009 words; Donald Trump talked 92 seconds of a total of 484 seconds.\n\nFormal transcript excerpt at start of draw:\nMark Carney, 00:00:00-00:00:02: Thank you, my friend.\nGianni Infantino, 00:00:50-00:01:22: So this is the World Cup trophy. This is the official bowl for the World Cup and we are now going to do the draw, ladies and gentlemen. But before that, as is customary, there is always a question that the moderator asks the draw assistant. So I would like to start with Mr. Carney. How big a deal is it to co-host the World Cup for Canada?\n\nFormal transcript excerpt of Trump's soccer answer:\nDonald Trump, 00:03:14-00:03:32: Well, for years, Gianni, they've thought soccer or football would be so big, so fast. And I remember, I shouldn't say this because it was a long time ago, but I remember watching Pele play on a team called the Cosmos, Pele, who was fantastic, as you know. I assume one of the greats.\n\nText-extraction/search notes:\nLocal Python urllib retrieval of the page returned HTTP 200 for the source URL and extracted approximately 175,864 characters of page text with Python html.parser. Case-sensitive searches in the extracted page text returned no occurrence of \"Ronaldo\" and no occurrence of \"Messi\". The same terms were not found using the browser page find function on the rendered page.\n\nSubmitted evidence:\n[plaintiff arguments] GovInfo DCPD202501162 transcript excerpt and metadata (ev_3fc783920414_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-3fc783920414)\nSource: https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/DCPD-202501162/html/DCPD-202501162.htm\nSHA-256: `3fc783920414399098d86210070dd9fe83c14fe1dbded1a56a554f8f4b3448f2`\nBytes: 2641\nRelevance: Official government transcript source corroborating that Trump spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center before the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw and said the strike word Ronaldo in World-Cup-related remarks.\n\n[defendant arguments] Roll Call/Factba.se formal FIFA World Cup Drawing transcript extraction (ev_fbb53e87ccb3_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-fbb53e87ccb3)\nSource: https://rollcall.com/factbase/trump/transcript/donald-trump-remarks-fifa-world-cup-drawing-december-5-2025/\nSHA-256: `fbb53e87ccb3f4381fc2bdc06ac2f2a1ea3848aadde56122b22d34dfbdf4533b`\nBytes: 2032\nRelevance: Formal drawing-program transcript evidence showing a separate formal Draw source from the pre-event reporter exchange; the extracted page text contains no occurrence of Ronaldo or Messi, supporting defendant's event-boundary argument.\n\nTechnical reports:\n[plaintiff] Plaintiff source and adverse-search ledger\nChecked the visible case packet and then searched official/source-specific repositories. GovInfo DCPD202501162 was opened and preserved as submitted evidence; it corroborates the packet transcript, source metadata, location, event date, and Ronaldo passages. The Roll Call/Factba.se formal drawing page rendered despite the packet's password-protection note; browser find searches for 'Ronaldo,' 'Cristiano,' and 'Messi' returned no matches. Plaintiff therefore treats the formal-program transcript as an adverse boundary check, not as proof of a formal-stage mention. The remaining dispute is contractual scope: whether the market clearly excluded public event-linked venue remarks immediately before the formal program.\n\n[defendant] Defense source-check ledger\nDefendant searched for the formal Roll Call/Factba.se transcript identified by the case packet, opened the rendered Roll Call page, and fetched it locally with Python urllib. The fetch returned HTTP 200 for the formal FIFA World Cup Drawing transcript page. Text extraction produced approximately 175,864 characters; searches for \"Ronaldo\" and \"Messi\" returned no occurrences. The retrieval also captured formal-program excerpts, including Infantino's statement that \"we are now going to do the draw\" and Trump's formal soccer answer mentioning Pele rather than Ronaldo. The focused extraction was submitted and accepted as ev_fbb53e87ccb3_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-fbb53e87ccb3.\n\nCall submit_council_vote with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated.\nKeep the rationale brief: no more than three sentences.\n\nCouncil API instructions:\nYou are a council member. Decide the proposition from the admitted record.\nYou may examine admitted evidence through read-only tools when exact bytes, metadata, or exhibit contents matter.\nDo not search the web, introduce new facts, create new evidence, or upload evidence.\nWhen ready, call submit_council_vote exactly once with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated and a concise rationale.\n","state":"ready","status":"ready","tools":[{"description":"Return the current visible arbitration record for this council member.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{},"type":"object"},"name":"get_case","read_only":true},{"description":"List visible immutable record evidence.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{},"type":"object"},"name":"list_evidence","read_only":true},{"description":"Return metadata and read limits for one visible evidence item.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"evidence_id":{"type":"string"}},"required":["evidence_id"],"type":"object"},"name":"stat_evidence","read_only":true},{"description":"Read a bounded byte range from one visible evidence item as base64.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"evidence_id":{"type":"string"},"length":{"minimum":1,"type":"integer"},"offset":{"minimum":0,"type":"integer"}},"required":["evidence_id","offset","length"],"type":"object"},"name":"read_evidence_range","read_only":true},{"description":"Submit one council vote for the current deliberation opportunity.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"rationale":{"type":"string"},"vote":{"enum":["demonstrated","not_demonstrated"],"type":"string"}},"required":["vote","rationale"],"type":"object"},"name":"submit_council_vote","read_only":false}],"turn":{"attempts_max":3,"attempts_remaining":3,"completed":false,"deadline":"2026-06-29T19:58:02.156322961Z","deliberation_round":1,"member_id":"C2","opportunity_id":"deliberation:1:C2","phase":"deliberation","remaining_ms":887183,"role_id":"council","turn_number":10},"wait":{"reason":"ready","state_version":12,"version":15}},"isError":false},"server":"aar","tool":"wait_for_opportunity"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1782762194987}}
{"type":"message_end","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_b9f90c55f2824ea0be4354","toolName":"mcp","content":[{"type":"text","text":"ok: true\nstatus: ready\nstate: ready\nmessage: An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\nafter_version: 15\nafter_opportunity_id: deliberation:1:C2\nmember_id: C2\ncase_id: arb-ex03-20260629192557\nwait_reason: ready\nphase: deliberation\nopportunity_id: deliberation:1:C2\nremaining_ms: 887183\nattempts_remaining: 3\njson: {\"after_opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C2\",\"after_version\":15,\"case_id\":\"arb-ex03-20260629192557\",\"limits\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"max_evidence_read_bytes\":65536,\"max_evidence_read_bytes_per_opportunity\":524288,\"max_evidence_reads_per_opportunity\":32,\"max_response_bytes\":131072,\"remaining_evidence_read_bytes_for_opportunity\":524288,\"remaining_evidence_reads_for_opportunity\":32},\"member_id\":\"C2\",\"message\":\"An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\",\"ok\":true,\"prompt\":\"Role: council member\\nMember ID: C2\\nDeliberation round: 1\\nProposition: For the Kalshi market \\\"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\\", the strike \\\"Ronaldo\\\" should resolve Yes because Trump said \\\"Ronaldo\\\" in public remarks at the World Cup Draw venue immediately before the formal program, and the market wording plus the governing mention-market terms did not clearly exclude those event-linked remarks.\\nStandard of evidence: Preponderance of the evidence.\\nPersona:\\nYou are a careful juror and council member.\\n\\nEvaluate the record faithfully. Decide only from the evidence, the stated rules, and the applicable burden of proof. Do not favor either side, fill gaps with speculation, or ignore uncertainty.\\n\\nGive weight to reliable sources, direct evidence, consistent reasoning, and clear admissions. Discount unsupported claims, rhetorical force, irrelevant facts, and conclusions that exceed the record.\\n\\nWhen the evidence supports one answer, state it plainly. When the evidence is incomplete or balanced, say so. Be concise, honest, and exact.\\n\\nRecord:\\nOpenings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, this case is not mainly about whether the syllables were spoken. The case-packet transcript says they were. The real dispute is the market boundary: when Kalshi asked what Trump would say \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw,\\\" did that phrase clearly exclude his public, event-linked remarks at the World Cup Draw venue immediately before the formal program? On this record, it did not.\\n\\nThe market page fixes the contract at issue: the public title was \\\"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\\"; the contract family was PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION; the strike was \\\"Ronaldo\\\"; Kalshi challenged the resolution as No; and the requested resolution is Yes. That means the council's task is to apply the mention-market terms to that title and strike, not to import a narrower limitation that the market did not plainly announce.\\n\\nThe reporter-exchange packet is direct evidence on the word and setting. It is titled as remarks in an exchange with reporters prior to the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw, dated December 5, 2025. It places the President at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts, speaking with FIFA President Gianni Infantino and reporters in a sequence repeatedly labeled around the 2026 World Cup and the Draw. In that exchange, in a soccer discussion, Trump says he met Ronaldo, praises him, and uses \\\"Ronaldo\\\" as a distinct standalone word. Under the mention rules, a distinct standalone appearance of the strike is the kind of use that counts if it falls within the time period.\\n\\nThe terms matter because they do not say that an event market is limited only to scripted remarks from a formal stage segment. They define a time period as potentially an event or context, and they give the Exchange power to specify what is included when a time period refers to a specific event. They also distinguish official/public event content from behind-the-scenes, rehearsals, and unofficial recordings. That distinction helps plaintiff: the packet is not a rumor, rehearsal, private soundcheck, or leaked recording. It is a sourced public transcript of remarks at the event venue, immediately tied to the Draw. If Kalshi meant \\\"only the formal televised draw program after doors close\\\" or \\\"only remarks in the separate formal archive,\\\" it needed to say so clearly.\\n\\nI also want to be candid about what the packet does not yet prove. The formal-draw archive note says a separate archived transcript page exists for Trump's formal attendance remarks, but that the session could not retrieve the full text because the page was password-protected. So, at opening, plaintiff is not asking you to infer that the formal program itself contained \\\"Ronaldo.\\\" Nor does plaintiff need that inference. The Yes theory is that the qualifying period reasonably includes the public pre-program reporter exchange that was part of Trump's World Cup Draw appearance. The formal archive is relevant because it marks defendant's likely narrower boundary; it does not resolve the boundary in defendant's favor.\\n\\nProvenance and weight also favor treating the packet seriously at this stage. The market and terms files are system case-packet records. The reporter exchange includes a source URL to a public presidential transcript source and notes a corrected transcript date, while also acknowledging that some audio could not be verified because the audio was incomplete. That caveat may affect inaudible portions, but it does not erase the visible, contextual Ronaldo passage. Later, when evidence admission opens, the parties should preserve the official transcript source, any govinfo or Presidency Project copy, the market page capture, and any accessible formal-program transcript or video. The adverse check should ask whether the formal program omits the word, but omission there would matter only if the council first accepts the defense's artificially narrow reading of \\\"during.\\\"\\n\\nThe plaintiff's burden is preponderance. The record already points to a straightforward path to Yes: Trump, the specified entity, said the specified strike as a standalone word in public remarks linked to and immediately preceding the World Cup Draw at the venue; the market title and governing terms did not clearly exclude that event-linked exchange. On a fair reading of the contract the trader saw, the challenged No resolution should give way to Yes.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the defense opening is simple: this case is not won by proving that the word \\\"Ronaldo\\\" appears somewhere in a public transcript. The plaintiff must prove, by a preponderance, that the word was said during the market's specified event: the FIFA World Cup Draw.\\n\\nThe current packet leaves that critical link unproven. The market page does not say \\\"while Trump was at the venue,\\\" \\\"during a World Cup press availability,\\\" or \\\"during any remarks connected to the Draw.\\\" It says: \\\"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\\" The challenged resolution was No. The requested Yes theory therefore needs more than event-adjacent context; it needs a boundary showing that the reporter exchange was part of the Draw period the market asked traders to price.\\n\\nThe plaintiff's own best transcript cuts against that boundary. The case-packet file is titled \\\"Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw.\\\" It says the President's remarks were joined in progress, and the source note says portions could not be verified because the audio was incomplete. It places Trump at the Kennedy Center and includes World Cup topics, and yes, it contains \\\"Ronaldo\\\" as a standalone word in a soccer exchange. But its title and structure identify those remarks as an exchange with reporters prior to the Draw, not the formal Draw itself.\\n\\nThe terms do not rescue plaintiff from that distinction. They define a mention market around words used by the entity during the time period. A time period may be a specific event, and when it is a specific event, the Exchange may specify what is included. The technical details also distinguish official presentation content from behind-the-scenes, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings unless those are officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. Those provisions do not mean every public, nearby, event-related conversation becomes part of the event. They make the event boundary the central question.\\n\\nThe formal-draw archive note reinforces why the distinction matters. It reports that there is a separate archived transcript page for Trump's formal attendance remarks at the FIFA World Cup Drawing, but that the full text was not retrieved because the page was password-protected. That note does not prove the formal program omitted Ronaldo. It also does not prove the formal program included it. What it does show, at opening, is that the record itself separates the pre-event reporter exchange from the formal drawing remarks.\\n\\nSo the defense will focus the council on proof of inclusion, not mere association. If later phases produce a market page provision, official broadcast record, program transcript, video metadata, or source-agency material showing that the red-carpet reporter exchange was officially part of the FIFA World Cup Draw presentation for this market, the council can weigh that. If the later evidence instead shows a formal program with a separate pre-program press availability, then the correct result is No even though the word was spoken nearby.\\n\\nOn this opening record, plaintiff has shown a Ronaldo mention in remarks prior to the event. Plaintiff has not shown that those remarks occurred during the market event. The defense position is that Kalshi's No resolution follows the market wording and the mention-market terms unless plaintiff supplies that missing boundary proof.\\n\\nArguments:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the merits question is whether the contract clearly limited “during the FIFA World Cup Draw” to only the formal staged ceremony. Plaintiff submits that it did not, and the record now proves the Yes result by a preponderance.\\n\\nFirst, the market itself is broad. PX-1 identifies the public question as “What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?”, contract family PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION, strike “Ronaldo,” challenged resolution No, and requested resolution Yes. The market page does not say “during the formal televised ceremony,” “on the main stage only,” or “excluding public remarks immediately before the program at the venue.” That absence matters because Kalshi drafted the boundary traders had to price.\\n\\nSecond, the word was said. PX-2, the case-packet transcript, and PX-5, the GovInfo/OFR source excerpt, both show Trump used “Ronaldo” as a standalone word in soccer-related remarks. PX-5 is especially useful on provenance: it is the GovInfo Compilation of Presidential Documents source, published by the Office of the Federal Register/NARA, for DCPD202501162. It identifies the same event date, title, and source note, and it places the remarks at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center. In the relevant passage, Trump says he met Ronaldo, then says Ronaldo is great; later, when asked whether he played soccer or football, Trump says he was not Ronaldo or Messi. Either use satisfies the mention rule if the remarks fall within the market’s time period.\\n\\nThird, the remarks are event-linked in the way the market title reasonably covers. PX-2 and PX-5 are not private gossip, rehearsal, or an unofficial leak. They are public presidential remarks at the World Cup Draw venue, with FIFA President Infantino present, repeatedly discussing the Draw, the World Cup, ticket sales, the Kennedy Center, the audience, and the imminent program. The transcript itself includes headings such as “2026 World Cup Draw Event,” “2026 World Cup Draw Event/John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts,” and “2026 World Cup Draw/Ticket Sales for World Cup.” Trump and Infantino even discuss being a little late to “get in there” and the audience waiting. That sequence is not a random earlier interview; it is part of the public event appearance immediately surrounding the Draw.\\n\\nFourth, PX-3’s terms do not impose defendant’s formal-only line. They say the underlying is words used by the entity during the specified time period; a time period may be an event or context; and, when a time period refers to a specific event, the Exchange may specify what is included. They also say official/published content presented as part of the official presentation can count, while behind-the-scenes, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings do not count unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. Those exclusions show what this is not. The transcript is an official published record of public remarks at the event venue, not a hidden backstage clip. Nothing in PX-1 or PX-3 clearly tells traders that public, event-linked venue remarks immediately before the formal program are out.\\n\\nDefendant’s best point is PX-4 and the formal Roll Call/Factba.se page: there is a separate formal-drawing transcript, and my search found no “Ronaldo” there. Plaintiff does not hide that. But that adverse point proves only that the narrower formal-program source may omit the strike. It does not answer the contractual question. If Kalshi had meant to resolve solely by that formal transcript, it could have said so. Instead, the public market title used the broader phrase “during the FIFA World Cup Draw,” and the mention terms leave event boundaries to what the market clearly specifies.\\n\\nOn burden, plaintiff does not need absolute certainty or a formal-stage mention. Plaintiff must show it is more likely than not that the market wording plus terms include the event-linked remarks. The evidence satisfies that standard: PX-1 gives no exclusion; PX-2 and PX-5 prove the standalone Ronaldo mentions in public World Cup Draw venue remarks; PX-3 supplies a flexible event/time-period framework and excludes only categories unlike this source; PX-4 merely identifies the defense’s alternate formal-program boundary. The fair resolution is Yes.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the record now makes the defense point sharper, not weaker. Plaintiff has proved that Trump said \\\"Ronaldo\\\" in an official transcript of remarks connected to the World Cup Draw. Plaintiff has not proved that those remarks were during the market event.\\n\\nStart with the contract. DX/PX-1 gives the trader-facing question: \\\"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\\" It does not say \\\"at the Kennedy Center,\\\" \\\"on World Cup Draw day,\\\" \\\"in remarks prior to the Draw,\\\" or \\\"in any public press exchange associated with the Draw.\\\" For this strike to resolve Yes, the relevant mention must fall inside that specified time period.\\n\\nThe strongest evidence of the Ronaldo utterance is also the strongest evidence against plaintiff's boundary. PX-2 and PX-5 are titled \\\"Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw.\\\" PX-5, plaintiff's GovInfo/OFR source, confirms the same title, says the remarks were joined in progress, identifies the source as an exchange with the news media, and notes that some portions could not be verified because the audio was incomplete. That evidence proves an official pre-event reporter transcript. It does not prove the reporter exchange was the FIFA World Cup Draw.\\n\\nThe terms, PX-3, require words used by the entity during the specified time period. They permit an event or context as a time period, and they discuss what is included when the time period is a specific event. That framework does not turn all event-adjacent speech into event speech. The distinction between official presentation content and non-included behind-the-scenes or unofficial content matters because the question is not just whether a record is public or official. The question is whether this source was part of the market's event period. A public official transcript can still be a transcript of remarks prior to the event.\\n\\nDX-2 supplies the missing contrast. It is a focused extraction from the separate Roll Call/Factba.se formal FIFA World Cup Drawing transcript. That page is the formal source identified in the case-packet archive note. It is titled \\\"Remarks: Donald Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing in Washington - December 5, 2025.\\\" Its transcript begins with the formal drawing participants; at 00:00:50, Infantino says, \\\"This is the World Cup trophy\\\" and \\\"we are now going to do the draw.\\\" The page's Trump soccer answer mentions Pele and the Cosmos, not Ronaldo. The extracted page text was searched for both \\\"Ronaldo\\\" and \\\"Messi\\\" and neither appears.\\n\\nThat does not prove Trump never said Ronaldo anywhere at the venue. It proves the opposite boundary from plaintiff's: the formal Draw transcript is separate from the pre-event reporter exchange, and the formal transcript does not contain the strike. Plaintiff needs a bridge between those two sources. It has not offered one. There is no market page detail saying red-carpet or pre-program press remarks count. There is no official program metadata showing the reporter exchange was part of the Draw presentation. There is no source hierarchy provision selecting the pre-event reporter exchange over the formal Draw transcript for this market.\\n\\nPlaintiff argues ambiguity should favor Yes because Kalshi could have drafted a narrower rule. But this is a preponderance case about a challenged No resolution, not a penalty for every conceivable ambiguity. The ordinary reading of \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw\\\" is the draw program, not every public appearance immediately before it. The record's own labels preserve that ordinary line: \\\"Prior to\\\" on the Ronaldo source; \\\"Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing\\\" on the formal source; and a formal transcript that starts the draw and omits the strike.\\n\\nWeight and provenance also favor the defense on the decisive issue. PX-5 is official and useful, but it authenticates a pre-event reporter exchange. DX-2 is a captured formal transcript extraction from the source class identified in PX-4; its absence finding is limited but material. PX-4 was initially only a note that the formal page existed and could not be retrieved. We have now retrieved and searched it. The adverse check therefore confirms, rather than merely speculates, that the formal drawing transcript does not carry plaintiff's Ronaldo mention.\\n\\nThe council should resolve the proposition against plaintiff. The record shows Trump said Ronaldo before the FIFA World Cup Draw in an event-linked reporter exchange. It does not show he said Ronaldo during the FIFA World Cup Draw. On this market wording and these terms, the challenged No resolution should stand.\\n\\nRebuttals:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, defendant’s new formal-transcript extraction proves less than defendant needs.\\n\\nPlaintiff accepts the narrow fact defendant has now preserved: the Roll Call/Factba.se formal drawing-program extraction contains no “Ronaldo” or “Messi.” That is why plaintiff did not build the case on a formal-stage mention. The proposition instead asks whether the market wording and mention terms clearly excluded Trump’s public, official, event-linked remarks at the venue immediately before the formal program. Defendant has not supplied that exclusion.\\n\\nDefendant’s argument treats the title “Prior to the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw” as if “prior to” automatically means outside the Kalshi market’s event period. But PX-1 does not say “formal transcript only,” “after the draw host begins,” “after 00:00:50,” or “excluding press availability at the venue.” It asks what Trump would say “during the FIFA World Cup Draw.” The source label tells us sequence; it does not tell us the market’s legal boundary.\\n\\nDX-2 actually illustrates why defendant’s bright line is chosen after the fact. In defendant’s own formal extraction, the page begins before the mechanical draw: Mark Carney speaks at 00:00:00, and Infantino says at 00:00:50, “we are now going to do the draw.” If “during the FIFA World Cup Draw” can include ceremony and preamble on the formal page before the draw itself begins, then the phrase is not self-defining down to a single moment or transcript. The question is what the market clearly specified. It did not specify defendant’s transcript-only rule.\\n\\nThe terms do not fill that gap for defendant. PX-3 excludes hidden categories such as rehearsals, sound checks, unofficial recordings, and behind-the-scenes content unless officially published as part of the period. PX-2 and PX-5 are not those categories. PX-5 is an official GovInfo/OFR presidential transcript, published with source metadata, at 11:13 a.m. at the Kennedy Center, with FIFA’s president present and the World Cup Draw repeatedly discussed. That gives the Ronaldo mentions strong provenance and an event connection; it does not make them informal backstage chatter.\\n\\nDefendant says plaintiff needs a bridge. The bridge is the market text plus the terms’ failure to draw the narrow line defendant proposes. A No resolution can stand only if the contract fairly told traders that “during the FIFA World Cup Draw” meant only the separate formal-program transcript. On this record, the more likely reading is broader: public, official remarks at the venue, immediately tied to and immediately preceding the World Cup Draw program, were within the event-linked period unless clearly excluded.\\n\\nSo DX-2 narrows one factual issue but does not decide the case. It shows no formal-stage Ronaldo mention. It does not show that the market excluded the official pre-program event remarks where Trump did say Ronaldo. Under the preponderance standard, the Yes resolution remains the fair one.\\n\\nSurrebuttals:\\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff’s rebuttal usefully narrows the dispute. Plaintiff accepts that the formal Roll Call/Factba.se drawing transcript contains no “Ronaldo” or “Messi.” So the case remains entirely about whether a separate reporter exchange titled “Prior to the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw” should be treated as inside the market period.\\n\\nPlaintiff says “prior to” is only sequence, not legal boundary. But sequence is exactly what the market phrase makes material. The contract asks what Trump would say “during the FIFA World Cup Draw.” A source-agency title identifying the Ronaldo transcript as an exchange with reporters prior to that Draw is not a stray label; it is the best record description of when and what that source is. Plaintiff cannot convert that source into the event itself by saying the market failed to list every excluded pre-event setting.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s formal-preamble point also does not carry the burden. Yes, the formal transcript begins before the mechanical ball selection, and Infantino says at 00:00:50 that “we are now going to do the draw.” But that supports the defense distinction. A host’s preamble inside the formal drawing transcript is part of the program. A separate press exchange, separately titled and sourced as prior to the Draw, is not made part of the program simply because it happened nearby and discussed the same event.\\n\\nNor does official publication settle the issue. PX-5 strengthens provenance: Trump did say Ronaldo in an official public transcript. But provenance answers whether the words were said, not whether they were said during the market’s specified event. The terms require both: the word by the entity, and the word during the time period. Plaintiff has the first element. The second is still missing.\\n\\nThe remaining bridge plaintiff proposes is essentially: public, official, event-linked, and not expressly excluded. That is not enough under a preponderance standard when the same record supplies a cleaner boundary: the Ronaldo source is prior to the Draw, and the formal Draw source omits the strike. The challenged No resolution should stand.\\n\\nClosings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the record has narrowed to one real issue.\\n\\nThe word is proven. The market page identifies the strike as “Ronaldo” and the challenged resolution as No. The case-packet transcript and the GovInfo/OFR excerpt prove that Trump said “Ronaldo” as a standalone word in public remarks at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center, in a World Cup Draw setting, with FIFA President Infantino present, and amid repeated discussion of the Draw, the Kennedy Center, ticket sales, the audience, and the imminent event. That is strong provenance: GovInfo, NARA/OFR, DCPD202501162, matching the packet source and note.\\n\\nDefendant has also proved its best fact. The Roll Call/Factba.se formal-program extraction does not contain “Ronaldo” or “Messi.” Plaintiff does not ask you to find otherwise. If the market had said “only the formal drawing transcript,” defendant would win. But that is not the market traders saw.\\n\\nThe market asked: “What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?” It did not say “during the formal transcript only,” “after the host announces the draw has begun,” “excluding public press remarks at the venue,” or “excluding remarks immediately before the program.” The governing terms do not add that limitation. They define words used by the entity during the time period, allow event/context time periods, and exclude categories such as rehearsals, sound checks, behind-the-scenes content, and unofficial recordings. Plaintiff’s source is none of those. It is an official public presidential transcript of event-linked remarks at the venue.\\n\\nDefendant’s formal extraction shows why a bright line cannot simply be assumed. Even on that page, before balls are drawn, there is ceremony, introduction, and Infantino saying “we are now going to do the draw.” Event boundaries are not self-defining. The question is whether Kalshi clearly chose defendant’s narrower boundary. The record contains no such choice.\\n\\nSo the burden is met. More likely than not, a reasonable reading of the market and terms includes Trump’s official, public, venue-based remarks immediately tied to the World Cup Draw. The strongest contrary evidence proves only that a narrower formal transcript omits the strike. It does not prove the contract excluded the remarks where the strike was actually said.\\n\\nThe challenged No resolution should be overturned. The strike “Ronaldo” should resolve Yes.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff’s closing concedes the decisive factual split: the formal World Cup Drawing transcript contains no “Ronaldo” or “Messi.” The only Ronaldo evidence is the separate official transcript titled “Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw.”\\n\\nThat is enough to decide the case. The market did not ask what Trump would say at the Kennedy Center, on World Cup Draw day, in public presidential remarks, or in event-linked press availability. It asked what Trump would say “during the FIFA World Cup Draw.” The terms require the word to be used by the entity during the specified time period. Plaintiff has proven the word and the speaker. It has not proven the time period.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s strongest point is that the market did not expressly say “formal transcript only” or “exclude pre-program remarks.” But plaintiff has the burden. A challenged No resolution does not become Yes merely because the contract could have been even more verbose. The record must make it more likely than not that the pre-event reporter exchange was inside the market period. The record does the opposite.\\n\\nThe source labels matter. PX-2 and PX-5 are official and probative, but they are official proof of remarks prior to the Draw. The formal Roll Call/Factba.se extraction is the source for Trump’s formal attendance at the FIFA World Cup Drawing; it begins the program, includes the draw presentation, and omits the strike. Plaintiff’s theory asks you to treat a separate prior reporter exchange as “during” the Draw even though the formal Draw source exists and does not contain the word.\\n\\nThe terms do not collapse that distinction. They recognize event/context time periods and official presentation content, but they still require the word to occur during the chosen time period. Official publication proves provenance. Event connection proves relevance. Neither proves inclusion. A public official transcript can be accurately preserved and still be outside the market window if it is, as titled, prior to the event.\\n\\nSo the fair synthesis is narrow and grounded: Trump said Ronaldo in event-linked public remarks before the FIFA World Cup Draw; Trump did not say Ronaldo in the formal drawing transcript preserved in this record; and no admitted market term or source-chain evidence bridges the pre-event exchange into the market’s “during the FIFA World Cup Draw” period.\\n\\nUnder the preponderance standard, plaintiff has not carried the proposition. The challenged No resolution should stand.\\n\\nExhibits:\\n[plaintiff] PX-1 Market page and challenged resolution\\nMarket URL: https://kalshi.com/markets/kxtrumpmentionb/trump-mention-b/kxtrumpmentionb-25dec06\\n\\nPublic market title: What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\n\\nContract family: PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION\\n\\nStrike at issue: Ronaldo\\n\\nChallenged resolution: No\\n\\nRequested resolution: Yes\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-2 Pre-event reporter exchange transcript\\nRemarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\nDecember 05, 2025\\n\\n[The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\\nThe President. It's a great honor to be here. Gianni has done a fantastic job. We're setting records—[inaudible].\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. Well, I think so. They have a little bit of a shot. Pretty stiff competition. But I would say they would have a small chance.\\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize\\nQ. [Inaudible]—win the FIFA Peace Award?\\nThe President. Well, it would be an honor.\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\nQ. Will you root for some selection? Will you root for someone?\\nThe President. Well, I root for a lot of countries, but in this case, I'll be rooting for the U.S.A. [Laughter]\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. That's great. That's great. We really love it.\\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize\\nQ. Mr. President, have you been told that you are going to receive the inaugural peace prize today——\\nThe President. I have not——\\nQ. ——from FIFA?\\nThe President. I have not been told. There's a rumor about it, but I have not been told. That would be a great honor, and I'm a big fan of Gianni, as you know.\\nQ. What can fans expect——\\nQ. Are you hoping to receive that?\\nThe President. Excuse me.\\nQ. Are you hoping to receive the peace prize?\\nThe President. Well, I don't like to say \\\"hope,\\\" but it would be a great honor.\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. What can fans expect of, like, the World Cup in the U.S.?\\nThe President. I think it's going to be fantastic. We've set every record you can set.\\nQ. What are you telling people who are worried——\\nFédération Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) President Giovanni V. Infantino\\nQ. [Inaudible]—friend Gianni—[inaudible]—a word about him?\\nThe President. I think he has done a fantastic job.\\nThe President's Schedule\\nQ. Are you going to be meeting with the President of Mexico today and the——\\nThe President. We might. Yes.\\nQ. ——Prime Minister of Canada as well?\\nThe President. I might. I might do that.\\nQ. Will you be discussing immigration and trade with them?\\nThe President. Yes, we'll be discussing.\\n[At this point, the President and Mr. Infantino posed for photographs.]\\nThe President. Thank you, everybody.\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event/John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts\\nQ. Mr. President, what do you think about the crowd?\\nThe President. Oh, look, the new star—[inaudible].\\nCongratulations.\\nQ. Thank you.\\nThe President. You're the new star of television and Fox.\\nQ. Thank you. How are you doing, Mr. President?\\nThe President. I'm doing very well.\\nQ. What do you think about the crowd here?\\nThe President. I think the crowd is great, and I think the building is great. We've made a lot of improvements over the last 6 months. Taking—the Kennedy Center was in very bad shape. Now it's getting to be really good. And in 6 months, it's going to be incredible with the improvements we've made.\\nQ. The first time for the U.S. to host since the nineties.\\nThe President. Right.\\nQ. Are you ready for it?\\nThe President. I'm ready for it, and they're ready for it. And Gianni, who you know——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——has done a fantastic job with FIFA. And we're looking to have—you know, we're set—we have already set records for tickets sales. I don't think there's ever been anything like it in any sport. And so, I want to congratulate you.\\nMr. Infantino. Thank you.\\nThe President. I don't even have to wait. But major records have been set.\\nHow are you?\\nQ. Good, how are you, sir?\\nThe President. Nice to see you.\\nQ. Today it's not football—American football. It's soccer. It's——\\nThe President. Right.\\nQ. ——the big event of soccer.\\nThe President. That's right. That's right.\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\nQ. So can you tell me about this big day today?\\nThe President. It's just a big day, and it's a great sport. And it really is coming to America. And never—nobody ever thought a thing like this could happen. And I'm very happy to say that we've already set the alltime record on ticket sales long before the first ball is kicked. Right?\\nMr. Infantino. A hundred percent. One hundred percent.\\n2026 World Cup Host Cities\\nQ. You've had some concerns about crime in American cities, some of the cities that will be hosting. Have they remedied that for you? Are you still considering maybe asking FIFA to move some of those cities?\\nThe President. No, I don't want to do that. But I will tell you, if they do have a problem, by the time we get there, we'll take care of that problem. We can solve that problem.\\nI've proven that in DC and everywhere else we went, so we'll take care of that very easily. So, if they have a problem, hopefully, they'll let us know that, and we will solve any problem.\\nOkay? Thank you.\\nQ. Thank you so much.\\nMr. Infantino. All right, thank you so much.\\nQ. Thank you, Mr. President.\\nQ. Thank you. Appreciate it.\\nThe President. Congratulations.\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. Mr. President, Brazilian television. America will be hosting the World Cup and the Olympics in 2 years. How important it is—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. I think very. It's a great honor. I think Gianni is doing a phenomenal job. We've set every record on ticket sales. It's been really fantastic. But Gianni has done an unbelievable job with FIFA.\\nThe President's Experience With Soccer\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. He was a great—not only that. I got to see a man name Pelé play—right?—that tells you how old I am—when he was on the Cosmos. Do you remember that a long time ago? And it was quite a treat. That was quite an event. And he was—not only was he playing, he was great. He scored two goals, I think. And so, I was one of the few who got to see Pelé, and I assume he is one of your alltime greats. Right?\\nMr. Infantino. Definitely.\\nThe President. So I got to see him.\\nThe President's Favorite World Cup Competitor\\nQ. Do you have some favorite teams for World Cup?\\nThe President. Well, I have a favorite. It's the U.S.A. [Laughter] I don't know what their chances are, Gianni, but maybe the U.S.A. is the——\\nMr. Infantino. They're getting better and better, actually.\\nThe President. I think they'll do well.\\nMr. Infantino. They are getting better and better.\\nThe President. I think they'll do well.\\nThank you very much, everybody.\\nQ. Thank you so much.\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. Mr. President, World Cup in America just means—[inaudible]. So what do you expect from this World Cup?\\nThe President. [Inaudible]—record business and only in the United States, but we're also doing record ticket sales with FIFA. And they've already bought—beat their highest record. And we—you know, this a long time before the first ball is kicked. You've sold more tickets than they've ever done before, and better pricing than they've ever gotten before. It's a tremendous success. And it's an honor. And Gianni has done a phenomenal job with FIFA.\\nQ. [Inaudible]—ever?\\nThe President. I think so. I think it's going to be—I mean, ideally, you want to see that every year. Every 4 years, it gets bigger and better. I think we have set every record in the book. We're very happy about it.\\nThank you.\\nThe President's Favorite World Cup Competitor\\nQ. [Inaudible]—part of America. Who are you going to support as well?\\nThe President. Well, I think I have to support U.S.A. Otherwise, I'd be in trouble. I wouldn't be President for long.\\nMr. Infantino. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. [Inaudible]—but you have a lot of great teams. You're going to have a lot of great teams.\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\\\"football,\\\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\\n2026 World Cup Draw/Ticket Sales for World Cup\\nQ. How does it feel to be part of this amazing event? And obviously, your being a part of participating in all the—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. The President of Mexico is here, and she's doing a very good job. She's a good woman, very, very excellent job. It's an honor, and we're setting every record, and you're helping us set those records.\\nMr. Infantino. And we will do it.\\nThe President. You know, Mexico and Canada are helping us set those records. But as you know, we have a record in ticket sales already, long before the first ball is kicked, and we're going to do great.\\nI think that Gianni—as you know, he's the head, and he has done a fantastic job.\\nU.S. Cooperation With Mexico and Canada\\nQ. And how is the biggest challenge being three countries?\\nThe President. Well, I think that—do you mean for the three countries?\\nWell, they've gotten together really well, I mean.\\nMr. Infantino. All right.\\nThe President. They're getting along very well.\\nMr. Infantino. Collaboration is fantastic between the three.\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer/2026 World Cup\\nQ. And you like soccer?\\nThe President. I do. I like it. I like it more and more.\\nQ. Yes?\\nThe President. I like it. It's growing in this country—very, really—I mean, someday, maybe it's going to be bigger than anything else.\\nMr. Infantino. We'll have to become number one.\\nThe President. I will say this——\\nMr. Infantino. Definitely.\\nThe President. ——the ticket sales——\\nQ. Definitely will happen.\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. Ticket sales are bigger than anything we have ever done in the history of the country, in terms of sports.\\nMr. Infantino. For certain.\\nQ. And the audience is going to be huge.\\nThe President. The audience is going to be tremendous.\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. Yes.\\nMr. Infantino. Six billion people.\\nThe President. [Inaudible]\\nQ. Six billion? That's amazing.\\nMr. Infantino. Six billion people.\\nAnd today, one billion.\\nQ. Wow.\\nMr. Infantino. [Inaudible]\\nQ. Enjoy show time. Thank you so much.\\nThe President. [Inaudible]\\nQ. Mr. President, how are you? Just a quick—[inaudible].\\nQ. This is for Telemundo.\\nThe President. How are you?\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\nQ. Hello, Mr. President. How are you? This for Telemundo.\\nThe President. How are you? Good.\\nQ. How are you?\\nThe President. Very good. Thank you.\\nQ. How does it feel to have the most important event of sports—that global—in the U.S.?\\nThe President. Well, we do. And right at the Kennedy Center. I'm Chairman of the Kennedy Center. And I hear the Kennedy Center is doing a very good job, so it feels great. Really good.\\nAnd Telemundo is doing a good job, too. Thank you.\\nQ. Thank you.\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. What is the significance of hosting the FIFA World Cup this year?\\nThe President. It's a—in terms of sports, I would say the ultimate. There is no sport like this. It's the biggest sport in the world. And we are setting every record. You know, our ticket sales have gone and set every—every sport—no matter what it is, we've set the record. So—and every though it's very early, there's no ball being kicked yet, but we've already set a ticket sales record.\\nArgentina National Team\\nQ. How do you see Argentinean team for this World Cup?\\nThe President. Well, I love Argentina. And your President is doing a very good job, as you know. Milei. You know that right? It's make Argentina great again. MAGA.\\nQ. And——\\nU.S. National Team\\nQ. Do you think the States are building a powerful team for next year?\\nThe President. Who?\\nQ. The States.\\nThe President. Oh, yes. Sure. I—you're going to have a lot of powerful teams. Everybody has a lot of powerful teams, but you're going to have a lot of great teams. [Inaudible]\\nU.S. Role in Hosting the 2026 World Cup\\nQ. Mr. President, what does it mean for you guys to host the World Cup right here in the U.S.?\\nThe President. I'm honored to host it. It's a great honor. I mean, it's turned out to be bigger than we thought. We're setting a record for ticket sales, the likes of which no sport has ever seen before.\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\\nThe President. But they have a little more speed.\\nBut no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\\nPopularity of Soccer in Latin America\\nQ. Mr. President, a message for the Latin America and soccer fans?\\nThe President. Yes, I am. And Latin America is great. And they have great soccer. So, good luck in the matches.\\n[A reporter asked a question in Spanish, which was translated by an interpreter as follows.]\\nU.S. Visas for World Cup Ticketholders\\nQ. Who is going to be in—[inaudible]—about these visas for the—these fans that want to come here to the World Cup?\\nThe President. Well, we're going to make it very easy for them. We're working on that right now. We're going to make it very easy. It's going to be a very easy process.\\nQ. Okay. Say, hi to Colombia over there.\\nThe President. Hello. Is that Colombia?\\nQ. Yes.\\nThe President. I love Colombia. Hello, Colombia. [Laughter]\\nQ. Okay. Okay. Muy bien.\\nThe President. So where are you from?\\nQ. Paraguay.\\nThe President. Oh.\\nQ. He's from Paraguay. Yes.\\nThe President. Very good. I love it. I—it's a beautiful country. We get along very well with them. We do a little trade deal with them, and they like us. And that's what's happening.\\nQ. Panama.\\nThe President. Where?\\nVery good. I like the canal. [Laughter] That canal is pretty good.\\n[A reporter spoke in Spanish; no translation was provided.]\\n2026 World Cup\\nThe President. What?\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. Well, it's going to be incredible. The event is going to be very good. Just this event alone—it's at the Kennedy Center. I see you have it fixed up perfectly.\\nMr. Infantino. It will set the tone.\\nThe President. Right? It's beautiful.\\nMr. Infantino. It's beautiful.\\nThe President. It's a beautiful place.\\nHave a good time.\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President.\\n[A reporter spoke in Spanish; no translation was provided.]\\nMr. Infantino. No, gracias. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. It's great.\\nJohn F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts/Renovation Work\\nQ. Mr. President, the U.S. press?\\nThe President. Thank you, everybody, very much. It's a great honor. This has been an honor for a lot of reasons. Number one, they've sold more tickets than any event has ever sold already—long before the kickoff.\\nAnd number two, we've done a lot of work at the Kennedy Center. It was falling apart, and now it's pretty much back. And we'll get it back within the next 4 or 5 months through construction, and—but you see the way it looks.\\nAnd Gianni is just telling me—who's done an incredible job, by the way. He's just telling, you know, how good a job we've done.\\nMr. Infantino. That's right.\\nThe President. You can look at the walls. The marble was broken. Everything was a mess. And we've really taken the Kennedy Center—a lot of people thought it was going to be ripped down, and we did just the opposite. So we've done a really great renovation job on it. And over the next 3, 4 months, it will be complete. And we're honored to have it here, and it's been—it's been very special.\\nWe've set a record on ticket sales, as you probably heard, already, even way before—long before the event itself. And we're working with Canada, and we're working with Mexico. And it's been a really spectacular—so far, it's been spectacular.\\nDaniel [Daniel Baldwin, One America News Network], do you have a question?\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. What are your expectations? You once said that the FIFA World Cup is an opportunity to put—a once-in-a-lifetime opportunity to put the greatness of the United States on display.\\nThe President. Well, I think—\\nQ. One billion eyeballs will be watching, Mr. President.\\nThe President. Yes, I—think——\\nQ. What will they here today?\\nThe President. Even today, I understand. I hear that, you know——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——I know we're a little late to get in there, but——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——that's okay.\\nMr. Infantino. They wait.\\nThe President. So all my friends, I guess they have to wait. They have no choice, right? [Laughter]\\nMr. Infantino. Yes, they wait.\\nThe President. But no, the numbers are incredible. I hear today's numbers are——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——very big. I hope CNN is covering this.\\nQ. One billion eyeballs.\\nMr. Infantino. Today, 1 billion eyeballs.\\nThe President. Today's numbers are very, very big.\\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize/The President's Foreign Policy\\nQ. We are covering it. And you're expected to get the FIFA Peace Prize, Mr. President. What would you say to people who say that prize might conflict with your pledge to strike Venezuela?\\nThe President. Well, I think the peace prize—I mean, I settled eight wars. I don't know that I'm getting it. I haven't been officially noticed. I've been hearing about a peace prize, and I'm here to represent our country in a different sense. But I can tell you, I did settle eight wars, and we have a ninth coming, but—which nobody has ever done before.\\nBut I want to really save lives. I don't need prizes. I need to save lives. And we're saving a lot of lives. And I've saved millions and millions of lives, and that's really what I want to do.\\nAnd I also want to run a great country. And the United States right now is the hottest country anywhere in the world. And 1 year ago, it was dead. We had a dead country, and now we have the hottest country anywhere in the world.\\nQ. Mr. President, will you——\\nThe President's Meeting With President Claudia Sheinbaum Pardo of Mexico and Prime Minister Mark Carney of Canada\\nQ. What are you going to discuss with Canada and Mexico, Mr.—what are you going to discuss with the leaders of Canada and Mexico?\\nThe President. Well, we're getting—we're going to meet with both. And we're getting along very well. You know, we're getting along very well. I don't know. I think we have a meeting set up for some time after the event.\\nQ. Will you discuss trade?\\nThe President. Yes, we'll discuss trade. We—get along very well.\\nThank you, everybody, very much.\\nQ. Will you pardon any other Honduran officials?\\nQ. Do you want them to keep trying to indict Ms. James?\\n\\nNOTE: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. In his remarks, he referred to Trey Yingst, chief foreign correspondent, Fox News Channel; Cristiano Ronaldo, forward for Saudi Pro League club Al-Nass and Portugal's national soccer team; and Lionel Messi, forward for Major League Soccer club Inter Miami and Argentina's national team. A reporter referred to New York State Attorney General Letitia James. The transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\n\\nSource URL: https://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/documents/remarks-exchange-with-reporters-prior-the-2026-federation-internationale-des-associations\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-3 PRESMENTION/NEWMENTION terms\\n                                         NEWMENTION\\n\\nScope: These rules shall apply to this contract.\\n\\nUnderlying: The Underlying for this Contract is words used by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nRevisions to the Underlying made after Expiration will not be accounted for in determining the\\nExpiration Value.\\n\\nSource Agency: The Source Agencies are \\u003csource\\u003e.\\n\\nType: The type of Contract is an Event Contract.\\n\\nIssuance: After the initial Contract, Contract iterations will be listed on an as-needed basis at\\nthe discretion of the Exchange and corresponding to the risk management needs of Members.\\n\\n\\u003centity\\u003e: \\u003centity\\u003e refers to the speaker, writer, performer, or communicator specified by the\\nExchange. This may include (but is not limited to): a specific named individual, multiple\\nindividuals specified using AND/OR logic, an individual identified by position or title, a group,\\nband, team or collective entity, a specified member or members of a group, an organization,\\ncompany, or institutional entity, or any combination of the aforementioned.\\n\\nWhen \\u003centity\\u003e is defined by a position or title, the Contract tracks whoever holds that position\\nduring \\u003ctime period\\u003e, even if the individual holding the position changes. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a\\nspecific named individual, the identity remains consistent throughout. Name changes (e.g.,\\nstage names, married names) do not create a new entity. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a group or\\norganization and the Contract does not specify particular members, any official\\ncommunication or statement by any member or designated spokesperson counts. When using\\nAND logic, all specified entities must independently say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e. When\\nusing OR logic, at least one of the specified entities must say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nThe Exchange may specify additional conditions such as “at least X members of” a group or\\n“the majority of” a group.\\n\\n\\u003csource\\u003e: \\u003csource\\u003e refers to a Source Agency or ordered collection of Source Agencies\\nspecified by the Exchange at the time of Contract listing, which will be incorporated into the\\nSource Agency hierarchy above and used to determine the occurrence of the Underlying.\\n\\u003csource\\u003e may refer to a singular agency, multiple agencies, an agency by distinguishing\\ncharacteristics, by category or type (e.g., “official government statistical body,” “primary wire\\nservice”), or any combination thereof. When multiple agencies are specified, they may be\\napplied in the hierarchical order designated by the Exchange if so specified, with the highest-\\nranked available and responsive agency taking precedence for purposes of determining the\\nExpiration Value. A lower-ranked agency shall only be consulted if all higher-ranked agencies\\nare unavailable, unresponsive, have not reported on the Underlying by the Expiration time, or\\nif the Exchange, in its sole discretion, determines that a higher-ranked agency’s reporting is\\nincomplete, erroneous, or otherwise insufficient to determine the Expiration Value. If \\u003csource\\u003e\\ndesignates multiple agencies without specifying a hierarchical order, the Exchange shall\\nresolve any conflict between reporting agencies at its sole discretion.\\n\\n\\u003cword\\u003e: \\u003cword\\u003e refers to the particular word or phrase potentially to be mentioned by\\n\\u003centity\\u003e. It may refer to a word being said a minimum number of times. It may also refer to\\none of multiple words/phrases, any of which are acceptable (e.g., “Doge/Dogecoin”).\\n\\f\\u003ctime period\\u003e: \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific range of time, event or discrete date and\\ntime specified by the Exchange. This may be defined by, but is not limited to: a specific event\\nor context (e.g., “during the State of the Union address”), exact dates or times, relative time\\nmarkers (e.g., “before July 1, 2027,” “in Q1 2026”), event-based periods (e.g., “during any\\ncampaign rally in October 2026,” “during the awards ceremony”), and broader intervals (e.g.,\\n“Q1–Q2 2027,” “January–March 2026”).\\n\\nUnless stated otherwise, “Between” is inclusive of both endpoints, while “before” and “after”\\nexclude the specified date. \\u003ctime period\\u003e may also refer to “Any” or “None”, to multiple dates\\n(even if non-consecutive), or to a singular and discrete date or time.\\n\\nWhen \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event (such as an address, speech, performance, or\\nbroadcast), the Exchange may specify what is included, including whether it includes both live\\nand pre-recorded segments (including whether advertisements are included). Where a\\ntimezone is not specified, ET is assumed.\\n\\n\\nPayout Criterion: The Payout Criterion for the Contract encompasses the Expiration Values that\\n\\u003cword\\u003e is said by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n\\n\\nThe word must appear as a distinct, standalone unit, not buried inside another word. Plural\\nand possessive noun forms count. Other grammatical changes (tense, conjugation, derivation)\\ndo not. If \\u003cword\\u003e appears separated from other words by a space or hyphen or in a\\ncompound form with a space or hyphen, it counts. If \\u003cword\\u003e is fused into a single\\nunhyphenated word, it does not count.\\n\\nIf \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled, and the market contains a\\nstrike stating “Event does not qualify/occur”, such a strike shall resolve “Yes” and all others\\n“No”. If \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled but such strikes are NOT\\nlisted, the Contracts will resolve to the last fair price determined at the discretion of the\\nExchange. If the event is postponed, and such a postponement is announced by the end of the\\nfollowing calendar day to be rescheduled to a time within 14 calendar days, the markets shall\\nremain open. If the event captured in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast, the\\nExchange may keep the market open for 24 hours for the release of an official recording.\\nFurther granular details on conditions for these Contracts is available below.\\n\\nAdditional clarification(s):\\n\\n     Possessive noun forms of \\u003cword\\u003e, plurals, and possessive plural noun forms are\\n     INCLUDED:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigrants” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Egg” → “eggs’ shells” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Russia” → “Russia’s” counts, “Russian” does not\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e exists only in adjective form, no plural form exists:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Economic” → “Economics” does not count (“Economic” is an adjective\\n          for which “Economics” is not a plural)\\n     Plural nouns occurring within proper nouns and noun phrases are included:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Cat” → “Cats the musical” counts\\n\\f    Grammatical variations beyond plurals/possessives are NOT included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigration” does NOT count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Run” → “Running” or “Ran” do NOT count\\n    When \\u003cword\\u003e specifies a plural form, the singular does NOT count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Veterans” → “Veteran” does NOT count\\n    Words that are spelled the same as the plural form of \\u003cword\\u003e (if such exists) but are\\n    themselves not a plural noun are included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Wind” → “Winds up the clock” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Border” → “The United States has strong borders” counts\\n    Open compounds (words separated by spaces) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fire station” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “couch” → “couch potato” counts\\n    Hyphenated compounds (words connected by hyphens) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Palestine” → “pro-Palestine” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fat” → “non-fat” counts\\n    Closed compounds (single word, no spaces/hyphens) do not count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire” does not count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firefighter” does not count\\n    Multi-word \\u003cword\\u003e in larger constructions: When \\u003cword\\u003e is a multi-word phrase\\n    appearing within a hyphenated construction, it counts only if \\u003cword\\u003e appears as a\\n    complete, unmodified element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “New York” → “New York-based” counts (complete element)\\n    Portmanteaus (words blended from two words where parts of each are combined) are\\n    NOT included unless the portmanteau clearly contains \\u003cword\\u003e as a distinct, unaltered\\n    element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “MAGA” → “MAGA-nificent” counts (MAGA appears as distinct element)\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “magnificent” → “MAGA-nificent” does NOT count (portmanteau blend)\\n\\nDictionary determination: Both the Merriam-Webster Dictionary (available online) AND the\\nOxford English Dictionary shall be used to determine compound type and/or conventional\\nspelling patterns. Inclusion in either dictionary as an open or hyphenated compound shall\\nsatisfy the Payout Criterion. If neither provides clarity (or the word is not included),\\ndetermination is based on whether written as single unit (closed/doesn’t count) vs. spaces or\\nhyphens (open or hyphenated/counts) and/or context and previous usage.\\n\\nPHONETIC EQUIVALENCIES\\n\\n    Homophones (same sound, different spelling) do not count:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “write” → “right” does not count\\n    Homonyms and homographs (same spelling) COUNT regardless of meaning or\\n    pronunciation:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “bass” → both “bass guitar” and “bass fishing” count\\n    Proper and common nouns are treated identically:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Apple” → both “Apple Inc.” and “apple” (fruit) count\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Will” → both “Will Smith” and “I will go” count\\n    Minor unintentional mispronunciations COUNT if context makes intent clear:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Mamdani” → “Mandani” counts\\n    Severe mispronunciations that make \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable do NOT count.\\n    Trademarked spellings do not count, even when pronounced identically, unless the word\\n\\fitself is the same:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “lift” → “Lyft” (pronounced “lift”) does not count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “uber” → “Uber” counts\\nWords with non-standard transliteration to English count within reason, provided they are\\nphonetically equivalent:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Zelensky” → any of “Zelenski,” “Zelenskii,” “Zelensky,” or “Zelenskiy”\\n      count if pronounced equivalently\\nContractions do not count for their constituent words unless otherwise explicitly specified\\nby the Exchange:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “not” → “won’t,” “can’t,” “don’t,” “isn’t” do not count\\nNumbers spoken as words COUNT, when spoken exactly (not part of a larger number):\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “five” → saying “five” or reading “$5” aloud as “five dollars” counts,\\n      saying “five hundred” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “410” → “four hundred ten”, “four one zero” or “four ten” counts\\nOrdinals COUNT when \\u003cword\\u003e is written numerically OR a phrase that includes a\\nnumber:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “January 6” → “January 6th” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “3” (written numerically) → “3rd” (spoken as “third”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Eight War” → “8 Wars” and “Eighth War” will count\\nCardinal and ordinal number words are distinct:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “one” → “first” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “first” → “one” does NOT count\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count when pronunciation or letter-by-letter spelling\\nmatches \\u003cword\\u003e:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “NASA” (pronounced “NAH-suh”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “N-A-S-A” (spelled out) counts\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count as \\u003cword\\u003e when pronounced as the full word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Doctor” → “Dr.” (pronounced “Doctor”) counts\\nExpanded forms of acronyms do NOT count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “AI” → “artificial intelligence” does not count\\nWords in foreign languages do NOT count unless they are perfect cognates with an\\nEnglish word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fuego” (Spanish) does NOT count\\nEnglish words within foreign sentences count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “policy” → “Nuestra policy es clara” counts\\n\\u003cword\\u003e in organization/company names counts:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Securities” → “Bank of America Securities” counts\\nWords in URLs, emails, handles, and hashtags (exclusive of domain structure, email\\nprovider or symbols) are treated as compounds when spoken as complete words, with the\\ntype of compound subject to aforementioned rules:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firestation.com” pronounced “fire station dot com” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire.com” pronounced “wildfire dot com” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “apple” → “apple.com” pronounced “apple dot com” does count\\n      When presented in URL, email, handle, or hashtag form, \\u003cword\\u003e shall be treated as\\n      a compound, not a multi-word word\\nSung, rapped, or poetic words COUNT if phonetically recognizable:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “money” → “moneyyy” (extended in rap) counts\\n      Extreme distortion making \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable does NOT count.\\nPhonetic alphabet spelling (“Foxtrot India Romeo Echo” for “FIRE”) does NOT count.\\n\\fCANCELLATIONS AND DELAYS\\n\\n   The Exchange may list an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike for any Contract. If listed,\\n   such a strike refers to the structural conditions of the market, and is NOT adjudicated as a\\n   \\u003cword\\u003e needing to be said by or validated by having been said by \\u003centity\\u003e. If listed, this\\n   strike resolves to “Yes” whenever the event fails to occur or qualify under the Payout\\n   Criterion, or any other circumstance prevents normal resolution.\\n   If no such strike is listed, and \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, the following rules\\n   apply if the event is cancelled, postponed, rescheduled, or materially altered (including\\n   being closed to press) such that no video is released within one calendar day of the\\n   original start time of the event:\\n         If the event is cancelled, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price determined in\\n         the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         If the event is postponed or rescheduled, the outcome depends on whether a new\\n         date is publicly announced within one calendar day (i.e. if the event was scheduled\\n         to begin on Monday, any time up to 11:59PM on Tuesday falls within this period) of\\n         the originally scheduled start time:\\n               If no new date is announced within one calendar day, the Contract will resolve\\n               to the last fair price determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n               If a new date is announced within one calendar day, the outcome depends on\\n               when the rescheduled event is set to occur:\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls within fourteen (14) calendar days of the\\n                     originally scheduled date, the Contract shall remain open and \\u003cword\\u003e\\n                     stated during the rescheduled event will count.\\n                           The fourteen-day window begins at 12:00 AM ET on the originally\\n                           scheduled date and ends at 11:59 PM ET fourteen days later, unless\\n                           an alternate timezone is explicitly specified.\\n                           Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the State of the Union on January\\n                           15, 2026” rescheduled to January 20, 2026 → words spoken during\\n                           the rescheduled address count.\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls more than fourteen (14) calendar days after\\n                     the originally scheduled date, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price\\n                     determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         Any Contract that cannot be resolved through the Source Agency hierarchy will\\n         instead be settled at the Last Fair Price. The Exchange will disclose the methodology\\n         used to determine the Last Fair Price (e.g., Last Traded Price, Time-Weighted\\n         Average Price) at the time of Issuance.\\n         If an event begins but is interrupted, abbreviated, or ends prematurely, words\\n         stated by \\u003centity\\u003e during the portion of the event that did occur will count and the\\n         market will otherwise resolve.\\n   If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window but the venue, format, or medium\\n   changes (e.g., moved to a different location, changed from in-person to virtual (with the\\n   exception of being closed to press)), words stated during the event will count.\\n   Special condition: Across both cases, whether an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike is\\n   listed or not, if the event specified as or in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast (or\\n   relayed as such) but the live stream/broadcast does not occur, the Exchange will instead\\n   use an officially released recording as the Underlying, and may delay resolution by up to\\n   one calendar day to allow for the release of such a recording.\\n\\f          If partial snippets are released, Contracts on words that do not appear will be\\n          resolved to last fair price, and Contracts on those that do will be resolved to “Yes”.\\n          If no recording is released, the relevant outcomes triggered by the\\n          presence/absence of an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike shall occur as outlined\\n          above.\\n\\nTECHNICAL DETAILS (UNLESS OTHERWISE SPECIFIED)\\n\\n     When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, pre-recorded content broadcast,\\n     streamed, or published as part of that event is included if presented as part of the official\\n     presentation.\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the concert” with pre-recorded video interlude\\n          where entity speaks → words from interlude count\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the television appearance” with pre-taped\\n          segment aired during broadcast → words from segment count\\n     Behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are NOT\\n     included unless officially broadcast or published as part of \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n     Subtitles and captions that display \\u003cword\\u003e on screen but are not spoken aloud by\\n     \\u003centity\\u003e do NOT count.\\n     Sign language interpretation or usage by entity does NOT count as saying \\u003cword\\u003e unless\\n     the Contract explicitly specifies that sign language counts.\\n     Text that entity displays on screen (presentation slides, teleprompter visible to audience,\\n     signatures) does NOT count unless entity reads it aloud.\\n     Content generated by AI, deepfakes, or synthetic voice technology impersonating entity\\n     does NOT count unless the synthetic content is officially commissioned, authorized, or\\n     published by entity, OR the Contract explicitly specifies that AI-generated content counts.\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e is muted due to technical failure or censorship it shall not count unless\\n     corroborating contextual evidence (including surrounding speech, or an official\\n     uncensored recording or transcript) confirms that \\u003centity\\u003e specifically uttered \\u003cword\\u003e\\n     during the muted period.\\n\\nMinimum Tick: The Minimum Tick size for the Contract shall be $0.01.\\n\\nPosition Accountability Level: The Position Accountability Level for the Contract shall be\\n$25,000 per strike, per Member.\\n\\nLast Trading Date: The Last Trading Date of the Contract will be the Expiration Date. The Last\\nTrading Time will be the Expiration time.\\n\\nSettlement Date: The Settlement Date of the Contract shall be no later than the day after the\\nExpiration Date, unless the Market Outcome is under review pursuant to Rule 7.1.\\n\\nExpiration Date: When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event: The latest Expiration Date of\\nthe Contract shall be fourteen (14) calendar days after the originally scheduled date of the\\nevent. If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window, expiration will be moved to an\\nearlier date and time in accordance with Rule 7.2. When \\u003ctime period\\u003e is defined by specific\\ndates: The latest Expiration Date of the Contract shall be two weeks after the end of \\u003ctime\\nperiod\\u003e. If an event described in the Payout Criterion occurs and a consensus has been\\nreached on all terms, then expiration will be moved to an earlier date and time in accordance\\nwith Rule 7.2.\\n\\fExpiration time: The Expiration time of the Contract shall be 10:00 AM ET.\\n\\nSettlement Value: The Settlement Value for this Contract is $1.00.\\n\\nExpiration Value: The Expiration Value is the value of the Underlying as documented by the\\nSource Agency on the Expiration Date at the Expiration time.\\n\\nContingencies: Before Settlement, Kalshi may, at its sole discretion, initiate the Market\\nOutcome Review Process pursuant to Rule 7.1 of the Rulebook. If an Expiration Value cannot\\nbe determined on the Expiration Date, Kalshi has the right to determine payouts pursuant to\\nRule 7.1 in the Rulebook.\\n\\f\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-4 Formal draw archive note\\nSource checked: Roll Call / Factba.se archive\\n\\nArchive title: Remarks: Donald Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing in Washington - December 5, 2025\\n\\nArchive URL: https://rollcall.com/factbase/trump/transcript/donald-trump-remarks-fifa-world-cup-drawing-december-5-2025/\\n\\nWhat this file establishes:\\n\\nThere is a separate archived transcript page for Trump's formal attendance remarks at the draw.\\n\\nWhat this file does not establish:\\n\\nThis session could not retrieve the full transcript text from that archive.  The page is password-protected.  This example therefore does not claim, from local files alone, whether the formal program transcript does or does not contain the word \\\"Ronaldo.\\\"\\n\\nWhy this matters:\\n\\nThe complaint does not need to prove that the formal program omitted the strike.  It needs to show that Trump said \\\"Ronaldo\\\" in event-linked remarks and that the market boundary reasonably includes those remarks.  The formal archive remains relevant because it marks the distinction between the pre-event reporter exchange and the formal program.\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-5 GovInfo official transcript excerpt and metadata\\nSource: GovInfo, DCPD202501162, Office of the Federal Register / National Archives and Records Administration.\\nURL: https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/DCPD-202501162/html/DCPD-202501162.htm\\nTitle: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\nEvent date: December 5, 2025.\\n\\nRelevant extracted page text:\\n\\\"Administration of Donald J. Trump, 2025\\\"\\n\\\"Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw December 5, 2025\\\"\\n\\\"[The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\\\"\\n\\nUnder the section \\\"The President's Interest in Soccer\\\":\\n\\\"Q. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\\\"\\n\\\"The President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\\\\\\\"football,\\\\\\\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\\\"\\n\\\"Thank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\\\"\\n\\nAdditional relevant extracted page text:\\n\\\"The President's Interest in Soccer\\\"\\n\\\"Q. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\\\"\\n\\\"The President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\\\"\\n\\\"Mr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\\\"\\n\\\"The President. But they have a little more speed. But no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\\\"\\n\\nGovInfo note:\\n\\\"NOTE: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. In his remarks, he referred to Trey Yingst, chief foreign correspondent, Fox News Channel; Cristiano Ronaldo, forward for Saudi Pro League club Al-Nass and Portugal's national soccer team; and Lionel Messi, forward for Major League Soccer club Inter Miami and Argentina's national team. A reporter referred to New York State Attorney General Letitia James. The transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\\"\\n\\nGovInfo content details page also identifies category \\\"Interviews With the News Media : Exchanges with reporters, Washington, DC,\\\" subjects including \\\"Federation Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) World Cup,\\\" \\\"John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts,\\\" and \\\"Soccer,\\\" and names including \\\"Ronaldo, Cristiano\\\" and \\\"Messi, Lionel.\\\"\\n\\n[defendant] DX-1 Market wording and challenged resolution\\nMarket URL: https://kalshi.com/markets/kxtrumpmentionb/trump-mention-b/kxtrumpmentionb-25dec06\\n\\nPublic market title: What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\n\\nContract family: PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION\\n\\nStrike at issue: Ronaldo\\n\\nChallenged resolution: No\\n\\nRequested resolution: Yes\\n\\n\\n[defendant] DX-2 Pre-event reporter exchange transcript\\nRemarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\nDecember 05, 2025\\n\\n[The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\\nThe President. It's a great honor to be here. Gianni has done a fantastic job. We're setting records—[inaudible].\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. Well, I think so. They have a little bit of a shot. Pretty stiff competition. But I would say they would have a small chance.\\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize\\nQ. [Inaudible]—win the FIFA Peace Award?\\nThe President. Well, it would be an honor.\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\nQ. Will you root for some selection? Will you root for someone?\\nThe President. Well, I root for a lot of countries, but in this case, I'll be rooting for the U.S.A. [Laughter]\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. That's great. That's great. We really love it.\\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize\\nQ. Mr. President, have you been told that you are going to receive the inaugural peace prize today——\\nThe President. I have not——\\nQ. ——from FIFA?\\nThe President. I have not been told. There's a rumor about it, but I have not been told. That would be a great honor, and I'm a big fan of Gianni, as you know.\\nQ. What can fans expect——\\nQ. Are you hoping to receive that?\\nThe President. Excuse me.\\nQ. Are you hoping to receive the peace prize?\\nThe President. Well, I don't like to say \\\"hope,\\\" but it would be a great honor.\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. What can fans expect of, like, the World Cup in the U.S.?\\nThe President. I think it's going to be fantastic. We've set every record you can set.\\nQ. What are you telling people who are worried——\\nFédération Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) President Giovanni V. Infantino\\nQ. [Inaudible]—friend Gianni—[inaudible]—a word about him?\\nThe President. I think he has done a fantastic job.\\nThe President's Schedule\\nQ. Are you going to be meeting with the President of Mexico today and the——\\nThe President. We might. Yes.\\nQ. ——Prime Minister of Canada as well?\\nThe President. I might. I might do that.\\nQ. Will you be discussing immigration and trade with them?\\nThe President. Yes, we'll be discussing.\\n[At this point, the President and Mr. Infantino posed for photographs.]\\nThe President. Thank you, everybody.\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event/John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts\\nQ. Mr. President, what do you think about the crowd?\\nThe President. Oh, look, the new star—[inaudible].\\nCongratulations.\\nQ. Thank you.\\nThe President. You're the new star of television and Fox.\\nQ. Thank you. How are you doing, Mr. President?\\nThe President. I'm doing very well.\\nQ. What do you think about the crowd here?\\nThe President. I think the crowd is great, and I think the building is great. We've made a lot of improvements over the last 6 months. Taking—the Kennedy Center was in very bad shape. Now it's getting to be really good. And in 6 months, it's going to be incredible with the improvements we've made.\\nQ. The first time for the U.S. to host since the nineties.\\nThe President. Right.\\nQ. Are you ready for it?\\nThe President. I'm ready for it, and they're ready for it. And Gianni, who you know——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——has done a fantastic job with FIFA. And we're looking to have—you know, we're set—we have already set records for tickets sales. I don't think there's ever been anything like it in any sport. And so, I want to congratulate you.\\nMr. Infantino. Thank you.\\nThe President. I don't even have to wait. But major records have been set.\\nHow are you?\\nQ. Good, how are you, sir?\\nThe President. Nice to see you.\\nQ. Today it's not football—American football. It's soccer. It's——\\nThe President. Right.\\nQ. ——the big event of soccer.\\nThe President. That's right. That's right.\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\nQ. So can you tell me about this big day today?\\nThe President. It's just a big day, and it's a great sport. And it really is coming to America. And never—nobody ever thought a thing like this could happen. And I'm very happy to say that we've already set the alltime record on ticket sales long before the first ball is kicked. Right?\\nMr. Infantino. A hundred percent. One hundred percent.\\n2026 World Cup Host Cities\\nQ. You've had some concerns about crime in American cities, some of the cities that will be hosting. Have they remedied that for you? Are you still considering maybe asking FIFA to move some of those cities?\\nThe President. No, I don't want to do that. But I will tell you, if they do have a problem, by the time we get there, we'll take care of that problem. We can solve that problem.\\nI've proven that in DC and everywhere else we went, so we'll take care of that very easily. So, if they have a problem, hopefully, they'll let us know that, and we will solve any problem.\\nOkay? Thank you.\\nQ. Thank you so much.\\nMr. Infantino. All right, thank you so much.\\nQ. Thank you, Mr. President.\\nQ. Thank you. Appreciate it.\\nThe President. Congratulations.\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. Mr. President, Brazilian television. America will be hosting the World Cup and the Olympics in 2 years. How important it is—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. I think very. It's a great honor. I think Gianni is doing a phenomenal job. We've set every record on ticket sales. It's been really fantastic. But Gianni has done an unbelievable job with FIFA.\\nThe President's Experience With Soccer\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. He was a great—not only that. I got to see a man name Pelé play—right?—that tells you how old I am—when he was on the Cosmos. Do you remember that a long time ago? And it was quite a treat. That was quite an event. And he was—not only was he playing, he was great. He scored two goals, I think. And so, I was one of the few who got to see Pelé, and I assume he is one of your alltime greats. Right?\\nMr. Infantino. Definitely.\\nThe President. So I got to see him.\\nThe President's Favorite World Cup Competitor\\nQ. Do you have some favorite teams for World Cup?\\nThe President. Well, I have a favorite. It's the U.S.A. [Laughter] I don't know what their chances are, Gianni, but maybe the U.S.A. is the——\\nMr. Infantino. They're getting better and better, actually.\\nThe President. I think they'll do well.\\nMr. Infantino. They are getting better and better.\\nThe President. I think they'll do well.\\nThank you very much, everybody.\\nQ. Thank you so much.\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. Mr. President, World Cup in America just means—[inaudible]. So what do you expect from this World Cup?\\nThe President. [Inaudible]—record business and only in the United States, but we're also doing record ticket sales with FIFA. And they've already bought—beat their highest record. And we—you know, this a long time before the first ball is kicked. You've sold more tickets than they've ever done before, and better pricing than they've ever gotten before. It's a tremendous success. And it's an honor. And Gianni has done a phenomenal job with FIFA.\\nQ. [Inaudible]—ever?\\nThe President. I think so. I think it's going to be—I mean, ideally, you want to see that every year. Every 4 years, it gets bigger and better. I think we have set every record in the book. We're very happy about it.\\nThank you.\\nThe President's Favorite World Cup Competitor\\nQ. [Inaudible]—part of America. Who are you going to support as well?\\nThe President. Well, I think I have to support U.S.A. Otherwise, I'd be in trouble. I wouldn't be President for long.\\nMr. Infantino. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. [Inaudible]—but you have a lot of great teams. You're going to have a lot of great teams.\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\\\"football,\\\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\\n2026 World Cup Draw/Ticket Sales for World Cup\\nQ. How does it feel to be part of this amazing event? And obviously, your being a part of participating in all the—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. The President of Mexico is here, and she's doing a very good job. She's a good woman, very, very excellent job. It's an honor, and we're setting every record, and you're helping us set those records.\\nMr. Infantino. And we will do it.\\nThe President. You know, Mexico and Canada are helping us set those records. But as you know, we have a record in ticket sales already, long before the first ball is kicked, and we're going to do great.\\nI think that Gianni—as you know, he's the head, and he has done a fantastic job.\\nU.S. Cooperation With Mexico and Canada\\nQ. And how is the biggest challenge being three countries?\\nThe President. Well, I think that—do you mean for the three countries?\\nWell, they've gotten together really well, I mean.\\nMr. Infantino. All right.\\nThe President. They're getting along very well.\\nMr. Infantino. Collaboration is fantastic between the three.\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer/2026 World Cup\\nQ. And you like soccer?\\nThe President. I do. I like it. I like it more and more.\\nQ. Yes?\\nThe President. I like it. It's growing in this country—very, really—I mean, someday, maybe it's going to be bigger than anything else.\\nMr. Infantino. We'll have to become number one.\\nThe President. I will say this——\\nMr. Infantino. Definitely.\\nThe President. ——the ticket sales——\\nQ. Definitely will happen.\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. Ticket sales are bigger than anything we have ever done in the history of the country, in terms of sports.\\nMr. Infantino. For certain.\\nQ. And the audience is going to be huge.\\nThe President. The audience is going to be tremendous.\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. Yes.\\nMr. Infantino. Six billion people.\\nThe President. [Inaudible]\\nQ. Six billion? That's amazing.\\nMr. Infantino. Six billion people.\\nAnd today, one billion.\\nQ. Wow.\\nMr. Infantino. [Inaudible]\\nQ. Enjoy show time. Thank you so much.\\nThe President. [Inaudible]\\nQ. Mr. President, how are you? Just a quick—[inaudible].\\nQ. This is for Telemundo.\\nThe President. How are you?\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\nQ. Hello, Mr. President. How are you? This for Telemundo.\\nThe President. How are you? Good.\\nQ. How are you?\\nThe President. Very good. Thank you.\\nQ. How does it feel to have the most important event of sports—that global—in the U.S.?\\nThe President. Well, we do. And right at the Kennedy Center. I'm Chairman of the Kennedy Center. And I hear the Kennedy Center is doing a very good job, so it feels great. Really good.\\nAnd Telemundo is doing a good job, too. Thank you.\\nQ. Thank you.\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. What is the significance of hosting the FIFA World Cup this year?\\nThe President. It's a—in terms of sports, I would say the ultimate. There is no sport like this. It's the biggest sport in the world. And we are setting every record. You know, our ticket sales have gone and set every—every sport—no matter what it is, we've set the record. So—and every though it's very early, there's no ball being kicked yet, but we've already set a ticket sales record.\\nArgentina National Team\\nQ. How do you see Argentinean team for this World Cup?\\nThe President. Well, I love Argentina. And your President is doing a very good job, as you know. Milei. You know that right? It's make Argentina great again. MAGA.\\nQ. And——\\nU.S. National Team\\nQ. Do you think the States are building a powerful team for next year?\\nThe President. Who?\\nQ. The States.\\nThe President. Oh, yes. Sure. I—you're going to have a lot of powerful teams. Everybody has a lot of powerful teams, but you're going to have a lot of great teams. [Inaudible]\\nU.S. Role in Hosting the 2026 World Cup\\nQ. Mr. President, what does it mean for you guys to host the World Cup right here in the U.S.?\\nThe President. I'm honored to host it. It's a great honor. I mean, it's turned out to be bigger than we thought. We're setting a record for ticket sales, the likes of which no sport has ever seen before.\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\\nThe President. But they have a little more speed.\\nBut no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\\nPopularity of Soccer in Latin America\\nQ. Mr. President, a message for the Latin America and soccer fans?\\nThe President. Yes, I am. And Latin America is great. And they have great soccer. So, good luck in the matches.\\n[A reporter asked a question in Spanish, which was translated by an interpreter as follows.]\\nU.S. Visas for World Cup Ticketholders\\nQ. Who is going to be in—[inaudible]—about these visas for the—these fans that want to come here to the World Cup?\\nThe President. Well, we're going to make it very easy for them. We're working on that right now. We're going to make it very easy. It's going to be a very easy process.\\nQ. Okay. Say, hi to Colombia over there.\\nThe President. Hello. Is that Colombia?\\nQ. Yes.\\nThe President. I love Colombia. Hello, Colombia. [Laughter]\\nQ. Okay. Okay. Muy bien.\\nThe President. So where are you from?\\nQ. Paraguay.\\nThe President. Oh.\\nQ. He's from Paraguay. Yes.\\nThe President. Very good. I love it. I—it's a beautiful country. We get along very well with them. We do a little trade deal with them, and they like us. And that's what's happening.\\nQ. Panama.\\nThe President. Where?\\nVery good. I like the canal. [Laughter] That canal is pretty good.\\n[A reporter spoke in Spanish; no translation was provided.]\\n2026 World Cup\\nThe President. What?\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. Well, it's going to be incredible. The event is going to be very good. Just this event alone—it's at the Kennedy Center. I see you have it fixed up perfectly.\\nMr. Infantino. It will set the tone.\\nThe President. Right? It's beautiful.\\nMr. Infantino. It's beautiful.\\nThe President. It's a beautiful place.\\nHave a good time.\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President.\\n[A reporter spoke in Spanish; no translation was provided.]\\nMr. Infantino. No, gracias. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. It's great.\\nJohn F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts/Renovation Work\\nQ. Mr. President, the U.S. press?\\nThe President. Thank you, everybody, very much. It's a great honor. This has been an honor for a lot of reasons. Number one, they've sold more tickets than any event has ever sold already—long before the kickoff.\\nAnd number two, we've done a lot of work at the Kennedy Center. It was falling apart, and now it's pretty much back. And we'll get it back within the next 4 or 5 months through construction, and—but you see the way it looks.\\nAnd Gianni is just telling me—who's done an incredible job, by the way. He's just telling, you know, how good a job we've done.\\nMr. Infantino. That's right.\\nThe President. You can look at the walls. The marble was broken. Everything was a mess. And we've really taken the Kennedy Center—a lot of people thought it was going to be ripped down, and we did just the opposite. So we've done a really great renovation job on it. And over the next 3, 4 months, it will be complete. And we're honored to have it here, and it's been—it's been very special.\\nWe've set a record on ticket sales, as you probably heard, already, even way before—long before the event itself. And we're working with Canada, and we're working with Mexico. And it's been a really spectacular—so far, it's been spectacular.\\nDaniel [Daniel Baldwin, One America News Network], do you have a question?\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. What are your expectations? You once said that the FIFA World Cup is an opportunity to put—a once-in-a-lifetime opportunity to put the greatness of the United States on display.\\nThe President. Well, I think—\\nQ. One billion eyeballs will be watching, Mr. President.\\nThe President. Yes, I—think——\\nQ. What will they here today?\\nThe President. Even today, I understand. I hear that, you know——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——I know we're a little late to get in there, but——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——that's okay.\\nMr. Infantino. They wait.\\nThe President. So all my friends, I guess they have to wait. They have no choice, right? [Laughter]\\nMr. Infantino. Yes, they wait.\\nThe President. But no, the numbers are incredible. I hear today's numbers are——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——very big. I hope CNN is covering this.\\nQ. One billion eyeballs.\\nMr. Infantino. Today, 1 billion eyeballs.\\nThe President. Today's numbers are very, very big.\\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize/The President's Foreign Policy\\nQ. We are covering it. And you're expected to get the FIFA Peace Prize, Mr. President. What would you say to people who say that prize might conflict with your pledge to strike Venezuela?\\nThe President. Well, I think the peace prize—I mean, I settled eight wars. I don't know that I'm getting it. I haven't been officially noticed. I've been hearing about a peace prize, and I'm here to represent our country in a different sense. But I can tell you, I did settle eight wars, and we have a ninth coming, but—which nobody has ever done before.\\nBut I want to really save lives. I don't need prizes. I need to save lives. And we're saving a lot of lives. And I've saved millions and millions of lives, and that's really what I want to do.\\nAnd I also want to run a great country. And the United States right now is the hottest country anywhere in the world. And 1 year ago, it was dead. We had a dead country, and now we have the hottest country anywhere in the world.\\nQ. Mr. President, will you——\\nThe President's Meeting With President Claudia Sheinbaum Pardo of Mexico and Prime Minister Mark Carney of Canada\\nQ. What are you going to discuss with Canada and Mexico, Mr.—what are you going to discuss with the leaders of Canada and Mexico?\\nThe President. Well, we're getting—we're going to meet with both. And we're getting along very well. You know, we're getting along very well. I don't know. I think we have a meeting set up for some time after the event.\\nQ. Will you discuss trade?\\nThe President. Yes, we'll discuss trade. We—get along very well.\\nThank you, everybody, very much.\\nQ. Will you pardon any other Honduran officials?\\nQ. Do you want them to keep trying to indict Ms. James?\\n\\nNOTE: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. In his remarks, he referred to Trey Yingst, chief foreign correspondent, Fox News Channel; Cristiano Ronaldo, forward for Saudi Pro League club Al-Nass and Portugal's national soccer team; and Lionel Messi, forward for Major League Soccer club Inter Miami and Argentina's national team. A reporter referred to New York State Attorney General Letitia James. The transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\n\\nSource URL: https://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/documents/remarks-exchange-with-reporters-prior-the-2026-federation-internationale-des-associations\\n\\n\\n[defendant] DX-3 GovInfo/OFR pre-event transcript excerpt\\nSource: GovInfo, DCPD202501162, Office of the Federal Register / National Archives and Records Administration.\\nURL: https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/DCPD-202501162/html/DCPD-202501162.htm\\nTitle: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\nEvent date: December 5, 2025.\\n\\nRelevant extracted page text:\\n\\\"Administration of Donald J. Trump, 2025\\\"\\n\\\"Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw December 5, 2025\\\"\\n\\\"[The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\\\"\\n\\nUnder the section \\\"The President's Interest in Soccer\\\":\\n\\\"Q. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\\\"\\n\\\"The President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\\\\\\\"football,\\\\\\\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\\\"\\n\\\"Thank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\\\"\\n\\nAdditional relevant extracted page text:\\n\\\"The President's Interest in Soccer\\\"\\n\\\"Q. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\\\"\\n\\\"The President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\\\"\\n\\\"Mr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\\\"\\n\\\"The President. But they have a little more speed. But no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\\\"\\n\\nGovInfo note:\\n\\\"NOTE: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. In his remarks, he referred to Trey Yingst, chief foreign correspondent, Fox News Channel; Cristiano Ronaldo, forward for Saudi Pro League club Al-Nass and Portugal's national soccer team; and Lionel Messi, forward for Major League Soccer club Inter Miami and Argentina's national team. A reporter referred to New York State Attorney General Letitia James. The transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\\"\\n\\nGovInfo content details page also identifies category \\\"Interviews With the News Media : Exchanges with reporters, Washington, DC,\\\" subjects including \\\"Federation Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) World Cup,\\\" \\\"John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts,\\\" and \\\"Soccer,\\\" and names including \\\"Ronaldo, Cristiano\\\" and \\\"Messi, Lionel.\\\"\\n\\n[defendant] DX-4 PRESMENTION/NEWMENTION terms\\n                                         NEWMENTION\\n\\nScope: These rules shall apply to this contract.\\n\\nUnderlying: The Underlying for this Contract is words used by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nRevisions to the Underlying made after Expiration will not be accounted for in determining the\\nExpiration Value.\\n\\nSource Agency: The Source Agencies are \\u003csource\\u003e.\\n\\nType: The type of Contract is an Event Contract.\\n\\nIssuance: After the initial Contract, Contract iterations will be listed on an as-needed basis at\\nthe discretion of the Exchange and corresponding to the risk management needs of Members.\\n\\n\\u003centity\\u003e: \\u003centity\\u003e refers to the speaker, writer, performer, or communicator specified by the\\nExchange. This may include (but is not limited to): a specific named individual, multiple\\nindividuals specified using AND/OR logic, an individual identified by position or title, a group,\\nband, team or collective entity, a specified member or members of a group, an organization,\\ncompany, or institutional entity, or any combination of the aforementioned.\\n\\nWhen \\u003centity\\u003e is defined by a position or title, the Contract tracks whoever holds that position\\nduring \\u003ctime period\\u003e, even if the individual holding the position changes. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a\\nspecific named individual, the identity remains consistent throughout. Name changes (e.g.,\\nstage names, married names) do not create a new entity. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a group or\\norganization and the Contract does not specify particular members, any official\\ncommunication or statement by any member or designated spokesperson counts. When using\\nAND logic, all specified entities must independently say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e. When\\nusing OR logic, at least one of the specified entities must say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nThe Exchange may specify additional conditions such as “at least X members of” a group or\\n“the majority of” a group.\\n\\n\\u003csource\\u003e: \\u003csource\\u003e refers to a Source Agency or ordered collection of Source Agencies\\nspecified by the Exchange at the time of Contract listing, which will be incorporated into the\\nSource Agency hierarchy above and used to determine the occurrence of the Underlying.\\n\\u003csource\\u003e may refer to a singular agency, multiple agencies, an agency by distinguishing\\ncharacteristics, by category or type (e.g., “official government statistical body,” “primary wire\\nservice”), or any combination thereof. When multiple agencies are specified, they may be\\napplied in the hierarchical order designated by the Exchange if so specified, with the highest-\\nranked available and responsive agency taking precedence for purposes of determining the\\nExpiration Value. A lower-ranked agency shall only be consulted if all higher-ranked agencies\\nare unavailable, unresponsive, have not reported on the Underlying by the Expiration time, or\\nif the Exchange, in its sole discretion, determines that a higher-ranked agency’s reporting is\\nincomplete, erroneous, or otherwise insufficient to determine the Expiration Value. If \\u003csource\\u003e\\ndesignates multiple agencies without specifying a hierarchical order, the Exchange shall\\nresolve any conflict between reporting agencies at its sole discretion.\\n\\n\\u003cword\\u003e: \\u003cword\\u003e refers to the particular word or phrase potentially to be mentioned by\\n\\u003centity\\u003e. It may refer to a word being said a minimum number of times. It may also refer to\\none of multiple words/phrases, any of which are acceptable (e.g., “Doge/Dogecoin”).\\n\\f\\u003ctime period\\u003e: \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific range of time, event or discrete date and\\ntime specified by the Exchange. This may be defined by, but is not limited to: a specific event\\nor context (e.g., “during the State of the Union address”), exact dates or times, relative time\\nmarkers (e.g., “before July 1, 2027,” “in Q1 2026”), event-based periods (e.g., “during any\\ncampaign rally in October 2026,” “during the awards ceremony”), and broader intervals (e.g.,\\n“Q1–Q2 2027,” “January–March 2026”).\\n\\nUnless stated otherwise, “Between” is inclusive of both endpoints, while “before” and “after”\\nexclude the specified date. \\u003ctime period\\u003e may also refer to “Any” or “None”, to multiple dates\\n(even if non-consecutive), or to a singular and discrete date or time.\\n\\nWhen \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event (such as an address, speech, performance, or\\nbroadcast), the Exchange may specify what is included, including whether it includes both live\\nand pre-recorded segments (including whether advertisements are included). Where a\\ntimezone is not specified, ET is assumed.\\n\\n\\nPayout Criterion: The Payout Criterion for the Contract encompasses the Expiration Values that\\n\\u003cword\\u003e is said by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n\\n\\nThe word must appear as a distinct, standalone unit, not buried inside another word. Plural\\nand possessive noun forms count. Other grammatical changes (tense, conjugation, derivation)\\ndo not. If \\u003cword\\u003e appears separated from other words by a space or hyphen or in a\\ncompound form with a space or hyphen, it counts. If \\u003cword\\u003e is fused into a single\\nunhyphenated word, it does not count.\\n\\nIf \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled, and the market contains a\\nstrike stating “Event does not qualify/occur”, such a strike shall resolve “Yes” and all others\\n“No”. If \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled but such strikes are NOT\\nlisted, the Contracts will resolve to the last fair price determined at the discretion of the\\nExchange. If the event is postponed, and such a postponement is announced by the end of the\\nfollowing calendar day to be rescheduled to a time within 14 calendar days, the markets shall\\nremain open. If the event captured in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast, the\\nExchange may keep the market open for 24 hours for the release of an official recording.\\nFurther granular details on conditions for these Contracts is available below.\\n\\nAdditional clarification(s):\\n\\n     Possessive noun forms of \\u003cword\\u003e, plurals, and possessive plural noun forms are\\n     INCLUDED:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigrants” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Egg” → “eggs’ shells” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Russia” → “Russia’s” counts, “Russian” does not\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e exists only in adjective form, no plural form exists:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Economic” → “Economics” does not count (“Economic” is an adjective\\n          for which “Economics” is not a plural)\\n     Plural nouns occurring within proper nouns and noun phrases are included:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Cat” → “Cats the musical” counts\\n\\f    Grammatical variations beyond plurals/possessives are NOT included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigration” does NOT count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Run” → “Running” or “Ran” do NOT count\\n    When \\u003cword\\u003e specifies a plural form, the singular does NOT count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Veterans” → “Veteran” does NOT count\\n    Words that are spelled the same as the plural form of \\u003cword\\u003e (if such exists) but are\\n    themselves not a plural noun are included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Wind” → “Winds up the clock” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Border” → “The United States has strong borders” counts\\n    Open compounds (words separated by spaces) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fire station” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “couch” → “couch potato” counts\\n    Hyphenated compounds (words connected by hyphens) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Palestine” → “pro-Palestine” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fat” → “non-fat” counts\\n    Closed compounds (single word, no spaces/hyphens) do not count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire” does not count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firefighter” does not count\\n    Multi-word \\u003cword\\u003e in larger constructions: When \\u003cword\\u003e is a multi-word phrase\\n    appearing within a hyphenated construction, it counts only if \\u003cword\\u003e appears as a\\n    complete, unmodified element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “New York” → “New York-based” counts (complete element)\\n    Portmanteaus (words blended from two words where parts of each are combined) are\\n    NOT included unless the portmanteau clearly contains \\u003cword\\u003e as a distinct, unaltered\\n    element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “MAGA” → “MAGA-nificent” counts (MAGA appears as distinct element)\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “magnificent” → “MAGA-nificent” does NOT count (portmanteau blend)\\n\\nDictionary determination: Both the Merriam-Webster Dictionary (available online) AND the\\nOxford English Dictionary shall be used to determine compound type and/or conventional\\nspelling patterns. Inclusion in either dictionary as an open or hyphenated compound shall\\nsatisfy the Payout Criterion. If neither provides clarity (or the word is not included),\\ndetermination is based on whether written as single unit (closed/doesn’t count) vs. spaces or\\nhyphens (open or hyphenated/counts) and/or context and previous usage.\\n\\nPHONETIC EQUIVALENCIES\\n\\n    Homophones (same sound, different spelling) do not count:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “write” → “right” does not count\\n    Homonyms and homographs (same spelling) COUNT regardless of meaning or\\n    pronunciation:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “bass” → both “bass guitar” and “bass fishing” count\\n    Proper and common nouns are treated identically:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Apple” → both “Apple Inc.” and “apple” (fruit) count\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Will” → both “Will Smith” and “I will go” count\\n    Minor unintentional mispronunciations COUNT if context makes intent clear:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Mamdani” → “Mandani” counts\\n    Severe mispronunciations that make \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable do NOT count.\\n    Trademarked spellings do not count, even when pronounced identically, unless the word\\n\\fitself is the same:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “lift” → “Lyft” (pronounced “lift”) does not count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “uber” → “Uber” counts\\nWords with non-standard transliteration to English count within reason, provided they are\\nphonetically equivalent:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Zelensky” → any of “Zelenski,” “Zelenskii,” “Zelensky,” or “Zelenskiy”\\n      count if pronounced equivalently\\nContractions do not count for their constituent words unless otherwise explicitly specified\\nby the Exchange:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “not” → “won’t,” “can’t,” “don’t,” “isn’t” do not count\\nNumbers spoken as words COUNT, when spoken exactly (not part of a larger number):\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “five” → saying “five” or reading “$5” aloud as “five dollars” counts,\\n      saying “five hundred” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “410” → “four hundred ten”, “four one zero” or “four ten” counts\\nOrdinals COUNT when \\u003cword\\u003e is written numerically OR a phrase that includes a\\nnumber:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “January 6” → “January 6th” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “3” (written numerically) → “3rd” (spoken as “third”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Eight War” → “8 Wars” and “Eighth War” will count\\nCardinal and ordinal number words are distinct:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “one” → “first” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “first” → “one” does NOT count\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count when pronunciation or letter-by-letter spelling\\nmatches \\u003cword\\u003e:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “NASA” (pronounced “NAH-suh”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “N-A-S-A” (spelled out) counts\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count as \\u003cword\\u003e when pronounced as the full word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Doctor” → “Dr.” (pronounced “Doctor”) counts\\nExpanded forms of acronyms do NOT count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “AI” → “artificial intelligence” does not count\\nWords in foreign languages do NOT count unless they are perfect cognates with an\\nEnglish word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fuego” (Spanish) does NOT count\\nEnglish words within foreign sentences count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “policy” → “Nuestra policy es clara” counts\\n\\u003cword\\u003e in organization/company names counts:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Securities” → “Bank of America Securities” counts\\nWords in URLs, emails, handles, and hashtags (exclusive of domain structure, email\\nprovider or symbols) are treated as compounds when spoken as complete words, with the\\ntype of compound subject to aforementioned rules:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firestation.com” pronounced “fire station dot com” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire.com” pronounced “wildfire dot com” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “apple” → “apple.com” pronounced “apple dot com” does count\\n      When presented in URL, email, handle, or hashtag form, \\u003cword\\u003e shall be treated as\\n      a compound, not a multi-word word\\nSung, rapped, or poetic words COUNT if phonetically recognizable:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “money” → “moneyyy” (extended in rap) counts\\n      Extreme distortion making \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable does NOT count.\\nPhonetic alphabet spelling (“Foxtrot India Romeo Echo” for “FIRE”) does NOT count.\\n\\fCANCELLATIONS AND DELAYS\\n\\n   The Exchange may list an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike for any Contract. If listed,\\n   such a strike refers to the structural conditions of the market, and is NOT adjudicated as a\\n   \\u003cword\\u003e needing to be said by or validated by having been said by \\u003centity\\u003e. If listed, this\\n   strike resolves to “Yes” whenever the event fails to occur or qualify under the Payout\\n   Criterion, or any other circumstance prevents normal resolution.\\n   If no such strike is listed, and \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, the following rules\\n   apply if the event is cancelled, postponed, rescheduled, or materially altered (including\\n   being closed to press) such that no video is released within one calendar day of the\\n   original start time of the event:\\n         If the event is cancelled, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price determined in\\n         the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         If the event is postponed or rescheduled, the outcome depends on whether a new\\n         date is publicly announced within one calendar day (i.e. if the event was scheduled\\n         to begin on Monday, any time up to 11:59PM on Tuesday falls within this period) of\\n         the originally scheduled start time:\\n               If no new date is announced within one calendar day, the Contract will resolve\\n               to the last fair price determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n               If a new date is announced within one calendar day, the outcome depends on\\n               when the rescheduled event is set to occur:\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls within fourteen (14) calendar days of the\\n                     originally scheduled date, the Contract shall remain open and \\u003cword\\u003e\\n                     stated during the rescheduled event will count.\\n                           The fourteen-day window begins at 12:00 AM ET on the originally\\n                           scheduled date and ends at 11:59 PM ET fourteen days later, unless\\n                           an alternate timezone is explicitly specified.\\n                           Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the State of the Union on January\\n                           15, 2026” rescheduled to January 20, 2026 → words spoken during\\n                           the rescheduled address count.\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls more than fourteen (14) calendar days after\\n                     the originally scheduled date, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price\\n                     determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         Any Contract that cannot be resolved through the Source Agency hierarchy will\\n         instead be settled at the Last Fair Price. The Exchange will disclose the methodology\\n         used to determine the Last Fair Price (e.g., Last Traded Price, Time-Weighted\\n         Average Price) at the time of Issuance.\\n         If an event begins but is interrupted, abbreviated, or ends prematurely, words\\n         stated by \\u003centity\\u003e during the portion of the event that did occur will count and the\\n         market will otherwise resolve.\\n   If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window but the venue, format, or medium\\n   changes (e.g., moved to a different location, changed from in-person to virtual (with the\\n   exception of being closed to press)), words stated during the event will count.\\n   Special condition: Across both cases, whether an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike is\\n   listed or not, if the event specified as or in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast (or\\n   relayed as such) but the live stream/broadcast does not occur, the Exchange will instead\\n   use an officially released recording as the Underlying, and may delay resolution by up to\\n   one calendar day to allow for the release of such a recording.\\n\\f          If partial snippets are released, Contracts on words that do not appear will be\\n          resolved to last fair price, and Contracts on those that do will be resolved to “Yes”.\\n          If no recording is released, the relevant outcomes triggered by the\\n          presence/absence of an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike shall occur as outlined\\n          above.\\n\\nTECHNICAL DETAILS (UNLESS OTHERWISE SPECIFIED)\\n\\n     When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, pre-recorded content broadcast,\\n     streamed, or published as part of that event is included if presented as part of the official\\n     presentation.\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the concert” with pre-recorded video interlude\\n          where entity speaks → words from interlude count\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the television appearance” with pre-taped\\n          segment aired during broadcast → words from segment count\\n     Behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are NOT\\n     included unless officially broadcast or published as part of \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n     Subtitles and captions that display \\u003cword\\u003e on screen but are not spoken aloud by\\n     \\u003centity\\u003e do NOT count.\\n     Sign language interpretation or usage by entity does NOT count as saying \\u003cword\\u003e unless\\n     the Contract explicitly specifies that sign language counts.\\n     Text that entity displays on screen (presentation slides, teleprompter visible to audience,\\n     signatures) does NOT count unless entity reads it aloud.\\n     Content generated by AI, deepfakes, or synthetic voice technology impersonating entity\\n     does NOT count unless the synthetic content is officially commissioned, authorized, or\\n     published by entity, OR the Contract explicitly specifies that AI-generated content counts.\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e is muted due to technical failure or censorship it shall not count unless\\n     corroborating contextual evidence (including surrounding speech, or an official\\n     uncensored recording or transcript) confirms that \\u003centity\\u003e specifically uttered \\u003cword\\u003e\\n     during the muted period.\\n\\nMinimum Tick: The Minimum Tick size for the Contract shall be $0.01.\\n\\nPosition Accountability Level: The Position Accountability Level for the Contract shall be\\n$25,000 per strike, per Member.\\n\\nLast Trading Date: The Last Trading Date of the Contract will be the Expiration Date. The Last\\nTrading Time will be the Expiration time.\\n\\nSettlement Date: The Settlement Date of the Contract shall be no later than the day after the\\nExpiration Date, unless the Market Outcome is under review pursuant to Rule 7.1.\\n\\nExpiration Date: When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event: The latest Expiration Date of\\nthe Contract shall be fourteen (14) calendar days after the originally scheduled date of the\\nevent. If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window, expiration will be moved to an\\nearlier date and time in accordance with Rule 7.2. When \\u003ctime period\\u003e is defined by specific\\ndates: The latest Expiration Date of the Contract shall be two weeks after the end of \\u003ctime\\nperiod\\u003e. If an event described in the Payout Criterion occurs and a consensus has been\\nreached on all terms, then expiration will be moved to an earlier date and time in accordance\\nwith Rule 7.2.\\n\\fExpiration time: The Expiration time of the Contract shall be 10:00 AM ET.\\n\\nSettlement Value: The Settlement Value for this Contract is $1.00.\\n\\nExpiration Value: The Expiration Value is the value of the Underlying as documented by the\\nSource Agency on the Expiration Date at the Expiration time.\\n\\nContingencies: Before Settlement, Kalshi may, at its sole discretion, initiate the Market\\nOutcome Review Process pursuant to Rule 7.1 of the Rulebook. If an Expiration Value cannot\\nbe determined on the Expiration Date, Kalshi has the right to determine payouts pursuant to\\nRule 7.1 in the Rulebook.\\n\\f\\n\\n[defendant] DX-5 Formal draw archive note\\nSource checked: Roll Call / Factba.se archive\\n\\nArchive title: Remarks: Donald Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing in Washington - December 5, 2025\\n\\nArchive URL: https://rollcall.com/factbase/trump/transcript/donald-trump-remarks-fifa-world-cup-drawing-december-5-2025/\\n\\nWhat this file establishes:\\n\\nThere is a separate archived transcript page for Trump's formal attendance remarks at the draw.\\n\\nWhat this file does not establish:\\n\\nThis session could not retrieve the full transcript text from that archive.  The page is password-protected.  This example therefore does not claim, from local files alone, whether the formal program transcript does or does not contain the word \\\"Ronaldo.\\\"\\n\\nWhy this matters:\\n\\nThe complaint does not need to prove that the formal program omitted the strike.  It needs to show that Trump said \\\"Ronaldo\\\" in event-linked remarks and that the market boundary reasonably includes those remarks.  The formal archive remains relevant because it marks the distinction between the pre-event reporter exchange and the formal program.\\n\\n\\n[defendant] DX-6 Formal Roll Call/Factba.se transcript extraction\\nSource: Roll Call / Factba.se\\nURL: https://rollcall.com/factbase/trump/transcript/donald-trump-remarks-fifa-world-cup-drawing-december-5-2025/\\nCaptured page title: Remarks: Donald Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing in Washington - December 5, 2025\\n\\nRendered page metadata excerpt:\\nTopics: Sport; Sport \\u003e Competition Discipline \\u003e Soccer; Lifestyle and Leisure \\u003e Leisure \\u003e Game.\\nEntities listed: bowl; deal; Donald J. Trump; FIFA World Cup; Mark Carney; place; President; trophy; United States; way.\\nSpeakers listed: Gianni Infantino, Donald Trump, Mark Carney, Claudia Sheinbaum.\\nSpeaker statistics excerpt: Donald Trump said 25 sentences of a total of 141 sentences; Donald Trump said 274 words of a total of 1009 words; Donald Trump talked 92 seconds of a total of 484 seconds.\\n\\nFormal transcript excerpt at start of draw:\\nMark Carney, 00:00:00-00:00:02: Thank you, my friend.\\nGianni Infantino, 00:00:50-00:01:22: So this is the World Cup trophy. This is the official bowl for the World Cup and we are now going to do the draw, ladies and gentlemen. But before that, as is customary, there is always a question that the moderator asks the draw assistant. So I would like to start with Mr. Carney. How big a deal is it to co-host the World Cup for Canada?\\n\\nFormal transcript excerpt of Trump's soccer answer:\\nDonald Trump, 00:03:14-00:03:32: Well, for years, Gianni, they've thought soccer or football would be so big, so fast. And I remember, I shouldn't say this because it was a long time ago, but I remember watching Pele play on a team called the Cosmos, Pele, who was fantastic, as you know. I assume one of the greats.\\n\\nText-extraction/search notes:\\nLocal Python urllib retrieval of the page returned HTTP 200 for the source URL and extracted approximately 175,864 characters of page text with Python html.parser. Case-sensitive searches in the extracted page text returned no occurrence of \\\"Ronaldo\\\" and no occurrence of \\\"Messi\\\". The same terms were not found using the browser page find function on the rendered page.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R1 Defendant formal transcript extraction for limited rebuttal use\\nSource: Roll Call / Factba.se\\nURL: https://rollcall.com/factbase/trump/transcript/donald-trump-remarks-fifa-world-cup-drawing-december-5-2025/\\nCaptured page title: Remarks: Donald Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing in Washington - December 5, 2025\\n\\nRendered page metadata excerpt:\\nTopics: Sport; Sport \\u003e Competition Discipline \\u003e Soccer; Lifestyle and Leisure \\u003e Leisure \\u003e Game.\\nEntities listed: bowl; deal; Donald J. Trump; FIFA World Cup; Mark Carney; place; President; trophy; United States; way.\\nSpeakers listed: Gianni Infantino, Donald Trump, Mark Carney, Claudia Sheinbaum.\\nSpeaker statistics excerpt: Donald Trump said 25 sentences of a total of 141 sentences; Donald Trump said 274 words of a total of 1009 words; Donald Trump talked 92 seconds of a total of 484 seconds.\\n\\nFormal transcript excerpt at start of draw:\\nMark Carney, 00:00:00-00:00:02: Thank you, my friend.\\nGianni Infantino, 00:00:50-00:01:22: So this is the World Cup trophy. This is the official bowl for the World Cup and we are now going to do the draw, ladies and gentlemen. But before that, as is customary, there is always a question that the moderator asks the draw assistant. So I would like to start with Mr. Carney. How big a deal is it to co-host the World Cup for Canada?\\n\\nFormal transcript excerpt of Trump's soccer answer:\\nDonald Trump, 00:03:14-00:03:32: Well, for years, Gianni, they've thought soccer or football would be so big, so fast. And I remember, I shouldn't say this because it was a long time ago, but I remember watching Pele play on a team called the Cosmos, Pele, who was fantastic, as you know. I assume one of the greats.\\n\\nText-extraction/search notes:\\nLocal Python urllib retrieval of the page returned HTTP 200 for the source URL and extracted approximately 175,864 characters of page text with Python html.parser. Case-sensitive searches in the extracted page text returned no occurrence of \\\"Ronaldo\\\" and no occurrence of \\\"Messi\\\". The same terms were not found using the browser page find function on the rendered page.\\n\\nSubmitted evidence:\\n[plaintiff arguments] GovInfo DCPD202501162 transcript excerpt and metadata (ev_3fc783920414_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-3fc783920414)\\nSource: https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/DCPD-202501162/html/DCPD-202501162.htm\\nSHA-256: `3fc783920414399098d86210070dd9fe83c14fe1dbded1a56a554f8f4b3448f2`\\nBytes: 2641\\nRelevance: Official government transcript source corroborating that Trump spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center before the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw and said the strike word Ronaldo in World-Cup-related remarks.\\n\\n[defendant arguments] Roll Call/Factba.se formal FIFA World Cup Drawing transcript extraction (ev_fbb53e87ccb3_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-fbb53e87ccb3)\\nSource: https://rollcall.com/factbase/trump/transcript/donald-trump-remarks-fifa-world-cup-drawing-december-5-2025/\\nSHA-256: `fbb53e87ccb3f4381fc2bdc06ac2f2a1ea3848aadde56122b22d34dfbdf4533b`\\nBytes: 2032\\nRelevance: Formal drawing-program transcript evidence showing a separate formal Draw source from the pre-event reporter exchange; the extracted page text contains no occurrence of Ronaldo or Messi, supporting defendant's event-boundary argument.\\n\\nTechnical reports:\\n[plaintiff] Plaintiff source and adverse-search ledger\\nChecked the visible case packet and then searched official/source-specific repositories. GovInfo DCPD202501162 was opened and preserved as submitted evidence; it corroborates the packet transcript, source metadata, location, event date, and Ronaldo passages. The Roll Call/Factba.se formal drawing page rendered despite the packet's password-protection note; browser find searches for 'Ronaldo,' 'Cristiano,' and 'Messi' returned no matches. Plaintiff therefore treats the formal-program transcript as an adverse boundary check, not as proof of a formal-stage mention. The remaining dispute is contractual scope: whether the market clearly excluded public event-linked venue remarks immediately before the formal program.\\n\\n[defendant] Defense source-check ledger\\nDefendant searched for the formal Roll Call/Factba.se transcript identified by the case packet, opened the rendered Roll Call page, and fetched it locally with Python urllib. The fetch returned HTTP 200 for the formal FIFA World Cup Drawing transcript page. Text extraction produced approximately 175,864 characters; searches for \\\"Ronaldo\\\" and \\\"Messi\\\" returned no occurrences. The retrieval also captured formal-program excerpts, including Infantino's statement that \\\"we are now going to do the draw\\\" and Trump's formal soccer answer mentioning Pele rather than Ronaldo. The focused extraction was submitted and accepted as ev_fbb53e87ccb3_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-fbb53e87ccb3.\\n\\nCall submit_council_vote with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated.\\nKeep the rationale brief: no more than three sentences.\\n\\nCouncil API instructions:\\nYou are a council member. Decide the proposition from the admitted record.\\nYou may examine admitted evidence through read-only tools when exact bytes, metadata, or exhibit contents matter.\\nDo not search the web, introduce new facts, create new evidence, or upload evidence.\\nWhen ready, call submit_council_vote exactly once with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated and a concise rationale.\\n\",\"state\":\"ready\",\"status\":\"ready\",\"tools\":[{\"description\":\"Return the current visible arbitration record for this council member.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"get_case\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"List visible immutable record evidence.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"list_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Return metadata and read limits for one visible evidence item.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"stat_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Read a bounded byte range from one visible evidence item as base64.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"length\":{\"minimum\":1,\"type\":\"integer\"},\"offset\":{\"minimum\":0,\"type\":\"integer\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\",\"offset\",\"length\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"read_evidence_range\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Submit one council vote for the current deliberation opportunity.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"rationale\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"vote\":{\"enum\":[\"demonstrated\",\"not_demonstrated\"],\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"vote\",\"rationale\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"submit_council_vote\",\"read_only\":false}],\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":false,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-29T19:58:02.156322961Z\",\"deliberation_round\":1,\"member_id\":\"C2\",\"opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C2\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"remaining_ms\":887183,\"role_id\":\"council\",\"turn_number\":10},\"wait\":{\"reason\":\"ready\",\"state_version\":12,\"version\":15}}"}],"details":{"mode":"call","mcpResult":{"content":[{"type":"text","text":"ok: true\nstatus: ready\nstate: ready\nmessage: An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\nafter_version: 15\nafter_opportunity_id: deliberation:1:C2\nmember_id: C2\ncase_id: arb-ex03-20260629192557\nwait_reason: ready\nphase: deliberation\nopportunity_id: deliberation:1:C2\nremaining_ms: 887183\nattempts_remaining: 3\njson: {\"after_opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C2\",\"after_version\":15,\"case_id\":\"arb-ex03-20260629192557\",\"limits\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"max_evidence_read_bytes\":65536,\"max_evidence_read_bytes_per_opportunity\":524288,\"max_evidence_reads_per_opportunity\":32,\"max_response_bytes\":131072,\"remaining_evidence_read_bytes_for_opportunity\":524288,\"remaining_evidence_reads_for_opportunity\":32},\"member_id\":\"C2\",\"message\":\"An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\",\"ok\":true,\"prompt\":\"Role: council member\\nMember ID: C2\\nDeliberation round: 1\\nProposition: For the Kalshi market \\\"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\\", the strike \\\"Ronaldo\\\" should resolve Yes because Trump said \\\"Ronaldo\\\" in public remarks at the World Cup Draw venue immediately before the formal program, and the market wording plus the governing mention-market terms did not clearly exclude those event-linked remarks.\\nStandard of evidence: Preponderance of the evidence.\\nPersona:\\nYou are a careful juror and council member.\\n\\nEvaluate the record faithfully. Decide only from the evidence, the stated rules, and the applicable burden of proof. Do not favor either side, fill gaps with speculation, or ignore uncertainty.\\n\\nGive weight to reliable sources, direct evidence, consistent reasoning, and clear admissions. Discount unsupported claims, rhetorical force, irrelevant facts, and conclusions that exceed the record.\\n\\nWhen the evidence supports one answer, state it plainly. When the evidence is incomplete or balanced, say so. Be concise, honest, and exact.\\n\\nRecord:\\nOpenings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, this case is not mainly about whether the syllables were spoken. The case-packet transcript says they were. The real dispute is the market boundary: when Kalshi asked what Trump would say \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw,\\\" did that phrase clearly exclude his public, event-linked remarks at the World Cup Draw venue immediately before the formal program? On this record, it did not.\\n\\nThe market page fixes the contract at issue: the public title was \\\"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\\"; the contract family was PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION; the strike was \\\"Ronaldo\\\"; Kalshi challenged the resolution as No; and the requested resolution is Yes. That means the council's task is to apply the mention-market terms to that title and strike, not to import a narrower limitation that the market did not plainly announce.\\n\\nThe reporter-exchange packet is direct evidence on the word and setting. It is titled as remarks in an exchange with reporters prior to the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw, dated December 5, 2025. It places the President at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts, speaking with FIFA President Gianni Infantino and reporters in a sequence repeatedly labeled around the 2026 World Cup and the Draw. In that exchange, in a soccer discussion, Trump says he met Ronaldo, praises him, and uses \\\"Ronaldo\\\" as a distinct standalone word. Under the mention rules, a distinct standalone appearance of the strike is the kind of use that counts if it falls within the time period.\\n\\nThe terms matter because they do not say that an event market is limited only to scripted remarks from a formal stage segment. They define a time period as potentially an event or context, and they give the Exchange power to specify what is included when a time period refers to a specific event. They also distinguish official/public event content from behind-the-scenes, rehearsals, and unofficial recordings. That distinction helps plaintiff: the packet is not a rumor, rehearsal, private soundcheck, or leaked recording. It is a sourced public transcript of remarks at the event venue, immediately tied to the Draw. If Kalshi meant \\\"only the formal televised draw program after doors close\\\" or \\\"only remarks in the separate formal archive,\\\" it needed to say so clearly.\\n\\nI also want to be candid about what the packet does not yet prove. The formal-draw archive note says a separate archived transcript page exists for Trump's formal attendance remarks, but that the session could not retrieve the full text because the page was password-protected. So, at opening, plaintiff is not asking you to infer that the formal program itself contained \\\"Ronaldo.\\\" Nor does plaintiff need that inference. The Yes theory is that the qualifying period reasonably includes the public pre-program reporter exchange that was part of Trump's World Cup Draw appearance. The formal archive is relevant because it marks defendant's likely narrower boundary; it does not resolve the boundary in defendant's favor.\\n\\nProvenance and weight also favor treating the packet seriously at this stage. The market and terms files are system case-packet records. The reporter exchange includes a source URL to a public presidential transcript source and notes a corrected transcript date, while also acknowledging that some audio could not be verified because the audio was incomplete. That caveat may affect inaudible portions, but it does not erase the visible, contextual Ronaldo passage. Later, when evidence admission opens, the parties should preserve the official transcript source, any govinfo or Presidency Project copy, the market page capture, and any accessible formal-program transcript or video. The adverse check should ask whether the formal program omits the word, but omission there would matter only if the council first accepts the defense's artificially narrow reading of \\\"during.\\\"\\n\\nThe plaintiff's burden is preponderance. The record already points to a straightforward path to Yes: Trump, the specified entity, said the specified strike as a standalone word in public remarks linked to and immediately preceding the World Cup Draw at the venue; the market title and governing terms did not clearly exclude that event-linked exchange. On a fair reading of the contract the trader saw, the challenged No resolution should give way to Yes.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the defense opening is simple: this case is not won by proving that the word \\\"Ronaldo\\\" appears somewhere in a public transcript. The plaintiff must prove, by a preponderance, that the word was said during the market's specified event: the FIFA World Cup Draw.\\n\\nThe current packet leaves that critical link unproven. The market page does not say \\\"while Trump was at the venue,\\\" \\\"during a World Cup press availability,\\\" or \\\"during any remarks connected to the Draw.\\\" It says: \\\"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\\" The challenged resolution was No. The requested Yes theory therefore needs more than event-adjacent context; it needs a boundary showing that the reporter exchange was part of the Draw period the market asked traders to price.\\n\\nThe plaintiff's own best transcript cuts against that boundary. The case-packet file is titled \\\"Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw.\\\" It says the President's remarks were joined in progress, and the source note says portions could not be verified because the audio was incomplete. It places Trump at the Kennedy Center and includes World Cup topics, and yes, it contains \\\"Ronaldo\\\" as a standalone word in a soccer exchange. But its title and structure identify those remarks as an exchange with reporters prior to the Draw, not the formal Draw itself.\\n\\nThe terms do not rescue plaintiff from that distinction. They define a mention market around words used by the entity during the time period. A time period may be a specific event, and when it is a specific event, the Exchange may specify what is included. The technical details also distinguish official presentation content from behind-the-scenes, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings unless those are officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. Those provisions do not mean every public, nearby, event-related conversation becomes part of the event. They make the event boundary the central question.\\n\\nThe formal-draw archive note reinforces why the distinction matters. It reports that there is a separate archived transcript page for Trump's formal attendance remarks at the FIFA World Cup Drawing, but that the full text was not retrieved because the page was password-protected. That note does not prove the formal program omitted Ronaldo. It also does not prove the formal program included it. What it does show, at opening, is that the record itself separates the pre-event reporter exchange from the formal drawing remarks.\\n\\nSo the defense will focus the council on proof of inclusion, not mere association. If later phases produce a market page provision, official broadcast record, program transcript, video metadata, or source-agency material showing that the red-carpet reporter exchange was officially part of the FIFA World Cup Draw presentation for this market, the council can weigh that. If the later evidence instead shows a formal program with a separate pre-program press availability, then the correct result is No even though the word was spoken nearby.\\n\\nOn this opening record, plaintiff has shown a Ronaldo mention in remarks prior to the event. Plaintiff has not shown that those remarks occurred during the market event. The defense position is that Kalshi's No resolution follows the market wording and the mention-market terms unless plaintiff supplies that missing boundary proof.\\n\\nArguments:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the merits question is whether the contract clearly limited “during the FIFA World Cup Draw” to only the formal staged ceremony. Plaintiff submits that it did not, and the record now proves the Yes result by a preponderance.\\n\\nFirst, the market itself is broad. PX-1 identifies the public question as “What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?”, contract family PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION, strike “Ronaldo,” challenged resolution No, and requested resolution Yes. The market page does not say “during the formal televised ceremony,” “on the main stage only,” or “excluding public remarks immediately before the program at the venue.” That absence matters because Kalshi drafted the boundary traders had to price.\\n\\nSecond, the word was said. PX-2, the case-packet transcript, and PX-5, the GovInfo/OFR source excerpt, both show Trump used “Ronaldo” as a standalone word in soccer-related remarks. PX-5 is especially useful on provenance: it is the GovInfo Compilation of Presidential Documents source, published by the Office of the Federal Register/NARA, for DCPD202501162. It identifies the same event date, title, and source note, and it places the remarks at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center. In the relevant passage, Trump says he met Ronaldo, then says Ronaldo is great; later, when asked whether he played soccer or football, Trump says he was not Ronaldo or Messi. Either use satisfies the mention rule if the remarks fall within the market’s time period.\\n\\nThird, the remarks are event-linked in the way the market title reasonably covers. PX-2 and PX-5 are not private gossip, rehearsal, or an unofficial leak. They are public presidential remarks at the World Cup Draw venue, with FIFA President Infantino present, repeatedly discussing the Draw, the World Cup, ticket sales, the Kennedy Center, the audience, and the imminent program. The transcript itself includes headings such as “2026 World Cup Draw Event,” “2026 World Cup Draw Event/John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts,” and “2026 World Cup Draw/Ticket Sales for World Cup.” Trump and Infantino even discuss being a little late to “get in there” and the audience waiting. That sequence is not a random earlier interview; it is part of the public event appearance immediately surrounding the Draw.\\n\\nFourth, PX-3’s terms do not impose defendant’s formal-only line. They say the underlying is words used by the entity during the specified time period; a time period may be an event or context; and, when a time period refers to a specific event, the Exchange may specify what is included. They also say official/published content presented as part of the official presentation can count, while behind-the-scenes, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings do not count unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. Those exclusions show what this is not. The transcript is an official published record of public remarks at the event venue, not a hidden backstage clip. Nothing in PX-1 or PX-3 clearly tells traders that public, event-linked venue remarks immediately before the formal program are out.\\n\\nDefendant’s best point is PX-4 and the formal Roll Call/Factba.se page: there is a separate formal-drawing transcript, and my search found no “Ronaldo” there. Plaintiff does not hide that. But that adverse point proves only that the narrower formal-program source may omit the strike. It does not answer the contractual question. If Kalshi had meant to resolve solely by that formal transcript, it could have said so. Instead, the public market title used the broader phrase “during the FIFA World Cup Draw,” and the mention terms leave event boundaries to what the market clearly specifies.\\n\\nOn burden, plaintiff does not need absolute certainty or a formal-stage mention. Plaintiff must show it is more likely than not that the market wording plus terms include the event-linked remarks. The evidence satisfies that standard: PX-1 gives no exclusion; PX-2 and PX-5 prove the standalone Ronaldo mentions in public World Cup Draw venue remarks; PX-3 supplies a flexible event/time-period framework and excludes only categories unlike this source; PX-4 merely identifies the defense’s alternate formal-program boundary. The fair resolution is Yes.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the record now makes the defense point sharper, not weaker. Plaintiff has proved that Trump said \\\"Ronaldo\\\" in an official transcript of remarks connected to the World Cup Draw. Plaintiff has not proved that those remarks were during the market event.\\n\\nStart with the contract. DX/PX-1 gives the trader-facing question: \\\"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\\" It does not say \\\"at the Kennedy Center,\\\" \\\"on World Cup Draw day,\\\" \\\"in remarks prior to the Draw,\\\" or \\\"in any public press exchange associated with the Draw.\\\" For this strike to resolve Yes, the relevant mention must fall inside that specified time period.\\n\\nThe strongest evidence of the Ronaldo utterance is also the strongest evidence against plaintiff's boundary. PX-2 and PX-5 are titled \\\"Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw.\\\" PX-5, plaintiff's GovInfo/OFR source, confirms the same title, says the remarks were joined in progress, identifies the source as an exchange with the news media, and notes that some portions could not be verified because the audio was incomplete. That evidence proves an official pre-event reporter transcript. It does not prove the reporter exchange was the FIFA World Cup Draw.\\n\\nThe terms, PX-3, require words used by the entity during the specified time period. They permit an event or context as a time period, and they discuss what is included when the time period is a specific event. That framework does not turn all event-adjacent speech into event speech. The distinction between official presentation content and non-included behind-the-scenes or unofficial content matters because the question is not just whether a record is public or official. The question is whether this source was part of the market's event period. A public official transcript can still be a transcript of remarks prior to the event.\\n\\nDX-2 supplies the missing contrast. It is a focused extraction from the separate Roll Call/Factba.se formal FIFA World Cup Drawing transcript. That page is the formal source identified in the case-packet archive note. It is titled \\\"Remarks: Donald Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing in Washington - December 5, 2025.\\\" Its transcript begins with the formal drawing participants; at 00:00:50, Infantino says, \\\"This is the World Cup trophy\\\" and \\\"we are now going to do the draw.\\\" The page's Trump soccer answer mentions Pele and the Cosmos, not Ronaldo. The extracted page text was searched for both \\\"Ronaldo\\\" and \\\"Messi\\\" and neither appears.\\n\\nThat does not prove Trump never said Ronaldo anywhere at the venue. It proves the opposite boundary from plaintiff's: the formal Draw transcript is separate from the pre-event reporter exchange, and the formal transcript does not contain the strike. Plaintiff needs a bridge between those two sources. It has not offered one. There is no market page detail saying red-carpet or pre-program press remarks count. There is no official program metadata showing the reporter exchange was part of the Draw presentation. There is no source hierarchy provision selecting the pre-event reporter exchange over the formal Draw transcript for this market.\\n\\nPlaintiff argues ambiguity should favor Yes because Kalshi could have drafted a narrower rule. But this is a preponderance case about a challenged No resolution, not a penalty for every conceivable ambiguity. The ordinary reading of \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw\\\" is the draw program, not every public appearance immediately before it. The record's own labels preserve that ordinary line: \\\"Prior to\\\" on the Ronaldo source; \\\"Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing\\\" on the formal source; and a formal transcript that starts the draw and omits the strike.\\n\\nWeight and provenance also favor the defense on the decisive issue. PX-5 is official and useful, but it authenticates a pre-event reporter exchange. DX-2 is a captured formal transcript extraction from the source class identified in PX-4; its absence finding is limited but material. PX-4 was initially only a note that the formal page existed and could not be retrieved. We have now retrieved and searched it. The adverse check therefore confirms, rather than merely speculates, that the formal drawing transcript does not carry plaintiff's Ronaldo mention.\\n\\nThe council should resolve the proposition against plaintiff. The record shows Trump said Ronaldo before the FIFA World Cup Draw in an event-linked reporter exchange. It does not show he said Ronaldo during the FIFA World Cup Draw. On this market wording and these terms, the challenged No resolution should stand.\\n\\nRebuttals:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, defendant’s new formal-transcript extraction proves less than defendant needs.\\n\\nPlaintiff accepts the narrow fact defendant has now preserved: the Roll Call/Factba.se formal drawing-program extraction contains no “Ronaldo” or “Messi.” That is why plaintiff did not build the case on a formal-stage mention. The proposition instead asks whether the market wording and mention terms clearly excluded Trump’s public, official, event-linked remarks at the venue immediately before the formal program. Defendant has not supplied that exclusion.\\n\\nDefendant’s argument treats the title “Prior to the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw” as if “prior to” automatically means outside the Kalshi market’s event period. But PX-1 does not say “formal transcript only,” “after the draw host begins,” “after 00:00:50,” or “excluding press availability at the venue.” It asks what Trump would say “during the FIFA World Cup Draw.” The source label tells us sequence; it does not tell us the market’s legal boundary.\\n\\nDX-2 actually illustrates why defendant’s bright line is chosen after the fact. In defendant’s own formal extraction, the page begins before the mechanical draw: Mark Carney speaks at 00:00:00, and Infantino says at 00:00:50, “we are now going to do the draw.” If “during the FIFA World Cup Draw” can include ceremony and preamble on the formal page before the draw itself begins, then the phrase is not self-defining down to a single moment or transcript. The question is what the market clearly specified. It did not specify defendant’s transcript-only rule.\\n\\nThe terms do not fill that gap for defendant. PX-3 excludes hidden categories such as rehearsals, sound checks, unofficial recordings, and behind-the-scenes content unless officially published as part of the period. PX-2 and PX-5 are not those categories. PX-5 is an official GovInfo/OFR presidential transcript, published with source metadata, at 11:13 a.m. at the Kennedy Center, with FIFA’s president present and the World Cup Draw repeatedly discussed. That gives the Ronaldo mentions strong provenance and an event connection; it does not make them informal backstage chatter.\\n\\nDefendant says plaintiff needs a bridge. The bridge is the market text plus the terms’ failure to draw the narrow line defendant proposes. A No resolution can stand only if the contract fairly told traders that “during the FIFA World Cup Draw” meant only the separate formal-program transcript. On this record, the more likely reading is broader: public, official remarks at the venue, immediately tied to and immediately preceding the World Cup Draw program, were within the event-linked period unless clearly excluded.\\n\\nSo DX-2 narrows one factual issue but does not decide the case. It shows no formal-stage Ronaldo mention. It does not show that the market excluded the official pre-program event remarks where Trump did say Ronaldo. Under the preponderance standard, the Yes resolution remains the fair one.\\n\\nSurrebuttals:\\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff’s rebuttal usefully narrows the dispute. Plaintiff accepts that the formal Roll Call/Factba.se drawing transcript contains no “Ronaldo” or “Messi.” So the case remains entirely about whether a separate reporter exchange titled “Prior to the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw” should be treated as inside the market period.\\n\\nPlaintiff says “prior to” is only sequence, not legal boundary. But sequence is exactly what the market phrase makes material. The contract asks what Trump would say “during the FIFA World Cup Draw.” A source-agency title identifying the Ronaldo transcript as an exchange with reporters prior to that Draw is not a stray label; it is the best record description of when and what that source is. Plaintiff cannot convert that source into the event itself by saying the market failed to list every excluded pre-event setting.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s formal-preamble point also does not carry the burden. Yes, the formal transcript begins before the mechanical ball selection, and Infantino says at 00:00:50 that “we are now going to do the draw.” But that supports the defense distinction. A host’s preamble inside the formal drawing transcript is part of the program. A separate press exchange, separately titled and sourced as prior to the Draw, is not made part of the program simply because it happened nearby and discussed the same event.\\n\\nNor does official publication settle the issue. PX-5 strengthens provenance: Trump did say Ronaldo in an official public transcript. But provenance answers whether the words were said, not whether they were said during the market’s specified event. The terms require both: the word by the entity, and the word during the time period. Plaintiff has the first element. The second is still missing.\\n\\nThe remaining bridge plaintiff proposes is essentially: public, official, event-linked, and not expressly excluded. That is not enough under a preponderance standard when the same record supplies a cleaner boundary: the Ronaldo source is prior to the Draw, and the formal Draw source omits the strike. The challenged No resolution should stand.\\n\\nClosings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the record has narrowed to one real issue.\\n\\nThe word is proven. The market page identifies the strike as “Ronaldo” and the challenged resolution as No. The case-packet transcript and the GovInfo/OFR excerpt prove that Trump said “Ronaldo” as a standalone word in public remarks at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center, in a World Cup Draw setting, with FIFA President Infantino present, and amid repeated discussion of the Draw, the Kennedy Center, ticket sales, the audience, and the imminent event. That is strong provenance: GovInfo, NARA/OFR, DCPD202501162, matching the packet source and note.\\n\\nDefendant has also proved its best fact. The Roll Call/Factba.se formal-program extraction does not contain “Ronaldo” or “Messi.” Plaintiff does not ask you to find otherwise. If the market had said “only the formal drawing transcript,” defendant would win. But that is not the market traders saw.\\n\\nThe market asked: “What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?” It did not say “during the formal transcript only,” “after the host announces the draw has begun,” “excluding public press remarks at the venue,” or “excluding remarks immediately before the program.” The governing terms do not add that limitation. They define words used by the entity during the time period, allow event/context time periods, and exclude categories such as rehearsals, sound checks, behind-the-scenes content, and unofficial recordings. Plaintiff’s source is none of those. It is an official public presidential transcript of event-linked remarks at the venue.\\n\\nDefendant’s formal extraction shows why a bright line cannot simply be assumed. Even on that page, before balls are drawn, there is ceremony, introduction, and Infantino saying “we are now going to do the draw.” Event boundaries are not self-defining. The question is whether Kalshi clearly chose defendant’s narrower boundary. The record contains no such choice.\\n\\nSo the burden is met. More likely than not, a reasonable reading of the market and terms includes Trump’s official, public, venue-based remarks immediately tied to the World Cup Draw. The strongest contrary evidence proves only that a narrower formal transcript omits the strike. It does not prove the contract excluded the remarks where the strike was actually said.\\n\\nThe challenged No resolution should be overturned. The strike “Ronaldo” should resolve Yes.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff’s closing concedes the decisive factual split: the formal World Cup Drawing transcript contains no “Ronaldo” or “Messi.” The only Ronaldo evidence is the separate official transcript titled “Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw.”\\n\\nThat is enough to decide the case. The market did not ask what Trump would say at the Kennedy Center, on World Cup Draw day, in public presidential remarks, or in event-linked press availability. It asked what Trump would say “during the FIFA World Cup Draw.” The terms require the word to be used by the entity during the specified time period. Plaintiff has proven the word and the speaker. It has not proven the time period.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s strongest point is that the market did not expressly say “formal transcript only” or “exclude pre-program remarks.” But plaintiff has the burden. A challenged No resolution does not become Yes merely because the contract could have been even more verbose. The record must make it more likely than not that the pre-event reporter exchange was inside the market period. The record does the opposite.\\n\\nThe source labels matter. PX-2 and PX-5 are official and probative, but they are official proof of remarks prior to the Draw. The formal Roll Call/Factba.se extraction is the source for Trump’s formal attendance at the FIFA World Cup Drawing; it begins the program, includes the draw presentation, and omits the strike. Plaintiff’s theory asks you to treat a separate prior reporter exchange as “during” the Draw even though the formal Draw source exists and does not contain the word.\\n\\nThe terms do not collapse that distinction. They recognize event/context time periods and official presentation content, but they still require the word to occur during the chosen time period. Official publication proves provenance. Event connection proves relevance. Neither proves inclusion. A public official transcript can be accurately preserved and still be outside the market window if it is, as titled, prior to the event.\\n\\nSo the fair synthesis is narrow and grounded: Trump said Ronaldo in event-linked public remarks before the FIFA World Cup Draw; Trump did not say Ronaldo in the formal drawing transcript preserved in this record; and no admitted market term or source-chain evidence bridges the pre-event exchange into the market’s “during the FIFA World Cup Draw” period.\\n\\nUnder the preponderance standard, plaintiff has not carried the proposition. The challenged No resolution should stand.\\n\\nExhibits:\\n[plaintiff] PX-1 Market page and challenged resolution\\nMarket URL: https://kalshi.com/markets/kxtrumpmentionb/trump-mention-b/kxtrumpmentionb-25dec06\\n\\nPublic market title: What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\n\\nContract family: PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION\\n\\nStrike at issue: Ronaldo\\n\\nChallenged resolution: No\\n\\nRequested resolution: Yes\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-2 Pre-event reporter exchange transcript\\nRemarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\nDecember 05, 2025\\n\\n[The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\\nThe President. It's a great honor to be here. Gianni has done a fantastic job. We're setting records—[inaudible].\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. Well, I think so. They have a little bit of a shot. Pretty stiff competition. But I would say they would have a small chance.\\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize\\nQ. [Inaudible]—win the FIFA Peace Award?\\nThe President. Well, it would be an honor.\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\nQ. Will you root for some selection? Will you root for someone?\\nThe President. Well, I root for a lot of countries, but in this case, I'll be rooting for the U.S.A. [Laughter]\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. That's great. That's great. We really love it.\\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize\\nQ. Mr. President, have you been told that you are going to receive the inaugural peace prize today——\\nThe President. I have not——\\nQ. ——from FIFA?\\nThe President. I have not been told. There's a rumor about it, but I have not been told. That would be a great honor, and I'm a big fan of Gianni, as you know.\\nQ. What can fans expect——\\nQ. Are you hoping to receive that?\\nThe President. Excuse me.\\nQ. Are you hoping to receive the peace prize?\\nThe President. Well, I don't like to say \\\"hope,\\\" but it would be a great honor.\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. What can fans expect of, like, the World Cup in the U.S.?\\nThe President. I think it's going to be fantastic. We've set every record you can set.\\nQ. What are you telling people who are worried——\\nFédération Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) President Giovanni V. Infantino\\nQ. [Inaudible]—friend Gianni—[inaudible]—a word about him?\\nThe President. I think he has done a fantastic job.\\nThe President's Schedule\\nQ. Are you going to be meeting with the President of Mexico today and the——\\nThe President. We might. Yes.\\nQ. ——Prime Minister of Canada as well?\\nThe President. I might. I might do that.\\nQ. Will you be discussing immigration and trade with them?\\nThe President. Yes, we'll be discussing.\\n[At this point, the President and Mr. Infantino posed for photographs.]\\nThe President. Thank you, everybody.\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event/John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts\\nQ. Mr. President, what do you think about the crowd?\\nThe President. Oh, look, the new star—[inaudible].\\nCongratulations.\\nQ. Thank you.\\nThe President. You're the new star of television and Fox.\\nQ. Thank you. How are you doing, Mr. President?\\nThe President. I'm doing very well.\\nQ. What do you think about the crowd here?\\nThe President. I think the crowd is great, and I think the building is great. We've made a lot of improvements over the last 6 months. Taking—the Kennedy Center was in very bad shape. Now it's getting to be really good. And in 6 months, it's going to be incredible with the improvements we've made.\\nQ. The first time for the U.S. to host since the nineties.\\nThe President. Right.\\nQ. Are you ready for it?\\nThe President. I'm ready for it, and they're ready for it. And Gianni, who you know——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——has done a fantastic job with FIFA. And we're looking to have—you know, we're set—we have already set records for tickets sales. I don't think there's ever been anything like it in any sport. And so, I want to congratulate you.\\nMr. Infantino. Thank you.\\nThe President. I don't even have to wait. But major records have been set.\\nHow are you?\\nQ. Good, how are you, sir?\\nThe President. Nice to see you.\\nQ. Today it's not football—American football. It's soccer. It's——\\nThe President. Right.\\nQ. ——the big event of soccer.\\nThe President. That's right. That's right.\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\nQ. So can you tell me about this big day today?\\nThe President. It's just a big day, and it's a great sport. And it really is coming to America. And never—nobody ever thought a thing like this could happen. And I'm very happy to say that we've already set the alltime record on ticket sales long before the first ball is kicked. Right?\\nMr. Infantino. A hundred percent. One hundred percent.\\n2026 World Cup Host Cities\\nQ. You've had some concerns about crime in American cities, some of the cities that will be hosting. Have they remedied that for you? Are you still considering maybe asking FIFA to move some of those cities?\\nThe President. No, I don't want to do that. But I will tell you, if they do have a problem, by the time we get there, we'll take care of that problem. We can solve that problem.\\nI've proven that in DC and everywhere else we went, so we'll take care of that very easily. So, if they have a problem, hopefully, they'll let us know that, and we will solve any problem.\\nOkay? Thank you.\\nQ. Thank you so much.\\nMr. Infantino. All right, thank you so much.\\nQ. Thank you, Mr. President.\\nQ. Thank you. Appreciate it.\\nThe President. Congratulations.\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. Mr. President, Brazilian television. America will be hosting the World Cup and the Olympics in 2 years. How important it is—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. I think very. It's a great honor. I think Gianni is doing a phenomenal job. We've set every record on ticket sales. It's been really fantastic. But Gianni has done an unbelievable job with FIFA.\\nThe President's Experience With Soccer\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. He was a great—not only that. I got to see a man name Pelé play—right?—that tells you how old I am—when he was on the Cosmos. Do you remember that a long time ago? And it was quite a treat. That was quite an event. And he was—not only was he playing, he was great. He scored two goals, I think. And so, I was one of the few who got to see Pelé, and I assume he is one of your alltime greats. Right?\\nMr. Infantino. Definitely.\\nThe President. So I got to see him.\\nThe President's Favorite World Cup Competitor\\nQ. Do you have some favorite teams for World Cup?\\nThe President. Well, I have a favorite. It's the U.S.A. [Laughter] I don't know what their chances are, Gianni, but maybe the U.S.A. is the——\\nMr. Infantino. They're getting better and better, actually.\\nThe President. I think they'll do well.\\nMr. Infantino. They are getting better and better.\\nThe President. I think they'll do well.\\nThank you very much, everybody.\\nQ. Thank you so much.\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. Mr. President, World Cup in America just means—[inaudible]. So what do you expect from this World Cup?\\nThe President. [Inaudible]—record business and only in the United States, but we're also doing record ticket sales with FIFA. And they've already bought—beat their highest record. And we—you know, this a long time before the first ball is kicked. You've sold more tickets than they've ever done before, and better pricing than they've ever gotten before. It's a tremendous success. And it's an honor. And Gianni has done a phenomenal job with FIFA.\\nQ. [Inaudible]—ever?\\nThe President. I think so. I think it's going to be—I mean, ideally, you want to see that every year. Every 4 years, it gets bigger and better. I think we have set every record in the book. We're very happy about it.\\nThank you.\\nThe President's Favorite World Cup Competitor\\nQ. [Inaudible]—part of America. Who are you going to support as well?\\nThe President. Well, I think I have to support U.S.A. Otherwise, I'd be in trouble. I wouldn't be President for long.\\nMr. Infantino. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. [Inaudible]—but you have a lot of great teams. You're going to have a lot of great teams.\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\\\"football,\\\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\\n2026 World Cup Draw/Ticket Sales for World Cup\\nQ. How does it feel to be part of this amazing event? And obviously, your being a part of participating in all the—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. The President of Mexico is here, and she's doing a very good job. She's a good woman, very, very excellent job. It's an honor, and we're setting every record, and you're helping us set those records.\\nMr. Infantino. And we will do it.\\nThe President. You know, Mexico and Canada are helping us set those records. But as you know, we have a record in ticket sales already, long before the first ball is kicked, and we're going to do great.\\nI think that Gianni—as you know, he's the head, and he has done a fantastic job.\\nU.S. Cooperation With Mexico and Canada\\nQ. And how is the biggest challenge being three countries?\\nThe President. Well, I think that—do you mean for the three countries?\\nWell, they've gotten together really well, I mean.\\nMr. Infantino. All right.\\nThe President. They're getting along very well.\\nMr. Infantino. Collaboration is fantastic between the three.\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer/2026 World Cup\\nQ. And you like soccer?\\nThe President. I do. I like it. I like it more and more.\\nQ. Yes?\\nThe President. I like it. It's growing in this country—very, really—I mean, someday, maybe it's going to be bigger than anything else.\\nMr. Infantino. We'll have to become number one.\\nThe President. I will say this——\\nMr. Infantino. Definitely.\\nThe President. ——the ticket sales——\\nQ. Definitely will happen.\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. Ticket sales are bigger than anything we have ever done in the history of the country, in terms of sports.\\nMr. Infantino. For certain.\\nQ. And the audience is going to be huge.\\nThe President. The audience is going to be tremendous.\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. Yes.\\nMr. Infantino. Six billion people.\\nThe President. [Inaudible]\\nQ. Six billion? That's amazing.\\nMr. Infantino. Six billion people.\\nAnd today, one billion.\\nQ. Wow.\\nMr. Infantino. [Inaudible]\\nQ. Enjoy show time. Thank you so much.\\nThe President. [Inaudible]\\nQ. Mr. President, how are you? Just a quick—[inaudible].\\nQ. This is for Telemundo.\\nThe President. How are you?\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\nQ. Hello, Mr. President. How are you? This for Telemundo.\\nThe President. How are you? Good.\\nQ. How are you?\\nThe President. Very good. Thank you.\\nQ. How does it feel to have the most important event of sports—that global—in the U.S.?\\nThe President. Well, we do. And right at the Kennedy Center. I'm Chairman of the Kennedy Center. And I hear the Kennedy Center is doing a very good job, so it feels great. Really good.\\nAnd Telemundo is doing a good job, too. Thank you.\\nQ. Thank you.\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. What is the significance of hosting the FIFA World Cup this year?\\nThe President. It's a—in terms of sports, I would say the ultimate. There is no sport like this. It's the biggest sport in the world. And we are setting every record. You know, our ticket sales have gone and set every—every sport—no matter what it is, we've set the record. So—and every though it's very early, there's no ball being kicked yet, but we've already set a ticket sales record.\\nArgentina National Team\\nQ. How do you see Argentinean team for this World Cup?\\nThe President. Well, I love Argentina. And your President is doing a very good job, as you know. Milei. You know that right? It's make Argentina great again. MAGA.\\nQ. And——\\nU.S. National Team\\nQ. Do you think the States are building a powerful team for next year?\\nThe President. Who?\\nQ. The States.\\nThe President. Oh, yes. Sure. I—you're going to have a lot of powerful teams. Everybody has a lot of powerful teams, but you're going to have a lot of great teams. [Inaudible]\\nU.S. Role in Hosting the 2026 World Cup\\nQ. Mr. President, what does it mean for you guys to host the World Cup right here in the U.S.?\\nThe President. I'm honored to host it. It's a great honor. I mean, it's turned out to be bigger than we thought. We're setting a record for ticket sales, the likes of which no sport has ever seen before.\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\\nThe President. But they have a little more speed.\\nBut no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\\nPopularity of Soccer in Latin America\\nQ. Mr. President, a message for the Latin America and soccer fans?\\nThe President. Yes, I am. And Latin America is great. And they have great soccer. So, good luck in the matches.\\n[A reporter asked a question in Spanish, which was translated by an interpreter as follows.]\\nU.S. Visas for World Cup Ticketholders\\nQ. Who is going to be in—[inaudible]—about these visas for the—these fans that want to come here to the World Cup?\\nThe President. Well, we're going to make it very easy for them. We're working on that right now. We're going to make it very easy. It's going to be a very easy process.\\nQ. Okay. Say, hi to Colombia over there.\\nThe President. Hello. Is that Colombia?\\nQ. Yes.\\nThe President. I love Colombia. Hello, Colombia. [Laughter]\\nQ. Okay. Okay. Muy bien.\\nThe President. So where are you from?\\nQ. Paraguay.\\nThe President. Oh.\\nQ. He's from Paraguay. Yes.\\nThe President. Very good. I love it. I—it's a beautiful country. We get along very well with them. We do a little trade deal with them, and they like us. And that's what's happening.\\nQ. Panama.\\nThe President. Where?\\nVery good. I like the canal. [Laughter] That canal is pretty good.\\n[A reporter spoke in Spanish; no translation was provided.]\\n2026 World Cup\\nThe President. What?\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. Well, it's going to be incredible. The event is going to be very good. Just this event alone—it's at the Kennedy Center. I see you have it fixed up perfectly.\\nMr. Infantino. It will set the tone.\\nThe President. Right? It's beautiful.\\nMr. Infantino. It's beautiful.\\nThe President. It's a beautiful place.\\nHave a good time.\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President.\\n[A reporter spoke in Spanish; no translation was provided.]\\nMr. Infantino. No, gracias. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. It's great.\\nJohn F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts/Renovation Work\\nQ. Mr. President, the U.S. press?\\nThe President. Thank you, everybody, very much. It's a great honor. This has been an honor for a lot of reasons. Number one, they've sold more tickets than any event has ever sold already—long before the kickoff.\\nAnd number two, we've done a lot of work at the Kennedy Center. It was falling apart, and now it's pretty much back. And we'll get it back within the next 4 or 5 months through construction, and—but you see the way it looks.\\nAnd Gianni is just telling me—who's done an incredible job, by the way. He's just telling, you know, how good a job we've done.\\nMr. Infantino. That's right.\\nThe President. You can look at the walls. The marble was broken. Everything was a mess. And we've really taken the Kennedy Center—a lot of people thought it was going to be ripped down, and we did just the opposite. So we've done a really great renovation job on it. And over the next 3, 4 months, it will be complete. And we're honored to have it here, and it's been—it's been very special.\\nWe've set a record on ticket sales, as you probably heard, already, even way before—long before the event itself. And we're working with Canada, and we're working with Mexico. And it's been a really spectacular—so far, it's been spectacular.\\nDaniel [Daniel Baldwin, One America News Network], do you have a question?\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. What are your expectations? You once said that the FIFA World Cup is an opportunity to put—a once-in-a-lifetime opportunity to put the greatness of the United States on display.\\nThe President. Well, I think—\\nQ. One billion eyeballs will be watching, Mr. President.\\nThe President. Yes, I—think——\\nQ. What will they here today?\\nThe President. Even today, I understand. I hear that, you know——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——I know we're a little late to get in there, but——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——that's okay.\\nMr. Infantino. They wait.\\nThe President. So all my friends, I guess they have to wait. They have no choice, right? [Laughter]\\nMr. Infantino. Yes, they wait.\\nThe President. But no, the numbers are incredible. I hear today's numbers are——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——very big. I hope CNN is covering this.\\nQ. One billion eyeballs.\\nMr. Infantino. Today, 1 billion eyeballs.\\nThe President. Today's numbers are very, very big.\\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize/The President's Foreign Policy\\nQ. We are covering it. And you're expected to get the FIFA Peace Prize, Mr. President. What would you say to people who say that prize might conflict with your pledge to strike Venezuela?\\nThe President. Well, I think the peace prize—I mean, I settled eight wars. I don't know that I'm getting it. I haven't been officially noticed. I've been hearing about a peace prize, and I'm here to represent our country in a different sense. But I can tell you, I did settle eight wars, and we have a ninth coming, but—which nobody has ever done before.\\nBut I want to really save lives. I don't need prizes. I need to save lives. And we're saving a lot of lives. And I've saved millions and millions of lives, and that's really what I want to do.\\nAnd I also want to run a great country. And the United States right now is the hottest country anywhere in the world. And 1 year ago, it was dead. We had a dead country, and now we have the hottest country anywhere in the world.\\nQ. Mr. President, will you——\\nThe President's Meeting With President Claudia Sheinbaum Pardo of Mexico and Prime Minister Mark Carney of Canada\\nQ. What are you going to discuss with Canada and Mexico, Mr.—what are you going to discuss with the leaders of Canada and Mexico?\\nThe President. Well, we're getting—we're going to meet with both. And we're getting along very well. You know, we're getting along very well. I don't know. I think we have a meeting set up for some time after the event.\\nQ. Will you discuss trade?\\nThe President. Yes, we'll discuss trade. We—get along very well.\\nThank you, everybody, very much.\\nQ. Will you pardon any other Honduran officials?\\nQ. Do you want them to keep trying to indict Ms. James?\\n\\nNOTE: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. In his remarks, he referred to Trey Yingst, chief foreign correspondent, Fox News Channel; Cristiano Ronaldo, forward for Saudi Pro League club Al-Nass and Portugal's national soccer team; and Lionel Messi, forward for Major League Soccer club Inter Miami and Argentina's national team. A reporter referred to New York State Attorney General Letitia James. The transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\n\\nSource URL: https://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/documents/remarks-exchange-with-reporters-prior-the-2026-federation-internationale-des-associations\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-3 PRESMENTION/NEWMENTION terms\\n                                         NEWMENTION\\n\\nScope: These rules shall apply to this contract.\\n\\nUnderlying: The Underlying for this Contract is words used by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nRevisions to the Underlying made after Expiration will not be accounted for in determining the\\nExpiration Value.\\n\\nSource Agency: The Source Agencies are \\u003csource\\u003e.\\n\\nType: The type of Contract is an Event Contract.\\n\\nIssuance: After the initial Contract, Contract iterations will be listed on an as-needed basis at\\nthe discretion of the Exchange and corresponding to the risk management needs of Members.\\n\\n\\u003centity\\u003e: \\u003centity\\u003e refers to the speaker, writer, performer, or communicator specified by the\\nExchange. This may include (but is not limited to): a specific named individual, multiple\\nindividuals specified using AND/OR logic, an individual identified by position or title, a group,\\nband, team or collective entity, a specified member or members of a group, an organization,\\ncompany, or institutional entity, or any combination of the aforementioned.\\n\\nWhen \\u003centity\\u003e is defined by a position or title, the Contract tracks whoever holds that position\\nduring \\u003ctime period\\u003e, even if the individual holding the position changes. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a\\nspecific named individual, the identity remains consistent throughout. Name changes (e.g.,\\nstage names, married names) do not create a new entity. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a group or\\norganization and the Contract does not specify particular members, any official\\ncommunication or statement by any member or designated spokesperson counts. When using\\nAND logic, all specified entities must independently say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e. When\\nusing OR logic, at least one of the specified entities must say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nThe Exchange may specify additional conditions such as “at least X members of” a group or\\n“the majority of” a group.\\n\\n\\u003csource\\u003e: \\u003csource\\u003e refers to a Source Agency or ordered collection of Source Agencies\\nspecified by the Exchange at the time of Contract listing, which will be incorporated into the\\nSource Agency hierarchy above and used to determine the occurrence of the Underlying.\\n\\u003csource\\u003e may refer to a singular agency, multiple agencies, an agency by distinguishing\\ncharacteristics, by category or type (e.g., “official government statistical body,” “primary wire\\nservice”), or any combination thereof. When multiple agencies are specified, they may be\\napplied in the hierarchical order designated by the Exchange if so specified, with the highest-\\nranked available and responsive agency taking precedence for purposes of determining the\\nExpiration Value. A lower-ranked agency shall only be consulted if all higher-ranked agencies\\nare unavailable, unresponsive, have not reported on the Underlying by the Expiration time, or\\nif the Exchange, in its sole discretion, determines that a higher-ranked agency’s reporting is\\nincomplete, erroneous, or otherwise insufficient to determine the Expiration Value. If \\u003csource\\u003e\\ndesignates multiple agencies without specifying a hierarchical order, the Exchange shall\\nresolve any conflict between reporting agencies at its sole discretion.\\n\\n\\u003cword\\u003e: \\u003cword\\u003e refers to the particular word or phrase potentially to be mentioned by\\n\\u003centity\\u003e. It may refer to a word being said a minimum number of times. It may also refer to\\none of multiple words/phrases, any of which are acceptable (e.g., “Doge/Dogecoin”).\\n\\f\\u003ctime period\\u003e: \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific range of time, event or discrete date and\\ntime specified by the Exchange. This may be defined by, but is not limited to: a specific event\\nor context (e.g., “during the State of the Union address”), exact dates or times, relative time\\nmarkers (e.g., “before July 1, 2027,” “in Q1 2026”), event-based periods (e.g., “during any\\ncampaign rally in October 2026,” “during the awards ceremony”), and broader intervals (e.g.,\\n“Q1–Q2 2027,” “January–March 2026”).\\n\\nUnless stated otherwise, “Between” is inclusive of both endpoints, while “before” and “after”\\nexclude the specified date. \\u003ctime period\\u003e may also refer to “Any” or “None”, to multiple dates\\n(even if non-consecutive), or to a singular and discrete date or time.\\n\\nWhen \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event (such as an address, speech, performance, or\\nbroadcast), the Exchange may specify what is included, including whether it includes both live\\nand pre-recorded segments (including whether advertisements are included). Where a\\ntimezone is not specified, ET is assumed.\\n\\n\\nPayout Criterion: The Payout Criterion for the Contract encompasses the Expiration Values that\\n\\u003cword\\u003e is said by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n\\n\\nThe word must appear as a distinct, standalone unit, not buried inside another word. Plural\\nand possessive noun forms count. Other grammatical changes (tense, conjugation, derivation)\\ndo not. If \\u003cword\\u003e appears separated from other words by a space or hyphen or in a\\ncompound form with a space or hyphen, it counts. If \\u003cword\\u003e is fused into a single\\nunhyphenated word, it does not count.\\n\\nIf \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled, and the market contains a\\nstrike stating “Event does not qualify/occur”, such a strike shall resolve “Yes” and all others\\n“No”. If \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled but such strikes are NOT\\nlisted, the Contracts will resolve to the last fair price determined at the discretion of the\\nExchange. If the event is postponed, and such a postponement is announced by the end of the\\nfollowing calendar day to be rescheduled to a time within 14 calendar days, the markets shall\\nremain open. If the event captured in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast, the\\nExchange may keep the market open for 24 hours for the release of an official recording.\\nFurther granular details on conditions for these Contracts is available below.\\n\\nAdditional clarification(s):\\n\\n     Possessive noun forms of \\u003cword\\u003e, plurals, and possessive plural noun forms are\\n     INCLUDED:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigrants” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Egg” → “eggs’ shells” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Russia” → “Russia’s” counts, “Russian” does not\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e exists only in adjective form, no plural form exists:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Economic” → “Economics” does not count (“Economic” is an adjective\\n          for which “Economics” is not a plural)\\n     Plural nouns occurring within proper nouns and noun phrases are included:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Cat” → “Cats the musical” counts\\n\\f    Grammatical variations beyond plurals/possessives are NOT included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigration” does NOT count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Run” → “Running” or “Ran” do NOT count\\n    When \\u003cword\\u003e specifies a plural form, the singular does NOT count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Veterans” → “Veteran” does NOT count\\n    Words that are spelled the same as the plural form of \\u003cword\\u003e (if such exists) but are\\n    themselves not a plural noun are included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Wind” → “Winds up the clock” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Border” → “The United States has strong borders” counts\\n    Open compounds (words separated by spaces) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fire station” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “couch” → “couch potato” counts\\n    Hyphenated compounds (words connected by hyphens) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Palestine” → “pro-Palestine” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fat” → “non-fat” counts\\n    Closed compounds (single word, no spaces/hyphens) do not count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire” does not count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firefighter” does not count\\n    Multi-word \\u003cword\\u003e in larger constructions: When \\u003cword\\u003e is a multi-word phrase\\n    appearing within a hyphenated construction, it counts only if \\u003cword\\u003e appears as a\\n    complete, unmodified element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “New York” → “New York-based” counts (complete element)\\n    Portmanteaus (words blended from two words where parts of each are combined) are\\n    NOT included unless the portmanteau clearly contains \\u003cword\\u003e as a distinct, unaltered\\n    element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “MAGA” → “MAGA-nificent” counts (MAGA appears as distinct element)\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “magnificent” → “MAGA-nificent” does NOT count (portmanteau blend)\\n\\nDictionary determination: Both the Merriam-Webster Dictionary (available online) AND the\\nOxford English Dictionary shall be used to determine compound type and/or conventional\\nspelling patterns. Inclusion in either dictionary as an open or hyphenated compound shall\\nsatisfy the Payout Criterion. If neither provides clarity (or the word is not included),\\ndetermination is based on whether written as single unit (closed/doesn’t count) vs. spaces or\\nhyphens (open or hyphenated/counts) and/or context and previous usage.\\n\\nPHONETIC EQUIVALENCIES\\n\\n    Homophones (same sound, different spelling) do not count:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “write” → “right” does not count\\n    Homonyms and homographs (same spelling) COUNT regardless of meaning or\\n    pronunciation:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “bass” → both “bass guitar” and “bass fishing” count\\n    Proper and common nouns are treated identically:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Apple” → both “Apple Inc.” and “apple” (fruit) count\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Will” → both “Will Smith” and “I will go” count\\n    Minor unintentional mispronunciations COUNT if context makes intent clear:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Mamdani” → “Mandani” counts\\n    Severe mispronunciations that make \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable do NOT count.\\n    Trademarked spellings do not count, even when pronounced identically, unless the word\\n\\fitself is the same:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “lift” → “Lyft” (pronounced “lift”) does not count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “uber” → “Uber” counts\\nWords with non-standard transliteration to English count within reason, provided they are\\nphonetically equivalent:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Zelensky” → any of “Zelenski,” “Zelenskii,” “Zelensky,” or “Zelenskiy”\\n      count if pronounced equivalently\\nContractions do not count for their constituent words unless otherwise explicitly specified\\nby the Exchange:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “not” → “won’t,” “can’t,” “don’t,” “isn’t” do not count\\nNumbers spoken as words COUNT, when spoken exactly (not part of a larger number):\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “five” → saying “five” or reading “$5” aloud as “five dollars” counts,\\n      saying “five hundred” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “410” → “four hundred ten”, “four one zero” or “four ten” counts\\nOrdinals COUNT when \\u003cword\\u003e is written numerically OR a phrase that includes a\\nnumber:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “January 6” → “January 6th” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “3” (written numerically) → “3rd” (spoken as “third”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Eight War” → “8 Wars” and “Eighth War” will count\\nCardinal and ordinal number words are distinct:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “one” → “first” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “first” → “one” does NOT count\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count when pronunciation or letter-by-letter spelling\\nmatches \\u003cword\\u003e:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “NASA” (pronounced “NAH-suh”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “N-A-S-A” (spelled out) counts\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count as \\u003cword\\u003e when pronounced as the full word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Doctor” → “Dr.” (pronounced “Doctor”) counts\\nExpanded forms of acronyms do NOT count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “AI” → “artificial intelligence” does not count\\nWords in foreign languages do NOT count unless they are perfect cognates with an\\nEnglish word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fuego” (Spanish) does NOT count\\nEnglish words within foreign sentences count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “policy” → “Nuestra policy es clara” counts\\n\\u003cword\\u003e in organization/company names counts:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Securities” → “Bank of America Securities” counts\\nWords in URLs, emails, handles, and hashtags (exclusive of domain structure, email\\nprovider or symbols) are treated as compounds when spoken as complete words, with the\\ntype of compound subject to aforementioned rules:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firestation.com” pronounced “fire station dot com” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire.com” pronounced “wildfire dot com” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “apple” → “apple.com” pronounced “apple dot com” does count\\n      When presented in URL, email, handle, or hashtag form, \\u003cword\\u003e shall be treated as\\n      a compound, not a multi-word word\\nSung, rapped, or poetic words COUNT if phonetically recognizable:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “money” → “moneyyy” (extended in rap) counts\\n      Extreme distortion making \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable does NOT count.\\nPhonetic alphabet spelling (“Foxtrot India Romeo Echo” for “FIRE”) does NOT count.\\n\\fCANCELLATIONS AND DELAYS\\n\\n   The Exchange may list an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike for any Contract. If listed,\\n   such a strike refers to the structural conditions of the market, and is NOT adjudicated as a\\n   \\u003cword\\u003e needing to be said by or validated by having been said by \\u003centity\\u003e. If listed, this\\n   strike resolves to “Yes” whenever the event fails to occur or qualify under the Payout\\n   Criterion, or any other circumstance prevents normal resolution.\\n   If no such strike is listed, and \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, the following rules\\n   apply if the event is cancelled, postponed, rescheduled, or materially altered (including\\n   being closed to press) such that no video is released within one calendar day of the\\n   original start time of the event:\\n         If the event is cancelled, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price determined in\\n         the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         If the event is postponed or rescheduled, the outcome depends on whether a new\\n         date is publicly announced within one calendar day (i.e. if the event was scheduled\\n         to begin on Monday, any time up to 11:59PM on Tuesday falls within this period) of\\n         the originally scheduled start time:\\n               If no new date is announced within one calendar day, the Contract will resolve\\n               to the last fair price determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n               If a new date is announced within one calendar day, the outcome depends on\\n               when the rescheduled event is set to occur:\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls within fourteen (14) calendar days of the\\n                     originally scheduled date, the Contract shall remain open and \\u003cword\\u003e\\n                     stated during the rescheduled event will count.\\n                           The fourteen-day window begins at 12:00 AM ET on the originally\\n                           scheduled date and ends at 11:59 PM ET fourteen days later, unless\\n                           an alternate timezone is explicitly specified.\\n                           Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the State of the Union on January\\n                           15, 2026” rescheduled to January 20, 2026 → words spoken during\\n                           the rescheduled address count.\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls more than fourteen (14) calendar days after\\n                     the originally scheduled date, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price\\n                     determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         Any Contract that cannot be resolved through the Source Agency hierarchy will\\n         instead be settled at the Last Fair Price. The Exchange will disclose the methodology\\n         used to determine the Last Fair Price (e.g., Last Traded Price, Time-Weighted\\n         Average Price) at the time of Issuance.\\n         If an event begins but is interrupted, abbreviated, or ends prematurely, words\\n         stated by \\u003centity\\u003e during the portion of the event that did occur will count and the\\n         market will otherwise resolve.\\n   If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window but the venue, format, or medium\\n   changes (e.g., moved to a different location, changed from in-person to virtual (with the\\n   exception of being closed to press)), words stated during the event will count.\\n   Special condition: Across both cases, whether an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike is\\n   listed or not, if the event specified as or in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast (or\\n   relayed as such) but the live stream/broadcast does not occur, the Exchange will instead\\n   use an officially released recording as the Underlying, and may delay resolution by up to\\n   one calendar day to allow for the release of such a recording.\\n\\f          If partial snippets are released, Contracts on words that do not appear will be\\n          resolved to last fair price, and Contracts on those that do will be resolved to “Yes”.\\n          If no recording is released, the relevant outcomes triggered by the\\n          presence/absence of an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike shall occur as outlined\\n          above.\\n\\nTECHNICAL DETAILS (UNLESS OTHERWISE SPECIFIED)\\n\\n     When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, pre-recorded content broadcast,\\n     streamed, or published as part of that event is included if presented as part of the official\\n     presentation.\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the concert” with pre-recorded video interlude\\n          where entity speaks → words from interlude count\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the television appearance” with pre-taped\\n          segment aired during broadcast → words from segment count\\n     Behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are NOT\\n     included unless officially broadcast or published as part of \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n     Subtitles and captions that display \\u003cword\\u003e on screen but are not spoken aloud by\\n     \\u003centity\\u003e do NOT count.\\n     Sign language interpretation or usage by entity does NOT count as saying \\u003cword\\u003e unless\\n     the Contract explicitly specifies that sign language counts.\\n     Text that entity displays on screen (presentation slides, teleprompter visible to audience,\\n     signatures) does NOT count unless entity reads it aloud.\\n     Content generated by AI, deepfakes, or synthetic voice technology impersonating entity\\n     does NOT count unless the synthetic content is officially commissioned, authorized, or\\n     published by entity, OR the Contract explicitly specifies that AI-generated content counts.\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e is muted due to technical failure or censorship it shall not count unless\\n     corroborating contextual evidence (including surrounding speech, or an official\\n     uncensored recording or transcript) confirms that \\u003centity\\u003e specifically uttered \\u003cword\\u003e\\n     during the muted period.\\n\\nMinimum Tick: The Minimum Tick size for the Contract shall be $0.01.\\n\\nPosition Accountability Level: The Position Accountability Level for the Contract shall be\\n$25,000 per strike, per Member.\\n\\nLast Trading Date: The Last Trading Date of the Contract will be the Expiration Date. The Last\\nTrading Time will be the Expiration time.\\n\\nSettlement Date: The Settlement Date of the Contract shall be no later than the day after the\\nExpiration Date, unless the Market Outcome is under review pursuant to Rule 7.1.\\n\\nExpiration Date: When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event: The latest Expiration Date of\\nthe Contract shall be fourteen (14) calendar days after the originally scheduled date of the\\nevent. If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window, expiration will be moved to an\\nearlier date and time in accordance with Rule 7.2. When \\u003ctime period\\u003e is defined by specific\\ndates: The latest Expiration Date of the Contract shall be two weeks after the end of \\u003ctime\\nperiod\\u003e. If an event described in the Payout Criterion occurs and a consensus has been\\nreached on all terms, then expiration will be moved to an earlier date and time in accordance\\nwith Rule 7.2.\\n\\fExpiration time: The Expiration time of the Contract shall be 10:00 AM ET.\\n\\nSettlement Value: The Settlement Value for this Contract is $1.00.\\n\\nExpiration Value: The Expiration Value is the value of the Underlying as documented by the\\nSource Agency on the Expiration Date at the Expiration time.\\n\\nContingencies: Before Settlement, Kalshi may, at its sole discretion, initiate the Market\\nOutcome Review Process pursuant to Rule 7.1 of the Rulebook. If an Expiration Value cannot\\nbe determined on the Expiration Date, Kalshi has the right to determine payouts pursuant to\\nRule 7.1 in the Rulebook.\\n\\f\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-4 Formal draw archive note\\nSource checked: Roll Call / Factba.se archive\\n\\nArchive title: Remarks: Donald Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing in Washington - December 5, 2025\\n\\nArchive URL: https://rollcall.com/factbase/trump/transcript/donald-trump-remarks-fifa-world-cup-drawing-december-5-2025/\\n\\nWhat this file establishes:\\n\\nThere is a separate archived transcript page for Trump's formal attendance remarks at the draw.\\n\\nWhat this file does not establish:\\n\\nThis session could not retrieve the full transcript text from that archive.  The page is password-protected.  This example therefore does not claim, from local files alone, whether the formal program transcript does or does not contain the word \\\"Ronaldo.\\\"\\n\\nWhy this matters:\\n\\nThe complaint does not need to prove that the formal program omitted the strike.  It needs to show that Trump said \\\"Ronaldo\\\" in event-linked remarks and that the market boundary reasonably includes those remarks.  The formal archive remains relevant because it marks the distinction between the pre-event reporter exchange and the formal program.\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-5 GovInfo official transcript excerpt and metadata\\nSource: GovInfo, DCPD202501162, Office of the Federal Register / National Archives and Records Administration.\\nURL: https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/DCPD-202501162/html/DCPD-202501162.htm\\nTitle: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\nEvent date: December 5, 2025.\\n\\nRelevant extracted page text:\\n\\\"Administration of Donald J. Trump, 2025\\\"\\n\\\"Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw December 5, 2025\\\"\\n\\\"[The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\\\"\\n\\nUnder the section \\\"The President's Interest in Soccer\\\":\\n\\\"Q. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\\\"\\n\\\"The President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\\\\\\\"football,\\\\\\\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\\\"\\n\\\"Thank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\\\"\\n\\nAdditional relevant extracted page text:\\n\\\"The President's Interest in Soccer\\\"\\n\\\"Q. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\\\"\\n\\\"The President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\\\"\\n\\\"Mr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\\\"\\n\\\"The President. But they have a little more speed. But no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\\\"\\n\\nGovInfo note:\\n\\\"NOTE: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. In his remarks, he referred to Trey Yingst, chief foreign correspondent, Fox News Channel; Cristiano Ronaldo, forward for Saudi Pro League club Al-Nass and Portugal's national soccer team; and Lionel Messi, forward for Major League Soccer club Inter Miami and Argentina's national team. A reporter referred to New York State Attorney General Letitia James. The transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\\"\\n\\nGovInfo content details page also identifies category \\\"Interviews With the News Media : Exchanges with reporters, Washington, DC,\\\" subjects including \\\"Federation Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) World Cup,\\\" \\\"John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts,\\\" and \\\"Soccer,\\\" and names including \\\"Ronaldo, Cristiano\\\" and \\\"Messi, Lionel.\\\"\\n\\n[defendant] DX-1 Market wording and challenged resolution\\nMarket URL: https://kalshi.com/markets/kxtrumpmentionb/trump-mention-b/kxtrumpmentionb-25dec06\\n\\nPublic market title: What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\n\\nContract family: PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION\\n\\nStrike at issue: Ronaldo\\n\\nChallenged resolution: No\\n\\nRequested resolution: Yes\\n\\n\\n[defendant] DX-2 Pre-event reporter exchange transcript\\nRemarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\nDecember 05, 2025\\n\\n[The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\\nThe President. It's a great honor to be here. Gianni has done a fantastic job. We're setting records—[inaudible].\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. Well, I think so. They have a little bit of a shot. Pretty stiff competition. But I would say they would have a small chance.\\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize\\nQ. [Inaudible]—win the FIFA Peace Award?\\nThe President. Well, it would be an honor.\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\nQ. Will you root for some selection? Will you root for someone?\\nThe President. Well, I root for a lot of countries, but in this case, I'll be rooting for the U.S.A. [Laughter]\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. That's great. That's great. We really love it.\\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize\\nQ. Mr. President, have you been told that you are going to receive the inaugural peace prize today——\\nThe President. I have not——\\nQ. ——from FIFA?\\nThe President. I have not been told. There's a rumor about it, but I have not been told. That would be a great honor, and I'm a big fan of Gianni, as you know.\\nQ. What can fans expect——\\nQ. Are you hoping to receive that?\\nThe President. Excuse me.\\nQ. Are you hoping to receive the peace prize?\\nThe President. Well, I don't like to say \\\"hope,\\\" but it would be a great honor.\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. What can fans expect of, like, the World Cup in the U.S.?\\nThe President. I think it's going to be fantastic. We've set every record you can set.\\nQ. What are you telling people who are worried——\\nFédération Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) President Giovanni V. Infantino\\nQ. [Inaudible]—friend Gianni—[inaudible]—a word about him?\\nThe President. I think he has done a fantastic job.\\nThe President's Schedule\\nQ. Are you going to be meeting with the President of Mexico today and the——\\nThe President. We might. Yes.\\nQ. ——Prime Minister of Canada as well?\\nThe President. I might. I might do that.\\nQ. Will you be discussing immigration and trade with them?\\nThe President. Yes, we'll be discussing.\\n[At this point, the President and Mr. Infantino posed for photographs.]\\nThe President. Thank you, everybody.\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event/John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts\\nQ. Mr. President, what do you think about the crowd?\\nThe President. Oh, look, the new star—[inaudible].\\nCongratulations.\\nQ. Thank you.\\nThe President. You're the new star of television and Fox.\\nQ. Thank you. How are you doing, Mr. President?\\nThe President. I'm doing very well.\\nQ. What do you think about the crowd here?\\nThe President. I think the crowd is great, and I think the building is great. We've made a lot of improvements over the last 6 months. Taking—the Kennedy Center was in very bad shape. Now it's getting to be really good. And in 6 months, it's going to be incredible with the improvements we've made.\\nQ. The first time for the U.S. to host since the nineties.\\nThe President. Right.\\nQ. Are you ready for it?\\nThe President. I'm ready for it, and they're ready for it. And Gianni, who you know——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——has done a fantastic job with FIFA. And we're looking to have—you know, we're set—we have already set records for tickets sales. I don't think there's ever been anything like it in any sport. And so, I want to congratulate you.\\nMr. Infantino. Thank you.\\nThe President. I don't even have to wait. But major records have been set.\\nHow are you?\\nQ. Good, how are you, sir?\\nThe President. Nice to see you.\\nQ. Today it's not football—American football. It's soccer. It's——\\nThe President. Right.\\nQ. ——the big event of soccer.\\nThe President. That's right. That's right.\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\nQ. So can you tell me about this big day today?\\nThe President. It's just a big day, and it's a great sport. And it really is coming to America. And never—nobody ever thought a thing like this could happen. And I'm very happy to say that we've already set the alltime record on ticket sales long before the first ball is kicked. Right?\\nMr. Infantino. A hundred percent. One hundred percent.\\n2026 World Cup Host Cities\\nQ. You've had some concerns about crime in American cities, some of the cities that will be hosting. Have they remedied that for you? Are you still considering maybe asking FIFA to move some of those cities?\\nThe President. No, I don't want to do that. But I will tell you, if they do have a problem, by the time we get there, we'll take care of that problem. We can solve that problem.\\nI've proven that in DC and everywhere else we went, so we'll take care of that very easily. So, if they have a problem, hopefully, they'll let us know that, and we will solve any problem.\\nOkay? Thank you.\\nQ. Thank you so much.\\nMr. Infantino. All right, thank you so much.\\nQ. Thank you, Mr. President.\\nQ. Thank you. Appreciate it.\\nThe President. Congratulations.\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. Mr. President, Brazilian television. America will be hosting the World Cup and the Olympics in 2 years. How important it is—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. I think very. It's a great honor. I think Gianni is doing a phenomenal job. We've set every record on ticket sales. It's been really fantastic. But Gianni has done an unbelievable job with FIFA.\\nThe President's Experience With Soccer\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. He was a great—not only that. I got to see a man name Pelé play—right?—that tells you how old I am—when he was on the Cosmos. Do you remember that a long time ago? And it was quite a treat. That was quite an event. And he was—not only was he playing, he was great. He scored two goals, I think. And so, I was one of the few who got to see Pelé, and I assume he is one of your alltime greats. Right?\\nMr. Infantino. Definitely.\\nThe President. So I got to see him.\\nThe President's Favorite World Cup Competitor\\nQ. Do you have some favorite teams for World Cup?\\nThe President. Well, I have a favorite. It's the U.S.A. [Laughter] I don't know what their chances are, Gianni, but maybe the U.S.A. is the——\\nMr. Infantino. They're getting better and better, actually.\\nThe President. I think they'll do well.\\nMr. Infantino. They are getting better and better.\\nThe President. I think they'll do well.\\nThank you very much, everybody.\\nQ. Thank you so much.\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. Mr. President, World Cup in America just means—[inaudible]. So what do you expect from this World Cup?\\nThe President. [Inaudible]—record business and only in the United States, but we're also doing record ticket sales with FIFA. And they've already bought—beat their highest record. And we—you know, this a long time before the first ball is kicked. You've sold more tickets than they've ever done before, and better pricing than they've ever gotten before. It's a tremendous success. And it's an honor. And Gianni has done a phenomenal job with FIFA.\\nQ. [Inaudible]—ever?\\nThe President. I think so. I think it's going to be—I mean, ideally, you want to see that every year. Every 4 years, it gets bigger and better. I think we have set every record in the book. We're very happy about it.\\nThank you.\\nThe President's Favorite World Cup Competitor\\nQ. [Inaudible]—part of America. Who are you going to support as well?\\nThe President. Well, I think I have to support U.S.A. Otherwise, I'd be in trouble. I wouldn't be President for long.\\nMr. Infantino. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. [Inaudible]—but you have a lot of great teams. You're going to have a lot of great teams.\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\\\"football,\\\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\\n2026 World Cup Draw/Ticket Sales for World Cup\\nQ. How does it feel to be part of this amazing event? And obviously, your being a part of participating in all the—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. The President of Mexico is here, and she's doing a very good job. She's a good woman, very, very excellent job. It's an honor, and we're setting every record, and you're helping us set those records.\\nMr. Infantino. And we will do it.\\nThe President. You know, Mexico and Canada are helping us set those records. But as you know, we have a record in ticket sales already, long before the first ball is kicked, and we're going to do great.\\nI think that Gianni—as you know, he's the head, and he has done a fantastic job.\\nU.S. Cooperation With Mexico and Canada\\nQ. And how is the biggest challenge being three countries?\\nThe President. Well, I think that—do you mean for the three countries?\\nWell, they've gotten together really well, I mean.\\nMr. Infantino. All right.\\nThe President. They're getting along very well.\\nMr. Infantino. Collaboration is fantastic between the three.\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer/2026 World Cup\\nQ. And you like soccer?\\nThe President. I do. I like it. I like it more and more.\\nQ. Yes?\\nThe President. I like it. It's growing in this country—very, really—I mean, someday, maybe it's going to be bigger than anything else.\\nMr. Infantino. We'll have to become number one.\\nThe President. I will say this——\\nMr. Infantino. Definitely.\\nThe President. ——the ticket sales——\\nQ. Definitely will happen.\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. Ticket sales are bigger than anything we have ever done in the history of the country, in terms of sports.\\nMr. Infantino. For certain.\\nQ. And the audience is going to be huge.\\nThe President. The audience is going to be tremendous.\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. Yes.\\nMr. Infantino. Six billion people.\\nThe President. [Inaudible]\\nQ. Six billion? That's amazing.\\nMr. Infantino. Six billion people.\\nAnd today, one billion.\\nQ. Wow.\\nMr. Infantino. [Inaudible]\\nQ. Enjoy show time. Thank you so much.\\nThe President. [Inaudible]\\nQ. Mr. President, how are you? Just a quick—[inaudible].\\nQ. This is for Telemundo.\\nThe President. How are you?\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\nQ. Hello, Mr. President. How are you? This for Telemundo.\\nThe President. How are you? Good.\\nQ. How are you?\\nThe President. Very good. Thank you.\\nQ. How does it feel to have the most important event of sports—that global—in the U.S.?\\nThe President. Well, we do. And right at the Kennedy Center. I'm Chairman of the Kennedy Center. And I hear the Kennedy Center is doing a very good job, so it feels great. Really good.\\nAnd Telemundo is doing a good job, too. Thank you.\\nQ. Thank you.\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. What is the significance of hosting the FIFA World Cup this year?\\nThe President. It's a—in terms of sports, I would say the ultimate. There is no sport like this. It's the biggest sport in the world. And we are setting every record. You know, our ticket sales have gone and set every—every sport—no matter what it is, we've set the record. So—and every though it's very early, there's no ball being kicked yet, but we've already set a ticket sales record.\\nArgentina National Team\\nQ. How do you see Argentinean team for this World Cup?\\nThe President. Well, I love Argentina. And your President is doing a very good job, as you know. Milei. You know that right? It's make Argentina great again. MAGA.\\nQ. And——\\nU.S. National Team\\nQ. Do you think the States are building a powerful team for next year?\\nThe President. Who?\\nQ. The States.\\nThe President. Oh, yes. Sure. I—you're going to have a lot of powerful teams. Everybody has a lot of powerful teams, but you're going to have a lot of great teams. [Inaudible]\\nU.S. Role in Hosting the 2026 World Cup\\nQ. Mr. President, what does it mean for you guys to host the World Cup right here in the U.S.?\\nThe President. I'm honored to host it. It's a great honor. I mean, it's turned out to be bigger than we thought. We're setting a record for ticket sales, the likes of which no sport has ever seen before.\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\\nThe President. But they have a little more speed.\\nBut no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\\nPopularity of Soccer in Latin America\\nQ. Mr. President, a message for the Latin America and soccer fans?\\nThe President. Yes, I am. And Latin America is great. And they have great soccer. So, good luck in the matches.\\n[A reporter asked a question in Spanish, which was translated by an interpreter as follows.]\\nU.S. Visas for World Cup Ticketholders\\nQ. Who is going to be in—[inaudible]—about these visas for the—these fans that want to come here to the World Cup?\\nThe President. Well, we're going to make it very easy for them. We're working on that right now. We're going to make it very easy. It's going to be a very easy process.\\nQ. Okay. Say, hi to Colombia over there.\\nThe President. Hello. Is that Colombia?\\nQ. Yes.\\nThe President. I love Colombia. Hello, Colombia. [Laughter]\\nQ. Okay. Okay. Muy bien.\\nThe President. So where are you from?\\nQ. Paraguay.\\nThe President. Oh.\\nQ. He's from Paraguay. Yes.\\nThe President. Very good. I love it. I—it's a beautiful country. We get along very well with them. We do a little trade deal with them, and they like us. And that's what's happening.\\nQ. Panama.\\nThe President. Where?\\nVery good. I like the canal. [Laughter] That canal is pretty good.\\n[A reporter spoke in Spanish; no translation was provided.]\\n2026 World Cup\\nThe President. What?\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. Well, it's going to be incredible. The event is going to be very good. Just this event alone—it's at the Kennedy Center. I see you have it fixed up perfectly.\\nMr. Infantino. It will set the tone.\\nThe President. Right? It's beautiful.\\nMr. Infantino. It's beautiful.\\nThe President. It's a beautiful place.\\nHave a good time.\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President.\\n[A reporter spoke in Spanish; no translation was provided.]\\nMr. Infantino. No, gracias. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. It's great.\\nJohn F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts/Renovation Work\\nQ. Mr. President, the U.S. press?\\nThe President. Thank you, everybody, very much. It's a great honor. This has been an honor for a lot of reasons. Number one, they've sold more tickets than any event has ever sold already—long before the kickoff.\\nAnd number two, we've done a lot of work at the Kennedy Center. It was falling apart, and now it's pretty much back. And we'll get it back within the next 4 or 5 months through construction, and—but you see the way it looks.\\nAnd Gianni is just telling me—who's done an incredible job, by the way. He's just telling, you know, how good a job we've done.\\nMr. Infantino. That's right.\\nThe President. You can look at the walls. The marble was broken. Everything was a mess. And we've really taken the Kennedy Center—a lot of people thought it was going to be ripped down, and we did just the opposite. So we've done a really great renovation job on it. And over the next 3, 4 months, it will be complete. And we're honored to have it here, and it's been—it's been very special.\\nWe've set a record on ticket sales, as you probably heard, already, even way before—long before the event itself. And we're working with Canada, and we're working with Mexico. And it's been a really spectacular—so far, it's been spectacular.\\nDaniel [Daniel Baldwin, One America News Network], do you have a question?\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. What are your expectations? You once said that the FIFA World Cup is an opportunity to put—a once-in-a-lifetime opportunity to put the greatness of the United States on display.\\nThe President. Well, I think—\\nQ. One billion eyeballs will be watching, Mr. President.\\nThe President. Yes, I—think——\\nQ. What will they here today?\\nThe President. Even today, I understand. I hear that, you know——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——I know we're a little late to get in there, but——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——that's okay.\\nMr. Infantino. They wait.\\nThe President. So all my friends, I guess they have to wait. They have no choice, right? [Laughter]\\nMr. Infantino. Yes, they wait.\\nThe President. But no, the numbers are incredible. I hear today's numbers are——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——very big. I hope CNN is covering this.\\nQ. One billion eyeballs.\\nMr. Infantino. Today, 1 billion eyeballs.\\nThe President. Today's numbers are very, very big.\\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize/The President's Foreign Policy\\nQ. We are covering it. And you're expected to get the FIFA Peace Prize, Mr. President. What would you say to people who say that prize might conflict with your pledge to strike Venezuela?\\nThe President. Well, I think the peace prize—I mean, I settled eight wars. I don't know that I'm getting it. I haven't been officially noticed. I've been hearing about a peace prize, and I'm here to represent our country in a different sense. But I can tell you, I did settle eight wars, and we have a ninth coming, but—which nobody has ever done before.\\nBut I want to really save lives. I don't need prizes. I need to save lives. And we're saving a lot of lives. And I've saved millions and millions of lives, and that's really what I want to do.\\nAnd I also want to run a great country. And the United States right now is the hottest country anywhere in the world. And 1 year ago, it was dead. We had a dead country, and now we have the hottest country anywhere in the world.\\nQ. Mr. President, will you——\\nThe President's Meeting With President Claudia Sheinbaum Pardo of Mexico and Prime Minister Mark Carney of Canada\\nQ. What are you going to discuss with Canada and Mexico, Mr.—what are you going to discuss with the leaders of Canada and Mexico?\\nThe President. Well, we're getting—we're going to meet with both. And we're getting along very well. You know, we're getting along very well. I don't know. I think we have a meeting set up for some time after the event.\\nQ. Will you discuss trade?\\nThe President. Yes, we'll discuss trade. We—get along very well.\\nThank you, everybody, very much.\\nQ. Will you pardon any other Honduran officials?\\nQ. Do you want them to keep trying to indict Ms. James?\\n\\nNOTE: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. In his remarks, he referred to Trey Yingst, chief foreign correspondent, Fox News Channel; Cristiano Ronaldo, forward for Saudi Pro League club Al-Nass and Portugal's national soccer team; and Lionel Messi, forward for Major League Soccer club Inter Miami and Argentina's national team. A reporter referred to New York State Attorney General Letitia James. The transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\n\\nSource URL: https://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/documents/remarks-exchange-with-reporters-prior-the-2026-federation-internationale-des-associations\\n\\n\\n[defendant] DX-3 GovInfo/OFR pre-event transcript excerpt\\nSource: GovInfo, DCPD202501162, Office of the Federal Register / National Archives and Records Administration.\\nURL: https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/DCPD-202501162/html/DCPD-202501162.htm\\nTitle: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\nEvent date: December 5, 2025.\\n\\nRelevant extracted page text:\\n\\\"Administration of Donald J. Trump, 2025\\\"\\n\\\"Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw December 5, 2025\\\"\\n\\\"[The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\\\"\\n\\nUnder the section \\\"The President's Interest in Soccer\\\":\\n\\\"Q. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\\\"\\n\\\"The President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\\\\\\\"football,\\\\\\\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\\\"\\n\\\"Thank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\\\"\\n\\nAdditional relevant extracted page text:\\n\\\"The President's Interest in Soccer\\\"\\n\\\"Q. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\\\"\\n\\\"The President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\\\"\\n\\\"Mr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\\\"\\n\\\"The President. But they have a little more speed. But no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\\\"\\n\\nGovInfo note:\\n\\\"NOTE: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. In his remarks, he referred to Trey Yingst, chief foreign correspondent, Fox News Channel; Cristiano Ronaldo, forward for Saudi Pro League club Al-Nass and Portugal's national soccer team; and Lionel Messi, forward for Major League Soccer club Inter Miami and Argentina's national team. A reporter referred to New York State Attorney General Letitia James. The transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\\"\\n\\nGovInfo content details page also identifies category \\\"Interviews With the News Media : Exchanges with reporters, Washington, DC,\\\" subjects including \\\"Federation Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) World Cup,\\\" \\\"John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts,\\\" and \\\"Soccer,\\\" and names including \\\"Ronaldo, Cristiano\\\" and \\\"Messi, Lionel.\\\"\\n\\n[defendant] DX-4 PRESMENTION/NEWMENTION terms\\n                                         NEWMENTION\\n\\nScope: These rules shall apply to this contract.\\n\\nUnderlying: The Underlying for this Contract is words used by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nRevisions to the Underlying made after Expiration will not be accounted for in determining the\\nExpiration Value.\\n\\nSource Agency: The Source Agencies are \\u003csource\\u003e.\\n\\nType: The type of Contract is an Event Contract.\\n\\nIssuance: After the initial Contract, Contract iterations will be listed on an as-needed basis at\\nthe discretion of the Exchange and corresponding to the risk management needs of Members.\\n\\n\\u003centity\\u003e: \\u003centity\\u003e refers to the speaker, writer, performer, or communicator specified by the\\nExchange. This may include (but is not limited to): a specific named individual, multiple\\nindividuals specified using AND/OR logic, an individual identified by position or title, a group,\\nband, team or collective entity, a specified member or members of a group, an organization,\\ncompany, or institutional entity, or any combination of the aforementioned.\\n\\nWhen \\u003centity\\u003e is defined by a position or title, the Contract tracks whoever holds that position\\nduring \\u003ctime period\\u003e, even if the individual holding the position changes. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a\\nspecific named individual, the identity remains consistent throughout. Name changes (e.g.,\\nstage names, married names) do not create a new entity. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a group or\\norganization and the Contract does not specify particular members, any official\\ncommunication or statement by any member or designated spokesperson counts. When using\\nAND logic, all specified entities must independently say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e. When\\nusing OR logic, at least one of the specified entities must say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nThe Exchange may specify additional conditions such as “at least X members of” a group or\\n“the majority of” a group.\\n\\n\\u003csource\\u003e: \\u003csource\\u003e refers to a Source Agency or ordered collection of Source Agencies\\nspecified by the Exchange at the time of Contract listing, which will be incorporated into the\\nSource Agency hierarchy above and used to determine the occurrence of the Underlying.\\n\\u003csource\\u003e may refer to a singular agency, multiple agencies, an agency by distinguishing\\ncharacteristics, by category or type (e.g., “official government statistical body,” “primary wire\\nservice”), or any combination thereof. When multiple agencies are specified, they may be\\napplied in the hierarchical order designated by the Exchange if so specified, with the highest-\\nranked available and responsive agency taking precedence for purposes of determining the\\nExpiration Value. A lower-ranked agency shall only be consulted if all higher-ranked agencies\\nare unavailable, unresponsive, have not reported on the Underlying by the Expiration time, or\\nif the Exchange, in its sole discretion, determines that a higher-ranked agency’s reporting is\\nincomplete, erroneous, or otherwise insufficient to determine the Expiration Value. If \\u003csource\\u003e\\ndesignates multiple agencies without specifying a hierarchical order, the Exchange shall\\nresolve any conflict between reporting agencies at its sole discretion.\\n\\n\\u003cword\\u003e: \\u003cword\\u003e refers to the particular word or phrase potentially to be mentioned by\\n\\u003centity\\u003e. It may refer to a word being said a minimum number of times. It may also refer to\\none of multiple words/phrases, any of which are acceptable (e.g., “Doge/Dogecoin”).\\n\\f\\u003ctime period\\u003e: \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific range of time, event or discrete date and\\ntime specified by the Exchange. This may be defined by, but is not limited to: a specific event\\nor context (e.g., “during the State of the Union address”), exact dates or times, relative time\\nmarkers (e.g., “before July 1, 2027,” “in Q1 2026”), event-based periods (e.g., “during any\\ncampaign rally in October 2026,” “during the awards ceremony”), and broader intervals (e.g.,\\n“Q1–Q2 2027,” “January–March 2026”).\\n\\nUnless stated otherwise, “Between” is inclusive of both endpoints, while “before” and “after”\\nexclude the specified date. \\u003ctime period\\u003e may also refer to “Any” or “None”, to multiple dates\\n(even if non-consecutive), or to a singular and discrete date or time.\\n\\nWhen \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event (such as an address, speech, performance, or\\nbroadcast), the Exchange may specify what is included, including whether it includes both live\\nand pre-recorded segments (including whether advertisements are included). Where a\\ntimezone is not specified, ET is assumed.\\n\\n\\nPayout Criterion: The Payout Criterion for the Contract encompasses the Expiration Values that\\n\\u003cword\\u003e is said by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n\\n\\nThe word must appear as a distinct, standalone unit, not buried inside another word. Plural\\nand possessive noun forms count. Other grammatical changes (tense, conjugation, derivation)\\ndo not. If \\u003cword\\u003e appears separated from other words by a space or hyphen or in a\\ncompound form with a space or hyphen, it counts. If \\u003cword\\u003e is fused into a single\\nunhyphenated word, it does not count.\\n\\nIf \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled, and the market contains a\\nstrike stating “Event does not qualify/occur”, such a strike shall resolve “Yes” and all others\\n“No”. If \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled but such strikes are NOT\\nlisted, the Contracts will resolve to the last fair price determined at the discretion of the\\nExchange. If the event is postponed, and such a postponement is announced by the end of the\\nfollowing calendar day to be rescheduled to a time within 14 calendar days, the markets shall\\nremain open. If the event captured in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast, the\\nExchange may keep the market open for 24 hours for the release of an official recording.\\nFurther granular details on conditions for these Contracts is available below.\\n\\nAdditional clarification(s):\\n\\n     Possessive noun forms of \\u003cword\\u003e, plurals, and possessive plural noun forms are\\n     INCLUDED:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigrants” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Egg” → “eggs’ shells” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Russia” → “Russia’s” counts, “Russian” does not\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e exists only in adjective form, no plural form exists:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Economic” → “Economics” does not count (“Economic” is an adjective\\n          for which “Economics” is not a plural)\\n     Plural nouns occurring within proper nouns and noun phrases are included:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Cat” → “Cats the musical” counts\\n\\f    Grammatical variations beyond plurals/possessives are NOT included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigration” does NOT count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Run” → “Running” or “Ran” do NOT count\\n    When \\u003cword\\u003e specifies a plural form, the singular does NOT count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Veterans” → “Veteran” does NOT count\\n    Words that are spelled the same as the plural form of \\u003cword\\u003e (if such exists) but are\\n    themselves not a plural noun are included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Wind” → “Winds up the clock” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Border” → “The United States has strong borders” counts\\n    Open compounds (words separated by spaces) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fire station” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “couch” → “couch potato” counts\\n    Hyphenated compounds (words connected by hyphens) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Palestine” → “pro-Palestine” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fat” → “non-fat” counts\\n    Closed compounds (single word, no spaces/hyphens) do not count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire” does not count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firefighter” does not count\\n    Multi-word \\u003cword\\u003e in larger constructions: When \\u003cword\\u003e is a multi-word phrase\\n    appearing within a hyphenated construction, it counts only if \\u003cword\\u003e appears as a\\n    complete, unmodified element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “New York” → “New York-based” counts (complete element)\\n    Portmanteaus (words blended from two words where parts of each are combined) are\\n    NOT included unless the portmanteau clearly contains \\u003cword\\u003e as a distinct, unaltered\\n    element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “MAGA” → “MAGA-nificent” counts (MAGA appears as distinct element)\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “magnificent” → “MAGA-nificent” does NOT count (portmanteau blend)\\n\\nDictionary determination: Both the Merriam-Webster Dictionary (available online) AND the\\nOxford English Dictionary shall be used to determine compound type and/or conventional\\nspelling patterns. Inclusion in either dictionary as an open or hyphenated compound shall\\nsatisfy the Payout Criterion. If neither provides clarity (or the word is not included),\\ndetermination is based on whether written as single unit (closed/doesn’t count) vs. spaces or\\nhyphens (open or hyphenated/counts) and/or context and previous usage.\\n\\nPHONETIC EQUIVALENCIES\\n\\n    Homophones (same sound, different spelling) do not count:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “write” → “right” does not count\\n    Homonyms and homographs (same spelling) COUNT regardless of meaning or\\n    pronunciation:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “bass” → both “bass guitar” and “bass fishing” count\\n    Proper and common nouns are treated identically:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Apple” → both “Apple Inc.” and “apple” (fruit) count\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Will” → both “Will Smith” and “I will go” count\\n    Minor unintentional mispronunciations COUNT if context makes intent clear:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Mamdani” → “Mandani” counts\\n    Severe mispronunciations that make \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable do NOT count.\\n    Trademarked spellings do not count, even when pronounced identically, unless the word\\n\\fitself is the same:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “lift” → “Lyft” (pronounced “lift”) does not count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “uber” → “Uber” counts\\nWords with non-standard transliteration to English count within reason, provided they are\\nphonetically equivalent:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Zelensky” → any of “Zelenski,” “Zelenskii,” “Zelensky,” or “Zelenskiy”\\n      count if pronounced equivalently\\nContractions do not count for their constituent words unless otherwise explicitly specified\\nby the Exchange:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “not” → “won’t,” “can’t,” “don’t,” “isn’t” do not count\\nNumbers spoken as words COUNT, when spoken exactly (not part of a larger number):\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “five” → saying “five” or reading “$5” aloud as “five dollars” counts,\\n      saying “five hundred” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “410” → “four hundred ten”, “four one zero” or “four ten” counts\\nOrdinals COUNT when \\u003cword\\u003e is written numerically OR a phrase that includes a\\nnumber:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “January 6” → “January 6th” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “3” (written numerically) → “3rd” (spoken as “third”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Eight War” → “8 Wars” and “Eighth War” will count\\nCardinal and ordinal number words are distinct:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “one” → “first” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “first” → “one” does NOT count\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count when pronunciation or letter-by-letter spelling\\nmatches \\u003cword\\u003e:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “NASA” (pronounced “NAH-suh”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “N-A-S-A” (spelled out) counts\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count as \\u003cword\\u003e when pronounced as the full word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Doctor” → “Dr.” (pronounced “Doctor”) counts\\nExpanded forms of acronyms do NOT count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “AI” → “artificial intelligence” does not count\\nWords in foreign languages do NOT count unless they are perfect cognates with an\\nEnglish word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fuego” (Spanish) does NOT count\\nEnglish words within foreign sentences count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “policy” → “Nuestra policy es clara” counts\\n\\u003cword\\u003e in organization/company names counts:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Securities” → “Bank of America Securities” counts\\nWords in URLs, emails, handles, and hashtags (exclusive of domain structure, email\\nprovider or symbols) are treated as compounds when spoken as complete words, with the\\ntype of compound subject to aforementioned rules:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firestation.com” pronounced “fire station dot com” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire.com” pronounced “wildfire dot com” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “apple” → “apple.com” pronounced “apple dot com” does count\\n      When presented in URL, email, handle, or hashtag form, \\u003cword\\u003e shall be treated as\\n      a compound, not a multi-word word\\nSung, rapped, or poetic words COUNT if phonetically recognizable:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “money” → “moneyyy” (extended in rap) counts\\n      Extreme distortion making \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable does NOT count.\\nPhonetic alphabet spelling (“Foxtrot India Romeo Echo” for “FIRE”) does NOT count.\\n\\fCANCELLATIONS AND DELAYS\\n\\n   The Exchange may list an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike for any Contract. If listed,\\n   such a strike refers to the structural conditions of the market, and is NOT adjudicated as a\\n   \\u003cword\\u003e needing to be said by or validated by having been said by \\u003centity\\u003e. If listed, this\\n   strike resolves to “Yes” whenever the event fails to occur or qualify under the Payout\\n   Criterion, or any other circumstance prevents normal resolution.\\n   If no such strike is listed, and \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, the following rules\\n   apply if the event is cancelled, postponed, rescheduled, or materially altered (including\\n   being closed to press) such that no video is released within one calendar day of the\\n   original start time of the event:\\n         If the event is cancelled, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price determined in\\n         the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         If the event is postponed or rescheduled, the outcome depends on whether a new\\n         date is publicly announced within one calendar day (i.e. if the event was scheduled\\n         to begin on Monday, any time up to 11:59PM on Tuesday falls within this period) of\\n         the originally scheduled start time:\\n               If no new date is announced within one calendar day, the Contract will resolve\\n               to the last fair price determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n               If a new date is announced within one calendar day, the outcome depends on\\n               when the rescheduled event is set to occur:\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls within fourteen (14) calendar days of the\\n                     originally scheduled date, the Contract shall remain open and \\u003cword\\u003e\\n                     stated during the rescheduled event will count.\\n                           The fourteen-day window begins at 12:00 AM ET on the originally\\n                           scheduled date and ends at 11:59 PM ET fourteen days later, unless\\n                           an alternate timezone is explicitly specified.\\n                           Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the State of the Union on January\\n                           15, 2026” rescheduled to January 20, 2026 → words spoken during\\n                           the rescheduled address count.\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls more than fourteen (14) calendar days after\\n                     the originally scheduled date, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price\\n                     determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         Any Contract that cannot be resolved through the Source Agency hierarchy will\\n         instead be settled at the Last Fair Price. The Exchange will disclose the methodology\\n         used to determine the Last Fair Price (e.g., Last Traded Price, Time-Weighted\\n         Average Price) at the time of Issuance.\\n         If an event begins but is interrupted, abbreviated, or ends prematurely, words\\n         stated by \\u003centity\\u003e during the portion of the event that did occur will count and the\\n         market will otherwise resolve.\\n   If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window but the venue, format, or medium\\n   changes (e.g., moved to a different location, changed from in-person to virtual (with the\\n   exception of being closed to press)), words stated during the event will count.\\n   Special condition: Across both cases, whether an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike is\\n   listed or not, if the event specified as or in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast (or\\n   relayed as such) but the live stream/broadcast does not occur, the Exchange will instead\\n   use an officially released recording as the Underlying, and may delay resolution by up to\\n   one calendar day to allow for the release of such a recording.\\n\\f          If partial snippets are released, Contracts on words that do not appear will be\\n          resolved to last fair price, and Contracts on those that do will be resolved to “Yes”.\\n          If no recording is released, the relevant outcomes triggered by the\\n          presence/absence of an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike shall occur as outlined\\n          above.\\n\\nTECHNICAL DETAILS (UNLESS OTHERWISE SPECIFIED)\\n\\n     When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, pre-recorded content broadcast,\\n     streamed, or published as part of that event is included if presented as part of the official\\n     presentation.\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the concert” with pre-recorded video interlude\\n          where entity speaks → words from interlude count\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the television appearance” with pre-taped\\n          segment aired during broadcast → words from segment count\\n     Behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are NOT\\n     included unless officially broadcast or published as part of \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n     Subtitles and captions that display \\u003cword\\u003e on screen but are not spoken aloud by\\n     \\u003centity\\u003e do NOT count.\\n     Sign language interpretation or usage by entity does NOT count as saying \\u003cword\\u003e unless\\n     the Contract explicitly specifies that sign language counts.\\n     Text that entity displays on screen (presentation slides, teleprompter visible to audience,\\n     signatures) does NOT count unless entity reads it aloud.\\n     Content generated by AI, deepfakes, or synthetic voice technology impersonating entity\\n     does NOT count unless the synthetic content is officially commissioned, authorized, or\\n     published by entity, OR the Contract explicitly specifies that AI-generated content counts.\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e is muted due to technical failure or censorship it shall not count unless\\n     corroborating contextual evidence (including surrounding speech, or an official\\n     uncensored recording or transcript) confirms that \\u003centity\\u003e specifically uttered \\u003cword\\u003e\\n     during the muted period.\\n\\nMinimum Tick: The Minimum Tick size for the Contract shall be $0.01.\\n\\nPosition Accountability Level: The Position Accountability Level for the Contract shall be\\n$25,000 per strike, per Member.\\n\\nLast Trading Date: The Last Trading Date of the Contract will be the Expiration Date. The Last\\nTrading Time will be the Expiration time.\\n\\nSettlement Date: The Settlement Date of the Contract shall be no later than the day after the\\nExpiration Date, unless the Market Outcome is under review pursuant to Rule 7.1.\\n\\nExpiration Date: When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event: The latest Expiration Date of\\nthe Contract shall be fourteen (14) calendar days after the originally scheduled date of the\\nevent. If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window, expiration will be moved to an\\nearlier date and time in accordance with Rule 7.2. When \\u003ctime period\\u003e is defined by specific\\ndates: The latest Expiration Date of the Contract shall be two weeks after the end of \\u003ctime\\nperiod\\u003e. If an event described in the Payout Criterion occurs and a consensus has been\\nreached on all terms, then expiration will be moved to an earlier date and time in accordance\\nwith Rule 7.2.\\n\\fExpiration time: The Expiration time of the Contract shall be 10:00 AM ET.\\n\\nSettlement Value: The Settlement Value for this Contract is $1.00.\\n\\nExpiration Value: The Expiration Value is the value of the Underlying as documented by the\\nSource Agency on the Expiration Date at the Expiration time.\\n\\nContingencies: Before Settlement, Kalshi may, at its sole discretion, initiate the Market\\nOutcome Review Process pursuant to Rule 7.1 of the Rulebook. If an Expiration Value cannot\\nbe determined on the Expiration Date, Kalshi has the right to determine payouts pursuant to\\nRule 7.1 in the Rulebook.\\n\\f\\n\\n[defendant] DX-5 Formal draw archive note\\nSource checked: Roll Call / Factba.se archive\\n\\nArchive title: Remarks: Donald Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing in Washington - December 5, 2025\\n\\nArchive URL: https://rollcall.com/factbase/trump/transcript/donald-trump-remarks-fifa-world-cup-drawing-december-5-2025/\\n\\nWhat this file establishes:\\n\\nThere is a separate archived transcript page for Trump's formal attendance remarks at the draw.\\n\\nWhat this file does not establish:\\n\\nThis session could not retrieve the full transcript text from that archive.  The page is password-protected.  This example therefore does not claim, from local files alone, whether the formal program transcript does or does not contain the word \\\"Ronaldo.\\\"\\n\\nWhy this matters:\\n\\nThe complaint does not need to prove that the formal program omitted the strike.  It needs to show that Trump said \\\"Ronaldo\\\" in event-linked remarks and that the market boundary reasonably includes those remarks.  The formal archive remains relevant because it marks the distinction between the pre-event reporter exchange and the formal program.\\n\\n\\n[defendant] DX-6 Formal Roll Call/Factba.se transcript extraction\\nSource: Roll Call / Factba.se\\nURL: https://rollcall.com/factbase/trump/transcript/donald-trump-remarks-fifa-world-cup-drawing-december-5-2025/\\nCaptured page title: Remarks: Donald Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing in Washington - December 5, 2025\\n\\nRendered page metadata excerpt:\\nTopics: Sport; Sport \\u003e Competition Discipline \\u003e Soccer; Lifestyle and Leisure \\u003e Leisure \\u003e Game.\\nEntities listed: bowl; deal; Donald J. Trump; FIFA World Cup; Mark Carney; place; President; trophy; United States; way.\\nSpeakers listed: Gianni Infantino, Donald Trump, Mark Carney, Claudia Sheinbaum.\\nSpeaker statistics excerpt: Donald Trump said 25 sentences of a total of 141 sentences; Donald Trump said 274 words of a total of 1009 words; Donald Trump talked 92 seconds of a total of 484 seconds.\\n\\nFormal transcript excerpt at start of draw:\\nMark Carney, 00:00:00-00:00:02: Thank you, my friend.\\nGianni Infantino, 00:00:50-00:01:22: So this is the World Cup trophy. This is the official bowl for the World Cup and we are now going to do the draw, ladies and gentlemen. But before that, as is customary, there is always a question that the moderator asks the draw assistant. So I would like to start with Mr. Carney. How big a deal is it to co-host the World Cup for Canada?\\n\\nFormal transcript excerpt of Trump's soccer answer:\\nDonald Trump, 00:03:14-00:03:32: Well, for years, Gianni, they've thought soccer or football would be so big, so fast. And I remember, I shouldn't say this because it was a long time ago, but I remember watching Pele play on a team called the Cosmos, Pele, who was fantastic, as you know. I assume one of the greats.\\n\\nText-extraction/search notes:\\nLocal Python urllib retrieval of the page returned HTTP 200 for the source URL and extracted approximately 175,864 characters of page text with Python html.parser. Case-sensitive searches in the extracted page text returned no occurrence of \\\"Ronaldo\\\" and no occurrence of \\\"Messi\\\". The same terms were not found using the browser page find function on the rendered page.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R1 Defendant formal transcript extraction for limited rebuttal use\\nSource: Roll Call / Factba.se\\nURL: https://rollcall.com/factbase/trump/transcript/donald-trump-remarks-fifa-world-cup-drawing-december-5-2025/\\nCaptured page title: Remarks: Donald Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing in Washington - December 5, 2025\\n\\nRendered page metadata excerpt:\\nTopics: Sport; Sport \\u003e Competition Discipline \\u003e Soccer; Lifestyle and Leisure \\u003e Leisure \\u003e Game.\\nEntities listed: bowl; deal; Donald J. Trump; FIFA World Cup; Mark Carney; place; President; trophy; United States; way.\\nSpeakers listed: Gianni Infantino, Donald Trump, Mark Carney, Claudia Sheinbaum.\\nSpeaker statistics excerpt: Donald Trump said 25 sentences of a total of 141 sentences; Donald Trump said 274 words of a total of 1009 words; Donald Trump talked 92 seconds of a total of 484 seconds.\\n\\nFormal transcript excerpt at start of draw:\\nMark Carney, 00:00:00-00:00:02: Thank you, my friend.\\nGianni Infantino, 00:00:50-00:01:22: So this is the World Cup trophy. This is the official bowl for the World Cup and we are now going to do the draw, ladies and gentlemen. But before that, as is customary, there is always a question that the moderator asks the draw assistant. So I would like to start with Mr. Carney. How big a deal is it to co-host the World Cup for Canada?\\n\\nFormal transcript excerpt of Trump's soccer answer:\\nDonald Trump, 00:03:14-00:03:32: Well, for years, Gianni, they've thought soccer or football would be so big, so fast. And I remember, I shouldn't say this because it was a long time ago, but I remember watching Pele play on a team called the Cosmos, Pele, who was fantastic, as you know. I assume one of the greats.\\n\\nText-extraction/search notes:\\nLocal Python urllib retrieval of the page returned HTTP 200 for the source URL and extracted approximately 175,864 characters of page text with Python html.parser. Case-sensitive searches in the extracted page text returned no occurrence of \\\"Ronaldo\\\" and no occurrence of \\\"Messi\\\". The same terms were not found using the browser page find function on the rendered page.\\n\\nSubmitted evidence:\\n[plaintiff arguments] GovInfo DCPD202501162 transcript excerpt and metadata (ev_3fc783920414_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-3fc783920414)\\nSource: https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/DCPD-202501162/html/DCPD-202501162.htm\\nSHA-256: `3fc783920414399098d86210070dd9fe83c14fe1dbded1a56a554f8f4b3448f2`\\nBytes: 2641\\nRelevance: Official government transcript source corroborating that Trump spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center before the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw and said the strike word Ronaldo in World-Cup-related remarks.\\n\\n[defendant arguments] Roll Call/Factba.se formal FIFA World Cup Drawing transcript extraction (ev_fbb53e87ccb3_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-fbb53e87ccb3)\\nSource: https://rollcall.com/factbase/trump/transcript/donald-trump-remarks-fifa-world-cup-drawing-december-5-2025/\\nSHA-256: `fbb53e87ccb3f4381fc2bdc06ac2f2a1ea3848aadde56122b22d34dfbdf4533b`\\nBytes: 2032\\nRelevance: Formal drawing-program transcript evidence showing a separate formal Draw source from the pre-event reporter exchange; the extracted page text contains no occurrence of Ronaldo or Messi, supporting defendant's event-boundary argument.\\n\\nTechnical reports:\\n[plaintiff] Plaintiff source and adverse-search ledger\\nChecked the visible case packet and then searched official/source-specific repositories. GovInfo DCPD202501162 was opened and preserved as submitted evidence; it corroborates the packet transcript, source metadata, location, event date, and Ronaldo passages. The Roll Call/Factba.se formal drawing page rendered despite the packet's password-protection note; browser find searches for 'Ronaldo,' 'Cristiano,' and 'Messi' returned no matches. Plaintiff therefore treats the formal-program transcript as an adverse boundary check, not as proof of a formal-stage mention. The remaining dispute is contractual scope: whether the market clearly excluded public event-linked venue remarks immediately before the formal program.\\n\\n[defendant] Defense source-check ledger\\nDefendant searched for the formal Roll Call/Factba.se transcript identified by the case packet, opened the rendered Roll Call page, and fetched it locally with Python urllib. The fetch returned HTTP 200 for the formal FIFA World Cup Drawing transcript page. Text extraction produced approximately 175,864 characters; searches for \\\"Ronaldo\\\" and \\\"Messi\\\" returned no occurrences. The retrieval also captured formal-program excerpts, including Infantino's statement that \\\"we are now going to do the draw\\\" and Trump's formal soccer answer mentioning Pele rather than Ronaldo. The focused extraction was submitted and accepted as ev_fbb53e87ccb3_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-fbb53e87ccb3.\\n\\nCall submit_council_vote with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated.\\nKeep the rationale brief: no more than three sentences.\\n\\nCouncil API instructions:\\nYou are a council member. Decide the proposition from the admitted record.\\nYou may examine admitted evidence through read-only tools when exact bytes, metadata, or exhibit contents matter.\\nDo not search the web, introduce new facts, create new evidence, or upload evidence.\\nWhen ready, call submit_council_vote exactly once with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated and a concise rationale.\\n\",\"state\":\"ready\",\"status\":\"ready\",\"tools\":[{\"description\":\"Return the current visible arbitration record for this council member.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"get_case\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"List visible immutable record evidence.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"list_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Return metadata and read limits for one visible evidence item.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"stat_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Read a bounded byte range from one visible evidence item as base64.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"length\":{\"minimum\":1,\"type\":\"integer\"},\"offset\":{\"minimum\":0,\"type\":\"integer\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\",\"offset\",\"length\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"read_evidence_range\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Submit one council vote for the current deliberation opportunity.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"rationale\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"vote\":{\"enum\":[\"demonstrated\",\"not_demonstrated\"],\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"vote\",\"rationale\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"submit_council_vote\",\"read_only\":false}],\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":false,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-29T19:58:02.156322961Z\",\"deliberation_round\":1,\"member_id\":\"C2\",\"opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C2\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"remaining_ms\":887183,\"role_id\":\"council\",\"turn_number\":10},\"wait\":{\"reason\":\"ready\",\"state_version\":12,\"version\":15}}"}],"structuredContent":{"after_opportunity_id":"deliberation:1:C2","after_version":15,"case_id":"arb-ex03-20260629192557","limits":{"attempts_max":3,"attempts_remaining":3,"max_evidence_read_bytes":65536,"max_evidence_read_bytes_per_opportunity":524288,"max_evidence_reads_per_opportunity":32,"max_response_bytes":131072,"remaining_evidence_read_bytes_for_opportunity":524288,"remaining_evidence_reads_for_opportunity":32},"member_id":"C2","message":"An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.","ok":true,"prompt":"Role: council member\nMember ID: C2\nDeliberation round: 1\nProposition: For the Kalshi market \"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\", the strike \"Ronaldo\" should resolve Yes because Trump said \"Ronaldo\" in public remarks at the World Cup Draw venue immediately before the formal program, and the market wording plus the governing mention-market terms did not clearly exclude those event-linked remarks.\nStandard of evidence: Preponderance of the evidence.\nPersona:\nYou are a careful juror and council member.\n\nEvaluate the record faithfully. Decide only from the evidence, the stated rules, and the applicable burden of proof. Do not favor either side, fill gaps with speculation, or ignore uncertainty.\n\nGive weight to reliable sources, direct evidence, consistent reasoning, and clear admissions. Discount unsupported claims, rhetorical force, irrelevant facts, and conclusions that exceed the record.\n\nWhen the evidence supports one answer, state it plainly. When the evidence is incomplete or balanced, say so. Be concise, honest, and exact.\n\nRecord:\nOpenings:\n[plaintiff] Council members, this case is not mainly about whether the syllables were spoken. The case-packet transcript says they were. The real dispute is the market boundary: when Kalshi asked what Trump would say \"during the FIFA World Cup Draw,\" did that phrase clearly exclude his public, event-linked remarks at the World Cup Draw venue immediately before the formal program? On this record, it did not.\n\nThe market page fixes the contract at issue: the public title was \"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\"; the contract family was PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION; the strike was \"Ronaldo\"; Kalshi challenged the resolution as No; and the requested resolution is Yes. That means the council's task is to apply the mention-market terms to that title and strike, not to import a narrower limitation that the market did not plainly announce.\n\nThe reporter-exchange packet is direct evidence on the word and setting. It is titled as remarks in an exchange with reporters prior to the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw, dated December 5, 2025. It places the President at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts, speaking with FIFA President Gianni Infantino and reporters in a sequence repeatedly labeled around the 2026 World Cup and the Draw. In that exchange, in a soccer discussion, Trump says he met Ronaldo, praises him, and uses \"Ronaldo\" as a distinct standalone word. Under the mention rules, a distinct standalone appearance of the strike is the kind of use that counts if it falls within the time period.\n\nThe terms matter because they do not say that an event market is limited only to scripted remarks from a formal stage segment. They define a time period as potentially an event or context, and they give the Exchange power to specify what is included when a time period refers to a specific event. They also distinguish official/public event content from behind-the-scenes, rehearsals, and unofficial recordings. That distinction helps plaintiff: the packet is not a rumor, rehearsal, private soundcheck, or leaked recording. It is a sourced public transcript of remarks at the event venue, immediately tied to the Draw. If Kalshi meant \"only the formal televised draw program after doors close\" or \"only remarks in the separate formal archive,\" it needed to say so clearly.\n\nI also want to be candid about what the packet does not yet prove. The formal-draw archive note says a separate archived transcript page exists for Trump's formal attendance remarks, but that the session could not retrieve the full text because the page was password-protected. So, at opening, plaintiff is not asking you to infer that the formal program itself contained \"Ronaldo.\" Nor does plaintiff need that inference. The Yes theory is that the qualifying period reasonably includes the public pre-program reporter exchange that was part of Trump's World Cup Draw appearance. The formal archive is relevant because it marks defendant's likely narrower boundary; it does not resolve the boundary in defendant's favor.\n\nProvenance and weight also favor treating the packet seriously at this stage. The market and terms files are system case-packet records. The reporter exchange includes a source URL to a public presidential transcript source and notes a corrected transcript date, while also acknowledging that some audio could not be verified because the audio was incomplete. That caveat may affect inaudible portions, but it does not erase the visible, contextual Ronaldo passage. Later, when evidence admission opens, the parties should preserve the official transcript source, any govinfo or Presidency Project copy, the market page capture, and any accessible formal-program transcript or video. The adverse check should ask whether the formal program omits the word, but omission there would matter only if the council first accepts the defense's artificially narrow reading of \"during.\"\n\nThe plaintiff's burden is preponderance. The record already points to a straightforward path to Yes: Trump, the specified entity, said the specified strike as a standalone word in public remarks linked to and immediately preceding the World Cup Draw at the venue; the market title and governing terms did not clearly exclude that event-linked exchange. On a fair reading of the contract the trader saw, the challenged No resolution should give way to Yes.\n\n[defendant] Council members, the defense opening is simple: this case is not won by proving that the word \"Ronaldo\" appears somewhere in a public transcript. The plaintiff must prove, by a preponderance, that the word was said during the market's specified event: the FIFA World Cup Draw.\n\nThe current packet leaves that critical link unproven. The market page does not say \"while Trump was at the venue,\" \"during a World Cup press availability,\" or \"during any remarks connected to the Draw.\" It says: \"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\" The challenged resolution was No. The requested Yes theory therefore needs more than event-adjacent context; it needs a boundary showing that the reporter exchange was part of the Draw period the market asked traders to price.\n\nThe plaintiff's own best transcript cuts against that boundary. The case-packet file is titled \"Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw.\" It says the President's remarks were joined in progress, and the source note says portions could not be verified because the audio was incomplete. It places Trump at the Kennedy Center and includes World Cup topics, and yes, it contains \"Ronaldo\" as a standalone word in a soccer exchange. But its title and structure identify those remarks as an exchange with reporters prior to the Draw, not the formal Draw itself.\n\nThe terms do not rescue plaintiff from that distinction. They define a mention market around words used by the entity during the time period. A time period may be a specific event, and when it is a specific event, the Exchange may specify what is included. The technical details also distinguish official presentation content from behind-the-scenes, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings unless those are officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. Those provisions do not mean every public, nearby, event-related conversation becomes part of the event. They make the event boundary the central question.\n\nThe formal-draw archive note reinforces why the distinction matters. It reports that there is a separate archived transcript page for Trump's formal attendance remarks at the FIFA World Cup Drawing, but that the full text was not retrieved because the page was password-protected. That note does not prove the formal program omitted Ronaldo. It also does not prove the formal program included it. What it does show, at opening, is that the record itself separates the pre-event reporter exchange from the formal drawing remarks.\n\nSo the defense will focus the council on proof of inclusion, not mere association. If later phases produce a market page provision, official broadcast record, program transcript, video metadata, or source-agency material showing that the red-carpet reporter exchange was officially part of the FIFA World Cup Draw presentation for this market, the council can weigh that. If the later evidence instead shows a formal program with a separate pre-program press availability, then the correct result is No even though the word was spoken nearby.\n\nOn this opening record, plaintiff has shown a Ronaldo mention in remarks prior to the event. Plaintiff has not shown that those remarks occurred during the market event. The defense position is that Kalshi's No resolution follows the market wording and the mention-market terms unless plaintiff supplies that missing boundary proof.\n\nArguments:\n[plaintiff] Council members, the merits question is whether the contract clearly limited “during the FIFA World Cup Draw” to only the formal staged ceremony. Plaintiff submits that it did not, and the record now proves the Yes result by a preponderance.\n\nFirst, the market itself is broad. PX-1 identifies the public question as “What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?”, contract family PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION, strike “Ronaldo,” challenged resolution No, and requested resolution Yes. The market page does not say “during the formal televised ceremony,” “on the main stage only,” or “excluding public remarks immediately before the program at the venue.” That absence matters because Kalshi drafted the boundary traders had to price.\n\nSecond, the word was said. PX-2, the case-packet transcript, and PX-5, the GovInfo/OFR source excerpt, both show Trump used “Ronaldo” as a standalone word in soccer-related remarks. PX-5 is especially useful on provenance: it is the GovInfo Compilation of Presidential Documents source, published by the Office of the Federal Register/NARA, for DCPD202501162. It identifies the same event date, title, and source note, and it places the remarks at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center. In the relevant passage, Trump says he met Ronaldo, then says Ronaldo is great; later, when asked whether he played soccer or football, Trump says he was not Ronaldo or Messi. Either use satisfies the mention rule if the remarks fall within the market’s time period.\n\nThird, the remarks are event-linked in the way the market title reasonably covers. PX-2 and PX-5 are not private gossip, rehearsal, or an unofficial leak. They are public presidential remarks at the World Cup Draw venue, with FIFA President Infantino present, repeatedly discussing the Draw, the World Cup, ticket sales, the Kennedy Center, the audience, and the imminent program. The transcript itself includes headings such as “2026 World Cup Draw Event,” “2026 World Cup Draw Event/John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts,” and “2026 World Cup Draw/Ticket Sales for World Cup.” Trump and Infantino even discuss being a little late to “get in there” and the audience waiting. That sequence is not a random earlier interview; it is part of the public event appearance immediately surrounding the Draw.\n\nFourth, PX-3’s terms do not impose defendant’s formal-only line. They say the underlying is words used by the entity during the specified time period; a time period may be an event or context; and, when a time period refers to a specific event, the Exchange may specify what is included. They also say official/published content presented as part of the official presentation can count, while behind-the-scenes, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings do not count unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. Those exclusions show what this is not. The transcript is an official published record of public remarks at the event venue, not a hidden backstage clip. Nothing in PX-1 or PX-3 clearly tells traders that public, event-linked venue remarks immediately before the formal program are out.\n\nDefendant’s best point is PX-4 and the formal Roll Call/Factba.se page: there is a separate formal-drawing transcript, and my search found no “Ronaldo” there. Plaintiff does not hide that. But that adverse point proves only that the narrower formal-program source may omit the strike. It does not answer the contractual question. If Kalshi had meant to resolve solely by that formal transcript, it could have said so. Instead, the public market title used the broader phrase “during the FIFA World Cup Draw,” and the mention terms leave event boundaries to what the market clearly specifies.\n\nOn burden, plaintiff does not need absolute certainty or a formal-stage mention. Plaintiff must show it is more likely than not that the market wording plus terms include the event-linked remarks. The evidence satisfies that standard: PX-1 gives no exclusion; PX-2 and PX-5 prove the standalone Ronaldo mentions in public World Cup Draw venue remarks; PX-3 supplies a flexible event/time-period framework and excludes only categories unlike this source; PX-4 merely identifies the defense’s alternate formal-program boundary. The fair resolution is Yes.\n\n[defendant] Council members, the record now makes the defense point sharper, not weaker. Plaintiff has proved that Trump said \"Ronaldo\" in an official transcript of remarks connected to the World Cup Draw. Plaintiff has not proved that those remarks were during the market event.\n\nStart with the contract. DX/PX-1 gives the trader-facing question: \"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\" It does not say \"at the Kennedy Center,\" \"on World Cup Draw day,\" \"in remarks prior to the Draw,\" or \"in any public press exchange associated with the Draw.\" For this strike to resolve Yes, the relevant mention must fall inside that specified time period.\n\nThe strongest evidence of the Ronaldo utterance is also the strongest evidence against plaintiff's boundary. PX-2 and PX-5 are titled \"Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw.\" PX-5, plaintiff's GovInfo/OFR source, confirms the same title, says the remarks were joined in progress, identifies the source as an exchange with the news media, and notes that some portions could not be verified because the audio was incomplete. That evidence proves an official pre-event reporter transcript. It does not prove the reporter exchange was the FIFA World Cup Draw.\n\nThe terms, PX-3, require words used by the entity during the specified time period. They permit an event or context as a time period, and they discuss what is included when the time period is a specific event. That framework does not turn all event-adjacent speech into event speech. The distinction between official presentation content and non-included behind-the-scenes or unofficial content matters because the question is not just whether a record is public or official. The question is whether this source was part of the market's event period. A public official transcript can still be a transcript of remarks prior to the event.\n\nDX-2 supplies the missing contrast. It is a focused extraction from the separate Roll Call/Factba.se formal FIFA World Cup Drawing transcript. That page is the formal source identified in the case-packet archive note. It is titled \"Remarks: Donald Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing in Washington - December 5, 2025.\" Its transcript begins with the formal drawing participants; at 00:00:50, Infantino says, \"This is the World Cup trophy\" and \"we are now going to do the draw.\" The page's Trump soccer answer mentions Pele and the Cosmos, not Ronaldo. The extracted page text was searched for both \"Ronaldo\" and \"Messi\" and neither appears.\n\nThat does not prove Trump never said Ronaldo anywhere at the venue. It proves the opposite boundary from plaintiff's: the formal Draw transcript is separate from the pre-event reporter exchange, and the formal transcript does not contain the strike. Plaintiff needs a bridge between those two sources. It has not offered one. There is no market page detail saying red-carpet or pre-program press remarks count. There is no official program metadata showing the reporter exchange was part of the Draw presentation. There is no source hierarchy provision selecting the pre-event reporter exchange over the formal Draw transcript for this market.\n\nPlaintiff argues ambiguity should favor Yes because Kalshi could have drafted a narrower rule. But this is a preponderance case about a challenged No resolution, not a penalty for every conceivable ambiguity. The ordinary reading of \"during the FIFA World Cup Draw\" is the draw program, not every public appearance immediately before it. The record's own labels preserve that ordinary line: \"Prior to\" on the Ronaldo source; \"Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing\" on the formal source; and a formal transcript that starts the draw and omits the strike.\n\nWeight and provenance also favor the defense on the decisive issue. PX-5 is official and useful, but it authenticates a pre-event reporter exchange. DX-2 is a captured formal transcript extraction from the source class identified in PX-4; its absence finding is limited but material. PX-4 was initially only a note that the formal page existed and could not be retrieved. We have now retrieved and searched it. The adverse check therefore confirms, rather than merely speculates, that the formal drawing transcript does not carry plaintiff's Ronaldo mention.\n\nThe council should resolve the proposition against plaintiff. The record shows Trump said Ronaldo before the FIFA World Cup Draw in an event-linked reporter exchange. It does not show he said Ronaldo during the FIFA World Cup Draw. On this market wording and these terms, the challenged No resolution should stand.\n\nRebuttals:\n[plaintiff] Council members, defendant’s new formal-transcript extraction proves less than defendant needs.\n\nPlaintiff accepts the narrow fact defendant has now preserved: the Roll Call/Factba.se formal drawing-program extraction contains no “Ronaldo” or “Messi.” That is why plaintiff did not build the case on a formal-stage mention. The proposition instead asks whether the market wording and mention terms clearly excluded Trump’s public, official, event-linked remarks at the venue immediately before the formal program. Defendant has not supplied that exclusion.\n\nDefendant’s argument treats the title “Prior to the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw” as if “prior to” automatically means outside the Kalshi market’s event period. But PX-1 does not say “formal transcript only,” “after the draw host begins,” “after 00:00:50,” or “excluding press availability at the venue.” It asks what Trump would say “during the FIFA World Cup Draw.” The source label tells us sequence; it does not tell us the market’s legal boundary.\n\nDX-2 actually illustrates why defendant’s bright line is chosen after the fact. In defendant’s own formal extraction, the page begins before the mechanical draw: Mark Carney speaks at 00:00:00, and Infantino says at 00:00:50, “we are now going to do the draw.” If “during the FIFA World Cup Draw” can include ceremony and preamble on the formal page before the draw itself begins, then the phrase is not self-defining down to a single moment or transcript. The question is what the market clearly specified. It did not specify defendant’s transcript-only rule.\n\nThe terms do not fill that gap for defendant. PX-3 excludes hidden categories such as rehearsals, sound checks, unofficial recordings, and behind-the-scenes content unless officially published as part of the period. PX-2 and PX-5 are not those categories. PX-5 is an official GovInfo/OFR presidential transcript, published with source metadata, at 11:13 a.m. at the Kennedy Center, with FIFA’s president present and the World Cup Draw repeatedly discussed. That gives the Ronaldo mentions strong provenance and an event connection; it does not make them informal backstage chatter.\n\nDefendant says plaintiff needs a bridge. The bridge is the market text plus the terms’ failure to draw the narrow line defendant proposes. A No resolution can stand only if the contract fairly told traders that “during the FIFA World Cup Draw” meant only the separate formal-program transcript. On this record, the more likely reading is broader: public, official remarks at the venue, immediately tied to and immediately preceding the World Cup Draw program, were within the event-linked period unless clearly excluded.\n\nSo DX-2 narrows one factual issue but does not decide the case. It shows no formal-stage Ronaldo mention. It does not show that the market excluded the official pre-program event remarks where Trump did say Ronaldo. Under the preponderance standard, the Yes resolution remains the fair one.\n\nSurrebuttals:\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff’s rebuttal usefully narrows the dispute. Plaintiff accepts that the formal Roll Call/Factba.se drawing transcript contains no “Ronaldo” or “Messi.” So the case remains entirely about whether a separate reporter exchange titled “Prior to the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw” should be treated as inside the market period.\n\nPlaintiff says “prior to” is only sequence, not legal boundary. But sequence is exactly what the market phrase makes material. The contract asks what Trump would say “during the FIFA World Cup Draw.” A source-agency title identifying the Ronaldo transcript as an exchange with reporters prior to that Draw is not a stray label; it is the best record description of when and what that source is. Plaintiff cannot convert that source into the event itself by saying the market failed to list every excluded pre-event setting.\n\nPlaintiff’s formal-preamble point also does not carry the burden. Yes, the formal transcript begins before the mechanical ball selection, and Infantino says at 00:00:50 that “we are now going to do the draw.” But that supports the defense distinction. A host’s preamble inside the formal drawing transcript is part of the program. A separate press exchange, separately titled and sourced as prior to the Draw, is not made part of the program simply because it happened nearby and discussed the same event.\n\nNor does official publication settle the issue. PX-5 strengthens provenance: Trump did say Ronaldo in an official public transcript. But provenance answers whether the words were said, not whether they were said during the market’s specified event. The terms require both: the word by the entity, and the word during the time period. Plaintiff has the first element. The second is still missing.\n\nThe remaining bridge plaintiff proposes is essentially: public, official, event-linked, and not expressly excluded. That is not enough under a preponderance standard when the same record supplies a cleaner boundary: the Ronaldo source is prior to the Draw, and the formal Draw source omits the strike. The challenged No resolution should stand.\n\nClosings:\n[plaintiff] Council members, the record has narrowed to one real issue.\n\nThe word is proven. The market page identifies the strike as “Ronaldo” and the challenged resolution as No. The case-packet transcript and the GovInfo/OFR excerpt prove that Trump said “Ronaldo” as a standalone word in public remarks at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center, in a World Cup Draw setting, with FIFA President Infantino present, and amid repeated discussion of the Draw, the Kennedy Center, ticket sales, the audience, and the imminent event. That is strong provenance: GovInfo, NARA/OFR, DCPD202501162, matching the packet source and note.\n\nDefendant has also proved its best fact. The Roll Call/Factba.se formal-program extraction does not contain “Ronaldo” or “Messi.” Plaintiff does not ask you to find otherwise. If the market had said “only the formal drawing transcript,” defendant would win. But that is not the market traders saw.\n\nThe market asked: “What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?” It did not say “during the formal transcript only,” “after the host announces the draw has begun,” “excluding public press remarks at the venue,” or “excluding remarks immediately before the program.” The governing terms do not add that limitation. They define words used by the entity during the time period, allow event/context time periods, and exclude categories such as rehearsals, sound checks, behind-the-scenes content, and unofficial recordings. Plaintiff’s source is none of those. It is an official public presidential transcript of event-linked remarks at the venue.\n\nDefendant’s formal extraction shows why a bright line cannot simply be assumed. Even on that page, before balls are drawn, there is ceremony, introduction, and Infantino saying “we are now going to do the draw.” Event boundaries are not self-defining. The question is whether Kalshi clearly chose defendant’s narrower boundary. The record contains no such choice.\n\nSo the burden is met. More likely than not, a reasonable reading of the market and terms includes Trump’s official, public, venue-based remarks immediately tied to the World Cup Draw. The strongest contrary evidence proves only that a narrower formal transcript omits the strike. It does not prove the contract excluded the remarks where the strike was actually said.\n\nThe challenged No resolution should be overturned. The strike “Ronaldo” should resolve Yes.\n\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff’s closing concedes the decisive factual split: the formal World Cup Drawing transcript contains no “Ronaldo” or “Messi.” The only Ronaldo evidence is the separate official transcript titled “Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw.”\n\nThat is enough to decide the case. The market did not ask what Trump would say at the Kennedy Center, on World Cup Draw day, in public presidential remarks, or in event-linked press availability. It asked what Trump would say “during the FIFA World Cup Draw.” The terms require the word to be used by the entity during the specified time period. Plaintiff has proven the word and the speaker. It has not proven the time period.\n\nPlaintiff’s strongest point is that the market did not expressly say “formal transcript only” or “exclude pre-program remarks.” But plaintiff has the burden. A challenged No resolution does not become Yes merely because the contract could have been even more verbose. The record must make it more likely than not that the pre-event reporter exchange was inside the market period. The record does the opposite.\n\nThe source labels matter. PX-2 and PX-5 are official and probative, but they are official proof of remarks prior to the Draw. The formal Roll Call/Factba.se extraction is the source for Trump’s formal attendance at the FIFA World Cup Drawing; it begins the program, includes the draw presentation, and omits the strike. Plaintiff’s theory asks you to treat a separate prior reporter exchange as “during” the Draw even though the formal Draw source exists and does not contain the word.\n\nThe terms do not collapse that distinction. They recognize event/context time periods and official presentation content, but they still require the word to occur during the chosen time period. Official publication proves provenance. Event connection proves relevance. Neither proves inclusion. A public official transcript can be accurately preserved and still be outside the market window if it is, as titled, prior to the event.\n\nSo the fair synthesis is narrow and grounded: Trump said Ronaldo in event-linked public remarks before the FIFA World Cup Draw; Trump did not say Ronaldo in the formal drawing transcript preserved in this record; and no admitted market term or source-chain evidence bridges the pre-event exchange into the market’s “during the FIFA World Cup Draw” period.\n\nUnder the preponderance standard, plaintiff has not carried the proposition. The challenged No resolution should stand.\n\nExhibits:\n[plaintiff] PX-1 Market page and challenged resolution\nMarket URL: https://kalshi.com/markets/kxtrumpmentionb/trump-mention-b/kxtrumpmentionb-25dec06\n\nPublic market title: What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\n\nContract family: PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION\n\nStrike at issue: Ronaldo\n\nChallenged resolution: No\n\nRequested resolution: Yes\n\n\n[plaintiff] PX-2 Pre-event reporter exchange transcript\nRemarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\nDecember 05, 2025\n\n[The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\nThe President. It's a great honor to be here. Gianni has done a fantastic job. We're setting records—[inaudible].\nQ. [Inaudible]\nThe President. Well, I think so. They have a little bit of a shot. Pretty stiff competition. But I would say they would have a small chance.\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize\nQ. [Inaudible]—win the FIFA Peace Award?\nThe President. Well, it would be an honor.\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\nQ. Will you root for some selection? Will you root for someone?\nThe President. Well, I root for a lot of countries, but in this case, I'll be rooting for the U.S.A. [Laughter]\nQ. [Inaudible]\nThe President. That's great. That's great. We really love it.\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize\nQ. Mr. President, have you been told that you are going to receive the inaugural peace prize today——\nThe President. I have not——\nQ. ——from FIFA?\nThe President. I have not been told. There's a rumor about it, but I have not been told. That would be a great honor, and I'm a big fan of Gianni, as you know.\nQ. What can fans expect——\nQ. Are you hoping to receive that?\nThe President. Excuse me.\nQ. Are you hoping to receive the peace prize?\nThe President. Well, I don't like to say \"hope,\" but it would be a great honor.\n2026 World Cup\nQ. What can fans expect of, like, the World Cup in the U.S.?\nThe President. I think it's going to be fantastic. We've set every record you can set.\nQ. What are you telling people who are worried——\nFédération Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) President Giovanni V. Infantino\nQ. [Inaudible]—friend Gianni—[inaudible]—a word about him?\nThe President. I think he has done a fantastic job.\nThe President's Schedule\nQ. Are you going to be meeting with the President of Mexico today and the——\nThe President. We might. Yes.\nQ. ——Prime Minister of Canada as well?\nThe President. I might. I might do that.\nQ. Will you be discussing immigration and trade with them?\nThe President. Yes, we'll be discussing.\n[At this point, the President and Mr. Infantino posed for photographs.]\nThe President. Thank you, everybody.\n2026 World Cup Draw Event/John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts\nQ. Mr. President, what do you think about the crowd?\nThe President. Oh, look, the new star—[inaudible].\nCongratulations.\nQ. Thank you.\nThe President. You're the new star of television and Fox.\nQ. Thank you. How are you doing, Mr. President?\nThe President. I'm doing very well.\nQ. What do you think about the crowd here?\nThe President. I think the crowd is great, and I think the building is great. We've made a lot of improvements over the last 6 months. Taking—the Kennedy Center was in very bad shape. Now it's getting to be really good. And in 6 months, it's going to be incredible with the improvements we've made.\nQ. The first time for the U.S. to host since the nineties.\nThe President. Right.\nQ. Are you ready for it?\nThe President. I'm ready for it, and they're ready for it. And Gianni, who you know——\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\nThe President. ——has done a fantastic job with FIFA. And we're looking to have—you know, we're set—we have already set records for tickets sales. I don't think there's ever been anything like it in any sport. And so, I want to congratulate you.\nMr. Infantino. Thank you.\nThe President. I don't even have to wait. But major records have been set.\nHow are you?\nQ. Good, how are you, sir?\nThe President. Nice to see you.\nQ. Today it's not football—American football. It's soccer. It's——\nThe President. Right.\nQ. ——the big event of soccer.\nThe President. That's right. That's right.\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\nQ. So can you tell me about this big day today?\nThe President. It's just a big day, and it's a great sport. And it really is coming to America. And never—nobody ever thought a thing like this could happen. And I'm very happy to say that we've already set the alltime record on ticket sales long before the first ball is kicked. Right?\nMr. Infantino. A hundred percent. One hundred percent.\n2026 World Cup Host Cities\nQ. You've had some concerns about crime in American cities, some of the cities that will be hosting. Have they remedied that for you? Are you still considering maybe asking FIFA to move some of those cities?\nThe President. No, I don't want to do that. But I will tell you, if they do have a problem, by the time we get there, we'll take care of that problem. We can solve that problem.\nI've proven that in DC and everywhere else we went, so we'll take care of that very easily. So, if they have a problem, hopefully, they'll let us know that, and we will solve any problem.\nOkay? Thank you.\nQ. Thank you so much.\nMr. Infantino. All right, thank you so much.\nQ. Thank you, Mr. President.\nQ. Thank you. Appreciate it.\nThe President. Congratulations.\n2026 World Cup\nQ. Mr. President, Brazilian television. America will be hosting the World Cup and the Olympics in 2 years. How important it is—[inaudible]?\nThe President. I think very. It's a great honor. I think Gianni is doing a phenomenal job. We've set every record on ticket sales. It's been really fantastic. But Gianni has done an unbelievable job with FIFA.\nThe President's Experience With Soccer\nQ. [Inaudible]\nThe President. He was a great—not only that. I got to see a man name Pelé play—right?—that tells you how old I am—when he was on the Cosmos. Do you remember that a long time ago? And it was quite a treat. That was quite an event. And he was—not only was he playing, he was great. He scored two goals, I think. And so, I was one of the few who got to see Pelé, and I assume he is one of your alltime greats. Right?\nMr. Infantino. Definitely.\nThe President. So I got to see him.\nThe President's Favorite World Cup Competitor\nQ. Do you have some favorite teams for World Cup?\nThe President. Well, I have a favorite. It's the U.S.A. [Laughter] I don't know what their chances are, Gianni, but maybe the U.S.A. is the——\nMr. Infantino. They're getting better and better, actually.\nThe President. I think they'll do well.\nMr. Infantino. They are getting better and better.\nThe President. I think they'll do well.\nThank you very much, everybody.\nQ. Thank you so much.\n2026 World Cup\nQ. Mr. President, World Cup in America just means—[inaudible]. So what do you expect from this World Cup?\nThe President. [Inaudible]—record business and only in the United States, but we're also doing record ticket sales with FIFA. And they've already bought—beat their highest record. And we—you know, this a long time before the first ball is kicked. You've sold more tickets than they've ever done before, and better pricing than they've ever gotten before. It's a tremendous success. And it's an honor. And Gianni has done a phenomenal job with FIFA.\nQ. [Inaudible]—ever?\nThe President. I think so. I think it's going to be—I mean, ideally, you want to see that every year. Every 4 years, it gets bigger and better. I think we have set every record in the book. We're very happy about it.\nThank you.\nThe President's Favorite World Cup Competitor\nQ. [Inaudible]—part of America. Who are you going to support as well?\nThe President. Well, I think I have to support U.S.A. Otherwise, I'd be in trouble. I wouldn't be President for long.\nMr. Infantino. [Inaudible]\nThe President. [Inaudible]—but you have a lot of great teams. You're going to have a lot of great teams.\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\"football,\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\n2026 World Cup Draw/Ticket Sales for World Cup\nQ. How does it feel to be part of this amazing event? And obviously, your being a part of participating in all the—[inaudible]?\nThe President. The President of Mexico is here, and she's doing a very good job. She's a good woman, very, very excellent job. It's an honor, and we're setting every record, and you're helping us set those records.\nMr. Infantino. And we will do it.\nThe President. You know, Mexico and Canada are helping us set those records. But as you know, we have a record in ticket sales already, long before the first ball is kicked, and we're going to do great.\nI think that Gianni—as you know, he's the head, and he has done a fantastic job.\nU.S. Cooperation With Mexico and Canada\nQ. And how is the biggest challenge being three countries?\nThe President. Well, I think that—do you mean for the three countries?\nWell, they've gotten together really well, I mean.\nMr. Infantino. All right.\nThe President. They're getting along very well.\nMr. Infantino. Collaboration is fantastic between the three.\nThe President's Interest in Soccer/2026 World Cup\nQ. And you like soccer?\nThe President. I do. I like it. I like it more and more.\nQ. Yes?\nThe President. I like it. It's growing in this country—very, really—I mean, someday, maybe it's going to be bigger than anything else.\nMr. Infantino. We'll have to become number one.\nThe President. I will say this——\nMr. Infantino. Definitely.\nThe President. ——the ticket sales——\nQ. Definitely will happen.\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\nThe President. Ticket sales are bigger than anything we have ever done in the history of the country, in terms of sports.\nMr. Infantino. For certain.\nQ. And the audience is going to be huge.\nThe President. The audience is going to be tremendous.\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\nThe President. Yes.\nMr. Infantino. Six billion people.\nThe President. [Inaudible]\nQ. Six billion? That's amazing.\nMr. Infantino. Six billion people.\nAnd today, one billion.\nQ. Wow.\nMr. Infantino. [Inaudible]\nQ. Enjoy show time. Thank you so much.\nThe President. [Inaudible]\nQ. Mr. President, how are you? Just a quick—[inaudible].\nQ. This is for Telemundo.\nThe President. How are you?\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\nQ. Hello, Mr. President. How are you? This for Telemundo.\nThe President. How are you? Good.\nQ. How are you?\nThe President. Very good. Thank you.\nQ. How does it feel to have the most important event of sports—that global—in the U.S.?\nThe President. Well, we do. And right at the Kennedy Center. I'm Chairman of the Kennedy Center. And I hear the Kennedy Center is doing a very good job, so it feels great. Really good.\nAnd Telemundo is doing a good job, too. Thank you.\nQ. Thank you.\n2026 World Cup\nQ. What is the significance of hosting the FIFA World Cup this year?\nThe President. It's a—in terms of sports, I would say the ultimate. There is no sport like this. It's the biggest sport in the world. And we are setting every record. You know, our ticket sales have gone and set every—every sport—no matter what it is, we've set the record. So—and every though it's very early, there's no ball being kicked yet, but we've already set a ticket sales record.\nArgentina National Team\nQ. How do you see Argentinean team for this World Cup?\nThe President. Well, I love Argentina. And your President is doing a very good job, as you know. Milei. You know that right? It's make Argentina great again. MAGA.\nQ. And——\nU.S. National Team\nQ. Do you think the States are building a powerful team for next year?\nThe President. Who?\nQ. The States.\nThe President. Oh, yes. Sure. I—you're going to have a lot of powerful teams. Everybody has a lot of powerful teams, but you're going to have a lot of great teams. [Inaudible]\nU.S. Role in Hosting the 2026 World Cup\nQ. Mr. President, what does it mean for you guys to host the World Cup right here in the U.S.?\nThe President. I'm honored to host it. It's a great honor. I mean, it's turned out to be bigger than we thought. We're setting a record for ticket sales, the likes of which no sport has ever seen before.\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\nThe President. But they have a little more speed.\nBut no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\nPopularity of Soccer in Latin America\nQ. Mr. President, a message for the Latin America and soccer fans?\nThe President. Yes, I am. And Latin America is great. And they have great soccer. So, good luck in the matches.\n[A reporter asked a question in Spanish, which was translated by an interpreter as follows.]\nU.S. Visas for World Cup Ticketholders\nQ. Who is going to be in—[inaudible]—about these visas for the—these fans that want to come here to the World Cup?\nThe President. Well, we're going to make it very easy for them. We're working on that right now. We're going to make it very easy. It's going to be a very easy process.\nQ. Okay. Say, hi to Colombia over there.\nThe President. Hello. Is that Colombia?\nQ. Yes.\nThe President. I love Colombia. Hello, Colombia. [Laughter]\nQ. Okay. Okay. Muy bien.\nThe President. So where are you from?\nQ. Paraguay.\nThe President. Oh.\nQ. He's from Paraguay. Yes.\nThe President. Very good. I love it. I—it's a beautiful country. We get along very well with them. We do a little trade deal with them, and they like us. And that's what's happening.\nQ. Panama.\nThe President. Where?\nVery good. I like the canal. [Laughter] That canal is pretty good.\n[A reporter spoke in Spanish; no translation was provided.]\n2026 World Cup\nThe President. What?\nQ. [Inaudible]\nThe President. Well, it's going to be incredible. The event is going to be very good. Just this event alone—it's at the Kennedy Center. I see you have it fixed up perfectly.\nMr. Infantino. It will set the tone.\nThe President. Right? It's beautiful.\nMr. Infantino. It's beautiful.\nThe President. It's a beautiful place.\nHave a good time.\nQ. [Inaudible]\nThe President.\n[A reporter spoke in Spanish; no translation was provided.]\nMr. Infantino. No, gracias. [Inaudible]\nThe President. It's great.\nJohn F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts/Renovation Work\nQ. Mr. President, the U.S. press?\nThe President. Thank you, everybody, very much. It's a great honor. This has been an honor for a lot of reasons. Number one, they've sold more tickets than any event has ever sold already—long before the kickoff.\nAnd number two, we've done a lot of work at the Kennedy Center. It was falling apart, and now it's pretty much back. And we'll get it back within the next 4 or 5 months through construction, and—but you see the way it looks.\nAnd Gianni is just telling me—who's done an incredible job, by the way. He's just telling, you know, how good a job we've done.\nMr. Infantino. That's right.\nThe President. You can look at the walls. The marble was broken. Everything was a mess. And we've really taken the Kennedy Center—a lot of people thought it was going to be ripped down, and we did just the opposite. So we've done a really great renovation job on it. And over the next 3, 4 months, it will be complete. And we're honored to have it here, and it's been—it's been very special.\nWe've set a record on ticket sales, as you probably heard, already, even way before—long before the event itself. And we're working with Canada, and we're working with Mexico. And it's been a really spectacular—so far, it's been spectacular.\nDaniel [Daniel Baldwin, One America News Network], do you have a question?\n2026 World Cup\nQ. What are your expectations? You once said that the FIFA World Cup is an opportunity to put—a once-in-a-lifetime opportunity to put the greatness of the United States on display.\nThe President. Well, I think—\nQ. One billion eyeballs will be watching, Mr. President.\nThe President. Yes, I—think——\nQ. What will they here today?\nThe President. Even today, I understand. I hear that, you know——\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\nThe President. ——I know we're a little late to get in there, but——\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\nThe President. ——that's okay.\nMr. Infantino. They wait.\nThe President. So all my friends, I guess they have to wait. They have no choice, right? [Laughter]\nMr. Infantino. Yes, they wait.\nThe President. But no, the numbers are incredible. I hear today's numbers are——\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\nThe President. ——very big. I hope CNN is covering this.\nQ. One billion eyeballs.\nMr. Infantino. Today, 1 billion eyeballs.\nThe President. Today's numbers are very, very big.\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize/The President's Foreign Policy\nQ. We are covering it. And you're expected to get the FIFA Peace Prize, Mr. President. What would you say to people who say that prize might conflict with your pledge to strike Venezuela?\nThe President. Well, I think the peace prize—I mean, I settled eight wars. I don't know that I'm getting it. I haven't been officially noticed. I've been hearing about a peace prize, and I'm here to represent our country in a different sense. But I can tell you, I did settle eight wars, and we have a ninth coming, but—which nobody has ever done before.\nBut I want to really save lives. I don't need prizes. I need to save lives. And we're saving a lot of lives. And I've saved millions and millions of lives, and that's really what I want to do.\nAnd I also want to run a great country. And the United States right now is the hottest country anywhere in the world. And 1 year ago, it was dead. We had a dead country, and now we have the hottest country anywhere in the world.\nQ. Mr. President, will you——\nThe President's Meeting With President Claudia Sheinbaum Pardo of Mexico and Prime Minister Mark Carney of Canada\nQ. What are you going to discuss with Canada and Mexico, Mr.—what are you going to discuss with the leaders of Canada and Mexico?\nThe President. Well, we're getting—we're going to meet with both. And we're getting along very well. You know, we're getting along very well. I don't know. I think we have a meeting set up for some time after the event.\nQ. Will you discuss trade?\nThe President. Yes, we'll discuss trade. We—get along very well.\nThank you, everybody, very much.\nQ. Will you pardon any other Honduran officials?\nQ. Do you want them to keep trying to indict Ms. James?\n\nNOTE: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. In his remarks, he referred to Trey Yingst, chief foreign correspondent, Fox News Channel; Cristiano Ronaldo, forward for Saudi Pro League club Al-Nass and Portugal's national soccer team; and Lionel Messi, forward for Major League Soccer club Inter Miami and Argentina's national team. A reporter referred to New York State Attorney General Letitia James. The transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\n\nSource URL: https://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/documents/remarks-exchange-with-reporters-prior-the-2026-federation-internationale-des-associations\n\n\n[plaintiff] PX-3 PRESMENTION/NEWMENTION terms\n                                         NEWMENTION\n\nScope: These rules shall apply to this contract.\n\nUnderlying: The Underlying for this Contract is words used by <entity> <time period>.\nRevisions to the Underlying made after Expiration will not be accounted for in determining the\nExpiration Value.\n\nSource Agency: The Source Agencies are <source>.\n\nType: The type of Contract is an Event Contract.\n\nIssuance: After the initial Contract, Contract iterations will be listed on an as-needed basis at\nthe discretion of the Exchange and corresponding to the risk management needs of Members.\n\n<entity>: <entity> refers to the speaker, writer, performer, or communicator specified by the\nExchange. This may include (but is not limited to): a specific named individual, multiple\nindividuals specified using AND/OR logic, an individual identified by position or title, a group,\nband, team or collective entity, a specified member or members of a group, an organization,\ncompany, or institutional entity, or any combination of the aforementioned.\n\nWhen <entity> is defined by a position or title, the Contract tracks whoever holds that position\nduring <time period>, even if the individual holding the position changes. When <entity> is a\nspecific named individual, the identity remains consistent throughout. Name changes (e.g.,\nstage names, married names) do not create a new entity. When <entity> is a group or\norganization and the Contract does not specify particular members, any official\ncommunication or statement by any member or designated spokesperson counts. When using\nAND logic, all specified entities must independently say <word> during <time period>. When\nusing OR logic, at least one of the specified entities must say <word> during <time period>.\nThe Exchange may specify additional conditions such as “at least X members of” a group or\n“the majority of” a group.\n\n<source>: <source> refers to a Source Agency or ordered collection of Source Agencies\nspecified by the Exchange at the time of Contract listing, which will be incorporated into the\nSource Agency hierarchy above and used to determine the occurrence of the Underlying.\n<source> may refer to a singular agency, multiple agencies, an agency by distinguishing\ncharacteristics, by category or type (e.g., “official government statistical body,” “primary wire\nservice”), or any combination thereof. When multiple agencies are specified, they may be\napplied in the hierarchical order designated by the Exchange if so specified, with the highest-\nranked available and responsive agency taking precedence for purposes of determining the\nExpiration Value. A lower-ranked agency shall only be consulted if all higher-ranked agencies\nare unavailable, unresponsive, have not reported on the Underlying by the Expiration time, or\nif the Exchange, in its sole discretion, determines that a higher-ranked agency’s reporting is\nincomplete, erroneous, or otherwise insufficient to determine the Expiration Value. If <source>\ndesignates multiple agencies without specifying a hierarchical order, the Exchange shall\nresolve any conflict between reporting agencies at its sole discretion.\n\n<word>: <word> refers to the particular word or phrase potentially to be mentioned by\n<entity>. It may refer to a word being said a minimum number of times. It may also refer to\none of multiple words/phrases, any of which are acceptable (e.g., “Doge/Dogecoin”).\n\f<time period>: <time period> refers to a specific range of time, event or discrete date and\ntime specified by the Exchange. This may be defined by, but is not limited to: a specific event\nor context (e.g., “during the State of the Union address”), exact dates or times, relative time\nmarkers (e.g., “before July 1, 2027,” “in Q1 2026”), event-based periods (e.g., “during any\ncampaign rally in October 2026,” “during the awards ceremony”), and broader intervals (e.g.,\n“Q1–Q2 2027,” “January–March 2026”).\n\nUnless stated otherwise, “Between” is inclusive of both endpoints, while “before” and “after”\nexclude the specified date. <time period> may also refer to “Any” or “None”, to multiple dates\n(even if non-consecutive), or to a singular and discrete date or time.\n\nWhen <time period> refers to a specific event (such as an address, speech, performance, or\nbroadcast), the Exchange may specify what is included, including whether it includes both live\nand pre-recorded segments (including whether advertisements are included). Where a\ntimezone is not specified, ET is assumed.\n\n\nPayout Criterion: The Payout Criterion for the Contract encompasses the Expiration Values that\n<word> is said by <entity> <time period>.\n\n\nThe word must appear as a distinct, standalone unit, not buried inside another word. Plural\nand possessive noun forms count. Other grammatical changes (tense, conjugation, derivation)\ndo not. If <word> appears separated from other words by a space or hyphen or in a\ncompound form with a space or hyphen, it counts. If <word> is fused into a single\nunhyphenated word, it does not count.\n\nIf <time period> refers to an event and that event is cancelled, and the market contains a\nstrike stating “Event does not qualify/occur”, such a strike shall resolve “Yes” and all others\n“No”. If <time period> refers to an event and that event is cancelled but such strikes are NOT\nlisted, the Contracts will resolve to the last fair price determined at the discretion of the\nExchange. If the event is postponed, and such a postponement is announced by the end of the\nfollowing calendar day to be rescheduled to a time within 14 calendar days, the markets shall\nremain open. If the event captured in <time period> is a live-stream or broadcast, the\nExchange may keep the market open for 24 hours for the release of an official recording.\nFurther granular details on conditions for these Contracts is available below.\n\nAdditional clarification(s):\n\n     Possessive noun forms of <word>, plurals, and possessive plural noun forms are\n     INCLUDED:\n          <word> is “Immigrant” → “Immigrants” counts\n          <word> is “Egg” → “eggs’ shells” counts\n          <word> is “Russia” → “Russia’s” counts, “Russian” does not\n     If <word> exists only in adjective form, no plural form exists:\n          <word> is “Economic” → “Economics” does not count (“Economic” is an adjective\n          for which “Economics” is not a plural)\n     Plural nouns occurring within proper nouns and noun phrases are included:\n          <word> is “Cat” → “Cats the musical” counts\n\f    Grammatical variations beyond plurals/possessives are NOT included:\n         <word> is “Immigrant” → “Immigration” does NOT count\n         <word> is “Run” → “Running” or “Ran” do NOT count\n    When <word> specifies a plural form, the singular does NOT count:\n         <word> is “Veterans” → “Veteran” does NOT count\n    Words that are spelled the same as the plural form of <word> (if such exists) but are\n    themselves not a plural noun are included:\n         <word> is “Wind” → “Winds up the clock” counts\n         <word> is “Border” → “The United States has strong borders” counts\n    Open compounds (words separated by spaces) count:\n         <word> is “fire” → “fire station” counts\n         <word> is “couch” → “couch potato” counts\n    Hyphenated compounds (words connected by hyphens) count:\n         <word> is “Palestine” → “pro-Palestine” counts\n         <word> is “fat” → “non-fat” counts\n    Closed compounds (single word, no spaces/hyphens) do not count:\n         <word> is “fire” → “wildfire” does not count\n         <word> is “fire” → “firefighter” does not count\n    Multi-word <word> in larger constructions: When <word> is a multi-word phrase\n    appearing within a hyphenated construction, it counts only if <word> appears as a\n    complete, unmodified element:\n         <word> is “New York” → “New York-based” counts (complete element)\n    Portmanteaus (words blended from two words where parts of each are combined) are\n    NOT included unless the portmanteau clearly contains <word> as a distinct, unaltered\n    element:\n         <word> is “MAGA” → “MAGA-nificent” counts (MAGA appears as distinct element)\n         <word> is “magnificent” → “MAGA-nificent” does NOT count (portmanteau blend)\n\nDictionary determination: Both the Merriam-Webster Dictionary (available online) AND the\nOxford English Dictionary shall be used to determine compound type and/or conventional\nspelling patterns. Inclusion in either dictionary as an open or hyphenated compound shall\nsatisfy the Payout Criterion. If neither provides clarity (or the word is not included),\ndetermination is based on whether written as single unit (closed/doesn’t count) vs. spaces or\nhyphens (open or hyphenated/counts) and/or context and previous usage.\n\nPHONETIC EQUIVALENCIES\n\n    Homophones (same sound, different spelling) do not count:\n        <word> is “write” → “right” does not count\n    Homonyms and homographs (same spelling) COUNT regardless of meaning or\n    pronunciation:\n        <word> is “bass” → both “bass guitar” and “bass fishing” count\n    Proper and common nouns are treated identically:\n        <word> is “Apple” → both “Apple Inc.” and “apple” (fruit) count\n        <word> is “Will” → both “Will Smith” and “I will go” count\n    Minor unintentional mispronunciations COUNT if context makes intent clear:\n        <word> is “Mamdani” → “Mandani” counts\n    Severe mispronunciations that make <word> unrecognizable do NOT count.\n    Trademarked spellings do not count, even when pronounced identically, unless the word\n\fitself is the same:\n      <word> is “lift” → “Lyft” (pronounced “lift”) does not count\n      <word> is “uber” → “Uber” counts\nWords with non-standard transliteration to English count within reason, provided they are\nphonetically equivalent:\n      <word> is “Zelensky” → any of “Zelenski,” “Zelenskii,” “Zelensky,” or “Zelenskiy”\n      count if pronounced equivalently\nContractions do not count for their constituent words unless otherwise explicitly specified\nby the Exchange:\n      <word> is “not” → “won’t,” “can’t,” “don’t,” “isn’t” do not count\nNumbers spoken as words COUNT, when spoken exactly (not part of a larger number):\n      <word> is “five” → saying “five” or reading “$5” aloud as “five dollars” counts,\n      saying “five hundred” does NOT count\n      <word> is “410” → “four hundred ten”, “four one zero” or “four ten” counts\nOrdinals COUNT when <word> is written numerically OR a phrase that includes a\nnumber:\n      <word> is “January 6” → “January 6th” counts\n      <word> is “3” (written numerically) → “3rd” (spoken as “third”) counts\n      <word> is “Eight War” → “8 Wars” and “Eighth War” will count\nCardinal and ordinal number words are distinct:\n      <word> is “one” → “first” does NOT count\n      <word> is “first” → “one” does NOT count\nAcronyms and abbreviations count when pronunciation or letter-by-letter spelling\nmatches <word>:\n      <word> is “NASA” → “NASA” (pronounced “NAH-suh”) counts\n      <word> is “NASA” → “N-A-S-A” (spelled out) counts\nAcronyms and abbreviations count as <word> when pronounced as the full word:\n      <word> is “Doctor” → “Dr.” (pronounced “Doctor”) counts\nExpanded forms of acronyms do NOT count:\n      <word> is “AI” → “artificial intelligence” does not count\nWords in foreign languages do NOT count unless they are perfect cognates with an\nEnglish word:\n      <word> is “fire” → “fuego” (Spanish) does NOT count\nEnglish words within foreign sentences count:\n      <word> is “policy” → “Nuestra policy es clara” counts\n<word> in organization/company names counts:\n      <word> is “Securities” → “Bank of America Securities” counts\nWords in URLs, emails, handles, and hashtags (exclusive of domain structure, email\nprovider or symbols) are treated as compounds when spoken as complete words, with the\ntype of compound subject to aforementioned rules:\n      <word> is “fire” → “firestation.com” pronounced “fire station dot com” counts\n      <word> is “fire” → “wildfire.com” pronounced “wildfire dot com” does NOT count\n      <word> is “apple” → “apple.com” pronounced “apple dot com” does count\n      When presented in URL, email, handle, or hashtag form, <word> shall be treated as\n      a compound, not a multi-word word\nSung, rapped, or poetic words COUNT if phonetically recognizable:\n      <word> is “money” → “moneyyy” (extended in rap) counts\n      Extreme distortion making <word> unrecognizable does NOT count.\nPhonetic alphabet spelling (“Foxtrot India Romeo Echo” for “FIRE”) does NOT count.\n\fCANCELLATIONS AND DELAYS\n\n   The Exchange may list an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike for any Contract. If listed,\n   such a strike refers to the structural conditions of the market, and is NOT adjudicated as a\n   <word> needing to be said by or validated by having been said by <entity>. If listed, this\n   strike resolves to “Yes” whenever the event fails to occur or qualify under the Payout\n   Criterion, or any other circumstance prevents normal resolution.\n   If no such strike is listed, and <time period> refers to a specific event, the following rules\n   apply if the event is cancelled, postponed, rescheduled, or materially altered (including\n   being closed to press) such that no video is released within one calendar day of the\n   original start time of the event:\n         If the event is cancelled, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price determined in\n         the sole discretion of the Exchange.\n         If the event is postponed or rescheduled, the outcome depends on whether a new\n         date is publicly announced within one calendar day (i.e. if the event was scheduled\n         to begin on Monday, any time up to 11:59PM on Tuesday falls within this period) of\n         the originally scheduled start time:\n               If no new date is announced within one calendar day, the Contract will resolve\n               to the last fair price determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\n               If a new date is announced within one calendar day, the outcome depends on\n               when the rescheduled event is set to occur:\n                     If the rescheduled date falls within fourteen (14) calendar days of the\n                     originally scheduled date, the Contract shall remain open and <word>\n                     stated during the rescheduled event will count.\n                           The fourteen-day window begins at 12:00 AM ET on the originally\n                           scheduled date and ends at 11:59 PM ET fourteen days later, unless\n                           an alternate timezone is explicitly specified.\n                           Example: <time period> is “during the State of the Union on January\n                           15, 2026” rescheduled to January 20, 2026 → words spoken during\n                           the rescheduled address count.\n                     If the rescheduled date falls more than fourteen (14) calendar days after\n                     the originally scheduled date, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price\n                     determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\n         Any Contract that cannot be resolved through the Source Agency hierarchy will\n         instead be settled at the Last Fair Price. The Exchange will disclose the methodology\n         used to determine the Last Fair Price (e.g., Last Traded Price, Time-Weighted\n         Average Price) at the time of Issuance.\n         If an event begins but is interrupted, abbreviated, or ends prematurely, words\n         stated by <entity> during the portion of the event that did occur will count and the\n         market will otherwise resolve.\n   If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window but the venue, format, or medium\n   changes (e.g., moved to a different location, changed from in-person to virtual (with the\n   exception of being closed to press)), words stated during the event will count.\n   Special condition: Across both cases, whether an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike is\n   listed or not, if the event specified as or in <time period> is a live-stream or broadcast (or\n   relayed as such) but the live stream/broadcast does not occur, the Exchange will instead\n   use an officially released recording as the Underlying, and may delay resolution by up to\n   one calendar day to allow for the release of such a recording.\n\f          If partial snippets are released, Contracts on words that do not appear will be\n          resolved to last fair price, and Contracts on those that do will be resolved to “Yes”.\n          If no recording is released, the relevant outcomes triggered by the\n          presence/absence of an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike shall occur as outlined\n          above.\n\nTECHNICAL DETAILS (UNLESS OTHERWISE SPECIFIED)\n\n     When <time period> refers to a specific event, pre-recorded content broadcast,\n     streamed, or published as part of that event is included if presented as part of the official\n     presentation.\n          Example: <time period> is “during the concert” with pre-recorded video interlude\n          where entity speaks → words from interlude count\n          Example: <time period> is “during the television appearance” with pre-taped\n          segment aired during broadcast → words from segment count\n     Behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are NOT\n     included unless officially broadcast or published as part of <time period>.\n     Subtitles and captions that display <word> on screen but are not spoken aloud by\n     <entity> do NOT count.\n     Sign language interpretation or usage by entity does NOT count as saying <word> unless\n     the Contract explicitly specifies that sign language counts.\n     Text that entity displays on screen (presentation slides, teleprompter visible to audience,\n     signatures) does NOT count unless entity reads it aloud.\n     Content generated by AI, deepfakes, or synthetic voice technology impersonating entity\n     does NOT count unless the synthetic content is officially commissioned, authorized, or\n     published by entity, OR the Contract explicitly specifies that AI-generated content counts.\n     If <word> is muted due to technical failure or censorship it shall not count unless\n     corroborating contextual evidence (including surrounding speech, or an official\n     uncensored recording or transcript) confirms that <entity> specifically uttered <word>\n     during the muted period.\n\nMinimum Tick: The Minimum Tick size for the Contract shall be $0.01.\n\nPosition Accountability Level: The Position Accountability Level for the Contract shall be\n$25,000 per strike, per Member.\n\nLast Trading Date: The Last Trading Date of the Contract will be the Expiration Date. The Last\nTrading Time will be the Expiration time.\n\nSettlement Date: The Settlement Date of the Contract shall be no later than the day after the\nExpiration Date, unless the Market Outcome is under review pursuant to Rule 7.1.\n\nExpiration Date: When <time period> refers to a specific event: The latest Expiration Date of\nthe Contract shall be fourteen (14) calendar days after the originally scheduled date of the\nevent. If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window, expiration will be moved to an\nearlier date and time in accordance with Rule 7.2. When <time period> is defined by specific\ndates: The latest Expiration Date of the Contract shall be two weeks after the end of <time\nperiod>. If an event described in the Payout Criterion occurs and a consensus has been\nreached on all terms, then expiration will be moved to an earlier date and time in accordance\nwith Rule 7.2.\n\fExpiration time: The Expiration time of the Contract shall be 10:00 AM ET.\n\nSettlement Value: The Settlement Value for this Contract is $1.00.\n\nExpiration Value: The Expiration Value is the value of the Underlying as documented by the\nSource Agency on the Expiration Date at the Expiration time.\n\nContingencies: Before Settlement, Kalshi may, at its sole discretion, initiate the Market\nOutcome Review Process pursuant to Rule 7.1 of the Rulebook. If an Expiration Value cannot\nbe determined on the Expiration Date, Kalshi has the right to determine payouts pursuant to\nRule 7.1 in the Rulebook.\n\f\n\n[plaintiff] PX-4 Formal draw archive note\nSource checked: Roll Call / Factba.se archive\n\nArchive title: Remarks: Donald Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing in Washington - December 5, 2025\n\nArchive URL: https://rollcall.com/factbase/trump/transcript/donald-trump-remarks-fifa-world-cup-drawing-december-5-2025/\n\nWhat this file establishes:\n\nThere is a separate archived transcript page for Trump's formal attendance remarks at the draw.\n\nWhat this file does not establish:\n\nThis session could not retrieve the full transcript text from that archive.  The page is password-protected.  This example therefore does not claim, from local files alone, whether the formal program transcript does or does not contain the word \"Ronaldo.\"\n\nWhy this matters:\n\nThe complaint does not need to prove that the formal program omitted the strike.  It needs to show that Trump said \"Ronaldo\" in event-linked remarks and that the market boundary reasonably includes those remarks.  The formal archive remains relevant because it marks the distinction between the pre-event reporter exchange and the formal program.\n\n\n[plaintiff] PX-5 GovInfo official transcript excerpt and metadata\nSource: GovInfo, DCPD202501162, Office of the Federal Register / National Archives and Records Administration.\nURL: https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/DCPD-202501162/html/DCPD-202501162.htm\nTitle: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\nEvent date: December 5, 2025.\n\nRelevant extracted page text:\n\"Administration of Donald J. Trump, 2025\"\n\"Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw December 5, 2025\"\n\"[The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\"\n\nUnder the section \"The President's Interest in Soccer\":\n\"Q. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\"\n\"The President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\\\"football,\\\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\"\n\"Thank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\"\n\nAdditional relevant extracted page text:\n\"The President's Interest in Soccer\"\n\"Q. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\"\n\"The President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\"\n\"Mr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\"\n\"The President. But they have a little more speed. But no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\"\n\nGovInfo note:\n\"NOTE: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. In his remarks, he referred to Trey Yingst, chief foreign correspondent, Fox News Channel; Cristiano Ronaldo, forward for Saudi Pro League club Al-Nass and Portugal's national soccer team; and Lionel Messi, forward for Major League Soccer club Inter Miami and Argentina's national team. A reporter referred to New York State Attorney General Letitia James. The transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\"\n\nGovInfo content details page also identifies category \"Interviews With the News Media : Exchanges with reporters, Washington, DC,\" subjects including \"Federation Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) World Cup,\" \"John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts,\" and \"Soccer,\" and names including \"Ronaldo, Cristiano\" and \"Messi, Lionel.\"\n\n[defendant] DX-1 Market wording and challenged resolution\nMarket URL: https://kalshi.com/markets/kxtrumpmentionb/trump-mention-b/kxtrumpmentionb-25dec06\n\nPublic market title: What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\n\nContract family: PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION\n\nStrike at issue: Ronaldo\n\nChallenged resolution: No\n\nRequested resolution: Yes\n\n\n[defendant] DX-2 Pre-event reporter exchange transcript\nRemarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\nDecember 05, 2025\n\n[The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\nThe President. It's a great honor to be here. Gianni has done a fantastic job. We're setting records—[inaudible].\nQ. [Inaudible]\nThe President. Well, I think so. They have a little bit of a shot. Pretty stiff competition. But I would say they would have a small chance.\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize\nQ. [Inaudible]—win the FIFA Peace Award?\nThe President. Well, it would be an honor.\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\nQ. Will you root for some selection? Will you root for someone?\nThe President. Well, I root for a lot of countries, but in this case, I'll be rooting for the U.S.A. [Laughter]\nQ. [Inaudible]\nThe President. That's great. That's great. We really love it.\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize\nQ. Mr. President, have you been told that you are going to receive the inaugural peace prize today——\nThe President. I have not——\nQ. ——from FIFA?\nThe President. I have not been told. There's a rumor about it, but I have not been told. That would be a great honor, and I'm a big fan of Gianni, as you know.\nQ. What can fans expect——\nQ. Are you hoping to receive that?\nThe President. Excuse me.\nQ. Are you hoping to receive the peace prize?\nThe President. Well, I don't like to say \"hope,\" but it would be a great honor.\n2026 World Cup\nQ. What can fans expect of, like, the World Cup in the U.S.?\nThe President. I think it's going to be fantastic. We've set every record you can set.\nQ. What are you telling people who are worried——\nFédération Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) President Giovanni V. Infantino\nQ. [Inaudible]—friend Gianni—[inaudible]—a word about him?\nThe President. I think he has done a fantastic job.\nThe President's Schedule\nQ. Are you going to be meeting with the President of Mexico today and the——\nThe President. We might. Yes.\nQ. ——Prime Minister of Canada as well?\nThe President. I might. I might do that.\nQ. Will you be discussing immigration and trade with them?\nThe President. Yes, we'll be discussing.\n[At this point, the President and Mr. Infantino posed for photographs.]\nThe President. Thank you, everybody.\n2026 World Cup Draw Event/John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts\nQ. Mr. President, what do you think about the crowd?\nThe President. Oh, look, the new star—[inaudible].\nCongratulations.\nQ. Thank you.\nThe President. You're the new star of television and Fox.\nQ. Thank you. How are you doing, Mr. President?\nThe President. I'm doing very well.\nQ. What do you think about the crowd here?\nThe President. I think the crowd is great, and I think the building is great. We've made a lot of improvements over the last 6 months. Taking—the Kennedy Center was in very bad shape. Now it's getting to be really good. And in 6 months, it's going to be incredible with the improvements we've made.\nQ. The first time for the U.S. to host since the nineties.\nThe President. Right.\nQ. Are you ready for it?\nThe President. I'm ready for it, and they're ready for it. And Gianni, who you know——\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\nThe President. ——has done a fantastic job with FIFA. And we're looking to have—you know, we're set—we have already set records for tickets sales. I don't think there's ever been anything like it in any sport. And so, I want to congratulate you.\nMr. Infantino. Thank you.\nThe President. I don't even have to wait. But major records have been set.\nHow are you?\nQ. Good, how are you, sir?\nThe President. Nice to see you.\nQ. Today it's not football—American football. It's soccer. It's——\nThe President. Right.\nQ. ——the big event of soccer.\nThe President. That's right. That's right.\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\nQ. So can you tell me about this big day today?\nThe President. It's just a big day, and it's a great sport. And it really is coming to America. And never—nobody ever thought a thing like this could happen. And I'm very happy to say that we've already set the alltime record on ticket sales long before the first ball is kicked. Right?\nMr. Infantino. A hundred percent. One hundred percent.\n2026 World Cup Host Cities\nQ. You've had some concerns about crime in American cities, some of the cities that will be hosting. Have they remedied that for you? Are you still considering maybe asking FIFA to move some of those cities?\nThe President. No, I don't want to do that. But I will tell you, if they do have a problem, by the time we get there, we'll take care of that problem. We can solve that problem.\nI've proven that in DC and everywhere else we went, so we'll take care of that very easily. So, if they have a problem, hopefully, they'll let us know that, and we will solve any problem.\nOkay? Thank you.\nQ. Thank you so much.\nMr. Infantino. All right, thank you so much.\nQ. Thank you, Mr. President.\nQ. Thank you. Appreciate it.\nThe President. Congratulations.\n2026 World Cup\nQ. Mr. President, Brazilian television. America will be hosting the World Cup and the Olympics in 2 years. How important it is—[inaudible]?\nThe President. I think very. It's a great honor. I think Gianni is doing a phenomenal job. We've set every record on ticket sales. It's been really fantastic. But Gianni has done an unbelievable job with FIFA.\nThe President's Experience With Soccer\nQ. [Inaudible]\nThe President. He was a great—not only that. I got to see a man name Pelé play—right?—that tells you how old I am—when he was on the Cosmos. Do you remember that a long time ago? And it was quite a treat. That was quite an event. And he was—not only was he playing, he was great. He scored two goals, I think. And so, I was one of the few who got to see Pelé, and I assume he is one of your alltime greats. Right?\nMr. Infantino. Definitely.\nThe President. So I got to see him.\nThe President's Favorite World Cup Competitor\nQ. Do you have some favorite teams for World Cup?\nThe President. Well, I have a favorite. It's the U.S.A. [Laughter] I don't know what their chances are, Gianni, but maybe the U.S.A. is the——\nMr. Infantino. They're getting better and better, actually.\nThe President. I think they'll do well.\nMr. Infantino. They are getting better and better.\nThe President. I think they'll do well.\nThank you very much, everybody.\nQ. Thank you so much.\n2026 World Cup\nQ. Mr. President, World Cup in America just means—[inaudible]. So what do you expect from this World Cup?\nThe President. [Inaudible]—record business and only in the United States, but we're also doing record ticket sales with FIFA. And they've already bought—beat their highest record. And we—you know, this a long time before the first ball is kicked. You've sold more tickets than they've ever done before, and better pricing than they've ever gotten before. It's a tremendous success. And it's an honor. And Gianni has done a phenomenal job with FIFA.\nQ. [Inaudible]—ever?\nThe President. I think so. I think it's going to be—I mean, ideally, you want to see that every year. Every 4 years, it gets bigger and better. I think we have set every record in the book. We're very happy about it.\nThank you.\nThe President's Favorite World Cup Competitor\nQ. [Inaudible]—part of America. Who are you going to support as well?\nThe President. Well, I think I have to support U.S.A. Otherwise, I'd be in trouble. I wouldn't be President for long.\nMr. Infantino. [Inaudible]\nThe President. [Inaudible]—but you have a lot of great teams. You're going to have a lot of great teams.\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\"football,\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\n2026 World Cup Draw/Ticket Sales for World Cup\nQ. How does it feel to be part of this amazing event? And obviously, your being a part of participating in all the—[inaudible]?\nThe President. The President of Mexico is here, and she's doing a very good job. She's a good woman, very, very excellent job. It's an honor, and we're setting every record, and you're helping us set those records.\nMr. Infantino. And we will do it.\nThe President. You know, Mexico and Canada are helping us set those records. But as you know, we have a record in ticket sales already, long before the first ball is kicked, and we're going to do great.\nI think that Gianni—as you know, he's the head, and he has done a fantastic job.\nU.S. Cooperation With Mexico and Canada\nQ. And how is the biggest challenge being three countries?\nThe President. Well, I think that—do you mean for the three countries?\nWell, they've gotten together really well, I mean.\nMr. Infantino. All right.\nThe President. They're getting along very well.\nMr. Infantino. Collaboration is fantastic between the three.\nThe President's Interest in Soccer/2026 World Cup\nQ. And you like soccer?\nThe President. I do. I like it. I like it more and more.\nQ. Yes?\nThe President. I like it. It's growing in this country—very, really—I mean, someday, maybe it's going to be bigger than anything else.\nMr. Infantino. We'll have to become number one.\nThe President. I will say this——\nMr. Infantino. Definitely.\nThe President. ——the ticket sales——\nQ. Definitely will happen.\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\nThe President. Ticket sales are bigger than anything we have ever done in the history of the country, in terms of sports.\nMr. Infantino. For certain.\nQ. And the audience is going to be huge.\nThe President. The audience is going to be tremendous.\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\nThe President. Yes.\nMr. Infantino. Six billion people.\nThe President. [Inaudible]\nQ. Six billion? That's amazing.\nMr. Infantino. Six billion people.\nAnd today, one billion.\nQ. Wow.\nMr. Infantino. [Inaudible]\nQ. Enjoy show time. Thank you so much.\nThe President. [Inaudible]\nQ. Mr. President, how are you? Just a quick—[inaudible].\nQ. This is for Telemundo.\nThe President. How are you?\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\nQ. Hello, Mr. President. How are you? This for Telemundo.\nThe President. How are you? Good.\nQ. How are you?\nThe President. Very good. Thank you.\nQ. How does it feel to have the most important event of sports—that global—in the U.S.?\nThe President. Well, we do. And right at the Kennedy Center. I'm Chairman of the Kennedy Center. And I hear the Kennedy Center is doing a very good job, so it feels great. Really good.\nAnd Telemundo is doing a good job, too. Thank you.\nQ. Thank you.\n2026 World Cup\nQ. What is the significance of hosting the FIFA World Cup this year?\nThe President. It's a—in terms of sports, I would say the ultimate. There is no sport like this. It's the biggest sport in the world. And we are setting every record. You know, our ticket sales have gone and set every—every sport—no matter what it is, we've set the record. So—and every though it's very early, there's no ball being kicked yet, but we've already set a ticket sales record.\nArgentina National Team\nQ. How do you see Argentinean team for this World Cup?\nThe President. Well, I love Argentina. And your President is doing a very good job, as you know. Milei. You know that right? It's make Argentina great again. MAGA.\nQ. And——\nU.S. National Team\nQ. Do you think the States are building a powerful team for next year?\nThe President. Who?\nQ. The States.\nThe President. Oh, yes. Sure. I—you're going to have a lot of powerful teams. Everybody has a lot of powerful teams, but you're going to have a lot of great teams. [Inaudible]\nU.S. Role in Hosting the 2026 World Cup\nQ. Mr. President, what does it mean for you guys to host the World Cup right here in the U.S.?\nThe President. I'm honored to host it. It's a great honor. I mean, it's turned out to be bigger than we thought. We're setting a record for ticket sales, the likes of which no sport has ever seen before.\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\nThe President. But they have a little more speed.\nBut no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\nPopularity of Soccer in Latin America\nQ. Mr. President, a message for the Latin America and soccer fans?\nThe President. Yes, I am. And Latin America is great. And they have great soccer. So, good luck in the matches.\n[A reporter asked a question in Spanish, which was translated by an interpreter as follows.]\nU.S. Visas for World Cup Ticketholders\nQ. Who is going to be in—[inaudible]—about these visas for the—these fans that want to come here to the World Cup?\nThe President. Well, we're going to make it very easy for them. We're working on that right now. We're going to make it very easy. It's going to be a very easy process.\nQ. Okay. Say, hi to Colombia over there.\nThe President. Hello. Is that Colombia?\nQ. Yes.\nThe President. I love Colombia. Hello, Colombia. [Laughter]\nQ. Okay. Okay. Muy bien.\nThe President. So where are you from?\nQ. Paraguay.\nThe President. Oh.\nQ. He's from Paraguay. Yes.\nThe President. Very good. I love it. I—it's a beautiful country. We get along very well with them. We do a little trade deal with them, and they like us. And that's what's happening.\nQ. Panama.\nThe President. Where?\nVery good. I like the canal. [Laughter] That canal is pretty good.\n[A reporter spoke in Spanish; no translation was provided.]\n2026 World Cup\nThe President. What?\nQ. [Inaudible]\nThe President. Well, it's going to be incredible. The event is going to be very good. Just this event alone—it's at the Kennedy Center. I see you have it fixed up perfectly.\nMr. Infantino. It will set the tone.\nThe President. Right? It's beautiful.\nMr. Infantino. It's beautiful.\nThe President. It's a beautiful place.\nHave a good time.\nQ. [Inaudible]\nThe President.\n[A reporter spoke in Spanish; no translation was provided.]\nMr. Infantino. No, gracias. [Inaudible]\nThe President. It's great.\nJohn F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts/Renovation Work\nQ. Mr. President, the U.S. press?\nThe President. Thank you, everybody, very much. It's a great honor. This has been an honor for a lot of reasons. Number one, they've sold more tickets than any event has ever sold already—long before the kickoff.\nAnd number two, we've done a lot of work at the Kennedy Center. It was falling apart, and now it's pretty much back. And we'll get it back within the next 4 or 5 months through construction, and—but you see the way it looks.\nAnd Gianni is just telling me—who's done an incredible job, by the way. He's just telling, you know, how good a job we've done.\nMr. Infantino. That's right.\nThe President. You can look at the walls. The marble was broken. Everything was a mess. And we've really taken the Kennedy Center—a lot of people thought it was going to be ripped down, and we did just the opposite. So we've done a really great renovation job on it. And over the next 3, 4 months, it will be complete. And we're honored to have it here, and it's been—it's been very special.\nWe've set a record on ticket sales, as you probably heard, already, even way before—long before the event itself. And we're working with Canada, and we're working with Mexico. And it's been a really spectacular—so far, it's been spectacular.\nDaniel [Daniel Baldwin, One America News Network], do you have a question?\n2026 World Cup\nQ. What are your expectations? You once said that the FIFA World Cup is an opportunity to put—a once-in-a-lifetime opportunity to put the greatness of the United States on display.\nThe President. Well, I think—\nQ. One billion eyeballs will be watching, Mr. President.\nThe President. Yes, I—think——\nQ. What will they here today?\nThe President. Even today, I understand. I hear that, you know——\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\nThe President. ——I know we're a little late to get in there, but——\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\nThe President. ——that's okay.\nMr. Infantino. They wait.\nThe President. So all my friends, I guess they have to wait. They have no choice, right? [Laughter]\nMr. Infantino. Yes, they wait.\nThe President. But no, the numbers are incredible. I hear today's numbers are——\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\nThe President. ——very big. I hope CNN is covering this.\nQ. One billion eyeballs.\nMr. Infantino. Today, 1 billion eyeballs.\nThe President. Today's numbers are very, very big.\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize/The President's Foreign Policy\nQ. We are covering it. And you're expected to get the FIFA Peace Prize, Mr. President. What would you say to people who say that prize might conflict with your pledge to strike Venezuela?\nThe President. Well, I think the peace prize—I mean, I settled eight wars. I don't know that I'm getting it. I haven't been officially noticed. I've been hearing about a peace prize, and I'm here to represent our country in a different sense. But I can tell you, I did settle eight wars, and we have a ninth coming, but—which nobody has ever done before.\nBut I want to really save lives. I don't need prizes. I need to save lives. And we're saving a lot of lives. And I've saved millions and millions of lives, and that's really what I want to do.\nAnd I also want to run a great country. And the United States right now is the hottest country anywhere in the world. And 1 year ago, it was dead. We had a dead country, and now we have the hottest country anywhere in the world.\nQ. Mr. President, will you——\nThe President's Meeting With President Claudia Sheinbaum Pardo of Mexico and Prime Minister Mark Carney of Canada\nQ. What are you going to discuss with Canada and Mexico, Mr.—what are you going to discuss with the leaders of Canada and Mexico?\nThe President. Well, we're getting—we're going to meet with both. And we're getting along very well. You know, we're getting along very well. I don't know. I think we have a meeting set up for some time after the event.\nQ. Will you discuss trade?\nThe President. Yes, we'll discuss trade. We—get along very well.\nThank you, everybody, very much.\nQ. Will you pardon any other Honduran officials?\nQ. Do you want them to keep trying to indict Ms. James?\n\nNOTE: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. In his remarks, he referred to Trey Yingst, chief foreign correspondent, Fox News Channel; Cristiano Ronaldo, forward for Saudi Pro League club Al-Nass and Portugal's national soccer team; and Lionel Messi, forward for Major League Soccer club Inter Miami and Argentina's national team. A reporter referred to New York State Attorney General Letitia James. The transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\n\nSource URL: https://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/documents/remarks-exchange-with-reporters-prior-the-2026-federation-internationale-des-associations\n\n\n[defendant] DX-3 GovInfo/OFR pre-event transcript excerpt\nSource: GovInfo, DCPD202501162, Office of the Federal Register / National Archives and Records Administration.\nURL: https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/DCPD-202501162/html/DCPD-202501162.htm\nTitle: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\nEvent date: December 5, 2025.\n\nRelevant extracted page text:\n\"Administration of Donald J. Trump, 2025\"\n\"Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw December 5, 2025\"\n\"[The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\"\n\nUnder the section \"The President's Interest in Soccer\":\n\"Q. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\"\n\"The President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\\\"football,\\\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\"\n\"Thank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\"\n\nAdditional relevant extracted page text:\n\"The President's Interest in Soccer\"\n\"Q. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\"\n\"The President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\"\n\"Mr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\"\n\"The President. But they have a little more speed. But no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\"\n\nGovInfo note:\n\"NOTE: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. In his remarks, he referred to Trey Yingst, chief foreign correspondent, Fox News Channel; Cristiano Ronaldo, forward for Saudi Pro League club Al-Nass and Portugal's national soccer team; and Lionel Messi, forward for Major League Soccer club Inter Miami and Argentina's national team. A reporter referred to New York State Attorney General Letitia James. The transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\"\n\nGovInfo content details page also identifies category \"Interviews With the News Media : Exchanges with reporters, Washington, DC,\" subjects including \"Federation Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) World Cup,\" \"John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts,\" and \"Soccer,\" and names including \"Ronaldo, Cristiano\" and \"Messi, Lionel.\"\n\n[defendant] DX-4 PRESMENTION/NEWMENTION terms\n                                         NEWMENTION\n\nScope: These rules shall apply to this contract.\n\nUnderlying: The Underlying for this Contract is words used by <entity> <time period>.\nRevisions to the Underlying made after Expiration will not be accounted for in determining the\nExpiration Value.\n\nSource Agency: The Source Agencies are <source>.\n\nType: The type of Contract is an Event Contract.\n\nIssuance: After the initial Contract, Contract iterations will be listed on an as-needed basis at\nthe discretion of the Exchange and corresponding to the risk management needs of Members.\n\n<entity>: <entity> refers to the speaker, writer, performer, or communicator specified by the\nExchange. This may include (but is not limited to): a specific named individual, multiple\nindividuals specified using AND/OR logic, an individual identified by position or title, a group,\nband, team or collective entity, a specified member or members of a group, an organization,\ncompany, or institutional entity, or any combination of the aforementioned.\n\nWhen <entity> is defined by a position or title, the Contract tracks whoever holds that position\nduring <time period>, even if the individual holding the position changes. When <entity> is a\nspecific named individual, the identity remains consistent throughout. Name changes (e.g.,\nstage names, married names) do not create a new entity. When <entity> is a group or\norganization and the Contract does not specify particular members, any official\ncommunication or statement by any member or designated spokesperson counts. When using\nAND logic, all specified entities must independently say <word> during <time period>. When\nusing OR logic, at least one of the specified entities must say <word> during <time period>.\nThe Exchange may specify additional conditions such as “at least X members of” a group or\n“the majority of” a group.\n\n<source>: <source> refers to a Source Agency or ordered collection of Source Agencies\nspecified by the Exchange at the time of Contract listing, which will be incorporated into the\nSource Agency hierarchy above and used to determine the occurrence of the Underlying.\n<source> may refer to a singular agency, multiple agencies, an agency by distinguishing\ncharacteristics, by category or type (e.g., “official government statistical body,” “primary wire\nservice”), or any combination thereof. When multiple agencies are specified, they may be\napplied in the hierarchical order designated by the Exchange if so specified, with the highest-\nranked available and responsive agency taking precedence for purposes of determining the\nExpiration Value. A lower-ranked agency shall only be consulted if all higher-ranked agencies\nare unavailable, unresponsive, have not reported on the Underlying by the Expiration time, or\nif the Exchange, in its sole discretion, determines that a higher-ranked agency’s reporting is\nincomplete, erroneous, or otherwise insufficient to determine the Expiration Value. If <source>\ndesignates multiple agencies without specifying a hierarchical order, the Exchange shall\nresolve any conflict between reporting agencies at its sole discretion.\n\n<word>: <word> refers to the particular word or phrase potentially to be mentioned by\n<entity>. It may refer to a word being said a minimum number of times. It may also refer to\none of multiple words/phrases, any of which are acceptable (e.g., “Doge/Dogecoin”).\n\f<time period>: <time period> refers to a specific range of time, event or discrete date and\ntime specified by the Exchange. This may be defined by, but is not limited to: a specific event\nor context (e.g., “during the State of the Union address”), exact dates or times, relative time\nmarkers (e.g., “before July 1, 2027,” “in Q1 2026”), event-based periods (e.g., “during any\ncampaign rally in October 2026,” “during the awards ceremony”), and broader intervals (e.g.,\n“Q1–Q2 2027,” “January–March 2026”).\n\nUnless stated otherwise, “Between” is inclusive of both endpoints, while “before” and “after”\nexclude the specified date. <time period> may also refer to “Any” or “None”, to multiple dates\n(even if non-consecutive), or to a singular and discrete date or time.\n\nWhen <time period> refers to a specific event (such as an address, speech, performance, or\nbroadcast), the Exchange may specify what is included, including whether it includes both live\nand pre-recorded segments (including whether advertisements are included). Where a\ntimezone is not specified, ET is assumed.\n\n\nPayout Criterion: The Payout Criterion for the Contract encompasses the Expiration Values that\n<word> is said by <entity> <time period>.\n\n\nThe word must appear as a distinct, standalone unit, not buried inside another word. Plural\nand possessive noun forms count. Other grammatical changes (tense, conjugation, derivation)\ndo not. If <word> appears separated from other words by a space or hyphen or in a\ncompound form with a space or hyphen, it counts. If <word> is fused into a single\nunhyphenated word, it does not count.\n\nIf <time period> refers to an event and that event is cancelled, and the market contains a\nstrike stating “Event does not qualify/occur”, such a strike shall resolve “Yes” and all others\n“No”. If <time period> refers to an event and that event is cancelled but such strikes are NOT\nlisted, the Contracts will resolve to the last fair price determined at the discretion of the\nExchange. If the event is postponed, and such a postponement is announced by the end of the\nfollowing calendar day to be rescheduled to a time within 14 calendar days, the markets shall\nremain open. If the event captured in <time period> is a live-stream or broadcast, the\nExchange may keep the market open for 24 hours for the release of an official recording.\nFurther granular details on conditions for these Contracts is available below.\n\nAdditional clarification(s):\n\n     Possessive noun forms of <word>, plurals, and possessive plural noun forms are\n     INCLUDED:\n          <word> is “Immigrant” → “Immigrants” counts\n          <word> is “Egg” → “eggs’ shells” counts\n          <word> is “Russia” → “Russia’s” counts, “Russian” does not\n     If <word> exists only in adjective form, no plural form exists:\n          <word> is “Economic” → “Economics” does not count (“Economic” is an adjective\n          for which “Economics” is not a plural)\n     Plural nouns occurring within proper nouns and noun phrases are included:\n          <word> is “Cat” → “Cats the musical” counts\n\f    Grammatical variations beyond plurals/possessives are NOT included:\n         <word> is “Immigrant” → “Immigration” does NOT count\n         <word> is “Run” → “Running” or “Ran” do NOT count\n    When <word> specifies a plural form, the singular does NOT count:\n         <word> is “Veterans” → “Veteran” does NOT count\n    Words that are spelled the same as the plural form of <word> (if such exists) but are\n    themselves not a plural noun are included:\n         <word> is “Wind” → “Winds up the clock” counts\n         <word> is “Border” → “The United States has strong borders” counts\n    Open compounds (words separated by spaces) count:\n         <word> is “fire” → “fire station” counts\n         <word> is “couch” → “couch potato” counts\n    Hyphenated compounds (words connected by hyphens) count:\n         <word> is “Palestine” → “pro-Palestine” counts\n         <word> is “fat” → “non-fat” counts\n    Closed compounds (single word, no spaces/hyphens) do not count:\n         <word> is “fire” → “wildfire” does not count\n         <word> is “fire” → “firefighter” does not count\n    Multi-word <word> in larger constructions: When <word> is a multi-word phrase\n    appearing within a hyphenated construction, it counts only if <word> appears as a\n    complete, unmodified element:\n         <word> is “New York” → “New York-based” counts (complete element)\n    Portmanteaus (words blended from two words where parts of each are combined) are\n    NOT included unless the portmanteau clearly contains <word> as a distinct, unaltered\n    element:\n         <word> is “MAGA” → “MAGA-nificent” counts (MAGA appears as distinct element)\n         <word> is “magnificent” → “MAGA-nificent” does NOT count (portmanteau blend)\n\nDictionary determination: Both the Merriam-Webster Dictionary (available online) AND the\nOxford English Dictionary shall be used to determine compound type and/or conventional\nspelling patterns. Inclusion in either dictionary as an open or hyphenated compound shall\nsatisfy the Payout Criterion. If neither provides clarity (or the word is not included),\ndetermination is based on whether written as single unit (closed/doesn’t count) vs. spaces or\nhyphens (open or hyphenated/counts) and/or context and previous usage.\n\nPHONETIC EQUIVALENCIES\n\n    Homophones (same sound, different spelling) do not count:\n        <word> is “write” → “right” does not count\n    Homonyms and homographs (same spelling) COUNT regardless of meaning or\n    pronunciation:\n        <word> is “bass” → both “bass guitar” and “bass fishing” count\n    Proper and common nouns are treated identically:\n        <word> is “Apple” → both “Apple Inc.” and “apple” (fruit) count\n        <word> is “Will” → both “Will Smith” and “I will go” count\n    Minor unintentional mispronunciations COUNT if context makes intent clear:\n        <word> is “Mamdani” → “Mandani” counts\n    Severe mispronunciations that make <word> unrecognizable do NOT count.\n    Trademarked spellings do not count, even when pronounced identically, unless the word\n\fitself is the same:\n      <word> is “lift” → “Lyft” (pronounced “lift”) does not count\n      <word> is “uber” → “Uber” counts\nWords with non-standard transliteration to English count within reason, provided they are\nphonetically equivalent:\n      <word> is “Zelensky” → any of “Zelenski,” “Zelenskii,” “Zelensky,” or “Zelenskiy”\n      count if pronounced equivalently\nContractions do not count for their constituent words unless otherwise explicitly specified\nby the Exchange:\n      <word> is “not” → “won’t,” “can’t,” “don’t,” “isn’t” do not count\nNumbers spoken as words COUNT, when spoken exactly (not part of a larger number):\n      <word> is “five” → saying “five” or reading “$5” aloud as “five dollars” counts,\n      saying “five hundred” does NOT count\n      <word> is “410” → “four hundred ten”, “four one zero” or “four ten” counts\nOrdinals COUNT when <word> is written numerically OR a phrase that includes a\nnumber:\n      <word> is “January 6” → “January 6th” counts\n      <word> is “3” (written numerically) → “3rd” (spoken as “third”) counts\n      <word> is “Eight War” → “8 Wars” and “Eighth War” will count\nCardinal and ordinal number words are distinct:\n      <word> is “one” → “first” does NOT count\n      <word> is “first” → “one” does NOT count\nAcronyms and abbreviations count when pronunciation or letter-by-letter spelling\nmatches <word>:\n      <word> is “NASA” → “NASA” (pronounced “NAH-suh”) counts\n      <word> is “NASA” → “N-A-S-A” (spelled out) counts\nAcronyms and abbreviations count as <word> when pronounced as the full word:\n      <word> is “Doctor” → “Dr.” (pronounced “Doctor”) counts\nExpanded forms of acronyms do NOT count:\n      <word> is “AI” → “artificial intelligence” does not count\nWords in foreign languages do NOT count unless they are perfect cognates with an\nEnglish word:\n      <word> is “fire” → “fuego” (Spanish) does NOT count\nEnglish words within foreign sentences count:\n      <word> is “policy” → “Nuestra policy es clara” counts\n<word> in organization/company names counts:\n      <word> is “Securities” → “Bank of America Securities” counts\nWords in URLs, emails, handles, and hashtags (exclusive of domain structure, email\nprovider or symbols) are treated as compounds when spoken as complete words, with the\ntype of compound subject to aforementioned rules:\n      <word> is “fire” → “firestation.com” pronounced “fire station dot com” counts\n      <word> is “fire” → “wildfire.com” pronounced “wildfire dot com” does NOT count\n      <word> is “apple” → “apple.com” pronounced “apple dot com” does count\n      When presented in URL, email, handle, or hashtag form, <word> shall be treated as\n      a compound, not a multi-word word\nSung, rapped, or poetic words COUNT if phonetically recognizable:\n      <word> is “money” → “moneyyy” (extended in rap) counts\n      Extreme distortion making <word> unrecognizable does NOT count.\nPhonetic alphabet spelling (“Foxtrot India Romeo Echo” for “FIRE”) does NOT count.\n\fCANCELLATIONS AND DELAYS\n\n   The Exchange may list an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike for any Contract. If listed,\n   such a strike refers to the structural conditions of the market, and is NOT adjudicated as a\n   <word> needing to be said by or validated by having been said by <entity>. If listed, this\n   strike resolves to “Yes” whenever the event fails to occur or qualify under the Payout\n   Criterion, or any other circumstance prevents normal resolution.\n   If no such strike is listed, and <time period> refers to a specific event, the following rules\n   apply if the event is cancelled, postponed, rescheduled, or materially altered (including\n   being closed to press) such that no video is released within one calendar day of the\n   original start time of the event:\n         If the event is cancelled, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price determined in\n         the sole discretion of the Exchange.\n         If the event is postponed or rescheduled, the outcome depends on whether a new\n         date is publicly announced within one calendar day (i.e. if the event was scheduled\n         to begin on Monday, any time up to 11:59PM on Tuesday falls within this period) of\n         the originally scheduled start time:\n               If no new date is announced within one calendar day, the Contract will resolve\n               to the last fair price determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\n               If a new date is announced within one calendar day, the outcome depends on\n               when the rescheduled event is set to occur:\n                     If the rescheduled date falls within fourteen (14) calendar days of the\n                     originally scheduled date, the Contract shall remain open and <word>\n                     stated during the rescheduled event will count.\n                           The fourteen-day window begins at 12:00 AM ET on the originally\n                           scheduled date and ends at 11:59 PM ET fourteen days later, unless\n                           an alternate timezone is explicitly specified.\n                           Example: <time period> is “during the State of the Union on January\n                           15, 2026” rescheduled to January 20, 2026 → words spoken during\n                           the rescheduled address count.\n                     If the rescheduled date falls more than fourteen (14) calendar days after\n                     the originally scheduled date, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price\n                     determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\n         Any Contract that cannot be resolved through the Source Agency hierarchy will\n         instead be settled at the Last Fair Price. The Exchange will disclose the methodology\n         used to determine the Last Fair Price (e.g., Last Traded Price, Time-Weighted\n         Average Price) at the time of Issuance.\n         If an event begins but is interrupted, abbreviated, or ends prematurely, words\n         stated by <entity> during the portion of the event that did occur will count and the\n         market will otherwise resolve.\n   If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window but the venue, format, or medium\n   changes (e.g., moved to a different location, changed from in-person to virtual (with the\n   exception of being closed to press)), words stated during the event will count.\n   Special condition: Across both cases, whether an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike is\n   listed or not, if the event specified as or in <time period> is a live-stream or broadcast (or\n   relayed as such) but the live stream/broadcast does not occur, the Exchange will instead\n   use an officially released recording as the Underlying, and may delay resolution by up to\n   one calendar day to allow for the release of such a recording.\n\f          If partial snippets are released, Contracts on words that do not appear will be\n          resolved to last fair price, and Contracts on those that do will be resolved to “Yes”.\n          If no recording is released, the relevant outcomes triggered by the\n          presence/absence of an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike shall occur as outlined\n          above.\n\nTECHNICAL DETAILS (UNLESS OTHERWISE SPECIFIED)\n\n     When <time period> refers to a specific event, pre-recorded content broadcast,\n     streamed, or published as part of that event is included if presented as part of the official\n     presentation.\n          Example: <time period> is “during the concert” with pre-recorded video interlude\n          where entity speaks → words from interlude count\n          Example: <time period> is “during the television appearance” with pre-taped\n          segment aired during broadcast → words from segment count\n     Behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are NOT\n     included unless officially broadcast or published as part of <time period>.\n     Subtitles and captions that display <word> on screen but are not spoken aloud by\n     <entity> do NOT count.\n     Sign language interpretation or usage by entity does NOT count as saying <word> unless\n     the Contract explicitly specifies that sign language counts.\n     Text that entity displays on screen (presentation slides, teleprompter visible to audience,\n     signatures) does NOT count unless entity reads it aloud.\n     Content generated by AI, deepfakes, or synthetic voice technology impersonating entity\n     does NOT count unless the synthetic content is officially commissioned, authorized, or\n     published by entity, OR the Contract explicitly specifies that AI-generated content counts.\n     If <word> is muted due to technical failure or censorship it shall not count unless\n     corroborating contextual evidence (including surrounding speech, or an official\n     uncensored recording or transcript) confirms that <entity> specifically uttered <word>\n     during the muted period.\n\nMinimum Tick: The Minimum Tick size for the Contract shall be $0.01.\n\nPosition Accountability Level: The Position Accountability Level for the Contract shall be\n$25,000 per strike, per Member.\n\nLast Trading Date: The Last Trading Date of the Contract will be the Expiration Date. The Last\nTrading Time will be the Expiration time.\n\nSettlement Date: The Settlement Date of the Contract shall be no later than the day after the\nExpiration Date, unless the Market Outcome is under review pursuant to Rule 7.1.\n\nExpiration Date: When <time period> refers to a specific event: The latest Expiration Date of\nthe Contract shall be fourteen (14) calendar days after the originally scheduled date of the\nevent. If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window, expiration will be moved to an\nearlier date and time in accordance with Rule 7.2. When <time period> is defined by specific\ndates: The latest Expiration Date of the Contract shall be two weeks after the end of <time\nperiod>. If an event described in the Payout Criterion occurs and a consensus has been\nreached on all terms, then expiration will be moved to an earlier date and time in accordance\nwith Rule 7.2.\n\fExpiration time: The Expiration time of the Contract shall be 10:00 AM ET.\n\nSettlement Value: The Settlement Value for this Contract is $1.00.\n\nExpiration Value: The Expiration Value is the value of the Underlying as documented by the\nSource Agency on the Expiration Date at the Expiration time.\n\nContingencies: Before Settlement, Kalshi may, at its sole discretion, initiate the Market\nOutcome Review Process pursuant to Rule 7.1 of the Rulebook. If an Expiration Value cannot\nbe determined on the Expiration Date, Kalshi has the right to determine payouts pursuant to\nRule 7.1 in the Rulebook.\n\f\n\n[defendant] DX-5 Formal draw archive note\nSource checked: Roll Call / Factba.se archive\n\nArchive title: Remarks: Donald Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing in Washington - December 5, 2025\n\nArchive URL: https://rollcall.com/factbase/trump/transcript/donald-trump-remarks-fifa-world-cup-drawing-december-5-2025/\n\nWhat this file establishes:\n\nThere is a separate archived transcript page for Trump's formal attendance remarks at the draw.\n\nWhat this file does not establish:\n\nThis session could not retrieve the full transcript text from that archive.  The page is password-protected.  This example therefore does not claim, from local files alone, whether the formal program transcript does or does not contain the word \"Ronaldo.\"\n\nWhy this matters:\n\nThe complaint does not need to prove that the formal program omitted the strike.  It needs to show that Trump said \"Ronaldo\" in event-linked remarks and that the market boundary reasonably includes those remarks.  The formal archive remains relevant because it marks the distinction between the pre-event reporter exchange and the formal program.\n\n\n[defendant] DX-6 Formal Roll Call/Factba.se transcript extraction\nSource: Roll Call / Factba.se\nURL: https://rollcall.com/factbase/trump/transcript/donald-trump-remarks-fifa-world-cup-drawing-december-5-2025/\nCaptured page title: Remarks: Donald Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing in Washington - December 5, 2025\n\nRendered page metadata excerpt:\nTopics: Sport; Sport > Competition Discipline > Soccer; Lifestyle and Leisure > Leisure > Game.\nEntities listed: bowl; deal; Donald J. Trump; FIFA World Cup; Mark Carney; place; President; trophy; United States; way.\nSpeakers listed: Gianni Infantino, Donald Trump, Mark Carney, Claudia Sheinbaum.\nSpeaker statistics excerpt: Donald Trump said 25 sentences of a total of 141 sentences; Donald Trump said 274 words of a total of 1009 words; Donald Trump talked 92 seconds of a total of 484 seconds.\n\nFormal transcript excerpt at start of draw:\nMark Carney, 00:00:00-00:00:02: Thank you, my friend.\nGianni Infantino, 00:00:50-00:01:22: So this is the World Cup trophy. This is the official bowl for the World Cup and we are now going to do the draw, ladies and gentlemen. But before that, as is customary, there is always a question that the moderator asks the draw assistant. So I would like to start with Mr. Carney. How big a deal is it to co-host the World Cup for Canada?\n\nFormal transcript excerpt of Trump's soccer answer:\nDonald Trump, 00:03:14-00:03:32: Well, for years, Gianni, they've thought soccer or football would be so big, so fast. And I remember, I shouldn't say this because it was a long time ago, but I remember watching Pele play on a team called the Cosmos, Pele, who was fantastic, as you know. I assume one of the greats.\n\nText-extraction/search notes:\nLocal Python urllib retrieval of the page returned HTTP 200 for the source URL and extracted approximately 175,864 characters of page text with Python html.parser. Case-sensitive searches in the extracted page text returned no occurrence of \"Ronaldo\" and no occurrence of \"Messi\". The same terms were not found using the browser page find function on the rendered page.\n\n[plaintiff] PX-R1 Defendant formal transcript extraction for limited rebuttal use\nSource: Roll Call / Factba.se\nURL: https://rollcall.com/factbase/trump/transcript/donald-trump-remarks-fifa-world-cup-drawing-december-5-2025/\nCaptured page title: Remarks: Donald Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing in Washington - December 5, 2025\n\nRendered page metadata excerpt:\nTopics: Sport; Sport > Competition Discipline > Soccer; Lifestyle and Leisure > Leisure > Game.\nEntities listed: bowl; deal; Donald J. Trump; FIFA World Cup; Mark Carney; place; President; trophy; United States; way.\nSpeakers listed: Gianni Infantino, Donald Trump, Mark Carney, Claudia Sheinbaum.\nSpeaker statistics excerpt: Donald Trump said 25 sentences of a total of 141 sentences; Donald Trump said 274 words of a total of 1009 words; Donald Trump talked 92 seconds of a total of 484 seconds.\n\nFormal transcript excerpt at start of draw:\nMark Carney, 00:00:00-00:00:02: Thank you, my friend.\nGianni Infantino, 00:00:50-00:01:22: So this is the World Cup trophy. This is the official bowl for the World Cup and we are now going to do the draw, ladies and gentlemen. But before that, as is customary, there is always a question that the moderator asks the draw assistant. So I would like to start with Mr. Carney. How big a deal is it to co-host the World Cup for Canada?\n\nFormal transcript excerpt of Trump's soccer answer:\nDonald Trump, 00:03:14-00:03:32: Well, for years, Gianni, they've thought soccer or football would be so big, so fast. And I remember, I shouldn't say this because it was a long time ago, but I remember watching Pele play on a team called the Cosmos, Pele, who was fantastic, as you know. I assume one of the greats.\n\nText-extraction/search notes:\nLocal Python urllib retrieval of the page returned HTTP 200 for the source URL and extracted approximately 175,864 characters of page text with Python html.parser. Case-sensitive searches in the extracted page text returned no occurrence of \"Ronaldo\" and no occurrence of \"Messi\". The same terms were not found using the browser page find function on the rendered page.\n\nSubmitted evidence:\n[plaintiff arguments] GovInfo DCPD202501162 transcript excerpt and metadata (ev_3fc783920414_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-3fc783920414)\nSource: https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/DCPD-202501162/html/DCPD-202501162.htm\nSHA-256: `3fc783920414399098d86210070dd9fe83c14fe1dbded1a56a554f8f4b3448f2`\nBytes: 2641\nRelevance: Official government transcript source corroborating that Trump spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center before the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw and said the strike word Ronaldo in World-Cup-related remarks.\n\n[defendant arguments] Roll Call/Factba.se formal FIFA World Cup Drawing transcript extraction (ev_fbb53e87ccb3_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-fbb53e87ccb3)\nSource: https://rollcall.com/factbase/trump/transcript/donald-trump-remarks-fifa-world-cup-drawing-december-5-2025/\nSHA-256: `fbb53e87ccb3f4381fc2bdc06ac2f2a1ea3848aadde56122b22d34dfbdf4533b`\nBytes: 2032\nRelevance: Formal drawing-program transcript evidence showing a separate formal Draw source from the pre-event reporter exchange; the extracted page text contains no occurrence of Ronaldo or Messi, supporting defendant's event-boundary argument.\n\nTechnical reports:\n[plaintiff] Plaintiff source and adverse-search ledger\nChecked the visible case packet and then searched official/source-specific repositories. GovInfo DCPD202501162 was opened and preserved as submitted evidence; it corroborates the packet transcript, source metadata, location, event date, and Ronaldo passages. The Roll Call/Factba.se formal drawing page rendered despite the packet's password-protection note; browser find searches for 'Ronaldo,' 'Cristiano,' and 'Messi' returned no matches. Plaintiff therefore treats the formal-program transcript as an adverse boundary check, not as proof of a formal-stage mention. The remaining dispute is contractual scope: whether the market clearly excluded public event-linked venue remarks immediately before the formal program.\n\n[defendant] Defense source-check ledger\nDefendant searched for the formal Roll Call/Factba.se transcript identified by the case packet, opened the rendered Roll Call page, and fetched it locally with Python urllib. The fetch returned HTTP 200 for the formal FIFA World Cup Drawing transcript page. Text extraction produced approximately 175,864 characters; searches for \"Ronaldo\" and \"Messi\" returned no occurrences. The retrieval also captured formal-program excerpts, including Infantino's statement that \"we are now going to do the draw\" and Trump's formal soccer answer mentioning Pele rather than Ronaldo. The focused extraction was submitted and accepted as ev_fbb53e87ccb3_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-fbb53e87ccb3.\n\nCall submit_council_vote with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated.\nKeep the rationale brief: no more than three sentences.\n\nCouncil API instructions:\nYou are a council member. Decide the proposition from the admitted record.\nYou may examine admitted evidence through read-only tools when exact bytes, metadata, or exhibit contents matter.\nDo not search the web, introduce new facts, create new evidence, or upload evidence.\nWhen ready, call submit_council_vote exactly once with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated and a concise rationale.\n","state":"ready","status":"ready","tools":[{"description":"Return the current visible arbitration record for this council member.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{},"type":"object"},"name":"get_case","read_only":true},{"description":"List visible immutable record evidence.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{},"type":"object"},"name":"list_evidence","read_only":true},{"description":"Return metadata and read limits for one visible evidence item.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"evidence_id":{"type":"string"}},"required":["evidence_id"],"type":"object"},"name":"stat_evidence","read_only":true},{"description":"Read a bounded byte range from one visible evidence item as base64.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"evidence_id":{"type":"string"},"length":{"minimum":1,"type":"integer"},"offset":{"minimum":0,"type":"integer"}},"required":["evidence_id","offset","length"],"type":"object"},"name":"read_evidence_range","read_only":true},{"description":"Submit one council vote for the current deliberation opportunity.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"rationale":{"type":"string"},"vote":{"enum":["demonstrated","not_demonstrated"],"type":"string"}},"required":["vote","rationale"],"type":"object"},"name":"submit_council_vote","read_only":false}],"turn":{"attempts_max":3,"attempts_remaining":3,"completed":false,"deadline":"2026-06-29T19:58:02.156322961Z","deliberation_round":1,"member_id":"C2","opportunity_id":"deliberation:1:C2","phase":"deliberation","remaining_ms":887183,"role_id":"council","turn_number":10},"wait":{"reason":"ready","state_version":12,"version":15}},"isError":false},"server":"aar","tool":"wait_for_opportunity"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1782762194987}}
{"type":"turn_end","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Okay, let's see. The user is council member C2 for the AAR case arb-ex03-20260629192557. They need to use the Pi MCP proxy tool to call AAR tools, which are prefixed with 'aar_'. The first step is to call mcp with tool aar_wait_for_opportunity and args \"{}\".\n\nSo I should trigger that initial call. Let me check the instructions again. The mcp tool requires exactly a tool string and an args string. So for the first call, it's {\"tool\": \"aar_wait_for_opportunity\", \"args\": \"{}\"}.\n\nThen, depending on the response, if it's \"state: waiting\", I need to call again with after_version from the response. If ready, read the prompt, turn, limits, etc. Then review the case evidence using other tools like aar_get_case, aar_list_evidence, etc. Once ready, submit the vote.\n\nBut first, I need to execute the initial wait_for_opportunity call. Let me structure the mcp call properly. The mcp function should have the tool and args as specified. Since the user said \"First call mcp with {'tool':'aar_wait_for_opportunity','args':'{}'}\", so the arguments for the mcp function should be:\n\n{\"tool\": \"aar_wait_for_opportunity\", \"args\": \"{}\"}\n\nYes. Because when using the mcp tool, the parameters are tool and args as a string. So in the tool call, it's \"mcp\" function, and the arguments are tool: \"aar_wait_for_opportunity\", args: \"{}\".\n\nWait, looking at the mcp function parameters. The mcp function's parameters include \"tool\" as a string, and \"args\" as a string. So in the tool call for mcp, I need to pass those. So:\n\nThe mcp call would have tool set to \"aar_wait_for_opportunity\" and args set to \"{}\" as a string.\n\nYes. So the JSON for the mcp function call would be:\n\n{\n  \"tool\": \"aar_wait_for_opportunity\",\n  \"args\": \"{}\"\n}\n\nSo the tool call should be structured like that. Let's confirm the mcp parameters: the mcp function has properties tool (string), args (string), etc. So yes, when calling mcp, set tool and args accordingly.\n\nSo first step: call mcp with tool aar_wait_for_opportunity and args \"{}\".\n\nSo the tool invocation would be:\n\n<tools>\n{\"name\": \"mcp\", \"arguments\": {\"tool\": \"aar_wait_for_opportunity\", \"args\": \"{}\"}}\n</tools>\n\nThat's the first step. Let's do that. Then process the response. Depending on the response, proceed.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_b9f90c55f2824ea0be4354","name":"mcp","arguments":{"tool":"aar_wait_for_opportunity","args":"{}"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"qwen/qwen3-next-80b-a3b-thinking","usage":{"input":2405,"output":609,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":3014,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1782762190625,"responseId":"gen-1782762190-AHlISazOUS9roxn4UTCM","responseModel":"qwen/qwen3-next-80b-a3b-thinking-2509"},"toolResults":[{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_b9f90c55f2824ea0be4354","toolName":"mcp","content":[{"type":"text","text":"ok: true\nstatus: ready\nstate: ready\nmessage: An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\nafter_version: 15\nafter_opportunity_id: deliberation:1:C2\nmember_id: C2\ncase_id: arb-ex03-20260629192557\nwait_reason: ready\nphase: deliberation\nopportunity_id: deliberation:1:C2\nremaining_ms: 887183\nattempts_remaining: 3\njson: {\"after_opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C2\",\"after_version\":15,\"case_id\":\"arb-ex03-20260629192557\",\"limits\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"max_evidence_read_bytes\":65536,\"max_evidence_read_bytes_per_opportunity\":524288,\"max_evidence_reads_per_opportunity\":32,\"max_response_bytes\":131072,\"remaining_evidence_read_bytes_for_opportunity\":524288,\"remaining_evidence_reads_for_opportunity\":32},\"member_id\":\"C2\",\"message\":\"An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\",\"ok\":true,\"prompt\":\"Role: council member\\nMember ID: C2\\nDeliberation round: 1\\nProposition: For the Kalshi market \\\"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\\", the strike \\\"Ronaldo\\\" should resolve Yes because Trump said \\\"Ronaldo\\\" in public remarks at the World Cup Draw venue immediately before the formal program, and the market wording plus the governing mention-market terms did not clearly exclude those event-linked remarks.\\nStandard of evidence: Preponderance of the evidence.\\nPersona:\\nYou are a careful juror and council member.\\n\\nEvaluate the record faithfully. Decide only from the evidence, the stated rules, and the applicable burden of proof. Do not favor either side, fill gaps with speculation, or ignore uncertainty.\\n\\nGive weight to reliable sources, direct evidence, consistent reasoning, and clear admissions. Discount unsupported claims, rhetorical force, irrelevant facts, and conclusions that exceed the record.\\n\\nWhen the evidence supports one answer, state it plainly. When the evidence is incomplete or balanced, say so. Be concise, honest, and exact.\\n\\nRecord:\\nOpenings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, this case is not mainly about whether the syllables were spoken. The case-packet transcript says they were. The real dispute is the market boundary: when Kalshi asked what Trump would say \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw,\\\" did that phrase clearly exclude his public, event-linked remarks at the World Cup Draw venue immediately before the formal program? On this record, it did not.\\n\\nThe market page fixes the contract at issue: the public title was \\\"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\\"; the contract family was PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION; the strike was \\\"Ronaldo\\\"; Kalshi challenged the resolution as No; and the requested resolution is Yes. That means the council's task is to apply the mention-market terms to that title and strike, not to import a narrower limitation that the market did not plainly announce.\\n\\nThe reporter-exchange packet is direct evidence on the word and setting. It is titled as remarks in an exchange with reporters prior to the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw, dated December 5, 2025. It places the President at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts, speaking with FIFA President Gianni Infantino and reporters in a sequence repeatedly labeled around the 2026 World Cup and the Draw. In that exchange, in a soccer discussion, Trump says he met Ronaldo, praises him, and uses \\\"Ronaldo\\\" as a distinct standalone word. Under the mention rules, a distinct standalone appearance of the strike is the kind of use that counts if it falls within the time period.\\n\\nThe terms matter because they do not say that an event market is limited only to scripted remarks from a formal stage segment. They define a time period as potentially an event or context, and they give the Exchange power to specify what is included when a time period refers to a specific event. They also distinguish official/public event content from behind-the-scenes, rehearsals, and unofficial recordings. That distinction helps plaintiff: the packet is not a rumor, rehearsal, private soundcheck, or leaked recording. It is a sourced public transcript of remarks at the event venue, immediately tied to the Draw. If Kalshi meant \\\"only the formal televised draw program after doors close\\\" or \\\"only remarks in the separate formal archive,\\\" it needed to say so clearly.\\n\\nI also want to be candid about what the packet does not yet prove. The formal-draw archive note says a separate archived transcript page exists for Trump's formal attendance remarks, but that the session could not retrieve the full text because the page was password-protected. So, at opening, plaintiff is not asking you to infer that the formal program itself contained \\\"Ronaldo.\\\" Nor does plaintiff need that inference. The Yes theory is that the qualifying period reasonably includes the public pre-program reporter exchange that was part of Trump's World Cup Draw appearance. The formal archive is relevant because it marks defendant's likely narrower boundary; it does not resolve the boundary in defendant's favor.\\n\\nProvenance and weight also favor treating the packet seriously at this stage. The market and terms files are system case-packet records. The reporter exchange includes a source URL to a public presidential transcript source and notes a corrected transcript date, while also acknowledging that some audio could not be verified because the audio was incomplete. That caveat may affect inaudible portions, but it does not erase the visible, contextual Ronaldo passage. Later, when evidence admission opens, the parties should preserve the official transcript source, any govinfo or Presidency Project copy, the market page capture, and any accessible formal-program transcript or video. The adverse check should ask whether the formal program omits the word, but omission there would matter only if the council first accepts the defense's artificially narrow reading of \\\"during.\\\"\\n\\nThe plaintiff's burden is preponderance. The record already points to a straightforward path to Yes: Trump, the specified entity, said the specified strike as a standalone word in public remarks linked to and immediately preceding the World Cup Draw at the venue; the market title and governing terms did not clearly exclude that event-linked exchange. On a fair reading of the contract the trader saw, the challenged No resolution should give way to Yes.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the defense opening is simple: this case is not won by proving that the word \\\"Ronaldo\\\" appears somewhere in a public transcript. The plaintiff must prove, by a preponderance, that the word was said during the market's specified event: the FIFA World Cup Draw.\\n\\nThe current packet leaves that critical link unproven. The market page does not say \\\"while Trump was at the venue,\\\" \\\"during a World Cup press availability,\\\" or \\\"during any remarks connected to the Draw.\\\" It says: \\\"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\\" The challenged resolution was No. The requested Yes theory therefore needs more than event-adjacent context; it needs a boundary showing that the reporter exchange was part of the Draw period the market asked traders to price.\\n\\nThe plaintiff's own best transcript cuts against that boundary. The case-packet file is titled \\\"Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw.\\\" It says the President's remarks were joined in progress, and the source note says portions could not be verified because the audio was incomplete. It places Trump at the Kennedy Center and includes World Cup topics, and yes, it contains \\\"Ronaldo\\\" as a standalone word in a soccer exchange. But its title and structure identify those remarks as an exchange with reporters prior to the Draw, not the formal Draw itself.\\n\\nThe terms do not rescue plaintiff from that distinction. They define a mention market around words used by the entity during the time period. A time period may be a specific event, and when it is a specific event, the Exchange may specify what is included. The technical details also distinguish official presentation content from behind-the-scenes, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings unless those are officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. Those provisions do not mean every public, nearby, event-related conversation becomes part of the event. They make the event boundary the central question.\\n\\nThe formal-draw archive note reinforces why the distinction matters. It reports that there is a separate archived transcript page for Trump's formal attendance remarks at the FIFA World Cup Drawing, but that the full text was not retrieved because the page was password-protected. That note does not prove the formal program omitted Ronaldo. It also does not prove the formal program included it. What it does show, at opening, is that the record itself separates the pre-event reporter exchange from the formal drawing remarks.\\n\\nSo the defense will focus the council on proof of inclusion, not mere association. If later phases produce a market page provision, official broadcast record, program transcript, video metadata, or source-agency material showing that the red-carpet reporter exchange was officially part of the FIFA World Cup Draw presentation for this market, the council can weigh that. If the later evidence instead shows a formal program with a separate pre-program press availability, then the correct result is No even though the word was spoken nearby.\\n\\nOn this opening record, plaintiff has shown a Ronaldo mention in remarks prior to the event. Plaintiff has not shown that those remarks occurred during the market event. The defense position is that Kalshi's No resolution follows the market wording and the mention-market terms unless plaintiff supplies that missing boundary proof.\\n\\nArguments:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the merits question is whether the contract clearly limited “during the FIFA World Cup Draw” to only the formal staged ceremony. Plaintiff submits that it did not, and the record now proves the Yes result by a preponderance.\\n\\nFirst, the market itself is broad. PX-1 identifies the public question as “What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?”, contract family PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION, strike “Ronaldo,” challenged resolution No, and requested resolution Yes. The market page does not say “during the formal televised ceremony,” “on the main stage only,” or “excluding public remarks immediately before the program at the venue.” That absence matters because Kalshi drafted the boundary traders had to price.\\n\\nSecond, the word was said. PX-2, the case-packet transcript, and PX-5, the GovInfo/OFR source excerpt, both show Trump used “Ronaldo” as a standalone word in soccer-related remarks. PX-5 is especially useful on provenance: it is the GovInfo Compilation of Presidential Documents source, published by the Office of the Federal Register/NARA, for DCPD202501162. It identifies the same event date, title, and source note, and it places the remarks at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center. In the relevant passage, Trump says he met Ronaldo, then says Ronaldo is great; later, when asked whether he played soccer or football, Trump says he was not Ronaldo or Messi. Either use satisfies the mention rule if the remarks fall within the market’s time period.\\n\\nThird, the remarks are event-linked in the way the market title reasonably covers. PX-2 and PX-5 are not private gossip, rehearsal, or an unofficial leak. They are public presidential remarks at the World Cup Draw venue, with FIFA President Infantino present, repeatedly discussing the Draw, the World Cup, ticket sales, the Kennedy Center, the audience, and the imminent program. The transcript itself includes headings such as “2026 World Cup Draw Event,” “2026 World Cup Draw Event/John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts,” and “2026 World Cup Draw/Ticket Sales for World Cup.” Trump and Infantino even discuss being a little late to “get in there” and the audience waiting. That sequence is not a random earlier interview; it is part of the public event appearance immediately surrounding the Draw.\\n\\nFourth, PX-3’s terms do not impose defendant’s formal-only line. They say the underlying is words used by the entity during the specified time period; a time period may be an event or context; and, when a time period refers to a specific event, the Exchange may specify what is included. They also say official/published content presented as part of the official presentation can count, while behind-the-scenes, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings do not count unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. Those exclusions show what this is not. The transcript is an official published record of public remarks at the event venue, not a hidden backstage clip. Nothing in PX-1 or PX-3 clearly tells traders that public, event-linked venue remarks immediately before the formal program are out.\\n\\nDefendant’s best point is PX-4 and the formal Roll Call/Factba.se page: there is a separate formal-drawing transcript, and my search found no “Ronaldo” there. Plaintiff does not hide that. But that adverse point proves only that the narrower formal-program source may omit the strike. It does not answer the contractual question. If Kalshi had meant to resolve solely by that formal transcript, it could have said so. Instead, the public market title used the broader phrase “during the FIFA World Cup Draw,” and the mention terms leave event boundaries to what the market clearly specifies.\\n\\nOn burden, plaintiff does not need absolute certainty or a formal-stage mention. Plaintiff must show it is more likely than not that the market wording plus terms include the event-linked remarks. The evidence satisfies that standard: PX-1 gives no exclusion; PX-2 and PX-5 prove the standalone Ronaldo mentions in public World Cup Draw venue remarks; PX-3 supplies a flexible event/time-period framework and excludes only categories unlike this source; PX-4 merely identifies the defense’s alternate formal-program boundary. The fair resolution is Yes.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the record now makes the defense point sharper, not weaker. Plaintiff has proved that Trump said \\\"Ronaldo\\\" in an official transcript of remarks connected to the World Cup Draw. Plaintiff has not proved that those remarks were during the market event.\\n\\nStart with the contract. DX/PX-1 gives the trader-facing question: \\\"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\\" It does not say \\\"at the Kennedy Center,\\\" \\\"on World Cup Draw day,\\\" \\\"in remarks prior to the Draw,\\\" or \\\"in any public press exchange associated with the Draw.\\\" For this strike to resolve Yes, the relevant mention must fall inside that specified time period.\\n\\nThe strongest evidence of the Ronaldo utterance is also the strongest evidence against plaintiff's boundary. PX-2 and PX-5 are titled \\\"Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw.\\\" PX-5, plaintiff's GovInfo/OFR source, confirms the same title, says the remarks were joined in progress, identifies the source as an exchange with the news media, and notes that some portions could not be verified because the audio was incomplete. That evidence proves an official pre-event reporter transcript. It does not prove the reporter exchange was the FIFA World Cup Draw.\\n\\nThe terms, PX-3, require words used by the entity during the specified time period. They permit an event or context as a time period, and they discuss what is included when the time period is a specific event. That framework does not turn all event-adjacent speech into event speech. The distinction between official presentation content and non-included behind-the-scenes or unofficial content matters because the question is not just whether a record is public or official. The question is whether this source was part of the market's event period. A public official transcript can still be a transcript of remarks prior to the event.\\n\\nDX-2 supplies the missing contrast. It is a focused extraction from the separate Roll Call/Factba.se formal FIFA World Cup Drawing transcript. That page is the formal source identified in the case-packet archive note. It is titled \\\"Remarks: Donald Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing in Washington - December 5, 2025.\\\" Its transcript begins with the formal drawing participants; at 00:00:50, Infantino says, \\\"This is the World Cup trophy\\\" and \\\"we are now going to do the draw.\\\" The page's Trump soccer answer mentions Pele and the Cosmos, not Ronaldo. The extracted page text was searched for both \\\"Ronaldo\\\" and \\\"Messi\\\" and neither appears.\\n\\nThat does not prove Trump never said Ronaldo anywhere at the venue. It proves the opposite boundary from plaintiff's: the formal Draw transcript is separate from the pre-event reporter exchange, and the formal transcript does not contain the strike. Plaintiff needs a bridge between those two sources. It has not offered one. There is no market page detail saying red-carpet or pre-program press remarks count. There is no official program metadata showing the reporter exchange was part of the Draw presentation. There is no source hierarchy provision selecting the pre-event reporter exchange over the formal Draw transcript for this market.\\n\\nPlaintiff argues ambiguity should favor Yes because Kalshi could have drafted a narrower rule. But this is a preponderance case about a challenged No resolution, not a penalty for every conceivable ambiguity. The ordinary reading of \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw\\\" is the draw program, not every public appearance immediately before it. The record's own labels preserve that ordinary line: \\\"Prior to\\\" on the Ronaldo source; \\\"Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing\\\" on the formal source; and a formal transcript that starts the draw and omits the strike.\\n\\nWeight and provenance also favor the defense on the decisive issue. PX-5 is official and useful, but it authenticates a pre-event reporter exchange. DX-2 is a captured formal transcript extraction from the source class identified in PX-4; its absence finding is limited but material. PX-4 was initially only a note that the formal page existed and could not be retrieved. We have now retrieved and searched it. The adverse check therefore confirms, rather than merely speculates, that the formal drawing transcript does not carry plaintiff's Ronaldo mention.\\n\\nThe council should resolve the proposition against plaintiff. The record shows Trump said Ronaldo before the FIFA World Cup Draw in an event-linked reporter exchange. It does not show he said Ronaldo during the FIFA World Cup Draw. On this market wording and these terms, the challenged No resolution should stand.\\n\\nRebuttals:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, defendant’s new formal-transcript extraction proves less than defendant needs.\\n\\nPlaintiff accepts the narrow fact defendant has now preserved: the Roll Call/Factba.se formal drawing-program extraction contains no “Ronaldo” or “Messi.” That is why plaintiff did not build the case on a formal-stage mention. The proposition instead asks whether the market wording and mention terms clearly excluded Trump’s public, official, event-linked remarks at the venue immediately before the formal program. Defendant has not supplied that exclusion.\\n\\nDefendant’s argument treats the title “Prior to the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw” as if “prior to” automatically means outside the Kalshi market’s event period. But PX-1 does not say “formal transcript only,” “after the draw host begins,” “after 00:00:50,” or “excluding press availability at the venue.” It asks what Trump would say “during the FIFA World Cup Draw.” The source label tells us sequence; it does not tell us the market’s legal boundary.\\n\\nDX-2 actually illustrates why defendant’s bright line is chosen after the fact. In defendant’s own formal extraction, the page begins before the mechanical draw: Mark Carney speaks at 00:00:00, and Infantino says at 00:00:50, “we are now going to do the draw.” If “during the FIFA World Cup Draw” can include ceremony and preamble on the formal page before the draw itself begins, then the phrase is not self-defining down to a single moment or transcript. The question is what the market clearly specified. It did not specify defendant’s transcript-only rule.\\n\\nThe terms do not fill that gap for defendant. PX-3 excludes hidden categories such as rehearsals, sound checks, unofficial recordings, and behind-the-scenes content unless officially published as part of the period. PX-2 and PX-5 are not those categories. PX-5 is an official GovInfo/OFR presidential transcript, published with source metadata, at 11:13 a.m. at the Kennedy Center, with FIFA’s president present and the World Cup Draw repeatedly discussed. That gives the Ronaldo mentions strong provenance and an event connection; it does not make them informal backstage chatter.\\n\\nDefendant says plaintiff needs a bridge. The bridge is the market text plus the terms’ failure to draw the narrow line defendant proposes. A No resolution can stand only if the contract fairly told traders that “during the FIFA World Cup Draw” meant only the separate formal-program transcript. On this record, the more likely reading is broader: public, official remarks at the venue, immediately tied to and immediately preceding the World Cup Draw program, were within the event-linked period unless clearly excluded.\\n\\nSo DX-2 narrows one factual issue but does not decide the case. It shows no formal-stage Ronaldo mention. It does not show that the market excluded the official pre-program event remarks where Trump did say Ronaldo. Under the preponderance standard, the Yes resolution remains the fair one.\\n\\nSurrebuttals:\\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff’s rebuttal usefully narrows the dispute. Plaintiff accepts that the formal Roll Call/Factba.se drawing transcript contains no “Ronaldo” or “Messi.” So the case remains entirely about whether a separate reporter exchange titled “Prior to the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw” should be treated as inside the market period.\\n\\nPlaintiff says “prior to” is only sequence, not legal boundary. But sequence is exactly what the market phrase makes material. The contract asks what Trump would say “during the FIFA World Cup Draw.” A source-agency title identifying the Ronaldo transcript as an exchange with reporters prior to that Draw is not a stray label; it is the best record description of when and what that source is. Plaintiff cannot convert that source into the event itself by saying the market failed to list every excluded pre-event setting.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s formal-preamble point also does not carry the burden. Yes, the formal transcript begins before the mechanical ball selection, and Infantino says at 00:00:50 that “we are now going to do the draw.” But that supports the defense distinction. A host’s preamble inside the formal drawing transcript is part of the program. A separate press exchange, separately titled and sourced as prior to the Draw, is not made part of the program simply because it happened nearby and discussed the same event.\\n\\nNor does official publication settle the issue. PX-5 strengthens provenance: Trump did say Ronaldo in an official public transcript. But provenance answers whether the words were said, not whether they were said during the market’s specified event. The terms require both: the word by the entity, and the word during the time period. Plaintiff has the first element. The second is still missing.\\n\\nThe remaining bridge plaintiff proposes is essentially: public, official, event-linked, and not expressly excluded. That is not enough under a preponderance standard when the same record supplies a cleaner boundary: the Ronaldo source is prior to the Draw, and the formal Draw source omits the strike. The challenged No resolution should stand.\\n\\nClosings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the record has narrowed to one real issue.\\n\\nThe word is proven. The market page identifies the strike as “Ronaldo” and the challenged resolution as No. The case-packet transcript and the GovInfo/OFR excerpt prove that Trump said “Ronaldo” as a standalone word in public remarks at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center, in a World Cup Draw setting, with FIFA President Infantino present, and amid repeated discussion of the Draw, the Kennedy Center, ticket sales, the audience, and the imminent event. That is strong provenance: GovInfo, NARA/OFR, DCPD202501162, matching the packet source and note.\\n\\nDefendant has also proved its best fact. The Roll Call/Factba.se formal-program extraction does not contain “Ronaldo” or “Messi.” Plaintiff does not ask you to find otherwise. If the market had said “only the formal drawing transcript,” defendant would win. But that is not the market traders saw.\\n\\nThe market asked: “What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?” It did not say “during the formal transcript only,” “after the host announces the draw has begun,” “excluding public press remarks at the venue,” or “excluding remarks immediately before the program.” The governing terms do not add that limitation. They define words used by the entity during the time period, allow event/context time periods, and exclude categories such as rehearsals, sound checks, behind-the-scenes content, and unofficial recordings. Plaintiff’s source is none of those. It is an official public presidential transcript of event-linked remarks at the venue.\\n\\nDefendant’s formal extraction shows why a bright line cannot simply be assumed. Even on that page, before balls are drawn, there is ceremony, introduction, and Infantino saying “we are now going to do the draw.” Event boundaries are not self-defining. The question is whether Kalshi clearly chose defendant’s narrower boundary. The record contains no such choice.\\n\\nSo the burden is met. More likely than not, a reasonable reading of the market and terms includes Trump’s official, public, venue-based remarks immediately tied to the World Cup Draw. The strongest contrary evidence proves only that a narrower formal transcript omits the strike. It does not prove the contract excluded the remarks where the strike was actually said.\\n\\nThe challenged No resolution should be overturned. The strike “Ronaldo” should resolve Yes.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff’s closing concedes the decisive factual split: the formal World Cup Drawing transcript contains no “Ronaldo” or “Messi.” The only Ronaldo evidence is the separate official transcript titled “Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw.”\\n\\nThat is enough to decide the case. The market did not ask what Trump would say at the Kennedy Center, on World Cup Draw day, in public presidential remarks, or in event-linked press availability. It asked what Trump would say “during the FIFA World Cup Draw.” The terms require the word to be used by the entity during the specified time period. Plaintiff has proven the word and the speaker. It has not proven the time period.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s strongest point is that the market did not expressly say “formal transcript only” or “exclude pre-program remarks.” But plaintiff has the burden. A challenged No resolution does not become Yes merely because the contract could have been even more verbose. The record must make it more likely than not that the pre-event reporter exchange was inside the market period. The record does the opposite.\\n\\nThe source labels matter. PX-2 and PX-5 are official and probative, but they are official proof of remarks prior to the Draw. The formal Roll Call/Factba.se extraction is the source for Trump’s formal attendance at the FIFA World Cup Drawing; it begins the program, includes the draw presentation, and omits the strike. Plaintiff’s theory asks you to treat a separate prior reporter exchange as “during” the Draw even though the formal Draw source exists and does not contain the word.\\n\\nThe terms do not collapse that distinction. They recognize event/context time periods and official presentation content, but they still require the word to occur during the chosen time period. Official publication proves provenance. Event connection proves relevance. Neither proves inclusion. A public official transcript can be accurately preserved and still be outside the market window if it is, as titled, prior to the event.\\n\\nSo the fair synthesis is narrow and grounded: Trump said Ronaldo in event-linked public remarks before the FIFA World Cup Draw; Trump did not say Ronaldo in the formal drawing transcript preserved in this record; and no admitted market term or source-chain evidence bridges the pre-event exchange into the market’s “during the FIFA World Cup Draw” period.\\n\\nUnder the preponderance standard, plaintiff has not carried the proposition. The challenged No resolution should stand.\\n\\nExhibits:\\n[plaintiff] PX-1 Market page and challenged resolution\\nMarket URL: https://kalshi.com/markets/kxtrumpmentionb/trump-mention-b/kxtrumpmentionb-25dec06\\n\\nPublic market title: What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\n\\nContract family: PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION\\n\\nStrike at issue: Ronaldo\\n\\nChallenged resolution: No\\n\\nRequested resolution: Yes\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-2 Pre-event reporter exchange transcript\\nRemarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\nDecember 05, 2025\\n\\n[The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\\nThe President. It's a great honor to be here. Gianni has done a fantastic job. We're setting records—[inaudible].\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. Well, I think so. They have a little bit of a shot. Pretty stiff competition. But I would say they would have a small chance.\\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize\\nQ. [Inaudible]—win the FIFA Peace Award?\\nThe President. Well, it would be an honor.\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\nQ. Will you root for some selection? Will you root for someone?\\nThe President. Well, I root for a lot of countries, but in this case, I'll be rooting for the U.S.A. [Laughter]\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. That's great. That's great. We really love it.\\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize\\nQ. Mr. President, have you been told that you are going to receive the inaugural peace prize today——\\nThe President. I have not——\\nQ. ——from FIFA?\\nThe President. I have not been told. There's a rumor about it, but I have not been told. That would be a great honor, and I'm a big fan of Gianni, as you know.\\nQ. What can fans expect——\\nQ. Are you hoping to receive that?\\nThe President. Excuse me.\\nQ. Are you hoping to receive the peace prize?\\nThe President. Well, I don't like to say \\\"hope,\\\" but it would be a great honor.\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. What can fans expect of, like, the World Cup in the U.S.?\\nThe President. I think it's going to be fantastic. We've set every record you can set.\\nQ. What are you telling people who are worried——\\nFédération Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) President Giovanni V. Infantino\\nQ. [Inaudible]—friend Gianni—[inaudible]—a word about him?\\nThe President. I think he has done a fantastic job.\\nThe President's Schedule\\nQ. Are you going to be meeting with the President of Mexico today and the——\\nThe President. We might. Yes.\\nQ. ——Prime Minister of Canada as well?\\nThe President. I might. I might do that.\\nQ. Will you be discussing immigration and trade with them?\\nThe President. Yes, we'll be discussing.\\n[At this point, the President and Mr. Infantino posed for photographs.]\\nThe President. Thank you, everybody.\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event/John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts\\nQ. Mr. President, what do you think about the crowd?\\nThe President. Oh, look, the new star—[inaudible].\\nCongratulations.\\nQ. Thank you.\\nThe President. You're the new star of television and Fox.\\nQ. Thank you. How are you doing, Mr. President?\\nThe President. I'm doing very well.\\nQ. What do you think about the crowd here?\\nThe President. I think the crowd is great, and I think the building is great. We've made a lot of improvements over the last 6 months. Taking—the Kennedy Center was in very bad shape. Now it's getting to be really good. And in 6 months, it's going to be incredible with the improvements we've made.\\nQ. The first time for the U.S. to host since the nineties.\\nThe President. Right.\\nQ. Are you ready for it?\\nThe President. I'm ready for it, and they're ready for it. And Gianni, who you know——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——has done a fantastic job with FIFA. And we're looking to have—you know, we're set—we have already set records for tickets sales. I don't think there's ever been anything like it in any sport. And so, I want to congratulate you.\\nMr. Infantino. Thank you.\\nThe President. I don't even have to wait. But major records have been set.\\nHow are you?\\nQ. Good, how are you, sir?\\nThe President. Nice to see you.\\nQ. Today it's not football—American football. It's soccer. It's——\\nThe President. Right.\\nQ. ——the big event of soccer.\\nThe President. That's right. That's right.\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\nQ. So can you tell me about this big day today?\\nThe President. It's just a big day, and it's a great sport. And it really is coming to America. And never—nobody ever thought a thing like this could happen. And I'm very happy to say that we've already set the alltime record on ticket sales long before the first ball is kicked. Right?\\nMr. Infantino. A hundred percent. One hundred percent.\\n2026 World Cup Host Cities\\nQ. You've had some concerns about crime in American cities, some of the cities that will be hosting. Have they remedied that for you? Are you still considering maybe asking FIFA to move some of those cities?\\nThe President. No, I don't want to do that. But I will tell you, if they do have a problem, by the time we get there, we'll take care of that problem. We can solve that problem.\\nI've proven that in DC and everywhere else we went, so we'll take care of that very easily. So, if they have a problem, hopefully, they'll let us know that, and we will solve any problem.\\nOkay? Thank you.\\nQ. Thank you so much.\\nMr. Infantino. All right, thank you so much.\\nQ. Thank you, Mr. President.\\nQ. Thank you. Appreciate it.\\nThe President. Congratulations.\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. Mr. President, Brazilian television. America will be hosting the World Cup and the Olympics in 2 years. How important it is—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. I think very. It's a great honor. I think Gianni is doing a phenomenal job. We've set every record on ticket sales. It's been really fantastic. But Gianni has done an unbelievable job with FIFA.\\nThe President's Experience With Soccer\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. He was a great—not only that. I got to see a man name Pelé play—right?—that tells you how old I am—when he was on the Cosmos. Do you remember that a long time ago? And it was quite a treat. That was quite an event. And he was—not only was he playing, he was great. He scored two goals, I think. And so, I was one of the few who got to see Pelé, and I assume he is one of your alltime greats. Right?\\nMr. Infantino. Definitely.\\nThe President. So I got to see him.\\nThe President's Favorite World Cup Competitor\\nQ. Do you have some favorite teams for World Cup?\\nThe President. Well, I have a favorite. It's the U.S.A. [Laughter] I don't know what their chances are, Gianni, but maybe the U.S.A. is the——\\nMr. Infantino. They're getting better and better, actually.\\nThe President. I think they'll do well.\\nMr. Infantino. They are getting better and better.\\nThe President. I think they'll do well.\\nThank you very much, everybody.\\nQ. Thank you so much.\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. Mr. President, World Cup in America just means—[inaudible]. So what do you expect from this World Cup?\\nThe President. [Inaudible]—record business and only in the United States, but we're also doing record ticket sales with FIFA. And they've already bought—beat their highest record. And we—you know, this a long time before the first ball is kicked. You've sold more tickets than they've ever done before, and better pricing than they've ever gotten before. It's a tremendous success. And it's an honor. And Gianni has done a phenomenal job with FIFA.\\nQ. [Inaudible]—ever?\\nThe President. I think so. I think it's going to be—I mean, ideally, you want to see that every year. Every 4 years, it gets bigger and better. I think we have set every record in the book. We're very happy about it.\\nThank you.\\nThe President's Favorite World Cup Competitor\\nQ. [Inaudible]—part of America. Who are you going to support as well?\\nThe President. Well, I think I have to support U.S.A. Otherwise, I'd be in trouble. I wouldn't be President for long.\\nMr. Infantino. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. [Inaudible]—but you have a lot of great teams. You're going to have a lot of great teams.\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\\\"football,\\\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\\n2026 World Cup Draw/Ticket Sales for World Cup\\nQ. How does it feel to be part of this amazing event? And obviously, your being a part of participating in all the—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. The President of Mexico is here, and she's doing a very good job. She's a good woman, very, very excellent job. It's an honor, and we're setting every record, and you're helping us set those records.\\nMr. Infantino. And we will do it.\\nThe President. You know, Mexico and Canada are helping us set those records. But as you know, we have a record in ticket sales already, long before the first ball is kicked, and we're going to do great.\\nI think that Gianni—as you know, he's the head, and he has done a fantastic job.\\nU.S. Cooperation With Mexico and Canada\\nQ. And how is the biggest challenge being three countries?\\nThe President. Well, I think that—do you mean for the three countries?\\nWell, they've gotten together really well, I mean.\\nMr. Infantino. All right.\\nThe President. They're getting along very well.\\nMr. Infantino. Collaboration is fantastic between the three.\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer/2026 World Cup\\nQ. And you like soccer?\\nThe President. I do. I like it. I like it more and more.\\nQ. Yes?\\nThe President. I like it. It's growing in this country—very, really—I mean, someday, maybe it's going to be bigger than anything else.\\nMr. Infantino. We'll have to become number one.\\nThe President. I will say this——\\nMr. Infantino. Definitely.\\nThe President. ——the ticket sales——\\nQ. Definitely will happen.\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. Ticket sales are bigger than anything we have ever done in the history of the country, in terms of sports.\\nMr. Infantino. For certain.\\nQ. And the audience is going to be huge.\\nThe President. The audience is going to be tremendous.\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. Yes.\\nMr. Infantino. Six billion people.\\nThe President. [Inaudible]\\nQ. Six billion? That's amazing.\\nMr. Infantino. Six billion people.\\nAnd today, one billion.\\nQ. Wow.\\nMr. Infantino. [Inaudible]\\nQ. Enjoy show time. Thank you so much.\\nThe President. [Inaudible]\\nQ. Mr. President, how are you? Just a quick—[inaudible].\\nQ. This is for Telemundo.\\nThe President. How are you?\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\nQ. Hello, Mr. President. How are you? This for Telemundo.\\nThe President. How are you? Good.\\nQ. How are you?\\nThe President. Very good. Thank you.\\nQ. How does it feel to have the most important event of sports—that global—in the U.S.?\\nThe President. Well, we do. And right at the Kennedy Center. I'm Chairman of the Kennedy Center. And I hear the Kennedy Center is doing a very good job, so it feels great. Really good.\\nAnd Telemundo is doing a good job, too. Thank you.\\nQ. Thank you.\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. What is the significance of hosting the FIFA World Cup this year?\\nThe President. It's a—in terms of sports, I would say the ultimate. There is no sport like this. It's the biggest sport in the world. And we are setting every record. You know, our ticket sales have gone and set every—every sport—no matter what it is, we've set the record. So—and every though it's very early, there's no ball being kicked yet, but we've already set a ticket sales record.\\nArgentina National Team\\nQ. How do you see Argentinean team for this World Cup?\\nThe President. Well, I love Argentina. And your President is doing a very good job, as you know. Milei. You know that right? It's make Argentina great again. MAGA.\\nQ. And——\\nU.S. National Team\\nQ. Do you think the States are building a powerful team for next year?\\nThe President. Who?\\nQ. The States.\\nThe President. Oh, yes. Sure. I—you're going to have a lot of powerful teams. Everybody has a lot of powerful teams, but you're going to have a lot of great teams. [Inaudible]\\nU.S. Role in Hosting the 2026 World Cup\\nQ. Mr. President, what does it mean for you guys to host the World Cup right here in the U.S.?\\nThe President. I'm honored to host it. It's a great honor. I mean, it's turned out to be bigger than we thought. We're setting a record for ticket sales, the likes of which no sport has ever seen before.\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\\nThe President. But they have a little more speed.\\nBut no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\\nPopularity of Soccer in Latin America\\nQ. Mr. President, a message for the Latin America and soccer fans?\\nThe President. Yes, I am. And Latin America is great. And they have great soccer. So, good luck in the matches.\\n[A reporter asked a question in Spanish, which was translated by an interpreter as follows.]\\nU.S. Visas for World Cup Ticketholders\\nQ. Who is going to be in—[inaudible]—about these visas for the—these fans that want to come here to the World Cup?\\nThe President. Well, we're going to make it very easy for them. We're working on that right now. We're going to make it very easy. It's going to be a very easy process.\\nQ. Okay. Say, hi to Colombia over there.\\nThe President. Hello. Is that Colombia?\\nQ. Yes.\\nThe President. I love Colombia. Hello, Colombia. [Laughter]\\nQ. Okay. Okay. Muy bien.\\nThe President. So where are you from?\\nQ. Paraguay.\\nThe President. Oh.\\nQ. He's from Paraguay. Yes.\\nThe President. Very good. I love it. I—it's a beautiful country. We get along very well with them. We do a little trade deal with them, and they like us. And that's what's happening.\\nQ. Panama.\\nThe President. Where?\\nVery good. I like the canal. [Laughter] That canal is pretty good.\\n[A reporter spoke in Spanish; no translation was provided.]\\n2026 World Cup\\nThe President. What?\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. Well, it's going to be incredible. The event is going to be very good. Just this event alone—it's at the Kennedy Center. I see you have it fixed up perfectly.\\nMr. Infantino. It will set the tone.\\nThe President. Right? It's beautiful.\\nMr. Infantino. It's beautiful.\\nThe President. It's a beautiful place.\\nHave a good time.\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President.\\n[A reporter spoke in Spanish; no translation was provided.]\\nMr. Infantino. No, gracias. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. It's great.\\nJohn F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts/Renovation Work\\nQ. Mr. President, the U.S. press?\\nThe President. Thank you, everybody, very much. It's a great honor. This has been an honor for a lot of reasons. Number one, they've sold more tickets than any event has ever sold already—long before the kickoff.\\nAnd number two, we've done a lot of work at the Kennedy Center. It was falling apart, and now it's pretty much back. And we'll get it back within the next 4 or 5 months through construction, and—but you see the way it looks.\\nAnd Gianni is just telling me—who's done an incredible job, by the way. He's just telling, you know, how good a job we've done.\\nMr. Infantino. That's right.\\nThe President. You can look at the walls. The marble was broken. Everything was a mess. And we've really taken the Kennedy Center—a lot of people thought it was going to be ripped down, and we did just the opposite. So we've done a really great renovation job on it. And over the next 3, 4 months, it will be complete. And we're honored to have it here, and it's been—it's been very special.\\nWe've set a record on ticket sales, as you probably heard, already, even way before—long before the event itself. And we're working with Canada, and we're working with Mexico. And it's been a really spectacular—so far, it's been spectacular.\\nDaniel [Daniel Baldwin, One America News Network], do you have a question?\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. What are your expectations? You once said that the FIFA World Cup is an opportunity to put—a once-in-a-lifetime opportunity to put the greatness of the United States on display.\\nThe President. Well, I think—\\nQ. One billion eyeballs will be watching, Mr. President.\\nThe President. Yes, I—think——\\nQ. What will they here today?\\nThe President. Even today, I understand. I hear that, you know——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——I know we're a little late to get in there, but——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——that's okay.\\nMr. Infantino. They wait.\\nThe President. So all my friends, I guess they have to wait. They have no choice, right? [Laughter]\\nMr. Infantino. Yes, they wait.\\nThe President. But no, the numbers are incredible. I hear today's numbers are——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——very big. I hope CNN is covering this.\\nQ. One billion eyeballs.\\nMr. Infantino. Today, 1 billion eyeballs.\\nThe President. Today's numbers are very, very big.\\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize/The President's Foreign Policy\\nQ. We are covering it. And you're expected to get the FIFA Peace Prize, Mr. President. What would you say to people who say that prize might conflict with your pledge to strike Venezuela?\\nThe President. Well, I think the peace prize—I mean, I settled eight wars. I don't know that I'm getting it. I haven't been officially noticed. I've been hearing about a peace prize, and I'm here to represent our country in a different sense. But I can tell you, I did settle eight wars, and we have a ninth coming, but—which nobody has ever done before.\\nBut I want to really save lives. I don't need prizes. I need to save lives. And we're saving a lot of lives. And I've saved millions and millions of lives, and that's really what I want to do.\\nAnd I also want to run a great country. And the United States right now is the hottest country anywhere in the world. And 1 year ago, it was dead. We had a dead country, and now we have the hottest country anywhere in the world.\\nQ. Mr. President, will you——\\nThe President's Meeting With President Claudia Sheinbaum Pardo of Mexico and Prime Minister Mark Carney of Canada\\nQ. What are you going to discuss with Canada and Mexico, Mr.—what are you going to discuss with the leaders of Canada and Mexico?\\nThe President. Well, we're getting—we're going to meet with both. And we're getting along very well. You know, we're getting along very well. I don't know. I think we have a meeting set up for some time after the event.\\nQ. Will you discuss trade?\\nThe President. Yes, we'll discuss trade. We—get along very well.\\nThank you, everybody, very much.\\nQ. Will you pardon any other Honduran officials?\\nQ. Do you want them to keep trying to indict Ms. James?\\n\\nNOTE: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. In his remarks, he referred to Trey Yingst, chief foreign correspondent, Fox News Channel; Cristiano Ronaldo, forward for Saudi Pro League club Al-Nass and Portugal's national soccer team; and Lionel Messi, forward for Major League Soccer club Inter Miami and Argentina's national team. A reporter referred to New York State Attorney General Letitia James. The transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\n\\nSource URL: https://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/documents/remarks-exchange-with-reporters-prior-the-2026-federation-internationale-des-associations\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-3 PRESMENTION/NEWMENTION terms\\n                                         NEWMENTION\\n\\nScope: These rules shall apply to this contract.\\n\\nUnderlying: The Underlying for this Contract is words used by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nRevisions to the Underlying made after Expiration will not be accounted for in determining the\\nExpiration Value.\\n\\nSource Agency: The Source Agencies are \\u003csource\\u003e.\\n\\nType: The type of Contract is an Event Contract.\\n\\nIssuance: After the initial Contract, Contract iterations will be listed on an as-needed basis at\\nthe discretion of the Exchange and corresponding to the risk management needs of Members.\\n\\n\\u003centity\\u003e: \\u003centity\\u003e refers to the speaker, writer, performer, or communicator specified by the\\nExchange. This may include (but is not limited to): a specific named individual, multiple\\nindividuals specified using AND/OR logic, an individual identified by position or title, a group,\\nband, team or collective entity, a specified member or members of a group, an organization,\\ncompany, or institutional entity, or any combination of the aforementioned.\\n\\nWhen \\u003centity\\u003e is defined by a position or title, the Contract tracks whoever holds that position\\nduring \\u003ctime period\\u003e, even if the individual holding the position changes. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a\\nspecific named individual, the identity remains consistent throughout. Name changes (e.g.,\\nstage names, married names) do not create a new entity. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a group or\\norganization and the Contract does not specify particular members, any official\\ncommunication or statement by any member or designated spokesperson counts. When using\\nAND logic, all specified entities must independently say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e. When\\nusing OR logic, at least one of the specified entities must say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nThe Exchange may specify additional conditions such as “at least X members of” a group or\\n“the majority of” a group.\\n\\n\\u003csource\\u003e: \\u003csource\\u003e refers to a Source Agency or ordered collection of Source Agencies\\nspecified by the Exchange at the time of Contract listing, which will be incorporated into the\\nSource Agency hierarchy above and used to determine the occurrence of the Underlying.\\n\\u003csource\\u003e may refer to a singular agency, multiple agencies, an agency by distinguishing\\ncharacteristics, by category or type (e.g., “official government statistical body,” “primary wire\\nservice”), or any combination thereof. When multiple agencies are specified, they may be\\napplied in the hierarchical order designated by the Exchange if so specified, with the highest-\\nranked available and responsive agency taking precedence for purposes of determining the\\nExpiration Value. A lower-ranked agency shall only be consulted if all higher-ranked agencies\\nare unavailable, unresponsive, have not reported on the Underlying by the Expiration time, or\\nif the Exchange, in its sole discretion, determines that a higher-ranked agency’s reporting is\\nincomplete, erroneous, or otherwise insufficient to determine the Expiration Value. If \\u003csource\\u003e\\ndesignates multiple agencies without specifying a hierarchical order, the Exchange shall\\nresolve any conflict between reporting agencies at its sole discretion.\\n\\n\\u003cword\\u003e: \\u003cword\\u003e refers to the particular word or phrase potentially to be mentioned by\\n\\u003centity\\u003e. It may refer to a word being said a minimum number of times. It may also refer to\\none of multiple words/phrases, any of which are acceptable (e.g., “Doge/Dogecoin”).\\n\\f\\u003ctime period\\u003e: \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific range of time, event or discrete date and\\ntime specified by the Exchange. This may be defined by, but is not limited to: a specific event\\nor context (e.g., “during the State of the Union address”), exact dates or times, relative time\\nmarkers (e.g., “before July 1, 2027,” “in Q1 2026”), event-based periods (e.g., “during any\\ncampaign rally in October 2026,” “during the awards ceremony”), and broader intervals (e.g.,\\n“Q1–Q2 2027,” “January–March 2026”).\\n\\nUnless stated otherwise, “Between” is inclusive of both endpoints, while “before” and “after”\\nexclude the specified date. \\u003ctime period\\u003e may also refer to “Any” or “None”, to multiple dates\\n(even if non-consecutive), or to a singular and discrete date or time.\\n\\nWhen \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event (such as an address, speech, performance, or\\nbroadcast), the Exchange may specify what is included, including whether it includes both live\\nand pre-recorded segments (including whether advertisements are included). Where a\\ntimezone is not specified, ET is assumed.\\n\\n\\nPayout Criterion: The Payout Criterion for the Contract encompasses the Expiration Values that\\n\\u003cword\\u003e is said by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n\\n\\nThe word must appear as a distinct, standalone unit, not buried inside another word. Plural\\nand possessive noun forms count. Other grammatical changes (tense, conjugation, derivation)\\ndo not. If \\u003cword\\u003e appears separated from other words by a space or hyphen or in a\\ncompound form with a space or hyphen, it counts. If \\u003cword\\u003e is fused into a single\\nunhyphenated word, it does not count.\\n\\nIf \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled, and the market contains a\\nstrike stating “Event does not qualify/occur”, such a strike shall resolve “Yes” and all others\\n“No”. If \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled but such strikes are NOT\\nlisted, the Contracts will resolve to the last fair price determined at the discretion of the\\nExchange. If the event is postponed, and such a postponement is announced by the end of the\\nfollowing calendar day to be rescheduled to a time within 14 calendar days, the markets shall\\nremain open. If the event captured in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast, the\\nExchange may keep the market open for 24 hours for the release of an official recording.\\nFurther granular details on conditions for these Contracts is available below.\\n\\nAdditional clarification(s):\\n\\n     Possessive noun forms of \\u003cword\\u003e, plurals, and possessive plural noun forms are\\n     INCLUDED:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigrants” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Egg” → “eggs’ shells” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Russia” → “Russia’s” counts, “Russian” does not\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e exists only in adjective form, no plural form exists:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Economic” → “Economics” does not count (“Economic” is an adjective\\n          for which “Economics” is not a plural)\\n     Plural nouns occurring within proper nouns and noun phrases are included:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Cat” → “Cats the musical” counts\\n\\f    Grammatical variations beyond plurals/possessives are NOT included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigration” does NOT count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Run” → “Running” or “Ran” do NOT count\\n    When \\u003cword\\u003e specifies a plural form, the singular does NOT count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Veterans” → “Veteran” does NOT count\\n    Words that are spelled the same as the plural form of \\u003cword\\u003e (if such exists) but are\\n    themselves not a plural noun are included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Wind” → “Winds up the clock” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Border” → “The United States has strong borders” counts\\n    Open compounds (words separated by spaces) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fire station” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “couch” → “couch potato” counts\\n    Hyphenated compounds (words connected by hyphens) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Palestine” → “pro-Palestine” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fat” → “non-fat” counts\\n    Closed compounds (single word, no spaces/hyphens) do not count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire” does not count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firefighter” does not count\\n    Multi-word \\u003cword\\u003e in larger constructions: When \\u003cword\\u003e is a multi-word phrase\\n    appearing within a hyphenated construction, it counts only if \\u003cword\\u003e appears as a\\n    complete, unmodified element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “New York” → “New York-based” counts (complete element)\\n    Portmanteaus (words blended from two words where parts of each are combined) are\\n    NOT included unless the portmanteau clearly contains \\u003cword\\u003e as a distinct, unaltered\\n    element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “MAGA” → “MAGA-nificent” counts (MAGA appears as distinct element)\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “magnificent” → “MAGA-nificent” does NOT count (portmanteau blend)\\n\\nDictionary determination: Both the Merriam-Webster Dictionary (available online) AND the\\nOxford English Dictionary shall be used to determine compound type and/or conventional\\nspelling patterns. Inclusion in either dictionary as an open or hyphenated compound shall\\nsatisfy the Payout Criterion. If neither provides clarity (or the word is not included),\\ndetermination is based on whether written as single unit (closed/doesn’t count) vs. spaces or\\nhyphens (open or hyphenated/counts) and/or context and previous usage.\\n\\nPHONETIC EQUIVALENCIES\\n\\n    Homophones (same sound, different spelling) do not count:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “write” → “right” does not count\\n    Homonyms and homographs (same spelling) COUNT regardless of meaning or\\n    pronunciation:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “bass” → both “bass guitar” and “bass fishing” count\\n    Proper and common nouns are treated identically:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Apple” → both “Apple Inc.” and “apple” (fruit) count\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Will” → both “Will Smith” and “I will go” count\\n    Minor unintentional mispronunciations COUNT if context makes intent clear:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Mamdani” → “Mandani” counts\\n    Severe mispronunciations that make \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable do NOT count.\\n    Trademarked spellings do not count, even when pronounced identically, unless the word\\n\\fitself is the same:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “lift” → “Lyft” (pronounced “lift”) does not count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “uber” → “Uber” counts\\nWords with non-standard transliteration to English count within reason, provided they are\\nphonetically equivalent:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Zelensky” → any of “Zelenski,” “Zelenskii,” “Zelensky,” or “Zelenskiy”\\n      count if pronounced equivalently\\nContractions do not count for their constituent words unless otherwise explicitly specified\\nby the Exchange:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “not” → “won’t,” “can’t,” “don’t,” “isn’t” do not count\\nNumbers spoken as words COUNT, when spoken exactly (not part of a larger number):\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “five” → saying “five” or reading “$5” aloud as “five dollars” counts,\\n      saying “five hundred” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “410” → “four hundred ten”, “four one zero” or “four ten” counts\\nOrdinals COUNT when \\u003cword\\u003e is written numerically OR a phrase that includes a\\nnumber:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “January 6” → “January 6th” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “3” (written numerically) → “3rd” (spoken as “third”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Eight War” → “8 Wars” and “Eighth War” will count\\nCardinal and ordinal number words are distinct:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “one” → “first” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “first” → “one” does NOT count\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count when pronunciation or letter-by-letter spelling\\nmatches \\u003cword\\u003e:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “NASA” (pronounced “NAH-suh”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “N-A-S-A” (spelled out) counts\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count as \\u003cword\\u003e when pronounced as the full word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Doctor” → “Dr.” (pronounced “Doctor”) counts\\nExpanded forms of acronyms do NOT count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “AI” → “artificial intelligence” does not count\\nWords in foreign languages do NOT count unless they are perfect cognates with an\\nEnglish word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fuego” (Spanish) does NOT count\\nEnglish words within foreign sentences count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “policy” → “Nuestra policy es clara” counts\\n\\u003cword\\u003e in organization/company names counts:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Securities” → “Bank of America Securities” counts\\nWords in URLs, emails, handles, and hashtags (exclusive of domain structure, email\\nprovider or symbols) are treated as compounds when spoken as complete words, with the\\ntype of compound subject to aforementioned rules:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firestation.com” pronounced “fire station dot com” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire.com” pronounced “wildfire dot com” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “apple” → “apple.com” pronounced “apple dot com” does count\\n      When presented in URL, email, handle, or hashtag form, \\u003cword\\u003e shall be treated as\\n      a compound, not a multi-word word\\nSung, rapped, or poetic words COUNT if phonetically recognizable:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “money” → “moneyyy” (extended in rap) counts\\n      Extreme distortion making \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable does NOT count.\\nPhonetic alphabet spelling (“Foxtrot India Romeo Echo” for “FIRE”) does NOT count.\\n\\fCANCELLATIONS AND DELAYS\\n\\n   The Exchange may list an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike for any Contract. If listed,\\n   such a strike refers to the structural conditions of the market, and is NOT adjudicated as a\\n   \\u003cword\\u003e needing to be said by or validated by having been said by \\u003centity\\u003e. If listed, this\\n   strike resolves to “Yes” whenever the event fails to occur or qualify under the Payout\\n   Criterion, or any other circumstance prevents normal resolution.\\n   If no such strike is listed, and \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, the following rules\\n   apply if the event is cancelled, postponed, rescheduled, or materially altered (including\\n   being closed to press) such that no video is released within one calendar day of the\\n   original start time of the event:\\n         If the event is cancelled, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price determined in\\n         the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         If the event is postponed or rescheduled, the outcome depends on whether a new\\n         date is publicly announced within one calendar day (i.e. if the event was scheduled\\n         to begin on Monday, any time up to 11:59PM on Tuesday falls within this period) of\\n         the originally scheduled start time:\\n               If no new date is announced within one calendar day, the Contract will resolve\\n               to the last fair price determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n               If a new date is announced within one calendar day, the outcome depends on\\n               when the rescheduled event is set to occur:\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls within fourteen (14) calendar days of the\\n                     originally scheduled date, the Contract shall remain open and \\u003cword\\u003e\\n                     stated during the rescheduled event will count.\\n                           The fourteen-day window begins at 12:00 AM ET on the originally\\n                           scheduled date and ends at 11:59 PM ET fourteen days later, unless\\n                           an alternate timezone is explicitly specified.\\n                           Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the State of the Union on January\\n                           15, 2026” rescheduled to January 20, 2026 → words spoken during\\n                           the rescheduled address count.\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls more than fourteen (14) calendar days after\\n                     the originally scheduled date, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price\\n                     determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         Any Contract that cannot be resolved through the Source Agency hierarchy will\\n         instead be settled at the Last Fair Price. The Exchange will disclose the methodology\\n         used to determine the Last Fair Price (e.g., Last Traded Price, Time-Weighted\\n         Average Price) at the time of Issuance.\\n         If an event begins but is interrupted, abbreviated, or ends prematurely, words\\n         stated by \\u003centity\\u003e during the portion of the event that did occur will count and the\\n         market will otherwise resolve.\\n   If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window but the venue, format, or medium\\n   changes (e.g., moved to a different location, changed from in-person to virtual (with the\\n   exception of being closed to press)), words stated during the event will count.\\n   Special condition: Across both cases, whether an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike is\\n   listed or not, if the event specified as or in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast (or\\n   relayed as such) but the live stream/broadcast does not occur, the Exchange will instead\\n   use an officially released recording as the Underlying, and may delay resolution by up to\\n   one calendar day to allow for the release of such a recording.\\n\\f          If partial snippets are released, Contracts on words that do not appear will be\\n          resolved to last fair price, and Contracts on those that do will be resolved to “Yes”.\\n          If no recording is released, the relevant outcomes triggered by the\\n          presence/absence of an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike shall occur as outlined\\n          above.\\n\\nTECHNICAL DETAILS (UNLESS OTHERWISE SPECIFIED)\\n\\n     When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, pre-recorded content broadcast,\\n     streamed, or published as part of that event is included if presented as part of the official\\n     presentation.\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the concert” with pre-recorded video interlude\\n          where entity speaks → words from interlude count\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the television appearance” with pre-taped\\n          segment aired during broadcast → words from segment count\\n     Behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are NOT\\n     included unless officially broadcast or published as part of \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n     Subtitles and captions that display \\u003cword\\u003e on screen but are not spoken aloud by\\n     \\u003centity\\u003e do NOT count.\\n     Sign language interpretation or usage by entity does NOT count as saying \\u003cword\\u003e unless\\n     the Contract explicitly specifies that sign language counts.\\n     Text that entity displays on screen (presentation slides, teleprompter visible to audience,\\n     signatures) does NOT count unless entity reads it aloud.\\n     Content generated by AI, deepfakes, or synthetic voice technology impersonating entity\\n     does NOT count unless the synthetic content is officially commissioned, authorized, or\\n     published by entity, OR the Contract explicitly specifies that AI-generated content counts.\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e is muted due to technical failure or censorship it shall not count unless\\n     corroborating contextual evidence (including surrounding speech, or an official\\n     uncensored recording or transcript) confirms that \\u003centity\\u003e specifically uttered \\u003cword\\u003e\\n     during the muted period.\\n\\nMinimum Tick: The Minimum Tick size for the Contract shall be $0.01.\\n\\nPosition Accountability Level: The Position Accountability Level for the Contract shall be\\n$25,000 per strike, per Member.\\n\\nLast Trading Date: The Last Trading Date of the Contract will be the Expiration Date. The Last\\nTrading Time will be the Expiration time.\\n\\nSettlement Date: The Settlement Date of the Contract shall be no later than the day after the\\nExpiration Date, unless the Market Outcome is under review pursuant to Rule 7.1.\\n\\nExpiration Date: When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event: The latest Expiration Date of\\nthe Contract shall be fourteen (14) calendar days after the originally scheduled date of the\\nevent. If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window, expiration will be moved to an\\nearlier date and time in accordance with Rule 7.2. When \\u003ctime period\\u003e is defined by specific\\ndates: The latest Expiration Date of the Contract shall be two weeks after the end of \\u003ctime\\nperiod\\u003e. If an event described in the Payout Criterion occurs and a consensus has been\\nreached on all terms, then expiration will be moved to an earlier date and time in accordance\\nwith Rule 7.2.\\n\\fExpiration time: The Expiration time of the Contract shall be 10:00 AM ET.\\n\\nSettlement Value: The Settlement Value for this Contract is $1.00.\\n\\nExpiration Value: The Expiration Value is the value of the Underlying as documented by the\\nSource Agency on the Expiration Date at the Expiration time.\\n\\nContingencies: Before Settlement, Kalshi may, at its sole discretion, initiate the Market\\nOutcome Review Process pursuant to Rule 7.1 of the Rulebook. If an Expiration Value cannot\\nbe determined on the Expiration Date, Kalshi has the right to determine payouts pursuant to\\nRule 7.1 in the Rulebook.\\n\\f\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-4 Formal draw archive note\\nSource checked: Roll Call / Factba.se archive\\n\\nArchive title: Remarks: Donald Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing in Washington - December 5, 2025\\n\\nArchive URL: https://rollcall.com/factbase/trump/transcript/donald-trump-remarks-fifa-world-cup-drawing-december-5-2025/\\n\\nWhat this file establishes:\\n\\nThere is a separate archived transcript page for Trump's formal attendance remarks at the draw.\\n\\nWhat this file does not establish:\\n\\nThis session could not retrieve the full transcript text from that archive.  The page is password-protected.  This example therefore does not claim, from local files alone, whether the formal program transcript does or does not contain the word \\\"Ronaldo.\\\"\\n\\nWhy this matters:\\n\\nThe complaint does not need to prove that the formal program omitted the strike.  It needs to show that Trump said \\\"Ronaldo\\\" in event-linked remarks and that the market boundary reasonably includes those remarks.  The formal archive remains relevant because it marks the distinction between the pre-event reporter exchange and the formal program.\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-5 GovInfo official transcript excerpt and metadata\\nSource: GovInfo, DCPD202501162, Office of the Federal Register / National Archives and Records Administration.\\nURL: https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/DCPD-202501162/html/DCPD-202501162.htm\\nTitle: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\nEvent date: December 5, 2025.\\n\\nRelevant extracted page text:\\n\\\"Administration of Donald J. Trump, 2025\\\"\\n\\\"Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw December 5, 2025\\\"\\n\\\"[The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\\\"\\n\\nUnder the section \\\"The President's Interest in Soccer\\\":\\n\\\"Q. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\\\"\\n\\\"The President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\\\\\\\"football,\\\\\\\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\\\"\\n\\\"Thank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\\\"\\n\\nAdditional relevant extracted page text:\\n\\\"The President's Interest in Soccer\\\"\\n\\\"Q. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\\\"\\n\\\"The President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\\\"\\n\\\"Mr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\\\"\\n\\\"The President. But they have a little more speed. But no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\\\"\\n\\nGovInfo note:\\n\\\"NOTE: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. In his remarks, he referred to Trey Yingst, chief foreign correspondent, Fox News Channel; Cristiano Ronaldo, forward for Saudi Pro League club Al-Nass and Portugal's national soccer team; and Lionel Messi, forward for Major League Soccer club Inter Miami and Argentina's national team. A reporter referred to New York State Attorney General Letitia James. The transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\\"\\n\\nGovInfo content details page also identifies category \\\"Interviews With the News Media : Exchanges with reporters, Washington, DC,\\\" subjects including \\\"Federation Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) World Cup,\\\" \\\"John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts,\\\" and \\\"Soccer,\\\" and names including \\\"Ronaldo, Cristiano\\\" and \\\"Messi, Lionel.\\\"\\n\\n[defendant] DX-1 Market wording and challenged resolution\\nMarket URL: https://kalshi.com/markets/kxtrumpmentionb/trump-mention-b/kxtrumpmentionb-25dec06\\n\\nPublic market title: What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\n\\nContract family: PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION\\n\\nStrike at issue: Ronaldo\\n\\nChallenged resolution: No\\n\\nRequested resolution: Yes\\n\\n\\n[defendant] DX-2 Pre-event reporter exchange transcript\\nRemarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\nDecember 05, 2025\\n\\n[The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\\nThe President. It's a great honor to be here. Gianni has done a fantastic job. We're setting records—[inaudible].\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. Well, I think so. They have a little bit of a shot. Pretty stiff competition. But I would say they would have a small chance.\\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize\\nQ. [Inaudible]—win the FIFA Peace Award?\\nThe President. Well, it would be an honor.\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\nQ. Will you root for some selection? Will you root for someone?\\nThe President. Well, I root for a lot of countries, but in this case, I'll be rooting for the U.S.A. [Laughter]\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. That's great. That's great. We really love it.\\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize\\nQ. Mr. President, have you been told that you are going to receive the inaugural peace prize today——\\nThe President. I have not——\\nQ. ——from FIFA?\\nThe President. I have not been told. There's a rumor about it, but I have not been told. That would be a great honor, and I'm a big fan of Gianni, as you know.\\nQ. What can fans expect——\\nQ. Are you hoping to receive that?\\nThe President. Excuse me.\\nQ. Are you hoping to receive the peace prize?\\nThe President. Well, I don't like to say \\\"hope,\\\" but it would be a great honor.\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. What can fans expect of, like, the World Cup in the U.S.?\\nThe President. I think it's going to be fantastic. We've set every record you can set.\\nQ. What are you telling people who are worried——\\nFédération Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) President Giovanni V. Infantino\\nQ. [Inaudible]—friend Gianni—[inaudible]—a word about him?\\nThe President. I think he has done a fantastic job.\\nThe President's Schedule\\nQ. Are you going to be meeting with the President of Mexico today and the——\\nThe President. We might. Yes.\\nQ. ——Prime Minister of Canada as well?\\nThe President. I might. I might do that.\\nQ. Will you be discussing immigration and trade with them?\\nThe President. Yes, we'll be discussing.\\n[At this point, the President and Mr. Infantino posed for photographs.]\\nThe President. Thank you, everybody.\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event/John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts\\nQ. Mr. President, what do you think about the crowd?\\nThe President. Oh, look, the new star—[inaudible].\\nCongratulations.\\nQ. Thank you.\\nThe President. You're the new star of television and Fox.\\nQ. Thank you. How are you doing, Mr. President?\\nThe President. I'm doing very well.\\nQ. What do you think about the crowd here?\\nThe President. I think the crowd is great, and I think the building is great. We've made a lot of improvements over the last 6 months. Taking—the Kennedy Center was in very bad shape. Now it's getting to be really good. And in 6 months, it's going to be incredible with the improvements we've made.\\nQ. The first time for the U.S. to host since the nineties.\\nThe President. Right.\\nQ. Are you ready for it?\\nThe President. I'm ready for it, and they're ready for it. And Gianni, who you know——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——has done a fantastic job with FIFA. And we're looking to have—you know, we're set—we have already set records for tickets sales. I don't think there's ever been anything like it in any sport. And so, I want to congratulate you.\\nMr. Infantino. Thank you.\\nThe President. I don't even have to wait. But major records have been set.\\nHow are you?\\nQ. Good, how are you, sir?\\nThe President. Nice to see you.\\nQ. Today it's not football—American football. It's soccer. It's——\\nThe President. Right.\\nQ. ——the big event of soccer.\\nThe President. That's right. That's right.\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\nQ. So can you tell me about this big day today?\\nThe President. It's just a big day, and it's a great sport. And it really is coming to America. And never—nobody ever thought a thing like this could happen. And I'm very happy to say that we've already set the alltime record on ticket sales long before the first ball is kicked. Right?\\nMr. Infantino. A hundred percent. One hundred percent.\\n2026 World Cup Host Cities\\nQ. You've had some concerns about crime in American cities, some of the cities that will be hosting. Have they remedied that for you? Are you still considering maybe asking FIFA to move some of those cities?\\nThe President. No, I don't want to do that. But I will tell you, if they do have a problem, by the time we get there, we'll take care of that problem. We can solve that problem.\\nI've proven that in DC and everywhere else we went, so we'll take care of that very easily. So, if they have a problem, hopefully, they'll let us know that, and we will solve any problem.\\nOkay? Thank you.\\nQ. Thank you so much.\\nMr. Infantino. All right, thank you so much.\\nQ. Thank you, Mr. President.\\nQ. Thank you. Appreciate it.\\nThe President. Congratulations.\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. Mr. President, Brazilian television. America will be hosting the World Cup and the Olympics in 2 years. How important it is—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. I think very. It's a great honor. I think Gianni is doing a phenomenal job. We've set every record on ticket sales. It's been really fantastic. But Gianni has done an unbelievable job with FIFA.\\nThe President's Experience With Soccer\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. He was a great—not only that. I got to see a man name Pelé play—right?—that tells you how old I am—when he was on the Cosmos. Do you remember that a long time ago? And it was quite a treat. That was quite an event. And he was—not only was he playing, he was great. He scored two goals, I think. And so, I was one of the few who got to see Pelé, and I assume he is one of your alltime greats. Right?\\nMr. Infantino. Definitely.\\nThe President. So I got to see him.\\nThe President's Favorite World Cup Competitor\\nQ. Do you have some favorite teams for World Cup?\\nThe President. Well, I have a favorite. It's the U.S.A. [Laughter] I don't know what their chances are, Gianni, but maybe the U.S.A. is the——\\nMr. Infantino. They're getting better and better, actually.\\nThe President. I think they'll do well.\\nMr. Infantino. They are getting better and better.\\nThe President. I think they'll do well.\\nThank you very much, everybody.\\nQ. Thank you so much.\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. Mr. President, World Cup in America just means—[inaudible]. So what do you expect from this World Cup?\\nThe President. [Inaudible]—record business and only in the United States, but we're also doing record ticket sales with FIFA. And they've already bought—beat their highest record. And we—you know, this a long time before the first ball is kicked. You've sold more tickets than they've ever done before, and better pricing than they've ever gotten before. It's a tremendous success. And it's an honor. And Gianni has done a phenomenal job with FIFA.\\nQ. [Inaudible]—ever?\\nThe President. I think so. I think it's going to be—I mean, ideally, you want to see that every year. Every 4 years, it gets bigger and better. I think we have set every record in the book. We're very happy about it.\\nThank you.\\nThe President's Favorite World Cup Competitor\\nQ. [Inaudible]—part of America. Who are you going to support as well?\\nThe President. Well, I think I have to support U.S.A. Otherwise, I'd be in trouble. I wouldn't be President for long.\\nMr. Infantino. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. [Inaudible]—but you have a lot of great teams. You're going to have a lot of great teams.\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\\\"football,\\\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\\n2026 World Cup Draw/Ticket Sales for World Cup\\nQ. How does it feel to be part of this amazing event? And obviously, your being a part of participating in all the—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. The President of Mexico is here, and she's doing a very good job. She's a good woman, very, very excellent job. It's an honor, and we're setting every record, and you're helping us set those records.\\nMr. Infantino. And we will do it.\\nThe President. You know, Mexico and Canada are helping us set those records. But as you know, we have a record in ticket sales already, long before the first ball is kicked, and we're going to do great.\\nI think that Gianni—as you know, he's the head, and he has done a fantastic job.\\nU.S. Cooperation With Mexico and Canada\\nQ. And how is the biggest challenge being three countries?\\nThe President. Well, I think that—do you mean for the three countries?\\nWell, they've gotten together really well, I mean.\\nMr. Infantino. All right.\\nThe President. They're getting along very well.\\nMr. Infantino. Collaboration is fantastic between the three.\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer/2026 World Cup\\nQ. And you like soccer?\\nThe President. I do. I like it. I like it more and more.\\nQ. Yes?\\nThe President. I like it. It's growing in this country—very, really—I mean, someday, maybe it's going to be bigger than anything else.\\nMr. Infantino. We'll have to become number one.\\nThe President. I will say this——\\nMr. Infantino. Definitely.\\nThe President. ——the ticket sales——\\nQ. Definitely will happen.\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. Ticket sales are bigger than anything we have ever done in the history of the country, in terms of sports.\\nMr. Infantino. For certain.\\nQ. And the audience is going to be huge.\\nThe President. The audience is going to be tremendous.\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. Yes.\\nMr. Infantino. Six billion people.\\nThe President. [Inaudible]\\nQ. Six billion? That's amazing.\\nMr. Infantino. Six billion people.\\nAnd today, one billion.\\nQ. Wow.\\nMr. Infantino. [Inaudible]\\nQ. Enjoy show time. Thank you so much.\\nThe President. [Inaudible]\\nQ. Mr. President, how are you? Just a quick—[inaudible].\\nQ. This is for Telemundo.\\nThe President. How are you?\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\nQ. Hello, Mr. President. How are you? This for Telemundo.\\nThe President. How are you? Good.\\nQ. How are you?\\nThe President. Very good. Thank you.\\nQ. How does it feel to have the most important event of sports—that global—in the U.S.?\\nThe President. Well, we do. And right at the Kennedy Center. I'm Chairman of the Kennedy Center. And I hear the Kennedy Center is doing a very good job, so it feels great. Really good.\\nAnd Telemundo is doing a good job, too. Thank you.\\nQ. Thank you.\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. What is the significance of hosting the FIFA World Cup this year?\\nThe President. It's a—in terms of sports, I would say the ultimate. There is no sport like this. It's the biggest sport in the world. And we are setting every record. You know, our ticket sales have gone and set every—every sport—no matter what it is, we've set the record. So—and every though it's very early, there's no ball being kicked yet, but we've already set a ticket sales record.\\nArgentina National Team\\nQ. How do you see Argentinean team for this World Cup?\\nThe President. Well, I love Argentina. And your President is doing a very good job, as you know. Milei. You know that right? It's make Argentina great again. MAGA.\\nQ. And——\\nU.S. National Team\\nQ. Do you think the States are building a powerful team for next year?\\nThe President. Who?\\nQ. The States.\\nThe President. Oh, yes. Sure. I—you're going to have a lot of powerful teams. Everybody has a lot of powerful teams, but you're going to have a lot of great teams. [Inaudible]\\nU.S. Role in Hosting the 2026 World Cup\\nQ. Mr. President, what does it mean for you guys to host the World Cup right here in the U.S.?\\nThe President. I'm honored to host it. It's a great honor. I mean, it's turned out to be bigger than we thought. We're setting a record for ticket sales, the likes of which no sport has ever seen before.\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\\nThe President. But they have a little more speed.\\nBut no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\\nPopularity of Soccer in Latin America\\nQ. Mr. President, a message for the Latin America and soccer fans?\\nThe President. Yes, I am. And Latin America is great. And they have great soccer. So, good luck in the matches.\\n[A reporter asked a question in Spanish, which was translated by an interpreter as follows.]\\nU.S. Visas for World Cup Ticketholders\\nQ. Who is going to be in—[inaudible]—about these visas for the—these fans that want to come here to the World Cup?\\nThe President. Well, we're going to make it very easy for them. We're working on that right now. We're going to make it very easy. It's going to be a very easy process.\\nQ. Okay. Say, hi to Colombia over there.\\nThe President. Hello. Is that Colombia?\\nQ. Yes.\\nThe President. I love Colombia. Hello, Colombia. [Laughter]\\nQ. Okay. Okay. Muy bien.\\nThe President. So where are you from?\\nQ. Paraguay.\\nThe President. Oh.\\nQ. He's from Paraguay. Yes.\\nThe President. Very good. I love it. I—it's a beautiful country. We get along very well with them. We do a little trade deal with them, and they like us. And that's what's happening.\\nQ. Panama.\\nThe President. Where?\\nVery good. I like the canal. [Laughter] That canal is pretty good.\\n[A reporter spoke in Spanish; no translation was provided.]\\n2026 World Cup\\nThe President. What?\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. Well, it's going to be incredible. The event is going to be very good. Just this event alone—it's at the Kennedy Center. I see you have it fixed up perfectly.\\nMr. Infantino. It will set the tone.\\nThe President. Right? It's beautiful.\\nMr. Infantino. It's beautiful.\\nThe President. It's a beautiful place.\\nHave a good time.\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President.\\n[A reporter spoke in Spanish; no translation was provided.]\\nMr. Infantino. No, gracias. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. It's great.\\nJohn F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts/Renovation Work\\nQ. Mr. President, the U.S. press?\\nThe President. Thank you, everybody, very much. It's a great honor. This has been an honor for a lot of reasons. Number one, they've sold more tickets than any event has ever sold already—long before the kickoff.\\nAnd number two, we've done a lot of work at the Kennedy Center. It was falling apart, and now it's pretty much back. And we'll get it back within the next 4 or 5 months through construction, and—but you see the way it looks.\\nAnd Gianni is just telling me—who's done an incredible job, by the way. He's just telling, you know, how good a job we've done.\\nMr. Infantino. That's right.\\nThe President. You can look at the walls. The marble was broken. Everything was a mess. And we've really taken the Kennedy Center—a lot of people thought it was going to be ripped down, and we did just the opposite. So we've done a really great renovation job on it. And over the next 3, 4 months, it will be complete. And we're honored to have it here, and it's been—it's been very special.\\nWe've set a record on ticket sales, as you probably heard, already, even way before—long before the event itself. And we're working with Canada, and we're working with Mexico. And it's been a really spectacular—so far, it's been spectacular.\\nDaniel [Daniel Baldwin, One America News Network], do you have a question?\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. What are your expectations? You once said that the FIFA World Cup is an opportunity to put—a once-in-a-lifetime opportunity to put the greatness of the United States on display.\\nThe President. Well, I think—\\nQ. One billion eyeballs will be watching, Mr. President.\\nThe President. Yes, I—think——\\nQ. What will they here today?\\nThe President. Even today, I understand. I hear that, you know——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——I know we're a little late to get in there, but——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——that's okay.\\nMr. Infantino. They wait.\\nThe President. So all my friends, I guess they have to wait. They have no choice, right? [Laughter]\\nMr. Infantino. Yes, they wait.\\nThe President. But no, the numbers are incredible. I hear today's numbers are——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——very big. I hope CNN is covering this.\\nQ. One billion eyeballs.\\nMr. Infantino. Today, 1 billion eyeballs.\\nThe President. Today's numbers are very, very big.\\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize/The President's Foreign Policy\\nQ. We are covering it. And you're expected to get the FIFA Peace Prize, Mr. President. What would you say to people who say that prize might conflict with your pledge to strike Venezuela?\\nThe President. Well, I think the peace prize—I mean, I settled eight wars. I don't know that I'm getting it. I haven't been officially noticed. I've been hearing about a peace prize, and I'm here to represent our country in a different sense. But I can tell you, I did settle eight wars, and we have a ninth coming, but—which nobody has ever done before.\\nBut I want to really save lives. I don't need prizes. I need to save lives. And we're saving a lot of lives. And I've saved millions and millions of lives, and that's really what I want to do.\\nAnd I also want to run a great country. And the United States right now is the hottest country anywhere in the world. And 1 year ago, it was dead. We had a dead country, and now we have the hottest country anywhere in the world.\\nQ. Mr. President, will you——\\nThe President's Meeting With President Claudia Sheinbaum Pardo of Mexico and Prime Minister Mark Carney of Canada\\nQ. What are you going to discuss with Canada and Mexico, Mr.—what are you going to discuss with the leaders of Canada and Mexico?\\nThe President. Well, we're getting—we're going to meet with both. And we're getting along very well. You know, we're getting along very well. I don't know. I think we have a meeting set up for some time after the event.\\nQ. Will you discuss trade?\\nThe President. Yes, we'll discuss trade. We—get along very well.\\nThank you, everybody, very much.\\nQ. Will you pardon any other Honduran officials?\\nQ. Do you want them to keep trying to indict Ms. James?\\n\\nNOTE: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. In his remarks, he referred to Trey Yingst, chief foreign correspondent, Fox News Channel; Cristiano Ronaldo, forward for Saudi Pro League club Al-Nass and Portugal's national soccer team; and Lionel Messi, forward for Major League Soccer club Inter Miami and Argentina's national team. A reporter referred to New York State Attorney General Letitia James. The transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\n\\nSource URL: https://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/documents/remarks-exchange-with-reporters-prior-the-2026-federation-internationale-des-associations\\n\\n\\n[defendant] DX-3 GovInfo/OFR pre-event transcript excerpt\\nSource: GovInfo, DCPD202501162, Office of the Federal Register / National Archives and Records Administration.\\nURL: https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/DCPD-202501162/html/DCPD-202501162.htm\\nTitle: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\nEvent date: December 5, 2025.\\n\\nRelevant extracted page text:\\n\\\"Administration of Donald J. Trump, 2025\\\"\\n\\\"Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw December 5, 2025\\\"\\n\\\"[The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\\\"\\n\\nUnder the section \\\"The President's Interest in Soccer\\\":\\n\\\"Q. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\\\"\\n\\\"The President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\\\\\\\"football,\\\\\\\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\\\"\\n\\\"Thank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\\\"\\n\\nAdditional relevant extracted page text:\\n\\\"The President's Interest in Soccer\\\"\\n\\\"Q. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\\\"\\n\\\"The President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\\\"\\n\\\"Mr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\\\"\\n\\\"The President. But they have a little more speed. But no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\\\"\\n\\nGovInfo note:\\n\\\"NOTE: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. In his remarks, he referred to Trey Yingst, chief foreign correspondent, Fox News Channel; Cristiano Ronaldo, forward for Saudi Pro League club Al-Nass and Portugal's national soccer team; and Lionel Messi, forward for Major League Soccer club Inter Miami and Argentina's national team. A reporter referred to New York State Attorney General Letitia James. The transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\\"\\n\\nGovInfo content details page also identifies category \\\"Interviews With the News Media : Exchanges with reporters, Washington, DC,\\\" subjects including \\\"Federation Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) World Cup,\\\" \\\"John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts,\\\" and \\\"Soccer,\\\" and names including \\\"Ronaldo, Cristiano\\\" and \\\"Messi, Lionel.\\\"\\n\\n[defendant] DX-4 PRESMENTION/NEWMENTION terms\\n                                         NEWMENTION\\n\\nScope: These rules shall apply to this contract.\\n\\nUnderlying: The Underlying for this Contract is words used by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nRevisions to the Underlying made after Expiration will not be accounted for in determining the\\nExpiration Value.\\n\\nSource Agency: The Source Agencies are \\u003csource\\u003e.\\n\\nType: The type of Contract is an Event Contract.\\n\\nIssuance: After the initial Contract, Contract iterations will be listed on an as-needed basis at\\nthe discretion of the Exchange and corresponding to the risk management needs of Members.\\n\\n\\u003centity\\u003e: \\u003centity\\u003e refers to the speaker, writer, performer, or communicator specified by the\\nExchange. This may include (but is not limited to): a specific named individual, multiple\\nindividuals specified using AND/OR logic, an individual identified by position or title, a group,\\nband, team or collective entity, a specified member or members of a group, an organization,\\ncompany, or institutional entity, or any combination of the aforementioned.\\n\\nWhen \\u003centity\\u003e is defined by a position or title, the Contract tracks whoever holds that position\\nduring \\u003ctime period\\u003e, even if the individual holding the position changes. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a\\nspecific named individual, the identity remains consistent throughout. Name changes (e.g.,\\nstage names, married names) do not create a new entity. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a group or\\norganization and the Contract does not specify particular members, any official\\ncommunication or statement by any member or designated spokesperson counts. When using\\nAND logic, all specified entities must independently say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e. When\\nusing OR logic, at least one of the specified entities must say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nThe Exchange may specify additional conditions such as “at least X members of” a group or\\n“the majority of” a group.\\n\\n\\u003csource\\u003e: \\u003csource\\u003e refers to a Source Agency or ordered collection of Source Agencies\\nspecified by the Exchange at the time of Contract listing, which will be incorporated into the\\nSource Agency hierarchy above and used to determine the occurrence of the Underlying.\\n\\u003csource\\u003e may refer to a singular agency, multiple agencies, an agency by distinguishing\\ncharacteristics, by category or type (e.g., “official government statistical body,” “primary wire\\nservice”), or any combination thereof. When multiple agencies are specified, they may be\\napplied in the hierarchical order designated by the Exchange if so specified, with the highest-\\nranked available and responsive agency taking precedence for purposes of determining the\\nExpiration Value. A lower-ranked agency shall only be consulted if all higher-ranked agencies\\nare unavailable, unresponsive, have not reported on the Underlying by the Expiration time, or\\nif the Exchange, in its sole discretion, determines that a higher-ranked agency’s reporting is\\nincomplete, erroneous, or otherwise insufficient to determine the Expiration Value. If \\u003csource\\u003e\\ndesignates multiple agencies without specifying a hierarchical order, the Exchange shall\\nresolve any conflict between reporting agencies at its sole discretion.\\n\\n\\u003cword\\u003e: \\u003cword\\u003e refers to the particular word or phrase potentially to be mentioned by\\n\\u003centity\\u003e. It may refer to a word being said a minimum number of times. It may also refer to\\none of multiple words/phrases, any of which are acceptable (e.g., “Doge/Dogecoin”).\\n\\f\\u003ctime period\\u003e: \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific range of time, event or discrete date and\\ntime specified by the Exchange. This may be defined by, but is not limited to: a specific event\\nor context (e.g., “during the State of the Union address”), exact dates or times, relative time\\nmarkers (e.g., “before July 1, 2027,” “in Q1 2026”), event-based periods (e.g., “during any\\ncampaign rally in October 2026,” “during the awards ceremony”), and broader intervals (e.g.,\\n“Q1–Q2 2027,” “January–March 2026”).\\n\\nUnless stated otherwise, “Between” is inclusive of both endpoints, while “before” and “after”\\nexclude the specified date. \\u003ctime period\\u003e may also refer to “Any” or “None”, to multiple dates\\n(even if non-consecutive), or to a singular and discrete date or time.\\n\\nWhen \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event (such as an address, speech, performance, or\\nbroadcast), the Exchange may specify what is included, including whether it includes both live\\nand pre-recorded segments (including whether advertisements are included). Where a\\ntimezone is not specified, ET is assumed.\\n\\n\\nPayout Criterion: The Payout Criterion for the Contract encompasses the Expiration Values that\\n\\u003cword\\u003e is said by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n\\n\\nThe word must appear as a distinct, standalone unit, not buried inside another word. Plural\\nand possessive noun forms count. Other grammatical changes (tense, conjugation, derivation)\\ndo not. If \\u003cword\\u003e appears separated from other words by a space or hyphen or in a\\ncompound form with a space or hyphen, it counts. If \\u003cword\\u003e is fused into a single\\nunhyphenated word, it does not count.\\n\\nIf \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled, and the market contains a\\nstrike stating “Event does not qualify/occur”, such a strike shall resolve “Yes” and all others\\n“No”. If \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled but such strikes are NOT\\nlisted, the Contracts will resolve to the last fair price determined at the discretion of the\\nExchange. If the event is postponed, and such a postponement is announced by the end of the\\nfollowing calendar day to be rescheduled to a time within 14 calendar days, the markets shall\\nremain open. If the event captured in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast, the\\nExchange may keep the market open for 24 hours for the release of an official recording.\\nFurther granular details on conditions for these Contracts is available below.\\n\\nAdditional clarification(s):\\n\\n     Possessive noun forms of \\u003cword\\u003e, plurals, and possessive plural noun forms are\\n     INCLUDED:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigrants” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Egg” → “eggs’ shells” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Russia” → “Russia’s” counts, “Russian” does not\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e exists only in adjective form, no plural form exists:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Economic” → “Economics” does not count (“Economic” is an adjective\\n          for which “Economics” is not a plural)\\n     Plural nouns occurring within proper nouns and noun phrases are included:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Cat” → “Cats the musical” counts\\n\\f    Grammatical variations beyond plurals/possessives are NOT included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigration” does NOT count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Run” → “Running” or “Ran” do NOT count\\n    When \\u003cword\\u003e specifies a plural form, the singular does NOT count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Veterans” → “Veteran” does NOT count\\n    Words that are spelled the same as the plural form of \\u003cword\\u003e (if such exists) but are\\n    themselves not a plural noun are included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Wind” → “Winds up the clock” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Border” → “The United States has strong borders” counts\\n    Open compounds (words separated by spaces) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fire station” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “couch” → “couch potato” counts\\n    Hyphenated compounds (words connected by hyphens) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Palestine” → “pro-Palestine” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fat” → “non-fat” counts\\n    Closed compounds (single word, no spaces/hyphens) do not count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire” does not count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firefighter” does not count\\n    Multi-word \\u003cword\\u003e in larger constructions: When \\u003cword\\u003e is a multi-word phrase\\n    appearing within a hyphenated construction, it counts only if \\u003cword\\u003e appears as a\\n    complete, unmodified element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “New York” → “New York-based” counts (complete element)\\n    Portmanteaus (words blended from two words where parts of each are combined) are\\n    NOT included unless the portmanteau clearly contains \\u003cword\\u003e as a distinct, unaltered\\n    element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “MAGA” → “MAGA-nificent” counts (MAGA appears as distinct element)\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “magnificent” → “MAGA-nificent” does NOT count (portmanteau blend)\\n\\nDictionary determination: Both the Merriam-Webster Dictionary (available online) AND the\\nOxford English Dictionary shall be used to determine compound type and/or conventional\\nspelling patterns. Inclusion in either dictionary as an open or hyphenated compound shall\\nsatisfy the Payout Criterion. If neither provides clarity (or the word is not included),\\ndetermination is based on whether written as single unit (closed/doesn’t count) vs. spaces or\\nhyphens (open or hyphenated/counts) and/or context and previous usage.\\n\\nPHONETIC EQUIVALENCIES\\n\\n    Homophones (same sound, different spelling) do not count:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “write” → “right” does not count\\n    Homonyms and homographs (same spelling) COUNT regardless of meaning or\\n    pronunciation:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “bass” → both “bass guitar” and “bass fishing” count\\n    Proper and common nouns are treated identically:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Apple” → both “Apple Inc.” and “apple” (fruit) count\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Will” → both “Will Smith” and “I will go” count\\n    Minor unintentional mispronunciations COUNT if context makes intent clear:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Mamdani” → “Mandani” counts\\n    Severe mispronunciations that make \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable do NOT count.\\n    Trademarked spellings do not count, even when pronounced identically, unless the word\\n\\fitself is the same:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “lift” → “Lyft” (pronounced “lift”) does not count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “uber” → “Uber” counts\\nWords with non-standard transliteration to English count within reason, provided they are\\nphonetically equivalent:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Zelensky” → any of “Zelenski,” “Zelenskii,” “Zelensky,” or “Zelenskiy”\\n      count if pronounced equivalently\\nContractions do not count for their constituent words unless otherwise explicitly specified\\nby the Exchange:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “not” → “won’t,” “can’t,” “don’t,” “isn’t” do not count\\nNumbers spoken as words COUNT, when spoken exactly (not part of a larger number):\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “five” → saying “five” or reading “$5” aloud as “five dollars” counts,\\n      saying “five hundred” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “410” → “four hundred ten”, “four one zero” or “four ten” counts\\nOrdinals COUNT when \\u003cword\\u003e is written numerically OR a phrase that includes a\\nnumber:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “January 6” → “January 6th” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “3” (written numerically) → “3rd” (spoken as “third”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Eight War” → “8 Wars” and “Eighth War” will count\\nCardinal and ordinal number words are distinct:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “one” → “first” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “first” → “one” does NOT count\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count when pronunciation or letter-by-letter spelling\\nmatches \\u003cword\\u003e:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “NASA” (pronounced “NAH-suh”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “N-A-S-A” (spelled out) counts\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count as \\u003cword\\u003e when pronounced as the full word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Doctor” → “Dr.” (pronounced “Doctor”) counts\\nExpanded forms of acronyms do NOT count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “AI” → “artificial intelligence” does not count\\nWords in foreign languages do NOT count unless they are perfect cognates with an\\nEnglish word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fuego” (Spanish) does NOT count\\nEnglish words within foreign sentences count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “policy” → “Nuestra policy es clara” counts\\n\\u003cword\\u003e in organization/company names counts:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Securities” → “Bank of America Securities” counts\\nWords in URLs, emails, handles, and hashtags (exclusive of domain structure, email\\nprovider or symbols) are treated as compounds when spoken as complete words, with the\\ntype of compound subject to aforementioned rules:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firestation.com” pronounced “fire station dot com” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire.com” pronounced “wildfire dot com” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “apple” → “apple.com” pronounced “apple dot com” does count\\n      When presented in URL, email, handle, or hashtag form, \\u003cword\\u003e shall be treated as\\n      a compound, not a multi-word word\\nSung, rapped, or poetic words COUNT if phonetically recognizable:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “money” → “moneyyy” (extended in rap) counts\\n      Extreme distortion making \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable does NOT count.\\nPhonetic alphabet spelling (“Foxtrot India Romeo Echo” for “FIRE”) does NOT count.\\n\\fCANCELLATIONS AND DELAYS\\n\\n   The Exchange may list an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike for any Contract. If listed,\\n   such a strike refers to the structural conditions of the market, and is NOT adjudicated as a\\n   \\u003cword\\u003e needing to be said by or validated by having been said by \\u003centity\\u003e. If listed, this\\n   strike resolves to “Yes” whenever the event fails to occur or qualify under the Payout\\n   Criterion, or any other circumstance prevents normal resolution.\\n   If no such strike is listed, and \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, the following rules\\n   apply if the event is cancelled, postponed, rescheduled, or materially altered (including\\n   being closed to press) such that no video is released within one calendar day of the\\n   original start time of the event:\\n         If the event is cancelled, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price determined in\\n         the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         If the event is postponed or rescheduled, the outcome depends on whether a new\\n         date is publicly announced within one calendar day (i.e. if the event was scheduled\\n         to begin on Monday, any time up to 11:59PM on Tuesday falls within this period) of\\n         the originally scheduled start time:\\n               If no new date is announced within one calendar day, the Contract will resolve\\n               to the last fair price determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n               If a new date is announced within one calendar day, the outcome depends on\\n               when the rescheduled event is set to occur:\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls within fourteen (14) calendar days of the\\n                     originally scheduled date, the Contract shall remain open and \\u003cword\\u003e\\n                     stated during the rescheduled event will count.\\n                           The fourteen-day window begins at 12:00 AM ET on the originally\\n                           scheduled date and ends at 11:59 PM ET fourteen days later, unless\\n                           an alternate timezone is explicitly specified.\\n                           Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the State of the Union on January\\n                           15, 2026” rescheduled to January 20, 2026 → words spoken during\\n                           the rescheduled address count.\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls more than fourteen (14) calendar days after\\n                     the originally scheduled date, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price\\n                     determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         Any Contract that cannot be resolved through the Source Agency hierarchy will\\n         instead be settled at the Last Fair Price. The Exchange will disclose the methodology\\n         used to determine the Last Fair Price (e.g., Last Traded Price, Time-Weighted\\n         Average Price) at the time of Issuance.\\n         If an event begins but is interrupted, abbreviated, or ends prematurely, words\\n         stated by \\u003centity\\u003e during the portion of the event that did occur will count and the\\n         market will otherwise resolve.\\n   If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window but the venue, format, or medium\\n   changes (e.g., moved to a different location, changed from in-person to virtual (with the\\n   exception of being closed to press)), words stated during the event will count.\\n   Special condition: Across both cases, whether an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike is\\n   listed or not, if the event specified as or in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast (or\\n   relayed as such) but the live stream/broadcast does not occur, the Exchange will instead\\n   use an officially released recording as the Underlying, and may delay resolution by up to\\n   one calendar day to allow for the release of such a recording.\\n\\f          If partial snippets are released, Contracts on words that do not appear will be\\n          resolved to last fair price, and Contracts on those that do will be resolved to “Yes”.\\n          If no recording is released, the relevant outcomes triggered by the\\n          presence/absence of an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike shall occur as outlined\\n          above.\\n\\nTECHNICAL DETAILS (UNLESS OTHERWISE SPECIFIED)\\n\\n     When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, pre-recorded content broadcast,\\n     streamed, or published as part of that event is included if presented as part of the official\\n     presentation.\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the concert” with pre-recorded video interlude\\n          where entity speaks → words from interlude count\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the television appearance” with pre-taped\\n          segment aired during broadcast → words from segment count\\n     Behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are NOT\\n     included unless officially broadcast or published as part of \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n     Subtitles and captions that display \\u003cword\\u003e on screen but are not spoken aloud by\\n     \\u003centity\\u003e do NOT count.\\n     Sign language interpretation or usage by entity does NOT count as saying \\u003cword\\u003e unless\\n     the Contract explicitly specifies that sign language counts.\\n     Text that entity displays on screen (presentation slides, teleprompter visible to audience,\\n     signatures) does NOT count unless entity reads it aloud.\\n     Content generated by AI, deepfakes, or synthetic voice technology impersonating entity\\n     does NOT count unless the synthetic content is officially commissioned, authorized, or\\n     published by entity, OR the Contract explicitly specifies that AI-generated content counts.\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e is muted due to technical failure or censorship it shall not count unless\\n     corroborating contextual evidence (including surrounding speech, or an official\\n     uncensored recording or transcript) confirms that \\u003centity\\u003e specifically uttered \\u003cword\\u003e\\n     during the muted period.\\n\\nMinimum Tick: The Minimum Tick size for the Contract shall be $0.01.\\n\\nPosition Accountability Level: The Position Accountability Level for the Contract shall be\\n$25,000 per strike, per Member.\\n\\nLast Trading Date: The Last Trading Date of the Contract will be the Expiration Date. The Last\\nTrading Time will be the Expiration time.\\n\\nSettlement Date: The Settlement Date of the Contract shall be no later than the day after the\\nExpiration Date, unless the Market Outcome is under review pursuant to Rule 7.1.\\n\\nExpiration Date: When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event: The latest Expiration Date of\\nthe Contract shall be fourteen (14) calendar days after the originally scheduled date of the\\nevent. If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window, expiration will be moved to an\\nearlier date and time in accordance with Rule 7.2. When \\u003ctime period\\u003e is defined by specific\\ndates: The latest Expiration Date of the Contract shall be two weeks after the end of \\u003ctime\\nperiod\\u003e. If an event described in the Payout Criterion occurs and a consensus has been\\nreached on all terms, then expiration will be moved to an earlier date and time in accordance\\nwith Rule 7.2.\\n\\fExpiration time: The Expiration time of the Contract shall be 10:00 AM ET.\\n\\nSettlement Value: The Settlement Value for this Contract is $1.00.\\n\\nExpiration Value: The Expiration Value is the value of the Underlying as documented by the\\nSource Agency on the Expiration Date at the Expiration time.\\n\\nContingencies: Before Settlement, Kalshi may, at its sole discretion, initiate the Market\\nOutcome Review Process pursuant to Rule 7.1 of the Rulebook. If an Expiration Value cannot\\nbe determined on the Expiration Date, Kalshi has the right to determine payouts pursuant to\\nRule 7.1 in the Rulebook.\\n\\f\\n\\n[defendant] DX-5 Formal draw archive note\\nSource checked: Roll Call / Factba.se archive\\n\\nArchive title: Remarks: Donald Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing in Washington - December 5, 2025\\n\\nArchive URL: https://rollcall.com/factbase/trump/transcript/donald-trump-remarks-fifa-world-cup-drawing-december-5-2025/\\n\\nWhat this file establishes:\\n\\nThere is a separate archived transcript page for Trump's formal attendance remarks at the draw.\\n\\nWhat this file does not establish:\\n\\nThis session could not retrieve the full transcript text from that archive.  The page is password-protected.  This example therefore does not claim, from local files alone, whether the formal program transcript does or does not contain the word \\\"Ronaldo.\\\"\\n\\nWhy this matters:\\n\\nThe complaint does not need to prove that the formal program omitted the strike.  It needs to show that Trump said \\\"Ronaldo\\\" in event-linked remarks and that the market boundary reasonably includes those remarks.  The formal archive remains relevant because it marks the distinction between the pre-event reporter exchange and the formal program.\\n\\n\\n[defendant] DX-6 Formal Roll Call/Factba.se transcript extraction\\nSource: Roll Call / Factba.se\\nURL: https://rollcall.com/factbase/trump/transcript/donald-trump-remarks-fifa-world-cup-drawing-december-5-2025/\\nCaptured page title: Remarks: Donald Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing in Washington - December 5, 2025\\n\\nRendered page metadata excerpt:\\nTopics: Sport; Sport \\u003e Competition Discipline \\u003e Soccer; Lifestyle and Leisure \\u003e Leisure \\u003e Game.\\nEntities listed: bowl; deal; Donald J. Trump; FIFA World Cup; Mark Carney; place; President; trophy; United States; way.\\nSpeakers listed: Gianni Infantino, Donald Trump, Mark Carney, Claudia Sheinbaum.\\nSpeaker statistics excerpt: Donald Trump said 25 sentences of a total of 141 sentences; Donald Trump said 274 words of a total of 1009 words; Donald Trump talked 92 seconds of a total of 484 seconds.\\n\\nFormal transcript excerpt at start of draw:\\nMark Carney, 00:00:00-00:00:02: Thank you, my friend.\\nGianni Infantino, 00:00:50-00:01:22: So this is the World Cup trophy. This is the official bowl for the World Cup and we are now going to do the draw, ladies and gentlemen. But before that, as is customary, there is always a question that the moderator asks the draw assistant. So I would like to start with Mr. Carney. How big a deal is it to co-host the World Cup for Canada?\\n\\nFormal transcript excerpt of Trump's soccer answer:\\nDonald Trump, 00:03:14-00:03:32: Well, for years, Gianni, they've thought soccer or football would be so big, so fast. And I remember, I shouldn't say this because it was a long time ago, but I remember watching Pele play on a team called the Cosmos, Pele, who was fantastic, as you know. I assume one of the greats.\\n\\nText-extraction/search notes:\\nLocal Python urllib retrieval of the page returned HTTP 200 for the source URL and extracted approximately 175,864 characters of page text with Python html.parser. Case-sensitive searches in the extracted page text returned no occurrence of \\\"Ronaldo\\\" and no occurrence of \\\"Messi\\\". The same terms were not found using the browser page find function on the rendered page.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R1 Defendant formal transcript extraction for limited rebuttal use\\nSource: Roll Call / Factba.se\\nURL: https://rollcall.com/factbase/trump/transcript/donald-trump-remarks-fifa-world-cup-drawing-december-5-2025/\\nCaptured page title: Remarks: Donald Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing in Washington - December 5, 2025\\n\\nRendered page metadata excerpt:\\nTopics: Sport; Sport \\u003e Competition Discipline \\u003e Soccer; Lifestyle and Leisure \\u003e Leisure \\u003e Game.\\nEntities listed: bowl; deal; Donald J. Trump; FIFA World Cup; Mark Carney; place; President; trophy; United States; way.\\nSpeakers listed: Gianni Infantino, Donald Trump, Mark Carney, Claudia Sheinbaum.\\nSpeaker statistics excerpt: Donald Trump said 25 sentences of a total of 141 sentences; Donald Trump said 274 words of a total of 1009 words; Donald Trump talked 92 seconds of a total of 484 seconds.\\n\\nFormal transcript excerpt at start of draw:\\nMark Carney, 00:00:00-00:00:02: Thank you, my friend.\\nGianni Infantino, 00:00:50-00:01:22: So this is the World Cup trophy. This is the official bowl for the World Cup and we are now going to do the draw, ladies and gentlemen. But before that, as is customary, there is always a question that the moderator asks the draw assistant. So I would like to start with Mr. Carney. How big a deal is it to co-host the World Cup for Canada?\\n\\nFormal transcript excerpt of Trump's soccer answer:\\nDonald Trump, 00:03:14-00:03:32: Well, for years, Gianni, they've thought soccer or football would be so big, so fast. And I remember, I shouldn't say this because it was a long time ago, but I remember watching Pele play on a team called the Cosmos, Pele, who was fantastic, as you know. I assume one of the greats.\\n\\nText-extraction/search notes:\\nLocal Python urllib retrieval of the page returned HTTP 200 for the source URL and extracted approximately 175,864 characters of page text with Python html.parser. Case-sensitive searches in the extracted page text returned no occurrence of \\\"Ronaldo\\\" and no occurrence of \\\"Messi\\\". The same terms were not found using the browser page find function on the rendered page.\\n\\nSubmitted evidence:\\n[plaintiff arguments] GovInfo DCPD202501162 transcript excerpt and metadata (ev_3fc783920414_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-3fc783920414)\\nSource: https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/DCPD-202501162/html/DCPD-202501162.htm\\nSHA-256: `3fc783920414399098d86210070dd9fe83c14fe1dbded1a56a554f8f4b3448f2`\\nBytes: 2641\\nRelevance: Official government transcript source corroborating that Trump spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center before the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw and said the strike word Ronaldo in World-Cup-related remarks.\\n\\n[defendant arguments] Roll Call/Factba.se formal FIFA World Cup Drawing transcript extraction (ev_fbb53e87ccb3_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-fbb53e87ccb3)\\nSource: https://rollcall.com/factbase/trump/transcript/donald-trump-remarks-fifa-world-cup-drawing-december-5-2025/\\nSHA-256: `fbb53e87ccb3f4381fc2bdc06ac2f2a1ea3848aadde56122b22d34dfbdf4533b`\\nBytes: 2032\\nRelevance: Formal drawing-program transcript evidence showing a separate formal Draw source from the pre-event reporter exchange; the extracted page text contains no occurrence of Ronaldo or Messi, supporting defendant's event-boundary argument.\\n\\nTechnical reports:\\n[plaintiff] Plaintiff source and adverse-search ledger\\nChecked the visible case packet and then searched official/source-specific repositories. GovInfo DCPD202501162 was opened and preserved as submitted evidence; it corroborates the packet transcript, source metadata, location, event date, and Ronaldo passages. The Roll Call/Factba.se formal drawing page rendered despite the packet's password-protection note; browser find searches for 'Ronaldo,' 'Cristiano,' and 'Messi' returned no matches. Plaintiff therefore treats the formal-program transcript as an adverse boundary check, not as proof of a formal-stage mention. The remaining dispute is contractual scope: whether the market clearly excluded public event-linked venue remarks immediately before the formal program.\\n\\n[defendant] Defense source-check ledger\\nDefendant searched for the formal Roll Call/Factba.se transcript identified by the case packet, opened the rendered Roll Call page, and fetched it locally with Python urllib. The fetch returned HTTP 200 for the formal FIFA World Cup Drawing transcript page. Text extraction produced approximately 175,864 characters; searches for \\\"Ronaldo\\\" and \\\"Messi\\\" returned no occurrences. The retrieval also captured formal-program excerpts, including Infantino's statement that \\\"we are now going to do the draw\\\" and Trump's formal soccer answer mentioning Pele rather than Ronaldo. The focused extraction was submitted and accepted as ev_fbb53e87ccb3_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-fbb53e87ccb3.\\n\\nCall submit_council_vote with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated.\\nKeep the rationale brief: no more than three sentences.\\n\\nCouncil API instructions:\\nYou are a council member. Decide the proposition from the admitted record.\\nYou may examine admitted evidence through read-only tools when exact bytes, metadata, or exhibit contents matter.\\nDo not search the web, introduce new facts, create new evidence, or upload evidence.\\nWhen ready, call submit_council_vote exactly once with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated and a concise rationale.\\n\",\"state\":\"ready\",\"status\":\"ready\",\"tools\":[{\"description\":\"Return the current visible arbitration record for this council member.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"get_case\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"List visible immutable record evidence.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"list_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Return metadata and read limits for one visible evidence item.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"stat_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Read a bounded byte range from one visible evidence item as base64.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"length\":{\"minimum\":1,\"type\":\"integer\"},\"offset\":{\"minimum\":0,\"type\":\"integer\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\",\"offset\",\"length\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"read_evidence_range\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Submit one council vote for the current deliberation opportunity.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"rationale\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"vote\":{\"enum\":[\"demonstrated\",\"not_demonstrated\"],\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"vote\",\"rationale\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"submit_council_vote\",\"read_only\":false}],\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":false,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-29T19:58:02.156322961Z\",\"deliberation_round\":1,\"member_id\":\"C2\",\"opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C2\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"remaining_ms\":887183,\"role_id\":\"council\",\"turn_number\":10},\"wait\":{\"reason\":\"ready\",\"state_version\":12,\"version\":15}}"}],"details":{"mode":"call","mcpResult":{"content":[{"type":"text","text":"ok: true\nstatus: ready\nstate: ready\nmessage: An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\nafter_version: 15\nafter_opportunity_id: deliberation:1:C2\nmember_id: C2\ncase_id: arb-ex03-20260629192557\nwait_reason: ready\nphase: deliberation\nopportunity_id: deliberation:1:C2\nremaining_ms: 887183\nattempts_remaining: 3\njson: {\"after_opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C2\",\"after_version\":15,\"case_id\":\"arb-ex03-20260629192557\",\"limits\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"max_evidence_read_bytes\":65536,\"max_evidence_read_bytes_per_opportunity\":524288,\"max_evidence_reads_per_opportunity\":32,\"max_response_bytes\":131072,\"remaining_evidence_read_bytes_for_opportunity\":524288,\"remaining_evidence_reads_for_opportunity\":32},\"member_id\":\"C2\",\"message\":\"An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\",\"ok\":true,\"prompt\":\"Role: council member\\nMember ID: C2\\nDeliberation round: 1\\nProposition: For the Kalshi market \\\"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\\", the strike \\\"Ronaldo\\\" should resolve Yes because Trump said \\\"Ronaldo\\\" in public remarks at the World Cup Draw venue immediately before the formal program, and the market wording plus the governing mention-market terms did not clearly exclude those event-linked remarks.\\nStandard of evidence: Preponderance of the evidence.\\nPersona:\\nYou are a careful juror and council member.\\n\\nEvaluate the record faithfully. Decide only from the evidence, the stated rules, and the applicable burden of proof. Do not favor either side, fill gaps with speculation, or ignore uncertainty.\\n\\nGive weight to reliable sources, direct evidence, consistent reasoning, and clear admissions. Discount unsupported claims, rhetorical force, irrelevant facts, and conclusions that exceed the record.\\n\\nWhen the evidence supports one answer, state it plainly. When the evidence is incomplete or balanced, say so. Be concise, honest, and exact.\\n\\nRecord:\\nOpenings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, this case is not mainly about whether the syllables were spoken. The case-packet transcript says they were. The real dispute is the market boundary: when Kalshi asked what Trump would say \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw,\\\" did that phrase clearly exclude his public, event-linked remarks at the World Cup Draw venue immediately before the formal program? On this record, it did not.\\n\\nThe market page fixes the contract at issue: the public title was \\\"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\\"; the contract family was PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION; the strike was \\\"Ronaldo\\\"; Kalshi challenged the resolution as No; and the requested resolution is Yes. That means the council's task is to apply the mention-market terms to that title and strike, not to import a narrower limitation that the market did not plainly announce.\\n\\nThe reporter-exchange packet is direct evidence on the word and setting. It is titled as remarks in an exchange with reporters prior to the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw, dated December 5, 2025. It places the President at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts, speaking with FIFA President Gianni Infantino and reporters in a sequence repeatedly labeled around the 2026 World Cup and the Draw. In that exchange, in a soccer discussion, Trump says he met Ronaldo, praises him, and uses \\\"Ronaldo\\\" as a distinct standalone word. Under the mention rules, a distinct standalone appearance of the strike is the kind of use that counts if it falls within the time period.\\n\\nThe terms matter because they do not say that an event market is limited only to scripted remarks from a formal stage segment. They define a time period as potentially an event or context, and they give the Exchange power to specify what is included when a time period refers to a specific event. They also distinguish official/public event content from behind-the-scenes, rehearsals, and unofficial recordings. That distinction helps plaintiff: the packet is not a rumor, rehearsal, private soundcheck, or leaked recording. It is a sourced public transcript of remarks at the event venue, immediately tied to the Draw. If Kalshi meant \\\"only the formal televised draw program after doors close\\\" or \\\"only remarks in the separate formal archive,\\\" it needed to say so clearly.\\n\\nI also want to be candid about what the packet does not yet prove. The formal-draw archive note says a separate archived transcript page exists for Trump's formal attendance remarks, but that the session could not retrieve the full text because the page was password-protected. So, at opening, plaintiff is not asking you to infer that the formal program itself contained \\\"Ronaldo.\\\" Nor does plaintiff need that inference. The Yes theory is that the qualifying period reasonably includes the public pre-program reporter exchange that was part of Trump's World Cup Draw appearance. The formal archive is relevant because it marks defendant's likely narrower boundary; it does not resolve the boundary in defendant's favor.\\n\\nProvenance and weight also favor treating the packet seriously at this stage. The market and terms files are system case-packet records. The reporter exchange includes a source URL to a public presidential transcript source and notes a corrected transcript date, while also acknowledging that some audio could not be verified because the audio was incomplete. That caveat may affect inaudible portions, but it does not erase the visible, contextual Ronaldo passage. Later, when evidence admission opens, the parties should preserve the official transcript source, any govinfo or Presidency Project copy, the market page capture, and any accessible formal-program transcript or video. The adverse check should ask whether the formal program omits the word, but omission there would matter only if the council first accepts the defense's artificially narrow reading of \\\"during.\\\"\\n\\nThe plaintiff's burden is preponderance. The record already points to a straightforward path to Yes: Trump, the specified entity, said the specified strike as a standalone word in public remarks linked to and immediately preceding the World Cup Draw at the venue; the market title and governing terms did not clearly exclude that event-linked exchange. On a fair reading of the contract the trader saw, the challenged No resolution should give way to Yes.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the defense opening is simple: this case is not won by proving that the word \\\"Ronaldo\\\" appears somewhere in a public transcript. The plaintiff must prove, by a preponderance, that the word was said during the market's specified event: the FIFA World Cup Draw.\\n\\nThe current packet leaves that critical link unproven. The market page does not say \\\"while Trump was at the venue,\\\" \\\"during a World Cup press availability,\\\" or \\\"during any remarks connected to the Draw.\\\" It says: \\\"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\\" The challenged resolution was No. The requested Yes theory therefore needs more than event-adjacent context; it needs a boundary showing that the reporter exchange was part of the Draw period the market asked traders to price.\\n\\nThe plaintiff's own best transcript cuts against that boundary. The case-packet file is titled \\\"Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw.\\\" It says the President's remarks were joined in progress, and the source note says portions could not be verified because the audio was incomplete. It places Trump at the Kennedy Center and includes World Cup topics, and yes, it contains \\\"Ronaldo\\\" as a standalone word in a soccer exchange. But its title and structure identify those remarks as an exchange with reporters prior to the Draw, not the formal Draw itself.\\n\\nThe terms do not rescue plaintiff from that distinction. They define a mention market around words used by the entity during the time period. A time period may be a specific event, and when it is a specific event, the Exchange may specify what is included. The technical details also distinguish official presentation content from behind-the-scenes, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings unless those are officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. Those provisions do not mean every public, nearby, event-related conversation becomes part of the event. They make the event boundary the central question.\\n\\nThe formal-draw archive note reinforces why the distinction matters. It reports that there is a separate archived transcript page for Trump's formal attendance remarks at the FIFA World Cup Drawing, but that the full text was not retrieved because the page was password-protected. That note does not prove the formal program omitted Ronaldo. It also does not prove the formal program included it. What it does show, at opening, is that the record itself separates the pre-event reporter exchange from the formal drawing remarks.\\n\\nSo the defense will focus the council on proof of inclusion, not mere association. If later phases produce a market page provision, official broadcast record, program transcript, video metadata, or source-agency material showing that the red-carpet reporter exchange was officially part of the FIFA World Cup Draw presentation for this market, the council can weigh that. If the later evidence instead shows a formal program with a separate pre-program press availability, then the correct result is No even though the word was spoken nearby.\\n\\nOn this opening record, plaintiff has shown a Ronaldo mention in remarks prior to the event. Plaintiff has not shown that those remarks occurred during the market event. The defense position is that Kalshi's No resolution follows the market wording and the mention-market terms unless plaintiff supplies that missing boundary proof.\\n\\nArguments:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the merits question is whether the contract clearly limited “during the FIFA World Cup Draw” to only the formal staged ceremony. Plaintiff submits that it did not, and the record now proves the Yes result by a preponderance.\\n\\nFirst, the market itself is broad. PX-1 identifies the public question as “What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?”, contract family PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION, strike “Ronaldo,” challenged resolution No, and requested resolution Yes. The market page does not say “during the formal televised ceremony,” “on the main stage only,” or “excluding public remarks immediately before the program at the venue.” That absence matters because Kalshi drafted the boundary traders had to price.\\n\\nSecond, the word was said. PX-2, the case-packet transcript, and PX-5, the GovInfo/OFR source excerpt, both show Trump used “Ronaldo” as a standalone word in soccer-related remarks. PX-5 is especially useful on provenance: it is the GovInfo Compilation of Presidential Documents source, published by the Office of the Federal Register/NARA, for DCPD202501162. It identifies the same event date, title, and source note, and it places the remarks at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center. In the relevant passage, Trump says he met Ronaldo, then says Ronaldo is great; later, when asked whether he played soccer or football, Trump says he was not Ronaldo or Messi. Either use satisfies the mention rule if the remarks fall within the market’s time period.\\n\\nThird, the remarks are event-linked in the way the market title reasonably covers. PX-2 and PX-5 are not private gossip, rehearsal, or an unofficial leak. They are public presidential remarks at the World Cup Draw venue, with FIFA President Infantino present, repeatedly discussing the Draw, the World Cup, ticket sales, the Kennedy Center, the audience, and the imminent program. The transcript itself includes headings such as “2026 World Cup Draw Event,” “2026 World Cup Draw Event/John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts,” and “2026 World Cup Draw/Ticket Sales for World Cup.” Trump and Infantino even discuss being a little late to “get in there” and the audience waiting. That sequence is not a random earlier interview; it is part of the public event appearance immediately surrounding the Draw.\\n\\nFourth, PX-3’s terms do not impose defendant’s formal-only line. They say the underlying is words used by the entity during the specified time period; a time period may be an event or context; and, when a time period refers to a specific event, the Exchange may specify what is included. They also say official/published content presented as part of the official presentation can count, while behind-the-scenes, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings do not count unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. Those exclusions show what this is not. The transcript is an official published record of public remarks at the event venue, not a hidden backstage clip. Nothing in PX-1 or PX-3 clearly tells traders that public, event-linked venue remarks immediately before the formal program are out.\\n\\nDefendant’s best point is PX-4 and the formal Roll Call/Factba.se page: there is a separate formal-drawing transcript, and my search found no “Ronaldo” there. Plaintiff does not hide that. But that adverse point proves only that the narrower formal-program source may omit the strike. It does not answer the contractual question. If Kalshi had meant to resolve solely by that formal transcript, it could have said so. Instead, the public market title used the broader phrase “during the FIFA World Cup Draw,” and the mention terms leave event boundaries to what the market clearly specifies.\\n\\nOn burden, plaintiff does not need absolute certainty or a formal-stage mention. Plaintiff must show it is more likely than not that the market wording plus terms include the event-linked remarks. The evidence satisfies that standard: PX-1 gives no exclusion; PX-2 and PX-5 prove the standalone Ronaldo mentions in public World Cup Draw venue remarks; PX-3 supplies a flexible event/time-period framework and excludes only categories unlike this source; PX-4 merely identifies the defense’s alternate formal-program boundary. The fair resolution is Yes.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the record now makes the defense point sharper, not weaker. Plaintiff has proved that Trump said \\\"Ronaldo\\\" in an official transcript of remarks connected to the World Cup Draw. Plaintiff has not proved that those remarks were during the market event.\\n\\nStart with the contract. DX/PX-1 gives the trader-facing question: \\\"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\\" It does not say \\\"at the Kennedy Center,\\\" \\\"on World Cup Draw day,\\\" \\\"in remarks prior to the Draw,\\\" or \\\"in any public press exchange associated with the Draw.\\\" For this strike to resolve Yes, the relevant mention must fall inside that specified time period.\\n\\nThe strongest evidence of the Ronaldo utterance is also the strongest evidence against plaintiff's boundary. PX-2 and PX-5 are titled \\\"Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw.\\\" PX-5, plaintiff's GovInfo/OFR source, confirms the same title, says the remarks were joined in progress, identifies the source as an exchange with the news media, and notes that some portions could not be verified because the audio was incomplete. That evidence proves an official pre-event reporter transcript. It does not prove the reporter exchange was the FIFA World Cup Draw.\\n\\nThe terms, PX-3, require words used by the entity during the specified time period. They permit an event or context as a time period, and they discuss what is included when the time period is a specific event. That framework does not turn all event-adjacent speech into event speech. The distinction between official presentation content and non-included behind-the-scenes or unofficial content matters because the question is not just whether a record is public or official. The question is whether this source was part of the market's event period. A public official transcript can still be a transcript of remarks prior to the event.\\n\\nDX-2 supplies the missing contrast. It is a focused extraction from the separate Roll Call/Factba.se formal FIFA World Cup Drawing transcript. That page is the formal source identified in the case-packet archive note. It is titled \\\"Remarks: Donald Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing in Washington - December 5, 2025.\\\" Its transcript begins with the formal drawing participants; at 00:00:50, Infantino says, \\\"This is the World Cup trophy\\\" and \\\"we are now going to do the draw.\\\" The page's Trump soccer answer mentions Pele and the Cosmos, not Ronaldo. The extracted page text was searched for both \\\"Ronaldo\\\" and \\\"Messi\\\" and neither appears.\\n\\nThat does not prove Trump never said Ronaldo anywhere at the venue. It proves the opposite boundary from plaintiff's: the formal Draw transcript is separate from the pre-event reporter exchange, and the formal transcript does not contain the strike. Plaintiff needs a bridge between those two sources. It has not offered one. There is no market page detail saying red-carpet or pre-program press remarks count. There is no official program metadata showing the reporter exchange was part of the Draw presentation. There is no source hierarchy provision selecting the pre-event reporter exchange over the formal Draw transcript for this market.\\n\\nPlaintiff argues ambiguity should favor Yes because Kalshi could have drafted a narrower rule. But this is a preponderance case about a challenged No resolution, not a penalty for every conceivable ambiguity. The ordinary reading of \\\"during the FIFA World Cup Draw\\\" is the draw program, not every public appearance immediately before it. The record's own labels preserve that ordinary line: \\\"Prior to\\\" on the Ronaldo source; \\\"Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing\\\" on the formal source; and a formal transcript that starts the draw and omits the strike.\\n\\nWeight and provenance also favor the defense on the decisive issue. PX-5 is official and useful, but it authenticates a pre-event reporter exchange. DX-2 is a captured formal transcript extraction from the source class identified in PX-4; its absence finding is limited but material. PX-4 was initially only a note that the formal page existed and could not be retrieved. We have now retrieved and searched it. The adverse check therefore confirms, rather than merely speculates, that the formal drawing transcript does not carry plaintiff's Ronaldo mention.\\n\\nThe council should resolve the proposition against plaintiff. The record shows Trump said Ronaldo before the FIFA World Cup Draw in an event-linked reporter exchange. It does not show he said Ronaldo during the FIFA World Cup Draw. On this market wording and these terms, the challenged No resolution should stand.\\n\\nRebuttals:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, defendant’s new formal-transcript extraction proves less than defendant needs.\\n\\nPlaintiff accepts the narrow fact defendant has now preserved: the Roll Call/Factba.se formal drawing-program extraction contains no “Ronaldo” or “Messi.” That is why plaintiff did not build the case on a formal-stage mention. The proposition instead asks whether the market wording and mention terms clearly excluded Trump’s public, official, event-linked remarks at the venue immediately before the formal program. Defendant has not supplied that exclusion.\\n\\nDefendant’s argument treats the title “Prior to the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw” as if “prior to” automatically means outside the Kalshi market’s event period. But PX-1 does not say “formal transcript only,” “after the draw host begins,” “after 00:00:50,” or “excluding press availability at the venue.” It asks what Trump would say “during the FIFA World Cup Draw.” The source label tells us sequence; it does not tell us the market’s legal boundary.\\n\\nDX-2 actually illustrates why defendant’s bright line is chosen after the fact. In defendant’s own formal extraction, the page begins before the mechanical draw: Mark Carney speaks at 00:00:00, and Infantino says at 00:00:50, “we are now going to do the draw.” If “during the FIFA World Cup Draw” can include ceremony and preamble on the formal page before the draw itself begins, then the phrase is not self-defining down to a single moment or transcript. The question is what the market clearly specified. It did not specify defendant’s transcript-only rule.\\n\\nThe terms do not fill that gap for defendant. PX-3 excludes hidden categories such as rehearsals, sound checks, unofficial recordings, and behind-the-scenes content unless officially published as part of the period. PX-2 and PX-5 are not those categories. PX-5 is an official GovInfo/OFR presidential transcript, published with source metadata, at 11:13 a.m. at the Kennedy Center, with FIFA’s president present and the World Cup Draw repeatedly discussed. That gives the Ronaldo mentions strong provenance and an event connection; it does not make them informal backstage chatter.\\n\\nDefendant says plaintiff needs a bridge. The bridge is the market text plus the terms’ failure to draw the narrow line defendant proposes. A No resolution can stand only if the contract fairly told traders that “during the FIFA World Cup Draw” meant only the separate formal-program transcript. On this record, the more likely reading is broader: public, official remarks at the venue, immediately tied to and immediately preceding the World Cup Draw program, were within the event-linked period unless clearly excluded.\\n\\nSo DX-2 narrows one factual issue but does not decide the case. It shows no formal-stage Ronaldo mention. It does not show that the market excluded the official pre-program event remarks where Trump did say Ronaldo. Under the preponderance standard, the Yes resolution remains the fair one.\\n\\nSurrebuttals:\\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff’s rebuttal usefully narrows the dispute. Plaintiff accepts that the formal Roll Call/Factba.se drawing transcript contains no “Ronaldo” or “Messi.” So the case remains entirely about whether a separate reporter exchange titled “Prior to the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw” should be treated as inside the market period.\\n\\nPlaintiff says “prior to” is only sequence, not legal boundary. But sequence is exactly what the market phrase makes material. The contract asks what Trump would say “during the FIFA World Cup Draw.” A source-agency title identifying the Ronaldo transcript as an exchange with reporters prior to that Draw is not a stray label; it is the best record description of when and what that source is. Plaintiff cannot convert that source into the event itself by saying the market failed to list every excluded pre-event setting.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s formal-preamble point also does not carry the burden. Yes, the formal transcript begins before the mechanical ball selection, and Infantino says at 00:00:50 that “we are now going to do the draw.” But that supports the defense distinction. A host’s preamble inside the formal drawing transcript is part of the program. A separate press exchange, separately titled and sourced as prior to the Draw, is not made part of the program simply because it happened nearby and discussed the same event.\\n\\nNor does official publication settle the issue. PX-5 strengthens provenance: Trump did say Ronaldo in an official public transcript. But provenance answers whether the words were said, not whether they were said during the market’s specified event. The terms require both: the word by the entity, and the word during the time period. Plaintiff has the first element. The second is still missing.\\n\\nThe remaining bridge plaintiff proposes is essentially: public, official, event-linked, and not expressly excluded. That is not enough under a preponderance standard when the same record supplies a cleaner boundary: the Ronaldo source is prior to the Draw, and the formal Draw source omits the strike. The challenged No resolution should stand.\\n\\nClosings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the record has narrowed to one real issue.\\n\\nThe word is proven. The market page identifies the strike as “Ronaldo” and the challenged resolution as No. The case-packet transcript and the GovInfo/OFR excerpt prove that Trump said “Ronaldo” as a standalone word in public remarks at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center, in a World Cup Draw setting, with FIFA President Infantino present, and amid repeated discussion of the Draw, the Kennedy Center, ticket sales, the audience, and the imminent event. That is strong provenance: GovInfo, NARA/OFR, DCPD202501162, matching the packet source and note.\\n\\nDefendant has also proved its best fact. The Roll Call/Factba.se formal-program extraction does not contain “Ronaldo” or “Messi.” Plaintiff does not ask you to find otherwise. If the market had said “only the formal drawing transcript,” defendant would win. But that is not the market traders saw.\\n\\nThe market asked: “What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?” It did not say “during the formal transcript only,” “after the host announces the draw has begun,” “excluding public press remarks at the venue,” or “excluding remarks immediately before the program.” The governing terms do not add that limitation. They define words used by the entity during the time period, allow event/context time periods, and exclude categories such as rehearsals, sound checks, behind-the-scenes content, and unofficial recordings. Plaintiff’s source is none of those. It is an official public presidential transcript of event-linked remarks at the venue.\\n\\nDefendant’s formal extraction shows why a bright line cannot simply be assumed. Even on that page, before balls are drawn, there is ceremony, introduction, and Infantino saying “we are now going to do the draw.” Event boundaries are not self-defining. The question is whether Kalshi clearly chose defendant’s narrower boundary. The record contains no such choice.\\n\\nSo the burden is met. More likely than not, a reasonable reading of the market and terms includes Trump’s official, public, venue-based remarks immediately tied to the World Cup Draw. The strongest contrary evidence proves only that a narrower formal transcript omits the strike. It does not prove the contract excluded the remarks where the strike was actually said.\\n\\nThe challenged No resolution should be overturned. The strike “Ronaldo” should resolve Yes.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff’s closing concedes the decisive factual split: the formal World Cup Drawing transcript contains no “Ronaldo” or “Messi.” The only Ronaldo evidence is the separate official transcript titled “Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw.”\\n\\nThat is enough to decide the case. The market did not ask what Trump would say at the Kennedy Center, on World Cup Draw day, in public presidential remarks, or in event-linked press availability. It asked what Trump would say “during the FIFA World Cup Draw.” The terms require the word to be used by the entity during the specified time period. Plaintiff has proven the word and the speaker. It has not proven the time period.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s strongest point is that the market did not expressly say “formal transcript only” or “exclude pre-program remarks.” But plaintiff has the burden. A challenged No resolution does not become Yes merely because the contract could have been even more verbose. The record must make it more likely than not that the pre-event reporter exchange was inside the market period. The record does the opposite.\\n\\nThe source labels matter. PX-2 and PX-5 are official and probative, but they are official proof of remarks prior to the Draw. The formal Roll Call/Factba.se extraction is the source for Trump’s formal attendance at the FIFA World Cup Drawing; it begins the program, includes the draw presentation, and omits the strike. Plaintiff’s theory asks you to treat a separate prior reporter exchange as “during” the Draw even though the formal Draw source exists and does not contain the word.\\n\\nThe terms do not collapse that distinction. They recognize event/context time periods and official presentation content, but they still require the word to occur during the chosen time period. Official publication proves provenance. Event connection proves relevance. Neither proves inclusion. A public official transcript can be accurately preserved and still be outside the market window if it is, as titled, prior to the event.\\n\\nSo the fair synthesis is narrow and grounded: Trump said Ronaldo in event-linked public remarks before the FIFA World Cup Draw; Trump did not say Ronaldo in the formal drawing transcript preserved in this record; and no admitted market term or source-chain evidence bridges the pre-event exchange into the market’s “during the FIFA World Cup Draw” period.\\n\\nUnder the preponderance standard, plaintiff has not carried the proposition. The challenged No resolution should stand.\\n\\nExhibits:\\n[plaintiff] PX-1 Market page and challenged resolution\\nMarket URL: https://kalshi.com/markets/kxtrumpmentionb/trump-mention-b/kxtrumpmentionb-25dec06\\n\\nPublic market title: What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\n\\nContract family: PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION\\n\\nStrike at issue: Ronaldo\\n\\nChallenged resolution: No\\n\\nRequested resolution: Yes\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-2 Pre-event reporter exchange transcript\\nRemarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\nDecember 05, 2025\\n\\n[The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\\nThe President. It's a great honor to be here. Gianni has done a fantastic job. We're setting records—[inaudible].\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. Well, I think so. They have a little bit of a shot. Pretty stiff competition. But I would say they would have a small chance.\\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize\\nQ. [Inaudible]—win the FIFA Peace Award?\\nThe President. Well, it would be an honor.\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\nQ. Will you root for some selection? Will you root for someone?\\nThe President. Well, I root for a lot of countries, but in this case, I'll be rooting for the U.S.A. [Laughter]\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. That's great. That's great. We really love it.\\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize\\nQ. Mr. President, have you been told that you are going to receive the inaugural peace prize today——\\nThe President. I have not——\\nQ. ——from FIFA?\\nThe President. I have not been told. There's a rumor about it, but I have not been told. That would be a great honor, and I'm a big fan of Gianni, as you know.\\nQ. What can fans expect——\\nQ. Are you hoping to receive that?\\nThe President. Excuse me.\\nQ. Are you hoping to receive the peace prize?\\nThe President. Well, I don't like to say \\\"hope,\\\" but it would be a great honor.\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. What can fans expect of, like, the World Cup in the U.S.?\\nThe President. I think it's going to be fantastic. We've set every record you can set.\\nQ. What are you telling people who are worried——\\nFédération Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) President Giovanni V. Infantino\\nQ. [Inaudible]—friend Gianni—[inaudible]—a word about him?\\nThe President. I think he has done a fantastic job.\\nThe President's Schedule\\nQ. Are you going to be meeting with the President of Mexico today and the——\\nThe President. We might. Yes.\\nQ. ——Prime Minister of Canada as well?\\nThe President. I might. I might do that.\\nQ. Will you be discussing immigration and trade with them?\\nThe President. Yes, we'll be discussing.\\n[At this point, the President and Mr. Infantino posed for photographs.]\\nThe President. Thank you, everybody.\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event/John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts\\nQ. Mr. President, what do you think about the crowd?\\nThe President. Oh, look, the new star—[inaudible].\\nCongratulations.\\nQ. Thank you.\\nThe President. You're the new star of television and Fox.\\nQ. Thank you. How are you doing, Mr. President?\\nThe President. I'm doing very well.\\nQ. What do you think about the crowd here?\\nThe President. I think the crowd is great, and I think the building is great. We've made a lot of improvements over the last 6 months. Taking—the Kennedy Center was in very bad shape. Now it's getting to be really good. And in 6 months, it's going to be incredible with the improvements we've made.\\nQ. The first time for the U.S. to host since the nineties.\\nThe President. Right.\\nQ. Are you ready for it?\\nThe President. I'm ready for it, and they're ready for it. And Gianni, who you know——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——has done a fantastic job with FIFA. And we're looking to have—you know, we're set—we have already set records for tickets sales. I don't think there's ever been anything like it in any sport. And so, I want to congratulate you.\\nMr. Infantino. Thank you.\\nThe President. I don't even have to wait. But major records have been set.\\nHow are you?\\nQ. Good, how are you, sir?\\nThe President. Nice to see you.\\nQ. Today it's not football—American football. It's soccer. It's——\\nThe President. Right.\\nQ. ——the big event of soccer.\\nThe President. That's right. That's right.\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\nQ. So can you tell me about this big day today?\\nThe President. It's just a big day, and it's a great sport. And it really is coming to America. And never—nobody ever thought a thing like this could happen. And I'm very happy to say that we've already set the alltime record on ticket sales long before the first ball is kicked. Right?\\nMr. Infantino. A hundred percent. One hundred percent.\\n2026 World Cup Host Cities\\nQ. You've had some concerns about crime in American cities, some of the cities that will be hosting. Have they remedied that for you? Are you still considering maybe asking FIFA to move some of those cities?\\nThe President. No, I don't want to do that. But I will tell you, if they do have a problem, by the time we get there, we'll take care of that problem. We can solve that problem.\\nI've proven that in DC and everywhere else we went, so we'll take care of that very easily. So, if they have a problem, hopefully, they'll let us know that, and we will solve any problem.\\nOkay? Thank you.\\nQ. Thank you so much.\\nMr. Infantino. All right, thank you so much.\\nQ. Thank you, Mr. President.\\nQ. Thank you. Appreciate it.\\nThe President. Congratulations.\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. Mr. President, Brazilian television. America will be hosting the World Cup and the Olympics in 2 years. How important it is—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. I think very. It's a great honor. I think Gianni is doing a phenomenal job. We've set every record on ticket sales. It's been really fantastic. But Gianni has done an unbelievable job with FIFA.\\nThe President's Experience With Soccer\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. He was a great—not only that. I got to see a man name Pelé play—right?—that tells you how old I am—when he was on the Cosmos. Do you remember that a long time ago? And it was quite a treat. That was quite an event. And he was—not only was he playing, he was great. He scored two goals, I think. And so, I was one of the few who got to see Pelé, and I assume he is one of your alltime greats. Right?\\nMr. Infantino. Definitely.\\nThe President. So I got to see him.\\nThe President's Favorite World Cup Competitor\\nQ. Do you have some favorite teams for World Cup?\\nThe President. Well, I have a favorite. It's the U.S.A. [Laughter] I don't know what their chances are, Gianni, but maybe the U.S.A. is the——\\nMr. Infantino. They're getting better and better, actually.\\nThe President. I think they'll do well.\\nMr. Infantino. They are getting better and better.\\nThe President. I think they'll do well.\\nThank you very much, everybody.\\nQ. Thank you so much.\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. Mr. President, World Cup in America just means—[inaudible]. So what do you expect from this World Cup?\\nThe President. [Inaudible]—record business and only in the United States, but we're also doing record ticket sales with FIFA. And they've already bought—beat their highest record. And we—you know, this a long time before the first ball is kicked. You've sold more tickets than they've ever done before, and better pricing than they've ever gotten before. It's a tremendous success. And it's an honor. And Gianni has done a phenomenal job with FIFA.\\nQ. [Inaudible]—ever?\\nThe President. I think so. I think it's going to be—I mean, ideally, you want to see that every year. Every 4 years, it gets bigger and better. I think we have set every record in the book. We're very happy about it.\\nThank you.\\nThe President's Favorite World Cup Competitor\\nQ. [Inaudible]—part of America. Who are you going to support as well?\\nThe President. Well, I think I have to support U.S.A. Otherwise, I'd be in trouble. I wouldn't be President for long.\\nMr. Infantino. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. [Inaudible]—but you have a lot of great teams. You're going to have a lot of great teams.\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\\\"football,\\\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\\n2026 World Cup Draw/Ticket Sales for World Cup\\nQ. How does it feel to be part of this amazing event? And obviously, your being a part of participating in all the—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. The President of Mexico is here, and she's doing a very good job. She's a good woman, very, very excellent job. It's an honor, and we're setting every record, and you're helping us set those records.\\nMr. Infantino. And we will do it.\\nThe President. You know, Mexico and Canada are helping us set those records. But as you know, we have a record in ticket sales already, long before the first ball is kicked, and we're going to do great.\\nI think that Gianni—as you know, he's the head, and he has done a fantastic job.\\nU.S. Cooperation With Mexico and Canada\\nQ. And how is the biggest challenge being three countries?\\nThe President. Well, I think that—do you mean for the three countries?\\nWell, they've gotten together really well, I mean.\\nMr. Infantino. All right.\\nThe President. They're getting along very well.\\nMr. Infantino. Collaboration is fantastic between the three.\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer/2026 World Cup\\nQ. And you like soccer?\\nThe President. I do. I like it. I like it more and more.\\nQ. Yes?\\nThe President. I like it. It's growing in this country—very, really—I mean, someday, maybe it's going to be bigger than anything else.\\nMr. Infantino. We'll have to become number one.\\nThe President. I will say this——\\nMr. Infantino. Definitely.\\nThe President. ——the ticket sales——\\nQ. Definitely will happen.\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. Ticket sales are bigger than anything we have ever done in the history of the country, in terms of sports.\\nMr. Infantino. For certain.\\nQ. And the audience is going to be huge.\\nThe President. The audience is going to be tremendous.\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. Yes.\\nMr. Infantino. Six billion people.\\nThe President. [Inaudible]\\nQ. Six billion? That's amazing.\\nMr. Infantino. Six billion people.\\nAnd today, one billion.\\nQ. Wow.\\nMr. Infantino. [Inaudible]\\nQ. Enjoy show time. Thank you so much.\\nThe President. [Inaudible]\\nQ. Mr. President, how are you? Just a quick—[inaudible].\\nQ. This is for Telemundo.\\nThe President. How are you?\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\nQ. Hello, Mr. President. How are you? This for Telemundo.\\nThe President. How are you? Good.\\nQ. How are you?\\nThe President. Very good. Thank you.\\nQ. How does it feel to have the most important event of sports—that global—in the U.S.?\\nThe President. Well, we do. And right at the Kennedy Center. I'm Chairman of the Kennedy Center. And I hear the Kennedy Center is doing a very good job, so it feels great. Really good.\\nAnd Telemundo is doing a good job, too. Thank you.\\nQ. Thank you.\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. What is the significance of hosting the FIFA World Cup this year?\\nThe President. It's a—in terms of sports, I would say the ultimate. There is no sport like this. It's the biggest sport in the world. And we are setting every record. You know, our ticket sales have gone and set every—every sport—no matter what it is, we've set the record. So—and every though it's very early, there's no ball being kicked yet, but we've already set a ticket sales record.\\nArgentina National Team\\nQ. How do you see Argentinean team for this World Cup?\\nThe President. Well, I love Argentina. And your President is doing a very good job, as you know. Milei. You know that right? It's make Argentina great again. MAGA.\\nQ. And——\\nU.S. National Team\\nQ. Do you think the States are building a powerful team for next year?\\nThe President. Who?\\nQ. The States.\\nThe President. Oh, yes. Sure. I—you're going to have a lot of powerful teams. Everybody has a lot of powerful teams, but you're going to have a lot of great teams. [Inaudible]\\nU.S. Role in Hosting the 2026 World Cup\\nQ. Mr. President, what does it mean for you guys to host the World Cup right here in the U.S.?\\nThe President. I'm honored to host it. It's a great honor. I mean, it's turned out to be bigger than we thought. We're setting a record for ticket sales, the likes of which no sport has ever seen before.\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\\nThe President. But they have a little more speed.\\nBut no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\\nPopularity of Soccer in Latin America\\nQ. Mr. President, a message for the Latin America and soccer fans?\\nThe President. Yes, I am. And Latin America is great. And they have great soccer. So, good luck in the matches.\\n[A reporter asked a question in Spanish, which was translated by an interpreter as follows.]\\nU.S. Visas for World Cup Ticketholders\\nQ. Who is going to be in—[inaudible]—about these visas for the—these fans that want to come here to the World Cup?\\nThe President. Well, we're going to make it very easy for them. We're working on that right now. We're going to make it very easy. It's going to be a very easy process.\\nQ. Okay. Say, hi to Colombia over there.\\nThe President. Hello. Is that Colombia?\\nQ. Yes.\\nThe President. I love Colombia. Hello, Colombia. [Laughter]\\nQ. Okay. Okay. Muy bien.\\nThe President. So where are you from?\\nQ. Paraguay.\\nThe President. Oh.\\nQ. He's from Paraguay. Yes.\\nThe President. Very good. I love it. I—it's a beautiful country. We get along very well with them. We do a little trade deal with them, and they like us. And that's what's happening.\\nQ. Panama.\\nThe President. Where?\\nVery good. I like the canal. [Laughter] That canal is pretty good.\\n[A reporter spoke in Spanish; no translation was provided.]\\n2026 World Cup\\nThe President. What?\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. Well, it's going to be incredible. The event is going to be very good. Just this event alone—it's at the Kennedy Center. I see you have it fixed up perfectly.\\nMr. Infantino. It will set the tone.\\nThe President. Right? It's beautiful.\\nMr. Infantino. It's beautiful.\\nThe President. It's a beautiful place.\\nHave a good time.\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President.\\n[A reporter spoke in Spanish; no translation was provided.]\\nMr. Infantino. No, gracias. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. It's great.\\nJohn F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts/Renovation Work\\nQ. Mr. President, the U.S. press?\\nThe President. Thank you, everybody, very much. It's a great honor. This has been an honor for a lot of reasons. Number one, they've sold more tickets than any event has ever sold already—long before the kickoff.\\nAnd number two, we've done a lot of work at the Kennedy Center. It was falling apart, and now it's pretty much back. And we'll get it back within the next 4 or 5 months through construction, and—but you see the way it looks.\\nAnd Gianni is just telling me—who's done an incredible job, by the way. He's just telling, you know, how good a job we've done.\\nMr. Infantino. That's right.\\nThe President. You can look at the walls. The marble was broken. Everything was a mess. And we've really taken the Kennedy Center—a lot of people thought it was going to be ripped down, and we did just the opposite. So we've done a really great renovation job on it. And over the next 3, 4 months, it will be complete. And we're honored to have it here, and it's been—it's been very special.\\nWe've set a record on ticket sales, as you probably heard, already, even way before—long before the event itself. And we're working with Canada, and we're working with Mexico. And it's been a really spectacular—so far, it's been spectacular.\\nDaniel [Daniel Baldwin, One America News Network], do you have a question?\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. What are your expectations? You once said that the FIFA World Cup is an opportunity to put—a once-in-a-lifetime opportunity to put the greatness of the United States on display.\\nThe President. Well, I think—\\nQ. One billion eyeballs will be watching, Mr. President.\\nThe President. Yes, I—think——\\nQ. What will they here today?\\nThe President. Even today, I understand. I hear that, you know——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——I know we're a little late to get in there, but——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——that's okay.\\nMr. Infantino. They wait.\\nThe President. So all my friends, I guess they have to wait. They have no choice, right? [Laughter]\\nMr. Infantino. Yes, they wait.\\nThe President. But no, the numbers are incredible. I hear today's numbers are——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——very big. I hope CNN is covering this.\\nQ. One billion eyeballs.\\nMr. Infantino. Today, 1 billion eyeballs.\\nThe President. Today's numbers are very, very big.\\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize/The President's Foreign Policy\\nQ. We are covering it. And you're expected to get the FIFA Peace Prize, Mr. President. What would you say to people who say that prize might conflict with your pledge to strike Venezuela?\\nThe President. Well, I think the peace prize—I mean, I settled eight wars. I don't know that I'm getting it. I haven't been officially noticed. I've been hearing about a peace prize, and I'm here to represent our country in a different sense. But I can tell you, I did settle eight wars, and we have a ninth coming, but—which nobody has ever done before.\\nBut I want to really save lives. I don't need prizes. I need to save lives. And we're saving a lot of lives. And I've saved millions and millions of lives, and that's really what I want to do.\\nAnd I also want to run a great country. And the United States right now is the hottest country anywhere in the world. And 1 year ago, it was dead. We had a dead country, and now we have the hottest country anywhere in the world.\\nQ. Mr. President, will you——\\nThe President's Meeting With President Claudia Sheinbaum Pardo of Mexico and Prime Minister Mark Carney of Canada\\nQ. What are you going to discuss with Canada and Mexico, Mr.—what are you going to discuss with the leaders of Canada and Mexico?\\nThe President. Well, we're getting—we're going to meet with both. And we're getting along very well. You know, we're getting along very well. I don't know. I think we have a meeting set up for some time after the event.\\nQ. Will you discuss trade?\\nThe President. Yes, we'll discuss trade. We—get along very well.\\nThank you, everybody, very much.\\nQ. Will you pardon any other Honduran officials?\\nQ. Do you want them to keep trying to indict Ms. James?\\n\\nNOTE: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. In his remarks, he referred to Trey Yingst, chief foreign correspondent, Fox News Channel; Cristiano Ronaldo, forward for Saudi Pro League club Al-Nass and Portugal's national soccer team; and Lionel Messi, forward for Major League Soccer club Inter Miami and Argentina's national team. A reporter referred to New York State Attorney General Letitia James. The transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\n\\nSource URL: https://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/documents/remarks-exchange-with-reporters-prior-the-2026-federation-internationale-des-associations\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-3 PRESMENTION/NEWMENTION terms\\n                                         NEWMENTION\\n\\nScope: These rules shall apply to this contract.\\n\\nUnderlying: The Underlying for this Contract is words used by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nRevisions to the Underlying made after Expiration will not be accounted for in determining the\\nExpiration Value.\\n\\nSource Agency: The Source Agencies are \\u003csource\\u003e.\\n\\nType: The type of Contract is an Event Contract.\\n\\nIssuance: After the initial Contract, Contract iterations will be listed on an as-needed basis at\\nthe discretion of the Exchange and corresponding to the risk management needs of Members.\\n\\n\\u003centity\\u003e: \\u003centity\\u003e refers to the speaker, writer, performer, or communicator specified by the\\nExchange. This may include (but is not limited to): a specific named individual, multiple\\nindividuals specified using AND/OR logic, an individual identified by position or title, a group,\\nband, team or collective entity, a specified member or members of a group, an organization,\\ncompany, or institutional entity, or any combination of the aforementioned.\\n\\nWhen \\u003centity\\u003e is defined by a position or title, the Contract tracks whoever holds that position\\nduring \\u003ctime period\\u003e, even if the individual holding the position changes. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a\\nspecific named individual, the identity remains consistent throughout. Name changes (e.g.,\\nstage names, married names) do not create a new entity. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a group or\\norganization and the Contract does not specify particular members, any official\\ncommunication or statement by any member or designated spokesperson counts. When using\\nAND logic, all specified entities must independently say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e. When\\nusing OR logic, at least one of the specified entities must say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nThe Exchange may specify additional conditions such as “at least X members of” a group or\\n“the majority of” a group.\\n\\n\\u003csource\\u003e: \\u003csource\\u003e refers to a Source Agency or ordered collection of Source Agencies\\nspecified by the Exchange at the time of Contract listing, which will be incorporated into the\\nSource Agency hierarchy above and used to determine the occurrence of the Underlying.\\n\\u003csource\\u003e may refer to a singular agency, multiple agencies, an agency by distinguishing\\ncharacteristics, by category or type (e.g., “official government statistical body,” “primary wire\\nservice”), or any combination thereof. When multiple agencies are specified, they may be\\napplied in the hierarchical order designated by the Exchange if so specified, with the highest-\\nranked available and responsive agency taking precedence for purposes of determining the\\nExpiration Value. A lower-ranked agency shall only be consulted if all higher-ranked agencies\\nare unavailable, unresponsive, have not reported on the Underlying by the Expiration time, or\\nif the Exchange, in its sole discretion, determines that a higher-ranked agency’s reporting is\\nincomplete, erroneous, or otherwise insufficient to determine the Expiration Value. If \\u003csource\\u003e\\ndesignates multiple agencies without specifying a hierarchical order, the Exchange shall\\nresolve any conflict between reporting agencies at its sole discretion.\\n\\n\\u003cword\\u003e: \\u003cword\\u003e refers to the particular word or phrase potentially to be mentioned by\\n\\u003centity\\u003e. It may refer to a word being said a minimum number of times. It may also refer to\\none of multiple words/phrases, any of which are acceptable (e.g., “Doge/Dogecoin”).\\n\\f\\u003ctime period\\u003e: \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific range of time, event or discrete date and\\ntime specified by the Exchange. This may be defined by, but is not limited to: a specific event\\nor context (e.g., “during the State of the Union address”), exact dates or times, relative time\\nmarkers (e.g., “before July 1, 2027,” “in Q1 2026”), event-based periods (e.g., “during any\\ncampaign rally in October 2026,” “during the awards ceremony”), and broader intervals (e.g.,\\n“Q1–Q2 2027,” “January–March 2026”).\\n\\nUnless stated otherwise, “Between” is inclusive of both endpoints, while “before” and “after”\\nexclude the specified date. \\u003ctime period\\u003e may also refer to “Any” or “None”, to multiple dates\\n(even if non-consecutive), or to a singular and discrete date or time.\\n\\nWhen \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event (such as an address, speech, performance, or\\nbroadcast), the Exchange may specify what is included, including whether it includes both live\\nand pre-recorded segments (including whether advertisements are included). Where a\\ntimezone is not specified, ET is assumed.\\n\\n\\nPayout Criterion: The Payout Criterion for the Contract encompasses the Expiration Values that\\n\\u003cword\\u003e is said by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n\\n\\nThe word must appear as a distinct, standalone unit, not buried inside another word. Plural\\nand possessive noun forms count. Other grammatical changes (tense, conjugation, derivation)\\ndo not. If \\u003cword\\u003e appears separated from other words by a space or hyphen or in a\\ncompound form with a space or hyphen, it counts. If \\u003cword\\u003e is fused into a single\\nunhyphenated word, it does not count.\\n\\nIf \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled, and the market contains a\\nstrike stating “Event does not qualify/occur”, such a strike shall resolve “Yes” and all others\\n“No”. If \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled but such strikes are NOT\\nlisted, the Contracts will resolve to the last fair price determined at the discretion of the\\nExchange. If the event is postponed, and such a postponement is announced by the end of the\\nfollowing calendar day to be rescheduled to a time within 14 calendar days, the markets shall\\nremain open. If the event captured in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast, the\\nExchange may keep the market open for 24 hours for the release of an official recording.\\nFurther granular details on conditions for these Contracts is available below.\\n\\nAdditional clarification(s):\\n\\n     Possessive noun forms of \\u003cword\\u003e, plurals, and possessive plural noun forms are\\n     INCLUDED:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigrants” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Egg” → “eggs’ shells” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Russia” → “Russia’s” counts, “Russian” does not\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e exists only in adjective form, no plural form exists:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Economic” → “Economics” does not count (“Economic” is an adjective\\n          for which “Economics” is not a plural)\\n     Plural nouns occurring within proper nouns and noun phrases are included:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Cat” → “Cats the musical” counts\\n\\f    Grammatical variations beyond plurals/possessives are NOT included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigration” does NOT count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Run” → “Running” or “Ran” do NOT count\\n    When \\u003cword\\u003e specifies a plural form, the singular does NOT count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Veterans” → “Veteran” does NOT count\\n    Words that are spelled the same as the plural form of \\u003cword\\u003e (if such exists) but are\\n    themselves not a plural noun are included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Wind” → “Winds up the clock” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Border” → “The United States has strong borders” counts\\n    Open compounds (words separated by spaces) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fire station” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “couch” → “couch potato” counts\\n    Hyphenated compounds (words connected by hyphens) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Palestine” → “pro-Palestine” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fat” → “non-fat” counts\\n    Closed compounds (single word, no spaces/hyphens) do not count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire” does not count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firefighter” does not count\\n    Multi-word \\u003cword\\u003e in larger constructions: When \\u003cword\\u003e is a multi-word phrase\\n    appearing within a hyphenated construction, it counts only if \\u003cword\\u003e appears as a\\n    complete, unmodified element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “New York” → “New York-based” counts (complete element)\\n    Portmanteaus (words blended from two words where parts of each are combined) are\\n    NOT included unless the portmanteau clearly contains \\u003cword\\u003e as a distinct, unaltered\\n    element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “MAGA” → “MAGA-nificent” counts (MAGA appears as distinct element)\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “magnificent” → “MAGA-nificent” does NOT count (portmanteau blend)\\n\\nDictionary determination: Both the Merriam-Webster Dictionary (available online) AND the\\nOxford English Dictionary shall be used to determine compound type and/or conventional\\nspelling patterns. Inclusion in either dictionary as an open or hyphenated compound shall\\nsatisfy the Payout Criterion. If neither provides clarity (or the word is not included),\\ndetermination is based on whether written as single unit (closed/doesn’t count) vs. spaces or\\nhyphens (open or hyphenated/counts) and/or context and previous usage.\\n\\nPHONETIC EQUIVALENCIES\\n\\n    Homophones (same sound, different spelling) do not count:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “write” → “right” does not count\\n    Homonyms and homographs (same spelling) COUNT regardless of meaning or\\n    pronunciation:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “bass” → both “bass guitar” and “bass fishing” count\\n    Proper and common nouns are treated identically:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Apple” → both “Apple Inc.” and “apple” (fruit) count\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Will” → both “Will Smith” and “I will go” count\\n    Minor unintentional mispronunciations COUNT if context makes intent clear:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Mamdani” → “Mandani” counts\\n    Severe mispronunciations that make \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable do NOT count.\\n    Trademarked spellings do not count, even when pronounced identically, unless the word\\n\\fitself is the same:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “lift” → “Lyft” (pronounced “lift”) does not count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “uber” → “Uber” counts\\nWords with non-standard transliteration to English count within reason, provided they are\\nphonetically equivalent:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Zelensky” → any of “Zelenski,” “Zelenskii,” “Zelensky,” or “Zelenskiy”\\n      count if pronounced equivalently\\nContractions do not count for their constituent words unless otherwise explicitly specified\\nby the Exchange:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “not” → “won’t,” “can’t,” “don’t,” “isn’t” do not count\\nNumbers spoken as words COUNT, when spoken exactly (not part of a larger number):\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “five” → saying “five” or reading “$5” aloud as “five dollars” counts,\\n      saying “five hundred” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “410” → “four hundred ten”, “four one zero” or “four ten” counts\\nOrdinals COUNT when \\u003cword\\u003e is written numerically OR a phrase that includes a\\nnumber:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “January 6” → “January 6th” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “3” (written numerically) → “3rd” (spoken as “third”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Eight War” → “8 Wars” and “Eighth War” will count\\nCardinal and ordinal number words are distinct:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “one” → “first” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “first” → “one” does NOT count\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count when pronunciation or letter-by-letter spelling\\nmatches \\u003cword\\u003e:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “NASA” (pronounced “NAH-suh”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “N-A-S-A” (spelled out) counts\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count as \\u003cword\\u003e when pronounced as the full word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Doctor” → “Dr.” (pronounced “Doctor”) counts\\nExpanded forms of acronyms do NOT count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “AI” → “artificial intelligence” does not count\\nWords in foreign languages do NOT count unless they are perfect cognates with an\\nEnglish word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fuego” (Spanish) does NOT count\\nEnglish words within foreign sentences count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “policy” → “Nuestra policy es clara” counts\\n\\u003cword\\u003e in organization/company names counts:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Securities” → “Bank of America Securities” counts\\nWords in URLs, emails, handles, and hashtags (exclusive of domain structure, email\\nprovider or symbols) are treated as compounds when spoken as complete words, with the\\ntype of compound subject to aforementioned rules:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firestation.com” pronounced “fire station dot com” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire.com” pronounced “wildfire dot com” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “apple” → “apple.com” pronounced “apple dot com” does count\\n      When presented in URL, email, handle, or hashtag form, \\u003cword\\u003e shall be treated as\\n      a compound, not a multi-word word\\nSung, rapped, or poetic words COUNT if phonetically recognizable:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “money” → “moneyyy” (extended in rap) counts\\n      Extreme distortion making \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable does NOT count.\\nPhonetic alphabet spelling (“Foxtrot India Romeo Echo” for “FIRE”) does NOT count.\\n\\fCANCELLATIONS AND DELAYS\\n\\n   The Exchange may list an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike for any Contract. If listed,\\n   such a strike refers to the structural conditions of the market, and is NOT adjudicated as a\\n   \\u003cword\\u003e needing to be said by or validated by having been said by \\u003centity\\u003e. If listed, this\\n   strike resolves to “Yes” whenever the event fails to occur or qualify under the Payout\\n   Criterion, or any other circumstance prevents normal resolution.\\n   If no such strike is listed, and \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, the following rules\\n   apply if the event is cancelled, postponed, rescheduled, or materially altered (including\\n   being closed to press) such that no video is released within one calendar day of the\\n   original start time of the event:\\n         If the event is cancelled, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price determined in\\n         the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         If the event is postponed or rescheduled, the outcome depends on whether a new\\n         date is publicly announced within one calendar day (i.e. if the event was scheduled\\n         to begin on Monday, any time up to 11:59PM on Tuesday falls within this period) of\\n         the originally scheduled start time:\\n               If no new date is announced within one calendar day, the Contract will resolve\\n               to the last fair price determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n               If a new date is announced within one calendar day, the outcome depends on\\n               when the rescheduled event is set to occur:\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls within fourteen (14) calendar days of the\\n                     originally scheduled date, the Contract shall remain open and \\u003cword\\u003e\\n                     stated during the rescheduled event will count.\\n                           The fourteen-day window begins at 12:00 AM ET on the originally\\n                           scheduled date and ends at 11:59 PM ET fourteen days later, unless\\n                           an alternate timezone is explicitly specified.\\n                           Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the State of the Union on January\\n                           15, 2026” rescheduled to January 20, 2026 → words spoken during\\n                           the rescheduled address count.\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls more than fourteen (14) calendar days after\\n                     the originally scheduled date, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price\\n                     determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         Any Contract that cannot be resolved through the Source Agency hierarchy will\\n         instead be settled at the Last Fair Price. The Exchange will disclose the methodology\\n         used to determine the Last Fair Price (e.g., Last Traded Price, Time-Weighted\\n         Average Price) at the time of Issuance.\\n         If an event begins but is interrupted, abbreviated, or ends prematurely, words\\n         stated by \\u003centity\\u003e during the portion of the event that did occur will count and the\\n         market will otherwise resolve.\\n   If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window but the venue, format, or medium\\n   changes (e.g., moved to a different location, changed from in-person to virtual (with the\\n   exception of being closed to press)), words stated during the event will count.\\n   Special condition: Across both cases, whether an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike is\\n   listed or not, if the event specified as or in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast (or\\n   relayed as such) but the live stream/broadcast does not occur, the Exchange will instead\\n   use an officially released recording as the Underlying, and may delay resolution by up to\\n   one calendar day to allow for the release of such a recording.\\n\\f          If partial snippets are released, Contracts on words that do not appear will be\\n          resolved to last fair price, and Contracts on those that do will be resolved to “Yes”.\\n          If no recording is released, the relevant outcomes triggered by the\\n          presence/absence of an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike shall occur as outlined\\n          above.\\n\\nTECHNICAL DETAILS (UNLESS OTHERWISE SPECIFIED)\\n\\n     When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, pre-recorded content broadcast,\\n     streamed, or published as part of that event is included if presented as part of the official\\n     presentation.\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the concert” with pre-recorded video interlude\\n          where entity speaks → words from interlude count\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the television appearance” with pre-taped\\n          segment aired during broadcast → words from segment count\\n     Behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are NOT\\n     included unless officially broadcast or published as part of \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n     Subtitles and captions that display \\u003cword\\u003e on screen but are not spoken aloud by\\n     \\u003centity\\u003e do NOT count.\\n     Sign language interpretation or usage by entity does NOT count as saying \\u003cword\\u003e unless\\n     the Contract explicitly specifies that sign language counts.\\n     Text that entity displays on screen (presentation slides, teleprompter visible to audience,\\n     signatures) does NOT count unless entity reads it aloud.\\n     Content generated by AI, deepfakes, or synthetic voice technology impersonating entity\\n     does NOT count unless the synthetic content is officially commissioned, authorized, or\\n     published by entity, OR the Contract explicitly specifies that AI-generated content counts.\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e is muted due to technical failure or censorship it shall not count unless\\n     corroborating contextual evidence (including surrounding speech, or an official\\n     uncensored recording or transcript) confirms that \\u003centity\\u003e specifically uttered \\u003cword\\u003e\\n     during the muted period.\\n\\nMinimum Tick: The Minimum Tick size for the Contract shall be $0.01.\\n\\nPosition Accountability Level: The Position Accountability Level for the Contract shall be\\n$25,000 per strike, per Member.\\n\\nLast Trading Date: The Last Trading Date of the Contract will be the Expiration Date. The Last\\nTrading Time will be the Expiration time.\\n\\nSettlement Date: The Settlement Date of the Contract shall be no later than the day after the\\nExpiration Date, unless the Market Outcome is under review pursuant to Rule 7.1.\\n\\nExpiration Date: When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event: The latest Expiration Date of\\nthe Contract shall be fourteen (14) calendar days after the originally scheduled date of the\\nevent. If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window, expiration will be moved to an\\nearlier date and time in accordance with Rule 7.2. When \\u003ctime period\\u003e is defined by specific\\ndates: The latest Expiration Date of the Contract shall be two weeks after the end of \\u003ctime\\nperiod\\u003e. If an event described in the Payout Criterion occurs and a consensus has been\\nreached on all terms, then expiration will be moved to an earlier date and time in accordance\\nwith Rule 7.2.\\n\\fExpiration time: The Expiration time of the Contract shall be 10:00 AM ET.\\n\\nSettlement Value: The Settlement Value for this Contract is $1.00.\\n\\nExpiration Value: The Expiration Value is the value of the Underlying as documented by the\\nSource Agency on the Expiration Date at the Expiration time.\\n\\nContingencies: Before Settlement, Kalshi may, at its sole discretion, initiate the Market\\nOutcome Review Process pursuant to Rule 7.1 of the Rulebook. If an Expiration Value cannot\\nbe determined on the Expiration Date, Kalshi has the right to determine payouts pursuant to\\nRule 7.1 in the Rulebook.\\n\\f\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-4 Formal draw archive note\\nSource checked: Roll Call / Factba.se archive\\n\\nArchive title: Remarks: Donald Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing in Washington - December 5, 2025\\n\\nArchive URL: https://rollcall.com/factbase/trump/transcript/donald-trump-remarks-fifa-world-cup-drawing-december-5-2025/\\n\\nWhat this file establishes:\\n\\nThere is a separate archived transcript page for Trump's formal attendance remarks at the draw.\\n\\nWhat this file does not establish:\\n\\nThis session could not retrieve the full transcript text from that archive.  The page is password-protected.  This example therefore does not claim, from local files alone, whether the formal program transcript does or does not contain the word \\\"Ronaldo.\\\"\\n\\nWhy this matters:\\n\\nThe complaint does not need to prove that the formal program omitted the strike.  It needs to show that Trump said \\\"Ronaldo\\\" in event-linked remarks and that the market boundary reasonably includes those remarks.  The formal archive remains relevant because it marks the distinction between the pre-event reporter exchange and the formal program.\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-5 GovInfo official transcript excerpt and metadata\\nSource: GovInfo, DCPD202501162, Office of the Federal Register / National Archives and Records Administration.\\nURL: https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/DCPD-202501162/html/DCPD-202501162.htm\\nTitle: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\nEvent date: December 5, 2025.\\n\\nRelevant extracted page text:\\n\\\"Administration of Donald J. Trump, 2025\\\"\\n\\\"Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw December 5, 2025\\\"\\n\\\"[The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\\\"\\n\\nUnder the section \\\"The President's Interest in Soccer\\\":\\n\\\"Q. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\\\"\\n\\\"The President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\\\\\\\"football,\\\\\\\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\\\"\\n\\\"Thank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\\\"\\n\\nAdditional relevant extracted page text:\\n\\\"The President's Interest in Soccer\\\"\\n\\\"Q. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\\\"\\n\\\"The President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\\\"\\n\\\"Mr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\\\"\\n\\\"The President. But they have a little more speed. But no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\\\"\\n\\nGovInfo note:\\n\\\"NOTE: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. In his remarks, he referred to Trey Yingst, chief foreign correspondent, Fox News Channel; Cristiano Ronaldo, forward for Saudi Pro League club Al-Nass and Portugal's national soccer team; and Lionel Messi, forward for Major League Soccer club Inter Miami and Argentina's national team. A reporter referred to New York State Attorney General Letitia James. The transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\\"\\n\\nGovInfo content details page also identifies category \\\"Interviews With the News Media : Exchanges with reporters, Washington, DC,\\\" subjects including \\\"Federation Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) World Cup,\\\" \\\"John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts,\\\" and \\\"Soccer,\\\" and names including \\\"Ronaldo, Cristiano\\\" and \\\"Messi, Lionel.\\\"\\n\\n[defendant] DX-1 Market wording and challenged resolution\\nMarket URL: https://kalshi.com/markets/kxtrumpmentionb/trump-mention-b/kxtrumpmentionb-25dec06\\n\\nPublic market title: What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\\n\\nContract family: PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION\\n\\nStrike at issue: Ronaldo\\n\\nChallenged resolution: No\\n\\nRequested resolution: Yes\\n\\n\\n[defendant] DX-2 Pre-event reporter exchange transcript\\nRemarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\nDecember 05, 2025\\n\\n[The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\\nThe President. It's a great honor to be here. Gianni has done a fantastic job. We're setting records—[inaudible].\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. Well, I think so. They have a little bit of a shot. Pretty stiff competition. But I would say they would have a small chance.\\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize\\nQ. [Inaudible]—win the FIFA Peace Award?\\nThe President. Well, it would be an honor.\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\nQ. Will you root for some selection? Will you root for someone?\\nThe President. Well, I root for a lot of countries, but in this case, I'll be rooting for the U.S.A. [Laughter]\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. That's great. That's great. We really love it.\\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize\\nQ. Mr. President, have you been told that you are going to receive the inaugural peace prize today——\\nThe President. I have not——\\nQ. ——from FIFA?\\nThe President. I have not been told. There's a rumor about it, but I have not been told. That would be a great honor, and I'm a big fan of Gianni, as you know.\\nQ. What can fans expect——\\nQ. Are you hoping to receive that?\\nThe President. Excuse me.\\nQ. Are you hoping to receive the peace prize?\\nThe President. Well, I don't like to say \\\"hope,\\\" but it would be a great honor.\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. What can fans expect of, like, the World Cup in the U.S.?\\nThe President. I think it's going to be fantastic. We've set every record you can set.\\nQ. What are you telling people who are worried——\\nFédération Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) President Giovanni V. Infantino\\nQ. [Inaudible]—friend Gianni—[inaudible]—a word about him?\\nThe President. I think he has done a fantastic job.\\nThe President's Schedule\\nQ. Are you going to be meeting with the President of Mexico today and the——\\nThe President. We might. Yes.\\nQ. ——Prime Minister of Canada as well?\\nThe President. I might. I might do that.\\nQ. Will you be discussing immigration and trade with them?\\nThe President. Yes, we'll be discussing.\\n[At this point, the President and Mr. Infantino posed for photographs.]\\nThe President. Thank you, everybody.\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event/John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts\\nQ. Mr. President, what do you think about the crowd?\\nThe President. Oh, look, the new star—[inaudible].\\nCongratulations.\\nQ. Thank you.\\nThe President. You're the new star of television and Fox.\\nQ. Thank you. How are you doing, Mr. President?\\nThe President. I'm doing very well.\\nQ. What do you think about the crowd here?\\nThe President. I think the crowd is great, and I think the building is great. We've made a lot of improvements over the last 6 months. Taking—the Kennedy Center was in very bad shape. Now it's getting to be really good. And in 6 months, it's going to be incredible with the improvements we've made.\\nQ. The first time for the U.S. to host since the nineties.\\nThe President. Right.\\nQ. Are you ready for it?\\nThe President. I'm ready for it, and they're ready for it. And Gianni, who you know——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——has done a fantastic job with FIFA. And we're looking to have—you know, we're set—we have already set records for tickets sales. I don't think there's ever been anything like it in any sport. And so, I want to congratulate you.\\nMr. Infantino. Thank you.\\nThe President. I don't even have to wait. But major records have been set.\\nHow are you?\\nQ. Good, how are you, sir?\\nThe President. Nice to see you.\\nQ. Today it's not football—American football. It's soccer. It's——\\nThe President. Right.\\nQ. ——the big event of soccer.\\nThe President. That's right. That's right.\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\nQ. So can you tell me about this big day today?\\nThe President. It's just a big day, and it's a great sport. And it really is coming to America. And never—nobody ever thought a thing like this could happen. And I'm very happy to say that we've already set the alltime record on ticket sales long before the first ball is kicked. Right?\\nMr. Infantino. A hundred percent. One hundred percent.\\n2026 World Cup Host Cities\\nQ. You've had some concerns about crime in American cities, some of the cities that will be hosting. Have they remedied that for you? Are you still considering maybe asking FIFA to move some of those cities?\\nThe President. No, I don't want to do that. But I will tell you, if they do have a problem, by the time we get there, we'll take care of that problem. We can solve that problem.\\nI've proven that in DC and everywhere else we went, so we'll take care of that very easily. So, if they have a problem, hopefully, they'll let us know that, and we will solve any problem.\\nOkay? Thank you.\\nQ. Thank you so much.\\nMr. Infantino. All right, thank you so much.\\nQ. Thank you, Mr. President.\\nQ. Thank you. Appreciate it.\\nThe President. Congratulations.\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. Mr. President, Brazilian television. America will be hosting the World Cup and the Olympics in 2 years. How important it is—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. I think very. It's a great honor. I think Gianni is doing a phenomenal job. We've set every record on ticket sales. It's been really fantastic. But Gianni has done an unbelievable job with FIFA.\\nThe President's Experience With Soccer\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. He was a great—not only that. I got to see a man name Pelé play—right?—that tells you how old I am—when he was on the Cosmos. Do you remember that a long time ago? And it was quite a treat. That was quite an event. And he was—not only was he playing, he was great. He scored two goals, I think. And so, I was one of the few who got to see Pelé, and I assume he is one of your alltime greats. Right?\\nMr. Infantino. Definitely.\\nThe President. So I got to see him.\\nThe President's Favorite World Cup Competitor\\nQ. Do you have some favorite teams for World Cup?\\nThe President. Well, I have a favorite. It's the U.S.A. [Laughter] I don't know what their chances are, Gianni, but maybe the U.S.A. is the——\\nMr. Infantino. They're getting better and better, actually.\\nThe President. I think they'll do well.\\nMr. Infantino. They are getting better and better.\\nThe President. I think they'll do well.\\nThank you very much, everybody.\\nQ. Thank you so much.\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. Mr. President, World Cup in America just means—[inaudible]. So what do you expect from this World Cup?\\nThe President. [Inaudible]—record business and only in the United States, but we're also doing record ticket sales with FIFA. And they've already bought—beat their highest record. And we—you know, this a long time before the first ball is kicked. You've sold more tickets than they've ever done before, and better pricing than they've ever gotten before. It's a tremendous success. And it's an honor. And Gianni has done a phenomenal job with FIFA.\\nQ. [Inaudible]—ever?\\nThe President. I think so. I think it's going to be—I mean, ideally, you want to see that every year. Every 4 years, it gets bigger and better. I think we have set every record in the book. We're very happy about it.\\nThank you.\\nThe President's Favorite World Cup Competitor\\nQ. [Inaudible]—part of America. Who are you going to support as well?\\nThe President. Well, I think I have to support U.S.A. Otherwise, I'd be in trouble. I wouldn't be President for long.\\nMr. Infantino. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. [Inaudible]—but you have a lot of great teams. You're going to have a lot of great teams.\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\\\"football,\\\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\\n2026 World Cup Draw/Ticket Sales for World Cup\\nQ. How does it feel to be part of this amazing event? And obviously, your being a part of participating in all the—[inaudible]?\\nThe President. The President of Mexico is here, and she's doing a very good job. She's a good woman, very, very excellent job. It's an honor, and we're setting every record, and you're helping us set those records.\\nMr. Infantino. And we will do it.\\nThe President. You know, Mexico and Canada are helping us set those records. But as you know, we have a record in ticket sales already, long before the first ball is kicked, and we're going to do great.\\nI think that Gianni—as you know, he's the head, and he has done a fantastic job.\\nU.S. Cooperation With Mexico and Canada\\nQ. And how is the biggest challenge being three countries?\\nThe President. Well, I think that—do you mean for the three countries?\\nWell, they've gotten together really well, I mean.\\nMr. Infantino. All right.\\nThe President. They're getting along very well.\\nMr. Infantino. Collaboration is fantastic between the three.\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer/2026 World Cup\\nQ. And you like soccer?\\nThe President. I do. I like it. I like it more and more.\\nQ. Yes?\\nThe President. I like it. It's growing in this country—very, really—I mean, someday, maybe it's going to be bigger than anything else.\\nMr. Infantino. We'll have to become number one.\\nThe President. I will say this——\\nMr. Infantino. Definitely.\\nThe President. ——the ticket sales——\\nQ. Definitely will happen.\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. Ticket sales are bigger than anything we have ever done in the history of the country, in terms of sports.\\nMr. Infantino. For certain.\\nQ. And the audience is going to be huge.\\nThe President. The audience is going to be tremendous.\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. Yes.\\nMr. Infantino. Six billion people.\\nThe President. [Inaudible]\\nQ. Six billion? That's amazing.\\nMr. Infantino. Six billion people.\\nAnd today, one billion.\\nQ. Wow.\\nMr. Infantino. [Inaudible]\\nQ. Enjoy show time. Thank you so much.\\nThe President. [Inaudible]\\nQ. Mr. President, how are you? Just a quick—[inaudible].\\nQ. This is for Telemundo.\\nThe President. How are you?\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\\nQ. Hello, Mr. President. How are you? This for Telemundo.\\nThe President. How are you? Good.\\nQ. How are you?\\nThe President. Very good. Thank you.\\nQ. How does it feel to have the most important event of sports—that global—in the U.S.?\\nThe President. Well, we do. And right at the Kennedy Center. I'm Chairman of the Kennedy Center. And I hear the Kennedy Center is doing a very good job, so it feels great. Really good.\\nAnd Telemundo is doing a good job, too. Thank you.\\nQ. Thank you.\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. What is the significance of hosting the FIFA World Cup this year?\\nThe President. It's a—in terms of sports, I would say the ultimate. There is no sport like this. It's the biggest sport in the world. And we are setting every record. You know, our ticket sales have gone and set every—every sport—no matter what it is, we've set the record. So—and every though it's very early, there's no ball being kicked yet, but we've already set a ticket sales record.\\nArgentina National Team\\nQ. How do you see Argentinean team for this World Cup?\\nThe President. Well, I love Argentina. And your President is doing a very good job, as you know. Milei. You know that right? It's make Argentina great again. MAGA.\\nQ. And——\\nU.S. National Team\\nQ. Do you think the States are building a powerful team for next year?\\nThe President. Who?\\nQ. The States.\\nThe President. Oh, yes. Sure. I—you're going to have a lot of powerful teams. Everybody has a lot of powerful teams, but you're going to have a lot of great teams. [Inaudible]\\nU.S. Role in Hosting the 2026 World Cup\\nQ. Mr. President, what does it mean for you guys to host the World Cup right here in the U.S.?\\nThe President. I'm honored to host it. It's a great honor. I mean, it's turned out to be bigger than we thought. We're setting a record for ticket sales, the likes of which no sport has ever seen before.\\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\\nThe President. But they have a little more speed.\\nBut no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\\nPopularity of Soccer in Latin America\\nQ. Mr. President, a message for the Latin America and soccer fans?\\nThe President. Yes, I am. And Latin America is great. And they have great soccer. So, good luck in the matches.\\n[A reporter asked a question in Spanish, which was translated by an interpreter as follows.]\\nU.S. Visas for World Cup Ticketholders\\nQ. Who is going to be in—[inaudible]—about these visas for the—these fans that want to come here to the World Cup?\\nThe President. Well, we're going to make it very easy for them. We're working on that right now. We're going to make it very easy. It's going to be a very easy process.\\nQ. Okay. Say, hi to Colombia over there.\\nThe President. Hello. Is that Colombia?\\nQ. Yes.\\nThe President. I love Colombia. Hello, Colombia. [Laughter]\\nQ. Okay. Okay. Muy bien.\\nThe President. So where are you from?\\nQ. Paraguay.\\nThe President. Oh.\\nQ. He's from Paraguay. Yes.\\nThe President. Very good. I love it. I—it's a beautiful country. We get along very well with them. We do a little trade deal with them, and they like us. And that's what's happening.\\nQ. Panama.\\nThe President. Where?\\nVery good. I like the canal. [Laughter] That canal is pretty good.\\n[A reporter spoke in Spanish; no translation was provided.]\\n2026 World Cup\\nThe President. What?\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. Well, it's going to be incredible. The event is going to be very good. Just this event alone—it's at the Kennedy Center. I see you have it fixed up perfectly.\\nMr. Infantino. It will set the tone.\\nThe President. Right? It's beautiful.\\nMr. Infantino. It's beautiful.\\nThe President. It's a beautiful place.\\nHave a good time.\\nQ. [Inaudible]\\nThe President.\\n[A reporter spoke in Spanish; no translation was provided.]\\nMr. Infantino. No, gracias. [Inaudible]\\nThe President. It's great.\\nJohn F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts/Renovation Work\\nQ. Mr. President, the U.S. press?\\nThe President. Thank you, everybody, very much. It's a great honor. This has been an honor for a lot of reasons. Number one, they've sold more tickets than any event has ever sold already—long before the kickoff.\\nAnd number two, we've done a lot of work at the Kennedy Center. It was falling apart, and now it's pretty much back. And we'll get it back within the next 4 or 5 months through construction, and—but you see the way it looks.\\nAnd Gianni is just telling me—who's done an incredible job, by the way. He's just telling, you know, how good a job we've done.\\nMr. Infantino. That's right.\\nThe President. You can look at the walls. The marble was broken. Everything was a mess. And we've really taken the Kennedy Center—a lot of people thought it was going to be ripped down, and we did just the opposite. So we've done a really great renovation job on it. And over the next 3, 4 months, it will be complete. And we're honored to have it here, and it's been—it's been very special.\\nWe've set a record on ticket sales, as you probably heard, already, even way before—long before the event itself. And we're working with Canada, and we're working with Mexico. And it's been a really spectacular—so far, it's been spectacular.\\nDaniel [Daniel Baldwin, One America News Network], do you have a question?\\n2026 World Cup\\nQ. What are your expectations? You once said that the FIFA World Cup is an opportunity to put—a once-in-a-lifetime opportunity to put the greatness of the United States on display.\\nThe President. Well, I think—\\nQ. One billion eyeballs will be watching, Mr. President.\\nThe President. Yes, I—think——\\nQ. What will they here today?\\nThe President. Even today, I understand. I hear that, you know——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——I know we're a little late to get in there, but——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——that's okay.\\nMr. Infantino. They wait.\\nThe President. So all my friends, I guess they have to wait. They have no choice, right? [Laughter]\\nMr. Infantino. Yes, they wait.\\nThe President. But no, the numbers are incredible. I hear today's numbers are——\\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\\nThe President. ——very big. I hope CNN is covering this.\\nQ. One billion eyeballs.\\nMr. Infantino. Today, 1 billion eyeballs.\\nThe President. Today's numbers are very, very big.\\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize/The President's Foreign Policy\\nQ. We are covering it. And you're expected to get the FIFA Peace Prize, Mr. President. What would you say to people who say that prize might conflict with your pledge to strike Venezuela?\\nThe President. Well, I think the peace prize—I mean, I settled eight wars. I don't know that I'm getting it. I haven't been officially noticed. I've been hearing about a peace prize, and I'm here to represent our country in a different sense. But I can tell you, I did settle eight wars, and we have a ninth coming, but—which nobody has ever done before.\\nBut I want to really save lives. I don't need prizes. I need to save lives. And we're saving a lot of lives. And I've saved millions and millions of lives, and that's really what I want to do.\\nAnd I also want to run a great country. And the United States right now is the hottest country anywhere in the world. And 1 year ago, it was dead. We had a dead country, and now we have the hottest country anywhere in the world.\\nQ. Mr. President, will you——\\nThe President's Meeting With President Claudia Sheinbaum Pardo of Mexico and Prime Minister Mark Carney of Canada\\nQ. What are you going to discuss with Canada and Mexico, Mr.—what are you going to discuss with the leaders of Canada and Mexico?\\nThe President. Well, we're getting—we're going to meet with both. And we're getting along very well. You know, we're getting along very well. I don't know. I think we have a meeting set up for some time after the event.\\nQ. Will you discuss trade?\\nThe President. Yes, we'll discuss trade. We—get along very well.\\nThank you, everybody, very much.\\nQ. Will you pardon any other Honduran officials?\\nQ. Do you want them to keep trying to indict Ms. James?\\n\\nNOTE: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. In his remarks, he referred to Trey Yingst, chief foreign correspondent, Fox News Channel; Cristiano Ronaldo, forward for Saudi Pro League club Al-Nass and Portugal's national soccer team; and Lionel Messi, forward for Major League Soccer club Inter Miami and Argentina's national team. A reporter referred to New York State Attorney General Letitia James. The transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\n\\nSource URL: https://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/documents/remarks-exchange-with-reporters-prior-the-2026-federation-internationale-des-associations\\n\\n\\n[defendant] DX-3 GovInfo/OFR pre-event transcript excerpt\\nSource: GovInfo, DCPD202501162, Office of the Federal Register / National Archives and Records Administration.\\nURL: https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/DCPD-202501162/html/DCPD-202501162.htm\\nTitle: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\\nEvent date: December 5, 2025.\\n\\nRelevant extracted page text:\\n\\\"Administration of Donald J. Trump, 2025\\\"\\n\\\"Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw December 5, 2025\\\"\\n\\\"[The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\\\"\\n\\nUnder the section \\\"The President's Interest in Soccer\\\":\\n\\\"Q. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\\\"\\n\\\"The President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\\\\\\\"football,\\\\\\\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\\\"\\n\\\"Thank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\\\"\\n\\nAdditional relevant extracted page text:\\n\\\"The President's Interest in Soccer\\\"\\n\\\"Q. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\\\"\\n\\\"The President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\\\"\\n\\\"Mr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\\\"\\n\\\"The President. But they have a little more speed. But no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\\\"\\n\\nGovInfo note:\\n\\\"NOTE: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. In his remarks, he referred to Trey Yingst, chief foreign correspondent, Fox News Channel; Cristiano Ronaldo, forward for Saudi Pro League club Al-Nass and Portugal's national soccer team; and Lionel Messi, forward for Major League Soccer club Inter Miami and Argentina's national team. A reporter referred to New York State Attorney General Letitia James. The transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\\\"\\n\\nGovInfo content details page also identifies category \\\"Interviews With the News Media : Exchanges with reporters, Washington, DC,\\\" subjects including \\\"Federation Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) World Cup,\\\" \\\"John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts,\\\" and \\\"Soccer,\\\" and names including \\\"Ronaldo, Cristiano\\\" and \\\"Messi, Lionel.\\\"\\n\\n[defendant] DX-4 PRESMENTION/NEWMENTION terms\\n                                         NEWMENTION\\n\\nScope: These rules shall apply to this contract.\\n\\nUnderlying: The Underlying for this Contract is words used by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nRevisions to the Underlying made after Expiration will not be accounted for in determining the\\nExpiration Value.\\n\\nSource Agency: The Source Agencies are \\u003csource\\u003e.\\n\\nType: The type of Contract is an Event Contract.\\n\\nIssuance: After the initial Contract, Contract iterations will be listed on an as-needed basis at\\nthe discretion of the Exchange and corresponding to the risk management needs of Members.\\n\\n\\u003centity\\u003e: \\u003centity\\u003e refers to the speaker, writer, performer, or communicator specified by the\\nExchange. This may include (but is not limited to): a specific named individual, multiple\\nindividuals specified using AND/OR logic, an individual identified by position or title, a group,\\nband, team or collective entity, a specified member or members of a group, an organization,\\ncompany, or institutional entity, or any combination of the aforementioned.\\n\\nWhen \\u003centity\\u003e is defined by a position or title, the Contract tracks whoever holds that position\\nduring \\u003ctime period\\u003e, even if the individual holding the position changes. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a\\nspecific named individual, the identity remains consistent throughout. Name changes (e.g.,\\nstage names, married names) do not create a new entity. When \\u003centity\\u003e is a group or\\norganization and the Contract does not specify particular members, any official\\ncommunication or statement by any member or designated spokesperson counts. When using\\nAND logic, all specified entities must independently say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e. When\\nusing OR logic, at least one of the specified entities must say \\u003cword\\u003e during \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\nThe Exchange may specify additional conditions such as “at least X members of” a group or\\n“the majority of” a group.\\n\\n\\u003csource\\u003e: \\u003csource\\u003e refers to a Source Agency or ordered collection of Source Agencies\\nspecified by the Exchange at the time of Contract listing, which will be incorporated into the\\nSource Agency hierarchy above and used to determine the occurrence of the Underlying.\\n\\u003csource\\u003e may refer to a singular agency, multiple agencies, an agency by distinguishing\\ncharacteristics, by category or type (e.g., “official government statistical body,” “primary wire\\nservice”), or any combination thereof. When multiple agencies are specified, they may be\\napplied in the hierarchical order designated by the Exchange if so specified, with the highest-\\nranked available and responsive agency taking precedence for purposes of determining the\\nExpiration Value. A lower-ranked agency shall only be consulted if all higher-ranked agencies\\nare unavailable, unresponsive, have not reported on the Underlying by the Expiration time, or\\nif the Exchange, in its sole discretion, determines that a higher-ranked agency’s reporting is\\nincomplete, erroneous, or otherwise insufficient to determine the Expiration Value. If \\u003csource\\u003e\\ndesignates multiple agencies without specifying a hierarchical order, the Exchange shall\\nresolve any conflict between reporting agencies at its sole discretion.\\n\\n\\u003cword\\u003e: \\u003cword\\u003e refers to the particular word or phrase potentially to be mentioned by\\n\\u003centity\\u003e. It may refer to a word being said a minimum number of times. It may also refer to\\none of multiple words/phrases, any of which are acceptable (e.g., “Doge/Dogecoin”).\\n\\f\\u003ctime period\\u003e: \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific range of time, event or discrete date and\\ntime specified by the Exchange. This may be defined by, but is not limited to: a specific event\\nor context (e.g., “during the State of the Union address”), exact dates or times, relative time\\nmarkers (e.g., “before July 1, 2027,” “in Q1 2026”), event-based periods (e.g., “during any\\ncampaign rally in October 2026,” “during the awards ceremony”), and broader intervals (e.g.,\\n“Q1–Q2 2027,” “January–March 2026”).\\n\\nUnless stated otherwise, “Between” is inclusive of both endpoints, while “before” and “after”\\nexclude the specified date. \\u003ctime period\\u003e may also refer to “Any” or “None”, to multiple dates\\n(even if non-consecutive), or to a singular and discrete date or time.\\n\\nWhen \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event (such as an address, speech, performance, or\\nbroadcast), the Exchange may specify what is included, including whether it includes both live\\nand pre-recorded segments (including whether advertisements are included). Where a\\ntimezone is not specified, ET is assumed.\\n\\n\\nPayout Criterion: The Payout Criterion for the Contract encompasses the Expiration Values that\\n\\u003cword\\u003e is said by \\u003centity\\u003e \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n\\n\\nThe word must appear as a distinct, standalone unit, not buried inside another word. Plural\\nand possessive noun forms count. Other grammatical changes (tense, conjugation, derivation)\\ndo not. If \\u003cword\\u003e appears separated from other words by a space or hyphen or in a\\ncompound form with a space or hyphen, it counts. If \\u003cword\\u003e is fused into a single\\nunhyphenated word, it does not count.\\n\\nIf \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled, and the market contains a\\nstrike stating “Event does not qualify/occur”, such a strike shall resolve “Yes” and all others\\n“No”. If \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to an event and that event is cancelled but such strikes are NOT\\nlisted, the Contracts will resolve to the last fair price determined at the discretion of the\\nExchange. If the event is postponed, and such a postponement is announced by the end of the\\nfollowing calendar day to be rescheduled to a time within 14 calendar days, the markets shall\\nremain open. If the event captured in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast, the\\nExchange may keep the market open for 24 hours for the release of an official recording.\\nFurther granular details on conditions for these Contracts is available below.\\n\\nAdditional clarification(s):\\n\\n     Possessive noun forms of \\u003cword\\u003e, plurals, and possessive plural noun forms are\\n     INCLUDED:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigrants” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Egg” → “eggs’ shells” counts\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Russia” → “Russia’s” counts, “Russian” does not\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e exists only in adjective form, no plural form exists:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Economic” → “Economics” does not count (“Economic” is an adjective\\n          for which “Economics” is not a plural)\\n     Plural nouns occurring within proper nouns and noun phrases are included:\\n          \\u003cword\\u003e is “Cat” → “Cats the musical” counts\\n\\f    Grammatical variations beyond plurals/possessives are NOT included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Immigrant” → “Immigration” does NOT count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Run” → “Running” or “Ran” do NOT count\\n    When \\u003cword\\u003e specifies a plural form, the singular does NOT count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Veterans” → “Veteran” does NOT count\\n    Words that are spelled the same as the plural form of \\u003cword\\u003e (if such exists) but are\\n    themselves not a plural noun are included:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Wind” → “Winds up the clock” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Border” → “The United States has strong borders” counts\\n    Open compounds (words separated by spaces) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fire station” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “couch” → “couch potato” counts\\n    Hyphenated compounds (words connected by hyphens) count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “Palestine” → “pro-Palestine” counts\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fat” → “non-fat” counts\\n    Closed compounds (single word, no spaces/hyphens) do not count:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire” does not count\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firefighter” does not count\\n    Multi-word \\u003cword\\u003e in larger constructions: When \\u003cword\\u003e is a multi-word phrase\\n    appearing within a hyphenated construction, it counts only if \\u003cword\\u003e appears as a\\n    complete, unmodified element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “New York” → “New York-based” counts (complete element)\\n    Portmanteaus (words blended from two words where parts of each are combined) are\\n    NOT included unless the portmanteau clearly contains \\u003cword\\u003e as a distinct, unaltered\\n    element:\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “MAGA” → “MAGA-nificent” counts (MAGA appears as distinct element)\\n         \\u003cword\\u003e is “magnificent” → “MAGA-nificent” does NOT count (portmanteau blend)\\n\\nDictionary determination: Both the Merriam-Webster Dictionary (available online) AND the\\nOxford English Dictionary shall be used to determine compound type and/or conventional\\nspelling patterns. Inclusion in either dictionary as an open or hyphenated compound shall\\nsatisfy the Payout Criterion. If neither provides clarity (or the word is not included),\\ndetermination is based on whether written as single unit (closed/doesn’t count) vs. spaces or\\nhyphens (open or hyphenated/counts) and/or context and previous usage.\\n\\nPHONETIC EQUIVALENCIES\\n\\n    Homophones (same sound, different spelling) do not count:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “write” → “right” does not count\\n    Homonyms and homographs (same spelling) COUNT regardless of meaning or\\n    pronunciation:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “bass” → both “bass guitar” and “bass fishing” count\\n    Proper and common nouns are treated identically:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Apple” → both “Apple Inc.” and “apple” (fruit) count\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Will” → both “Will Smith” and “I will go” count\\n    Minor unintentional mispronunciations COUNT if context makes intent clear:\\n        \\u003cword\\u003e is “Mamdani” → “Mandani” counts\\n    Severe mispronunciations that make \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable do NOT count.\\n    Trademarked spellings do not count, even when pronounced identically, unless the word\\n\\fitself is the same:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “lift” → “Lyft” (pronounced “lift”) does not count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “uber” → “Uber” counts\\nWords with non-standard transliteration to English count within reason, provided they are\\nphonetically equivalent:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Zelensky” → any of “Zelenski,” “Zelenskii,” “Zelensky,” or “Zelenskiy”\\n      count if pronounced equivalently\\nContractions do not count for their constituent words unless otherwise explicitly specified\\nby the Exchange:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “not” → “won’t,” “can’t,” “don’t,” “isn’t” do not count\\nNumbers spoken as words COUNT, when spoken exactly (not part of a larger number):\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “five” → saying “five” or reading “$5” aloud as “five dollars” counts,\\n      saying “five hundred” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “410” → “four hundred ten”, “four one zero” or “four ten” counts\\nOrdinals COUNT when \\u003cword\\u003e is written numerically OR a phrase that includes a\\nnumber:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “January 6” → “January 6th” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “3” (written numerically) → “3rd” (spoken as “third”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Eight War” → “8 Wars” and “Eighth War” will count\\nCardinal and ordinal number words are distinct:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “one” → “first” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “first” → “one” does NOT count\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count when pronunciation or letter-by-letter spelling\\nmatches \\u003cword\\u003e:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “NASA” (pronounced “NAH-suh”) counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “NASA” → “N-A-S-A” (spelled out) counts\\nAcronyms and abbreviations count as \\u003cword\\u003e when pronounced as the full word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Doctor” → “Dr.” (pronounced “Doctor”) counts\\nExpanded forms of acronyms do NOT count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “AI” → “artificial intelligence” does not count\\nWords in foreign languages do NOT count unless they are perfect cognates with an\\nEnglish word:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “fuego” (Spanish) does NOT count\\nEnglish words within foreign sentences count:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “policy” → “Nuestra policy es clara” counts\\n\\u003cword\\u003e in organization/company names counts:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “Securities” → “Bank of America Securities” counts\\nWords in URLs, emails, handles, and hashtags (exclusive of domain structure, email\\nprovider or symbols) are treated as compounds when spoken as complete words, with the\\ntype of compound subject to aforementioned rules:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “firestation.com” pronounced “fire station dot com” counts\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “fire” → “wildfire.com” pronounced “wildfire dot com” does NOT count\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “apple” → “apple.com” pronounced “apple dot com” does count\\n      When presented in URL, email, handle, or hashtag form, \\u003cword\\u003e shall be treated as\\n      a compound, not a multi-word word\\nSung, rapped, or poetic words COUNT if phonetically recognizable:\\n      \\u003cword\\u003e is “money” → “moneyyy” (extended in rap) counts\\n      Extreme distortion making \\u003cword\\u003e unrecognizable does NOT count.\\nPhonetic alphabet spelling (“Foxtrot India Romeo Echo” for “FIRE”) does NOT count.\\n\\fCANCELLATIONS AND DELAYS\\n\\n   The Exchange may list an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike for any Contract. If listed,\\n   such a strike refers to the structural conditions of the market, and is NOT adjudicated as a\\n   \\u003cword\\u003e needing to be said by or validated by having been said by \\u003centity\\u003e. If listed, this\\n   strike resolves to “Yes” whenever the event fails to occur or qualify under the Payout\\n   Criterion, or any other circumstance prevents normal resolution.\\n   If no such strike is listed, and \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, the following rules\\n   apply if the event is cancelled, postponed, rescheduled, or materially altered (including\\n   being closed to press) such that no video is released within one calendar day of the\\n   original start time of the event:\\n         If the event is cancelled, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price determined in\\n         the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         If the event is postponed or rescheduled, the outcome depends on whether a new\\n         date is publicly announced within one calendar day (i.e. if the event was scheduled\\n         to begin on Monday, any time up to 11:59PM on Tuesday falls within this period) of\\n         the originally scheduled start time:\\n               If no new date is announced within one calendar day, the Contract will resolve\\n               to the last fair price determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n               If a new date is announced within one calendar day, the outcome depends on\\n               when the rescheduled event is set to occur:\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls within fourteen (14) calendar days of the\\n                     originally scheduled date, the Contract shall remain open and \\u003cword\\u003e\\n                     stated during the rescheduled event will count.\\n                           The fourteen-day window begins at 12:00 AM ET on the originally\\n                           scheduled date and ends at 11:59 PM ET fourteen days later, unless\\n                           an alternate timezone is explicitly specified.\\n                           Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the State of the Union on January\\n                           15, 2026” rescheduled to January 20, 2026 → words spoken during\\n                           the rescheduled address count.\\n                     If the rescheduled date falls more than fourteen (14) calendar days after\\n                     the originally scheduled date, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price\\n                     determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\\n         Any Contract that cannot be resolved through the Source Agency hierarchy will\\n         instead be settled at the Last Fair Price. The Exchange will disclose the methodology\\n         used to determine the Last Fair Price (e.g., Last Traded Price, Time-Weighted\\n         Average Price) at the time of Issuance.\\n         If an event begins but is interrupted, abbreviated, or ends prematurely, words\\n         stated by \\u003centity\\u003e during the portion of the event that did occur will count and the\\n         market will otherwise resolve.\\n   If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window but the venue, format, or medium\\n   changes (e.g., moved to a different location, changed from in-person to virtual (with the\\n   exception of being closed to press)), words stated during the event will count.\\n   Special condition: Across both cases, whether an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike is\\n   listed or not, if the event specified as or in \\u003ctime period\\u003e is a live-stream or broadcast (or\\n   relayed as such) but the live stream/broadcast does not occur, the Exchange will instead\\n   use an officially released recording as the Underlying, and may delay resolution by up to\\n   one calendar day to allow for the release of such a recording.\\n\\f          If partial snippets are released, Contracts on words that do not appear will be\\n          resolved to last fair price, and Contracts on those that do will be resolved to “Yes”.\\n          If no recording is released, the relevant outcomes triggered by the\\n          presence/absence of an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike shall occur as outlined\\n          above.\\n\\nTECHNICAL DETAILS (UNLESS OTHERWISE SPECIFIED)\\n\\n     When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event, pre-recorded content broadcast,\\n     streamed, or published as part of that event is included if presented as part of the official\\n     presentation.\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the concert” with pre-recorded video interlude\\n          where entity speaks → words from interlude count\\n          Example: \\u003ctime period\\u003e is “during the television appearance” with pre-taped\\n          segment aired during broadcast → words from segment count\\n     Behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are NOT\\n     included unless officially broadcast or published as part of \\u003ctime period\\u003e.\\n     Subtitles and captions that display \\u003cword\\u003e on screen but are not spoken aloud by\\n     \\u003centity\\u003e do NOT count.\\n     Sign language interpretation or usage by entity does NOT count as saying \\u003cword\\u003e unless\\n     the Contract explicitly specifies that sign language counts.\\n     Text that entity displays on screen (presentation slides, teleprompter visible to audience,\\n     signatures) does NOT count unless entity reads it aloud.\\n     Content generated by AI, deepfakes, or synthetic voice technology impersonating entity\\n     does NOT count unless the synthetic content is officially commissioned, authorized, or\\n     published by entity, OR the Contract explicitly specifies that AI-generated content counts.\\n     If \\u003cword\\u003e is muted due to technical failure or censorship it shall not count unless\\n     corroborating contextual evidence (including surrounding speech, or an official\\n     uncensored recording or transcript) confirms that \\u003centity\\u003e specifically uttered \\u003cword\\u003e\\n     during the muted period.\\n\\nMinimum Tick: The Minimum Tick size for the Contract shall be $0.01.\\n\\nPosition Accountability Level: The Position Accountability Level for the Contract shall be\\n$25,000 per strike, per Member.\\n\\nLast Trading Date: The Last Trading Date of the Contract will be the Expiration Date. The Last\\nTrading Time will be the Expiration time.\\n\\nSettlement Date: The Settlement Date of the Contract shall be no later than the day after the\\nExpiration Date, unless the Market Outcome is under review pursuant to Rule 7.1.\\n\\nExpiration Date: When \\u003ctime period\\u003e refers to a specific event: The latest Expiration Date of\\nthe Contract shall be fourteen (14) calendar days after the originally scheduled date of the\\nevent. If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window, expiration will be moved to an\\nearlier date and time in accordance with Rule 7.2. When \\u003ctime period\\u003e is defined by specific\\ndates: The latest Expiration Date of the Contract shall be two weeks after the end of \\u003ctime\\nperiod\\u003e. If an event described in the Payout Criterion occurs and a consensus has been\\nreached on all terms, then expiration will be moved to an earlier date and time in accordance\\nwith Rule 7.2.\\n\\fExpiration time: The Expiration time of the Contract shall be 10:00 AM ET.\\n\\nSettlement Value: The Settlement Value for this Contract is $1.00.\\n\\nExpiration Value: The Expiration Value is the value of the Underlying as documented by the\\nSource Agency on the Expiration Date at the Expiration time.\\n\\nContingencies: Before Settlement, Kalshi may, at its sole discretion, initiate the Market\\nOutcome Review Process pursuant to Rule 7.1 of the Rulebook. If an Expiration Value cannot\\nbe determined on the Expiration Date, Kalshi has the right to determine payouts pursuant to\\nRule 7.1 in the Rulebook.\\n\\f\\n\\n[defendant] DX-5 Formal draw archive note\\nSource checked: Roll Call / Factba.se archive\\n\\nArchive title: Remarks: Donald Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing in Washington - December 5, 2025\\n\\nArchive URL: https://rollcall.com/factbase/trump/transcript/donald-trump-remarks-fifa-world-cup-drawing-december-5-2025/\\n\\nWhat this file establishes:\\n\\nThere is a separate archived transcript page for Trump's formal attendance remarks at the draw.\\n\\nWhat this file does not establish:\\n\\nThis session could not retrieve the full transcript text from that archive.  The page is password-protected.  This example therefore does not claim, from local files alone, whether the formal program transcript does or does not contain the word \\\"Ronaldo.\\\"\\n\\nWhy this matters:\\n\\nThe complaint does not need to prove that the formal program omitted the strike.  It needs to show that Trump said \\\"Ronaldo\\\" in event-linked remarks and that the market boundary reasonably includes those remarks.  The formal archive remains relevant because it marks the distinction between the pre-event reporter exchange and the formal program.\\n\\n\\n[defendant] DX-6 Formal Roll Call/Factba.se transcript extraction\\nSource: Roll Call / Factba.se\\nURL: https://rollcall.com/factbase/trump/transcript/donald-trump-remarks-fifa-world-cup-drawing-december-5-2025/\\nCaptured page title: Remarks: Donald Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing in Washington - December 5, 2025\\n\\nRendered page metadata excerpt:\\nTopics: Sport; Sport \\u003e Competition Discipline \\u003e Soccer; Lifestyle and Leisure \\u003e Leisure \\u003e Game.\\nEntities listed: bowl; deal; Donald J. Trump; FIFA World Cup; Mark Carney; place; President; trophy; United States; way.\\nSpeakers listed: Gianni Infantino, Donald Trump, Mark Carney, Claudia Sheinbaum.\\nSpeaker statistics excerpt: Donald Trump said 25 sentences of a total of 141 sentences; Donald Trump said 274 words of a total of 1009 words; Donald Trump talked 92 seconds of a total of 484 seconds.\\n\\nFormal transcript excerpt at start of draw:\\nMark Carney, 00:00:00-00:00:02: Thank you, my friend.\\nGianni Infantino, 00:00:50-00:01:22: So this is the World Cup trophy. This is the official bowl for the World Cup and we are now going to do the draw, ladies and gentlemen. But before that, as is customary, there is always a question that the moderator asks the draw assistant. So I would like to start with Mr. Carney. How big a deal is it to co-host the World Cup for Canada?\\n\\nFormal transcript excerpt of Trump's soccer answer:\\nDonald Trump, 00:03:14-00:03:32: Well, for years, Gianni, they've thought soccer or football would be so big, so fast. And I remember, I shouldn't say this because it was a long time ago, but I remember watching Pele play on a team called the Cosmos, Pele, who was fantastic, as you know. I assume one of the greats.\\n\\nText-extraction/search notes:\\nLocal Python urllib retrieval of the page returned HTTP 200 for the source URL and extracted approximately 175,864 characters of page text with Python html.parser. Case-sensitive searches in the extracted page text returned no occurrence of \\\"Ronaldo\\\" and no occurrence of \\\"Messi\\\". The same terms were not found using the browser page find function on the rendered page.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R1 Defendant formal transcript extraction for limited rebuttal use\\nSource: Roll Call / Factba.se\\nURL: https://rollcall.com/factbase/trump/transcript/donald-trump-remarks-fifa-world-cup-drawing-december-5-2025/\\nCaptured page title: Remarks: Donald Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing in Washington - December 5, 2025\\n\\nRendered page metadata excerpt:\\nTopics: Sport; Sport \\u003e Competition Discipline \\u003e Soccer; Lifestyle and Leisure \\u003e Leisure \\u003e Game.\\nEntities listed: bowl; deal; Donald J. Trump; FIFA World Cup; Mark Carney; place; President; trophy; United States; way.\\nSpeakers listed: Gianni Infantino, Donald Trump, Mark Carney, Claudia Sheinbaum.\\nSpeaker statistics excerpt: Donald Trump said 25 sentences of a total of 141 sentences; Donald Trump said 274 words of a total of 1009 words; Donald Trump talked 92 seconds of a total of 484 seconds.\\n\\nFormal transcript excerpt at start of draw:\\nMark Carney, 00:00:00-00:00:02: Thank you, my friend.\\nGianni Infantino, 00:00:50-00:01:22: So this is the World Cup trophy. This is the official bowl for the World Cup and we are now going to do the draw, ladies and gentlemen. But before that, as is customary, there is always a question that the moderator asks the draw assistant. So I would like to start with Mr. Carney. How big a deal is it to co-host the World Cup for Canada?\\n\\nFormal transcript excerpt of Trump's soccer answer:\\nDonald Trump, 00:03:14-00:03:32: Well, for years, Gianni, they've thought soccer or football would be so big, so fast. And I remember, I shouldn't say this because it was a long time ago, but I remember watching Pele play on a team called the Cosmos, Pele, who was fantastic, as you know. I assume one of the greats.\\n\\nText-extraction/search notes:\\nLocal Python urllib retrieval of the page returned HTTP 200 for the source URL and extracted approximately 175,864 characters of page text with Python html.parser. Case-sensitive searches in the extracted page text returned no occurrence of \\\"Ronaldo\\\" and no occurrence of \\\"Messi\\\". The same terms were not found using the browser page find function on the rendered page.\\n\\nSubmitted evidence:\\n[plaintiff arguments] GovInfo DCPD202501162 transcript excerpt and metadata (ev_3fc783920414_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-3fc783920414)\\nSource: https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/DCPD-202501162/html/DCPD-202501162.htm\\nSHA-256: `3fc783920414399098d86210070dd9fe83c14fe1dbded1a56a554f8f4b3448f2`\\nBytes: 2641\\nRelevance: Official government transcript source corroborating that Trump spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center before the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw and said the strike word Ronaldo in World-Cup-related remarks.\\n\\n[defendant arguments] Roll Call/Factba.se formal FIFA World Cup Drawing transcript extraction (ev_fbb53e87ccb3_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-fbb53e87ccb3)\\nSource: https://rollcall.com/factbase/trump/transcript/donald-trump-remarks-fifa-world-cup-drawing-december-5-2025/\\nSHA-256: `fbb53e87ccb3f4381fc2bdc06ac2f2a1ea3848aadde56122b22d34dfbdf4533b`\\nBytes: 2032\\nRelevance: Formal drawing-program transcript evidence showing a separate formal Draw source from the pre-event reporter exchange; the extracted page text contains no occurrence of Ronaldo or Messi, supporting defendant's event-boundary argument.\\n\\nTechnical reports:\\n[plaintiff] Plaintiff source and adverse-search ledger\\nChecked the visible case packet and then searched official/source-specific repositories. GovInfo DCPD202501162 was opened and preserved as submitted evidence; it corroborates the packet transcript, source metadata, location, event date, and Ronaldo passages. The Roll Call/Factba.se formal drawing page rendered despite the packet's password-protection note; browser find searches for 'Ronaldo,' 'Cristiano,' and 'Messi' returned no matches. Plaintiff therefore treats the formal-program transcript as an adverse boundary check, not as proof of a formal-stage mention. The remaining dispute is contractual scope: whether the market clearly excluded public event-linked venue remarks immediately before the formal program.\\n\\n[defendant] Defense source-check ledger\\nDefendant searched for the formal Roll Call/Factba.se transcript identified by the case packet, opened the rendered Roll Call page, and fetched it locally with Python urllib. The fetch returned HTTP 200 for the formal FIFA World Cup Drawing transcript page. Text extraction produced approximately 175,864 characters; searches for \\\"Ronaldo\\\" and \\\"Messi\\\" returned no occurrences. The retrieval also captured formal-program excerpts, including Infantino's statement that \\\"we are now going to do the draw\\\" and Trump's formal soccer answer mentioning Pele rather than Ronaldo. The focused extraction was submitted and accepted as ev_fbb53e87ccb3_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-fbb53e87ccb3.\\n\\nCall submit_council_vote with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated.\\nKeep the rationale brief: no more than three sentences.\\n\\nCouncil API instructions:\\nYou are a council member. Decide the proposition from the admitted record.\\nYou may examine admitted evidence through read-only tools when exact bytes, metadata, or exhibit contents matter.\\nDo not search the web, introduce new facts, create new evidence, or upload evidence.\\nWhen ready, call submit_council_vote exactly once with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated and a concise rationale.\\n\",\"state\":\"ready\",\"status\":\"ready\",\"tools\":[{\"description\":\"Return the current visible arbitration record for this council member.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"get_case\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"List visible immutable record evidence.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"list_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Return metadata and read limits for one visible evidence item.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"stat_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Read a bounded byte range from one visible evidence item as base64.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"length\":{\"minimum\":1,\"type\":\"integer\"},\"offset\":{\"minimum\":0,\"type\":\"integer\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\",\"offset\",\"length\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"read_evidence_range\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Submit one council vote for the current deliberation opportunity.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"rationale\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"vote\":{\"enum\":[\"demonstrated\",\"not_demonstrated\"],\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"vote\",\"rationale\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"submit_council_vote\",\"read_only\":false}],\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":false,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-29T19:58:02.156322961Z\",\"deliberation_round\":1,\"member_id\":\"C2\",\"opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C2\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"remaining_ms\":887183,\"role_id\":\"council\",\"turn_number\":10},\"wait\":{\"reason\":\"ready\",\"state_version\":12,\"version\":15}}"}],"structuredContent":{"after_opportunity_id":"deliberation:1:C2","after_version":15,"case_id":"arb-ex03-20260629192557","limits":{"attempts_max":3,"attempts_remaining":3,"max_evidence_read_bytes":65536,"max_evidence_read_bytes_per_opportunity":524288,"max_evidence_reads_per_opportunity":32,"max_response_bytes":131072,"remaining_evidence_read_bytes_for_opportunity":524288,"remaining_evidence_reads_for_opportunity":32},"member_id":"C2","message":"An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.","ok":true,"prompt":"Role: council member\nMember ID: C2\nDeliberation round: 1\nProposition: For the Kalshi market \"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\", the strike \"Ronaldo\" should resolve Yes because Trump said \"Ronaldo\" in public remarks at the World Cup Draw venue immediately before the formal program, and the market wording plus the governing mention-market terms did not clearly exclude those event-linked remarks.\nStandard of evidence: Preponderance of the evidence.\nPersona:\nYou are a careful juror and council member.\n\nEvaluate the record faithfully. Decide only from the evidence, the stated rules, and the applicable burden of proof. Do not favor either side, fill gaps with speculation, or ignore uncertainty.\n\nGive weight to reliable sources, direct evidence, consistent reasoning, and clear admissions. Discount unsupported claims, rhetorical force, irrelevant facts, and conclusions that exceed the record.\n\nWhen the evidence supports one answer, state it plainly. When the evidence is incomplete or balanced, say so. Be concise, honest, and exact.\n\nRecord:\nOpenings:\n[plaintiff] Council members, this case is not mainly about whether the syllables were spoken. The case-packet transcript says they were. The real dispute is the market boundary: when Kalshi asked what Trump would say \"during the FIFA World Cup Draw,\" did that phrase clearly exclude his public, event-linked remarks at the World Cup Draw venue immediately before the formal program? On this record, it did not.\n\nThe market page fixes the contract at issue: the public title was \"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\"; the contract family was PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION; the strike was \"Ronaldo\"; Kalshi challenged the resolution as No; and the requested resolution is Yes. That means the council's task is to apply the mention-market terms to that title and strike, not to import a narrower limitation that the market did not plainly announce.\n\nThe reporter-exchange packet is direct evidence on the word and setting. It is titled as remarks in an exchange with reporters prior to the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw, dated December 5, 2025. It places the President at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts, speaking with FIFA President Gianni Infantino and reporters in a sequence repeatedly labeled around the 2026 World Cup and the Draw. In that exchange, in a soccer discussion, Trump says he met Ronaldo, praises him, and uses \"Ronaldo\" as a distinct standalone word. Under the mention rules, a distinct standalone appearance of the strike is the kind of use that counts if it falls within the time period.\n\nThe terms matter because they do not say that an event market is limited only to scripted remarks from a formal stage segment. They define a time period as potentially an event or context, and they give the Exchange power to specify what is included when a time period refers to a specific event. They also distinguish official/public event content from behind-the-scenes, rehearsals, and unofficial recordings. That distinction helps plaintiff: the packet is not a rumor, rehearsal, private soundcheck, or leaked recording. It is a sourced public transcript of remarks at the event venue, immediately tied to the Draw. If Kalshi meant \"only the formal televised draw program after doors close\" or \"only remarks in the separate formal archive,\" it needed to say so clearly.\n\nI also want to be candid about what the packet does not yet prove. The formal-draw archive note says a separate archived transcript page exists for Trump's formal attendance remarks, but that the session could not retrieve the full text because the page was password-protected. So, at opening, plaintiff is not asking you to infer that the formal program itself contained \"Ronaldo.\" Nor does plaintiff need that inference. The Yes theory is that the qualifying period reasonably includes the public pre-program reporter exchange that was part of Trump's World Cup Draw appearance. The formal archive is relevant because it marks defendant's likely narrower boundary; it does not resolve the boundary in defendant's favor.\n\nProvenance and weight also favor treating the packet seriously at this stage. The market and terms files are system case-packet records. The reporter exchange includes a source URL to a public presidential transcript source and notes a corrected transcript date, while also acknowledging that some audio could not be verified because the audio was incomplete. That caveat may affect inaudible portions, but it does not erase the visible, contextual Ronaldo passage. Later, when evidence admission opens, the parties should preserve the official transcript source, any govinfo or Presidency Project copy, the market page capture, and any accessible formal-program transcript or video. The adverse check should ask whether the formal program omits the word, but omission there would matter only if the council first accepts the defense's artificially narrow reading of \"during.\"\n\nThe plaintiff's burden is preponderance. The record already points to a straightforward path to Yes: Trump, the specified entity, said the specified strike as a standalone word in public remarks linked to and immediately preceding the World Cup Draw at the venue; the market title and governing terms did not clearly exclude that event-linked exchange. On a fair reading of the contract the trader saw, the challenged No resolution should give way to Yes.\n\n[defendant] Council members, the defense opening is simple: this case is not won by proving that the word \"Ronaldo\" appears somewhere in a public transcript. The plaintiff must prove, by a preponderance, that the word was said during the market's specified event: the FIFA World Cup Draw.\n\nThe current packet leaves that critical link unproven. The market page does not say \"while Trump was at the venue,\" \"during a World Cup press availability,\" or \"during any remarks connected to the Draw.\" It says: \"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\" The challenged resolution was No. The requested Yes theory therefore needs more than event-adjacent context; it needs a boundary showing that the reporter exchange was part of the Draw period the market asked traders to price.\n\nThe plaintiff's own best transcript cuts against that boundary. The case-packet file is titled \"Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw.\" It says the President's remarks were joined in progress, and the source note says portions could not be verified because the audio was incomplete. It places Trump at the Kennedy Center and includes World Cup topics, and yes, it contains \"Ronaldo\" as a standalone word in a soccer exchange. But its title and structure identify those remarks as an exchange with reporters prior to the Draw, not the formal Draw itself.\n\nThe terms do not rescue plaintiff from that distinction. They define a mention market around words used by the entity during the time period. A time period may be a specific event, and when it is a specific event, the Exchange may specify what is included. The technical details also distinguish official presentation content from behind-the-scenes, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings unless those are officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. Those provisions do not mean every public, nearby, event-related conversation becomes part of the event. They make the event boundary the central question.\n\nThe formal-draw archive note reinforces why the distinction matters. It reports that there is a separate archived transcript page for Trump's formal attendance remarks at the FIFA World Cup Drawing, but that the full text was not retrieved because the page was password-protected. That note does not prove the formal program omitted Ronaldo. It also does not prove the formal program included it. What it does show, at opening, is that the record itself separates the pre-event reporter exchange from the formal drawing remarks.\n\nSo the defense will focus the council on proof of inclusion, not mere association. If later phases produce a market page provision, official broadcast record, program transcript, video metadata, or source-agency material showing that the red-carpet reporter exchange was officially part of the FIFA World Cup Draw presentation for this market, the council can weigh that. If the later evidence instead shows a formal program with a separate pre-program press availability, then the correct result is No even though the word was spoken nearby.\n\nOn this opening record, plaintiff has shown a Ronaldo mention in remarks prior to the event. Plaintiff has not shown that those remarks occurred during the market event. The defense position is that Kalshi's No resolution follows the market wording and the mention-market terms unless plaintiff supplies that missing boundary proof.\n\nArguments:\n[plaintiff] Council members, the merits question is whether the contract clearly limited “during the FIFA World Cup Draw” to only the formal staged ceremony. Plaintiff submits that it did not, and the record now proves the Yes result by a preponderance.\n\nFirst, the market itself is broad. PX-1 identifies the public question as “What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?”, contract family PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION, strike “Ronaldo,” challenged resolution No, and requested resolution Yes. The market page does not say “during the formal televised ceremony,” “on the main stage only,” or “excluding public remarks immediately before the program at the venue.” That absence matters because Kalshi drafted the boundary traders had to price.\n\nSecond, the word was said. PX-2, the case-packet transcript, and PX-5, the GovInfo/OFR source excerpt, both show Trump used “Ronaldo” as a standalone word in soccer-related remarks. PX-5 is especially useful on provenance: it is the GovInfo Compilation of Presidential Documents source, published by the Office of the Federal Register/NARA, for DCPD202501162. It identifies the same event date, title, and source note, and it places the remarks at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center. In the relevant passage, Trump says he met Ronaldo, then says Ronaldo is great; later, when asked whether he played soccer or football, Trump says he was not Ronaldo or Messi. Either use satisfies the mention rule if the remarks fall within the market’s time period.\n\nThird, the remarks are event-linked in the way the market title reasonably covers. PX-2 and PX-5 are not private gossip, rehearsal, or an unofficial leak. They are public presidential remarks at the World Cup Draw venue, with FIFA President Infantino present, repeatedly discussing the Draw, the World Cup, ticket sales, the Kennedy Center, the audience, and the imminent program. The transcript itself includes headings such as “2026 World Cup Draw Event,” “2026 World Cup Draw Event/John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts,” and “2026 World Cup Draw/Ticket Sales for World Cup.” Trump and Infantino even discuss being a little late to “get in there” and the audience waiting. That sequence is not a random earlier interview; it is part of the public event appearance immediately surrounding the Draw.\n\nFourth, PX-3’s terms do not impose defendant’s formal-only line. They say the underlying is words used by the entity during the specified time period; a time period may be an event or context; and, when a time period refers to a specific event, the Exchange may specify what is included. They also say official/published content presented as part of the official presentation can count, while behind-the-scenes, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings do not count unless officially broadcast or published as part of the time period. Those exclusions show what this is not. The transcript is an official published record of public remarks at the event venue, not a hidden backstage clip. Nothing in PX-1 or PX-3 clearly tells traders that public, event-linked venue remarks immediately before the formal program are out.\n\nDefendant’s best point is PX-4 and the formal Roll Call/Factba.se page: there is a separate formal-drawing transcript, and my search found no “Ronaldo” there. Plaintiff does not hide that. But that adverse point proves only that the narrower formal-program source may omit the strike. It does not answer the contractual question. If Kalshi had meant to resolve solely by that formal transcript, it could have said so. Instead, the public market title used the broader phrase “during the FIFA World Cup Draw,” and the mention terms leave event boundaries to what the market clearly specifies.\n\nOn burden, plaintiff does not need absolute certainty or a formal-stage mention. Plaintiff must show it is more likely than not that the market wording plus terms include the event-linked remarks. The evidence satisfies that standard: PX-1 gives no exclusion; PX-2 and PX-5 prove the standalone Ronaldo mentions in public World Cup Draw venue remarks; PX-3 supplies a flexible event/time-period framework and excludes only categories unlike this source; PX-4 merely identifies the defense’s alternate formal-program boundary. The fair resolution is Yes.\n\n[defendant] Council members, the record now makes the defense point sharper, not weaker. Plaintiff has proved that Trump said \"Ronaldo\" in an official transcript of remarks connected to the World Cup Draw. Plaintiff has not proved that those remarks were during the market event.\n\nStart with the contract. DX/PX-1 gives the trader-facing question: \"What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\" It does not say \"at the Kennedy Center,\" \"on World Cup Draw day,\" \"in remarks prior to the Draw,\" or \"in any public press exchange associated with the Draw.\" For this strike to resolve Yes, the relevant mention must fall inside that specified time period.\n\nThe strongest evidence of the Ronaldo utterance is also the strongest evidence against plaintiff's boundary. PX-2 and PX-5 are titled \"Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw.\" PX-5, plaintiff's GovInfo/OFR source, confirms the same title, says the remarks were joined in progress, identifies the source as an exchange with the news media, and notes that some portions could not be verified because the audio was incomplete. That evidence proves an official pre-event reporter transcript. It does not prove the reporter exchange was the FIFA World Cup Draw.\n\nThe terms, PX-3, require words used by the entity during the specified time period. They permit an event or context as a time period, and they discuss what is included when the time period is a specific event. That framework does not turn all event-adjacent speech into event speech. The distinction between official presentation content and non-included behind-the-scenes or unofficial content matters because the question is not just whether a record is public or official. The question is whether this source was part of the market's event period. A public official transcript can still be a transcript of remarks prior to the event.\n\nDX-2 supplies the missing contrast. It is a focused extraction from the separate Roll Call/Factba.se formal FIFA World Cup Drawing transcript. That page is the formal source identified in the case-packet archive note. It is titled \"Remarks: Donald Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing in Washington - December 5, 2025.\" Its transcript begins with the formal drawing participants; at 00:00:50, Infantino says, \"This is the World Cup trophy\" and \"we are now going to do the draw.\" The page's Trump soccer answer mentions Pele and the Cosmos, not Ronaldo. The extracted page text was searched for both \"Ronaldo\" and \"Messi\" and neither appears.\n\nThat does not prove Trump never said Ronaldo anywhere at the venue. It proves the opposite boundary from plaintiff's: the formal Draw transcript is separate from the pre-event reporter exchange, and the formal transcript does not contain the strike. Plaintiff needs a bridge between those two sources. It has not offered one. There is no market page detail saying red-carpet or pre-program press remarks count. There is no official program metadata showing the reporter exchange was part of the Draw presentation. There is no source hierarchy provision selecting the pre-event reporter exchange over the formal Draw transcript for this market.\n\nPlaintiff argues ambiguity should favor Yes because Kalshi could have drafted a narrower rule. But this is a preponderance case about a challenged No resolution, not a penalty for every conceivable ambiguity. The ordinary reading of \"during the FIFA World Cup Draw\" is the draw program, not every public appearance immediately before it. The record's own labels preserve that ordinary line: \"Prior to\" on the Ronaldo source; \"Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing\" on the formal source; and a formal transcript that starts the draw and omits the strike.\n\nWeight and provenance also favor the defense on the decisive issue. PX-5 is official and useful, but it authenticates a pre-event reporter exchange. DX-2 is a captured formal transcript extraction from the source class identified in PX-4; its absence finding is limited but material. PX-4 was initially only a note that the formal page existed and could not be retrieved. We have now retrieved and searched it. The adverse check therefore confirms, rather than merely speculates, that the formal drawing transcript does not carry plaintiff's Ronaldo mention.\n\nThe council should resolve the proposition against plaintiff. The record shows Trump said Ronaldo before the FIFA World Cup Draw in an event-linked reporter exchange. It does not show he said Ronaldo during the FIFA World Cup Draw. On this market wording and these terms, the challenged No resolution should stand.\n\nRebuttals:\n[plaintiff] Council members, defendant’s new formal-transcript extraction proves less than defendant needs.\n\nPlaintiff accepts the narrow fact defendant has now preserved: the Roll Call/Factba.se formal drawing-program extraction contains no “Ronaldo” or “Messi.” That is why plaintiff did not build the case on a formal-stage mention. The proposition instead asks whether the market wording and mention terms clearly excluded Trump’s public, official, event-linked remarks at the venue immediately before the formal program. Defendant has not supplied that exclusion.\n\nDefendant’s argument treats the title “Prior to the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw” as if “prior to” automatically means outside the Kalshi market’s event period. But PX-1 does not say “formal transcript only,” “after the draw host begins,” “after 00:00:50,” or “excluding press availability at the venue.” It asks what Trump would say “during the FIFA World Cup Draw.” The source label tells us sequence; it does not tell us the market’s legal boundary.\n\nDX-2 actually illustrates why defendant’s bright line is chosen after the fact. In defendant’s own formal extraction, the page begins before the mechanical draw: Mark Carney speaks at 00:00:00, and Infantino says at 00:00:50, “we are now going to do the draw.” If “during the FIFA World Cup Draw” can include ceremony and preamble on the formal page before the draw itself begins, then the phrase is not self-defining down to a single moment or transcript. The question is what the market clearly specified. It did not specify defendant’s transcript-only rule.\n\nThe terms do not fill that gap for defendant. PX-3 excludes hidden categories such as rehearsals, sound checks, unofficial recordings, and behind-the-scenes content unless officially published as part of the period. PX-2 and PX-5 are not those categories. PX-5 is an official GovInfo/OFR presidential transcript, published with source metadata, at 11:13 a.m. at the Kennedy Center, with FIFA’s president present and the World Cup Draw repeatedly discussed. That gives the Ronaldo mentions strong provenance and an event connection; it does not make them informal backstage chatter.\n\nDefendant says plaintiff needs a bridge. The bridge is the market text plus the terms’ failure to draw the narrow line defendant proposes. A No resolution can stand only if the contract fairly told traders that “during the FIFA World Cup Draw” meant only the separate formal-program transcript. On this record, the more likely reading is broader: public, official remarks at the venue, immediately tied to and immediately preceding the World Cup Draw program, were within the event-linked period unless clearly excluded.\n\nSo DX-2 narrows one factual issue but does not decide the case. It shows no formal-stage Ronaldo mention. It does not show that the market excluded the official pre-program event remarks where Trump did say Ronaldo. Under the preponderance standard, the Yes resolution remains the fair one.\n\nSurrebuttals:\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff’s rebuttal usefully narrows the dispute. Plaintiff accepts that the formal Roll Call/Factba.se drawing transcript contains no “Ronaldo” or “Messi.” So the case remains entirely about whether a separate reporter exchange titled “Prior to the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw” should be treated as inside the market period.\n\nPlaintiff says “prior to” is only sequence, not legal boundary. But sequence is exactly what the market phrase makes material. The contract asks what Trump would say “during the FIFA World Cup Draw.” A source-agency title identifying the Ronaldo transcript as an exchange with reporters prior to that Draw is not a stray label; it is the best record description of when and what that source is. Plaintiff cannot convert that source into the event itself by saying the market failed to list every excluded pre-event setting.\n\nPlaintiff’s formal-preamble point also does not carry the burden. Yes, the formal transcript begins before the mechanical ball selection, and Infantino says at 00:00:50 that “we are now going to do the draw.” But that supports the defense distinction. A host’s preamble inside the formal drawing transcript is part of the program. A separate press exchange, separately titled and sourced as prior to the Draw, is not made part of the program simply because it happened nearby and discussed the same event.\n\nNor does official publication settle the issue. PX-5 strengthens provenance: Trump did say Ronaldo in an official public transcript. But provenance answers whether the words were said, not whether they were said during the market’s specified event. The terms require both: the word by the entity, and the word during the time period. Plaintiff has the first element. The second is still missing.\n\nThe remaining bridge plaintiff proposes is essentially: public, official, event-linked, and not expressly excluded. That is not enough under a preponderance standard when the same record supplies a cleaner boundary: the Ronaldo source is prior to the Draw, and the formal Draw source omits the strike. The challenged No resolution should stand.\n\nClosings:\n[plaintiff] Council members, the record has narrowed to one real issue.\n\nThe word is proven. The market page identifies the strike as “Ronaldo” and the challenged resolution as No. The case-packet transcript and the GovInfo/OFR excerpt prove that Trump said “Ronaldo” as a standalone word in public remarks at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center, in a World Cup Draw setting, with FIFA President Infantino present, and amid repeated discussion of the Draw, the Kennedy Center, ticket sales, the audience, and the imminent event. That is strong provenance: GovInfo, NARA/OFR, DCPD202501162, matching the packet source and note.\n\nDefendant has also proved its best fact. The Roll Call/Factba.se formal-program extraction does not contain “Ronaldo” or “Messi.” Plaintiff does not ask you to find otherwise. If the market had said “only the formal drawing transcript,” defendant would win. But that is not the market traders saw.\n\nThe market asked: “What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?” It did not say “during the formal transcript only,” “after the host announces the draw has begun,” “excluding public press remarks at the venue,” or “excluding remarks immediately before the program.” The governing terms do not add that limitation. They define words used by the entity during the time period, allow event/context time periods, and exclude categories such as rehearsals, sound checks, behind-the-scenes content, and unofficial recordings. Plaintiff’s source is none of those. It is an official public presidential transcript of event-linked remarks at the venue.\n\nDefendant’s formal extraction shows why a bright line cannot simply be assumed. Even on that page, before balls are drawn, there is ceremony, introduction, and Infantino saying “we are now going to do the draw.” Event boundaries are not self-defining. The question is whether Kalshi clearly chose defendant’s narrower boundary. The record contains no such choice.\n\nSo the burden is met. More likely than not, a reasonable reading of the market and terms includes Trump’s official, public, venue-based remarks immediately tied to the World Cup Draw. The strongest contrary evidence proves only that a narrower formal transcript omits the strike. It does not prove the contract excluded the remarks where the strike was actually said.\n\nThe challenged No resolution should be overturned. The strike “Ronaldo” should resolve Yes.\n\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff’s closing concedes the decisive factual split: the formal World Cup Drawing transcript contains no “Ronaldo” or “Messi.” The only Ronaldo evidence is the separate official transcript titled “Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw.”\n\nThat is enough to decide the case. The market did not ask what Trump would say at the Kennedy Center, on World Cup Draw day, in public presidential remarks, or in event-linked press availability. It asked what Trump would say “during the FIFA World Cup Draw.” The terms require the word to be used by the entity during the specified time period. Plaintiff has proven the word and the speaker. It has not proven the time period.\n\nPlaintiff’s strongest point is that the market did not expressly say “formal transcript only” or “exclude pre-program remarks.” But plaintiff has the burden. A challenged No resolution does not become Yes merely because the contract could have been even more verbose. The record must make it more likely than not that the pre-event reporter exchange was inside the market period. The record does the opposite.\n\nThe source labels matter. PX-2 and PX-5 are official and probative, but they are official proof of remarks prior to the Draw. The formal Roll Call/Factba.se extraction is the source for Trump’s formal attendance at the FIFA World Cup Drawing; it begins the program, includes the draw presentation, and omits the strike. Plaintiff’s theory asks you to treat a separate prior reporter exchange as “during” the Draw even though the formal Draw source exists and does not contain the word.\n\nThe terms do not collapse that distinction. They recognize event/context time periods and official presentation content, but they still require the word to occur during the chosen time period. Official publication proves provenance. Event connection proves relevance. Neither proves inclusion. A public official transcript can be accurately preserved and still be outside the market window if it is, as titled, prior to the event.\n\nSo the fair synthesis is narrow and grounded: Trump said Ronaldo in event-linked public remarks before the FIFA World Cup Draw; Trump did not say Ronaldo in the formal drawing transcript preserved in this record; and no admitted market term or source-chain evidence bridges the pre-event exchange into the market’s “during the FIFA World Cup Draw” period.\n\nUnder the preponderance standard, plaintiff has not carried the proposition. The challenged No resolution should stand.\n\nExhibits:\n[plaintiff] PX-1 Market page and challenged resolution\nMarket URL: https://kalshi.com/markets/kxtrumpmentionb/trump-mention-b/kxtrumpmentionb-25dec06\n\nPublic market title: What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\n\nContract family: PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION\n\nStrike at issue: Ronaldo\n\nChallenged resolution: No\n\nRequested resolution: Yes\n\n\n[plaintiff] PX-2 Pre-event reporter exchange transcript\nRemarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\nDecember 05, 2025\n\n[The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\nThe President. It's a great honor to be here. Gianni has done a fantastic job. We're setting records—[inaudible].\nQ. [Inaudible]\nThe President. Well, I think so. They have a little bit of a shot. Pretty stiff competition. But I would say they would have a small chance.\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize\nQ. [Inaudible]—win the FIFA Peace Award?\nThe President. Well, it would be an honor.\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\nQ. Will you root for some selection? Will you root for someone?\nThe President. Well, I root for a lot of countries, but in this case, I'll be rooting for the U.S.A. [Laughter]\nQ. [Inaudible]\nThe President. That's great. That's great. We really love it.\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize\nQ. Mr. President, have you been told that you are going to receive the inaugural peace prize today——\nThe President. I have not——\nQ. ——from FIFA?\nThe President. I have not been told. There's a rumor about it, but I have not been told. That would be a great honor, and I'm a big fan of Gianni, as you know.\nQ. What can fans expect——\nQ. Are you hoping to receive that?\nThe President. Excuse me.\nQ. Are you hoping to receive the peace prize?\nThe President. Well, I don't like to say \"hope,\" but it would be a great honor.\n2026 World Cup\nQ. What can fans expect of, like, the World Cup in the U.S.?\nThe President. I think it's going to be fantastic. We've set every record you can set.\nQ. What are you telling people who are worried——\nFédération Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) President Giovanni V. Infantino\nQ. [Inaudible]—friend Gianni—[inaudible]—a word about him?\nThe President. I think he has done a fantastic job.\nThe President's Schedule\nQ. Are you going to be meeting with the President of Mexico today and the——\nThe President. We might. Yes.\nQ. ——Prime Minister of Canada as well?\nThe President. I might. I might do that.\nQ. Will you be discussing immigration and trade with them?\nThe President. Yes, we'll be discussing.\n[At this point, the President and Mr. Infantino posed for photographs.]\nThe President. Thank you, everybody.\n2026 World Cup Draw Event/John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts\nQ. Mr. President, what do you think about the crowd?\nThe President. Oh, look, the new star—[inaudible].\nCongratulations.\nQ. Thank you.\nThe President. You're the new star of television and Fox.\nQ. Thank you. How are you doing, Mr. President?\nThe President. I'm doing very well.\nQ. What do you think about the crowd here?\nThe President. I think the crowd is great, and I think the building is great. We've made a lot of improvements over the last 6 months. Taking—the Kennedy Center was in very bad shape. Now it's getting to be really good. And in 6 months, it's going to be incredible with the improvements we've made.\nQ. The first time for the U.S. to host since the nineties.\nThe President. Right.\nQ. Are you ready for it?\nThe President. I'm ready for it, and they're ready for it. And Gianni, who you know——\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\nThe President. ——has done a fantastic job with FIFA. And we're looking to have—you know, we're set—we have already set records for tickets sales. I don't think there's ever been anything like it in any sport. And so, I want to congratulate you.\nMr. Infantino. Thank you.\nThe President. I don't even have to wait. But major records have been set.\nHow are you?\nQ. Good, how are you, sir?\nThe President. Nice to see you.\nQ. Today it's not football—American football. It's soccer. It's——\nThe President. Right.\nQ. ——the big event of soccer.\nThe President. That's right. That's right.\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\nQ. So can you tell me about this big day today?\nThe President. It's just a big day, and it's a great sport. And it really is coming to America. And never—nobody ever thought a thing like this could happen. And I'm very happy to say that we've already set the alltime record on ticket sales long before the first ball is kicked. Right?\nMr. Infantino. A hundred percent. One hundred percent.\n2026 World Cup Host Cities\nQ. You've had some concerns about crime in American cities, some of the cities that will be hosting. Have they remedied that for you? Are you still considering maybe asking FIFA to move some of those cities?\nThe President. No, I don't want to do that. But I will tell you, if they do have a problem, by the time we get there, we'll take care of that problem. We can solve that problem.\nI've proven that in DC and everywhere else we went, so we'll take care of that very easily. So, if they have a problem, hopefully, they'll let us know that, and we will solve any problem.\nOkay? Thank you.\nQ. Thank you so much.\nMr. Infantino. All right, thank you so much.\nQ. Thank you, Mr. President.\nQ. Thank you. Appreciate it.\nThe President. Congratulations.\n2026 World Cup\nQ. Mr. President, Brazilian television. America will be hosting the World Cup and the Olympics in 2 years. How important it is—[inaudible]?\nThe President. I think very. It's a great honor. I think Gianni is doing a phenomenal job. We've set every record on ticket sales. It's been really fantastic. But Gianni has done an unbelievable job with FIFA.\nThe President's Experience With Soccer\nQ. [Inaudible]\nThe President. He was a great—not only that. I got to see a man name Pelé play—right?—that tells you how old I am—when he was on the Cosmos. Do you remember that a long time ago? And it was quite a treat. That was quite an event. And he was—not only was he playing, he was great. He scored two goals, I think. And so, I was one of the few who got to see Pelé, and I assume he is one of your alltime greats. Right?\nMr. Infantino. Definitely.\nThe President. So I got to see him.\nThe President's Favorite World Cup Competitor\nQ. Do you have some favorite teams for World Cup?\nThe President. Well, I have a favorite. It's the U.S.A. [Laughter] I don't know what their chances are, Gianni, but maybe the U.S.A. is the——\nMr. Infantino. They're getting better and better, actually.\nThe President. I think they'll do well.\nMr. Infantino. They are getting better and better.\nThe President. I think they'll do well.\nThank you very much, everybody.\nQ. Thank you so much.\n2026 World Cup\nQ. Mr. President, World Cup in America just means—[inaudible]. So what do you expect from this World Cup?\nThe President. [Inaudible]—record business and only in the United States, but we're also doing record ticket sales with FIFA. And they've already bought—beat their highest record. And we—you know, this a long time before the first ball is kicked. You've sold more tickets than they've ever done before, and better pricing than they've ever gotten before. It's a tremendous success. And it's an honor. And Gianni has done a phenomenal job with FIFA.\nQ. [Inaudible]—ever?\nThe President. I think so. I think it's going to be—I mean, ideally, you want to see that every year. Every 4 years, it gets bigger and better. I think we have set every record in the book. We're very happy about it.\nThank you.\nThe President's Favorite World Cup Competitor\nQ. [Inaudible]—part of America. Who are you going to support as well?\nThe President. Well, I think I have to support U.S.A. Otherwise, I'd be in trouble. I wouldn't be President for long.\nMr. Infantino. [Inaudible]\nThe President. [Inaudible]—but you have a lot of great teams. You're going to have a lot of great teams.\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\"football,\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\n2026 World Cup Draw/Ticket Sales for World Cup\nQ. How does it feel to be part of this amazing event? And obviously, your being a part of participating in all the—[inaudible]?\nThe President. The President of Mexico is here, and she's doing a very good job. She's a good woman, very, very excellent job. It's an honor, and we're setting every record, and you're helping us set those records.\nMr. Infantino. And we will do it.\nThe President. You know, Mexico and Canada are helping us set those records. But as you know, we have a record in ticket sales already, long before the first ball is kicked, and we're going to do great.\nI think that Gianni—as you know, he's the head, and he has done a fantastic job.\nU.S. Cooperation With Mexico and Canada\nQ. And how is the biggest challenge being three countries?\nThe President. Well, I think that—do you mean for the three countries?\nWell, they've gotten together really well, I mean.\nMr. Infantino. All right.\nThe President. They're getting along very well.\nMr. Infantino. Collaboration is fantastic between the three.\nThe President's Interest in Soccer/2026 World Cup\nQ. And you like soccer?\nThe President. I do. I like it. I like it more and more.\nQ. Yes?\nThe President. I like it. It's growing in this country—very, really—I mean, someday, maybe it's going to be bigger than anything else.\nMr. Infantino. We'll have to become number one.\nThe President. I will say this——\nMr. Infantino. Definitely.\nThe President. ——the ticket sales——\nQ. Definitely will happen.\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\nThe President. Ticket sales are bigger than anything we have ever done in the history of the country, in terms of sports.\nMr. Infantino. For certain.\nQ. And the audience is going to be huge.\nThe President. The audience is going to be tremendous.\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\nThe President. Yes.\nMr. Infantino. Six billion people.\nThe President. [Inaudible]\nQ. Six billion? That's amazing.\nMr. Infantino. Six billion people.\nAnd today, one billion.\nQ. Wow.\nMr. Infantino. [Inaudible]\nQ. Enjoy show time. Thank you so much.\nThe President. [Inaudible]\nQ. Mr. President, how are you? Just a quick—[inaudible].\nQ. This is for Telemundo.\nThe President. How are you?\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\nQ. Hello, Mr. President. How are you? This for Telemundo.\nThe President. How are you? Good.\nQ. How are you?\nThe President. Very good. Thank you.\nQ. How does it feel to have the most important event of sports—that global—in the U.S.?\nThe President. Well, we do. And right at the Kennedy Center. I'm Chairman of the Kennedy Center. And I hear the Kennedy Center is doing a very good job, so it feels great. Really good.\nAnd Telemundo is doing a good job, too. Thank you.\nQ. Thank you.\n2026 World Cup\nQ. What is the significance of hosting the FIFA World Cup this year?\nThe President. It's a—in terms of sports, I would say the ultimate. There is no sport like this. It's the biggest sport in the world. And we are setting every record. You know, our ticket sales have gone and set every—every sport—no matter what it is, we've set the record. So—and every though it's very early, there's no ball being kicked yet, but we've already set a ticket sales record.\nArgentina National Team\nQ. How do you see Argentinean team for this World Cup?\nThe President. Well, I love Argentina. And your President is doing a very good job, as you know. Milei. You know that right? It's make Argentina great again. MAGA.\nQ. And——\nU.S. National Team\nQ. Do you think the States are building a powerful team for next year?\nThe President. Who?\nQ. The States.\nThe President. Oh, yes. Sure. I—you're going to have a lot of powerful teams. Everybody has a lot of powerful teams, but you're going to have a lot of great teams. [Inaudible]\nU.S. Role in Hosting the 2026 World Cup\nQ. Mr. President, what does it mean for you guys to host the World Cup right here in the U.S.?\nThe President. I'm honored to host it. It's a great honor. I mean, it's turned out to be bigger than we thought. We're setting a record for ticket sales, the likes of which no sport has ever seen before.\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\nThe President. But they have a little more speed.\nBut no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\nPopularity of Soccer in Latin America\nQ. Mr. President, a message for the Latin America and soccer fans?\nThe President. Yes, I am. And Latin America is great. And they have great soccer. So, good luck in the matches.\n[A reporter asked a question in Spanish, which was translated by an interpreter as follows.]\nU.S. Visas for World Cup Ticketholders\nQ. Who is going to be in—[inaudible]—about these visas for the—these fans that want to come here to the World Cup?\nThe President. Well, we're going to make it very easy for them. We're working on that right now. We're going to make it very easy. It's going to be a very easy process.\nQ. Okay. Say, hi to Colombia over there.\nThe President. Hello. Is that Colombia?\nQ. Yes.\nThe President. I love Colombia. Hello, Colombia. [Laughter]\nQ. Okay. Okay. Muy bien.\nThe President. So where are you from?\nQ. Paraguay.\nThe President. Oh.\nQ. He's from Paraguay. Yes.\nThe President. Very good. I love it. I—it's a beautiful country. We get along very well with them. We do a little trade deal with them, and they like us. And that's what's happening.\nQ. Panama.\nThe President. Where?\nVery good. I like the canal. [Laughter] That canal is pretty good.\n[A reporter spoke in Spanish; no translation was provided.]\n2026 World Cup\nThe President. What?\nQ. [Inaudible]\nThe President. Well, it's going to be incredible. The event is going to be very good. Just this event alone—it's at the Kennedy Center. I see you have it fixed up perfectly.\nMr. Infantino. It will set the tone.\nThe President. Right? It's beautiful.\nMr. Infantino. It's beautiful.\nThe President. It's a beautiful place.\nHave a good time.\nQ. [Inaudible]\nThe President.\n[A reporter spoke in Spanish; no translation was provided.]\nMr. Infantino. No, gracias. [Inaudible]\nThe President. It's great.\nJohn F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts/Renovation Work\nQ. Mr. President, the U.S. press?\nThe President. Thank you, everybody, very much. It's a great honor. This has been an honor for a lot of reasons. Number one, they've sold more tickets than any event has ever sold already—long before the kickoff.\nAnd number two, we've done a lot of work at the Kennedy Center. It was falling apart, and now it's pretty much back. And we'll get it back within the next 4 or 5 months through construction, and—but you see the way it looks.\nAnd Gianni is just telling me—who's done an incredible job, by the way. He's just telling, you know, how good a job we've done.\nMr. Infantino. That's right.\nThe President. You can look at the walls. The marble was broken. Everything was a mess. And we've really taken the Kennedy Center—a lot of people thought it was going to be ripped down, and we did just the opposite. So we've done a really great renovation job on it. And over the next 3, 4 months, it will be complete. And we're honored to have it here, and it's been—it's been very special.\nWe've set a record on ticket sales, as you probably heard, already, even way before—long before the event itself. And we're working with Canada, and we're working with Mexico. And it's been a really spectacular—so far, it's been spectacular.\nDaniel [Daniel Baldwin, One America News Network], do you have a question?\n2026 World Cup\nQ. What are your expectations? You once said that the FIFA World Cup is an opportunity to put—a once-in-a-lifetime opportunity to put the greatness of the United States on display.\nThe President. Well, I think—\nQ. One billion eyeballs will be watching, Mr. President.\nThe President. Yes, I—think——\nQ. What will they here today?\nThe President. Even today, I understand. I hear that, you know——\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\nThe President. ——I know we're a little late to get in there, but——\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\nThe President. ——that's okay.\nMr. Infantino. They wait.\nThe President. So all my friends, I guess they have to wait. They have no choice, right? [Laughter]\nMr. Infantino. Yes, they wait.\nThe President. But no, the numbers are incredible. I hear today's numbers are——\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\nThe President. ——very big. I hope CNN is covering this.\nQ. One billion eyeballs.\nMr. Infantino. Today, 1 billion eyeballs.\nThe President. Today's numbers are very, very big.\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize/The President's Foreign Policy\nQ. We are covering it. And you're expected to get the FIFA Peace Prize, Mr. President. What would you say to people who say that prize might conflict with your pledge to strike Venezuela?\nThe President. Well, I think the peace prize—I mean, I settled eight wars. I don't know that I'm getting it. I haven't been officially noticed. I've been hearing about a peace prize, and I'm here to represent our country in a different sense. But I can tell you, I did settle eight wars, and we have a ninth coming, but—which nobody has ever done before.\nBut I want to really save lives. I don't need prizes. I need to save lives. And we're saving a lot of lives. And I've saved millions and millions of lives, and that's really what I want to do.\nAnd I also want to run a great country. And the United States right now is the hottest country anywhere in the world. And 1 year ago, it was dead. We had a dead country, and now we have the hottest country anywhere in the world.\nQ. Mr. President, will you——\nThe President's Meeting With President Claudia Sheinbaum Pardo of Mexico and Prime Minister Mark Carney of Canada\nQ. What are you going to discuss with Canada and Mexico, Mr.—what are you going to discuss with the leaders of Canada and Mexico?\nThe President. Well, we're getting—we're going to meet with both. And we're getting along very well. You know, we're getting along very well. I don't know. I think we have a meeting set up for some time after the event.\nQ. Will you discuss trade?\nThe President. Yes, we'll discuss trade. We—get along very well.\nThank you, everybody, very much.\nQ. Will you pardon any other Honduran officials?\nQ. Do you want them to keep trying to indict Ms. James?\n\nNOTE: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. In his remarks, he referred to Trey Yingst, chief foreign correspondent, Fox News Channel; Cristiano Ronaldo, forward for Saudi Pro League club Al-Nass and Portugal's national soccer team; and Lionel Messi, forward for Major League Soccer club Inter Miami and Argentina's national team. A reporter referred to New York State Attorney General Letitia James. The transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\n\nSource URL: https://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/documents/remarks-exchange-with-reporters-prior-the-2026-federation-internationale-des-associations\n\n\n[plaintiff] PX-3 PRESMENTION/NEWMENTION terms\n                                         NEWMENTION\n\nScope: These rules shall apply to this contract.\n\nUnderlying: The Underlying for this Contract is words used by <entity> <time period>.\nRevisions to the Underlying made after Expiration will not be accounted for in determining the\nExpiration Value.\n\nSource Agency: The Source Agencies are <source>.\n\nType: The type of Contract is an Event Contract.\n\nIssuance: After the initial Contract, Contract iterations will be listed on an as-needed basis at\nthe discretion of the Exchange and corresponding to the risk management needs of Members.\n\n<entity>: <entity> refers to the speaker, writer, performer, or communicator specified by the\nExchange. This may include (but is not limited to): a specific named individual, multiple\nindividuals specified using AND/OR logic, an individual identified by position or title, a group,\nband, team or collective entity, a specified member or members of a group, an organization,\ncompany, or institutional entity, or any combination of the aforementioned.\n\nWhen <entity> is defined by a position or title, the Contract tracks whoever holds that position\nduring <time period>, even if the individual holding the position changes. When <entity> is a\nspecific named individual, the identity remains consistent throughout. Name changes (e.g.,\nstage names, married names) do not create a new entity. When <entity> is a group or\norganization and the Contract does not specify particular members, any official\ncommunication or statement by any member or designated spokesperson counts. When using\nAND logic, all specified entities must independently say <word> during <time period>. When\nusing OR logic, at least one of the specified entities must say <word> during <time period>.\nThe Exchange may specify additional conditions such as “at least X members of” a group or\n“the majority of” a group.\n\n<source>: <source> refers to a Source Agency or ordered collection of Source Agencies\nspecified by the Exchange at the time of Contract listing, which will be incorporated into the\nSource Agency hierarchy above and used to determine the occurrence of the Underlying.\n<source> may refer to a singular agency, multiple agencies, an agency by distinguishing\ncharacteristics, by category or type (e.g., “official government statistical body,” “primary wire\nservice”), or any combination thereof. When multiple agencies are specified, they may be\napplied in the hierarchical order designated by the Exchange if so specified, with the highest-\nranked available and responsive agency taking precedence for purposes of determining the\nExpiration Value. A lower-ranked agency shall only be consulted if all higher-ranked agencies\nare unavailable, unresponsive, have not reported on the Underlying by the Expiration time, or\nif the Exchange, in its sole discretion, determines that a higher-ranked agency’s reporting is\nincomplete, erroneous, or otherwise insufficient to determine the Expiration Value. If <source>\ndesignates multiple agencies without specifying a hierarchical order, the Exchange shall\nresolve any conflict between reporting agencies at its sole discretion.\n\n<word>: <word> refers to the particular word or phrase potentially to be mentioned by\n<entity>. It may refer to a word being said a minimum number of times. It may also refer to\none of multiple words/phrases, any of which are acceptable (e.g., “Doge/Dogecoin”).\n\f<time period>: <time period> refers to a specific range of time, event or discrete date and\ntime specified by the Exchange. This may be defined by, but is not limited to: a specific event\nor context (e.g., “during the State of the Union address”), exact dates or times, relative time\nmarkers (e.g., “before July 1, 2027,” “in Q1 2026”), event-based periods (e.g., “during any\ncampaign rally in October 2026,” “during the awards ceremony”), and broader intervals (e.g.,\n“Q1–Q2 2027,” “January–March 2026”).\n\nUnless stated otherwise, “Between” is inclusive of both endpoints, while “before” and “after”\nexclude the specified date. <time period> may also refer to “Any” or “None”, to multiple dates\n(even if non-consecutive), or to a singular and discrete date or time.\n\nWhen <time period> refers to a specific event (such as an address, speech, performance, or\nbroadcast), the Exchange may specify what is included, including whether it includes both live\nand pre-recorded segments (including whether advertisements are included). Where a\ntimezone is not specified, ET is assumed.\n\n\nPayout Criterion: The Payout Criterion for the Contract encompasses the Expiration Values that\n<word> is said by <entity> <time period>.\n\n\nThe word must appear as a distinct, standalone unit, not buried inside another word. Plural\nand possessive noun forms count. Other grammatical changes (tense, conjugation, derivation)\ndo not. If <word> appears separated from other words by a space or hyphen or in a\ncompound form with a space or hyphen, it counts. If <word> is fused into a single\nunhyphenated word, it does not count.\n\nIf <time period> refers to an event and that event is cancelled, and the market contains a\nstrike stating “Event does not qualify/occur”, such a strike shall resolve “Yes” and all others\n“No”. If <time period> refers to an event and that event is cancelled but such strikes are NOT\nlisted, the Contracts will resolve to the last fair price determined at the discretion of the\nExchange. If the event is postponed, and such a postponement is announced by the end of the\nfollowing calendar day to be rescheduled to a time within 14 calendar days, the markets shall\nremain open. If the event captured in <time period> is a live-stream or broadcast, the\nExchange may keep the market open for 24 hours for the release of an official recording.\nFurther granular details on conditions for these Contracts is available below.\n\nAdditional clarification(s):\n\n     Possessive noun forms of <word>, plurals, and possessive plural noun forms are\n     INCLUDED:\n          <word> is “Immigrant” → “Immigrants” counts\n          <word> is “Egg” → “eggs’ shells” counts\n          <word> is “Russia” → “Russia’s” counts, “Russian” does not\n     If <word> exists only in adjective form, no plural form exists:\n          <word> is “Economic” → “Economics” does not count (“Economic” is an adjective\n          for which “Economics” is not a plural)\n     Plural nouns occurring within proper nouns and noun phrases are included:\n          <word> is “Cat” → “Cats the musical” counts\n\f    Grammatical variations beyond plurals/possessives are NOT included:\n         <word> is “Immigrant” → “Immigration” does NOT count\n         <word> is “Run” → “Running” or “Ran” do NOT count\n    When <word> specifies a plural form, the singular does NOT count:\n         <word> is “Veterans” → “Veteran” does NOT count\n    Words that are spelled the same as the plural form of <word> (if such exists) but are\n    themselves not a plural noun are included:\n         <word> is “Wind” → “Winds up the clock” counts\n         <word> is “Border” → “The United States has strong borders” counts\n    Open compounds (words separated by spaces) count:\n         <word> is “fire” → “fire station” counts\n         <word> is “couch” → “couch potato” counts\n    Hyphenated compounds (words connected by hyphens) count:\n         <word> is “Palestine” → “pro-Palestine” counts\n         <word> is “fat” → “non-fat” counts\n    Closed compounds (single word, no spaces/hyphens) do not count:\n         <word> is “fire” → “wildfire” does not count\n         <word> is “fire” → “firefighter” does not count\n    Multi-word <word> in larger constructions: When <word> is a multi-word phrase\n    appearing within a hyphenated construction, it counts only if <word> appears as a\n    complete, unmodified element:\n         <word> is “New York” → “New York-based” counts (complete element)\n    Portmanteaus (words blended from two words where parts of each are combined) are\n    NOT included unless the portmanteau clearly contains <word> as a distinct, unaltered\n    element:\n         <word> is “MAGA” → “MAGA-nificent” counts (MAGA appears as distinct element)\n         <word> is “magnificent” → “MAGA-nificent” does NOT count (portmanteau blend)\n\nDictionary determination: Both the Merriam-Webster Dictionary (available online) AND the\nOxford English Dictionary shall be used to determine compound type and/or conventional\nspelling patterns. Inclusion in either dictionary as an open or hyphenated compound shall\nsatisfy the Payout Criterion. If neither provides clarity (or the word is not included),\ndetermination is based on whether written as single unit (closed/doesn’t count) vs. spaces or\nhyphens (open or hyphenated/counts) and/or context and previous usage.\n\nPHONETIC EQUIVALENCIES\n\n    Homophones (same sound, different spelling) do not count:\n        <word> is “write” → “right” does not count\n    Homonyms and homographs (same spelling) COUNT regardless of meaning or\n    pronunciation:\n        <word> is “bass” → both “bass guitar” and “bass fishing” count\n    Proper and common nouns are treated identically:\n        <word> is “Apple” → both “Apple Inc.” and “apple” (fruit) count\n        <word> is “Will” → both “Will Smith” and “I will go” count\n    Minor unintentional mispronunciations COUNT if context makes intent clear:\n        <word> is “Mamdani” → “Mandani” counts\n    Severe mispronunciations that make <word> unrecognizable do NOT count.\n    Trademarked spellings do not count, even when pronounced identically, unless the word\n\fitself is the same:\n      <word> is “lift” → “Lyft” (pronounced “lift”) does not count\n      <word> is “uber” → “Uber” counts\nWords with non-standard transliteration to English count within reason, provided they are\nphonetically equivalent:\n      <word> is “Zelensky” → any of “Zelenski,” “Zelenskii,” “Zelensky,” or “Zelenskiy”\n      count if pronounced equivalently\nContractions do not count for their constituent words unless otherwise explicitly specified\nby the Exchange:\n      <word> is “not” → “won’t,” “can’t,” “don’t,” “isn’t” do not count\nNumbers spoken as words COUNT, when spoken exactly (not part of a larger number):\n      <word> is “five” → saying “five” or reading “$5” aloud as “five dollars” counts,\n      saying “five hundred” does NOT count\n      <word> is “410” → “four hundred ten”, “four one zero” or “four ten” counts\nOrdinals COUNT when <word> is written numerically OR a phrase that includes a\nnumber:\n      <word> is “January 6” → “January 6th” counts\n      <word> is “3” (written numerically) → “3rd” (spoken as “third”) counts\n      <word> is “Eight War” → “8 Wars” and “Eighth War” will count\nCardinal and ordinal number words are distinct:\n      <word> is “one” → “first” does NOT count\n      <word> is “first” → “one” does NOT count\nAcronyms and abbreviations count when pronunciation or letter-by-letter spelling\nmatches <word>:\n      <word> is “NASA” → “NASA” (pronounced “NAH-suh”) counts\n      <word> is “NASA” → “N-A-S-A” (spelled out) counts\nAcronyms and abbreviations count as <word> when pronounced as the full word:\n      <word> is “Doctor” → “Dr.” (pronounced “Doctor”) counts\nExpanded forms of acronyms do NOT count:\n      <word> is “AI” → “artificial intelligence” does not count\nWords in foreign languages do NOT count unless they are perfect cognates with an\nEnglish word:\n      <word> is “fire” → “fuego” (Spanish) does NOT count\nEnglish words within foreign sentences count:\n      <word> is “policy” → “Nuestra policy es clara” counts\n<word> in organization/company names counts:\n      <word> is “Securities” → “Bank of America Securities” counts\nWords in URLs, emails, handles, and hashtags (exclusive of domain structure, email\nprovider or symbols) are treated as compounds when spoken as complete words, with the\ntype of compound subject to aforementioned rules:\n      <word> is “fire” → “firestation.com” pronounced “fire station dot com” counts\n      <word> is “fire” → “wildfire.com” pronounced “wildfire dot com” does NOT count\n      <word> is “apple” → “apple.com” pronounced “apple dot com” does count\n      When presented in URL, email, handle, or hashtag form, <word> shall be treated as\n      a compound, not a multi-word word\nSung, rapped, or poetic words COUNT if phonetically recognizable:\n      <word> is “money” → “moneyyy” (extended in rap) counts\n      Extreme distortion making <word> unrecognizable does NOT count.\nPhonetic alphabet spelling (“Foxtrot India Romeo Echo” for “FIRE”) does NOT count.\n\fCANCELLATIONS AND DELAYS\n\n   The Exchange may list an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike for any Contract. If listed,\n   such a strike refers to the structural conditions of the market, and is NOT adjudicated as a\n   <word> needing to be said by or validated by having been said by <entity>. If listed, this\n   strike resolves to “Yes” whenever the event fails to occur or qualify under the Payout\n   Criterion, or any other circumstance prevents normal resolution.\n   If no such strike is listed, and <time period> refers to a specific event, the following rules\n   apply if the event is cancelled, postponed, rescheduled, or materially altered (including\n   being closed to press) such that no video is released within one calendar day of the\n   original start time of the event:\n         If the event is cancelled, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price determined in\n         the sole discretion of the Exchange.\n         If the event is postponed or rescheduled, the outcome depends on whether a new\n         date is publicly announced within one calendar day (i.e. if the event was scheduled\n         to begin on Monday, any time up to 11:59PM on Tuesday falls within this period) of\n         the originally scheduled start time:\n               If no new date is announced within one calendar day, the Contract will resolve\n               to the last fair price determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\n               If a new date is announced within one calendar day, the outcome depends on\n               when the rescheduled event is set to occur:\n                     If the rescheduled date falls within fourteen (14) calendar days of the\n                     originally scheduled date, the Contract shall remain open and <word>\n                     stated during the rescheduled event will count.\n                           The fourteen-day window begins at 12:00 AM ET on the originally\n                           scheduled date and ends at 11:59 PM ET fourteen days later, unless\n                           an alternate timezone is explicitly specified.\n                           Example: <time period> is “during the State of the Union on January\n                           15, 2026” rescheduled to January 20, 2026 → words spoken during\n                           the rescheduled address count.\n                     If the rescheduled date falls more than fourteen (14) calendar days after\n                     the originally scheduled date, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price\n                     determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\n         Any Contract that cannot be resolved through the Source Agency hierarchy will\n         instead be settled at the Last Fair Price. The Exchange will disclose the methodology\n         used to determine the Last Fair Price (e.g., Last Traded Price, Time-Weighted\n         Average Price) at the time of Issuance.\n         If an event begins but is interrupted, abbreviated, or ends prematurely, words\n         stated by <entity> during the portion of the event that did occur will count and the\n         market will otherwise resolve.\n   If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window but the venue, format, or medium\n   changes (e.g., moved to a different location, changed from in-person to virtual (with the\n   exception of being closed to press)), words stated during the event will count.\n   Special condition: Across both cases, whether an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike is\n   listed or not, if the event specified as or in <time period> is a live-stream or broadcast (or\n   relayed as such) but the live stream/broadcast does not occur, the Exchange will instead\n   use an officially released recording as the Underlying, and may delay resolution by up to\n   one calendar day to allow for the release of such a recording.\n\f          If partial snippets are released, Contracts on words that do not appear will be\n          resolved to last fair price, and Contracts on those that do will be resolved to “Yes”.\n          If no recording is released, the relevant outcomes triggered by the\n          presence/absence of an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike shall occur as outlined\n          above.\n\nTECHNICAL DETAILS (UNLESS OTHERWISE SPECIFIED)\n\n     When <time period> refers to a specific event, pre-recorded content broadcast,\n     streamed, or published as part of that event is included if presented as part of the official\n     presentation.\n          Example: <time period> is “during the concert” with pre-recorded video interlude\n          where entity speaks → words from interlude count\n          Example: <time period> is “during the television appearance” with pre-taped\n          segment aired during broadcast → words from segment count\n     Behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are NOT\n     included unless officially broadcast or published as part of <time period>.\n     Subtitles and captions that display <word> on screen but are not spoken aloud by\n     <entity> do NOT count.\n     Sign language interpretation or usage by entity does NOT count as saying <word> unless\n     the Contract explicitly specifies that sign language counts.\n     Text that entity displays on screen (presentation slides, teleprompter visible to audience,\n     signatures) does NOT count unless entity reads it aloud.\n     Content generated by AI, deepfakes, or synthetic voice technology impersonating entity\n     does NOT count unless the synthetic content is officially commissioned, authorized, or\n     published by entity, OR the Contract explicitly specifies that AI-generated content counts.\n     If <word> is muted due to technical failure or censorship it shall not count unless\n     corroborating contextual evidence (including surrounding speech, or an official\n     uncensored recording or transcript) confirms that <entity> specifically uttered <word>\n     during the muted period.\n\nMinimum Tick: The Minimum Tick size for the Contract shall be $0.01.\n\nPosition Accountability Level: The Position Accountability Level for the Contract shall be\n$25,000 per strike, per Member.\n\nLast Trading Date: The Last Trading Date of the Contract will be the Expiration Date. The Last\nTrading Time will be the Expiration time.\n\nSettlement Date: The Settlement Date of the Contract shall be no later than the day after the\nExpiration Date, unless the Market Outcome is under review pursuant to Rule 7.1.\n\nExpiration Date: When <time period> refers to a specific event: The latest Expiration Date of\nthe Contract shall be fourteen (14) calendar days after the originally scheduled date of the\nevent. If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window, expiration will be moved to an\nearlier date and time in accordance with Rule 7.2. When <time period> is defined by specific\ndates: The latest Expiration Date of the Contract shall be two weeks after the end of <time\nperiod>. If an event described in the Payout Criterion occurs and a consensus has been\nreached on all terms, then expiration will be moved to an earlier date and time in accordance\nwith Rule 7.2.\n\fExpiration time: The Expiration time of the Contract shall be 10:00 AM ET.\n\nSettlement Value: The Settlement Value for this Contract is $1.00.\n\nExpiration Value: The Expiration Value is the value of the Underlying as documented by the\nSource Agency on the Expiration Date at the Expiration time.\n\nContingencies: Before Settlement, Kalshi may, at its sole discretion, initiate the Market\nOutcome Review Process pursuant to Rule 7.1 of the Rulebook. If an Expiration Value cannot\nbe determined on the Expiration Date, Kalshi has the right to determine payouts pursuant to\nRule 7.1 in the Rulebook.\n\f\n\n[plaintiff] PX-4 Formal draw archive note\nSource checked: Roll Call / Factba.se archive\n\nArchive title: Remarks: Donald Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing in Washington - December 5, 2025\n\nArchive URL: https://rollcall.com/factbase/trump/transcript/donald-trump-remarks-fifa-world-cup-drawing-december-5-2025/\n\nWhat this file establishes:\n\nThere is a separate archived transcript page for Trump's formal attendance remarks at the draw.\n\nWhat this file does not establish:\n\nThis session could not retrieve the full transcript text from that archive.  The page is password-protected.  This example therefore does not claim, from local files alone, whether the formal program transcript does or does not contain the word \"Ronaldo.\"\n\nWhy this matters:\n\nThe complaint does not need to prove that the formal program omitted the strike.  It needs to show that Trump said \"Ronaldo\" in event-linked remarks and that the market boundary reasonably includes those remarks.  The formal archive remains relevant because it marks the distinction between the pre-event reporter exchange and the formal program.\n\n\n[plaintiff] PX-5 GovInfo official transcript excerpt and metadata\nSource: GovInfo, DCPD202501162, Office of the Federal Register / National Archives and Records Administration.\nURL: https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/DCPD-202501162/html/DCPD-202501162.htm\nTitle: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\nEvent date: December 5, 2025.\n\nRelevant extracted page text:\n\"Administration of Donald J. Trump, 2025\"\n\"Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw December 5, 2025\"\n\"[The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\"\n\nUnder the section \"The President's Interest in Soccer\":\n\"Q. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\"\n\"The President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\\\"football,\\\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\"\n\"Thank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\"\n\nAdditional relevant extracted page text:\n\"The President's Interest in Soccer\"\n\"Q. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\"\n\"The President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\"\n\"Mr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\"\n\"The President. But they have a little more speed. But no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\"\n\nGovInfo note:\n\"NOTE: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. In his remarks, he referred to Trey Yingst, chief foreign correspondent, Fox News Channel; Cristiano Ronaldo, forward for Saudi Pro League club Al-Nass and Portugal's national soccer team; and Lionel Messi, forward for Major League Soccer club Inter Miami and Argentina's national team. A reporter referred to New York State Attorney General Letitia James. The transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\"\n\nGovInfo content details page also identifies category \"Interviews With the News Media : Exchanges with reporters, Washington, DC,\" subjects including \"Federation Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) World Cup,\" \"John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts,\" and \"Soccer,\" and names including \"Ronaldo, Cristiano\" and \"Messi, Lionel.\"\n\n[defendant] DX-1 Market wording and challenged resolution\nMarket URL: https://kalshi.com/markets/kxtrumpmentionb/trump-mention-b/kxtrumpmentionb-25dec06\n\nPublic market title: What will Trump say during the FIFA World Cup Draw?\n\nContract family: PRESMENTION / NEWMENTION\n\nStrike at issue: Ronaldo\n\nChallenged resolution: No\n\nRequested resolution: Yes\n\n\n[defendant] DX-2 Pre-event reporter exchange transcript\nRemarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\nDecember 05, 2025\n\n[The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\nThe President. It's a great honor to be here. Gianni has done a fantastic job. We're setting records—[inaudible].\nQ. [Inaudible]\nThe President. Well, I think so. They have a little bit of a shot. Pretty stiff competition. But I would say they would have a small chance.\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize\nQ. [Inaudible]—win the FIFA Peace Award?\nThe President. Well, it would be an honor.\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\nQ. Will you root for some selection? Will you root for someone?\nThe President. Well, I root for a lot of countries, but in this case, I'll be rooting for the U.S.A. [Laughter]\nQ. [Inaudible]\nThe President. That's great. That's great. We really love it.\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize\nQ. Mr. President, have you been told that you are going to receive the inaugural peace prize today——\nThe President. I have not——\nQ. ——from FIFA?\nThe President. I have not been told. There's a rumor about it, but I have not been told. That would be a great honor, and I'm a big fan of Gianni, as you know.\nQ. What can fans expect——\nQ. Are you hoping to receive that?\nThe President. Excuse me.\nQ. Are you hoping to receive the peace prize?\nThe President. Well, I don't like to say \"hope,\" but it would be a great honor.\n2026 World Cup\nQ. What can fans expect of, like, the World Cup in the U.S.?\nThe President. I think it's going to be fantastic. We've set every record you can set.\nQ. What are you telling people who are worried——\nFédération Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) President Giovanni V. Infantino\nQ. [Inaudible]—friend Gianni—[inaudible]—a word about him?\nThe President. I think he has done a fantastic job.\nThe President's Schedule\nQ. Are you going to be meeting with the President of Mexico today and the——\nThe President. We might. Yes.\nQ. ——Prime Minister of Canada as well?\nThe President. I might. I might do that.\nQ. Will you be discussing immigration and trade with them?\nThe President. Yes, we'll be discussing.\n[At this point, the President and Mr. Infantino posed for photographs.]\nThe President. Thank you, everybody.\n2026 World Cup Draw Event/John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts\nQ. Mr. President, what do you think about the crowd?\nThe President. Oh, look, the new star—[inaudible].\nCongratulations.\nQ. Thank you.\nThe President. You're the new star of television and Fox.\nQ. Thank you. How are you doing, Mr. President?\nThe President. I'm doing very well.\nQ. What do you think about the crowd here?\nThe President. I think the crowd is great, and I think the building is great. We've made a lot of improvements over the last 6 months. Taking—the Kennedy Center was in very bad shape. Now it's getting to be really good. And in 6 months, it's going to be incredible with the improvements we've made.\nQ. The first time for the U.S. to host since the nineties.\nThe President. Right.\nQ. Are you ready for it?\nThe President. I'm ready for it, and they're ready for it. And Gianni, who you know——\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\nThe President. ——has done a fantastic job with FIFA. And we're looking to have—you know, we're set—we have already set records for tickets sales. I don't think there's ever been anything like it in any sport. And so, I want to congratulate you.\nMr. Infantino. Thank you.\nThe President. I don't even have to wait. But major records have been set.\nHow are you?\nQ. Good, how are you, sir?\nThe President. Nice to see you.\nQ. Today it's not football—American football. It's soccer. It's——\nThe President. Right.\nQ. ——the big event of soccer.\nThe President. That's right. That's right.\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\nQ. So can you tell me about this big day today?\nThe President. It's just a big day, and it's a great sport. And it really is coming to America. And never—nobody ever thought a thing like this could happen. And I'm very happy to say that we've already set the alltime record on ticket sales long before the first ball is kicked. Right?\nMr. Infantino. A hundred percent. One hundred percent.\n2026 World Cup Host Cities\nQ. You've had some concerns about crime in American cities, some of the cities that will be hosting. Have they remedied that for you? Are you still considering maybe asking FIFA to move some of those cities?\nThe President. No, I don't want to do that. But I will tell you, if they do have a problem, by the time we get there, we'll take care of that problem. We can solve that problem.\nI've proven that in DC and everywhere else we went, so we'll take care of that very easily. So, if they have a problem, hopefully, they'll let us know that, and we will solve any problem.\nOkay? Thank you.\nQ. Thank you so much.\nMr. Infantino. All right, thank you so much.\nQ. Thank you, Mr. President.\nQ. Thank you. Appreciate it.\nThe President. Congratulations.\n2026 World Cup\nQ. Mr. President, Brazilian television. America will be hosting the World Cup and the Olympics in 2 years. How important it is—[inaudible]?\nThe President. I think very. It's a great honor. I think Gianni is doing a phenomenal job. We've set every record on ticket sales. It's been really fantastic. But Gianni has done an unbelievable job with FIFA.\nThe President's Experience With Soccer\nQ. [Inaudible]\nThe President. He was a great—not only that. I got to see a man name Pelé play—right?—that tells you how old I am—when he was on the Cosmos. Do you remember that a long time ago? And it was quite a treat. That was quite an event. And he was—not only was he playing, he was great. He scored two goals, I think. And so, I was one of the few who got to see Pelé, and I assume he is one of your alltime greats. Right?\nMr. Infantino. Definitely.\nThe President. So I got to see him.\nThe President's Favorite World Cup Competitor\nQ. Do you have some favorite teams for World Cup?\nThe President. Well, I have a favorite. It's the U.S.A. [Laughter] I don't know what their chances are, Gianni, but maybe the U.S.A. is the——\nMr. Infantino. They're getting better and better, actually.\nThe President. I think they'll do well.\nMr. Infantino. They are getting better and better.\nThe President. I think they'll do well.\nThank you very much, everybody.\nQ. Thank you so much.\n2026 World Cup\nQ. Mr. President, World Cup in America just means—[inaudible]. So what do you expect from this World Cup?\nThe President. [Inaudible]—record business and only in the United States, but we're also doing record ticket sales with FIFA. And they've already bought—beat their highest record. And we—you know, this a long time before the first ball is kicked. You've sold more tickets than they've ever done before, and better pricing than they've ever gotten before. It's a tremendous success. And it's an honor. And Gianni has done a phenomenal job with FIFA.\nQ. [Inaudible]—ever?\nThe President. I think so. I think it's going to be—I mean, ideally, you want to see that every year. Every 4 years, it gets bigger and better. I think we have set every record in the book. We're very happy about it.\nThank you.\nThe President's Favorite World Cup Competitor\nQ. [Inaudible]—part of America. Who are you going to support as well?\nThe President. Well, I think I have to support U.S.A. Otherwise, I'd be in trouble. I wouldn't be President for long.\nMr. Infantino. [Inaudible]\nThe President. [Inaudible]—but you have a lot of great teams. You're going to have a lot of great teams.\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\nQ. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\nThe President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\"football,\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\nThank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\n2026 World Cup Draw/Ticket Sales for World Cup\nQ. How does it feel to be part of this amazing event? And obviously, your being a part of participating in all the—[inaudible]?\nThe President. The President of Mexico is here, and she's doing a very good job. She's a good woman, very, very excellent job. It's an honor, and we're setting every record, and you're helping us set those records.\nMr. Infantino. And we will do it.\nThe President. You know, Mexico and Canada are helping us set those records. But as you know, we have a record in ticket sales already, long before the first ball is kicked, and we're going to do great.\nI think that Gianni—as you know, he's the head, and he has done a fantastic job.\nU.S. Cooperation With Mexico and Canada\nQ. And how is the biggest challenge being three countries?\nThe President. Well, I think that—do you mean for the three countries?\nWell, they've gotten together really well, I mean.\nMr. Infantino. All right.\nThe President. They're getting along very well.\nMr. Infantino. Collaboration is fantastic between the three.\nThe President's Interest in Soccer/2026 World Cup\nQ. And you like soccer?\nThe President. I do. I like it. I like it more and more.\nQ. Yes?\nThe President. I like it. It's growing in this country—very, really—I mean, someday, maybe it's going to be bigger than anything else.\nMr. Infantino. We'll have to become number one.\nThe President. I will say this——\nMr. Infantino. Definitely.\nThe President. ——the ticket sales——\nQ. Definitely will happen.\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\nThe President. Ticket sales are bigger than anything we have ever done in the history of the country, in terms of sports.\nMr. Infantino. For certain.\nQ. And the audience is going to be huge.\nThe President. The audience is going to be tremendous.\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\nThe President. Yes.\nMr. Infantino. Six billion people.\nThe President. [Inaudible]\nQ. Six billion? That's amazing.\nMr. Infantino. Six billion people.\nAnd today, one billion.\nQ. Wow.\nMr. Infantino. [Inaudible]\nQ. Enjoy show time. Thank you so much.\nThe President. [Inaudible]\nQ. Mr. President, how are you? Just a quick—[inaudible].\nQ. This is for Telemundo.\nThe President. How are you?\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\n2026 World Cup Draw Event\nQ. Hello, Mr. President. How are you? This for Telemundo.\nThe President. How are you? Good.\nQ. How are you?\nThe President. Very good. Thank you.\nQ. How does it feel to have the most important event of sports—that global—in the U.S.?\nThe President. Well, we do. And right at the Kennedy Center. I'm Chairman of the Kennedy Center. And I hear the Kennedy Center is doing a very good job, so it feels great. Really good.\nAnd Telemundo is doing a good job, too. Thank you.\nQ. Thank you.\n2026 World Cup\nQ. What is the significance of hosting the FIFA World Cup this year?\nThe President. It's a—in terms of sports, I would say the ultimate. There is no sport like this. It's the biggest sport in the world. And we are setting every record. You know, our ticket sales have gone and set every—every sport—no matter what it is, we've set the record. So—and every though it's very early, there's no ball being kicked yet, but we've already set a ticket sales record.\nArgentina National Team\nQ. How do you see Argentinean team for this World Cup?\nThe President. Well, I love Argentina. And your President is doing a very good job, as you know. Milei. You know that right? It's make Argentina great again. MAGA.\nQ. And——\nU.S. National Team\nQ. Do you think the States are building a powerful team for next year?\nThe President. Who?\nQ. The States.\nThe President. Oh, yes. Sure. I—you're going to have a lot of powerful teams. Everybody has a lot of powerful teams, but you're going to have a lot of great teams. [Inaudible]\nU.S. Role in Hosting the 2026 World Cup\nQ. Mr. President, what does it mean for you guys to host the World Cup right here in the U.S.?\nThe President. I'm honored to host it. It's a great honor. I mean, it's turned out to be bigger than we thought. We're setting a record for ticket sales, the likes of which no sport has ever seen before.\nThe President's Interest in Soccer\nQ. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\nThe President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\nMr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\nThe President. But they have a little more speed.\nBut no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\nPopularity of Soccer in Latin America\nQ. Mr. President, a message for the Latin America and soccer fans?\nThe President. Yes, I am. And Latin America is great. And they have great soccer. So, good luck in the matches.\n[A reporter asked a question in Spanish, which was translated by an interpreter as follows.]\nU.S. Visas for World Cup Ticketholders\nQ. Who is going to be in—[inaudible]—about these visas for the—these fans that want to come here to the World Cup?\nThe President. Well, we're going to make it very easy for them. We're working on that right now. We're going to make it very easy. It's going to be a very easy process.\nQ. Okay. Say, hi to Colombia over there.\nThe President. Hello. Is that Colombia?\nQ. Yes.\nThe President. I love Colombia. Hello, Colombia. [Laughter]\nQ. Okay. Okay. Muy bien.\nThe President. So where are you from?\nQ. Paraguay.\nThe President. Oh.\nQ. He's from Paraguay. Yes.\nThe President. Very good. I love it. I—it's a beautiful country. We get along very well with them. We do a little trade deal with them, and they like us. And that's what's happening.\nQ. Panama.\nThe President. Where?\nVery good. I like the canal. [Laughter] That canal is pretty good.\n[A reporter spoke in Spanish; no translation was provided.]\n2026 World Cup\nThe President. What?\nQ. [Inaudible]\nThe President. Well, it's going to be incredible. The event is going to be very good. Just this event alone—it's at the Kennedy Center. I see you have it fixed up perfectly.\nMr. Infantino. It will set the tone.\nThe President. Right? It's beautiful.\nMr. Infantino. It's beautiful.\nThe President. It's a beautiful place.\nHave a good time.\nQ. [Inaudible]\nThe President.\n[A reporter spoke in Spanish; no translation was provided.]\nMr. Infantino. No, gracias. [Inaudible]\nThe President. It's great.\nJohn F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts/Renovation Work\nQ. Mr. President, the U.S. press?\nThe President. Thank you, everybody, very much. It's a great honor. This has been an honor for a lot of reasons. Number one, they've sold more tickets than any event has ever sold already—long before the kickoff.\nAnd number two, we've done a lot of work at the Kennedy Center. It was falling apart, and now it's pretty much back. And we'll get it back within the next 4 or 5 months through construction, and—but you see the way it looks.\nAnd Gianni is just telling me—who's done an incredible job, by the way. He's just telling, you know, how good a job we've done.\nMr. Infantino. That's right.\nThe President. You can look at the walls. The marble was broken. Everything was a mess. And we've really taken the Kennedy Center—a lot of people thought it was going to be ripped down, and we did just the opposite. So we've done a really great renovation job on it. And over the next 3, 4 months, it will be complete. And we're honored to have it here, and it's been—it's been very special.\nWe've set a record on ticket sales, as you probably heard, already, even way before—long before the event itself. And we're working with Canada, and we're working with Mexico. And it's been a really spectacular—so far, it's been spectacular.\nDaniel [Daniel Baldwin, One America News Network], do you have a question?\n2026 World Cup\nQ. What are your expectations? You once said that the FIFA World Cup is an opportunity to put—a once-in-a-lifetime opportunity to put the greatness of the United States on display.\nThe President. Well, I think—\nQ. One billion eyeballs will be watching, Mr. President.\nThe President. Yes, I—think——\nQ. What will they here today?\nThe President. Even today, I understand. I hear that, you know——\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\nThe President. ——I know we're a little late to get in there, but——\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\nThe President. ——that's okay.\nMr. Infantino. They wait.\nThe President. So all my friends, I guess they have to wait. They have no choice, right? [Laughter]\nMr. Infantino. Yes, they wait.\nThe President. But no, the numbers are incredible. I hear today's numbers are——\nMr. Infantino. Yes.\nThe President. ——very big. I hope CNN is covering this.\nQ. One billion eyeballs.\nMr. Infantino. Today, 1 billion eyeballs.\nThe President. Today's numbers are very, very big.\n2025 FIFA Peace Prize/The President's Foreign Policy\nQ. We are covering it. And you're expected to get the FIFA Peace Prize, Mr. President. What would you say to people who say that prize might conflict with your pledge to strike Venezuela?\nThe President. Well, I think the peace prize—I mean, I settled eight wars. I don't know that I'm getting it. I haven't been officially noticed. I've been hearing about a peace prize, and I'm here to represent our country in a different sense. But I can tell you, I did settle eight wars, and we have a ninth coming, but—which nobody has ever done before.\nBut I want to really save lives. I don't need prizes. I need to save lives. And we're saving a lot of lives. And I've saved millions and millions of lives, and that's really what I want to do.\nAnd I also want to run a great country. And the United States right now is the hottest country anywhere in the world. And 1 year ago, it was dead. We had a dead country, and now we have the hottest country anywhere in the world.\nQ. Mr. President, will you——\nThe President's Meeting With President Claudia Sheinbaum Pardo of Mexico and Prime Minister Mark Carney of Canada\nQ. What are you going to discuss with Canada and Mexico, Mr.—what are you going to discuss with the leaders of Canada and Mexico?\nThe President. Well, we're getting—we're going to meet with both. And we're getting along very well. You know, we're getting along very well. I don't know. I think we have a meeting set up for some time after the event.\nQ. Will you discuss trade?\nThe President. Yes, we'll discuss trade. We—get along very well.\nThank you, everybody, very much.\nQ. Will you pardon any other Honduran officials?\nQ. Do you want them to keep trying to indict Ms. James?\n\nNOTE: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. In his remarks, he referred to Trey Yingst, chief foreign correspondent, Fox News Channel; Cristiano Ronaldo, forward for Saudi Pro League club Al-Nass and Portugal's national soccer team; and Lionel Messi, forward for Major League Soccer club Inter Miami and Argentina's national team. A reporter referred to New York State Attorney General Letitia James. The transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\n\nSource URL: https://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/documents/remarks-exchange-with-reporters-prior-the-2026-federation-internationale-des-associations\n\n\n[defendant] DX-3 GovInfo/OFR pre-event transcript excerpt\nSource: GovInfo, DCPD202501162, Office of the Federal Register / National Archives and Records Administration.\nURL: https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/DCPD-202501162/html/DCPD-202501162.htm\nTitle: Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw\nEvent date: December 5, 2025.\n\nRelevant extracted page text:\n\"Administration of Donald J. Trump, 2025\"\n\"Remarks in an Exchange With Reporters Prior to the 2026 Fédération Internationale des Associations de Football (FIFA) World Cup Draw December 5, 2025\"\n\"[The President's remarks were joined in progress.]\"\n\nUnder the section \"The President's Interest in Soccer\":\n\"Q. Should there be a special final: American—[inaudible]?\"\n\"The President. No, but I got to meet Ronaldo the other day, came to the White House. He was fantastic. He's a handsome guy and a great guy. And my son Barron and him—and they had a big conversation. And my son loves soccer—\\\"football,\\\" as you would say. But Ronaldo is great. He's a great guy. He's got the whole package. He's a great player.\"\n\"Thank you very much. Thank you. [Inaudible]\"\n\nAdditional relevant extracted page text:\n\"The President's Interest in Soccer\"\n\"Q. Did you ever play soccer—or football?\"\n\"The President. Believe it or not, I did. I did, and I loved it. I had a—I was okay. I wouldn't say—I was not Ronaldo or Messi. I was a little bit short of them. [Laughter] But——\"\n\"Mr. Infantino. Just a little bit.\"\n\"The President. But they have a little more speed. But no, I was fine. But I loved playing soccer.\"\n\nGovInfo note:\n\"NOTE: The President spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. In his remarks, he referred to Trey Yingst, chief foreign correspondent, Fox News Channel; Cristiano Ronaldo, forward for Saudi Pro League club Al-Nass and Portugal's national soccer team; and Lionel Messi, forward for Major League Soccer club Inter Miami and Argentina's national team. A reporter referred to New York State Attorney General Letitia James. The transcript was released by the Office of Communications on December 8, 2025, with a corrected transcript released on January 2, 2026. Portions of these remarks could not be verified because the audio was incomplete.\"\n\nGovInfo content details page also identifies category \"Interviews With the News Media : Exchanges with reporters, Washington, DC,\" subjects including \"Federation Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) World Cup,\" \"John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts,\" and \"Soccer,\" and names including \"Ronaldo, Cristiano\" and \"Messi, Lionel.\"\n\n[defendant] DX-4 PRESMENTION/NEWMENTION terms\n                                         NEWMENTION\n\nScope: These rules shall apply to this contract.\n\nUnderlying: The Underlying for this Contract is words used by <entity> <time period>.\nRevisions to the Underlying made after Expiration will not be accounted for in determining the\nExpiration Value.\n\nSource Agency: The Source Agencies are <source>.\n\nType: The type of Contract is an Event Contract.\n\nIssuance: After the initial Contract, Contract iterations will be listed on an as-needed basis at\nthe discretion of the Exchange and corresponding to the risk management needs of Members.\n\n<entity>: <entity> refers to the speaker, writer, performer, or communicator specified by the\nExchange. This may include (but is not limited to): a specific named individual, multiple\nindividuals specified using AND/OR logic, an individual identified by position or title, a group,\nband, team or collective entity, a specified member or members of a group, an organization,\ncompany, or institutional entity, or any combination of the aforementioned.\n\nWhen <entity> is defined by a position or title, the Contract tracks whoever holds that position\nduring <time period>, even if the individual holding the position changes. When <entity> is a\nspecific named individual, the identity remains consistent throughout. Name changes (e.g.,\nstage names, married names) do not create a new entity. When <entity> is a group or\norganization and the Contract does not specify particular members, any official\ncommunication or statement by any member or designated spokesperson counts. When using\nAND logic, all specified entities must independently say <word> during <time period>. When\nusing OR logic, at least one of the specified entities must say <word> during <time period>.\nThe Exchange may specify additional conditions such as “at least X members of” a group or\n“the majority of” a group.\n\n<source>: <source> refers to a Source Agency or ordered collection of Source Agencies\nspecified by the Exchange at the time of Contract listing, which will be incorporated into the\nSource Agency hierarchy above and used to determine the occurrence of the Underlying.\n<source> may refer to a singular agency, multiple agencies, an agency by distinguishing\ncharacteristics, by category or type (e.g., “official government statistical body,” “primary wire\nservice”), or any combination thereof. When multiple agencies are specified, they may be\napplied in the hierarchical order designated by the Exchange if so specified, with the highest-\nranked available and responsive agency taking precedence for purposes of determining the\nExpiration Value. A lower-ranked agency shall only be consulted if all higher-ranked agencies\nare unavailable, unresponsive, have not reported on the Underlying by the Expiration time, or\nif the Exchange, in its sole discretion, determines that a higher-ranked agency’s reporting is\nincomplete, erroneous, or otherwise insufficient to determine the Expiration Value. If <source>\ndesignates multiple agencies without specifying a hierarchical order, the Exchange shall\nresolve any conflict between reporting agencies at its sole discretion.\n\n<word>: <word> refers to the particular word or phrase potentially to be mentioned by\n<entity>. It may refer to a word being said a minimum number of times. It may also refer to\none of multiple words/phrases, any of which are acceptable (e.g., “Doge/Dogecoin”).\n\f<time period>: <time period> refers to a specific range of time, event or discrete date and\ntime specified by the Exchange. This may be defined by, but is not limited to: a specific event\nor context (e.g., “during the State of the Union address”), exact dates or times, relative time\nmarkers (e.g., “before July 1, 2027,” “in Q1 2026”), event-based periods (e.g., “during any\ncampaign rally in October 2026,” “during the awards ceremony”), and broader intervals (e.g.,\n“Q1–Q2 2027,” “January–March 2026”).\n\nUnless stated otherwise, “Between” is inclusive of both endpoints, while “before” and “after”\nexclude the specified date. <time period> may also refer to “Any” or “None”, to multiple dates\n(even if non-consecutive), or to a singular and discrete date or time.\n\nWhen <time period> refers to a specific event (such as an address, speech, performance, or\nbroadcast), the Exchange may specify what is included, including whether it includes both live\nand pre-recorded segments (including whether advertisements are included). Where a\ntimezone is not specified, ET is assumed.\n\n\nPayout Criterion: The Payout Criterion for the Contract encompasses the Expiration Values that\n<word> is said by <entity> <time period>.\n\n\nThe word must appear as a distinct, standalone unit, not buried inside another word. Plural\nand possessive noun forms count. Other grammatical changes (tense, conjugation, derivation)\ndo not. If <word> appears separated from other words by a space or hyphen or in a\ncompound form with a space or hyphen, it counts. If <word> is fused into a single\nunhyphenated word, it does not count.\n\nIf <time period> refers to an event and that event is cancelled, and the market contains a\nstrike stating “Event does not qualify/occur”, such a strike shall resolve “Yes” and all others\n“No”. If <time period> refers to an event and that event is cancelled but such strikes are NOT\nlisted, the Contracts will resolve to the last fair price determined at the discretion of the\nExchange. If the event is postponed, and such a postponement is announced by the end of the\nfollowing calendar day to be rescheduled to a time within 14 calendar days, the markets shall\nremain open. If the event captured in <time period> is a live-stream or broadcast, the\nExchange may keep the market open for 24 hours for the release of an official recording.\nFurther granular details on conditions for these Contracts is available below.\n\nAdditional clarification(s):\n\n     Possessive noun forms of <word>, plurals, and possessive plural noun forms are\n     INCLUDED:\n          <word> is “Immigrant” → “Immigrants” counts\n          <word> is “Egg” → “eggs’ shells” counts\n          <word> is “Russia” → “Russia’s” counts, “Russian” does not\n     If <word> exists only in adjective form, no plural form exists:\n          <word> is “Economic” → “Economics” does not count (“Economic” is an adjective\n          for which “Economics” is not a plural)\n     Plural nouns occurring within proper nouns and noun phrases are included:\n          <word> is “Cat” → “Cats the musical” counts\n\f    Grammatical variations beyond plurals/possessives are NOT included:\n         <word> is “Immigrant” → “Immigration” does NOT count\n         <word> is “Run” → “Running” or “Ran” do NOT count\n    When <word> specifies a plural form, the singular does NOT count:\n         <word> is “Veterans” → “Veteran” does NOT count\n    Words that are spelled the same as the plural form of <word> (if such exists) but are\n    themselves not a plural noun are included:\n         <word> is “Wind” → “Winds up the clock” counts\n         <word> is “Border” → “The United States has strong borders” counts\n    Open compounds (words separated by spaces) count:\n         <word> is “fire” → “fire station” counts\n         <word> is “couch” → “couch potato” counts\n    Hyphenated compounds (words connected by hyphens) count:\n         <word> is “Palestine” → “pro-Palestine” counts\n         <word> is “fat” → “non-fat” counts\n    Closed compounds (single word, no spaces/hyphens) do not count:\n         <word> is “fire” → “wildfire” does not count\n         <word> is “fire” → “firefighter” does not count\n    Multi-word <word> in larger constructions: When <word> is a multi-word phrase\n    appearing within a hyphenated construction, it counts only if <word> appears as a\n    complete, unmodified element:\n         <word> is “New York” → “New York-based” counts (complete element)\n    Portmanteaus (words blended from two words where parts of each are combined) are\n    NOT included unless the portmanteau clearly contains <word> as a distinct, unaltered\n    element:\n         <word> is “MAGA” → “MAGA-nificent” counts (MAGA appears as distinct element)\n         <word> is “magnificent” → “MAGA-nificent” does NOT count (portmanteau blend)\n\nDictionary determination: Both the Merriam-Webster Dictionary (available online) AND the\nOxford English Dictionary shall be used to determine compound type and/or conventional\nspelling patterns. Inclusion in either dictionary as an open or hyphenated compound shall\nsatisfy the Payout Criterion. If neither provides clarity (or the word is not included),\ndetermination is based on whether written as single unit (closed/doesn’t count) vs. spaces or\nhyphens (open or hyphenated/counts) and/or context and previous usage.\n\nPHONETIC EQUIVALENCIES\n\n    Homophones (same sound, different spelling) do not count:\n        <word> is “write” → “right” does not count\n    Homonyms and homographs (same spelling) COUNT regardless of meaning or\n    pronunciation:\n        <word> is “bass” → both “bass guitar” and “bass fishing” count\n    Proper and common nouns are treated identically:\n        <word> is “Apple” → both “Apple Inc.” and “apple” (fruit) count\n        <word> is “Will” → both “Will Smith” and “I will go” count\n    Minor unintentional mispronunciations COUNT if context makes intent clear:\n        <word> is “Mamdani” → “Mandani” counts\n    Severe mispronunciations that make <word> unrecognizable do NOT count.\n    Trademarked spellings do not count, even when pronounced identically, unless the word\n\fitself is the same:\n      <word> is “lift” → “Lyft” (pronounced “lift”) does not count\n      <word> is “uber” → “Uber” counts\nWords with non-standard transliteration to English count within reason, provided they are\nphonetically equivalent:\n      <word> is “Zelensky” → any of “Zelenski,” “Zelenskii,” “Zelensky,” or “Zelenskiy”\n      count if pronounced equivalently\nContractions do not count for their constituent words unless otherwise explicitly specified\nby the Exchange:\n      <word> is “not” → “won’t,” “can’t,” “don’t,” “isn’t” do not count\nNumbers spoken as words COUNT, when spoken exactly (not part of a larger number):\n      <word> is “five” → saying “five” or reading “$5” aloud as “five dollars” counts,\n      saying “five hundred” does NOT count\n      <word> is “410” → “four hundred ten”, “four one zero” or “four ten” counts\nOrdinals COUNT when <word> is written numerically OR a phrase that includes a\nnumber:\n      <word> is “January 6” → “January 6th” counts\n      <word> is “3” (written numerically) → “3rd” (spoken as “third”) counts\n      <word> is “Eight War” → “8 Wars” and “Eighth War” will count\nCardinal and ordinal number words are distinct:\n      <word> is “one” → “first” does NOT count\n      <word> is “first” → “one” does NOT count\nAcronyms and abbreviations count when pronunciation or letter-by-letter spelling\nmatches <word>:\n      <word> is “NASA” → “NASA” (pronounced “NAH-suh”) counts\n      <word> is “NASA” → “N-A-S-A” (spelled out) counts\nAcronyms and abbreviations count as <word> when pronounced as the full word:\n      <word> is “Doctor” → “Dr.” (pronounced “Doctor”) counts\nExpanded forms of acronyms do NOT count:\n      <word> is “AI” → “artificial intelligence” does not count\nWords in foreign languages do NOT count unless they are perfect cognates with an\nEnglish word:\n      <word> is “fire” → “fuego” (Spanish) does NOT count\nEnglish words within foreign sentences count:\n      <word> is “policy” → “Nuestra policy es clara” counts\n<word> in organization/company names counts:\n      <word> is “Securities” → “Bank of America Securities” counts\nWords in URLs, emails, handles, and hashtags (exclusive of domain structure, email\nprovider or symbols) are treated as compounds when spoken as complete words, with the\ntype of compound subject to aforementioned rules:\n      <word> is “fire” → “firestation.com” pronounced “fire station dot com” counts\n      <word> is “fire” → “wildfire.com” pronounced “wildfire dot com” does NOT count\n      <word> is “apple” → “apple.com” pronounced “apple dot com” does count\n      When presented in URL, email, handle, or hashtag form, <word> shall be treated as\n      a compound, not a multi-word word\nSung, rapped, or poetic words COUNT if phonetically recognizable:\n      <word> is “money” → “moneyyy” (extended in rap) counts\n      Extreme distortion making <word> unrecognizable does NOT count.\nPhonetic alphabet spelling (“Foxtrot India Romeo Echo” for “FIRE”) does NOT count.\n\fCANCELLATIONS AND DELAYS\n\n   The Exchange may list an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike for any Contract. If listed,\n   such a strike refers to the structural conditions of the market, and is NOT adjudicated as a\n   <word> needing to be said by or validated by having been said by <entity>. If listed, this\n   strike resolves to “Yes” whenever the event fails to occur or qualify under the Payout\n   Criterion, or any other circumstance prevents normal resolution.\n   If no such strike is listed, and <time period> refers to a specific event, the following rules\n   apply if the event is cancelled, postponed, rescheduled, or materially altered (including\n   being closed to press) such that no video is released within one calendar day of the\n   original start time of the event:\n         If the event is cancelled, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price determined in\n         the sole discretion of the Exchange.\n         If the event is postponed or rescheduled, the outcome depends on whether a new\n         date is publicly announced within one calendar day (i.e. if the event was scheduled\n         to begin on Monday, any time up to 11:59PM on Tuesday falls within this period) of\n         the originally scheduled start time:\n               If no new date is announced within one calendar day, the Contract will resolve\n               to the last fair price determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\n               If a new date is announced within one calendar day, the outcome depends on\n               when the rescheduled event is set to occur:\n                     If the rescheduled date falls within fourteen (14) calendar days of the\n                     originally scheduled date, the Contract shall remain open and <word>\n                     stated during the rescheduled event will count.\n                           The fourteen-day window begins at 12:00 AM ET on the originally\n                           scheduled date and ends at 11:59 PM ET fourteen days later, unless\n                           an alternate timezone is explicitly specified.\n                           Example: <time period> is “during the State of the Union on January\n                           15, 2026” rescheduled to January 20, 2026 → words spoken during\n                           the rescheduled address count.\n                     If the rescheduled date falls more than fourteen (14) calendar days after\n                     the originally scheduled date, the Contract will resolve to the last fair price\n                     determined in the sole discretion of the Exchange.\n         Any Contract that cannot be resolved through the Source Agency hierarchy will\n         instead be settled at the Last Fair Price. The Exchange will disclose the methodology\n         used to determine the Last Fair Price (e.g., Last Traded Price, Time-Weighted\n         Average Price) at the time of Issuance.\n         If an event begins but is interrupted, abbreviated, or ends prematurely, words\n         stated by <entity> during the portion of the event that did occur will count and the\n         market will otherwise resolve.\n   If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window but the venue, format, or medium\n   changes (e.g., moved to a different location, changed from in-person to virtual (with the\n   exception of being closed to press)), words stated during the event will count.\n   Special condition: Across both cases, whether an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike is\n   listed or not, if the event specified as or in <time period> is a live-stream or broadcast (or\n   relayed as such) but the live stream/broadcast does not occur, the Exchange will instead\n   use an officially released recording as the Underlying, and may delay resolution by up to\n   one calendar day to allow for the release of such a recording.\n\f          If partial snippets are released, Contracts on words that do not appear will be\n          resolved to last fair price, and Contracts on those that do will be resolved to “Yes”.\n          If no recording is released, the relevant outcomes triggered by the\n          presence/absence of an “Event does not qualify/occur” strike shall occur as outlined\n          above.\n\nTECHNICAL DETAILS (UNLESS OTHERWISE SPECIFIED)\n\n     When <time period> refers to a specific event, pre-recorded content broadcast,\n     streamed, or published as part of that event is included if presented as part of the official\n     presentation.\n          Example: <time period> is “during the concert” with pre-recorded video interlude\n          where entity speaks → words from interlude count\n          Example: <time period> is “during the television appearance” with pre-taped\n          segment aired during broadcast → words from segment count\n     Behind-the-scenes content, rehearsals, sound checks, and unofficial recordings are NOT\n     included unless officially broadcast or published as part of <time period>.\n     Subtitles and captions that display <word> on screen but are not spoken aloud by\n     <entity> do NOT count.\n     Sign language interpretation or usage by entity does NOT count as saying <word> unless\n     the Contract explicitly specifies that sign language counts.\n     Text that entity displays on screen (presentation slides, teleprompter visible to audience,\n     signatures) does NOT count unless entity reads it aloud.\n     Content generated by AI, deepfakes, or synthetic voice technology impersonating entity\n     does NOT count unless the synthetic content is officially commissioned, authorized, or\n     published by entity, OR the Contract explicitly specifies that AI-generated content counts.\n     If <word> is muted due to technical failure or censorship it shall not count unless\n     corroborating contextual evidence (including surrounding speech, or an official\n     uncensored recording or transcript) confirms that <entity> specifically uttered <word>\n     during the muted period.\n\nMinimum Tick: The Minimum Tick size for the Contract shall be $0.01.\n\nPosition Accountability Level: The Position Accountability Level for the Contract shall be\n$25,000 per strike, per Member.\n\nLast Trading Date: The Last Trading Date of the Contract will be the Expiration Date. The Last\nTrading Time will be the Expiration time.\n\nSettlement Date: The Settlement Date of the Contract shall be no later than the day after the\nExpiration Date, unless the Market Outcome is under review pursuant to Rule 7.1.\n\nExpiration Date: When <time period> refers to a specific event: The latest Expiration Date of\nthe Contract shall be fourteen (14) calendar days after the originally scheduled date of the\nevent. If the event occurs within the fourteen-day window, expiration will be moved to an\nearlier date and time in accordance with Rule 7.2. When <time period> is defined by specific\ndates: The latest Expiration Date of the Contract shall be two weeks after the end of <time\nperiod>. If an event described in the Payout Criterion occurs and a consensus has been\nreached on all terms, then expiration will be moved to an earlier date and time in accordance\nwith Rule 7.2.\n\fExpiration time: The Expiration time of the Contract shall be 10:00 AM ET.\n\nSettlement Value: The Settlement Value for this Contract is $1.00.\n\nExpiration Value: The Expiration Value is the value of the Underlying as documented by the\nSource Agency on the Expiration Date at the Expiration time.\n\nContingencies: Before Settlement, Kalshi may, at its sole discretion, initiate the Market\nOutcome Review Process pursuant to Rule 7.1 of the Rulebook. If an Expiration Value cannot\nbe determined on the Expiration Date, Kalshi has the right to determine payouts pursuant to\nRule 7.1 in the Rulebook.\n\f\n\n[defendant] DX-5 Formal draw archive note\nSource checked: Roll Call / Factba.se archive\n\nArchive title: Remarks: Donald Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing in Washington - December 5, 2025\n\nArchive URL: https://rollcall.com/factbase/trump/transcript/donald-trump-remarks-fifa-world-cup-drawing-december-5-2025/\n\nWhat this file establishes:\n\nThere is a separate archived transcript page for Trump's formal attendance remarks at the draw.\n\nWhat this file does not establish:\n\nThis session could not retrieve the full transcript text from that archive.  The page is password-protected.  This example therefore does not claim, from local files alone, whether the formal program transcript does or does not contain the word \"Ronaldo.\"\n\nWhy this matters:\n\nThe complaint does not need to prove that the formal program omitted the strike.  It needs to show that Trump said \"Ronaldo\" in event-linked remarks and that the market boundary reasonably includes those remarks.  The formal archive remains relevant because it marks the distinction between the pre-event reporter exchange and the formal program.\n\n\n[defendant] DX-6 Formal Roll Call/Factba.se transcript extraction\nSource: Roll Call / Factba.se\nURL: https://rollcall.com/factbase/trump/transcript/donald-trump-remarks-fifa-world-cup-drawing-december-5-2025/\nCaptured page title: Remarks: Donald Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing in Washington - December 5, 2025\n\nRendered page metadata excerpt:\nTopics: Sport; Sport > Competition Discipline > Soccer; Lifestyle and Leisure > Leisure > Game.\nEntities listed: bowl; deal; Donald J. Trump; FIFA World Cup; Mark Carney; place; President; trophy; United States; way.\nSpeakers listed: Gianni Infantino, Donald Trump, Mark Carney, Claudia Sheinbaum.\nSpeaker statistics excerpt: Donald Trump said 25 sentences of a total of 141 sentences; Donald Trump said 274 words of a total of 1009 words; Donald Trump talked 92 seconds of a total of 484 seconds.\n\nFormal transcript excerpt at start of draw:\nMark Carney, 00:00:00-00:00:02: Thank you, my friend.\nGianni Infantino, 00:00:50-00:01:22: So this is the World Cup trophy. This is the official bowl for the World Cup and we are now going to do the draw, ladies and gentlemen. But before that, as is customary, there is always a question that the moderator asks the draw assistant. So I would like to start with Mr. Carney. How big a deal is it to co-host the World Cup for Canada?\n\nFormal transcript excerpt of Trump's soccer answer:\nDonald Trump, 00:03:14-00:03:32: Well, for years, Gianni, they've thought soccer or football would be so big, so fast. And I remember, I shouldn't say this because it was a long time ago, but I remember watching Pele play on a team called the Cosmos, Pele, who was fantastic, as you know. I assume one of the greats.\n\nText-extraction/search notes:\nLocal Python urllib retrieval of the page returned HTTP 200 for the source URL and extracted approximately 175,864 characters of page text with Python html.parser. Case-sensitive searches in the extracted page text returned no occurrence of \"Ronaldo\" and no occurrence of \"Messi\". The same terms were not found using the browser page find function on the rendered page.\n\n[plaintiff] PX-R1 Defendant formal transcript extraction for limited rebuttal use\nSource: Roll Call / Factba.se\nURL: https://rollcall.com/factbase/trump/transcript/donald-trump-remarks-fifa-world-cup-drawing-december-5-2025/\nCaptured page title: Remarks: Donald Trump Attends the FIFA World Cup Drawing in Washington - December 5, 2025\n\nRendered page metadata excerpt:\nTopics: Sport; Sport > Competition Discipline > Soccer; Lifestyle and Leisure > Leisure > Game.\nEntities listed: bowl; deal; Donald J. Trump; FIFA World Cup; Mark Carney; place; President; trophy; United States; way.\nSpeakers listed: Gianni Infantino, Donald Trump, Mark Carney, Claudia Sheinbaum.\nSpeaker statistics excerpt: Donald Trump said 25 sentences of a total of 141 sentences; Donald Trump said 274 words of a total of 1009 words; Donald Trump talked 92 seconds of a total of 484 seconds.\n\nFormal transcript excerpt at start of draw:\nMark Carney, 00:00:00-00:00:02: Thank you, my friend.\nGianni Infantino, 00:00:50-00:01:22: So this is the World Cup trophy. This is the official bowl for the World Cup and we are now going to do the draw, ladies and gentlemen. But before that, as is customary, there is always a question that the moderator asks the draw assistant. So I would like to start with Mr. Carney. How big a deal is it to co-host the World Cup for Canada?\n\nFormal transcript excerpt of Trump's soccer answer:\nDonald Trump, 00:03:14-00:03:32: Well, for years, Gianni, they've thought soccer or football would be so big, so fast. And I remember, I shouldn't say this because it was a long time ago, but I remember watching Pele play on a team called the Cosmos, Pele, who was fantastic, as you know. I assume one of the greats.\n\nText-extraction/search notes:\nLocal Python urllib retrieval of the page returned HTTP 200 for the source URL and extracted approximately 175,864 characters of page text with Python html.parser. Case-sensitive searches in the extracted page text returned no occurrence of \"Ronaldo\" and no occurrence of \"Messi\". The same terms were not found using the browser page find function on the rendered page.\n\nSubmitted evidence:\n[plaintiff arguments] GovInfo DCPD202501162 transcript excerpt and metadata (ev_3fc783920414_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-3fc783920414)\nSource: https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/DCPD-202501162/html/DCPD-202501162.htm\nSHA-256: `3fc783920414399098d86210070dd9fe83c14fe1dbded1a56a554f8f4b3448f2`\nBytes: 2641\nRelevance: Official government transcript source corroborating that Trump spoke at 11:13 a.m. at the John F. Kennedy Center before the 2026 FIFA World Cup Draw and said the strike word Ronaldo in World-Cup-related remarks.\n\n[defendant arguments] Roll Call/Factba.se formal FIFA World Cup Drawing transcript extraction (ev_fbb53e87ccb3_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-fbb53e87ccb3)\nSource: https://rollcall.com/factbase/trump/transcript/donald-trump-remarks-fifa-world-cup-drawing-december-5-2025/\nSHA-256: `fbb53e87ccb3f4381fc2bdc06ac2f2a1ea3848aadde56122b22d34dfbdf4533b`\nBytes: 2032\nRelevance: Formal drawing-program transcript evidence showing a separate formal Draw source from the pre-event reporter exchange; the extracted page text contains no occurrence of Ronaldo or Messi, supporting defendant's event-boundary argument.\n\nTechnical reports:\n[plaintiff] Plaintiff source and adverse-search ledger\nChecked the visible case packet and then searched official/source-specific repositories. GovInfo DCPD202501162 was opened and preserved as submitted evidence; it corroborates the packet transcript, source metadata, location, event date, and Ronaldo passages. The Roll Call/Factba.se formal drawing page rendered despite the packet's password-protection note; browser find searches for 'Ronaldo,' 'Cristiano,' and 'Messi' returned no matches. Plaintiff therefore treats the formal-program transcript as an adverse boundary check, not as proof of a formal-stage mention. The remaining dispute is contractual scope: whether the market clearly excluded public event-linked venue remarks immediately before the formal program.\n\n[defendant] Defense source-check ledger\nDefendant searched for the formal Roll Call/Factba.se transcript identified by the case packet, opened the rendered Roll Call page, and fetched it locally with Python urllib. The fetch returned HTTP 200 for the formal FIFA World Cup Drawing transcript page. Text extraction produced approximately 175,864 characters; searches for \"Ronaldo\" and \"Messi\" returned no occurrences. The retrieval also captured formal-program excerpts, including Infantino's statement that \"we are now going to do the draw\" and Trump's formal soccer answer mentioning Pele rather than Ronaldo. The focused extraction was submitted and accepted as ev_fbb53e87ccb3_submitted-evidence-02-defendant-fbb53e87ccb3.\n\nCall submit_council_vote with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated.\nKeep the rationale brief: no more than three sentences.\n\nCouncil API instructions:\nYou are a council member. Decide the proposition from the admitted record.\nYou may examine admitted evidence through read-only tools when exact bytes, metadata, or exhibit contents matter.\nDo not search the web, introduce new facts, create new evidence, or upload evidence.\nWhen ready, call submit_council_vote exactly once with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated and a concise rationale.\n","state":"ready","status":"ready","tools":[{"description":"Return the current visible arbitration record for this council member.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{},"type":"object"},"name":"get_case","read_only":true},{"description":"List visible immutable record evidence.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{},"type":"object"},"name":"list_evidence","read_only":true},{"description":"Return metadata and read limits for one visible evidence item.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"evidence_id":{"type":"string"}},"required":["evidence_id"],"type":"object"},"name":"stat_evidence","read_only":true},{"description":"Read a bounded byte range from one visible evidence item as base64.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"evidence_id":{"type":"string"},"length":{"minimum":1,"type":"integer"},"offset":{"minimum":0,"type":"integer"}},"required":["evidence_id","offset","length"],"type":"object"},"name":"read_evidence_range","read_only":true},{"description":"Submit one council vote for the current deliberation opportunity.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"rationale":{"type":"string"},"vote":{"enum":["demonstrated","not_demonstrated"],"type":"string"}},"required":["vote","rationale"],"type":"object"},"name":"submit_council_vote","read_only":false}],"turn":{"attempts_max":3,"attempts_remaining":3,"completed":false,"deadline":"2026-06-29T19:58:02.156322961Z","deliberation_round":1,"member_id":"C2","opportunity_id":"deliberation:1:C2","phase":"deliberation","remaining_ms":887183,"role_id":"council","turn_number":10},"wait":{"reason":"ready","state_version":12,"version":15}},"isError":false},"server":"aar","tool":"wait_for_opportunity"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1782762194987}]}
